<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-BALLMER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATES STEPS DOWN AS MICROSOFT CEO; BALLMER GETS THE JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After 25 years of building the company he co-founded
into one of the most powerful, influential and profitable engines
of the modern era, Bill Gates on Thursday stepped down as chief
executive officer of Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, 44, relinquished that title to Steve Ballmer, 43, his
friend and colleague of more than 20 years. The raucous, ebullient
Ballmer, who joined the company in the summer of 1980 and became
president in July 1998, will retain that title and also take a
board seat.
</P>
<P>
   Gates will remain chairman and take on a new role: chief
software architect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a nice milestone to look back and say, `Hey, over the
last 25 years we really got something done,' and I'm proud of
that,'' Gates said at a hastily convened press conference Thursday.
``But it's also a milestone to look forward and say, `What can
software _ and in particular, Microsoft software _ do to make
things a lot better in the 10 years to come?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gates led the company's spectacular rise to a business behemoth
worth more than $500 billion and steered it through its turbulent
recent history, including a federal judge's ruling in November that
Microsoft used monopoly powers to harm consumers and competitors.
</P>
<P>
   As Microsoft's new chief, Ballmer declared, ``I'm certainly
honored and very, very excited about the opportunity. I'm
enthusiastic about working with Bill in this new way over the
coming years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer called Gates ``one of the best idea machines in the
world, someone who can see things in a unique way.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how the two men will share their management
responsibilities wasn't immediately clear.
</P>
<P>
   But Paul Allen, who co-founded Microsoft with Gates, worked with
both men at the company and now sits on the company's board, said
he believes their changes in responsibility _ especially Ballmer's
_ will be major.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve has stepped up and taken the additional responsibility,
which is no small thing,'' said Allen, the world's third wealthiest
man, in a rare interview. ``As the CEO, the buck stops with you,
and you have to make real decisions. He'll make a lot of decisions
that formerly were Bill's to make. And he'll do it with his own
style.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer, who used to report to Gates, will now answer to the
board, just as Gates does.
</P>
<P>
   Each man now appears to be doing what he likes best. As
Microsoft's long-time vice president of sales, Ballmer helped make
Windows a household name in the 1990s. The new role, observers
said, is nothing more than an extension of his role as president.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people miss is that despite everything, Ballmer gets the
job done,'' said Michael Gartenberg, vice president of the
technology consulting firm, the Gartner Group.
</P>
<P>
   William Epifanio, an analyst with J.P. Morgan, said, ``This is a
good change. Microsoft faces a lot of challenges going forward, and
Ballmer is a terrific manager, really, with a personality more
suited to the chief executive's job than Bill Gates.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Gates, he said he has wanted for at least two years to
get back to a more strategic position. As chief software architect,
he will spend most of his time strategizing with the company's four
product groups, ``talking about feedback we get from developers and
making sure the pieces add up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates said he won't actually be writing code, as he did in the
company's formative years when he wrote operating systems for some
of the earliest personal computers. ``But I may be
(ital)threatening(end ital) to write code,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   The succession comes at what Gates called an inflection point in
the company's evolution. An intense, multi-year effort to create
Windows 2000, the business-oriented operating system that succeeds
Windows NT, came to a climax last month with the product's release
to manufacturing. Gates has described Windows 2000, which is set to
ship Feb. 17, as the most important product Microsoft has ever
produced.
</P>
<P>
   Now the company will turn its attention to an initiative it
calls Next Generation Windows Services, emphasizing the Internet as
a development and application platform at least as heavily as it
does the traditional focus of Microsoft's efforts: the personal
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Products will roll out over the next three years, with early
details to be revealed this spring at Forum 2000, a day for
discussing strategy with press and analysts. Additional details
will be released this summer at the annual developers' conference.
As part of the plan, updates to SQL Server, Exchange, and
development tools will be released over the next year, Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an evolutionary change in how the company is run, but the
company is at a revolutionary point'' in its development, said Jeff
Raikes, group vice president for worldwide sales and support.
</P>
<P>
   One skeptic suggested Thursday's announcements, which surely
have been pending for months, had nothing to do with the company's
product flow.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, suggested Giga Group analyst Rob Enderle, they may have
been timed to let Microsoft evade an agreement not to discuss
settlement negotiations in the Department of Justice's antitrust
suit.
</P>
<P>
   A government proposal, leaked Wednesday, suggested the
plaintiffs favor a harsh penalty: breaking up the company into
three pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Enderle suggested that Microsoft's responding to a press
question about that proposal would offer the company a chance to
comment without formally making a statement. And sure enough, in
answer to the first question asked at the press conference, Ballmer
blasted the government's idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be absolutely reckless and irresponsible for
anyone to try to break up this company,'' Ballmer said. ``I think
it would be unprecedented, and I think it would be the single
greatest disservice that anybody could do to consumers in this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer said in a teleconference call he believed the
government's leaks were deliberate.
</P>
<P>
   But Paul Allen rejected Enderle's theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who thinks this is a reaction to the lawsuit ... is
getting it completely wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On CNBC, President Clinton described Ballmer as ``a very able
man, and Gates is a genius with technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer is the son of Swiss immigrants. He grew up in Detroit,
where his father worked for Ford Motor Co. A graduate of Harvard
University, Ballmer earned a degree in applied math and economics
and later worked at Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. as an assistant product
manager, according to his official Microsoft biography. He then
attended the Stanford Graduate School of Business.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer's bulldog attitude is what attracted Gates when he first
met Ballmer at Harvard, where they were both students. The two have
worked closely together ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve is a great manager and a great motivator,'' Raikes said.
``I've worked for Steve for 18 years, and I can say that the
company's in good hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Material from P-I news services was included in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
