<HEADLINE>
LAKERS FACE PACERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS -- So, what does a team that's won 16 games
straight do for an encore? The possibilities for the Lakers are
endless, and poss ibly, ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, the 33-game NBA record set by the 1971-72
Lakers. But how about a modest 20-game set? That would tie the
second longest st reak in history.
</P>
<P>
   Or a 70-win season? That would move the current Lakers past the
1971-72 team's 69-win season and into Chicago Bulls territory (72
wins, 1995-96 ).
</P>
<P>
   Anything seems possible as the Lakers try to extend the streak
to 17 to night against the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Only seven teams in NBA history have won at least 17 in a row,
meaning the Lakers are already in heady company.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-win Lakers won the championship. The 20-win Milwaukee
Bucks of 1 971-72 did too. Three teams won 18 in a row, and two of
them -- the 1969 -70 Knicks and 1995-96 Bulls -- won the
championship. Two teams have won 17 straight, including the 1959-60
Celtics, who also won a championship .
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the current 16-game streak, matched by three
other tea ms and tying the second longest streak in Laker history,
which on its own, ``is an accomplishment,'' forward Rick Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously a franchise with a lot of great history. To be
one of the better teams that have put together a streak is
something that's nic e to be part of,'' he said. ``But I don't
necessarily think it's going t o amount to much if we don't really
accomplish what we ultimately set ou t to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   The 33-game record, coach Phil Jackson said, is still too far
off to co ntemplate. But a 70-win season, he can visualize.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has potential,'' Jackson said. ``I mean, it has
potential maybe not this year, maybe in the future ahead of it, the
potential to do that. It takes so many lucky things, like health
and scheduling and the right stuff. They're not quite ready yet.
They're not totally mature in their game.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Robert Horry was scheduled to be fitted for a
protective mask Thursday, but it's still uncertain whether he will
play tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Horry broke his nose when he caught an elbow from Milwaukee's
Tim Thoma s in Wednesday's victory over the Bucks. He was able to
practice Thursda y, without any protection, but his status tonight
might depend simply on his pain threshold.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have been relatively injury-free since Dec. 1, when
Kobe Bry ant returned from a broken hand. In the 21 games that have
followed, no member of the Lakers' nine-man rotation has been
injured, though Glen Rice missed one game with the flu.
</P>
</TEXT>
