<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC HAS PROPER FOCUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC's basketball season took a huge leap forward
after its victory over UCLA on Wednesday, but forward Brian
Scalabrine thinks the Trojans' fortunes really changed after the
team began to think small.
</P>
<P>
   Following an embarrassing 76-66 loss to Long Beach State on Dec.
16, USC coach Henry Bibby forced the Trojans to watch game films
until 2 a.m. the next morning. Afterward, the team decided to
re-evaluate its goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the year, we were so involved with looking
at the NCAA Tournament, and our chances of making it, it was really
hurting us,'' Scalabrine said. ``We figured out if we're going to
be the best team we can, we're just going to have to take it one
game at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're really putting something together.''
</P>
<P>
   Just average:Guard Jeff Trepagnier scored a career-high 26
points, made 11 of 15 shots and grabbed 10 rebounds against UCLA,
but that wasn't enough to impress Bibby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Jeff played average. I expect a little more out of
him,'' Bibby said. ``He didn't have his usual bounce he's had. But
you look at the stat sheet and he played a good game.''
</P>
<P>
   Trepagnier, who sprained his ankle during Monday's practice, did
not dispute Bibby's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was an average game also. I was getting burned on
defense,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
