<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-CUBA-BOY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUG OF WAR AS COMPLEX AS WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Which was tougher: prying three American soldiers
from the grasp of Slobodan Milosevic, or trying to liberate a
6-year-old Cuban boy from bureaucratic bumbling, juridical
hocus-pocus and political pandering in America?
</P>
<P>
   No contest, said the Rev. Joan Brown Campbell, until two weeks
ago the general secretary of the National Council of Churches in
New York. ``Getting the soldiers out of Serbia wasn't easy, but it
was easier,'' she said. ``As complicated as that was, the emotions
vested in the Cuban-Americans in Miami and the political weight
that they have _ that's the wild card in this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' as you have no doubt figured out, is the fate of Elian
Gonzalez, the boy who survived an escape from Cuba that drowned his
mother and who now carries four decades of miserable United
States-Cuban relations on his tiny shoulders. Had he come from any
other country, Ms. Campbell said, this affair would have been a
no-brainer. Elian would have been sent home to his father weeks
ago, instead of remaining in Miami with relatives and other
Cuban-Americans out to make an anti-Castro poster boy of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's deep in the American court system that children belong
with their families unless their families are abusive,'' she said
in her Manhattan apartment. ``And nobody, not even people who want
to make hay out of this, are saying this father is abusive. In
fact, he had primary care for the child.''
</P>
<P>
   How did a New Yorker get caught up in this messy business? Easy.
The same way Ms. Campbell joined the Rev. Jesse Jackson and other
American religious leaders on a mission to Serbia last spring to
free three soldiers held captive by Milosevic's forces.
</P>
<P>
   Getting involved is what she did for nine years as leader of the
church council, which encompasses 35 Christian denominations with
54 million members. The tug of war over Elian was a natural issue
for her. She has visited Cuba regularly for more than 30 years. The
Cuban Council of Churches enlisted her help, she said, even though
she was leaving the American council to become chaplain of the
Chautauqua Institution in western New York. The two councils had
strong relations since well before Castro took power in 1959. She
elaborated:
</P>
<P>
   ``We said, `Look, we're prepared to offer ourselves as a third
party that could take this boy back to Cuba, turn him over to the
Cuban Council of Churches rather than to the government, and they
would turn him over directly to his father.' Our government said,
`Interesting idea; it might work.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is different than Bill Clinton giving him to Fidel
Castro,'' she said. ``The hardest thing for the Miami people to
take would be, `OK, we'll hand him over to Castro.'''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, she visited Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, a
hotel worker in the coastal town of Cardenas. She and another
council official, the Rev. Oscar Bolioli, were among the few
outsiders given such access. There were also both sets of Elian's
grandparents and other relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are genuine emotions in this family, genuine grief,
genuine tears about this boy not being there,'' Ms. Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   What about suspicions that Gonzalez is little more than a Castro
marionette? Why does he not go to Miami, as some demand, and make
his case there?
</P>
<P>
   Because, Ms. Campbell replied, he fears ``being trapped'' by
lawsuits and subpoenas. His concern seems not unreasonable. We have
already been treated to political theatrics like a congressional
subpoena of little Elian. As for the family being puppets, Ms.
Campbell said, ``I've been in those situations many times in my
life, and there was no looking over the shoulder, the kind of thing
you see when people are nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   But wouldn't Elian have a happier, freer life in this country?
``I do think _this is more as a mother and a grandmother _ there is
a reason that in our country, we make the assumption that children
belong in their families, that that's where they can grow up to be
the healthiest adults,'' she said. ``If we don't believe that, the
whole family structure becomes up for grabs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter is a county commissioner in Cleveland,'' Ms.
Campbell continued. ``She said, `Mother, tonight we have over 5,000
children in protective custody for only one reason: nobody loves
them.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know for sure about the family is that they spoke from
their hearts, that they miss this little boy, and that they
certainly have the capacity to love him. That, in many ways, is all
you can ask of a family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
