<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LEAVING THE COCOON 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Jan. 14:
</P>
<P>
   Whether by prearrangement or on the advice of Walter Cronkite,
David Letterman was extremely gentle to Hillary Rodham Clinton as
she took her first steps this week into the real world of New
York's brand of performance politics. Mrs. Clinton should be
pleased with the good reviews she got for composure and humor. But
she should also know that this was only a small step in the
direction of conducting an open campaign. Now that she is a
resident of the state, it is time for Mrs. Clinton to emerge fully
from the White House cocoon.
</P>
<P>
   New York likes its politicians available _ on the phone, at the
subway, in your face. The local style is to be open to questions
from constituents and reporters on any and all subjects, instead of
seeking out hand-picked audiences and softball questions. To be
taken seriously as a candidate, Mrs. Clinton needs to show she does
not have to hide behind her advance team and press spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons, of course, that Mrs. Clinton has not been
readily available to potential constituents until the past few
days. She had the holiday scene at her former home in Washington.
She moved to a new house in Westchester County. And because she is
the president's wife, there are legitimate security concerns that
have to be honored.
</P>
<P>
   But by choosing to run she has obligated herself to find ways to
engage issues, the public and the press. In other words, it's
showtime. Surveys suggest that Mrs. Clinton's reclusiveness has
been costly. One poll even found that the first lady was running
behind Mayor Rudolph Giuliani in support among women. The message
seems to be that she needs to be more on view, countering the
general worry that she is too cautious and pre-packaged to make it
in New York's rowdy political arena.
</P>
<P>
   Every candidate faces threshold questions about campaign
competence and fitness for office. Some of these questions are
based on reality. Others are flukes, a ballooning of some momentary
image into a widespread conclusion about a political candidate. But
all candidates have to deal with these issues in full public view.
Giuliani is out there barking his views, making his mistakes and
defending them. Mrs. Clinton has yet to show how well she can
survive as an independent operator outside the cosseted world of
spinners and loyalists.
</P>
<P>
   Public politicking is a nonpartisan New York tradition. One
notable practitioner, former Mayor Ed Koch, says he has advised the
first lady to ``be open and around and available.'' That is wise
counsel. The Letterman appearance was an entertaining gesture in
the direction of openness. But Mrs. Clinton must move on to a truly
public campaign. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 0015EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
