<HEADER>
A5818 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-GIULIANI-NYT &LR;      01-14 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE MAYOR'S POLITICAL RENDERING 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Jan. 14:
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's State of the City speech on Thursday
was in part a summation of his now-familiar list of successes over
the last six years. Giuliani sought to define and secure his legacy
in what ``could be my last'' such annual accounting at New York's
City Hall. But it was also a highly political campaign speech for
his Senate race against the first lady, Hillary Rodham Clinton. The
mayor burnished his tax-cutting credentials by agreeing to push for
some $2 billion in business and income tax reductions to spur
economic growth. And he sought to distance himself from the city's
school crisis with proposals on privatization, vouchers and tenure
that might score points with the Republicans' core constituencies
but would cause more harm in the schools than good.
</P>
<P>
   With education stirring new passions nationwide, the mayor
showed his own intense feelings on the issue, heatedly complaining
at one point about the city's failure to educate vast numbers of
students each year. He called for an end to teacher tenure,
accusing the teachers' union, which supports Mrs. Clinton, of
caring more about job protection than schoolchildren. His proposal
could earn support, but such a plan might hamper the city's
nationwide recruiting program at a time when the system faces a
devastating shortage of teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also thumped for vouchers, a plan that wins support
from conservatives but serves only a few needs in a vastly needy
system like New York City's. A fight over the voucher issue has
already destabilized the school system once, and to reintroduce it
now, with new interim and permanent chancellors not even in place,
is needlessly provocative. Just as destabilizing is the mayor's
suggestion that private companies be used to conduct summer school
classes, which will have to serve 300,000 or more children who need
help this summer. Privatization would introduce a needless
complication into a task that has to be organized quickly by the
new interim chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor even announced plans to sell the city's big old school
administration building as a way to shrink the school bureaucracy,
a proposal that smacks more of posturing than of any serious effort
to reform school administration.
</P>
<P>
   Scorched by his latest policy of arresting the homeless, the
mayor tried once again to explain the complexity of treating a
population that includes not only criminals but also the needy and
the mentally ill. Giuliani promised to help convert the many
shelters now run by private or religious groups into ``New Start
Centers'' to give the homeless the various levels of help needed. A
new name, however, must come with the resolve to back these groups
with the funds to fulfill such a mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the mayor outlined tax cuts on commercial rents and
hotel occupancy, plus an income tax credit proposal that would have
widespread appeal. The plan must be weighed against future budget
gaps to be fully evaluated when a budget plan is released later
this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
