<HEADLINE>
CHOUINARD WIFE TELLS OF ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY FORD AND VICTORIA HARKER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Diamondbacks pitcher Bobby Chouinard's Christmas night
arrest for threatening to kill his wife was not the first time he
aimed a gun at his her during their turbulent 10-year relationship,
Erica Chouinard told police.
</P>
<P>
   In tape recorded interviews released Thursday, Jan. 13, Erica
Chouinard told police that her 27-year-old husband always had a
problem with his temper and often became physically abusive when he
drank.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been times when I think I've had broken ribs, times
where I've had more marks. I've taken punches to the stomach, more
slaps to the face. I've drawn blood on my lip,'' she told a Phoenix
police officer after her husband's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is the first time I can remember him actually loading
a gun, pointing it at me and threatening and threatening for more
than a second . . . I really actually thought he was going to beat
me, really, really bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Erica said the last time her husband aimed a gun at her was
about eight or nine months ago after he had been drinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got sent down from the major leagues to Triple A that day
and had some drinks and that night we got in a fight and he pointed
a gun at me,'' she told police. ``I can't even remember what we
were fighting about.''
</P>
<P>
   In a tape recording of Bobby Chouinard's police interview, which
was also made available to the media, he admitted pointing the
loaded weapon at his wife but told police he only meant ``to scare
her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I grabbed my gun, pointed it to my head and asked her if
that's what she wanted,`` he told the officers. ``She said `no.'
Then I pointed it at her and asked if that's what she wanted and
she said `no' and that's when I put it down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never intended on shooting her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Erica's interview with police, however, reveals a frightened
woman who was attacked, choked and slapped during a fight that
began when she refused to go out on Christmas night and buy her
husband more beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had both hands around my neck,'' she said, describing the
look on her husband's face as ``pure venom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said `stop, not in front of the baby, what are you doing? I
love you. . .' and he smacked me. It was an open-handed smack. He
slapped me and I started to cry.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a familiar Christmas scenario, Erica said. Exactly one
year earlier, her husband choked and slapped her as they argued on
Christmas Day, she told police.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, when her husband stormed into the bedroom to get
his gun, she was so afraid he would kill her that she dialed 911.
Moments later, her husband ripped the phone from the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I backed out of the room, got down on my hands and knees and
literally begged for my life,'' she told police. ``I was crying so
hard, begging so hard. I don't know what made him put the gun
away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was desperate. I was doing anything I could do so he
wouldn't shoot me,'' she told an investigator.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the alleged abuse, Christmas was the first time police
were called to the Chouinard house.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Jan. 13, Chouinard waived his right to appear in
court, where he was to face arraignment on aggravated assault
charges for the Christmas night attack.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Ronald Reinstein of Maricopa County Superior Court entered
a plea of innocent on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, the pitcher faces 5 to 15 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for both Erica and Bobby have said the two are back
together, in counseling and committed to keeping their marriage
together. It remains unclear whether she will testify against her
husband in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby, meanwhile, is working out with the Diamondbacks and
expects to participate in spring training, said his attorney, Larry
Debus.
</P>
<P>
   Neither husband nor wife could be reached for comment Thursday,
Jan. 13. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Beverly.Ford(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or at
(602) 444-8543. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 0024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
