<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD NIGHT TURNS BAD ON MURRAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Thursday night started out great for Glen Murray,
but it went south in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, a streaky goal scorer all season, got one 3:36 into the
game against St. Louis, just his second in the last 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   But minutes later, Murray was checked into the boards by the
Blues' Tyson Nash and injured his right shoulder. Murray went for
X-rays, which were negative, but he did receive a chest contusion
and did not return.
</P>
<P>
   Then between periods, there was a scoring change, giving Bryan
Smolinski the goal on a redirect of Murray's slap shot from the
slot.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, tied with Ziggy Palffy for second behind Luc Robitaille
with 14 goals, has been hot and cold most of the season. It started
during the first week when he was held to one assist in the first
six games then scored three goals at Edmonton on Oct. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Murray had his best stretch this year from Nov. 23 to Dec. 10
when he scored eight goals seven games. He had two goals in three
of those games.
</P>
<P>
   But until he scored an empty net goal Jan. 6 against Florida,
Murray went two games without a goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get more from him,'' coach Andy Murray said. ``We
need balanced scoring from the first and second lines and he is a
big part of that. He'll pick it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray, 27, scored a career-high 31 goals for the Kings during
the 1997-98 season. He dropped to 16 last year when he missed 19
games with a torn medial collateral in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you keep working hard, you will get your goals,'' Murray
said. ``When they aren't coming, you still can help your team by
doing the other things that help you win.''
</P>
<P>
   Snubbed: Kings right-winger Ziggy Palffy was not named to the
World team for the Feb. 6 All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy, who has missed four games since early December with a
sore lower back, has two goals since returning from injured
reserved on Dec. 14. He has missed two practices with flareups to
the back, but has remained the Kings leading scorer most of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy, who made the All-Star team two years ago when he played
with the New York Islanders, received 235,592 votes finished fourth
on the ballot to Pittsburgh's Jaromir Jagr (1,020,736), the Mighty
Ducks' Teemu Selanne (652,620) and Florida's Pavel Bure (435,161).
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he would have made it,'' general manager Dave Taylor
said. ``But the are some guys who made it that are hurt so
something might happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the forwards who made the team despite getting fewer votes
than Palffy: Calgary's Valeri Bure (235,095), Buffalo's Marovlav
Satan (160.301), St. Louis' Pavol Demitra (153,067), Carolina's
Sami Kapanen (100,596) and Montreal's Martin Rucinsky (49,266).
</P>
<P>
   Each team must have a representative in the game. Captain Rob
Blake will be the Kings' only representative. Last season, Blake
and Luc Robitaille played for North America. Mattias Norstrom
represented the World team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
