<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5826 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      01-14 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSED MERGER OF AOL, TIME WARNER IS MUCH ABOUT INTERNET MANIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Early investor reaction to the proposed merger of
America Online and Time Warner is the goofiest example yet of the
Internet stock mania.
</P>
<P>
   After the market had gotten over the shock of the announcement,
AOL's stock price came under pressure. One analyst said AOL chief
Steve Case's decision to acquire the Time Warner colossus implied
acknowledgement that his company's stock was worth $50 a share
rather than the $70-something it was fetching last week.
</P>
<P>
   How can this be? The corporate empires built by the respective
efforts of publishing magnate Henry Luce and the Warner Bros. movie
moguldom have been leaders in their industries during much of the
20th century. Together they have become a leading media
entertainment business.
</P>
<P>
   AOL is still in its infancy, but is nevertheless a dominant
Internet player. It owes its ability to buy Time Warner to the
fanciful valuations being given Internet companies by frenzied
speculators. AOL perceives the need for product, which Time Warner
has aplenty. It also needs entree into the millions of homes wired
to the Time Warner cable system. Time Warner perceives the need to
expand its distribution capability, and AOL brings millions of its
Internet customers to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   So if you're a rational being with a modest working knowledge of
traditional markets, what's not to like? AOL gets an established
corporation with tons of media and entertainment product; Time
Warner gets substantially more opportunity to market these wares.
How does this make AOL's stock worth less than when it was a
smaller, undiversified enterprise?
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to life in the wacky world of Internet stock
speculation. Last month a company with $14.5 million in losses on
revenue of about $18 million in the first nine months of 1999 saw
its publicly traded stock soar 700 percent on the same day it was
initially issued. The record eclipsed one set a year earlier by
another Internet company, which has since seen its stock price
crash and burn.
</P>
<P>
   The big question is whether AOL's stock price can remain high
enough long enough for the guppy to swallow the whale. Regulatory
approval could take 12 to 18 months; if AOL's stock decline
continues, the shares that are its currency could lose value to the
point of jeopardizing the deal.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal goes forward, however, it will mark the advent of a
new era in American business. It has always been a given that
Internet mania would run its course. Lucky speculators early to the
party with sense enough to leave before it's over will be the
richer for it. The latecomers will come to the same grief
latecomers always suffer when speculative craziness passes.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most apt analogy for today's Internet phenomenon is
what happened in the auto industry in the early 20th century.
Everyone knew there was a lot of money to be made from the new
technology, but most investment bets became losers during the
sorting-out process.
</P>
<P>
   For every General Motors, Ford and Chrysler, there were many
more start-ups that became investment croppers. AOL Time Warner may
prove the Internet industry's version of GM or Ford, while many
others will become the info-tech age's Hupmobile, Pierce-Arrow and
Stanley Steamer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
