<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5827 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-AOL-WORLDCOM-2NDTAKE-     01-14 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-WORLDCOM-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: lucrative business customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Large telecom carriers don't want the headaches of customer
service and call centers for small Internet users,'' said Joe
Eshoo, Internet analyst at A.G. Edwards. ``Sprint sold off its
residential customer base to Earthlink, and now acts as a
wholesaler. UUNet is also a wholesaler.''
</P>
<P>
   That may change.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the companies say the new WorldCom will
aggressively pursue residential customers. But the strategy to
blanket local markets with high bandwidth connections is still
piecemeal, relying on a hodgepodge of digital phone lines, fixed
wireless systems and possibly cable lines, if cable companies are
forced to open their networks to other competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say one effect of the AOL-Time Warner deal might be an
acceleration of all telephone companies' efforts to provide such
high-speed connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of these events creates more urgency in the
marketplace,'' Kagan said. ``It throws gasoline on the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   On the upside for the new WorldCom and competitors such as AT&AMP;T,
it could take years for AOL and Time Warner to figure out how to
digitize all of the content they own, put in software to deliver
it, upgrade their networks and figure out how to price the premium
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see that content will be the big driver in the future.
But how far in the future and how much is it going to cost?'' Eshoo
asked. ``There are economies of scale in delivering these services.
If you don't have enough potential customers out there, does it pay
to digitize the content?''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's Schell said the company had looked at the content
business for years but always concluded that ``content owners
maximize value by maximizing their distribution channels.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, AOL always will be looking for new customers and
will need to reach beyond the local networks that Time Warner owns,
cutting deals with other network providers to reach new markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get extraordinarily good at facilitating the
distribution of content,'' said Schell, downplaying the likelihood
that the new WorldCom would become a content provider.
</P>
<P>
   But the move toward content is already apparent. Sprint is
cutting deals almost weekly to bring news, information and
e-commerce content to its Sprint PCS Wireless Web service. And the
company talks about caching data for customers and hosting software
applications and servers on its Integrated On-Demand Network.
</P>
<P>
   That's content, analysts say, and it will only become more
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, this doesn't preclude a deal between AOL Time Warner
and MCI WorldCom,'' Kagan said. ``Put Steve Case (of AOL), Gerry
Levin (of Time Warner) and Bernie Ebbers together at a cocktail
party and we could have some serious mergers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebbers, whose company has completed 65 mergers since 1983,
hinted at the possibilities at Wednesday's news conference, albeit
jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed that AOL took Time Warner before we did,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
