<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-WORLDCOM-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AOL-TIME WARNER MERGER HAS PROFOUND IMPLICATIONS FOR THE NEW
WORLDCOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: The titans of telecommunications woke up Monday with a
new giant in their midst, one sending shock waves through an
industry already in upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts hailed the proposed combination of America
Online and Time Warner as the perfect marriage of new media and old
_ of content, customers and the high-tech networks to bring them
all together.
</P>
<P>
   This, many analysts concluded, is the shape of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``It confirms what the future is,'' said Peter Jarich of the
Strategis Group. ``This shows that you won't have traditional phone
companies. You'll have integrated media companies that do it all.''
</P>
<P>
   If true, the deal could have profound implications for the likes
of Sprint Corp. and MCI WorldCom Inc., whose planned merger was the
toast of media circles just two months ago but now sounds old hat.
</P>
<P>
   The new AOL Time Warner would control a vast collection of
entertainment and information, from movie and music libraries to
television channels and mainstream magazines. AOL has 20 million
online customers. Time Warner owns cable networks that pass 20
million homes, potentially with high-speed Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wake-up call for traditional telcos,'' said Jeanne
Schaaf, an analyst with Forrester Research. ``They're still
thinking about bundling local and long-distance service, and now
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this says is that content matters. Consumers don't want
pipes. They want what comes over the pipes.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, however, Sprint and MCI WorldCom say they're
delighted with the deal. Both companies say that, far from
undermining their deal, it validates the argument they are making
to regulators _ that only the strong will survive.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the National Press Club on Wednesday, MCI Chief
Executive Bernard Ebbers called the AOL-Time Warner deal ``a great
merger'' that would have wide implications for customers and his
corporation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to offer consumers some tremendous advantages they
haven't had before,'' he said. ``We view this as very positive for
MCI WorldCom.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Schell, senior vice president of strategic planning at
Sprint, echoed Ebbers' comments and downplayed the potential threat
from a new competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that Time Warner is a substantial player in the
cable industry,'' Schell said, ``but they really only run to a
small percentage of households in the U.S. ... This hasn't
transformed them overnight into a ubiquitous communications
provider.''
</P>
<P>
   If the respective deals make it past regulators, the AOL deal
clearly has implications for the new WorldCom. Investors sent a
clear message about the perceived consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The stock price of MCI WorldCom slipped 9.3 percent Tuesday,
partly on speculation that AOL _ MCI WorldCom's largest customer _
would no longer need the company's services.
</P>
<P>
   Customers who connect to AOL by dial-up modems do so over local
connections provided by MCI WorldCom's Internet division, UUNet.
MCI also provides AOL, the largest online service in the world,
with its connections to the Internet, known as Internet backbone
services.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to reporters' questions Wednesday, Ebbers said there
might be even greater demand for UUNet's services after the AOL
merger with Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We supply a lot of their capability of getting into homes, and
we feel this will provide them the capability of getting into a lot
more homes,'' Ebbers said. ``We are very excited about the
potential for that merger.''
</P>
<P>
   UUNet would lose out if AOL customers moved to Time Warner's
networks en masse to get their local connections through cable
modems. Those connections are 27 times faster than the dial-up
connections that UUNet provides.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts think that's unlikely, in the short run at least.
Internet users with high-speed connections are still in the
minority and are forecast to remain that way for the next two to
three years.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, AOL still would need a backbone provider to route its
customers onto the Internet. Ebbers said AOL was bound to a
long-term contract, though he wasn't specific.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a free world out there, and if they decide the service
they can get from someone else is better than they can get from us,
we deserve to lose it,'' Ebbers said. ``I can assure you we don't
intend to lose it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the new WorldCom eventually could find itself facing a
potent competitor in its traditional business _ networks _
particularly in areas where Time Warner owns cable networks.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner has 13 million customers and passes 20 million
homes, and is quickly upgrading its cable lines to provide
high-speed Internet service to customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a definite first-mover advantage,'' said Jeffrey
Kagan, an independent communications consultant. ``When a customer
signs up for a bundle of services with high-speed access, they're
not switching any time soon. The expense and the hassle is too
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the company also could provide local telephone
service over its cable networks. AOL is already a large reseller of
long-distance service and might start taking even more market share
when it can bundle that service with local and Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy enough for the combined company to add voice
services,'' Schaaf said. ``In places where Time Warner has a
footprint, (competitors) almost have to say, `Forget it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint and MCI are big dogs in long-distance, but they are
struggling to connect their vast web of fiber to customers in local
markets. Neither company is a big Internet provider to residential
customers. Instead, they act as wholesalers to smaller providers
and concentrate their efforts to sell data services to more
lucrative business customers. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
