r a BC-DWI-LAW-KAN &LR;      01-14 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DWI-LAW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR PROPOSES TOUGHENING MISSOURI'S DRUNKEN-DRIVING LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT CAMPBELL AND WILL SENTELL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan on Thursday called
for wholesale changes in the state's drunken-driving laws that
would lower the intoxication limit to 0.08 percent blood-alcohol
content and increase penalties for offenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lives are lost every day in this ultimate act of
carelessness,'' the Democratic governor said in Kansas City, vowing
to work hard to pass the package this legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Democratic leaders in Jefferson City on Thursday
outlined their own legislative agenda, and lowering the definition
of intoxication from 0.1 percent to 0.08 percent was absent.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan said he was disappointed but optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we've got to put some pressure on the
legislature, particularly the Senate, to accept and pass these
measures,'' he said. ``But I believe that we're within range of
doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mothers Against Drunk Driving reacted warmly to Carnahan's plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am gratified to see the list (of reforms) is as long as it
is,'' said Paula Kanyo, state director. ``I think there is going to
be a lot of people making this part of the agenda whether the
Democratic senators have it on their list or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan announced his plans in Kansas City and cited the
findings of The Kansas City Star. The newspaper last month reported
that Kansas City leads Missouri in alcohol-related accidents, the
number of repeat drunken drivers and the number of repeat offenders
with 10 or more convictions.
</P>
<P>
   And Missouri ranked worse than all but nine states and
Washington, D.C., in 1998 in the percentage of traffic fatalities
that are alcohol-related.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Carnahan was flanked by Jackson County
Prosecutor Bob Beaird, Kansas City Municipal Prosecutor Roger
Potter and Kansas City Police Chief Rick Easley.
</P>
<P>
   Beaird said he was pleased with the governor's package,
particularly a provision that would allow greater penalties for
involuntary manslaughter while driving drunk. The current maximum
of seven years would increase to 15.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's plan also would double the maximum penalty for
first offenders to one year in jail and create a possible life
sentence for people with more than five convictions.
</P>
<P>
   It would ban open alcohol containers for passengers in vehicles.
It would end suspension of sentences, which can conceal a drunken
driver's record.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan also supports penalties up to five years in prison for
people with a blood-alcohol content of 0.15 percent or greater. The
Missouri Highway Patrol reports more than two-thirds of
alcohol-related fatalities in Missouri in 1998 involved drivers at
that level.
</P>
<P>
   And he would extend drunken-driving laws to boaters on Missouri
lakes and rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan emphasized that lowering the state's intoxication level
to 0.08 _ as 17 other states including Kansas have done _ would
make the state eligible for up to $5 million in federal highway
incentives.
</P>
<P>
   But Carnahan's plan does not include two other provisions that
could avoid a cut of millions of dollars in federal highway
construction money: impoundment or immobilization of offenders'
vehicles and mandatory minimum penalties for repeat offenders.
Although his plan increases the range of penalties, judges still
would be able to grant probation or early release.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan said he was focusing on the incentive money available
for adopting a 0.08 intoxication limit.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan's efforts have support in the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Craig Hosmer and Rep. Mike Schilling, both Democrats of
Springfield, will push Carnahan's package in the House. Sen. Wayne
Goode, a Democrat of St. Louis County, has introduced an
``aggravated offender'' bill raising penalties for repeat offenders
with a 0.15 blood-alcohol content or higher.
</P>
<P>
   But other elements in the governor's plan appear to face major
hurdles in the Senate, which has been a stumbling block for years
in drunken-driving legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Key Senate leaders sounded lukewarm to the 0.08 percent plan
Thursday when they unveiled their priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Goode, who Carnahan hopes will support his package, on Thursday
complained that the 0.08 issue seems to have become a ``litmus
test'' for lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Pro Tem Ed Quick, a Liberty Democrat,
questioned whether the 0.08 proposal would address problem
drinkers. Passing the measure might make people think lawmakers had
done more on the alcohol problem than they really did, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most outspoken supporters of the 0.08 bill are
Republicans, including GOP sponsor Sen. Morris Westfall of Halfway.
He said he plans to push hard this year for a floor vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an election year I feel confident if we vote on it, it will
have (the necessary) 18 votes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan, a lame-duck governor who is challenging incumbent John
Ashcroft for his U.S. Senate seat this year, conceded it would be
difficult to get his package through the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is hard work,'' he said. ``This is going to take lobbying
efforts by me and other interested people in order to make
change.''
</P>
<P>
   The 0.08 percent bill is SB578 (Westfall); Open-container bill
is SB579 (Westfall). Legislation is available on the Missouri
General Assembly site on the Internet at the following address:
www.moga.state.mo.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 0053EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
