<HEADER>
A5830 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-MISSOURI-RIVER-KAN &LR;      01-14 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSOURI-RIVER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OFFICIALS RELEASE NEW PLAN TO CONTROL MISSOURI RIVER FLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Hoping to end decades of squabbling, federal
officials Thursday released a new plan to control flow of the
Missouri River from Montana to its mouth near St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The plan offered by the Army Corps of Engineers would maintain
enough water during times of drought to keep barges afloat on the
lower Missouri _ but not for the duration that Missouri officials
or the barge industry had sought.
</P>
<P>
   It offers a few more feet of water in the upper river's six main
reservoirs. That might help keep marinas and docks from being left
far from the water's edge, as they were during the drought of the
late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very big step,'' said Richard Opper, executive
director of the Missouri River Basin Association. ``It's about as
close as you can get to a plan that people can live with.''
</P>
<P>
   Some interests on the river will say it doesn't go far enough,
Opper added. Others will say it goes too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this plan will win some support,'' Opper said. ``The last
time, the corps didn't get any support.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan would not allow summertime flows to dwindle along the
lower river. With flows maintained, the navigation season would not
be split. And it doesn't promise to restore a spring rise in the
lower river's flow during drought, one of the most contentious
proposals for the river's future operation.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers in Missouri and other downstream states worry that a
spring rise would threaten crops. But environmentalists say that
the corps must do it to return endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   ``This plan does nothing substantive for endangered species,''
said Chad Smith of American Rivers, a national river conservation
group. ``The fate of the Missouri River is assuredly going to end
up in the hands of a federal judge.''
</P>
<P>
   American Rivers and the Environmental Defense Fund have
threatened to file a federal lawsuit if the corps doesn't restore
the river's flows to more natural rates.
</P>
<P>
   Restoring backwater areas, such as chutes and swamps, will help
fish and wildlife. But the endangered species won't return until
natural flows are restored, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   But corps officials were optimistic about their new plan's
chances for winning support and approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's considerable consensus and support for this,'' said
Paul Johnston, a spokesman for the corps in Omaha, Neb. ``If this
(revising the river's operation) is going to happen, this is the
time to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The corps plan released Thursday would not be implemented before
2002. The corps plans a series of workshops and public meetings
throughout the basin and a six-month public comment period.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the corps will release its draft environmental impact
statement, which will give more details on the new flow plan and
its impacts.
</P>
<P>
   The corps began in 1989 to revise its Master Manual, which
dictates the river's flows. Those flows are controlled largely by
six main dams, operated like giant bathtubs from which the corps
can hold water upstream or increase flows downstream.
</P>
<P>
   Upstream states pressured the corps to revise the river's
operation because of the drought of the late 1980s. Five years
later, the recommendations from the corps were met with so much
criticism that it withdrew its plan and started anew.
</P>
<P>
   Corps officials Thursday said their plan benefits from the
recent efforts of the basin association to broker an agreement
among its member states on flows during drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at the MRBA (basin association) as a grass-roots
operation,'' Johnston said. ``We've got really wide support for
their recommendations. Even though Missouri was not in support of
the basin association's plans, they were in support of most of the
recommendations.''
</P>
<P>
   In November, Missouri representatives to the basin association
declined to join the other association states in recommending a new
flow plan to the corps. Missouri wanted more water assured during
drought for the barge industry.
</P>
<P>
   The corps also hoped that the plan would withstand any legal or
regulatory challenges of the corps efforts to restore endangered
fish and wildlife in the Missouri basin, Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
   The corps and the basin association point to new efforts to help
the endangered piping plover and interior least tern, which like to
nest on sandbars and sandy shores, and the prehistoric pallid
sturgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to restore the sturgeon in the corps plan are restricted
to changes in flow below Fort Peck Dam in Montana, although other
federal efforts are under way to restore more backwater chutes and
swamps in the lower basin.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan and Kansas Gov. Bill
Graves said the governors had yet to review the new plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 0055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0017 </DOCNO>
