<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5840 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     01-14 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODDBALL SONICS AREN'T ALL THAT BAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A week or so ago, one of my Queen Anne dog-walking
friends asked a ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire'' question
regarding the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of Gary Payton and maybe Vin Baker, who are these
guys?'' was the basic gist.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Seahawks' faux playoff run had kept people in the dark
regarding the city's once superhyped NBA squad.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the league-wide, Post-Jordan, post-lockout identity
crisis was simply making it tough for otherwise good-intentioned
Seattle sports fans to get a handle on these Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   Not that they're alone.
</P>
<P>
   All across the country, NBA arenas are featuring plenty of empty
seats. Red ones. Orange ones. Green ones. Blue ones.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics have had just one sellout so far this season. That
was the first Laker game, which turned into an embarrassing blowout
with a crew that didn't yet include Kobe ``Air Part II'' Bryant,
who was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices are higher at KeyArena this season, thank you very
much, as they are elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   And in living rooms and dens across the nation, TV sets have
been tuning into fewer NBA games this season.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, news that Michael Jordan is joining the sinking
Wizards' ship has Beltway ballhogs salivating, they're so
desperate.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, an answer to the dog-walker's question included a list
of names that make up the Sonic roster: Horace Grant, Brent Barry,
Ruben Patterson, Greg Foster, Rashard Lewis, Vernon Maxwell,
Emanual Davis, Shammond Williams, Chuck Person, Jelani McCoy, Fred
Vinson, Vladimir Stepania and Lazaro Borrell.
</P>
<P>
   But the answer didn't clear things up much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, what's the identity of this team?'' the dog-walking
former Sonic enthusiast insisted. ``Who are they and where do they
think they're going?''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help matters much that the Sonics were mired in a
five-game losing streak at that particular time. The bad patch of
road was pocked with a few minor but notable outbursts, one by
Baker and another by Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   Both were frustrated with their roles and both made no bones
about letting head coach Paul Westphal know it, to which Westphal
apparently assured both players that their fates were in their own
hands.
</P>
<P>
   From the outside, the Sonics' serious little skid had all the
earmarks of a team dangerously close to sliding into the proverbial
tank.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, exactly one year to the week since the end of the 1999
lockout, the Sonics are pleasantly discovering that this season,
time is on their side.
</P>
<P>
   The rolling nature of a bonafide 82-game season is giving the
Sonics time to make adjustments and get the most out of an almost
all-new roster still looking to figure out its identity.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, a hodgepodge team culled together in the frantic
free-agent aftermath of last year's 50-game nutball season, the
Sonics are now riding a three-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been a six-game winning streak, except that after
beating San Antonio for a nice upset and then the Rockets, the
Sonics were whiplashed again by the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully for them, though, the follow-up work has been
encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   Wins over Golden State (barely) the Suns and Nuggets had the
Sonics acting giddy and loose during practice Thursday _ even in
the face of Friday night's rematch against the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   For a team no one can quite get a handle on, including
themselves, the Sonics have to get some credit for continuing to
try and work it all out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think by the time the last month of the season comes around,
it's going to be like the playoffs,'' Baker said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be a lot of teams scrapping and fighting to
make it. That's why all these road wins we collect are going to add
up.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Sonics, the prediction amongst most local soothsayers,
including the Queen Anne dog walker, was 40 to 45 wins. Tops. And
if they made the playoffs, it would be as a No. 8 seed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a worst-case scenario shows that the Sonics could go 22-24
over the last 46 games and still fulfill everyone's meager
expectations, although there still could be a playoff dogfight
between everyone in the West who isn't the Lakers and the Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, after the Lakers, Blazers, Spurs, Heat, Jazz, Knicks
and Pacers, the Sonics are in a mid-tier bubble with the likes of
Sacramento, Charlotte, Minnesota, Phoenix and Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   After that, there are still 16 other clubs, including 1999
playoff teams like the Sixers and Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   Odd as it may seem, for a team that seems to lack a
distinguishable personality, the Sonics are still wondrously ahead
of two-thirds of the rest of the league.
</P>
<P>
   We're not sure exactly what that says about the post-lockout,
post-Jordan NBA. Maybe it will wind up meaning that the Sonics are
one of the best dozen or so teams in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Or, perhaps as likely, it will reveal that other than the
Blazers, Lakers, Spurs and Heat, the NBA is just totally whacked.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
