<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, Jan. 14.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Argun) _ The Russian military insists it has
taken back this Chechen town. But Russian soldiers nervously
scanned the rooftops and windows of Argun's battered buildings as
they sought to keep order. Set in the Chechen lowlands, Argun was
taken by the Russian military in early December. Today, however, it
has become a salient example of how hard it may be for Russia to
take Chechnya and keep it. All across Chechnya, Russian troops
tried to tighten their grip over the swath of territory
``liberated'' by Russian forces. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SAHARA-VILLAGE (Araouane, Mali) _ The sand woman came out of the
blackness of the village master's house into the desert light,
bearing a bowl of sand her hands had scooped from the doorway and
would deposit several feet away. It is a lifetime's work, this
struggle against the sand, for Souda Cissey and Araouane's other
sand women, a daily contest to prevent the Sahara from burying,
once and for all, this ancient village in West Africa. The world's
largest desert has already taken away a mosque and countless houses
in recent years, the rooftops of some still visible on the sand's
surface, others fallen into the Sahara's bottomless pits. By
Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ANTIMISSILE-TEST (Undated) _ A critical test of an interceptor
designed to destroy ballistic warheads, hailed as a success when it
took place last Oct. 2, may not have been such a clear-cut
demonstration that antimissile technology is feasible, critics of
the effort say. Exclusive. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OLD-BLACKHOLES (Atlanta) _ In a discovery that could help
explain the origin of the earliest galaxies, a new astronomy
satellite has detected the first discret objects in a mysterious
glow of X-rays that pervades the distant universe. By John Noble
Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   TV-DRUGS-SCRIPTS (Undated) _ The White House drug office has
secretly been pushing TV networks for scripts with anti-drug
messages, and for at least a year has been helping edit the scripts
on selected shows. The White House provided millions of dollars of
financial incentives to networks to make sure the scripts were on
message. By Marc Lacey and Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-MINORITIES (Undated) _ For the first time, the
proportion of AIDS cases among black and Hispanic gay men exceeds
those among white gay men, federal health officials report. By
Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PRIMATE-EMBRYOS (Undated) _ Scientists in Oregon have
divided an eight cell monkey embryo into quarters, creating
identical quadruplet embryos. One of them survived and resulted in
the birth of a baby monkey. But the results do did not achieve
nearly the success that was accomplished with other animals. By
Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-OUTLOOK (Perry, Iowa) _ Over the years, the Iowa caucuses
have made some presidential candidates (like Jimmy Carter) and
unmade others (like Edward M. Kennedy). But this time, they have
seemed like a sideshow, and a poorly attended one at that, to the
main event in New Hampshire. That may be changing. With only 10
days left until Feb. 24, when tens of thousands of Iowans will
assemble in living rooms, clubs and school halls to declare their
preferences, two well-funded, well-organized underdogs, Bill
Bradley and Steve Forbes, have accelerated their efforts. If not to
defeat their respective rivals, Al Gore and George W. Bush, they
hope to come very close _- close enough to give them a lift as they
move to New Hampshire, whose critical primary takes place only
eight days later on Feb. 1. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DRUGS _ Drug company executives asked the White House on
Thursday for a cease-fire in their war over drug prices and said
unequivocally that they wanted to work with President Clinton and
Congress to establish Medicare coverage of prescription drugs this
year. Exclusive. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-INVEST (Undated) _ For almost a year, Internet
companies have had a sweet ride from investors, public and private,
willing to accept enormous losses on promises of great future
returns. But signs indicate that the climate of unlimited
forgiveness is changing, that imagined future earnings may not
justify sky-high stock prices. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT grahics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   UTILITIES-NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ It has long been taken for
granted that utility stocks always fall when interest rates rise.
After all, electric companies borrow a lot of money, and thus
suffer when rates rise, and their shares appeal only to the
diminishing band of investors who value dividends. So it is worth
asking why the stocks are rising. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ A significant step toward
bringing Madison Avenue and Hollywood closer together. By Stuart
Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLLINS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Gail Colllins on the perfect
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Thomas L. Friedman offers an
imaginary letter to President Clinton from President Assad's heir
apparant, his son Bashir.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN (New York) _ Sports of The Times column on
owners and billionaires, and why, when it comes to the Jets, we
prefer Good Old Woody, the heir, over Dolan, the ruler of a
corporate empire. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-MATCHUPS (Undated) _ How the survirors match up for this
weekend's NFL playoff games. By Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEKEND (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PERIOD-ROOMS (New York) _ Period rooms. Loosely defined, we all
live in them, don't we? Any one of our current abodes might be a
period room of tomorrow, a specimen of the as yet uncrystallized
turn-of-the-21st-century period style. But of course, loose is not
what's under discussion here. For an authentic period room you have
to leave your own fledgling interior and visit a major museum; in
New York this means going to the Metropolitan Museum of Art and the
Brooklyn Museum of Art. With roughly 80 period rooms between them,
they represent the greatest concentration to be found in any
American city. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-YORK-LIGHT (New York) _ Two years ago, Joe, the man I lived
with, suggested that we outfit our apartment with a light
especially created to combat the winter blues. Seasonal affective
disorder is its quaint moniker. I vetoed the proposal. What I
wanted was not to sit under 10,000 lux of white light to trick my
brain into believing it was spring. I wanted us to soak up the real
stuff, the unadorned light of the New York Harbor at sunset, say,
or the slow illumination of the city on a Sunday morning. Joe isn't
here anymore. He went hiking up a mountain one day last summer. It
is believed that he slipped and fell in the woods. Bloodhounds and
rescue teams were sent for him. But the forest is so dark and
dense, his body is yet to be found. This winter, with unusual
deliberation, I have taken to soaking up the light alone, or mostly
alone. I troll for outings that promise birds and sunsets on
Jamaica Bay in Queens. I bundle up for lunchtime sprints around
Bryant Park in Manhattan to watch how the windows of the library
spit out the sun's reflection. Unwittingly I have turned into a
student of light. The August light that envelopes the beaten-down
old streets of Red Hook, I have learned, is more melancholy than
the morning light during lilac season in the Brooklyn Botanic
Garden. The sun sparkling on the crown of the Chrysler building is
whimsical, like a woman dressed for a party at high noon. By Somini
Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH-NEW-YORK (New York) _ The minimum requirement for Le
Weekend New Yorkais was about as basic as a crusty baguette. My
French husband and I yearned for a Manhattan with a Gallic accent _
a bistro perhaps where a petit caniche begs for sugar cubes below a
polished bar, or a brasserie where the mood is casual, the air is
more smoke than oxygen and the frites are served with mustard and
the songs of Serge Gainsbourg. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
