<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5844 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-COLTS-MANNING-HNS     01-14 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLTS-MANNING-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
With any legend, it is difficult to separate fact from fiction, but
in the state of Tennessee, some insist that Peyton Manning is more
popular than Davy Crockett and more influential than Al Gore.
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it weren't for Elvis, Manning would be king of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Manning is an icon in the eastern part of the state because of
his football heroics at the University of Tennessee. There is a
street named after him in Knoxville, where he is more revered than
Johnny Majors and Doug Dickey.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's loyalties are divided this week because the Titans,
who have become the hottest thing in Nashville, are playing
Manning's Indianapolis Colts in a second-round playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's an interesting story for the fans and media,
but nobody on the Titans cares where I went to college, and nobody
on the Colts does, either,'' Manning said Thursday. ``I really
don't have much to add to that whole scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to my first playoff game, and I am glad
the game's at home.''
</P>
<P>
   The Manning/Tennessee story line would be more intriguing if the
game were being played at Adelphia Coliseum, site of the Music City
Miracle, where the Titans sold out every game and posted a 9-0
record, including their wild-card victory over Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if his friends in Tennessee became Titans fans this
season, Manning said, ``Oh, sure. People in Tennessee have really
adopted the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, you've seen how many teams struggled at their home
field because of the crowd noise. The crowd really got into it. So
a lot of my friends have become major Titans fans. That's a good
thing. That's the way it's supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing at home, and I'm certainly glad about that. We
need the advantage of playing in front of our home crowd. You saw
the Tennessee-Buffalo game. Tennessee's crowd was definitely an
advantage for them and gave Buffalo problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an NFL playoff game, and I can't worry about all the
other scenarios and stories dealing with the game. All I can do is
to try to help my team win.''
</P>
<P>
   Just imagine: Peyton Manning a villain in his adopted state. It
could never happen, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Manning is beloved in Tennessee for several reasons. First, he
left Louisiana, his home state, for a rival. Second, he didn't
attend Mississippi, the alma mater of his famous father, Archie
Manning, despite tremendous pressure to do so from people outside
his family. Third, even though he earned his degree in three years,
he passed up the NFL as an underclassman to return for his senior
year. And, finally, Manning is popular because he is a genuine
first-class guy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, when the Titans were still the Oilers, they got an idea
of just how popular Manning was in Tennessee. In his rookie season,
there was a major controversy when the CBS affiliate in Knoxville
elected to show Colts games over Oilers games when there was a
conflict. That policy still exists, but there were fewer conflicts
this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessean, Nashville's newspaper of record, conducted a
survey to find out if it is true that fans around the state,
especially in the eastern part, are pulling for Manning. The
results of the survey showed that fans want the Titans to win, but
they hope Manning will play well and stay healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something I really can't get into,'' Manning said.
``I'm sure the people in Tennessee are going to cheer for the
Titans because that's their team and that's the way they should do
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'm focusing on is just this game. I know it's boring. I'd
like to help you with your story, but I don't have much to add to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But others do. Take Titans tight end Frank Wycheck, for
instance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great story for the media, isn't it?'' Wycheck said.
``You guys can write about Peyton all week. That'll sure be a
change for us.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has to tell the Titans how respected Manning is in their
state or how good he is in any state in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great quarterback who's done an outstanding job in only
his second season,'' Titans offensive tackle Brad Hopkins said.
``You won't see many second-year quarterbacks play like Manning
does. It's like he's a 10-year veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can make every throw. He's hard to sack because he knows
when to get rid of the ball. He utilizes all of his weapons. We
know we've got our work cut out.''
</P>
<P>
   And the feeling is mutual. In truth, Sunday afternoon at the RCA
Dome in Indianapolis, the state of Tennessee won't be on Manning's
mind. He couldn't care less about who is rooting for him and who
isn't. He will enter the game with one goal _ to win.
</P>
<P>
   And to win, the Colts know they have to protect Manning from the
fierce Titans pass rush that has produced 60 sacks in 17 games,
including 16{ by defensive end Jevon Kearse, the NFL Defensive
Rookie of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a very active front seven,'' Manning said. ``They
rush the passer well. They're good against the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this stage, there's not much you can change. We're going to
try to run our offense. The Titans have won a lot of big games.
They've seen a lot of things. We have to execute very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Titans, the Colts have a lot of young players. This is
the first playoff experience for many of the Colts, and there could
be some nervousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's probably some truth to that,'' Manning said. ``I mean,
for a lot of us, this is the first playoff game we're in, and the
first playoff game at home for everybody here with the Colts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of been this way all season. We don't know any
better than to treat every game as if it's the most important game.
That's why we've played well the majority of the season. A playoff
game's certainly different. It's going to be more intense. It's
going to be faster. Hopefully, we can rise to the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
