<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5851 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN     01-14 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS POWERLESS TO STOP BLUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Kings know they can play with the better teams
in the National Hockey League. Now they have to find a way to win.
</P>
<P>
   After getting riddled with penalties two nights earlier, the
Kings again were beaten by the power play Thursday night, this time
on a third-period goal by Scott Young that gave the St. Louis Blues
a 3-2 victory in front of 16,278 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The key call was a questionable hit by Kings defenseman Sean
O'Donnell on Scott Pellerin that set up the man advantage.
</P>
<P>
   With 6:35 gone in the final period, Blues defenseman Al MacInnis
fired from the blue line and Thomas redirected the puck past Kings
goaltender Stephan Fiset for the winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   Hot teams get those calls and the Blues certainly are that,
unbeaten in their past eight games. The loss was the Kings' second
straight and ninth in the past 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   Also lost in the loss were two goals by Bryan Smolinski, who
leads the team with 38 points. Smolinski scored the game's first
goal less than four minutes in, then tied it at 2-2 with 29 seconds
left in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were coming off a sloppy 4-3 loss to Ottawa and facing
probably the hottest team in the league in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues were undefeated in their past seven (5-0-2) and had at
least four goals in each of those victories.
</P>
<P>
   They embarrassed San Jose last Tuesday without their top player,
Pierre Turgeon, who returned for the Kings game.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem with the Blues right now is they play in the
Central Division, which has been dominated by Detroit the past few
years. St. Louis entered Thursday's game with 58 points, just one
behind the Red Wings. But with division winners getting the first
three seeds, that puts the Blues fourth in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   For the Kings, who questioned team discipline in a meeting
Tuesday with coach Andy Murray and the team captains, Thursday
could have been a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the Ottawa game, where they were undone by penalties
and poor performances by Fiset and defenseman Aki Berg, the Kings
were sharp.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset was back in net for the ninth consecutive game. Jamie
Storr, sidelined since mid-December with a concussion, will play
tonight for the minor league Long Beach Ice Dogs and hopes to be
ready for the Kings game Saturday night in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Berg, who played a role in three of the four Ottawa goals, was
scratched Thursday, a move that drew cheers from the crowd. His
replacement, Garry Galley, returned from injured reserve after
missing a month with a concussion and assisted on Smolinski's
second goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings took a 1-0 lead just 3:36 into the game. At first, it
appeared to come on a goal by Glen Murray, who took a pass from Luc
Robitaille in the slot and fired a slap shot that sailed past the
left shoulder of McLennan.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been just the second goal in 13 games for Murray,
who had a scoreless string of 10. But after the first period, the
goal was credited to Smolinski, who redirected Murray's blast for
his goal of the night.
</P>
<P>
   While things got better for Smolinski, they got worse for
Murray. Just minutes after his apparent goal, he was knocked into
the board by the Blues' Tyson Nash. Murray suffered a bruised chest
muscle and did not return.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings controlled the action until the end of the period when
the Blues scored twice in the final 2:37.
</P>
<P>
   The first goal came when Jamal Mayers beat Sean O'Donnell to the
puck at the Kings' blue line and blew in on Fiset for his third
goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   With just 1:11 left in the period, St. Louis took the lead.
Pavol Demitra fired a slap shot from the Kings' blue line that was
well wide of Fiset. But Lubos Baretcko redirected the shot past
Fiset for his 10th goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 0144EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
