<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
PARTNERSHIP HELPS ESTABLISH GM ONLINE
</HEADLINE>
 BC- -LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jason Z.Cohen  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES, Calif., -- In a deal that could generate $100
million in revenue over the next four years, free Internet service
provider NetZero Inc. has formed a marketing partnership with
General Motors Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement calls for General Motors to be the exclusive
automotive sponsor of NetZero's Internet portal. In a few weeks,
NetZero will place a ``speed dial'' button on the ZeroPort that
takes users directly to the GM Buypower Web site.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors, which has a similar arrangement with the
nation's largest Internet service provider, America Online, will
distribute NetZero connection software in its dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   And the giant automaker will receive a gold mine of data in
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very excited. What's really unique is that the GM
agreement takes advantage of every revenue product that NetZero
offers,'' said Mark Goldston, NetZero's chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   NetZero, based in suburban Los Angeles' Westlake Village, will
revise its membership survey to include questions on customers' car
buying habits and other automotive preferences.
</P>
<P>
   NetZero subscribers fill out the survey when they first connect
to the service and again at regular intervals throughout their
membership.
</P>
<P>
   David Cooperstein, an analyst with Forrester Research who
follows General Motors' Internet initiatives, said the automaker
has been working hard to establish itself as a player in the online
world.
</P>
<P>
   The deal gives newcomer NetZero the credibility of an industrial
institution such as General Motors, Cooperstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For GM, it's a way of generating interest in the GM brand for
the Internet users or communicating with their existing
customers,'' he said. ``Clearly, I think this will be the year that
a lot of traditional brand advertisers wake up to the Net.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal also benefits both parties because it goes well beyond
banner advertising and ventures into the sharing of customer
information, Cooperstein said.
</P>
<P>
   While General Motors' deal with America Online benefits General
Motors in giving it a large Internet presence, the NetZero
partnership gives the automaker a presence and access to valuable
customer information, Cooperstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advertising angle is only half the story,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, General Motors will receive a warrant to purchase
575,000 shares of NetZero stock at $28.71 per share, a total
investment of $16.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The warrant is effective through the four-year life of the deal,
Goldston said.
</P>
<P>
   It allows General Motors a chance to take equity in a growing
company, said Mark Hogan, president of e-GM, the Internet division
of General Motors, which was formed in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that NetZero has some growth opportunity,'' Hogan
said. ``Perhaps GM can participate in that growth in some way, and
that's the reason behind this.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 0202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5872 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-TERRY-LUMBER-LADN     01-14 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRY-LUMBER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH FIRM BUYS VALLEY COMPANY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Chris Sieroty  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TARZANA Family-owned Terry Industries, a lumber company that
helped supply the San Fernando Valley's post-World War II building
boom, has been sold to a North Carolina company, officials said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal, which closed Jan. 7, were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a well-managed, well-run and profitable company,''
said Bryce Smith, spokesman Carolina Holdings Inc. of Raleigh,
N.C., a wholly owned subsidiary of Wolseley PLC, based in
Droitwich, England. ``We like companies like Terry Industries.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tarzana-based building materials company operates 14 Terry
Lumber Co. yards from Burbank to Bakersfield. The company also
operates three hanging door facilities, a lumber distribution
center and one mill-work plant.
</P>
<P>
   Company founder Terry Mullin, 78, said the decision to sell was
made before his son Tom died in July. The sale is ``in the best
interest of the family, the company and its employees,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it to be sold while I'm still active,'' added Mullin.
``I didn't want it sold by a bunch of bankers who don't understand
the lumber business. We are very happy with Carolina Holdings.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mullin family invested $6,000 to open its first lumberyard
in Tarzana in December 1949.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a good 50 years,'' Mullin said. ``I love the lumber
business, our customers and suppliers.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the company's name will remain the same. Lonnie
Schield will also remain company president, and none of the 735
employees is expected to be laid off at this point.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin doesn't plan many changes, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will remain active in the business to the extent they would
like me to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With sales of about $250 million last year, Terry Industries is
one of the top suppliers of building materials to the contractor
trade in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``They service builders and contractors, which is the focus of
our business,'' Smith said. ''All their manufacturing, including
their mill-work plant, supports that business.''
</P>
<P>
   Yossi Sayas, owner of Woodland Hills-based Lifetime Construction
Co., said he has shopped at Terry Lumber Co. for 10 years and would
continue to buy his doors and windows for his clients at any of its
locations.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Holdings last month purchased Columbia Lumber Co. of
Columbia, S.C, and McGinnes Lumber Supply in Plant City, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   With its recent acquisitions, Carolina Holdings now operates
more than 150 locations in 15 states and is one of the largest
suppliers of lumber and building materials in the nation. The
company reported sales of $1.7 billion for the fiscal year that
ended July 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 0203EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5873 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-LAKERS-JACKSON-HN     01-14 1343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-JACKSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
LOS ANGELES _ Maybe we shouldn't be surprised.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe the Lakers would be coasting along, owners of a 31-5
record and a 16-game winning streak, no matter who was coaching.
And maybe anyone could have gotten Shaquille O'Neal to make offense
secondary, instead having the colorful colossus focus on defense
and rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   But not many coaches could have O'Neal saying things like: ``I'm
like the Pythagorean theorem. Not a lot of people can figure out
the Pythagorean theorem ,'' or, ``He leads; we follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many at all.
</P>
<P>
   Only one comes to mind _ Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   And that's where you gauge Jackson's impact on the Lakers.
Forget the numbers they put up, the outrageous win totals and the
unending string of highlight-quality plays.
</P>
<P>
   No, these Lakers are not only playing the game, they're thinking
it as well, and that's where Jackson has made the biggest
difference.
</P>
<P>
   With players such as O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and Glen Rice, the
Lakers always had been able to rise to a physical challenge. But a
mental challenge was something else. Enter Jackson, the third man
in less than a year to coach the Lakers, following Del Harris and
Kurt Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm scared of the Lakers,'' said Portland's Damon Stoudamire.
``They're a load. Phil Jackson has been coaching there for only two
months, and they're playing the way they're playing. That man
doesn't even get off the bench anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say he will be there awhile. The Lakers have found
their man.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was the Lakers always figured they needed a coach
who was essentially young at heart. That's what led them to Harris,
who might have looked like a fuddy-duddy college professor but who
lived the life of a much younger man, getting his first tattoo at
age 60 and listening to rap.
</P>
<P>
   But after a series of crash-and-burn performances in the
playoffs, including last year's wipeout at the hands of the San
Antonio Spurs, the Lakers realized they had it wrong all along.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't require a coach who was young at heart. What they
needed was someone who was Jung at heart _ someone who had a grasp
of basketball and who had a helpful dose of Jungian psychology.
</P>
<P>
   In short, they needed Jackson, one of the few coaches who has
gotten maximum production (with a minimum of distractions) from
Dennis Rodman, no small reason the Bulls were able to win their
last three titles.
</P>
<P>
   And if Jackson could get Rodman to devote himself to team play,
then the Lakers would be a cakewalk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be honest _ I felt that after nine years of doing it with
the Bulls I felt like I had had enough,'' Jackson said. ``But after
being away a year, I felt like it would be fun to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has his biggest ally _ literally and figuratively _ in
O'Neal, who dropped in on his new coach before the season started.
O'Neal, in Montana to give a rap concert, figured the least he
could do was surprise Jackson with a visit to his log cabin in
Kalispell.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal wanted to feel out his new coach, so he spent the day
doing things like bouncing on the trampoline with Jackson's
children. He then went to karaoke night with Jackson's wife, June,
and sang _ if you can call it that _ I Believe I Can Fly into the
microphone.
</P>
<P>
   But all O'Neal remembered was what he first saw in the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as you walk through the front door, you see those big
gold balls _ all six of 'em,'' he said, referring to replicas of
the championship trophies Jackson won with the Chicago Bulls. ``The
sun was hitting them. They were sparkling.''
</P>
<P>
   That was enough to get O'Neal. And when you have the big fella,
you have the team. O'Neal respects the air of discipline Jackson
brings to the team, reminding him of his father, Phillip Harrison,
a military man who had no qualms about raising his voice while
raising his stepson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil is a straightforward kind of guy,'' O'Neal said. ``He's
also the type of guy that when you don't do what you're told to do,
you have to hear him a lot. And even though I enjoy being yelled
at, I really don't like being yelled at all the time. And me, being
a kid, you do what your father tells you to do and then you don't
have to hear him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one of these bratty superstars you can't talk to. I
grew up like that, and that's what's made me successful. And the
key to success is that you have to stick to what made you
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   And Jackson has been successful.
</P>
<P>
   Where other coaches tried a more laid-back approach, hoping to
ingratiate themselves with the young superstars, Jackson backs his
basketball philosophy with a stern hand. And that hand does not
have enough fingers for all his championship rings _ six as a coach
and one as a player with the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning is something that instills confidence in players, and
you believe in yourself that you can overcome certain odds,''
Jackson said. ``I think that's part of it. I think that's part of
winning. I think it's an attitude and it's a way you go about your
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is the way Jackson goes about his business. As a young
man, Jackson was the ultimate loner, but he finds his greatest
pleasure in perfect team play.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson learned the beauty of that selfless teamwork during his
playing days with the Knicks. In New York's beautifully
choreographed system, where the balletic moves of teammates Walt
Frazier and Earl Monroe were featured, Jackson stood out, more a
collection of involuntary twitches and tics, with elbows and knees
flying every which way.
</P>
<P>
   But now, in his mid-50s, Jackson's mind seems to fly in every
direction, with interests as far-reaching as O'Neal's wingspan _
philosophy, politics, comparative religions, Native Americana, pop
culture, travel and so on.
</P>
<P>
   So why does Jackson devote that mind to basketball rather than
applying his intellect to the many social issues for which he
crusades?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a forum,'' said Jackson after a pause as he searched for
the right words. ``It ends up being a really good forum for a
number of reasons that appeal to me. I just think it's part of the
fact that we come from such diverse backgrounds to get to this
position in basketball. We've got a smattering of kids from here
and there _ from Europe, from Africa, from Australia _ from all
over the world to play in this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we've got kids in this country who come from the poorest
situations to some of the wealthiest situations, so the
socio-economic background and status is so different. And to find
the common thread and to really kind of work on that
American-dream-type stuff is always interesting to me. To find
players who have very little education and players who are
educated, they all have a certain way of communicating.
</P>
<P>
   ``And finding a way to communicate is kind of my goal because
this is what I do as a coach is try to meld them together and have
them work in an atmosphere that is good like this. Yet when it's
over, what you have to have is yourself and you still have to be in
control of your person and not so enmeshed in the team or in this
business that it is all you have. I think that balance is
important.''
</P>
<P>
   And balance is what the Lakers are all about.
</P>
<P>
   In O'Neal, Bryant and Rice, they have three All-Star-caliber
players capable of scoring 40-plus points on any given night. But
in Jackson's triangle offense, the three have been content to share
the ball _ and the spotlight _ as they pursue the ultimate goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a really good chance (of winning the
championship),'' O'Neal said. ``We'd always win our 50 or 60 games,
but then we'd always get beat in the playoffs. I think Phil (knew
the Lakers) needed somebody to take us over the hump.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think this is the staff that's going to take us over
that hump. Everybody believes in it, and we all believe in each
other. I think that by February or March we should be able to tell
whether we have a great shot at it or not.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
