<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS TRIP AND FALL AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Most of the 14,659 spectators at the Target Center
proved they could recognize a blowout Thursday night. They began
leaving en masse in the fourth quarter, but they must have gone
with warm feelings into the cold Minnesota night as the
Timberwolves took a 103-85 win over the Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   This was a discouraging defeat for the Celtics, as the
Timberwolves patiently dissected their half-court defense and had
little difficulty solving the full-court press.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minnesota just outplayed us in every phase of the game,''
Celtics coach Rick Pitino said. ``They shot a high percentage and
we shot a low percentage. And they played good defense. Hopefully,
we will play better against New Jersey (Saturday).''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics fell out of contention early as their low-post
offense disappeared with the departure of Vitaly Potapenko after he
committed his second personal foul late in the first half. The
Celtic offense appeared disjointed, with no effective focal point
until Danny Fortson injected some power and spirit on the baseline
long after the outcome had been decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play better defense,'' guard Kenny Anderson said.
``Our rotation was terrible. We've got offensive players, that's
not the problem. The problem is stopping people from figuring out
our defensive game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ran their offense well and we broke down. It's been like
that the whole season. And we're going to have to do better if we
want to make the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics didn't look like a playoff team. They have won only
twice on the road this season, and should not have been expected to
overcome an efficient Minnesota attack. But the Celtics could not
even make things difficult for the Timberwolves, falling out of
contention during a third-quarter drought.
</P>
<P>
   Potapenko cut the deficit to 53-46 1:17 into the second half.
But the Celtics would score only once more from the field in the
next 9:57. And the Timberwolves would take command with a 17-3 run.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino called three timeouts in less than three minutes, but
failed to affect the Minnesota momentum. The Celtics'
ineffectiveness was apparent on their first possession after the
third timeout, as they failed to take a shot within the 24-second
time limit. Antoine Walker launched an airball 3-pointer on their
next possession, and Sam Mitchell countered with a 3-pointer with
one second remaining on the shot clock for a 70-49 Timberwolves
lead with 5:17 to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to the basket and thought we got fouled and didn't
make the basket,'' Pitino said. ``And we didn't get back in
transition. It was one of those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's patience was illustrated by four possessions that
concluded with successful, unguarded shots with less than four
seconds remaining on the shot clock.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's drive stretched the advantage to 80-56 with 1:13
left. The Celtics retaliated with an Eric Williams foul shot and
Dana Barros 3-pointer in the final minute. But Mitchell was fouled
by Barros with less than two seconds left in the half, and he
converted three foul shots for an 83-60 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Walter McCarty limited Minnesota's Kevin Garnett in the first
half. But Garnett remained poised _ except for a couple of
outbursts directed at official Ron Olesiak _ and sparked Minnesota
in the second half. And Terrell Brandon controlled the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Walker scored four seconds into the game but struggled in the
first half and launched two long-range airballs in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to find a way to win on the road if we want to be a
playoff team,'' Walker said. ``The whistle was more generous on
their end than it was on our end, but we missed some easy shots,
and that's just the nature of the game. We've got to find ways to
get to the foul line if we expect to win on the road.''
</P>
</TEXT>
