<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS POWERLESS TO STOP BLUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Kings know they can play with the better teams
in the National Hockey League. They just can't beat them.
</P>
<P>
   Take the St. Louis Blues, who have the league's best record
after a 3-2 victory over the Kings on Thursday night in front of
16,278 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   They have a tie and a one-goal win in the past 10 days against
the Kings. They were limited to just three shots in the first
period, but scored twice.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have outshot opponents in 11 of the past 12 games. The
problem is they are 2-9-1 during that stretch. If San Jose, which
plays the Kings on Saturday and the Mighty Ducks weren't also
struggling, the home team would be in big trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the good stuff really means anything when you need
victories,'' said Bryan Smolinski, who scored the Kings' two goals.
``Playing better doesn't matter when we have a chance to do some
things. We played better tonight, but it's not something you feel
good about.''
</P>
<P>
   After getting riddled with penalties two nights earlier, the
Kings again were beaten by the power play, this time on a
third-period goal by Scott Young.
</P>
<P>
   Sean O'Donnell received a questionable interference call on
Scott Pellerin that set up the man advantage.
</P>
<P>
   With 13:25 remaining, Blues defenseman Al MacInnis fired from
the blue line and Young redirected the puck past Kings goaltender
Stephan Fiset for the winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   Hot teams get those calls and the Blues certainly are that,
unbeaten in their past eight games
</P>
<P>
   Kings coach Andy Murray, who has scheduled a team meeting for
today, isn't critical of the team's effort.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were coming off a sloppy 4-3 loss to Ottawa and facing
the hottest team in the league in St. Louis. Holding the
high-scoring Blues to just 16 shots was admirable. Smolinski's
game-tying goal with 29 seconds left in the second period against
Roman Turek seemed to bring momentum.
</P>
<P>
   But that was it. They might catch a break against stumbling San
Jose, but the Kings now are saying injured center Jozef Stumpel
will be out two to three more weeks with a knee injury. The Kings
also lost Glen Murray in the first period after he got crunched
against the boards, but he is expected back Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this streak of misery we're on right now, we are trying to
grind up some offense,'' Andy Murray said. ``We wanted to play real
solid in the third period. St. Louis is on a roll right now and
things are happening for them, that happen when you are playing
well. We have to earn our breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   The only problem with the Blues right now is they play in the
Central Division, which has been dominated by Detroit the past few
years. St. Louis entered Thursday's game with 58 points, just one
behind the Red Wings. But with division winners getting the first
three seeds in the playoffs, a loss to the Kings would have put the
Blues fourth in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (18-17-7) are still seventh in the West, but only
because the Mighty Ducks are in a free fall.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the Ottawa game, where they were undone by penalties
and poor performances by Fiset and defenseman Aki Berg, the Kings
were sharp.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset was back in net for the ninth consecutive game. Jamie
Storr, sidelined since mid-December with a concussion, will play
Friday night for the minor-league Long Beach Ice Dogs and hopes to
be ready for the Kings' game Saturday night in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Berg, who played a role in three of the four Ottawa goals, was
scratched Thursday, a move that drew cheers from the crowd. His
replacement, Garry Galley, returned from injured reserve after
missing a month with a concussion and assisted on Smolinski's
second goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times where everything seemed to fall into place,''
said Smolinski, whose 38 points are just two short of last year's
total when he played with the New York Islanders. ``But not
enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
