<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 03:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5892 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MICROSOFT-CEO-SFCHRON     01-14 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-CEO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT CEO STEPS DOWN  
 
 
 
 
</HEADLINE>
   By KELLY ZITO and CARRIE KIRBY  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the world's most valuable company faces a potentially
wrenching breakup, Bill Gates stepped down as chief executive of
Microsoft Corp. Thursday, handing the reins to his former Harvard
classmate, Steve Ballmer, the company's gregarious president.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer, 43, whom Forbes magazine once called ``the George S.
Patton of the software industry'' and Microsoft's ``chief coach,
cheerleader and hatchet man,'' also will take a seat on Microsoft's
board beginning January 27.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, 44, will remain chairman and take on the new position of
chief software architect as the Redmond, Wash., company retools for
the Internet age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve's promotion will allow me to dedicate myself full time
to my passion _ building great software and strategizing on the
future,'' Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, the world's wealthiest person, founded Microsoft 25 years
ago with Paul Allen. Since then, the company has grown into a
juggernaut in the software industry: Its Windows operating systems,
its applications software and its Internet browser dominate their
respective markets.
</P>
<P>
   But that dominance has had its downside.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of Microsoft's management shuffle prompted widespread
speculation that it was tied to its acrimonious battle with the
Justice Department and the offices of 19 state attorneys general,
which charge that the company is an illegal monopoly that harms
consumers. A federal judge found last year that Microsoft used its
position in the industry to create a monopoly, but he has not yet
ruled on whether the company's actions were unlawful.
</P>
<P>
   This week, unnamed sources said the Justice Department will
demand that Microsoft break itself into three distinct ``Baby
Bills'' as part of an out-of-court settlement of the antitrust
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   But Ballmer said his promotion was not related to the lawsuit.
He used Thursday's press conference to lash out at what he called
the ``deliberate'' leaks out of the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would absolutely reckless and irresponsible for
anyone to try to break up this company,'' Ballmer said. ``I think
it would be unprecedented, and I think it would be the single
greatest disservice to consumers in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials didn't directly comment on the
announcement. A spokesman said, ``The department is committed to
seeking the remedy that will solve the serious competitive problems
reflected in the court's finding by promoting innovations and
consumer choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillard Sterling, an antitrust lawyer at Chicago's Gordon &AMP;
Glickson, doesn't believe the management change represents legal
maneuvering by Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were relevant to the litigation, the changes would
have fallen along product lines,'' he said. ``For example, Ballmer
could have become head of browser operations, thereby easing a
restructuring whereby the browser splits from the operating system
functions.''
</P>
<P>
   But the announcement does echo a similar event of two decades
ago. In 1979, as AT&AMP;T was fighting an antitrust case brought by the
federal government, AT&AMP;T's chairman and chief executive, John D.
deButts, stepped down a year before his scheduled retirement.
DeButts was vehemently opposed to the breakup of the company, which
eventually occurred under his successor, Charles Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gates, Ballmer has taken a strong stance against the
possibility of splitting up Microsoft. But some observers believe
his mere presence in the chief executive slot could thaw relations
with the government. ``He's emphatic that he doesn't want to break
up the company,'' said Andrew Roskill, an analyst at Warburg Dillon
Read. But ``it's possible the change in the guard at the
head-kahuna level will help make some progress on the negotiation
front. Bringing in a fresh face could help rejuvenate the
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Roskill also said Gates may be filling a hole left by Nathan
Myrhvold. Myrhvold, the company's chief technology officer, took a
year's leave of absence beginning July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Myrhvold) was always thinking about what is going to be
happening not this year, not next year, but three, four years down
the road,'' Roskill said. Since he left, ``they've lacked that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer, the world's fourth-richest man, is known for his
intensity, tenacity and passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one person at Microsoft I feel very good about,''
said Jeffrey Tarter, publisher of SoftLetter, in Watertown, Mass.
``He's a human being. He has a personality and he's fun. He's a
teddy bear with a big, booming voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Gates' bespectacled face has probably graced more
magazine covers, Ballmer is considered a driving force behind the
company's success.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian King, who worked beside Ballmer at Microsoft for five
years in the 1980s, told PC Magazine several years ago, ``Microsoft
could lose Bill Gates, but it could not survive without Steve's
sheer will to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of immigrants, Ballmer was friends with Gates at Harvard
and kept in touch with him after Gates dropped out to start
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer's first job was selling cake mixes for Procter &AMP; Gamble.
But in 1980, Gates lured him to Microsoft. In July 1998, he was
promoted to president _ a move many interpreted as an unofficial
grooming for the CEO post.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill hasn't been running the company for at least a year, ever
since Steve took over as president. If you look at the
organizational chart for Microsoft, Bill was in charge of a few R&AMP;D
people, and that's it,'' said Tarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Ballmer has already proven that he's in some ways much
better at running the company than Bill ever was,'' Tarter added.
``He's made the company far more focused on customers, taken a much
tougher attitude on product usabililty and made the development
process more demanding. He's running the company internally much
better; he's always been incredibly smart about the marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   In regular trading Thursday, Microsoft shares gained $1.81 to
close at $107.63. In after-hours trading, Microsoft shares dipped
as low as $101.50. The announcement was made after regular hours.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR; Chronicle staff writer Arthur Louis contributed to this report. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
