<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5984 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN15-COX     01-14 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Father should get Elian
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The raging debate regarding 6-year-old Elian
Gonzalez shows how far removed from our common sense _ and our
sense of common humanity _ we have become.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which kind of family is a less important factor in how this
boy should be raised than which kind of state,'' said attorney Jose
Garcia Pedrosa, who represents Elian's Miami relatives who are
trying to keep him in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The only people sent back to Cuba are criminals, opined
presidential hopeful John McCain. (Quick! Has the INS been alerted
of this policy?)
</P>
<P>
   Elian already lost his mother. Now, lawyers, politicians and
some Cuban-American activists are making the tortured argument that
because Elian lost his mother, he should also lose his father.
``She died to bring him here,'' goes the rallying cry. ``He should
be allowed to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, is attempting to
pre-empt the rights of the father, Juan Miguel, and even those of
his maternal grandparents. His supporters argue the boy could have
a ``better life'' in America. Translation: Affluence and a superior
political system supersede a family's love _ and a family's rights.
</P>
<P>
   It's good old-fashioned cultural imperialism masking itself as
``the best interests of the child.''
</P>
<P>
   Put aside, for the moment, the fact that the same argument could
be made to justify the kidnapping of every last child in Cuba. Put
yourself in the father's position: Your ex-wife flees with your
6-year-old son and risks his life in a desperate attempt to
emigrate to America. She dies; the boy miraculously survives.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine being told you can't have your son back because he will
have a ``better life'' _ without you _ in another country.
</P>
<P>
   It would be one thing if Juan Miguel Gonzalez were an absent
father. But here is a man actively involved in his son's life _ a
man who hasn't cut his hair since Elian left, since the two always
went to the barber together.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Meissner, commissioner of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, made the sensible, compassionate call that
``this little boy, who has been through so much, deserves to be
with his father.''
</P>
<P>
   That should have been the end of it. As we all know, it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Now Republicans in Congress, led by Dan Burton of Indiana, have
even issued a subpoena requiring Elian to appear before a House
subcommittee. Great idea. If he tells them he likes Barney, does
that mean he has to stay in America?
</P>
<P>
   People can't get enough of Elian, with his choir-boy eyes and
little-boy exuberance. The politicians, the Cuban-American
activists and lawyers have all claimed him as their own; the
cameras have all but devoured his image. But who is really seeing
him? Everyone is too wrapped up in his own agenda.
</P>
<P>
   A Florida family court ruled in favor of the Miami relatives,
granting the great-uncle temporary custody _ a decision swiftly
dismissed by Attorney General Janet Reno because the court has no
jurisdiction in federal matters.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope the federal courts move swiftly to return Elian to
his father in Cuba. Protracted custody battles do nobody any good,
least of all the child. (Remember baby Jessica?)
</P>
<P>
   ``Which kind of family is a less important factor in how this
boy should be raised than which kind of state,'' said the lawyer
for the boy's Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   He's forgetting that ours is a great state because we value the
rights of individuals, of families.
</P>
<P>
   And he's forgetting Elian is not a symbol or a rallying cry or a
political pawn, but a flesh-and-blood little boy who has lost his
mother.
</P>
<P>
   And who needs his father, now more than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
