<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5985 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN15-COX     01-14 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shaky AOL-Time Warner merger has everyone watching for hard fall
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Using American Online to connect to the Internet
is like riding a race bike with training wheels.
</P>
<P>
   AOL is slick, pretty, touchy-feely and in the way, in my
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   My opinion doesn't count because AOL just pulled off the biggest
merger in history when it plunked down $165 billion to buy Time
Warner.
</P>
<P>
   That's amazing when you consider that the smart money kept
saying AOL would fold as soon as newbie computer users wised up and
switched to cheaper and less intrusive Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently 20 million paying subscribers don't mind having their
hands held when they use the Internet through AOL.
</P>
<P>
   AOL subscribers must not mind all the offers for things they've
never thought about or the delays while AOL downloads something
supposed to upgrade something they've never complained about.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of Congress, including GOP presidential hopeful
Sen. Orrin Hatch, have said they are extremely concerned about this
mega-merger because it may hurt consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Congress members will look the merger over for antitrust
problems. None will be found since the two customer bases are
separate. Still, Congress members know that if they can regulate an
industry, they can hit it up for campaign donations. It's worth a
shot.
</P>
<P>
   This deal really isn't a merger. It's a buyout.
</P>
<P>
   AOL founder Steve Case, whose poor-boy whining recently helped
convince a federal judge that Microsoft founder Bill Gates was a
monopolist bully, bought Time Warner, which happens to own CNN,
HBO, Warner Bros., Sports Illustrated, Time and assorted other
magazines, music and movie studios and 13 million cable TV
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Case paid for Time Warner with an all-stock transaction. AOL
stock, like a lot of the dot.com companies, is based more on
expectations than profits. During its 15 years in business, AOL has
only barely begun to make a profit in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   To continue valuing AOL's stock based on expectations of profits
is not unlike Vegas craps shooters betting on the come.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fact, AOL's newfound profits look shaky when you
consider Case's company charges its customers more than $20 a month
for Internet access now given away free by other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of shaky, Time Warner has been having trouble turning a
profit since Warner Communications bought Time Inc. for $13.9
billion in 1989. At the time, people thought $13.9 billion to form
the biggest media conglomerate was a big deal. Silly us.
</P>
<P>
   At least Time Warner's stock is based on something people can
understand, such as profits, earnings, capital holdings and other
old-fashioned considerations.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder how Ted Turner is taking this. The master yachtsman
used to be master of his own ship, CNN, which he founded.
</P>
<P>
   CNN keeps sinking deeper into an ever-growing conglomerate. Now
Turner is some sort of a vice president. On top of that, him and
his better half, Jane Fonda, have seperated.
</P>
<P>
   As owner of the Atlanta Braves, Turner probably got enough money
out of the AOL-Time Warner deal to pay for John Rocker's
sensitivity training after Sports Illustrated, a Time Warner
publication, outed the flame-throwing pitcher as flaming bigot.
</P>
<P>
   These escalating mergers are entertainment in themselves. Now
that AOL has clasped hands with Time Warner and jumped over the
cliff together, everyone wants to see if the new company will land
on its feet and die from the fall.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, other mega-mergers and buyouts from filthy-rich
dot.com upstarts have to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gates can't be outdone like this. I just hope Ted Turner
will still have a job.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
