<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5986 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN15-COX     01-14 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delivery to your door no guarantee if on 'wrong' side of river
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Jean Laster has the angels on her side. If only we
could summon the National Guard, too.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the image of guardsmen escorting a pizza driver to the
doorstep of a forbidden address doesn't fit in with the righteous
causes of Little Rock and the University of Mississippi. But it
doesn't make the cause of the Precinct 7 justice of the peace less
right, which is to demand to have a pizza delivered to people
regardless of skin color.
</P>
<P>
   The big-cheese pizza companies involved say pigment isn't the
issue, that safety is what keeps them from sending drivers to
certain places.
</P>
<P>
   It just so happens that virtually every inhabitant in those
places is black. It just so happens, also, that some of those
places have nicely maintained homes, well-manicured lawns,
pro-active neighbors and every criterion of a safe destination.
</P>
<P>
   No company can be faulted for having employees steer clear of a
specific danger spot. Anyone in town could name a dozen or more.
</P>
<P>
   Even San Francisco, which at one time imposed a
nondiscrimination ordinance on such deliveries, had to soften and
allow businesses to steer clear of places that presented an
``unreasonable risk of harm.''
</P>
<P>
   Crime statistics don't back up the prejudices of those who'd
red-line East Waco. As the Waco Tribune's J.B. Smith reported
Sunday, predominantly black City Council District 1, in which
Laster resides, had 73 robberies in 1998 compared to 124 in more
diverse though still inner-city District 4 on the other side of the
river.
</P>
<P>
   City officials are right to put the crime figures on the table
and urge pizza companies to be more selective about their
selectivity.
</P>
<P>
   But we can't force them.
</P>
<P>
   If they were banks, we would have more standing in calling the
shots.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the 1970s, with rampant discrimination by banks in
denying loans to minorities, Congress did two things: First, in
1975 it required that banks start reporting where and to whom they
loaned under the Home Mortgage Disclosure Act. Second, in 1997 it
enacted the Community Reinvestment Act, which required banks to act
affirmatively in providing loans to inner-city residents.
</P>
<P>
   How possible? First, banks are chartered by the government.
Second, banks are insured by the government. They owe us, as
taxpayers, socially responsible practices, just as surely as their
debtors owe the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since, the Community Reinvestment Act has proved to
be a godsend to America's cities.
</P>
<P>
   And a lot of banks that opposed such requirements have come to
embrace the principle of putting something back into one's
community.
</P>
<P>
   A rational look at one's community, as banks have had to do,
breaks down a lot of barriers. A lesson for Pizza Inc.?
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that some banks don't skirt the law's intent.
While pledging nondiscrimination, some impose discriminatory
guidelines like minimum loan amounts and maximum housing age
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation that ended up with sweeping changes in banking last
year _ breaking the ``firewall'' between banking, insurance and
securities _ carried for a time a Senate-passed measure, authored
by Sen. Phil Gramm, that would have removed CRA requirements for
smaller banks (under $100 million in assets). It would have
affected rural communities throughout the nation.
</P>
<P>
   A Clinton veto threat and opposition in the House killed that
dangerous wrinkle.
</P>
<P>
   How does banking deregulation bear on the delivery of pizza? Not
at all, unless _ the insatiable bank-insurer-securities
mega-corporations convince Congress they need more. They get the
green light to get into the pizza and Chinese food businesses.
Bingo. Federally regulated, we could require home delivery (and egg
rolls?) to all.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
