<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5994 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD15-COX     01-14 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Japanese turning tools not as popular in U.S.
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Once or twice a year a postcard from a reader arrives,
typewritten and anonymous, with a few terse lines usually couched
as a complaint rather than a question.
</P>
<P>
   The latest arrival begins with my correspondent claiming that he
can't find a single free plan for a garden arbor on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there you go. People who produce work have a habit of
wanting to get paid for it. Why not just examine a few arbors
already made, take the features you like, and draw up your own
plans? Heck, maybe you could sell them on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Next he _ I assume it's a man _ wants to know who sells Japanese
turning tools.
</P>
<P>
   As far as I know, no one sells them. I'm not even sure they are
available factory-made. To the best of my knowledge the woodturning
generally done in Japan is basic, architectural and, like much of
their joinery, involves soft woods. The turners generally make
their own tools and they wouldn't be of much use in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Another gentleman wrote in to apprise me of the finish he's
always used, which turns out to be the same finish I've always
used. It's made of polyurethane varnish, linseed oil and
turpentine. I've lost his note, but I believe his recipe called for
about one part each of polyurethane and oil and two parts of
turpentine. That's about the same proportions I've used.
</P>
<P>
   You can also buy the same kind of finish in commercial
preparations if you don't want to mix up your own. Minwax Antique
Oil is probably the most easily found, but there are several
others; just about every major maker of finish has one.
</P>
<P>
   It's generally referred to as an oil-varnish finish, because
varnish is a word not all woodworkers care to use in polite
company. A chemist, however, would consider it a varnish. The
virtue is that it combines the increased protection of varnish with
the ease of application of a straight oil finish. It is also easy
to repair.
</P>
<P>
   You apply it just like oil _ flood it on, let it soak in a
while, and wipe it off before it dries. you can adjust the drying
rate by varying the amount of turpentine. The 2-1-1 mixture will
dry rapidly, so you don't want to try to cover too big an area in
one go. If it gets too tacky to wipe off, just apply some more
fresh finish, which will loosen up the tacky stuff enough to wipe
off.
</P>
<P>
   As with a straight oil finish, you don't want to hurry. Most
commercial finishes tell you to wait 24 hours between coats.
However, I think it's best to wait at least two days, especially in
humid weather.
</P>
<P>
   Expect to apply two or three coats. The heavier the buildup, the
more protection and gloss.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Maloof uses a finish like this, except for the final coats,
when he adds beeswax to the mixture and heats it in a double
boiler.
</P>
<P>
   Sam has the advantage of living in sunny Southern California,
and does this finishing outdoors. I wouldn't suggest doing it
indoors.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
