<HEADER>
A6034 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-ARMEY-BOS &LR;      01-14 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ARMEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE DIGGING PRODUCES A GEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EARTH CITY, Mo. _ Charley Armey was well into the tale of all
tales for the 1999 National Football League season, of how he found
Kurt Warner, lost in the ozone between Iowa and Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was aware of what Kurt had been doing in the Arena
Football League,'' said Armey, the former Patriots executive and
current vice president of player personnel for the St. Louis Rams.
``There were write-ups in the papers and videotapes, so you knew
about the guy. And I had worked out other Arena League guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner had a tryout with the Green Bay Packers in the 1994
training camp, but was so intimidated by Brett Favre and the other
quarterbacks that he was reluctant to even take snaps in
scrimmages.
</P>
<P>
   Many minds in the NFL closed. Warner went off to the Iowa
Barnstormers of the Arena League, where he played from 1995-97.
</P>
<P>
   Then, one day, coach Al Luginbill of the Amsterdam Admirals of
NFL Europe called _ his 12th NFL team as it were _ and talked to
Armey. Armey's mind was not closed especially since Luginbill,
Marshall Faulk's former coach at San Diego State, was a longtime
friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al was calling and and he was looking for a quarterback and he
was asking me about working out Kurt,'' said Armey. ``Kurt had come
from Northern Iowa and then what I did was look up the report I had
done on Kurt when I was with the Patriots. And then I noticed in
the report I'd done with the Patriots that I had written, `(Warner)
has a chance to develop into a solid player in the NFL.' I had
written that because of his accuracy and his arm strength. But, you
know, at New England, we weren't really looking for a quarterback
with Drew (Bledsoe) there and (Scott) Zolak.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL scouts have pals strewn through all the highways and byways
of America. It's a necessity. The pipeline must be replenished
every year with nuggets about a hidden gem at some unknown school.
Armey recalled that he had a pal, Mike Kolling, on the staff of
Northern Iowa ``and my first coaching job I ever had, at a high
school in Grainsville, Minn., Mike was my quarterback. So I just
called and asked him about Warner, to get a little background on
the kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike said, `You really need to work this guy out because his
arm is so accurate.' Already, it was an unbelievable story with
Warner, because in five years at Northern Iowa, it wasn't until his
senior year that he had ever played. And then he went into Green
Bay's camp and they never really gave him a chance since they had
Favre and (Mark) Brunell there.''
</P>
<P>
   So Armey went to Rams coach Dick Vermeil and the two decided to
bring in Warner for a workout. ``We were both struck by how quickly
he got rid of the ball _ and that was strictly because of the Arena
League and how fast-paced it is _ and how accurate he was,'' Armey
said. ``He always put the ball where the receivers could catch it
without adjusting their routes. But what you never know about a
quarterback is how well he runs a team and manages a team.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, Armey and Vermeil decided, could only be found in
NFL Europe. So Armey and the Rams signed Warner in December 1997
and shipped him to Amsterdam in 1998. ``He immediately started
lighting it up there,'' said Armey.
</P>
<P>
   Armey's mind was not closed _ the Rams signed a totally unknown
quarterback and shipped him off to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   And ``what's happened,'' said Armey, ``is one of the great
Cinderella stories you've ever heard of in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner, of course, replaced the injured Trent Green for St.
Louis in the exhibition season and has already won the MVP award
for the 1999 season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 1127EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 11:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6041 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-ARMEY-PARCELLS-BO     01-14 1578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ARMEY-PARCELLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMEY'S BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EARTH CITY, Mo. _ Their two personalities couldn't be more
different. One is demanding and driving. The other is relaxed and
accommodating.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells and Charley Armey truly did not mesh in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Armey is now flourishing as the St. Louis Rams' vice president
of player personnel, solidifying his reputation as a keen judge of
talent with the signing of quarterback Kurt Warner, who has risen
from the obscurity of the Arena Football League to garnering the
NFL's most valuable player award.
</P>
<P>
   But for all his _ and his team's _ success, the wounds Armey
suffered in New England still have not healed. From time to time,
he will be discussing one subject, only to have the specter of
Parcells slip back into the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Armey, who worked in New England from 1991-97, was the Patriots'
director of college scouting during Parcells's tenure and his words
about his former colleague are unusually blunt.
</P>
<P>
   For example, while discussing the coaches he has worked under,
Armey said the secret for all good coaches is ``they all have a
plan and they all stick to it. They're not wishy-washy with their
plan. And, without question, Dick Vermeil is the most overall and
well-rounded of all the coaches I've worked under. He has fewer
weaknesses and more strengths than any I've known.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all have strengths. Like Forrest Gregg was a great
disciplinarian out of the Lombardi era and I loved working under
Gregg. And Chuck Knox, too. And I loved working for Marv Levy. And
Bill? Everybody knows what Bill's all about. But Bill doesn't have
the compassion that Dick Vermeil has.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey talked on. Of how Vermeil ``is the most compassionate man
I've ever known and I'm not just talking about dealing with
football players and coaches. I mean, just with people. He
genuinely would treat the guy shingling his house as well as the
guy throwing his 40th touchdown pass. He is just an unusual
person.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he goes back to New England. Back to Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once Bill squeezed me out in New England, he didn't squeeze me
out totally because I had a great relationship with the owner (Bob
Kraft), but he squeezed me out out of the process of selecting
players,'' said Armey. ``The last two years I was there in New
England I really didn't have too much to do with selecting players
and who they took.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bill is a bully,'' he said. ``I think he bullies his
coaches and personally I think that's why (Bill) Belichick isn't
coaching the Jets. I think he bullies his coaches, I think he
bullies the people he works with and I think he tried to bully his
way through everything, and I just don't think you can do that in
modern-day football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him once, `When's the last time in the NFL a coach has
fired an owner?' . . . I don't know, I just think his personality
and my personality didn't mesh.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Armey's version of the unhappy relationship, ``Bill and I
never hit it off from Day 1. Bill was always trying to edge me out.
I'm sure, if he had had complete control, if Robert Kraft had let
him, he would have fired me.''
</P>
<P>
   As Armey looks back, he feels his system of scouting and
``layering'' the draft board paid dividends both before Parcells
arrived and after. ``Sam Gash? I drafted him in the eighth round
before Bill was even there. And Todd Collins was drafted before
Bill was there. And Ty Law was a player we were completely sold
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Armey said, ``Bill was a great coach'' and just as
certainly, a head coach has to be involved in who is drafted
``because he has to be the guy who cooks the meal'' and, ``He has
to have the type of players that fit in with the way he coaches.
And I've always believed this _ you've got to give the head coach
the players to work with because the personality with the team will
be the head coach's.''
</P>
<P>
   When Parcells was the coach and Armey the head of college
scouting, the Patriots would involve the assistant coaches in the
draft process. New England now has reverted to the late Dick
Steinberg's method, where the scouting department more or less
makes the call without much, if any, involvement from the men who
will coach the players. ``I've always believed, and I'm surprised
Bobby (Grier) might not, that all your people have to be
involved,'' said Armey.
</P>
<P>
   In his last two years, Armey was cast out of the process, and in
his last year (1997) _ because it was known he was coming to St.
Louis _ he was unable to say anything of import.
</P>
<P>
   Asked which picks in New England made him the proudest, Armey
replied, ``Ted Johnson . . . and Drew Bledsoe because of what he is
and I'm very, very, very proud of the fact that I stood up at the
table and we were able to draft Sam Gash because he turned out to
be a good player. From where Sam was rated to where he went is
probably my greatest thrill.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, said Armey, ``didn't make any selections at all''
after the infamous Terry Glenn episode on draft day in 1996. And,
by then, Armey had been relegated to being ``like any other scout.
I wasn't running the draft.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey wants to make clear that ``I wasn't treated poorly by
Bobby Grier or Robert Kraft or any of the scouts or the office
people. It was just my relationship with Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Arguments and debates persist endlessly in New England about who
was responsible for drafting whom during the Parcells years. Armey
was asked to give his view of the most famous decision the Patriots
had to make _ Bledsoe or Rick Mirer with the No. 1 pick in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``There'll always be the age-old argument (about who in the
organiation wanted Bledsoe and who wanted Mirer), and you'll always
get a story from Bill and a story from me,'' said Armey. ``The true
story and the facts are with (former New England owner) James
Orthwein. Orthwein knows the true story. But Bill never tipped his
hand. See, people think Bill had the final authority to make the
picks with the Patriots but that was never in his contract. Not
when I was there, and I left after he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, the final authority in the draft, before Kraft gave
it to Bobby Grier, was (former general manager) Patrick Forte. But
there was some debate between Bledsoe and Mirer . . . but Bledsoe
rated higher and it was obvious I wanted to pick Bledsoe. There was
also some entertainment about trading the pick, and bringing in
(Steve) Beuerlein.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `I was lucky that Coach Vermeil believed in my ability and (Rams
president) John Shaw believed in my ability and gave me an
opportunity,'' said Armey of his rebirth in St. Louis. ``I'm
probably lucky they didn't call Bill Parcells.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey places himself squarely on the side of Kraft in the messy
divorce that developed between the Patriots' owner and Parcells, a
divorce that has risen to a blood feud between the two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never have any complaints about how I was treated by
Robert Kraft _ zero,'' said Armey. ``But I can tell you from
first-hand experience, and you can quote me on this, that nobody
ever treated a coach better than Robert Kraft treated Bill
Parcells. There are things that went on that I wasn't aware of . .
. that's possible . . . but I saw how Robert Kraft revered him and
how he treated him from the first day. Robert Kraft loved him.''
</P>
<P>
   And the falling out?
</P>
<P>
   Somebody, said Armey, ``convinced Robert Kraft that coaches
should coach and scouts should scout and somebody should do the
(salary) cap. He just believes that. That's his philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   And Armey, the personnel guy, was in the middle ``and that
almost always happens because personnel guys are half-management
and half-coaches. The No. 1 responsibility is to get the players
for the head coach to win. And your No. 1 loyalty is to the
organization, to do what's best for the organization. So you can
see how that can be a pull and a tug.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was.
</P>
<P>
   So Armey was pushed aside, then pushed out, and landed in St.
Louis. He talks about his next brightest gem after Kurt Warner, a
5-foot-9-inch, 268-pound linebacker from Division 3 John Carroll
University that nobody in the NFL dared covet because of his size
and the competition he faced. But London Fletcher (after convincing
the Rams' PR people to list him in the team's media guide as 6
feet) has blossomed into one of the league's most promising
linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the Rams' players weren't in St. Louis when
Armey arrived, and with his team _ the men he acquired _ set to
begin its playoff quest Sunday against the Minnesota Vikings, there
is much to discuss. But back, inevitably, it seemed, he came to New
England, an area he misses and a team he cherished. And back he
came, of course, to Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert Kraft was as fair to me as anyone ever has been and
he's a real true friend,'' said Armey. ``And everybody coaches
their own way . . . I have no problems with Parcells. It's not part
of his job description to like me and it's not part of my job
description to like him. It's just that I don't believe that he
should bully people. He tried to intimidate everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, Armey continued, ``wins by the intimidation rule. And
that's what he is. That's who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   And Charley Armey is who he is _ laid-back and convivial _
except when it comes to discussing one man. Bill Parcells.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
