   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WINTER-GAMES (Albany, N.Y.) _ A month from now New York will
host an international sporting event in Lake Placid for which
taxpayers invested more than $23 million during the past two years.
But so far just 5,000 reserved tickets have been sold for the first
Winter Goodwill Games Feb. 17 to 20. Of a total of about 24,000
advanced tickets made available for the only reserved seats
required - for the figure skating events - just 5,000 have been
sold since the $25 seats went on sale in early October, according
to Olympic Regional Development Authority officials. By JAMES M.
ODATO. (Also filed in the `s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-SF (San Francisco) _ The director of the U.S. Census
Bureau has come to town to make sure that Census 2000 does not
repeat the disaster of the last census, in which 837,000
Californians, a disproportionate number of them children and
immigrants, were missed. By JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DOT.COMS (San Francisco) _ The dot-com dating game is heating up
in the wake of America Online's proposed purchase of Time Warner.
Three days after the deal of the new millennium was announced,
shares of Redwood City-based Excite At Home rose over 19 percent
Thursday on rumors of a possible liaison with AT&AMP;T Corp., which
already owns 40 percent of the Internet firm. By ALAN T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-SHOPPING (Undated) _ Despite complaints about
out-of-stock items and late deliveries, consumers spent even more
online this holiday season than many analysts predicted, according
to several studies. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   CHEVRON-PAYMENTS(San Francisco) _ Chevron Corp. has agreed to
pay the U.S. government $95 million to settle a federal court case
in which it was charged with underpaying royalties due for oil
produced on federal and Indian leases over 10 years. By GEORGE
RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   GAP-PROTESTS (San Francisco) _ After a year of anti-Gap protests
led by San Francisco-based Global Exchange, Gap Inc. said its sales
have not been affected and the company remains confident in its
global business practices. By ELIZABETH BRENNAN.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SOURDOUGH-DEMOCRACY (Oakland, Calif.) _ It's alive! A potent,
pungent creature thrives in deep plastic buckets at the
worker-owned Arizmendi Bakery in Oakland _ a 25-year-old sourdough
starter passed down from Berkeley's legendary Cheeseboard, a cheese
store, bakeshop and pizzeria. The ever-enlarging starter is
symbolic of one group's efforts to replicate democratic bakeries in
the Bay Area. By VANESSA HUA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-HURRICANE (Undated) _ Movies based on living people
are a morass of trouble. If they're slavish to the facts, the
results can be episodic and lack dramatic tension. If they're not
slavish enough, the film's living counterparts scream betrayal and
blab appropriately to the press. Rare is the movie that balances
truth with fiction, accuracy with narrative power. ``The
Hurricane'' comes close. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-GIRL (Undated) _ There wasn't a lot of screaming
described in Susanna Kaysen's memoir of her stay in a mental
institution. But since director James Mangold doesn't seem to know
how to convey ``crazy,'' he's added wall-to-wall shrieking as a
bonus of his film adaptation of ``Girl, Interrupted,'' Kaysen's
fragmented confessional. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-HBO-SOPRANOS (Undated) _ With everybody else singing its
praises, you can more than forgive ``The Sopranos'' for giving
itself a subtle pat on the back. After all, as Frank Sinatra sings
in the opening minutes of the HBO drama's second season premiere,
it was a very good year. But this is a new year, a new season. And
I'm not gonna gush about the new ``Sopranos'' season beginning at 9
p.m. EST Sunday. No way. Enough already with the platitudes. As
Tony Soprano (James Gandolfini) says, ``You gotta exercise impulse
control.'' By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RATTO-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ OK, now where? Steve Young
found his clearance to play in 2000. John Rocker is covering the
P.R. bases the way the manual says you should, but he hasn't yet
mastered ``convincing.'' Oh, to be an electrician in the ceiling of
the room where the Pro Football Hall of Fame committee meets when
the topic turns to Ronnie Lott. By RAY RATTO.
