<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 12:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6071 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-HBO-SOPRANOS-HNS &LR;      01-14 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HBO-SOPRANOS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HBO'S `SOPRANOS' NEEDS TUNING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With everybody else singing its praises, you can more than
forgive ``The Sopranos'' for giving itself a subtle pat on the
back.
</P>
<P>
   After all, as Frank Sinatra sings in the opening minutes of the
HBO drama's second season premiere, it was a very good year.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a new year, a new season. All those magazine covers
and Emmys and Golden Globe nominations and the rest don't mean
squat. You have to understand, this is just business.
</P>
<P>
   So I'm not gonna gush about the new ``Sopranos'' season
beginning at 9 p.m. EST Sunday. No way. Enough already with the
platitudes. As Tony Soprano (James Gandolfini) says, ``You gotta
exercise impulse control.''
</P>
<P>
   So we will cut to the facts. In the first three episodes:
</P>
<P>
   _ We meet Tony's sisters, including the wonderfully wacked
Janice (Aida Turturro). She also goes by the name of Pavarti and
may also have an agenda beyond just re-establishing links to her
family.
</P>
<P>
   _ We learn mommy dearest Livia (Nancy Marchand) survived her
``stroke,'' despite being ``dead'' as far as Tony is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   _ We are hit with a sledgehammer by the return home of new face
Richie Aprile (David Proval), brother of late mob boss Jackie
Aprile. After a long stretch in the pen, Richie is looking for his
street action again.
</P>
<P>
   _ He is not the only one to come in from the cold.
</P>
<P>
   _ We learn Tony likes Deep Purple (hey, that is the kind of
detail fans love).
</P>
<P>
   _ Dr. Jennifer Melfi (Lorraine Bracco), fearful of a hit, is
still meeting clients for therapy sessions in a motel.
</P>
<P>
   We also learn that the acting and writing of the mob hit created
by David Chase remains as sharp and captivating as it was in the
earth-shaking 13 episodes of season one.
</P>
<P>
   You call that gushing? Tough. Judging from the first three
episodes, there is nothing to indicate ``The Sopranos'' has slipped
from its perch.
</P>
<P>
   How can I tell? That old post-``Sopranos'' depression has
returned. It's a gnawing emptiness that arises after you see
upcoming episodes in advance and know that when the show actually
airs, you have already spent that initial rush. It's like eating
your Halloween candy while you're still trick-or-treating, then
having to watch your siblings gorge at the kitchen table afterward.
</P>
<P>
   It was just a little more than a year ago that the cast and crew
thought that this little drama they had slapped together would go
by unnoticed, a fun experience that would look good on a resume.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too bad people won't watch it,'' Chase told co-star Edie Falco
(Carmela Soprano).
</P>
<P>
   The only thing the people involved in this show have gotten
wrong is judging how good it really is: The initial tidal wave of
acclaim _ it was universal_ stunned Gandolfini and the rest. In
fact, Gandolfini said last summer that he didn't even expect to get
the part of the mob boss in need of psychiatry: ``They decided to
take a shot, I guess. But that's probably because I'm cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Gandolfini is a private man. When he met with
the press to accept an award from critics last summer, Gandolfini
was noticeably uncomfortable with the attention. Generous, but shy,
cast members said.
</P>
<P>
   Gandolfini, like others in the cast, has trouble pinpointing why
the show resonates with the public. This is where I could go on
with a dissertation of family, and how people can relate to the
flawed mob boss whose nearly unlimited power in the local mob does
nothing to ease his inner fears and troubles with family at home.
But if you've seen the show, either on HBO or on tapes that are
floating around everywhere, you already knew that.
</P>
<P>
   But, again, this is a new season. What about 2000? ``I'm sure
we'll screw it up,'' Gandolfini joked before filming began.
</P>
<P>
   How can people involved in something so right get it so wrong?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
