<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6072 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-SOPRANOS-CHASE-BOS     01-14 1344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SOPRANOS-CHASE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASE CREATES MOBSTERS JUST LIKE YOU AND ME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Chase is sitting in a strangely empty
hotel-restaurant near his apartment on Manhattan's Upper East Side,
noshing on a bagel and trying to articulate just what it is that
has made ``The Sopranos,'' his HBO series about the life of a Mafia
family, such a smash hit.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, in part, it's the realism of the show, but what does that
mean exactly? He hems, haws, meanders, muses. Then he hits on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this show has, that other shows don't have,'' he begins,
``is that people try to talk to each other _ sometimes _ but even
when they try, they fail because everyone's locked in their own
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of TV and movies today _ people say exactly what's on
their mind and they say it very eloquently and very well,'' he goes
on, warming to the subject. ``You know, two characters `have it
out,' and they end up hugging and teary, and each character has
come to a `new understanding' that the other was really trying to
help him in the last 42 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   He giggles, then says, ``I don't see that happening so often in
life. I see people fumbling and flailing. And when you do give
somebody your catalogue of all the things they've said in the past
to hurt you, they say, `I didn't say that!' '' He roars with
laughter.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI recently released excerpts of tapes on which senior
members of the New Jersey mafia are heard raving about ``The
Sopranos,'' extolling the writing, the acting, and wondering how
its makers know so much about them.
</P>
<P>
   Chase is amused and pleased by the reports. He grew up in New
Jersey, in an Italian-American family (the name was changed from De
Cesare back in the 1920s). He knew a few gangsters in his youth,
though nobody high up.
</P>
<P>
   But what clicks about this show isn't that Tony Soprano and his
crew are so much like real mobsters. It's that they're so much like
real people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason they seem real is because I've based them on people
in my family or someone I went to school with,'' Chase says.
``There's one episode where Tony says about Uncle Junior, 'I love
my uncle but, when I was growing up, he told my girl cousins I'd
never be a varsity athlete and that was a great blow to my
self-esteem.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Chase says, with a slight laugh, ``my uncle did tell
my girl cousins that I'd never be a varsity athlete, and it was a
huge blow to my self-esteem. That's why people think it's realistic
_ it's built on all the little grudges in life.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest influence here was Chase's mother, the model for
Tony Soprano's mother, Livia, a seething, manipulative (and
completely captivating) monster of a woman who gangs up with Tony's
uncle to bump off her only son.
</P>
<P>
   Chase has spoken of his mother before, but was she really such a
horror? ``No, of course not,'' he replies. ``But her id was right
there, ready to come out any time, and she had a great way with
words, very wild.''
</P>
<P>
   So, she didn't threaten to poke Chase's eyes out with a fork, as
Livia threatened to do to 9-year-old Tony in last season's
flashback-episode? Chase pauses. ``Well, yeah, she did do that,''
he admits.
</P>
<P>
   This comes as a visible shock, so he explains: ``There was a
snowstorm, we were cooped up in the house, and I kept moaning that
I wanted this little Hammond organ'' _ just like little Tony moaned
in that episode! _ ``and finally, she was driven up the wall, and
she said that.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't mean it,'' he adds, lightheartedly. ``I drove her
to it. My mother was very operatic, she was over the top. But she
never subjected me to any kind of physical abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   What's eerie is that these are almost precisely the words Tony
Soprano uttered, with the same moms-will-be-moms shrug, while
telling the tale to his alarmed psychiatrist. For a brief moment,
Chase _ the show's creator, director, and frequent writer _ looks
like, sounds like, seems to be Tony Soprano.
</P>
<P>
   Chase's mother, who died several years ago, was the key not only
to Livia but to the whole show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been milking stories about my mother at dinner parties for
years,'' he remembers, ``and my wife said I should write a show
about her. I said, `Nah, who cares?' But the idea that did come _ I
was in therapy _ was having a mobster in therapy, working out his
relationship with his cantankerous mother. And I had this notion
that the solution to his Oedipal and maternal dilemma would take
place not in the therapist's office but in the streets, through
gang warfare, with his mother siding with his uncle.''
</P>
<P>
   This, the germ of what would become ``The Sopranos,'' was in
1988, long before ``Analyze This'' or ``Grosse Point Blank.'' Chase
pitched it to his agents as a movie _ ``DeNiro and Anne Bancroft,
something like that,'' he recalls. ``They said, `A mob comedy? Come
on.' So I put it away.''
</P>
<P>
   Years later, he signed a deal with Brillstein-Grey, the company
that produced HBO's ``The Larry Sanders Show.'' They asked if he'd
like to make something like ``The Godfather'' as a TV series.
</P>
<P>
   Chase declined. ``I didn't want to do these guys in a black
car,'' he says. ``Then, I was driving home, and I thought about
this film idea I'd had _ a family drama, like `Year in the Life' or
`Eight Is Enough,' but about a mob family. I realized that the idea
could be expanded into that.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest is well-trod history. He sold the idea to Fox, which,
after mulling it over, backed off. ``They never said why,'' he
says. ``I think it was too dark for them.'' The three big networks
all passed, too. Finally, HBO got it, and gave Chase complete
artistic freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Had one of the majors signed up, it would have been very
different, not just in tone _ the show is rife with profanity _
but, even more, in its casting, especially of Tony, wonderfully
played by the balding, overweight James Gandolfini.
</P>
<P>
   ``No network would have cast him,'' Chase says, shaking his
head. ``They would have given him a sitcom maybe, put him on a
couch with a beer can in his hand. The thing with the networks,
it's all looks, `sexy.' It's so draining. They'll say, 'Let's get a
Winona Ryder type.' I don't even know what that means. I'd say,
`You can't get Winona Ryder, so let's get somebody else as good but
different.''' He laughs uproariously.
</P>
<P>
   Chase has worked on a number of successful network shows,
including ``Rockford Files'' and ``Northern Exposure,'' but ``The
Sopranos'' is the first show that is totally his.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have likened the show to Dennis Potter's ``The Singing
Detective,'' but Chase says he was more inspired by David Lynch's
``Twin Peaks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like stuff that has mysterious comings and goings, a vague
sense of menace, of something coiled that's ready to blow, stuff
that has a certain dreamlike quality to it,'' he says, in a
dreamlike reverie. Then, as if waking up, he adds, with a laugh,
``It's probably time I grew up.''
</P>
<P>
   The first season was all shot before a single episode aired, so
he had no idea how it would be received. By the time he started to
write for the second season, it was clearly not just a hit but a
phenomenon. The pressure was on to top himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not some kind of lion-like auteur who thinks, 'I don't
care if people like it or not!' '' he says. ``We're social animals.
We try to make something entertaining.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, he often found himself pushing way beyond the envelope
to fulfill or exceed expectations. ``This was not always a great
idea,'' he says. ``I ended up pulling back during the filming or
the editing.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis Coppola followed ``The Godfather'' with ``Godfather
II,'' but even he crashed with ``Godfather III.'' ``Twin Peaks''
dwindled into self-parody less than halfway through its first year.
How long can ``The Sopranos'' go on?
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years, tops,'' Chase states. The Soprano kids will grow
up; the actors will move on to movies. Aside from all that, he
adds, ``I hope we have the good sense to know when it's over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
