<HEADER>
A6073 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-14 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO BULLISH ON AMERICA? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For two decades Dick Greene was a legend, the Ted Williams of
Boston stockbrokers, a threat to lead the league in any given year.
The Splendid Splinter, however, could only daydream about the kind
of paychecks Greene brought home.
</P>
<P>
   Greene was the perennial number one producer in Merrill Lynch's
Boston office, some years the number one retail broker nationwide
for America's number one brokerage house. Neither Greene, who spent
years avoiding newspaper guys like me, nor Merrill Lynch will talk
numbers. But competitors estimate Greene could have had $1 billion
in assets under management, generated $10 million a year in
commissions, and taken home $4 million or more a year.
</P>
<P>
   A Boston Irishman with a fondness for cigars, Greene was an
old-school stockbroker who succeeded for exactly the reasons good
brokers do: He worked harder than the next guy and made his clients
money. Legend has it that Greene stopped to see a client every
morning on his way to work, and another every evening on his way
home. That adds up over four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Greene retired at the end of 1998, but now he is under scrutiny
by the state Division of Securities and the target of a slew of
complaints by unhappy former clients. He is also the latest local
Merrill Lynch broker to come under fire, raising the question
whether the big money manager, which has a good reputation for
policing itself, has simply hit a patch of bad luck or whether
there is something amiss.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Merrill's recent run here is bad for its image, in a
business where image counts.
</P>
<P>
   In October and November, The Globe ran stories about Merrill
Lynch broker Donald Martineau, who was charged with stealing $9
million from clients over 11 years. Last month the Boston Herald
outlined how a Merrill broker in Pittsfield, Mass., Donald Sarin,
churned the account of a dead woman, costing her estate $500,000 in
potential investment gains and $160,000 in commissions. Both
brokers have been fired.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch has terminated two other brokers in its Boston
office this month, including one who allegedly steered clients into
a company connected to his father. And now comes Dick Greene, an
icon in Boston's brokerage community.
</P>
<P>
   Greene spent 38 years at Merrill Lynch and retired without a
mark on his disciplinary record, a remarkable achievement in the
brokerage business. But now, in retirement, clients have come out
of the woodwork to complain that Greene put them in two stocks that
collapsed in the second half of 1998. At least seven clients have
filed complaints and more are expected to. Two clients each say
they lost $1 million; another client settled a $420,000 claim for
$25,000, records show.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years Greene was known for taking large positions in a
few stocks, and some of his clients are now charging that he had
their assets largely in the two stocks, Genesis Health Ventures
Inc. and IndyMac Mortgage Holdings Inc. Genesis, a nursing home
operator, was selling for $30 a share in early 1998, collapsed in
July, and is at $2.75 today. IndyMac, a real estate investment
trust, was at $27 early in 1998 before falling as low at $8 in a
tremendous one-day swoon in October; it is now at $11.50.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill says Greene's retirement at age 65 in December 1998 was
unrelated to the stocks' declines a few months earlier. Said Greene
in a statement Thursday: ``I, too, am disappointed by the
performance of these two stocks. Though I saw many ups and downs in
the market during my career, you never get used to significant
losses that occur when the unexpected happens.'' Neither he nor his
attorney, Gerald Rath, would comment further.
</P>
<P>
   The Greene case will turn on the narrow issues of whether the
investments were suitable for his clients and whether their
portfolios were overconcentrated. But more broadly his problems,
along with the other recent accidents at Merrill, have brought the
kind of attention that no brokerage house needs. The question, of
course, will be: Who's watching the store?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at their activities in a fairly comprehensive
way,'' says Secretary of State William Galvin.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a problem, no one has a greater stake in fixing it
than Merrill Lynch itself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steve Bailey is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
