u s BC-BOX-JONES-BOS &LR;      01-14 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-JONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES DOESN'T SPREAD THE NEWS IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Roy Jones chipped a tooth the day before he came to
New York. That may be the most damage he sustains in the next 48
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, Jones will make history when he becomes the
first prize fighter to defend a world title inside Radio City Music
Hall, a place known for high kicks, not low blows. He is there to
put what he contends is the undisputed light heavyweight title on
the line against No. 2-rated David Telesco, a local Westchester
county fighter with some punching power but not much more than
that.
</P>
<P>
   The show has been sold out for weeks, the Hall's 5,700 seats
going quickly because the price was reasonable ($300 ringside) and
the moment historic. But did Jones's presence have much to do with
it?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but you'd never know it because Roy Jones knows
everything about the fights except how to sell one.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctant to fly and unwilling to spend one more day outside his
native Pensacola, Fla., than necessary, Jones did not arrive in
Manhattan until 1:40 p.m. Wednesday afternoon. Since he's not
fighting until tomorrow night that might not have been a problem
except that HBO and the promoter had scheduled a press conference
to hype Jones at noon. By the time he strolled in, the room at the
Hilton was filled with some mighty displeased journalists. Roy
Jones didn't seem to notice. The following morning, he didn't seem
to notice his name in too many newspapers, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy's a good guy but I can't defend him on this,'' said HBO
senior vice president for programming Lou DiBella about his
fighter's consistently late arrivals. ``He did a lot to make this
fight possible but he still can't bring himself to act
professionally (outside the ring). Oscar (De La Hoya) has never
been late to a press conference.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but then Oscar long ago figured out that punctuality and
salesmanship have as much to do with earning millions of dollars
above the norm in the fight game as does boxing ability. Jones,
however, still thinks it's only about what he'll do to Telesco, a
12-1 underdog. That thinking is why Jones will make a couple of
million for his fight and De La Hoya will make a couple million
more than that to fight Derrell Coley next month in New York, with
no title at stake and with an even less compelling opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the business of boxing, and Jones professes not to care
about that. At least not much, which is why he reportedly agreed to
bring the fight to Radio City for a million dollars less in site
fees than he could have gotten from the Grand Casino in Biloxi,
Miss., which for all intents and purposes is now his home field.
</P>
<P>
   If it were solely up to Jones, he would never fight beyond
Mississippi's Gulf Coast but although he is loath to admit it, he
has advisors and occasionally he listens them.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was he would come into the media capital of America and
increase his visibility with a round of interviews and appearances.
Instead he failed to make most of the New York dailies Thursday
because he was so late he was upstaged by a charming, young
heavyweight named Derrick Jefferson, who stole the press conference
with his humor and his honest stories about his days growing up in
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   This week Jones lost the backpages of the tabloids and most of
the inside ones as well because of Bill Belichick's hearing at a
Manhattan law office that he hopes will free him from his contract
with the Jets and Bill Parcells's musings over whether or not he
will return as the Jets' head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Jones will get that big story Saturday, but so far he's
been upstaged even in the boxing headlines by Mike Tyson's battle
to get into England for his Jan. 29 fight with Julius Francis and
Jefferson's stories of street life in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't have to be this way for Jones, but it was said long
ago that 50 percent of success in life is showing up. Although he
did on Wednesday, he was 95 minutes late, and so he became an
afterthought even though he remains arguably the best fighter in
the world. It is a position he's used to.
</P>
<P>
   Slick and lethal in the ring, Jones is not the savviest guy when
it comes to marketing himself or his opponents. Admittedly, he is a
man trapped in a division that has no real competition and because
of that there are no Big Fights for him on the horizon or on his
resume unless he makes the mistake of challenging for the
heavyweight title against men twice his size.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite that dilemma, Jones repeatedly compounds that
problem by insulting the fitness of everyone he fights to be in the
same ring with him. That, like his broken watch, remained unchanged
this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have trouble getting up for these kind of guys but it's
not a problem I haven't dealt with in the past,'' Jones said when
asked if he is tiring of facing non-entities like Telesco. Instead
of building him up as a dangerous puncher, which he is, Jones
simply said that was all Telesco had and dismissed him curtly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him once or twice,'' Jones said. ``He can't beat
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably so but Jones would be wise to talk up his opposition
instead of down to them and to stop refusing to make the closest
thing he has to a big fight, which would be to travel to Germany
and face one of several light heavyweights there such as undefeated
Darius Michalzewski, who continue to call him out. They may not be
fit challengers either but at least they look the part.
</P>
<P>
   That Jones couldn't care less about this is readily apparent.
That much of the sports world feels the same about him was just as
apparent if you stopped anyone in mid-town Manhattan this week and
asked if they knew that the pound-for-pound best boxer in the world
was fighting in New York this week.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them didn't know who Jones was. Most of the ones who
knew of the fight knew only that it was at Radio City, where no
fight had ever been before. Admittedly, this was a small and far
from scientific polling of America's sports fans, but what it
proved was that even when he's making history, Roy Jones remains in
the shadows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 1243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
