<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6079 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-ASIAN-STEREOTYPE-BOS &LR;      01-14 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIAN-STEREOTYPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL CAMPAIGN AIMS AT DISPELLING STEREOTYPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HERMIONE MALONE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Professor Albert H. Yee calls it the Asian Stereotype:
If they are not typified as brilliant scholars, Asian people are
sometimes seen as secretive and conspiratorial.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of Wen Ho Lee, says Yee. A former scientist at the
Los Alamos Nuclear Laboratory, Lee is awaiting trial on charges he
shared US nuclear secrets with China. But his staunchest supporters
insist he is being made a scapegoat because he was the only
Chinese-American who worked on nuclear secrets at the lab for 18
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the thing is that if people would just put aside the
rampant stereotypes of Asians and look at Asians that they know . .
. you go to school with them, you work with them,'' said Yee, a
retired professor who taught at universities in the United States
and east Asia.
</P>
<P>
   It is schools, in fact, that have the best chance to change what
a new generation of Americans learn and perceive about Asia, says
Charlotte Mason, a high school teacher. She is among those trying
to change how American students learn about the continent and
passing on her passion for the culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have relationships with Asia in the 21st
century and we don't have any teachers in the schools currently
trained to teach about it,'' said Mason, who teaches social studies
and special education in Newton, Mass. ``And we have school systems
recognizing the importance of education about Asia, but what are
they going to do about it?''
</P>
<P>
   Her zeal for Asian studies prompted the Asia Society _ a
non-profit group started by John D. Rockefeller III in 1956 to
promote Asian culture _ to appoint Mason to help oversee the
National Commission on Asia in the Schools.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 18 months, Mason and the commission are launching a
national lobbying campaign for better training of teachers of Asian
studies _ and for all educators to teach historically accurate
information about the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have Marco Polo as one of the most enduring figures of
Chinese history,'' said Namji Kim Steinemann of the New York-based
Asia Society. ``This is a teenage son of a Venetian trader who
happened to go along on a sales trip. He certainly is not the most
enduring figure of Chinese history, but the way we teach about it
in our textbooks, he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason studied South Asia and Bengali language in college, but it
was after visiting China and seeing the culture come alive that she
became committed to teaching about it.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Mason stood in front of her ninth-grade world
history class, horrifying many students when she held a pair of
four-inch cloth shoes in the palm of her hand. On a trip to China,
Mason, who is not Asian, bought them at a market. She initially
thought they were baby shoes; but they were the shoes of an adult
woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more important to have small feet than a beautiful
face,'' Mason said, speaking of a thousand-year practice in China
of binding the feet of women to prevent them from growing. ``If you
were lucky, your toes would fall off. If not, you would continue to
be in excruciating pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, the class watched part of a video by a Chinese filmmaker
interviewing women who suffered from the practice, outlawed in the
early 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to say Chinese women bound their feet for thousands
of years, isn't that disgusting? But we forget the things we do to
ourselves,'' Mason said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This grosses them out,'' she said, still holding the shoes
after class, ``but plastic surgery doesn't? Well, why not?''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Asia Society say Mason is the kind of teacher
they want to see more of in the future: knowledgeable in the
culture, history, art and language of the 41 countries that combine
to form Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're proposing isn't that Asia-related education should
be taught at the expense of other subject matter,'' Steinemann
said. ``Asia is already being taught in schools, it's just not
being taught well.''
</P>
<P>
   She points to methods elementary teachers often use to introduce
new cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the lower grades, you might have a tendency to teach about
Asia through food, fun and festival. That's all good if you can
provide some context,'' she said. ``Teaching about Korea through
half-moon cakes trivializes these cultures . . . or teaching about
Japan through Origami. It's very much a part of Japanese culture,
but it stops there.''
</P>
<P>
   In Newton, students are exposed to the cultures of China, Ghana
and Mexico starting in the second grade. Sixth and seventh grade
see them learning of ancient China, the dynasties and inventions.
By high school, students are studying modern Chinese history and
ancient philosophies and can elect to take an Asia study course as
seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1985, about 40 students at Newton North have annually
traded places with Chinese students at a Beijing sister school.
Students spend four months at the Beijing Jingshan School, three
blocks east of the Forbidden City. Many teachers have taken the
trip as well.
</P>
<P>
   It is only with such widespread exposure to other cultures that
people become less discriminatory, say some.
</P>
<P>
   ``When most people think of Asia, I think a lot of people think
solely of Chinese, Korean, Japanese, now more so Vietnamese,'' said
Leverett Wing, a local Asian-American activist, who is a
fourth-generation, Chinese-American. ``I think a lot of people are
unaware of the amazingly heterogeneous nature of the Asian
community.''
</P>
<P>
   And, said Wing, stereotypes still abound. A popular one, he
said, is that all Asians are Buddhist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Christmastime and someone walks up to me and I say `Merry
Christmas.' They just looked at me and said, `Well how do you
Buddists celebrate?' And I think my exact response was, `Well, I'm
going to go to midnight Mass' and he asked, `Why would you go to
midnight Mass?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Asia Society hopes teachers and textbooks are the key to
correcting such misconceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this global society, we really need to think about what our
kids are learning in the short time they have available and ensure
that time is well spent,'' Steinemann said. ``That's the best
hope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 1244EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
