<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 12:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6081 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-AGUILERA-BOS &LR;      01-14 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-AGUILERA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT CHRISTINA AGUILERA WANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Christina Aguilera is holed up in a hotel room in Los Angeles
_ just a girl, a telephone, and a gaggle of handlers carving up the
day into 10-minute chunks of conversation with strangers. ``Oh, I
don't mind,'' says the audibly wilted but unfailingly polite
19-year-old of the rigors of the press circuit. Aguilera's sudden
and massive stardom is, after all, something she's been aiming for
since she made her national television debut on ``Star Search'' at
the age of 9.
</P>
<P>
   Only six months ago, Aguilera was a lesser-known teen singer,
one more ``Mickey Mouse Club'' alumna who had won attention for her
lovely rendering of ``Reflection'' on the ``Mulan'' soundtrack.
Then last summer ``Genie in a Bottle,'' the first single from her
debut, which has since sold 5 million copies, came out. It
catapulted Aguilera to the top of the Billboard charts, where the
single lodged for five weeks. Her new single, ``What a Girl
Wants,'' just knocked Santana's ``Smooth'' out of the top spot. And
the crowning achievement of a whirlwind half-year came last week
when Auguilera was nominated for two Grammy awards: Best New Artist
and Best Female Pop Vocal. She performs at the FleetCenter on
Thursday, with fellow Grammy nomi-
</P>
<P>
   nees TLC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so thrilled,'' she says of the nominations, and despite
her weariness _ Aguilera is speaking in a voice as small as her
singing is large _ it's clear she's not just paying lip service.
``I had no idea. People around me were saying it would happen, but
I'd only had one single out. I was not expecting this at all.''
</P>
<P>
   She has, however, been greasing the wheels for most of her life.
Born on Staten Island and raised near Pittsburgh by her mother and
grandmother after her parents split up, Aguilera listened
incessantly to her favorite singers, ``the great vocalists'' as she
calls them: Etta James, Billie Holiday, Barbra Streisand, and
contemporary powerhouses Whitney Houston and Mariah Carey. As a
precocious grade-schooler she was in demand as a National Anthem
performer at professional sporting events in and around Pittsburgh.
At 12, Auguilera went to Orlando to join the cast of ``The Mickey
Mouse Club.'' High-powered manager Steve Kurtz discovered her as a
Mouseketeer (alongside Britney Spears, Keri Russell, and members of
'N Sync) and offered to shepherd her career. In 1998, in a
remarkable display of faith in an untested artist, RCA signed her
to a seven-album contract. Aguilera was 17.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't want to release ``Genie in a Bottle'' as a single.
``Hearing that song in the first stages, it didn't let me go places
vocally. It sounded very Top 40 to me, very pop-driven, all about a
cool hook and melody. It fit too much into what was going on in
pop, and I wanted to be different. I never wanted to be a straight
pop singer.'' Indeed, the rest of the album is filled with songs
that display her striking range and power as a singer of R &AMP; B,
pop-soul, and ballads.
</P>
<P>
   Yet she is being positioned as a teen pinup (undoubtedly part of
RCA's plan to maximize the return on its hefty investment), and she
knows it. ``This one is the most pop-sounding album I will ever
do,'' declares Aguilera, who says that blues is her number one
favorite style. ``I definitely want to take it to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   She plans to record ``At Last,'' an Etta James tune, for a
hidden track on her sophomore CD and is eager to start writing
herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got songs from some great writers for this album,''
Aguilera says, including hitmeister Diane Warren, who is already on
board for the next album. ``But I want to write more about
experiences I've gone through. I've gone through bad situations. I
come from a divorced home. I've been around abuse. I've lived a
different life, been on the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends, Aguilera says, resented her success and were in short
supply as her career blossomed. ``But I turned negative situations
into positives by putting all my focus and energy into music. I was
always a deep thinker, an introverted person, to the point where
music was an escape.''
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, Aguilera will release a Spanish-language CD. Her
father, with whom she has no contact, is Ecuadoran, and Aguilera
wants to rediscover her Latin roots. Also, ``it makes my
grandparents happy,'' she says. Although it's not her intention,
that album should help distinguish Aguilera from the bevy of teen
sensations who appeared on the scene last year: Britney Spears,
Jessica Simpson, and Mandy Moore _ all blond teenagers with
dance-pop records. It's a phenomenon that Aguilera accepts, but
it's still disconcerting to her. ``It's so weird that we all came
out at the same time, and yeah, it's a little frustrating to
constantly get compared. We're all so very different,'' she says,
careful to point out in well-rehearsed tones that ``it doesn't take
away from what I think of them. They're all so talented.''
</P>
<P>
   More accurately, Aguilera is so very different _ far and away
the most gifted vocalist of the bunch. ``People,'' she says, ``will
see (the differences) as time goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, she is busy learning to navigate a world where
``everyone wants a piece of you. Good and bad. They either want to
put you down or talk to you. All these people are pulling, just
pulling on you.''
</P>
<P>
   She's constantly on the road. And as for dating?
</P>
<P>
   ``No time,'' Aguilera says. ``It's sort of sad. I see these
gorgeous guys in the audience and would love to get to know them.
But I'm off to the next airplane.'' Still, like any red-blooded
teenager, she is prone to crushes. Her latest? Limp Bizkit singer
Fred Durst. But with a schedule as hectic as hers, Aguilera says,
``I'm lucky if I get to see a movie. Alone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
