<HEADLINE>
MARINO LEAVES MIAMI IN THROES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it ends this weekend, at least it will be in Florida, where
it all began.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Marino may well be the greatest passer the National Football
League has ever seen, but what is clearest about him now is that
his time has past. He is not very often the Marino he once was. Not
often the most feared passer in football.
</P>
<P>
   But last Sunday _ for two drives and maybe for old time's sake _
Marino was all that once again, and that is why the Dolphins will
travel to Jacksonville to meet the heavily-favored Jaguars Saturday
in the second round of the AFC playoffs. An upset there and Marino
will be in the conference championship game for the first time in
seven years, one game away from seeking the only prize in pro
football that has eluded him: a Super Bowl ring.
</P>
<P>
   At 38, that is all Marino has left to play for. He has already
thrown more passes (8,358 in regular season) than anyone in
football history. He has already completed more of them, too
(4,967). He has already passed for more yards (61,361) than anyone
in football history, nearly 10,000 ahead of longtime rival John
Elway. He has already thrown more touchdown passes (420), too.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the lion is in winter now, and the clearest measure of that
is another, simpler stat. Marino has had just 32
sub-50-percent-completion games in his 17-year career. Three of
them, nearly 10 percent of the total, came this season. The
Dolphins won only 10 of those games. They lost all three this
season.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes.
</P>
<P>
   Through all the years the Dolphins and Marino have been linked,
the one long relied on the other to bring it victory. Although he
does that less often now, he did it again last Sunday in Seattle,
not by throwing often but by throwing well when needed most.
Throwing well when he completed six straight passes to open the
second half of a wild-card playoff game with a touchdown drive that
gave his team some life and throwing better still when he completed
4 of 6 throws for 82 yards to set up what ended up being the
winning touchdown with 4:48 to play in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 37th time Marino had led the Dolphins to a
come-from-behind, fourth-quarter victory. It may be the last or it
may not. That will be up to the Jaguars more than it is up to
Marino, because that is how it goes now for him much of the time.
</P>
<P>
   His arm is not what it used to be since a bulging disk in his
neck weakened it earlier this season and forced him to the sideline
with the fear, he now admits, that he might never throw like his
old self again.
</P>
<P>
   Marino's replacement, Damon Huard, went 5-1 during that stretch
and declared himself the future in Miami. But when Marino was
healthy, he returned to the lineup with the belief nothing had
changed. He was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Some around the NFL now say in almost funeral tones, that during
that layoff Marino lost more than arm strength. They say he lost
his nerve. They whisper that too often now he seems to have the
yips, making critical throwing errors that put his team in trouble.
They note that the Dolphins committed 19 turnovers in their final
six games, going 1-5 because of it. Twelve of those were
interceptions and three of those interceptions were returned for
touchdowns. They are the kind of lapses the young Marino seldom
suffered.
</P>
<P>
   In 17 years, Marino has had one season when he threw more
interceptions than touchdown passes. That year was 1999 (12 to 17)
and those turnovers were critical in the season's final weeks when
the Dolphins lost five of six games to blow the advantages of a
fast start. They barely snuck into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Miami is still alive today, and so is Marino's career after
leading the Dolphins to their first playoff road victory in 28
years last Sunday. Despite speculation of impending retirement and
a supposed on-going feud with coach Jimmy Johnson, Marino showed
one more time that when he is on, it is still the good old days.
</P>
<P>
   The receivers aren't as good as the ones he used to have, and
neither is he. They are not in the same league with Mark Clayton
and Mark Duper, and he is not in the same league with the real Dan
Marino. But they are good enough when he is good enough, and they
both know it. His receivers know it, and the rest of his teammates
know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only Dan could have thrown some of those passes,'' said Miami
middle linebacker Zach Thomas, after Marino's 23-yard completion on
third-and-17 from his own 8 started Miami rolling toward the
winning touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Marino spent the first half handing off and the
second half completing 12 of 21 for 168 yards and a touchdown plus
leading his team to the game-winning score by accounting for 82
yards in an 85-yard touchdown drive. In the end, at least for that
one game, he was Dan Marino the way he used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every guy gave everything he had to win this game,''
Seattle defensive end Phillip Daniels said after Marino had beaten
his Seahawks, 20-17. ``You never know which Marino is going to show
up. The right one showed up for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The right one? The real one? The one who used to be? Hard to say
what Dan Marino is anymore. Or at least what he will be come in
Jacksonville. But whatever he is in his next game, which he knows
could be his last, everyone around Marino knows who he really is.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best quarterback of all time,'' Thomas said. ``He
plays well when it counts. We all believe in Dan.''
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, they should.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
