<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-EVERETT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERETT NONCOMMITTAL ABOUT HIS SOX FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Almost a month to the day that the Red Sox acquired
Carl Everett from the Houston Astros, their new center fielder
showed up in Boston Thursday for introductions. He left the
impression that he also may take his time deciding whether he wants
to make a long-term commitment to the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I can't count anything out,'' said Everett, who
took off his rust-colored suit jacket to model a Red Sox jersey for
the cameras, then made his first public appearance at the baseball
writers dinner, where he was warmly received. ``I'll weigh all my
options, explore them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to sit here and say I'm boogieing after a year.
I'm the type of guy, I go with the flow. I'm not a demanding type
of guy, but I weigh everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett's agent, Larry Reynolds, said Everett's intentions might
take on more clarity after he sat down for his first negotiating
session with Sox general manager Dan Duquette, who gave up top
shortstop prospect Adam Everett and Single A pitcher Greg Miller
for the 28-year-old switch hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, who was paid $2.8 million by the Astros last season,
can expect to at least double that salary if he exercises his right
to salary arbitration, after a season in which he batted .325, hit
25 home runs, stole 27 bases, and drove in 108 runs.
</P>
<P>
   But with Everett eligible for free agency after next season,
Duquette has said he would like to lock up Everett long-term, as he
did with Pedro Martinez after trading for his righthanded ace under
similar circumstances two years ago. A long-term deal in the
four-to-five year range presumably would cost the Sox in the
neighborhood of $40 million, and that may be conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Everett acknowledged he was caught off-guard when the
division-winning Astros, who claim to be in a money crunch, traded
him. ``My initial reaction was like, `Wow,' '' said Everett. ``I
didn't expect it simply because of the year I had.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's baseball. I look at the business side of it. I take
it in stride.''
</P>
<P>
   But Everett, who got his first chance to play every day with the
Astros, clearly enjoyed Houston, which he said reminded him of his
native Tampa. ``Off the field, I have a real soft personality,'' he
said. ``I like to fish. I'm a real `green' kind of guy. I'm an
outdoor type of person.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett hasn't played in the American League _ he originally was
a No. 1 pick of the Yankees (1990), but was taken by the Marlins in
the 1992 expansion draft and later was traded to the Mets and
subsequently the Astros. But he once roomed with Troy O'Leary in
winter ball in Puerto Rico, was a teammate of Bret Saberhagen on
the Mets, and faced Pedro Martinez in the National League. He
already feels an affinity for the Sox, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the options you have to weigh is, `is it a good fit?'
'' Everett said. ``I'm quite sure, from the teammates I see here,
that they want to win. I want to be on a team that wants to win,
and looking at this team, I see that. To me, I fit in already with
the attitude this team has. That's on the plus side of the whole
thing . . . I don't see any fear in anyone. That's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox also are getting an assist in Tampa from one of
Everett's buddies, whose mother lives here. The friend has been
selling him on the virtues of life here.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a Red Sox fan again,'' Everett said. ``Ever since the
Buckner game (he'd lapsed), but he said `I'm rejuvenated now that
you're here.' He told me that I'm going to love it here, even
though I don't eat seafood. He said it's not what everybody
perceived it to be.''
</P>
<P>
   That was not a reference, Everett said, to Boston's reputation
for not being the most hospitable place for African-American
athletes, but to the intensity of scrutiny athletes receive here.
He was asked about the allegations of child abuse that were brought
against him and his wife, Linda. The charges were subsequently
dropped by a Family Court judge, who ruled that Linda Everett
inflicted ``excessive corporal punishment'' on their two children
and the player did little to stop her. The children, who were
placed in foster care for a time, are back in the custody of their
parents, said Everett, whose wife has given birth to two more
children since.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's three years old _ it's a dead issue,'' Everett said.
``There's nothing to worry about. My kids are here. Other than
that, everything is dead. Just leave it there, and play ball. To
me, it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams said he has not yet decided where Everett
will fit in the middle of the Sox order. Everett is expected either
to hit in the No. 3 hole, ahead of Nomar Garciaparra, or cleanup,
behind the Sox shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like our options a lot,'' Williams said. ``A switch hitter
with power. I'm not a numbers guy, but at times you have to look at
the numbers, and you see with what Carl hit, he brings an awful lot
to the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes to hit with guys on base. He likes to be in the box
when those base runners mean something . . . I think that's big. He
understands how to win, what it means to win, because of where he
comes from.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you can teach that, or how you learn it, but
you can see he has it. You can't touch it, but you can see it and
feel it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 1250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
