<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MR. DOTCOMGUY JUST LIVES FOR THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk about a gimmick. An unassuming fellow in Dallas decides to
lock himself up in an empty house for a year, just one man and a
computer. He can graze in the backyard, but other than that, he's
not allowed to leave for 366 days (remember, this is leap year).
Poor fellow. He can't go out to get a smoothie from 7-Eleven, one
of his favorite activities. But he can use the Internet and a
seemingly unlimited budget to bring in food, clothes, furniture, a
personal trainer, a decorator, musical entertainers _ you know, all
the essentials.
</P>
<P>
   Meet DotComGuy, 26, the wired world's version of P.T. Barnum.
His birth name is Mitch Maddox, but he changed it legally before
moving into what he refers to as the Dotcompound (what else?) on
Jan. 1. He says he's trying to prove that man can survive on
e-commerce alone. So what if he sells a few million ads on the
site? Remember, this is a sociological study conducted by a guy who
reminds us that he is ``blessed with an extremely high IQ, a dry
humor, and a personal demeanor.'' And you, too, can participate.
The whole world is invited to watch DotComGuy's every breathing
moment Webcast live on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Sound like a cure for insomnia? The next best thing to C-Span?
Plenty of journalists have tried similar experiments for a week or
so, and their published accounts have had an unintended narcotic
effect. But oddly enough, www.dotcomguy.com has attracted a cult
following, with 150,000 unique visitors a day. He's had marriage
proposals. Some folks tune in for hours; others have said they need
DotComGuy detox.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the appeal? We needed to know. ``Gosh, this has struck
a nerve bigger than we expected,'' he says when he answers the
phone in the kitchen. Remember, talking to the guy can be a surreal
experience; you can see exactly what he's doing on the Webcam on
his site, which films him from 12 different camera angles. First,
he puts you on the speaker phone and introduces you to the
``viewers,'' then he paces around the house during the
conversation. There you are asking brilliant questions about the
meaning of life, and he's putting strawberries on a chocolate cake.
A viewer gave him the recipe, of course.
</P>
<P>
   His project has been compared to ``The Truman Show'' and ``Ed
TV,'' but the guy himself rejects the comparision. ``This is
real,'' he says, strolling out to the patio. ``This isn't TV. This
is real life. This isn't a soap opera where every day there is a
twist and turn. It's showing that there are real people out there,
just like them, unlike television where everything is so unreal and
no one can relate.''
</P>
<P>
   Dramatic, it's not. See DotComGuy surf the Net. See him buy a
couch. See him hang out with his friend Blaine Twilley, who already
has his own fan club. See him lift weights. See his hair grow.
</P>
<P>
   But DotComGuy says, gosh, he is having the most exciting year of
his life. A band played in his living room the other night, and
tonight he's going to have a slumber party with some of his
buddies. The other day, he didn't have a pen, so the folks in the
chat room took notes as he made a shopping list, and when he later
found a writing implement, they reconstructed his list.
</P>
<P>
   The goal on the Internet is to attract ``eyeballs'' that
``stick'' to a site. And those eyeballs are always there, watching
his every move on the Webcam and deconstructing the minutiae of his
existence in the chat room, which is full 24 hours a day. When the
viewers don't like an interviewer, they make comments like, ``She's
not the next Barbara Walters.'' When UPS makes a delivery, they
guess what's in the box.
</P>
<P>
   Now certainly, Webcams are nothing new. Remember the Jennycam?
And it's certainly no big deal to live off e-commerce _ folks have
been banking, grocery shopping, and even buying bathing suits on
line for years. DotComGuy admits that, but he contends he can teach
valuable lessons about the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Like what? Gosh, maybe he'll teach the viewers how to look up
this very article in the Globe, he explains. He's providing a
service, he continues, for ``people who have disabilities that
cause them to be in my situation where they cannot leave the house.
They're so excited. This is showing that they can live a normal
life and be productive.''
</P>
<P>
   But, DotComGuy, most folks don't have unlimited budgets. Most
folks can't just log onto the Net and order up a storm. Most folks
don't generate revenue from selling banner ads. ``Oh gosh, sure,
definitely,'' he says. But just in case people are interested, he
wants them to know they can tune in to watch his personal trainings
sessions every Monday, Wednesday, and Friday. And he wants to say
hello to all the folks in Boston. The folks in the chat room send
their regards, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send e-mail to: p(dash)hartigan(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
