<HEADLINE>
HARVARD FIELDS A START-UP IN SILICON VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ Tucked among the high-flying venture
capitalists sitting on fabled Sand Hill Road is a sliver of
crimson, a tiny outpost from New England run by Harvard Business
School.
</P>
<P>
   More than just a representation of Harvard's efforts to gain a
toehold in the new economy, its office here in the heart of Silicon
Valley is an acknowledgment that the ascendancy of so-called
``dot-com'' companies is reshaping business education, not just at
Harvard but at business schools around the country.
</P>
<P>
   It is here, in an unassuming three-room office, that two
graduates of the school write case studies on Silicon Valley
companies, cases that help Harvard and other business schools to
make the transition from being factories that churn out consultants
and captains of industry to incubators for entrepreneurs wise in
the ways of risk-taking start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believed there were things happening in Silicon Valley that
were the microcosm of the future,'' said Kim Clark, dean of the
Harvard Business School. ``We believe we needed to build the human
capacity and the organizational capability to tap into that
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Called the California Research Center, the outpost does more
than produce case studies. Along with the school's alumni club, it
also acts as Harvard Business School's hub on the West Coast, a
networking vehicle for 3,500 graduates in the Bay Area and a place
for students and newly minted graduates to seek jobs, advice on how
to start a company or establish connections.
</P>
<P>
   Its mainstay, however, is creating a new generation of cases
that help Harvard update its curriculum to fit the technological
age. Since opening in the summer of 1997, the center's two writers,
Christina Darwall and Nicole Tempest, have produced 48 case
studies, many of which have been disseminated to dozens of business
schools around the world. This year, their dance card is already
filled with 25 cases, and professors now must wait until next year
to add new ones to the list.
</P>
<P>
   The Silicon Valley cases have been used by 70 out of the 200
faculty members at the business school to teach everything from
finance to management theory, in addition to entrepreneurship. ``It
has cut across all sorts of other areas of the curriculum,'' said
Clark, who along with William Sahlman, a Harvard professor of
entrepreneurship, helped set up the center. ``It's effects are
beyond our wildest imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the cases have been mined from the school's formidable
network of alumni, who are ensconced in the top echelons of
companies from eBay Inc. and Yahoo! Inc. to Intel Corp. and
Hewlett-Packard Co. At eBay, for example, Harvard featured Meg
Whitman, the on-line auction company's chief executive and a 1979
graduate of the business school, as the ``protagonist'' in a case
study on the San Jose, Calif. company's libertarian culture.
</P>
<P>
   In general, however, the center is ecumenical in its search for
cases, which feature executives of all stripes, as long as they
demonstrate some key business lesson that can generate discussion
in a classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Running between 15 to 30 pages long, each case is written by a
professor and the center's case writers, Darwall and Tempest. Ideas
can be generated by Darwall and Tempest, both of whom have
connections in the Bay Area from prior jobs, or by professors. The
cases often present real-world dilemmas that require students to
debate various courses of action _ whether to take on additional
business partners, what types of financing to pursue, or when to go
for an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any case should meet at least two objectives,'' said Michael
J. Roberts, senior lecturer at the business school who helped
shepherd the center in its early formation. ``It should capture
what is unique about Silicon Valley, and it should give students
analytical tools and skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the cases feature graduates of Harvard Business School
who have gone on to create companies, an increasingly common path.
``We like it when students pick up the case and they can see
themselves in the protagonist's shoes,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   The center's executive director, Darwall, lists one additional
ingredient in a good case study: tension. Indeed, several of the
cases are rather candid about the shortcomings of the companies
being featured. ``A good case has to have tension, and we make sure
people know that up front,'' said Darwall, who spent the last 25
years in Silicon Valley after graduating from Harvard Business
School in 1975. ``These are not promotional puff pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies, however, get to have final say over whether a case is
released, an option that makes protagonists more forthcoming in the
interviewing process, said Tempest, associate director of the
center. In a way, Silicon Valley's quirky culture makes it easier
for Darwall and Tempest to write cases that illustrate business
failures, which are seen here as something of a badge of honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies here are moving so fast that after three or six
months, it's history. People have moved on,'' said Darwall, who
cofounded a high-tech startup in the mid-1980s. ``Companies are not
at all nervous about water under the bridge, and out here, those
are things that happened two months ago! But for us, it's fresh,
and students love the timeliness.''
</P>
<P>
   Ann Meceda, whose Internet startup's demise in 1997 was disected
several months later in a 1998 case study, was undiminished by the
experience. ``You rarely ever get the opportunity to look backwards
and see what you've learned,'' said Meceda, 28, who sometimes
travels to Harvard to participate in the class discussion of her
case. ``To spend time thinking about about why we made the
decisions that we did was extremely interesting to me. I got more
out of the experience that way.''
</P>
<P>
   For others, the fame garnered from being a Harvard case is
another reward. ``You get a fair degree of notoriety from being in
a case study, and as a start-up, notoriety is good,'' said David
Perry, chief executive and founder of Chemdex.com, an on-line
marketplace for specialty chemicals based in Mountain View, Calif.
``We were struggling for attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry, a 1997 Harvard Business School graduate, said that while
Harvard came a bit late to the Silicon Valley party, the school is
catching on fast. ``Harvard Business School got a late start on
Silicon Valley,'' Perry said. ``If Harvard is to remain on the
edge, they know they've got to have a tight link with Silicon
Valley. It's not a nice-to-have. It's a must-do.''
</P>
<P>
   Others note that the center pulls together many of the school's
resources to create a window on Silicon Valley, what some consider
the world's greatest center of innovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I find amazing is how incredibly strong their network is.
They can pick up the alumni directory and call just about anyone
and get a return call back,'' said Randy Komisar, an Internet
entrepreneur who has worked with the center on several case
studies. ``It's a powerful network, and the center is a node, a
place to crystalize their network in the Valley.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
