<HEADLINE>
ORCHESTRA MORPHINE CARRIES ON TRIO'S LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sunlight streams through the windows of Mark Sandman's
fifth-story loft in Cambridge, Mass., where the remaining members
of his band, Morphine, are rehearsing in his memory. Sandman died
on stage in Italy last summer, but Dana Colley and Billy Conway are
determined to keep his songs alive, and have gathered their friends
and allies into a new group, Orchestra Morphine, which aims to do
just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the fans who followed this group over the years, it's
important to say goodbye and get some closure,'' says Colley, the
baritone saxophonist who helped define Morphine's unique sound,
dubbed ``low rock'' and ``noir jazz-rock,'' during the course of
five albums in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   A sixth is on the way _ an inspired disc called ``The Night,''
finished shortly before Sandman's July 3 death from a heart attack
at a festival at the Giardini del Principe in Palestrina, just east
of Rome. The new songs _ due Feb. 1 on the giant Dreamworks label _
are quintessential Sandman, featuring late-night poetics and a
funky amalgam of styles that summon comparisons to Tom Waits and
Allen Ginsberg rolled into one.
</P>
<P>
   The music was created in this same studio loft _ named the High
`N Dry Studio, though it's anything but high and dry in the way
that instruments and recording gear are spread all over the
spacious, exposed-brick room, which looks out on the Boston
skyline. Morphine posters adorn one corner, while a kind of Sandman
altar is in another, with pictures of him surrounded by
memorabilia, including his odd-looking single-string guitar.
</P>
<P>
   As the sun poured in this week, Orchestra Morphine powerfully
played several tunes from the album, topped by the rollicking ``A
Good Woman Is Hard to Find,'' given fresh energy from having nine
players in the band, as opposed to the three in Morphine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic that Morphine was so stripped down, and this band
is so overloaded,'' says saxophonist Russ Gershon. ``But maybe this
is a good thing, because if it was stripped-down, there would be
too many comparisons, and that would be unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard without Mark, but what can you do?'' says bassist
Mike Rivard. ``Yet it's a great bunch of songs and they deserve to
be played.''
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well, the hope is to return this summer to the same
festival in Italy where Sandman died, as a way of repaying festival
sponsors for the kindness shown during last year's tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking it one step at a time,'' says Colley when asked
if the group will continue beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want people to hear this music,'' says Conway,
Morphine's drummer. ``It's sad that Mark died _ and the sadness is
a pervasive thing _ but there's light in performing these songs.
It's the place where we find new health.''
</P>
<P>
   Orchestra Morphine is an all-star group. Apart from Colley and
Conway, there is Gershon (Sandman's colleague in their side group,
the Hypnosonics), Rivard (who runs the Club d'Elf jam nights around
town), trumpeter Tom Halter, singers Laurie Sargent (originally
with Face to Face) and Christian McNeill (with Hybrasil), drummer
Jerome Dupree (Morphine's original drummer), and keyboardist Evan
Harriman (from the Immortals).
</P>
<P>
   A smaller group of these same musicians was in Moveable Bubble,
which played two memorial tributes to Sandman last year. The group
kept growing, until it became Orchestra Morphine, in which many
members will sing Sandman's songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no one person who can take the place of Mark,'' says
Colley. ``We'll have different singers so there's no pressure on
just one of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The group will play some older Morphine and Hypnosonics tunes
but focus on the new album _ which is more orchestrated than past
Morphine CDs, so the increased size makes sense. It boasts a number
of guests (from cellist Jane Scarpantoni to Cambridge's Mr.
Airplane Man) and some exquisite numbers in the up-tempo ``Top
Floor, Bottom Buzzer'' (about finding a party across town), the
drawling love song ``Like a Mirror'' (``I'm like a mirror/I'm
nothing until you look at me''), the title track ``The Night'' (in
which Sandman describes a potential lover: ``you're a folk tale,
the unexplainable''), and the sexy, Middle Eastern-sounding ``Rope
on Fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandman is gone, but his music is living on.
</P>
<P>
   A Morphine documentary will be shot this year, followed by a
live album released in July, ``Live in St. Andrews Hall,'' recorded
in Detroit in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Duke Ellington and Count Basie passed away, their bands
continued to do their songs,'' says Colley. ``So this is nothing
new _ and we intend to do that with Mark's songs. He left a great
legacy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
