<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-KOHL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALLEN HERO KOHL TRIES TO RIDE OUT FINANCE SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ During the 16 years he was German chancellor, Helmut
Kohl drove his aides crazy whenever he was confronted with a crisis
because his usual response was to do nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aussitzen,'' his aides would whisper, which in German means to
sit and wait until the problem is forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's Aussitzen all over again as Kohl tries to ride out a
campaign finance scandal that has sullied his reputation as one of
Europe's most respected statesmen, torn his Christian Democrat
party apart, and may have irreparably damaged his hand-picked
successor as party leader.
</P>
<P>
   Some have called for Kohl to save the party by resigning and
retiring from public life. Kohl, who stepped down as party leader
but remained in Parliament after losing his bid for a record fifth
term as chancellor in 1998, refuses to go.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl's fall from grace has been as sudden and dramatic as the
allegations of an arms dealer who touched off the scandal by
claiming he gave Kohl's party money that was never declared.
Germans, just getting over the self-congratulatory hoopla that
marked the 10th anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall, are
reeling from the realization that their political system is as
vulnerable to influence peddling as any other in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Kohl was feted here as the leader who presided over
the collapse of the wall and the reunification of Germany, sharing
a stage with George Bush and Mikhail Gorbachev. But within a few
weeks of what amounted to his secular beatification, Kohl was
forced to admit he had stashed at least $1 million in secret
contributions in slush funds between 1993 and 1998. Under a German
law introduced, ironically, by Kohl, political parties are required
to disclose the name of anyone who makes a contribution of roughly
$10,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, people were debating how many streets and
squares across Germany would be named for Kohl. In countless ``end
of the Millennium polls,'' he ranked among the top 10 Germans of
all time, with Albert Einstein and Johann Wolfgang von Goethe. Now,
Christian Democrat candidates running in state elections next month
have asked him to not campaign for them.
</P>
<P>
   It got worse for the party this week. On Monday, Kohl's
handpicked successor as party leader, Wolfgang Schaeuble, admitted
on public television that he had accepted about $50,000 from
Karlheinz Schreiber, the arms dealer whose claims began what could
become the biggest political scandal in Germany since the end of
World War II. Schreiber says the money was to win the government's
support for a tank parts plant in Canada. Schaeuble says he took
the bag of cash from Schreiber but handed it over to the party
treasurer and forgot about it, an explanation few find plausible.
</P>
<P>
   Schaeuble, who has used a wheelchair since a 1990 assassination
attempt and long portrayed as squeaky clean, had sought to distance
himself from Kohl in the past month, but his admission has led some
observers to conclude his career is doomed.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, prosecutors began investigating Kohl's handling
of the contributions, and they want to extradite Schreiber from
Canada to testify. But while Schreiber is not budging from his
story, neither is he budging from Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   While admitting to running party slush funds, Kohl insists he
did nothing sinister and that his government was not for sale. He
said the money was used to cover party expenses. But his refusal to
name the contributors has fed speculation that he has something to
hide. Kohl says he promised the contributors anonymity, and has
called his refusal to name them honorable, not unlawful.
</P>
<P>
   A committee made up of members of the Bundestag will soon begin
hearings aimed at determining whether any of Kohl's decisions as
chancellor were influenced by the secret contributions. Unlike the
criminal investigation, the parliamentary probe will be public and
could drag on for two or three years.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl could face charges that carry up to five years in prison.
While few believe the 69-year-old Kohl will be indicted, much less
convicted, neither would they have believed two months ago that
Kohl would be caught up in such a scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Many Germans seem to accept Kohl's insistence that he did not
personally profit from the contributions. Kohl's love of frugal
comforts is legendary. His weakness is an appetite for saumagen,
pig's stomach. Unlike his successor as chancellor, Gerhard
Schroeder, who has been married four times, Kohl has been married
to the same woman for nearly half a century. He and his family
vacation yearly at the same place, Lake Wolfgangsee in Austria.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal that has engulfed Kohl and threatens to destroy his
party has stunned many Germans who thought their democracy was
beyond the petty corruption common in much of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Harald Grunert and Friedel Drautzburg run what is arguably
Berlin's most politically wired bar and restaurant, Standige
Vertretung, a mecca for politicians and natives of Kohl's beloved
Rhineland. The pair used to run Gambrinus, a political haunt in
Bonn, but when the government decided to move from Bonn to Berlin,
they moved, too. At Standige Vertretung, the walls are lined with
photographs of German politicians, and patrons throw back small
glasses of kolsch, a light beer, in an atmosphere where politics is
taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Grunert says many of his patrons, pols and ordinary people
alike, are glum and disillusioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew this sort of thing happens in other countries, but a
lot of people are shocked that it can happen in Germany,'' Grunert
said, standing next to a photo of Kohl which shows him,
uncharacteristically, grinning like a Cheshire cat. ``A lot of
people don't want to know about it. They'd prefer we ignore it
until it goes away.''
</P>
<P>
   Kohl may be banking on that old tactic, Aussitzen. Sitting in a
restaurant here, Wolfgang Kammler, 60, and his wife, Baibel, 58,
say they are not happy about the revelations, but not especially
angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more relaxed about it,'' Wolfgang Kammler says. He says he
is willing to overlook what Kohl did, but not Schaeuble.
</P>
<P>
   Baibel Kammler said she had already tired of the media's
obsession with the story. She said she and her friends avoid
discussing it.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his office a few hundred yards from Brandenberg Gate,
Guenter Nooke cannot avoid discussing it. As the Christian Democrat
representative in the Bundestag for the Mitte and Prenzlauer Berg
sections of east Berlin, Nooke knows the scandal will dominate
German politics, perhaps for years.
</P>
<P>
   Nooke is among those who say Kohl should not step down. But
Nooke says he favors Kohl naming the contributors, and cannot
understand why some of those contributors have not come forward to
save Kohl the humiliation he is enduring.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal has been a welcome diversion for Schroeder and his
Social Democrats, who had been reeling from a series of state
election losses last year. Before the scandal broke, the
conservative Christian Democrats were neck and neck in the polls
with the more liberal Social Democrats, and serious commentators
questioned whether Schroeder's coalition could last until the 2002
election.
</P>
<P>
   But Nooke and other Christian Democrats take some solace in the
lack of enthusiasm the Social Democrats have shown in fanning the
flames against Kohl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lack of fierce attacks from the other side suggests they
have skeletons of their own in some closet,'' said Nooke. ``There's
a larger issue here about campaign financing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nooke says party activists are more upset about the scandal than
ordinary voters, many of whom remain loyal to Kohl.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls suggest that about 90 percent of Germans now
believe that all German parties keep secret accounts and all
parties engage in what can loosely be described as corruption.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 1257EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6095 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-GIRL-BOS &LR;      01-14 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GIRL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GIRL, INTERRUPTED' TAKES SOME UNEXPECTED DETOURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
GIRL, INTERRUPTED 
Directed by: James Mangold 
Screenplay by: Mangold, Lisa Loomer and Anna Hamilton Phelan, based
on Susanna Kaysen's memoir 
Starring: Winona Ryder, Angelina Jolie, Vanessa Redgrave, Whoopi
Goldberg, Clea Duvall, Brittany Murphy, Elisabeth Moss, Jared Leto,
Jeffrey Tambor, Travis Fine, Jillian Armanette, Angela Bettis 
Rated: R (strong language and content relating to drugs,
sexualitry, and suicide) 
Running time: 125 minutes 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yes and no on James Mangold's film of Susanna Kaysen's ``Girl,
Interrupted.'' First the pluses, because I think they deserve
precedence. The pluses after Winona Ryder in the title role, that
is. It's difficult to imagine any actress today bringing more
sentience and intelligence to her role here as stand-in for the
17-year-old Kaysen in 1967. That Mangold has fashioned an honorable
film from Kaysen's memoir of her two years spent at McLean Hospital
in Belmont when she shuttled between _ in her image _ the parallel
universes of madness and so-called real life, is no small
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   The book is a string of vignettes, sharp-eyed recollections and
insights thrown into high relief with a gift for detail that marks
Kaysen as a natural writer. Without wanting to violate the tone or
sensibility of the book, Mangold, nevertheless, was faced with
turning it into a narrative. Some of Mangold's biggest successes
lie in the realm of what he has avoided. One anticipates a
skewering of psychiatry and at least some of its assumptions,
especially the ones based on the lopsided power relationship
between the medical establishment, which has it all, and the
patient, who has none. One needn't be a feminist to hear mental
alarm buzzers upon learning that one of the things that landed
Kaysen in McLean was promiscuity. When was the last time a man was
committed for that?
</P>
<P>
   But ``Girl, Interrupted'' has no intention of setting itself up
as a feminist ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest,'' with the
establishment as villain, drugging into submission anybody who
exceeded its narrow parameters of tolerable deviation. The medical
establishment depicted here remains observed through a prism of the
times, which is to say it emerges as merely obtuse, not evil. While
facing up to the fact that there was reason to believe that Kaysen
was genuinely depressed and posed a danger to herself, Mangold
takes his cue from her wittily reverberant observation that the
keepers were clueless and the patients had to be their own finders.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Girl, Interrupted'' neither glamorizes insanity by falsely
propagating the idea that the mentally ill see things more clearly
than the rest of us nor puts histrionic spin on that most
pernicious of Western myths, the noble savage. So far, so good. The
noble savage myth, with its corollary canonization of the mentally
ill, has always seemed to me nothing better than a convenient piece
of guilt-removing payback for colonialism. (It's also an
increasingly obsolete totem; what we need is a different paradigm,
one that suits what is about to be our revved-up competitiveness
with Europe and a revived Asia, not the looting of lands populated
by trusting people.) Mangold wisely avoids conventional critiques
of psychiatry, feminist and otherwise, because that's not what the
book is about.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the atmosphere of brittle camaraderie he does create,
he also avoids any hint that he's trying to fob off on us a pajama
party, a modern ``Little Women,'' but with bars on the windows. So
he's got the right idea _ don't be swerved off the book. But right
there on page 36, Kaysen spells out the pitfall when she writes:
``My motives were weak.'' As she herself saw at the time, she was
depressed, and more confused than pathological. Her suicide attempt
consisted of taking 50 aspirin, and it was just the luck of the
draw that the doctor she saw clapped her into a taxi and sent her
off to McLean as opposed to prescribing medication and handling her
case on an out-patient basis.
</P>
<P>
   She's the central figure, but she's also the least troubled of
the characters we meet. Most of the time, she's detached,
clear-eyed, acute, (rightly) pretty confident that she'll soon be
out of McLean (she was admitted in October, 1967, discharged in
January, 1969), quite aware that all she has to do is stay cool
during this respite from the pressures of life outside. Only the
fact that we keep wondering what's going on behind Ryder's big
hungry eyes prevents the film from being stolen away entirely by
Angelina Jolie in the much showier role of a charmismatic woman
named Lisa, who has panache, is a natural leader, thrillingly
nervy, and in a lot more trouble than Ryder's Kaysen because she,
Lisa, is a sociopath.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the big-screen Kaysen is that, dramatically,
she is given no compelling arc. The other patients _ most notably
Elisabeth Moss's burn victim, Polly, and Brittany Murphy's dutiful
daughter, Daisy, bent on meeting her father's demands _ have real
problems, to say nothing of Lisa. Jolie deserves nothing less than
a best supporting actress Oscar nomination for her high-voltage
performance and also for remembering to dull her wild eyes to
remind us that Lisa's sexiness can go only so far to divert
attention from her disorder (she's not a free soul being squelched
_ she's in undeniable trouble).
</P>
<P>
   It would be frivolous and wrong-headed to trivialize Kaysen's
youthful troubles in making the jump from adolescence to adulthood,
to hint that they may have been at least in part attibutable to
self-indulgence, or to discount them because she came from a
privileged background. But Ryder's integrity in muting the alarm
bells is going to work against her in terms of generating audience
empathy. She's only just a little unruly. She can pull back. Lisa,
Polly and Daisy can't. There's a lot of skilled, responsible work
on screen in ``Girl, Interrupted'' (which, incidentally, was filmed
on unused portions of an institution in Harrisburg, Penn.).
Ironically, though, the vibe it transmits is the one that usually
attaches to castigated institutions in movies. There's too much
control in it, and not enough danger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
