<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6097 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-HURRICANE     01-14 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-HURRICANE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DENZEL WASHINGTON A STEADY FORCE IN `HURRICANE' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Movies based on living people are a morass of trouble. If
they're slavish to the facts, the results can be episodic and lack
dramatic tension. If they're not slavish enough, the film's living
counterparts scream betrayal and blab appropriately to the press.
Rare is the movie that balances truth with fiction, accuracy with
narrative power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hurricane'' comes close. Despite a very public flap in
recent weeks over the film's simplification, elimination or frank
mutilation of the facts, Norman Jewison's startlingly effective
biography of prizefighter Rubin ``The Hurricane'' Carter finds a
consistent, combustible balance between telling his story and
lending it literary fire.
</P>
<P>
   It is not wholly accurate and should not _ could not, will not _
be mistaken for a documentary on boxing and the New Jersey justice
system. No chance of that. But like every good story, ``The
Hurricane'' informs the facts with a deeper truth, the truth of
metaphor and human meaning. And in that it is a triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Based on two sources _ ``Lazarus and the Hurricane,'' by Sam
Chaiton and Terry Swinton, and Carter's own memoir _ ``The
Hurricane'' features a revelatory star turn by Denzel Washington as
the middleweight boxing champ who spent 20 years in prison for
murders he didn't commit. Washington has always been a great actor,
and he's always been a sympathetic actor, but never before has his
greatness thrown such a warm light.
</P>
<P>
   If ``The Hurricane'' succeeds, it succeeds on the grit and heart
in Washington's performance and on his delicately touching scenes
with the extraordinary Vicellous Reon Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon plays Lesra, a teen-ager who reads Carter's memoir
(``The Sixteenth Round'') and, moved by his story, writes to him in
prison. The two strike up a correspondence that blossoms into
heartfelt friendship, which inspires Lesra to introduce Carter to
three friends and guardians (John Hannah, Liev Schreiber and
Deborah Kara Unger) who resolve to get him out of prison. (Two of
said friends went on to write the book mentioned above. One,
Unger's character, married and eventually divorced Carter. None of
this is alluded to in the film, although Washington and Unger have
a certain snazzy chemistry.) Lest all of this confuse and worry
you, rest assured: ``The Hurricane'' is a film about Rubin Carter,
not about the three yuppie do-gooders who rescue him from
immurement. It is not, to put a label on it, yet another virtuous
white folks save victimized black folks movie. Lesra's earnest
Canadian guardians do come across as a wee bit dippy and easily
qualify as the film's weakest links. But they're not disposable;
they taught Lesra to read; without them, Lesra's own story would
make little sense. And without Lesra, Carter's transformation from
hardened jailbird into a man of hope and love would prove far less
dramatic. It'd be missing half its heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hate put me in here,'' says Carter to Lesra in a scene (one of
several) that jerks huge tears. ``Love is gonna bust me out.''
</P>
<P>
   Such unabashed emotion fills the screenplay (by co-producer
Armyan Bernstein and Dan Gordon, who wrote the uneven but
shattering prison drama ``Murder in the First''), which bumps
around from Carter in prison to Lesra at home to Carter in
prizefight flashbacks, pulverizing opponents in black and white
(i.e., ``Raging Bull'') verite.
</P>
<P>
   In roughly linear fashion we follow Carter from his first,
tragic brush with the law and subsequent incarcerations through his
exultant rise as middleweight boxing champion. When he and a young
acquaintance are arrested for the murders of three white people in
a New Jersey bar, the film zooms us through the justice system and
whisks us off to prison, where Carter strips himself of emotion and
gets down to the unforgiving business of serving three life
sentences. He becomes a machine: His task is to endure his time,
nothing more. Enter Lesra.
</P>
<P>
   So much works with ``The Hurricane'' _ Washington's performance,
Shannon's performance, Clancy Brown's in a small role, Rod
Steiger's in an even smaller (but razor-sharp) one _ that the
film's sagging conventions and simplistic good-vs.-evil moralizing
barely matter.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hedaya has the unenviable job of playing the film's chief
tormentor, a heinous, racist sheriff who tampers with witnesses in
his quest to brand Carter Public Enemy No. 1. The guy would be
awful enough without turning him into Tony Soprano, but there he
is, age spots affixed in the final act, rasping pro-forma death
threats to the crusading Canadians.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the film nicely avoids other plot devices, spending
mercifully little time with Carter's early home life and treating
his prison scenes with compassion and firm restraint. (There is no
shower rape scene.) Jewison's direction has never been flashy _
from ``Moonstruck'' to ``Rollerball,'' story has always topped
style _ and his work in ``The Hurricane'' is characteristically
meat-and-potatoes. There's nothing new here; there's no frenzy of
innovation, no obsessive virtuosity (as in the incoherent
``Magnolia'') that mucks up the tale being told.
</P>
<P>
   It's simply a well-told, well-acted, viscerally satisfying
story. Conventional it is. Flaws it has. Weepy it may be. It's
nevertheless a gut-socking motion picture, a moving paean to the
power of justice and yet more proof that Denzel Washington is one
of his era's finest talents.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 1259EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6099 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIES-FANTASIA-BOS &LR;      01-14 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-FANTASIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FANTASIA/2000' A MIXED BAG OF COMPUTER WIZARDRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
FANTASIA/2000 
Animation directed by: Pixote Hunt, Hendel Butoy, Eric Goldberg,
James Algar, Francis Glebas, Gaetan Brizzi 
Music by: Beethoven, Respighi, Gershwin, Shostakovich, Saint-Saens,
Dukas, Elgar, Stravinsky 
Performed by: Chicago Symphony Orchestra, James Levine conducting;
Itzhak Perlman, violin soloist 
Hosted by: Levine, Steve Martin, Bette Midler, Perlman, James Earl
Jones, Angela Lansbury, Quincy Jones, Penn and Teller 
Running time: 75 minutes 
Rated: G 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seeing ``Fantasia/2000'' shouldn't be about the
visual and aural wraparound experience. The aesthetic experience _
conception, execution _ should be all. What's being delivered
should be what it's all about, not the delivery system. But part of
what's being delivered here is the delivery system. So it does
matter. People who see the usual IMAX nature films come away wowed
by just how much nature comes at them in an IMAX presentation. The
new ``Fantasia/2000,'' with seven new segments and a reprised
Mickey Mouse in ``The Sorcerer's Apprentice,'' is in part a
demonstration of just what Disney's artists can do with their new
computerized toys. Some of it is impressive, some seems
undersupplied. In baseball terms, it's a two-bagger, but not a home
run.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney intended to update and release ``Fantasia'' every
few years, but World War II intervened. ``Fantasia'' was a flop
that didn't move into the black until its abstract patternings made
it a money-making head movie in 1969, and music education itself
took a leap forward in the intervening years _ partly due to
``Fantasia.'' Its signature frame is the one in which conductor
Leopold Stokowski is shown shaking hands with Mickey Mouse before
conducting the Philadelphia Orchestra. ``Fantasia'' was kitsch from
the start. And the music was truncated. But Stokowski fulfilled a
function few conductors could have. He was the most unabashedly
hammy of conductors, whose flamboyance earned him armies of
detractors. Yet he possessed artistic credentials that meant he had
to be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   So he bridged a gap. James Levine, who mostly conducts the
Metropolitan Opera, but who has a history with the Chicago
Symphony, brings ease and poise to his interlocutor's role here
with that orchestra. And the new Disney masterminds have had the
good sense to divide the hosting among a handful of savvy, engaging
pros, ranging from Steve Martin to Bette Midler, to Quincy Jones to
Angela Lansbury to Penn &AMP; Teller, who drolly reintroduce what these
days looks like a very grainy Mickey Mouse, in his borrowed pointy
hat with the stars and the moons, trying to turn the magic off
before the brooms flood the sorcerer's lair with the pails of water
Mickey can't make them stop carrying in.
</P>
<P>
   If the grainy ``Sorcerer's Apprentice'' was included to offer
contrast to today's technical razzle-dazzle, provide continuity,
and repeat sci-fi's usual reactionary warning to avoid
venturesomeness, the seven new episodes more than once genuflect to
it. Stylistically, they spend more time looking back than forward.
The geometric shapes that morph into butterflies and bats in the
first section (to Beethoven's Fifth) seem perfunctory, less
compelling than the corresponding abstractions accompanying
Stokowski's Bach in the original. The flamingos dancing to
Saint-Saens' ``Carnival of the Animals,'' if no less inspired than
the hippos twinkle-toeing their way through Ponchielli's ``Dance of
the Hours,'' are certainly no more inspired.
</P>
<P>
   The kinetic, propulsive segment set to Stravinsky's 1919
``Firebird'' Suite (second _ and leanest _ of three he extracted
from the full score), depicting a pagan goddess regenerating the
earth after a volcanic firebird consumes it in flames, seems to owe
more to the demon rising up out of Mussorgsky's ``Night on Bald
Mountain'' than, to, say, the more recent and more innovative take
on nature in ``Princess Mononoke,'' or even this new Firebird's
purported source, the reappearance of plant life on the slopes of
Mount Saint Helens. It works as spectacle, and works best of all
with its music, whooshing through its motions as slickly as
``Tarzan.'' Yet, it typifies much in the new ``Fantasia/2000'' in
that it seems more intent on establishing a firm link to the
traditional Disney house style than to pushing into challengingly
innovative territory.
</P>
<P>
   The segment in which Donald Duck acts as a gatekeeper for Noah,
ushering pairs of animals into the Ark to Elgar's Pomp and
Circumstance Marches and nearly losing Daisy in the process, is
attractive enough, but it's just there, never really leaping off
the screen in any way that surprises and delights. Although there
are satisfactions, there are no surprises, either _ I wish there
were _ in the chapter played out to Gershwin's ``Rhapsody in Blue''
by characters from the pen of Broadway's legendary Line King, Al
Hirschfeld. New York never rides higher than on the music of
Gershwin, and Hirschfeld's drawings, with their elegant panache,
are in themselves a logo for Manhattan glamour. I only wish Disney
could have figured out a way for Hirschfeld to dot the lively but
modest Jazz Age vignettes with his unique takes on a few period
celebs. The closest we get is a rich woman's henpecked husband, who
suggests Alexander Wollcott doing a Walter Mitty number.
</P>
<P>
   I have saved the best for last: Hendel Butoy's two striking
segments that utilize the computer's ability to convey an almost
lunar stillness and isolation. Setting Hans Christian Andersen's
``The Steadfast Tin Soldier'' to the Allegro from Shostakovich's
Piano Concerto No. 2 freshens the film's traditional spirit with a
classy, affecting, arguably even existential interplay between a
mechanical ballerina, a menacing jack-in-the-box, and the brave
little one-legged tin soldier. Despite its heightened technical
finesse, there isn't as much to the new ``Fantasia'' as there was
to the old one, but the ``Tin Soldier'' segment, plus the remake's
most beautiful section, involving a pod of whales rising out of the
sea to serenely float like zeppelins amid clouds, make it mandatory
viewing. If the cool blues and greens don't get you, the trancy
mystery of it all surely will. Set to Respighi's ``Pines of Rome,''
it reminds us that it's much easier to set a riveting ballet to a
piece of second-rate music than to a towering masterpiece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
