<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COLTS' STRIDE LOOKS SUPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With all the NFL coaching changes in recent weeks, CBS analysts
Dan Dierdorf and Phil Simms say, don't expect to ever again hear a
coach say his team will be great in two or three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it's going now, there'll be at least five job openings
at the end of each regular season,'' said Dierdorf, who will share
the broadcast booth with play-by-play man Verne Lundquist for
Saturday's Miami-Jacksonville game.
</P>
<P>
   Simms, who'll work Sunday's Tennessee-Indianapolis contest with
Greg Gumbel, lamented the good old days when owners and fans had a
little more patience. ``Building a team is out of the question,''
Simms said. ``With free agency and player movement, teams have to
win right away. It's like everything else: People want instant
gratification. They have to be great now. They can't wait until
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierdorf, a Hall of Famer, recalled his playing days as a St.
Louis Cardinal in the '70s on one of the greatest offensive lines
ever assembled. ``The five of us played as a unit for six straight
seasons,'' he said. ``That will never happen again. And the burden
falls on the shoulders of the coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Jesse Jackson's protest of Green Bay's firing of coach
Ray Rhodes, Dierdorf was dismissive. ``To think that (Packers
general manager) Ron Wolf is all of a sudden a racist after he
hired Rhodes a year ago is absurd,'' Dierdorf said. ``To suggest
that the firing of Rhodes has anything to do with other than wins
and losses is absolutely ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Simms attributed the move to Rhodes's inability to get the most
out of his star players. ``That's what cost Rhodes his job,'' he
said. ``Players are always complaining about tough disciplinarian
coaches like (Bill) Parcells and (Mike) Holmgren. Let me tell you
something: If you hear players talking about how much they like
their coach, fire the coach.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CBS paying price
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press is reporting that longtime NBC announcer
Dick Enberg is close to signing a deal with CBS to do play-by-play
for the NFL, college basketball, US Open tennis, and golf. No
telling how much Enberg is costing the network, but one thing is
clear: Letting Sean McDonough go to clear the table for Enberg was
already too costly . . . John Rocker granted ESPN's Peter Gammons
an interview and, surprise, the controversial Atlanta Braves
reliever stated that he is not a racist. ``If I was a racist,'' he
said, ``would I want a black guy living in my house and would I
invite him to come to my house? I did that three times over.''
Racist or not, Rocker is stupid. Gammons later asked him what he
would think if he heard someone else make the kind of comments that
Sports Illustrated quoted him as saying. ``I'd think he was a
complete jerk,'' Rocker said. ``Who the heck does this guy think he
is, mouthing off like this? What kind of experiences does he have
to talk from? And if I could just take a second: It's not going to
justify my comments by any means, because I'll reiterate again and
apologize one more time to anybody I've offended. It certainly was
not my intent.'' Whatever, John.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anchoring down at NESN
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New England Sports Network has hired Wendi Nix as Jayme Parker's
co-anchor on ``NESN SportsDesk: The Weekend Edition.'' Nix comes
from WPDE-TV in South Carolina, where she worked as a general
assignment news reporter. Before that, she earned a master's degree
in Sports Management from the University of Massachusetts . . . ABC
Sports has hired Loren Matthews as senior vice president of
programming. Matthews was executive vice president of ESPN Regional
television . . . ABC Sports and Panasonic will work together to
broadcast the 2000 National Hockey League All-Star Game in HDTV
(high definition television) on Feb. 6 . . . New England Cable News
is launching a new nightly show, ``Sports Late Night,'' with hosts
Kristen Mastroianni, Steve Buckley, and Chris Collins. The show
airs at 11, for 30 minutes on weeknights and an hour on weekends .
. . Talk about cheap shots. ESPN the Magazine's Tony Kornheiser
writes: ``How about Chris Weinke agonizing over whether he should
pass up his senior season and go to the NFL. What's he waiting for,
his AARP card? He could be the first NFL draft choice to be
collecting his pension while he's playing.'' All right. It's kind
of funny.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
