<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES OF A LADY IN MOTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRESTON, Miss. &UR;  &LR; _ Several relatives of my grandmother, Lolee
Roberts, hunkered down at the breakfast table. We had to bury her
in four hours. It was the responsibility of the grandchildren to
say a tribute at the service.
</P>
<P>
   We recalled that Lolee Roberts was a grandmother of perpetual
motion, feeding and shooing chickens, checking the coop for fresh
eggs, shucking peas, grinding corn feed and so we thought in a flip
generality, cooking. This got Uncle Leonard cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Leonard was the only son of Lolee Roberts. Contrary to
assumptions about rural Southern women and soul food, Uncle Leonard
said grandmother really did not like to cook. When he said what she
liked the most, the table was stone silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have this image of mother that is frozen in my mind, and I
remember it just like yesterday,'' Uncle Leonard said. ``It was one
of those steaming hot summer days when she came back from picking
cotton. She had her sack slung over her back. Sweat was streaming
down her face from out under her straw hat. Her hands had scratches
and trickles of blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got to the door and said, `I love this.' I'll never forget
those words. `I love this.' Here she is, doing this hard, hot,
painful work, and she says, `I love this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, we had our speech. But the revelation about
grandmother was so much more. Uncle Leonard delivered a bolt of
lightning so hot in its truth, it fused our souls at the table.
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Leonard is a retired aerospace publications production
manager. Of the four grandchildren, one sells real estate in the
Dallas area. Another works at an auto assembly plant in Detroit and
has an excavation business on the side with a backhoe in mother's
backyard. Another is a newspaper columnist. The fourth hooks up
video/audio equipment for conventions and business meetings in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   It would be facile to say that all of us like or love our jobs
equally, but looking at it another way, not a single word last
weekend was spent complaining about our chosen lines of sweat. Not
over grandmother's grave. Not over the grave of someone who,
because of segregation, did not have our choices.
</P>
<P>
   Not when you are burying someone who comes in from labors so
hard and humble and says, ``I love this.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Luther King Jr. once said, ``If a man is called to be a
street sweeper, he should sweep streets even as Michaelangelo
painted, or Beethoven composed music, or Shakespeare wrote poetry.
He should sweep streets so well that all the hosts of heaven and
earth will pause to say, here lived a great street sweeper who did
is job well.''
</P>
<P>
   The post-King world is one where we rarely celebrate the street
sweeper, instead musing in tremendous volume last year on the
passings of celebrities like John Kennedy Jr., or Wilt Chamberlain.
The departure of people like Lolee Roberts, 87, farm wife, cotton
picker, chicken shooer and well-water carrier would ordinarily be
marked with a tiny local newspaper obituary.
</P>
<P>
   But who knows what percentage of dedication in this world is
actually spawned by women like grandmother as compared to the
elites? For instance, in a word where too many young people put
money over their hearts in choosing a career, I tell college
students that I love journalism because it is fun. I tell them
whatever you do, do it because it is fun.
</P>
<P>
   Yet I never quite understood where I got that sense of fun from
since I was surrounded in Milwaukee by adults who told us they
worked long hours in factories precisely so we would not have to
take such jobs. They too did their job well, but they'd cut you up
if you dared suggest it was ``fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet here is this image of grandmother, in the midst of the very
work that African-Americans fled North from, and saying ``I love
this.'' It is hard to believe that all of the work she did was
``fun'' in the childish sense, but what she was did was make the
most out of her piece of property, precious in a Mississippi where
she could not vote for her first 50 years of her life.
</P>
<P>
   You can easily chart how her attitude spawned. Uncle Leonard
tried singing before landing in aerospace. My mother Doris earned a
two-year degree in accounting 20 years after high school. My Aunt
Mae Kather, in her mid-60s and long done with her six kids, had
four foster boys when I visited her last fall.The perpetual motion
never stopped. The sweat never stopped dripping. Even in the vacant
depths of a decade of Alzheimer's disease, her work was not done.
</P>
<P>
   I took my 9-year-old son to see grandmother a month and a half
ago. I did not know what the meeting meant to him at the time. When
we told him last week that his great-grandmother had died, he
slumped in the couch as if he really knew her.
</P>
<P>
   Because of what Uncle Leonard said, I think I know why.
Somewhere, deep in the vacant depths, Lolee Roberts would not let
go of life. My son could sense it. As ludicrous as it might seem,
it was as if what precious little was left of her brain reached out
to her great-grandchild and said, ``I love this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Boston Globe columnist; his e-mail address
is djacks(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
