<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036 . )  
 EX-LOTUS CHIEF NOW A FULL-BLOWN VENTURE CAPITALIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLEST STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a type you are sure to find in any room full of
Internet venture capitalists: high energy mixed with a certain edge
just below the surface, flawless business-school pedigree, and a
preternaturally youthful appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Mitch Kapor.
</P>
<P>
   Kapor, the legendary founder of Lotus Development Corp.,
advocate for social causes in the real and virtual worlds,
respected technology visionary, onetime mental health counselor and
teacher of transcendental meditation who decades ago left MIT's
Sloan School of Management one term short of a degree, has jumped
into the big-money venture capital world with both feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have good radar for things coming over the
horizon,'' he said in an interview from the modest Kendall Square
office of Kapor Enterprises, a few blocks from Lotus headquarters
in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Kapor said his name often rings a bell with people who
can't quite place it. Many don't even associate him with Lotus. But
at a peak in the 1980s, Kapor was the best-known Boston leader in
the personal computer revolution, often mentioned in the same
breath with Bill Gates or Steve Jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Kapor, 49, has worked for the last year as a partner at Accel
Partners, a high-tech venture firm based in Palo Alto, dividing his
time between Boston and California. He is serving on boards of or
directly involved with four companies and will step down this month
as the director of a fifth, Allaire Corp. of Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Kapor's evolution into a full-blown venture capitalist stems
from more than four dozen private equity investments he made
personally since resigning as chief executive at Lotus in 1986.
Along with some bombs, Kapor scored several big early-stage hits
and brought them to Accel because they needed the support a venture
capital firm can offer.
</P>
<P>
   Kapor was an early investor in UUNet Technologies, later
acquired by MCI Worldcom Inc., and RealNetworks Inc., maker of the
software that brings audio and video to computer screens via the
Internet. He brought them both to Accel when they needed more help.
After six years investing with Accel as a limited partner, he
decided to join the firm full time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was doing angel investing before anyone called it angel
investing, before it became so popular,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the choices didn't go nearly so well. Kapor briefly ran
ON Technology Corp. in Waltham, Mass. with little success. His
ground-floor involvement in GO Corp., a big-concept business bust,
was chronicled in a book widely read throughout the high-tech
world, ``Startup: A Silicon Valley Adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapor said the setbacks taught him more than his winners as an
investor. ``I learned about timing, not being ahead of the market.
I learned a lot about focus. I learned about different investing
styles.''
</P>
<P>
   He learned what he liked and what was distasteful about the
venture capital world and the billions it sinks into the corporate
seeds of the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like huge challenges but I don't like the
swing-for-the-fences investment style that says get a world-class
team, have a big idea, get a big-name VC, create huge strategic
alliances, pump up your burn rate (your spending) to millions of
dollars per month and either it works or it doesn't,'' said Kapor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You find yourself being compelled by the business logic to do
things that shuffle people around like they're pawns on a
chessboard. That's outside the bounds of what I consider to be good
outcomes.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is the way of much of technology venture investing
today. Huge sums chasing the Internet's earliest investments,
pouring as much as $1 billion into individual funds, are forcing
managers to make increasingly larger bets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it's a boom time,'' Kapor said. ``There are huge
excesses that happen and there's certainly a lot of that going on
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapor is working with a handful of early-stage companies,
including HotDispatch Inc. of Cambridge, an on-line marketplace for
technology expertise, and aQuery of Somerville, Mass., a
search-technology company that came out of the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most intriguing is Groove Networks of Beverly, Mass.,
run by Lotus Notes software creator Ray Ozzie. It isn't clear yet
what Groove Networks is doing, and Kapor, an early investor, won't
say much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an ambitious technical project with a lot of people in it
doing something that has a similar innovation challenge level to
Notes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kapor said he tries to choose companies with the chance to
generate something new and compelling for its customers. The
paybacks: money, help with a long-term view, and less immediate
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost everything we do makes some amount of money, which
means we never walk away from things,'' he said of Accel. ``You can
argue economically that's sub-optimal. We don't have that culture
and it's one of the things that makes it possible for me to be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Among his other interests are the Mitchell Kapor Foundation,
which he said he has funded with ``a good chunk'' of his net worth.
It has funded environmental health work but plans to make grants
for projects related to Internet public policy.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Kapor if he would like to be back in the saddle, running a
company of his own again, and you will hear a mixed message. It's
too consuming, it doesn't fit with his life now. And so on.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've thought about it,'' he said with a grin. ``I've had
fantasies about it. It's probably the Warren Beatty answer: No
plans at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
