<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6122 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-GIRL-HNS &LR;      01-14 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-GIRL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `GIRL INTERRUPTED' EXPLORES A WORLD OF TORMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There wasn't a lot of screaming described in Susanna Kaysen's
memoir of her stay in a mental institution. But since director
James Mangold doesn't seem to know how to convey ``crazy,'' he's
added wall-to-wall shrieking as a bonus of his film adaptation of
``Girl, Interrupted,'' Kaysen's fragmented confessional.
</P>
<P>
   In Mangold's hands, it becomes a noisy statement less about the
distinction between insanity and simply having difficulty living in
the world and more like a glossy handbook on how to make some new
girlfriends at mental camp.
</P>
<P>
   The beautifully explained source of the book's title (a Vermeer
painting) has been jettisoned, and Kaysen's stream-of-consciousness
remembrances have been paved into a dramatic narrative complete
with a melodramatic finale that would shame Susan Hayward. But for
all Mangold and co-writers Lisa Loomer and Anna Hamilton Phelan's
simplifications, he refuses to indulge the darker, florid passages
in Kaysen's prose.
</P>
<P>
   In Winona Ryder's case, ``Girl Interrupted'' is a showcase in
which her brittle, angry portrait shows she has graduated from
ingenue to actress. Mangold, who made ``Copland'' in 1997, may not
have been able to say anything substantial about personality
disorder, but Ryder as an incarnation of Kaysen's twentysomething
self is a one-woman brokedown palace of self-doubt, self-loathing
and yes _ as Hollywood would have it _ self-discovery. But in the
most convincing work she's done so far, moments that could easily
have had the emotional wallop of a girl-scout training film are
endowed with pathos and sinew simply in the way Ryder contorts her
lines.
</P>
<P>
   In Ryder, Mangold knows he has something close to scrappy
divinity, so he uses her not simply as the movie's narrative
fulcrum but as its stylistic one as well. The film is set in 1967,
and, as photographed by Jack Green, looks like something from that
late-'60s-early-to-mid-'70s period fashioned by Cassavetes and
Polanski. The lighting is soft, establishing shots are nonexistent.
We see just striking close-ups of Ryder's Susanna completely lost
in the activity of her busy house, harangued by her mother (Joanna
Kerns), shaken by an affair with a friend's father and sharing her
thoughts on existence with her lover (Jared Leto). People talk to
Susanna across time, and Mangold uses that call-and-response
editing technique to erase the seams in her reality.
</P>
<P>
   Susanna is bewildered by her inability to catch up with the
world happening outside her head, and Ryder makes Susanna's
disorientation seem like a playground ride she can't get off. When
a shrink (Curtwood Smith) confronts her in a session about her
possible suicide attempt, Kevin Tent's editing slows down and Ryder
looks cornered in one long, claustrophobic take. Minutes later,
Susanna is booked for delusion and is headed to the psych wing of
Claymore Hospital (changed from the book's famous McLean).
</P>
<P>
   Claymore is a haven for Massachusetts' most wayward upper-
middle-class girls. And Mangold presents the place as a revolving
door of actual and affected derangement. Each girl appears to
suffer some imbalance, a combo of eating disorder and severe
paranoia resulting in her complete disempowerment, and the fierce
cast playing these girls seem to be gorging themselves on air and
scraps. Brittany Murphy's Daisy is addicted to laxatives and has a
horrible secret involving the storage of roast chicken carcasses,
and Janet (Angela Bettis) is just straight-up anorexic.
</P>
<P>
   The ward's bully is an emaciated hellion named Lisa, played with
equal parts menace and reserve by Angelina Jolie, who's so thin
here the screaming she has to do wipes her out. Lisa is the
``notice me'' one in a stable of dynamic characters, but Jolie
doesn't burn down the house. In a blond wig of coarse hair, she may
look like a rock groupie in rehab, but she plays Lisa with the
frailty and volatility of a Billie Holiday record. She pulls
people's strings and pushes their buttons, none worse than Georgina
(Clea Duvall), Susanna's roommate. But as it turns out, Lisa is
more complex than a mere bully. She's like the Brad Pitt character
in ``Fight Club'' transferred to the Claymore ladies psych ward,
the voice that taunts conflicted souls. Only, Lisa's real.
</P>
<P>
   The girls fight, bond, then scream and fight some more with
Susanna's calm eroding as her days pass in Claymore. But each girl
_ and there are five or six eddying around Susanna _ is more wily
and manipulative than the victimhood they feign. And Valerie
(Whoopi Goldberg), the ward's head nurse, knows the drill and meets
every temper tantrum with skeptical tough love. As an actress,
Goldberg resonates best when she looks like everyone around her has
worked her last nerve. And she couldn't be more exasperated than
she is here, exuding maternity that's ironclad, even through an
extra large wig that hides her dreadlocks and makes her look like
she just walked off a mother ship.
</P>
<P>
   The film's best scene is one that's not in the book (in which
the head nurse was white and very much in the background). In it,
Valerie tells Susanna to grow up, and Susanna retaliates by calling
her a mammy. It's a powerful face-off between two actresses in full
control who have never been better. And it's an encounter that
provides the piercing, adult clarity in a movie that has as its
theme song Petula Clark's ``Downtown,'' that girly girliest of
liberation anthems.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the way these girls perform it underscores the beguiling
convergence of banshee and Lorelei.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
