<SLUG> BC-GAP-PROTESTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PROTESTS AGAINST CLOTHING RETAILER GAP CONTINUE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ELIZABETH BRENNAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Gap Inc. said its sales have not been affected
by a year of demonstrations led by a San Francisco human rights
organization that is demanding improved human rights conditions at
the retailer's overseas garment factories.
</P>
<P>
   The protests ``have no effect on sales,'' Gap spokeswoman Maria
Moyer-Angus said. ``Sales are going up. We are confident in our
program and want to be proud of the vendors we have and improve
over time.''
</P>
<P>
   Gap Inc. has nearly 3,000 stores, including about 370
international stores. Company officials expect a $2 billion
increase in sales in 1999 from 1998 and plan to open about 550 more
Gap, Banana Republic and Old Navy stores in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 protesters, primarily from the Global Exchange,
gathered Thursday morning outside and in the lobby of Gap's
headquarters, exactly one year after first demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters hoped to deliver to Gap President Donald Fisher a
petition signed by some 10,000 people nationwide asking that Gap
ensure the workers who manufacture its goods are paid a living
wage, that they have the right to freely associate and that the
company allow independent monitors to inspect factories in 50
countries. But no senior official accepted the petition in person.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Mark of Global Exchange said he remains optimistic despite
the lack of response from Gap officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're raising a tremendous amount of awareness,'' Mark said.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen demonstrators were arrested Thursday for trespassing
while shouting, ``Gap workers have been wronged, one year is too
long.'' They were given a citation and a court date, said Capt.
Dennis Martel of the San Francisco police.
</P>
<P>
   Leila Salazar of Global Exchange, who was among those arrested,
said that she is confident the campaign will be effective.
</P>
<P>
   The Gap ``has an exemplary code of conduct, but we know it's not
being enforced,'' Salazar said. ``We need to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark said the organization has staged protests in front of Gap
stores in Chicago, Minneapolis, New York, Austin, Texas, and other
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Gap, like most clothing retailers, contracts with companies to
manufacture it products. Much of the manufacturing has moved out of
the United States to countries where labor and production costs are
lower. Labor and human rights groups contend that many of these
workers face exploitation in countries with minimal labor
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Gap has an 80-person staff to monitor working conditions at its
contract factories. The company does business in 50 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The officers generally visit the factories once every three
months and also conduct random inspections and check for human
rights violations and safety hazards, Moyer-Angus said.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has used independent monitors in El Salvador
and is working to develop more independent monitoring programs in
other Central American countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
