<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6151 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CHEVRON-PAYMENTS-HNS &LR;      01-14 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEVRON-PAYMENTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CHEVRON SETTLES LAWSUIT OVER OIL ROYALTIES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GEORGE RAINE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Chevron Corp. has agreed to pay $95 million to
settle a federal court case in which it was charged with
underpaying royalties due for oil produced on federal and Indian
land over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco-based Chevron did not acknowledge any wrongdoing
or liability in the settlement, which led to dismissal of the case
Thursday. The $95 million is not in the form of a civil fine or
penalty, but the sum the parties involved in the case agreed would
resolve the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Two Texas men acting as private whistle-blowers, J. Benjamin
Johnson Jr. and John Martineck, former employees of Arco, a
competing oil company, filed the lawsuit against Chevron and 15
other oil companies in U.S. District Court in Lufkin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Martineck filed on behalf of the federal government
under provisions of the False Claims Act. They will be paid
approximately $14.5 million of the $95 million settlement from
Chevron.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department subsequently joined the case that alleged
the oil companies used a variety of schemes to establish
artificially low prices. Chevron and the other defendants denied
the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   The case alleged Chevron and the other defendants systematically
underreported the value of oil the company produced on land leased
from the federal government and American-Indian tribes between Jan.
1, 1988, and Dec. 31, 1998, and, consequently, that they paid fewer
royalties than they owed.
</P>
<P>
   Federal leases are administered by the Minerals Management
Services of the Interior Department. Each month, Chevron is
required to report the amount of oil produced and the value of the
oil produced on federal and Indian leases, located throughout the
western United States and in the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron is one of the largest producers of oil from these leases
and paid the federal government more than $1.5 billion in royalties
during the period, said Jan Golen, a Chevron spokeswoman in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The $95 million payment represents about 6 percent of that
total, she noted.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron agreed to the payment to close the dispute and to avoid
the expense of litigation and exposure to other risk, the company
said.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron also noted that it had paid royalties consistent with a
long-standing practice by which the government accepted Chevron's
pricing as the appropriate value for the royalties.
</P>
<P>
   However, the government abandoned the practice and revoked it
retroactively for the 10-year period as the case progressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Publicity surrounding the agreement included harsh allegations
that Chevron and other oil companies `cheated' the government,
allegations which are totally unfounded,'' said Harvey Gunman, vice
president and general counsel for Chevron.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
