<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, Jan. 15:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Dateline to kum) _ A feature on a fighting
priest; plus spot developments in the war. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SECURITY (Moscow) _ A new Russian national security
document, signed into law on Monday by Vladimir Putin, the acting
president, and published in newspapers today, puts more emphasis on
nuclear weapons and accuses the U.S. of trying to dominate the
world.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ Friday is the deadline for Kofi
Annan to name a head for the new U.N. arms inspection commission.
But the candidates are being blackballed by various countries. By
Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-WARCRIMES (Paris) _ The U.N. criminal tribunal for the
Balkans on Friday found five Bosnian Croats guilty of crimes
against humanity for the massacre of Muslims in a central Bosnian
village in April 1993. It is the largest conviction to date; the
commander was sentenced to 25 years in prison. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET-SPAIN (Madrid) _ A Spanish magistrate will ask Britain
to conduct a new medical exam on Augusto Pinochet, the former
Chilean dictator, with Spanish doctors taking part, according to a
lawyer for victims of the Pinochet regime. By Al Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HEROIN-OVERDOSES (Seattle) _ At a gathering in a city with one
of the worst heroin problems in the country, experts are attending
an unusual conference on how to prevent heroin overdoses. By Sam
Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ Developments in the Elian Gonzalez
situation. By Peter Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CAROLINA-PRIMARIES (Atlanta) _ The Democratic presidential
primary in South Carolina is now on hold because of a Justice
Department inquiry, and the Republican primary may also be in
jeopardy. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-HISPANICS (San Jose, Calif.) _ The Republican party is
making a big push for Hispanic votes. By Don Van Natta.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-CANCER (Undated) _ Researchers analyzing records of
women who underwent lumpectomy for treatment of breast cancer found
that younger women were more likely to have a recurrence,
apparently because doctors, for cosmetic and other reasons, did not
remove enough tissue. By Denise Grady. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-XRAY-ASTRONOMY (Atlanta) _ The Chandra X-Ray telescope
yields more unprecedented visions of the universe. Based on its
data, astronomers meeting here report discoveries about the X-ray
source at center of the Milky Way; perplexingly cool X-rays around
the black hole in the Andromeda Galaxy; and the presence of oxygen
around an exploding star, which suggests how supernovas form oxygen
and heavy elements important to planet formation. By John Noble
Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HAND-TRANSPLANT (Undated) _ A French specialist heading an
international team of surgeons carried out the world's first ever
double hand transplant at the Edouard-Herriot hospital in Lyon,
southeast France. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GLAXO-SMITHKLINE (London) _ Glaxo Wellcome and SmithKline
Beecham, Britain's second- and third-biggest drug companies, say
they are in talks on a merger that would create the world's largest
pharmaceutical company. Talks between the two companies in 1998
collapsed over the issue of who would run the combination. By
Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Consumer prices rose 0.2 percent in
December, slightly weaker than expected in a report that may dampen
expectations that the Fed will raise interest rates next month by
more than a quarter point. The core CPI rate, which excludes the
usually volatile energy and food components, also showed subdued
inflation, rising 0.1 percent in December, following a 0.2 percent
rise the previous month. For the year, consumer prices were up 2.7
percent, the fastest pace in three years. Stocks surged in early
trading. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-BALLMER (Redmond, Wash.) _ Folo on the appointment of
Steve Ballmer as Microsoft's chief executive. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-TOURISM (Johannesburg) _ South Africa's name is famous
around the globe, a legacy of the apartheid era that etched the
country into the conscience of the world but left it a foreboding
and unfamiliar place to many of the travelers it would now like to
attract. Determined to dispel the myths, South Africa has turned to
Madison Avenue, and an $18 million ad campaign aimed at the United
States, Britain, Germany, France, Italy and the Netherlands is
about to begin. To listen to the leaders of this new democracy talk
about tourism, nothing less than the future of the nation is at
stake. By Henri E. Cauvin.
</P>
<P>
   WALMART-APPOINT (Undated) _ Wal-Mart Stores says David Glass is
stepping down as chief executive and president after 12 years and
will be succeeded by H. Lee Scott Jr. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-TIME-WARNER (Undated) _ Developments in the prospective
merger. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE-MANNESMANN (Dusseldorf, Germany) _ Mannesmann, the
German telecom company, outlines its defense strategy, suggesting
an Internet spinoff. But more shareholders and analysts are voicing
support for Vodafone's takeover bid. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-PRICES (Undated) _ Crude oil prices continue to climb
following a series of comments from OPEC oil ministers indicating
that the cartel will extend current production ceilings beyond
March. Crude oil for February delivery is up 2.2 percent, to $27.28
on the New York Mercantile Exchange. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks were higher in mid-afternoon trading.
At 2 p.m., the Dow Jones industrial average was up 147 points, the
S&AMP;P 500 up 16 points and the Nasdaq composite index up 119 points.
The yield on the 30-year bond was 6.69 percent. European markets
were also higher, with London up 2.04 percent and Frankfurt up 3.56
percent. In Asia, Japan's Nikkei closed up 0.65 percent; Hong
Kong's Hang Seng index ended down 0.59 percent.
</P>
