<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Saturday, Jan . 15:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IDEAS PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BHAGWATI-ECONOMICS (Undated) _ Like the liberals he often
excoriates, the economist Jagdish Bhagwati passionately deplores
child and prison labor, a lack of regulatory controls and the
failure to enforce anti-pollution laws in the developing world. At
the same time, Bhagwati, a committed free trader, manages to
perplex his conservative colleagues by opposing the enforcement of
intellectual property rights in countries like India and Brazil.
And he argues that laws against illegal immigrants already inside
the United States are ``pointless.'' A profile by Chris Hedges.
(1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   MENTAL-ILLNESS-RACE () Race, mental illness and how definitions
of normal and abnormal behavior are shaped by the values of the
society that makes them. By Emily Eakin. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER CULTURE AND ENTERTAINMENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SOPRANOS-INSIDE-VIEW (Undated) _ A former mob hitman gives his
critique of the show. By Nancy Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   SUPERNOVA-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Supernova'': Walter Hill,
director; with James Spader, Angela Bassett. Reviewed by Lawrence
Van Gelder.
</P>
