<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6205 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-SOURDOUGH-DEMOCRACY-H     01-14 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOURDOUGH-DEMOCRACY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WORKERS SHARE ALL THE DOUGH AT THESE BAY-AREA BAKERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VANESSA HUA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ A potent, pungent creature thrives in deep
plastic buckets
</P>
<P>
   at the worker-owned Arizmendi Bakery in Oakland, a 25-year-old
sourdough starter passed down from Berkeley's legendary
Cheeseboard, a cheese store, bake shop and pizzeria.
</P>
<P>
   Replenished by flour, water and faith, the beery-smelling
starter grows and grows. A bit of the starter (a symbiotic mix of
yeast and bacteria) goes into each batch of sourdough, permeating
the air with its tangy scent.
</P>
<P>
   The ever-enlarging starter is symbolic of one group's efforts to
replicate democratic bakeries in the San Francisco Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Cheeseboard loaned $20,000, its sourdough starter,
its recipes and its worker knowledge to Arizmendi in 1997, so too
will Arizmendi now assist in opening a bakery on the Ninth Avenue
in San Francisco this year.
</P>
<P>
   Starting next week, the Association of Arizmendi Cooperatives _
an organizing group with employees from the Cheeseboard, Arizmendi
and others interested in
</P>
<P>
   worker cooperatives _ will begin holding information sessions to
attract workers who knead good bread and want democratic rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``A sourdough starter produces a certain culture, that when you
move to another place, can take on a life of its own,'' said Tim
Huet, who helped coordinate
</P>
<P>
   efforts to launch Arizmendi and the latest San Francisco bakery
venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to replicate a democratic business, with
good-paying jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The co-op bakeries show that workers can have their ideals and
eat, too. Last year Arizmendi rang up more than $1 million in
sales, and the Cheeseboard more than $2 million, on pizza,
chocolate goodies and zampanos. The name ``Arizmendi'' refers to a
line of Spanish worker co-ops.
</P>
<P>
   The newest bakery will join other San Francisco worker co-ops
such as the radical Bound Together Bookstore and the Good
Vibrations sex emporium.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Inner Sunset neighborhood, a vibrant restaurant
and cafe area, has rallied for the co-op bakery. After the Planning
Department erroneously classified the bakery as a fast-food joint
and rejected its application, residents gathered signatures in
support last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to support local businesses over a national chain
store,'' said Rolf Mueller, president of the Inner Sunset Merchants
Association. ``If people own their own business, they put effort
into making the business successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Though co-ops may seem a 1960s anachronism, such collectives
have flourished in the last five years, said Paul Hazen, president
and chief executive of the National Cooperative Business
Association in Washington, D.C. Today's movement has evolved to
include professionals fleeing the corporate world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is that people feel they are losing control of
their lives,'' Hazen said. ``They can control capital they have, if
they're involved with a cooperative.''
</P>
<P>
   Every employee at each store, no matter their tenure, takes the
same cut of the profits. The common hourly wage and benefits are
determined each year by the collective. At Arizmendi, workers
bumped their earnings by $3 to $13 per hour after a profitable
year.
</P>
<P>
   The co-op association's plans for expansion have some parallels
to traditional franchises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Businesses are so hard to start. What we're trying to do is
provide a framework to be successful,'' said Steve Sutcher, 43, the
association's founder and longtime Cheeseboard worker.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike a franchise, which expands its empire by selling
know-how for thousands of dollars and taking sales royalties,
bakeries in the co-op pass along their recipes for free and provide
start-up loans and legal advice. They also start training workers
six to nine months before a store opens.
</P>
<P>
   At Arizmendi, workers initially paid a $5,000 start-up fee to
join the collective. With the bakery's success since its opening in
August 1997, the workers voted to drop the start-up fee to $3,000.
Employees have the option of paying off the debt through payroll
deduction.
</P>
<P>
   A hiring committee interviews prospective workers, looking not
so much for baking skills but an ability to operate within a
collective. They must also try out at the store for a couple hours,
to test their interactions with others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cumbersome, but worth it,'' said Bridget Berrigen, 51, of
Oakland. Though the former human relations manager now has to
report to work at 4 a.m. and lift 50 pound bags of flour, she gains
the satisfaction of group decision-making. ``We're taking on
partners, not just hiring an employee.''
</P>
<P>
   At co-ops, all workers must reach a consensus on issues that
range from how much of the profit should go back into the business
to what to include in the product line. Arizmendi shuts down
mid-afternoon on Mondays, so its roughly 16 worker-members can
meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in a co-op is harder than being employed,'' said Michael
Addison, 36, a bespectacled Oakland resident pouring eggs, flour
and butter into a giant mixer at Arizmendi.
</P>
<P>
   ``The questions are open and you provide the answer. You can't
complain about decisions made without your participation,'' Addison
said.
</P>
<P>
   That freedom allows workers to tailor their environment to their
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   At Arizmendi, co-op members agreed to celebrate holidays such as
International Worker's Day and donate some profits to charities. At
the Cheeseboard, workers used some of their profits to buy a cabin
in Mendocino.
</P>
<P>
   The co-op structure also mandates that workers rotate in all
jobs, giving them equal opportunity in baking, bookkeeping and
over-the-counter service.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Oviedo, 36, came to the United States from Nicaragua five
years ago and worked as a house cleaner until joining Arizmendi
last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy they gave me the opportunity,'' Oviedo said.
``People here have (an) open mind and good humor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
