<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINTER-GAMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TICKET SALES SLOW FOR WINTER GOODWILL GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JAMES M. ODATO  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A month from now New York will host an
international sporting event in Lake Placid for which state
taxpayers invested more than $23 million during the past two years.
But so far just 5,000 reserved tickets have been sold for the first
Winter Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
   The 5,000 are part of about 24,000 advanced tickets made
available for the only reserved seats required, the figure-skating
events. The $25 seats went on sale in early October for the Feb.
17-20 games, according to Olympic Regional Development Authority
(ORDA) officials.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for the opening ceremony on the evening of Feb. 16 went
on sale Friday. The ceremony will include music by Bruce Hornsby
and Edwin McCain, and will cost $30 per seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the least indicative of (success) . . . are the
number of tickets sold,'' said Republican Assemblyman Chris Ortloff
of Plattsburgh, N.Y., a former member of the Lake Placid village
board and the 1980 Winter Olympics Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an event, like the Olympics, that was built for
worldwide television viewers. It should be judged by the number of
viewers and the ratings and the long-term enhancement of the
worldwide reputation of the community. (It's) almost like the
return of having a motion picture shot in your community,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Goodwill Games, to be given 16 hours of coverage on TNT,
will be held at former Olympic venues in the Lake Placid region and
will feature 11 winter sports.
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of New York Gov. George Pataki, the
facilities have been substantially upgraded. The biggest projects
include a $5 million, high-speed gondola to carry people up and
down the Whiteface Mountain downhill skiing facility and an $18
million, revamped luge and bobsled run on Mt. VanHoevenberg. The
$18 million was part of a $24 million investment on the track that
included federal funds of about $6 million. Work is nearing
completion.
</P>
<P>
   This week Pataki proposed an increased operating budget for
ORDA, the state authority that runs the competition sites used in
the 1980 Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said New York taxpayers should finance 31 percent, or
$7.6 million, of the authority's $24.2 million proposed operating
budget. That's up from almost $6.3 million in general fund support
of ORDA in the fiscal year that ends March 31, during which the
governor provided another $8.3 million to beef up facilities needed
for the Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a long term investment,'' said Sandy Caligiore, a
spokesman for ORDA.
</P>
<P>
   The Goodwill Games, with the support of Turner Broadcasting
System, Inc. and parent company Time Warner Inc., are the key
organizers of the event, and they are underwriting the
entertainment costs for the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Caligiore said ORDA will receive all gate revenues from the
opening event and the sporting events. He added that about 30,000
ticket sales will be needed to break even on security and other
staff added for the events.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first ever Winter Goodwill Games. It's a new
brand. So we're trying to sell that brand,'' Caligiore said.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of ORDA, he said, is to promote and create business in
the region. ``We hope we get 12,000 to 15,000 tourists _ overnight
and day-trippers. Then we would be creating a day that is very
similar to a busy summer day. If we create that for the town, than
we would have been successful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another goal, he said, is to promote the village as a
world-class winter sports capital and a potential future Olympics
site.
</P>
<P>
   The Lake Placid/Essex County Visitors Bureau reports that 75
percent of the 2,500 rooms in the region within 10 miles of the
village are booked, many by athletes and crews associated with the
games and the television coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for the 11-sport event range in price from $5 for many
general admission competitions to $46 for a Whiteface skiing pass.
About 150,000 tickets will be available for sale for the five days.
</P>
<P>
   William Curren, an Adirondack Park Agency executive, said 50,000
visitors are expected during the four days of competition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
