r f BC-DOT-COMS-HNS &LR;      01-14 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOT-COMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AT&AMP;T, EXCITE AT HOME BID MAKES SENSE AFTER AOL MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The dot-com dating game is heating up in the
aftermath of America Online's proposed purchase of Time Warner Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Redwood City-based Excite At Home jumped 19 percent
Thursday on rumors of a possible liaison with AT&AMP;T Corp., which
already owns 40 percent of the Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman Brothers investment analyst Vik Grover wrote a report
that helped fuel the speculation. He said by acquiring the smaller
company, AT&AMP;T would strengthen its position by acquiring Excite At
Home's Internet portal and its service of providing Internet access
over cable television lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The AOL-Time Warner deal supports our belief that ownership of
content is becoming critical to the success of telecommunications
companies worldwide,'' Grover wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies declined to comment on Grover's report.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Grover explained the logic behind his
prediction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The AOL takeover of Time Warner in our view raises the bar for
AT&AMP;T,'' said Grover, whose New York-based firm specializes in
telecommunications. ``If you look at the technology space and
what's going on, there's a massive poker game going on. The
AOL-Time Warner merger is a major bet on the cable space.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that this merger moves a number of issues to the front
burner for AT&AMP;T,'' Grover said.
</P>
<P>
   Primarily, it forces AT&AMP;T's hand with regard to the delivery of
Internet services over existing cable lines. Time Warner's
Roadrunner service, which does just that, is the only major
competitor to Excite At Home's cable modem technology, which
pioneered the delivery of the Net through copper cable wires,
Grover said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is involved, too, having invested $5 billion last year
in AT&AMP;T's Internet efforts.
</P>
<P>
   With that investment bearing little fruit, he said, AT&AMP;T is
feeling pressure from Microsoft to make a stronger Internet play.
Excite At Home would serve that purpose, said Grover, creating an
on-line triumvirate that could rival AOL-Time Warner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
