<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6233 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-ONLINE-SHOPPING-HNS &LR;      01-14 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-SHOPPING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SURVEYS SHOW INTERNET HOLIDAY SHOPPING WAY UP IN 1999 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite complaints about out-of-stock items and late deliveries,
surveys show that consumers spent even more on line this past
holiday season than many analysts had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best-known on-line market research firms, New
York-based Jupiter Communications, reported holiday shoppers spent
$7 billion between Nov. 1 and Dec. 31, up from $3.1 million for the
same period in 1998 and even higher than the $6 million Jupiter
projected.
</P>
<P>
   And even amid reports of on-line retailers that couldn't deliver
on their promises, consumers said they liked shopping on line.
</P>
<P>
   The Jupiter report found 90 percent of 810 shoppers interviewed
were ``largely satisfied'' with their on line experience, up from
74 percent in 1998. Only 4 percent said they would decrease their
on-line spending in 2000 based on this past season's experience.
</P>
<P>
   In another survey, PC Data Online estimated shoppers spent $5
billion between Nov. 14 and Dec. 31. The Reston, Va.-based company
tracks the on-line activity of 100,000 home computer users.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers may be higher than some expectations, but overly
optimistic projections made early in the season put some estimates
over the $10 billion mark. Part of the enthusiasm was tied to the
strong economy and high expectations at traditional stores, which
were borne out last week when retailers reported their highest
numbers in seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Commerce estimates that consumers spent
$259.6 billion in December, both on line and off. That is a 9.7
percent increase from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   PC Data Online released a satisfaction survey, which was
conducted with Goldman Sachs, that found 97 percent of shoppers
said they would buy through on-line companies again. In the survey
of 4,742 Internet shoppers, 95.6 percent reported their experience
``met, exceeded or significantly exceeded'' their expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron Meierhoefer, an e-commerce analyst for PC Data Online,
said he suspected the inability of some retailers _ most notably
Toys R Us and Wal-Mart _ to meet stock and delivery needs this
season as well as complaints by consumers over poor customer
service and long downloading times were more the exception than the
norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised. Most people were pretty happy with their
experience,'' Meierhoefer said. He said he was also surprised by
the breadth of what people were buying over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was the concentration of spending in the traditional
gift categories _ toys, electronics, apparel _ but that flowed over
to some non-traditional sites like drugstores. I think people got
intrigued by all that was available out there,'' said Meierhoefer,
adding that the addition of well-known brands and retailers to the
Web also contributed to increased consumer confidence in cyber
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Media Metrix Inc., a New York-based company that tracked the
most popular sites, crowned Amazon.com Inc. the top e-commerce site
for the five-week period from Nov. 14 through Dec. 26. Amazon was
followed closely by eBay Inc. and then, after a considerable drop
in numbers, eToys Inc., barnesandnoble.com and Toysrus.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
