<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6241 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN15-CO     01-14 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: On the baby-go-round
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ So far this year, I'm averaging a new grandson
every week.
</P>
<P>
   First came William Joseph Langston, son of my daughter Kate and
her husband, Keith, born New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's Edward Wesley Bonner, son of my daughter Erin and
her husband, Jessie, born Jan. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Both are named for their grandfathers _ my middle name is Edward
_ and everybody is doing just fine. Never mind that it's put a lot
of miles on me.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, who has been in Waco helping with William Joseph,
called on the morning of Jan. 13 to tell me the other baby was on
the way, and for me to come get her and we'd drive from there to
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   There was no real reason to rush. By the time I got to Waco,
word had reached us that Edward Wesley already had made his
appearance. The two hours to Dallas were interstate all the way, a
hard fight but I won. All the while the mix-master in downtown Big
D was waiting for me.
</P>
<P>
   Any city where interstates intersect ought to be closed off,
paved over and boarded up. It's the traffic jam that never jells.
Makes no difference if you arrive at high noon or 3 a.m., cars will
be backed up to the suburbs of El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   All the way to Dallas, my wife hadn't said a word. Old married
couples are that way. We can go 100 miles without acknowledging
each other's presence. Now, all of a sudden, she was making
conversation that only made things worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's that tall building? Isn't that a hotel? Didn't we stay
there one time? ... That sign said 45. I thought we were supposed
to be on 30. ... Are you in the right lane? The others are moving
faster. ... I think there's a wreck up ahead. I bet a lot of cars
ran together. Yes, I'm right. Look at all those smashed cars. ...
Why is that man honking at us? I'm going to give him a dirty
look.''
</P>
<P>
   We made it past the mix-master, past the tall building where we
may have stayed before, past all those wrecked cars, past the man
who blew his horn at us ... and, finding our way onto I-30,
eventually found the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Wesley is one fine looking boy. At 6 pounds, 11 ounces,
he has hands like catcher's mitts and feet the size of snowshoes. I
have no doubt he'll follow in his father's footsteps. His father
wears size 15 shoes.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, be it noted that husband Jessie distinguished
himself in the delivery room. I have it from the highest authority,
my daughter Erin. He even assisted the doctor's staff with
recording vital signs and such.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when he and I were alone, he asked if I ever had to be in
the delivery room for the birth of any of my three daughters. I
told him no, that back then the man's responsibility ended at the
curbside. All that was expected of the husband was to get his wife
to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Jessie sighed. ``That sounds a lot easier,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I shrugged. ``It depended on the traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   My wife stayed in Dallas to help with the baby when they come
home from the hospital. I drove on back to Lufkin that night. It
had been a round trip of 500 miles. I made it a point to honk and
wave when I met myself coming.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. His address is P.O. Box
151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915; e-mail, jmurray(AT)lcc.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
