<HEADER>
A6243 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MLK-SCHULKE17-COX     01-14 1948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MLK-SCHULKE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Photographer keeps MLK's image, ideas alive
 &HT;    (Eds: For Monday, Jan. 17. Moving in (a) National and (l)
Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By Jill Young Miller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Flip Schulke last saw Martin Luther King
Jr. alive in late 1967.
</P>
<P>
   King was flying from Atlanta to Montgomery, Ala., to serve jail
time for trespassing during marches in Birmingham. King had asked
Schulke, a freelance photographer chronicling the civil-rights
movement, to come along.
</P>
<P>
   Schulke sat down next to King and told him he was worried. Why
was he was moving about through airports and other public places
with so much advance notice? Racial tension was flaring, and
Schulke had heard talk about the need to ``get rid of Martin Luther
King.''
</P>
<P>
   King sat with a Bible on his lap. He said he was sure he would
be around as long as God wanted him to be.
</P>
<P>
   The photographer replied that he didn't place that much trust in
the Almighty.
</P>
<P>
   King looked at Schulke and said: ``We're going to talk about
your faith.'' And the Baptist preacher, who already had plenty to
worry about, proceded to minister to the photographer.
</P>
<P>
   Schulke, now 69, chokes up at the memory. ``He was more
concerned about me than his own troubles,'' he says at his office
in West Palm Beach. ``It's hard to talk about it sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   The next time Schulke saw King was in a coffin.
</P>
<P>
   Life magazine ran his memorable photo of Coretta Scott King,
veiled and grieving at her husband's funeral, her chin held high,
on its cover. For his effort, Schulke won a first place in the
prestigious Pictures of the Year competition. But he had lost a
hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. King was the greatest man I ever met,'' he says. ``By
far.''
</P>
<P>
   Flip Schulke was one of the most influential photojournalists of
the civil-rights movement, shooting primarily for Life. His
friendship with and access to King helped get the movement's
message out across the land. The two met in 1958 after a rally in
Miami, staying up all night to talk about civil rights. The talk
forged a trust between them.
</P>
<P>
   King was 29, and Schulke was 28.
</P>
<P>
   Schulke, who turns 70 in June, doesn't shoot anymore. He has
lost some feeling in his legs, and going up a flight of stairs is
difficult for him, never mind the nimbleness photojournalism
requires. Still, he projects vitality and passion and remains
deeply committed to King's teachings of nonviolence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to claim to be a goody two-shoes,'' he says.
``It's a matter of trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulke is immersed in a half-million-dollar project to place
his archive of more than 300,000 photos _ including 11,000 related
to King and the civil-rights movement _ at the Center for American
History at the University of Texas. Some 9,000 of his pictures will
be digitized on CD-ROM. ``I'm just trying to do my little bit to
keep history accurate,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year project is funded by the University of Texas
primarily and Macalester College, Schulke's alma mater in St. Paul,
Minn. Initially only students in those two states will have access
to the photos, but Schulke hopes that eventually all students will.
</P>
<P>
   Schulke also is working on his seventh book, this one about the
Berlin Wall. His latest book, ``Muhammad Ali: The Birth of a
Legend: Miami, 1961-1964,'' was published last fall. ``He's
committed to journalism and to a general fight for justice,'' says
Matt Schudel, co-author of the Ali book. ``He's not out there just
to take pretty pictures. He wants his photographs to make a
difference in how the world works.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulke, who never joined a staff but worked as a freelancer and
kept the copyrights to all his photos, covered more than the
civil-rights movement. He shot pre-Castro Cuba, sports figures, the
space program, auto racing, hurricanes and the rise and fall of the
Berlin Wall. Associated his whole career with the Black Star photo
agency, he has contributed not only to Life but also to Time,
Newsweek, National Geographic, Jet, Ebony and many other magazines.
</P>
<P>
   But it is his vast and powerful collection of images of the
civil-rights movement for which is he most recognized. By virtue of
his passion for the cause, he had thorough access to some of the
major figures of the time, visiting King, for instance, at home
many times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was more than someone with a camera,'' says U.S. Rep. John
Lewis, D-Atlanta, a civil-rights activist who knew Schulke in the
'60s. ``The photographs that he made are some of the most powerful
images of that period. ... He was so talented, and at the same time
he was very committed and dedicated to the ideal of a just and open
society.'' Covering the civil-rights movement in the South was
dangerous work, even for a white man. ``I was very careful,''
Schulke says. ``I had short hair, and I kept my mouth shut.'' A
naturally talkative man, Schulke feared his Northern accent would
give him away. Even taking precautions, Schulke was threatened by
hostile whites, tear-gassed by police, and locked in squad cars so
he couldn't shoot demonstrations. On assignment in the South, he
rented Cadillacs because they could outrun pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   If Schulke's admiration of King violated journalism's goal of
absolute objectivity, it was because the photographer felt the
cause was right and violence and racism were wrong. Period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very strongly that you don't win anything by hitting
people,'' Schulke says. His own difficult childhood reinforced his
ideals. His alcoholic father was so abusive that at 15 Schulke ran
away from home in New Hampshire to live with relatives in Ulm,
Minn. ``I've never told anybody about the worst parts of the
violence. It would just make me feel bad _ for him.''
</P>
<P>
   In Ulm, he took up gymnastics, earning the name he has gone by
for more than half a century: ``Flip.'' (His given name is Phelps.)
At 17, Flip sold his first photos. He'd snapped pictures with his
first camera, a Baby Brownie Special, of a town parade, then
discovered that people would pay for copies. He used his earnings
to buy a better camera.
</P>
<P>
   Today he's a tall man, 6 foot 3, with sparkling eyes and long
gray hair combed back from his forehead. He has traveled the world,
and is married, for the fourth time. Days and nights on the road
took a toll on his earlier marriages. Softly he says they were
``the only failures in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   As a sought-after freelancer, Schulke could pick his assignments
_ or refuse them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, a federal court ordered Alabama Gov. George Wallace to
integrate schools in Mobile, Montgomery and Huntsville. Life sent
Schulke and a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Schulke was shooting in Wallace's office when the governor,
using a degrading racial slur, talked about deploying the state
police to keep blacks out of white schools. Wallace assumed what
was said would go unreported because the Life reporter had been
ushered from the office. But Schulke excused himself and went to
the men's room, where he told the reporter what he had heard.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Schulke was banned from the governor's office, but that was
fine with him. He told Life he couldn't photograph Wallace with any
fairness, anyway, because he disliked him so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a mean face, and it was very hard to make good pictures
of him _ besides mean pictures,'' Schulke said.
</P>
<P>
   Access is crucial for any journalist. King, in particular, had a
way of giving it to the empathetic photographer from Life. King was
intent on urging photojournalists to record the suffering of
American blacks so other Americans would know. ``King had a very
savvy appreciation about how ... very politically important the
photojournalism coverage was,'' says David J. Garrow, a historian
and expert on King at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important to get these images out across the land to
build up the political and moral support for the movement,'' Lewis
says. Without the media, people leading the movement ``would have
been like birds without wings.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Schulke, whose family lived in Miami, couldn't make it
home for weekends, and King would invite him to his Atlanta home
for Sunday lunch after church. Schulke, who like King had four
children and loved fried chicken, usually left his cameras in the
car. But the November 1964 day King learned he had won the Nobel
Peace Prize, King invited Schulke to bring in the cameras. Schulke
snapped intimate photos of the King family at the dining table,
with a portrait of Mahatma Gandhi looking over them, and of King
playing with his children in the yard. ``He loved his family,''
Schulke says.
</P>
<P>
   The year earlier, he visited another civil-rights leader's home,
but under much different circumstances. Medgar Evers, of the NAACP,
had been gunned down in front of his house in Jackson, Miss. When
Schulke got there, reporters and photographers were camped outside.
Schulke knocked on the door, and Myrlie Evers let him in, he says.
He was the only member of the press with access to the family.
</P>
<P>
   When Mrs. Evers and her children went to the funeral home to
view Evers's body, Schulke was there. He disliked intruding, he
says, but remembered King's words about documenting the pain.
Still, he couldn't hold back his tears. Four years later, Myrlie
Evers published her book ``For Us, the Living.'' In it she
describes the day she stood at her husband's casket:
</P>
<P>
   I sensed that I was not alone. I turned and the Life
photographer was there. His eyes were filled with tears. For the
first time since Medgar's death the hatred I had felt for all
whites was gone. It never returned.
</P>
<P>
   These days, to Schulke's delight, his photos are selling well as
art photography, and at least one celebrity has opened his wallet.
Last spring, at a show in Manhattan, Jerry Seinfeld bought works
featuring John F. Kennedy at the Orange Bowl, Schulke says. ``I'm
name-dropping,'' he says with a laugh, ``but it impressed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulke himself focuses on impressing students. He carries
King's message of nonviolence _ and 160 slides from the
civil-rights movement _ to schools throughout Palm Beach County,
under the aegis of the local attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes history come alive,'' says Renalda Mack, chief of the
attorney general's civil rights unit.
</P>
<P>
   A West Palm Beach high school girl wrote to Schulke: ``I was
really troubled about something that someone did to me and I wanted
to get revenge. But after listening to you talk in our class I
changed my mind about the whole situation. I've decided just to
drop it. ... Thanks for helping me decide on doing the right things
in life.''
</P>
<P>
   When Schulke organized his slide show for students, he included
images of King in death. But he was careful not to end the
presentation there. Instead he shows a barrage of pictures of the
living King: the father playing with his children, the minister
smiling while leaving church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he's not dead,'' Schulke says, tears shining in his
eyes again. ``His spirit isn't dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Flip Schulke, photojournalist
</P>
<P>
   Age: 69
</P>
<P>
   Residence: West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Family: Wife, Donna. Four children.
</P>
<P>
   Connection to MLK Jr.: Documented the civil rights movement
intensely for a decade. Helped King in his effort to publicize the
suffering of Southern blacks. Was with King at key moments,
including the day he won the Nobel Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Current projects: Digitally archiving thousands of his
photographs. Lectures on civil rights and nonviolence in local
schools. New book is ``Muhammad Ali: The Birth of a Legend: Miami,
1961-1964.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
