<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6250 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-CENSUS-SF-HNS &LR;      01-14 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-SF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COMMUNITY LEADERS WARY OF CENSUS CLAIMS THAT THE COUNT WILL BE
ACCURATE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JULIE CHAO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The director of the U.S. Census Bureau has come
to town to make sure that Census 2000 does not repeat the disaster
of the last decade, in which 837,000 Californians, a
disproportionate number of them children and immigrants, were
missed.
</P>
<P>
   However, despite Kenneth Prewitt's assurances that he is
committed to getting an accurate count, some community leaders
expressed concerns at a local forum in Oakland on Thursday, saying
grass-roots groups are being left out and the national media
campaign is not reaching its intended targets.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, a state census committee met in Sacramento to
announce how $24.7 million allocated last July for census outreach
will be distributed.
</P>
<P>
   With millions of census questionnaires set to be mailed out in
mid-March, community groups are eager for the money to be
distributed as quickly as possible so that hard-to-reach groups
such as immigrants, ethnic minorities and homeless will be ready
and willing to fill them out.
</P>
<P>
   Massive demographic shifts in the last decade, spurred largely
by immigration from Asia and Latin America, will help make the
United States a majority-minority country by 2050, when no racial
group will make up more than 50 percent of the population, Prewitt
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are creating the first world nation, the first country made
up of people from every other country,'' he said. ``We need a
complete picture if we're going to build the kind of society we
want to build.''
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting Thursday morning hosted by U.S. Rep. Barbara Lee,
D-Calif, Prewitt met with about 40 East San Francisco Bay clergy
members to discuss ways they can encourage their congregation to
return census forms.
</P>
<P>
   At an afternoon meeting with community members involved in the
census count in Oakland and Alameda County, several people
complained that the Census Bureau's national media strategy was not
reaching African Americans in the East Bay.
</P>
<P>
   To lead the $160 million ad campaign, the Census Bureau hired
the New York advertising firm Young &AMP; Rubicam, which then
subcontracted with four ad agencies to target the main minority
groups _ blacks, Asians, Latinos and American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   As for reaching East Bay blacks, a single one-page ad in the
Oakland Post, a black-owned newspaper, ran last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Dillard, president of the Oakland Black Board of Trade and
Commerce, said no other ads have run on the radio or TV stations
most popular with African Americans in the East Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to do this repetitively to get people's consciousness
level raised,'' said Dillard. ``We get one shot at this. If we
don't do it right, we get 10 years to suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt responded that he expected the second phase of the media
campaign, which is just rolling out, to have more targeted ads.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said part of the problem is that the ad campaign, led by the
New York-based Chisholm-Mingo Group, which specializes in reaching
black audiences, is skewed toward the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   She said the Congressional Black Caucus is engaged in ``daily
warfare'' on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed the requirement wasn't there to contract
with regional advertising agencies,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Sacramento, the California Complete Count Committee, created
by Gov. Gray Davis last November, divvied up $24.7 million
allocated by the legislature last summer for census outreach.
</P>
<P>
   Among the disbursements, it will give $5 million to individual
counties, $3.9 million to community groups and $1.2 million for
school-based outreach efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Wang, policy director of Chinese for Affirmative Action, a
San Francisco civil rights group, said that because the state took
longer than expected to decide how to spend the $24.7 million, it
will be a challenge for community groups and counties to reach
hard-to-count groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 1554EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
