HILLARY SCORES, DAVE EaSES UP, BUSH ROLLS ON 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Random comments on people in the news:
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY CLINTON: The first lady may be losing _ or at least
trailing in the polls _ in her still-unofficial campaign for the
U.S. Senate, but she scored a resounding victory in her highly
hyped appearance on David Letterman's TV show.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton traded quips with the host, breezed through a quiz on
New York minutiae such as the state bird, offered her own version
of a Letterman Top Ten List and sneaked in a clever cheap shot on
her expected opponent in the Senate race, New York City Mayor Rudy
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Her best line came in response to Letterman's comment that
``every idiot in the area'' would be driving by her house and
honking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was that you?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   If Hillary is as smart as her boosters say she is, she'll get
herself booked on the Letterman show as often as he'll have her.
</P>
<P>
   DAVID LETTERMAN: Some of the morning-after babblemeisters were
critical of Dave for parking his usual slashing sarcasm and giving
Hillary a free ride with softball questions and hanging-curve
straight lines that a trained chimp could have hit out of the park.
So what's wrong with that?
</P>
<P>
   Hillary is the nation's first lady, after all, and Letterman had
been carving her up for weeks. Giving her a break was the decent
thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN GONZALEZ: Do you suppose any of the folks who want to
decide what happens to this kid have given a moment's thought to
what he wants? All these politicians, bureaucrats, activists and
even relatives who claim to have his best interests at heart know
exactly what sort of life they want for Elian, but none seems
interested in what he wants for himself. He must have an opinion.
</P>
<P>
   JANET RENO: The attorney general has hardly been the epitome of
decisiveness where Elian Gonzalez is concerned, but Reno made a
statement Thursday that ought to guide the decision-making of all
those involved in the controversy: ``The issue is a father who
wants his son home and grandparents who want their grandson home,
and these are bonds that should be honored.''
</P>
<P>
   That is definitely the issue. So why can't the world's lone
remaining superpower figure out a way to do the right thing for a
6-year-old boy who has been manipulated by everyone who's come
within a country mile of him in recent weeks?
</P>
<P>
   DAN BURTON: The Indiana congressman who once called the
president of the United States a ``scumbag'' and who recently
subpoenaed Elian Gonzalez to testify before a congressional
committee was mentioned during Indiana native Letterman's chat with
Hillary Clinton. Dave called his home state congressman a
``bonehead.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave apparently decided to go easy on everybody the other night.
</P>
<P>
   The president has earned whatever scorn is tossed his way, but
Burton is richly deserving in his own right. ``Bonehead'' doesn't
begin to describe him; he's an arrogant, self-aggrandizing moron.
The people of Indiana should give this jerk his walking papers.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: There's bad news for Bush-bashers. Despite the
reported surge by John McCain in New Hampshire, despite the nightly
sniping by Letterman and Leno, despite the relentless criticism by
assorted pundits _ despite all that, a new USA Today/CNN/Gallup
Poll gives Bush a commanding lead over McCain in the race for the
Republican presidential nomination. The poll shows Bush ahead of
both would-be Democratic nominees in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   So much for those predictions that Bush would self-destruct,
that familiarity would breed contempt, that the front-runner would
be done in by his participation in a series of televised debates
with the other candidates. It just hasn't happened.
</P>
<P>
   While his opponents continue to spin their wheels, the Bush
bandwagon keeps rolling on.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised, in fact, if Bush wins the Feb. 1 New
Hampshire primary _ making a spectacular comeback in a race that
many pundits have chalked up for McCain. And if McCain doesn't win
in New Hampshire, he'll be right back where he started: nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
