<SLUG> BC-TV-ANGELS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIGINALITY WOULD BE GOOD MEDICINE FOR `ANGELS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
CITY OF ANGELS 
Starring: Blair Underwood, Vivica A. Fox, Phil Buckman, Robert
Morse, Michael Warren, Hill Harper, Maya Rudolph, Viola Davis 
On: CBS 
Time: Premieres Sunday at 8 p.m., then moves to its regular
timeslot this Wednesday at 8 p.m. 
Rated: TV14 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new hospital drama ``City of Angels'' arrives with some
heavy baggage riding on its gurney.
</P>
<P>
   A network series with a predominantly African-American cast,
it's being called the most significant event of the TV season, a
season that opened with an NAACP critique of prime-time diversity.
And it's being viewed as a test balloon on whether white people _
the majority of viewers _ are ready to bond with a non-comedic show
that doesn't quite look like them. So far, largely black dramas
like ``South Central'' in 1994 and ``Under One Roof'' in 1995 have
failed quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath all the expectation and symbolism, of course, there
is a TV show that will be good or bad regardless of the racial
composition of its cast. And ``City of Angels,'' which premieres
Sunday before moving to its home on Wednesdays at 8, is both good
and bad. It has some obvious strengths (a strong, easy-to-like
cast, a distinctive urban look) and one or two structural
weaknesses (conventional plots, flat attempts at humor). If the
creators _ including Steven Bochco _ can edge ``City of Angels'' a
few more inches into the originality zone in the next few weeks, it
has the potential to join TV's growing collection of quality
hour-long series.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, the show is a state-of-the-art ensemble drama set in
an underfunded LA hospital called Angels of Mercy. That means that
the staff _ doctors, nurses, residents, administrators _ cope with
plenty of juicy interpersonal affairs as they work together running
the busy facility. Vivica A. Fox plays Lillian Price, a new
director brought in to generate money and accreditation, and Blair
Underwood is Ben Turner, the acting chief of surgery. Turns out the
two were engaged seven years ago, but Turner jumped ship shortly
before the wedding. That promises to create melodrama in the weeks
to come, particularly since Price has inadvertently befriended
Turner's current girlfriend. Michael Warren is also on hand as a
businessman, and Robert Morse plays a mysteriously powerful board
president.
</P>
<P>
   While ``City of Angels'' doesn't rely on racial issues for most
of its story lines, a few of its best moments do have a racial
component. A black patient ribs a white resident, Dr. Weiss, for
being Jewish; a black resident accuses Turner of favoring Weiss
because Weiss is white; Weiss panics when he sees a young black
girl with a residue on her legs, not realizing it's simply ash _
dry skin. ``It's a black thing,'' the girl tells the befuddled
Weiss. These are the sort of relevant scenes that, despite its
black cast members, ``ER'' seems to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   But too many of the little stories on ``City of Angels'' feel
like standard fare. You know, a noble older woman doesn't want to
get a needed operation because she's caring for her grandchildren,
an anesthetized man accidentally ends up in the morgue, like that.
It may be that, in the wake of ``ER'' and ``Chicago Hope,'' both of
which have been churning out medical vignettes for six-plus years,
there's nothing new to show about the daily operations of a
hospital. Even the quirky silly business on ``City of Angels'' _ a
gay man with a Golden Globe award stuck in a very bad spot _ seems
cliched.
</P>
<P>
   But ``City of Angels'' moves slower than the fever-pitched
``ER,'' and that gives it the advantage of being able to explore
characters and issues more thoroughly. The show could distinguish
itself by delving deeper into the ambivalences and conflicts of
both the regular characters and the guest stars. If the medical and
romantic situations have to be familiar, at least they can be done
with added complexity. The actors, particularly Underwood, are
clearly up to it. ``City of Angels'' is a promising hour that, with
some tinkering and growth, could take flight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
