<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV20-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING A FIRM STAND AGAINST CLUTTER
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Jan. 20)  
(dw) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   c.2000
N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, you make this resolution to clear out all the old nests
around the house and you end up with a giant head cold and
collapsed on the couch, surrounded by a menacing tower of old
magazines and a nagging box of Christmas lights that needs to be
picked over for rejects before being packed away.
</P>
<P>
   In the bedroom is a starter stack of clothes to go and in the
kitchen there are pitiful jars of pickles and months-old marmalade
waiting for a thumbs up or down.
</P>
<P>
   It's too exhausting to de-clutter. The end result is supposed to
be less chaos in our lives but the very effort sends some of us to
bed. Not everything is an easy yes or no, go or stay. Some items
are in transition. That's why we have junk drawers and dark
recesses in bedroom closets. That's why one bathroom cupboard is
full of nothing but bubble pack because I may need it someday,
there's no place else to store it and if I throw it out I'll be
adding to the landfill burden.
</P>
<P>
   How long do you save magazines? Do you wait until they encroach
on every flat surface or do you get tough? On the other hand, will
you some day wish you had that great New Yorker cover from 1996 of
Whistler's Mother glaring at the telephone? And the 1997 Newsweek
story on Dylan?
</P>
<P>
   What about the recipes optimistically ripped from the newspaper
and piling up on the kitchen table? Will you ever copy them over on
note cards to add to your recipe file box so that you can gather
the ingredients and dazzle your guests? Or will they end up jammed
in a seldom-used cookbook, maybe the one on New Orleans favorites,
now shelved between the five-year-old bottle of Triple Sec and a
vintage Boggle game.
</P>
<P>
   What about that shopping bag full of photographs from two
vacations ago? How about those instructions for installing the
battery backup for the computer? How long do you save the box the
answering machine came in, in case you need to take it back?
</P>
<P>
   What loony thought she needed all of this? Here's five different
hair conditioning products, none of which made me look like Rene
Russo. Here are several crusty bottles of nail polish from the
mauve period.
</P>
<P>
   Why did I save all these lone earrings after losing their mates?
Am I secretly planning to get something pierced?
</P>
<P>
   I am pretty sure I will never wear these socks that say ``Life's
a bitch and so am I.'' But I'm not giving up my three goddesses
T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Some things are obviously no longer essential. It takes effort
but you can let them go, laughing gaily as you toss them into the
proper recycling bin.
</P>
<P>
   But others beg for one last chance and sometimes they are right.
People who write books on how to streamline your life by getting
rid of clutter say to dump any article of clothing that has gone
unworn for more than a year. But they don't know about coming
across a soft gray crewneck abandoned by your husband in the back
of his closet but which now fits you. Or about rediscovering a lacy
blouse that you held onto only because it came from your
mother-in-law but was suddenly perfect one night for a party.
</P>
<P>
   In purging some old newspaper files I found a yellowed column by
the late writer Charles McCabe whose words are perfect for a book I
will someday write. And when I was ransacking my book shelves I
found a dusty copy of the Hite Report on women and sex that
provided hours of fascinating reading.
</P>
<P>
   I have made some progress. I deleted a whole bunch of e-mail
messages, dating from June 1997 and am looking sternly at a food
processor that's been missing a part for two years.
</P>
<P>
   The nail polish is history. I think that's enough decluttering
for a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
