<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6261 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV1     01-14 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV16-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HEAT SAVER ON SMOKESTACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 16, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have had a heat saver on the smokestack of my heater for
many years, and it has served well, transferring heat from the
smokestack to the basement. It was set on the horizontal part of
the smokestack. Now I have to replace it, but the only replacement
that I can find is designed to attach to a vertical stack. I have
no vertical stack; it is all horizontal. Now what?
</P>
<P>
   RUSSELL SMITH, Auburn, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Those heat savers were developed during the big oil crisis of
the 1970s, and served quite well in heating basements, whether the
heat was needed or not. I am surprised one has lasted this long, 20
to 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   In my opinion, virtually any heat saver (heat exchanger) can be
installed on a vertical or horizontal smokestack. The standard
exchangers transfer heat from the stack through a series of pipes
in the exchanger, inserted in the smokestack. They are powered by a
small electric motor, which blows the warmed air into the basement,
and while set in a section of the smokestack, they are airtight, so
should be able to be installed vertically or horizontally.
</P>
<P>
   If you have the least bit of doubt, then don't. Let a pro do it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The electric service in my condo is served by a fuse box. My
lights flicker and dim often, especially when another light is
turned on or an appliance starts up. What can I do? Can I put a
20-amp fuse in a 15-amp socket? Should I switch to circuit
breakers?
</P>
<P>
   LINDA BAKER, Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It sounds as if one or more circuits are overloaded, and the
lights dim and flicker when an extra load is put on the circuit.
This is particularly true when a motor or toaster starts up.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent this, use fewer lamps and appliances on each circuit.
For a permanent fix, have an electrician put in an extra circuit
that you could put those excess appliances on.
</P>
<P>
   But do not put a 20-amp fuse in a 15-amp socket. You already
have an overload, and putting in a high fuse would override that
overload; in doing so it would heat up the wires, often enough to
start a fire. So it is a real hazard.
</P>
<P>
   I don't see any need to switch to circuit breakers, except to
bring the system up to code (I think existing fuse boxes are
grandfathered) and to make it easier for the homeowner to flip the
breaker back into position; easier than replacing a fuse. But a
fuse will show why it blew, while a breaker will not. You can tell
why a fuse blew by looking in its window. A fuse blown by an
overload will be all smoky; a fuse blown by a short circuit will
show a broken filament. Because of this, you can make repairs
faster and more easily.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I moved into a brand-new house last September. The concrete
cellar floor has hairline cracks. Is this important or significant?
</P>
<P>
   BOB ALLEN, Pembroke, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If there is no water oozing or gushing up through the cracks,
the cracks are neither important nor significant. If water were
seeping up, it would do so, along the border, even if there were no
cracks. The slab is not structural, so there is no concern for
that, either.
</P>
<P>
   The house is in warranty for a year, so the contractor is
responsible for anything that goes wrong. Often a contractor,
responding to such a complaint, will fill the cracks with mortar or
hydraulic cement, to make the homeowner feel better, and make him
look like a nice guy. But it is strictly cosmetic.
</P>
<P>
   As to why the slab cracks, it could be for several reasons: 1.
The slab is too thin (less than two inches) and cracks under foot
pressure. 2. The slab is not reinforced with steel mesh or rods. 3.
Some of the ground on which the slab was poured sagged a bit,
causing the ssag. 4. The slab was poured directly on the
ground, not crushed stone for drainage, and water pressure under it
caused the cracks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am having a tough time keeping turnpike noise out of my
house, which faces the turnpike not far away. I replaced my old
windows and storms with double-glazed windows, without much help.
What can I do to reduce the sound further? Will triple glazing
work? The sound is particularly disturbing in my bedroom at night.
</P>
<P>
   DAHLIA, too near the turnpike
</P>
<P>
   A. Triple glazing (a third layer of glass) will help, but there
is no need to replace your present windows with triple-glazed ones.
You can add a third layer of glass by putting in exterior storms,
or interior storms, or both. A good exterior storm is True Channel
by Harvey Industries. Interior storms are getting hard to find, but
a good one is by Innerglass of Simsbury, Conn., 800-743-6207,
860-651-3951.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure the windows are properly weatherstripped and airtight.
Another way to get interior storms is to fasten thin polyethylene
to the inside casing. Home centers carry these kits.
</P>
<P>
   You can do the entire front of the house facing the turnpike or
just the bedroom windows. Heavy draperies on those windows will
also help.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
