   For Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-SCOUTS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court agrees to decide
whether the Boy Scouts can exclude homosexuals as members and troop
leaders. The justices say they will review a ruling in which New
Jersey's highest court said the organization unlawfully ousted a
young man, James Dale, after learning he is gay. A decision is
expected by July. By STEVE LASH and PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-ABORTION (Washington) _ The Supreme Court set the stage
for its most important abortion ruling in recent years, agreeing to
decide whether states may ban a surgical procedure that opponents
call ``partial-birth abortion.'' The justices voted to review a
Nebraska law that made it a crime for doctors to perform such
procedures. Thirty states have enacted such laws but courts have
been reluctant to enforce them. By STEVE LASH and PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DROUGHT-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ ``If we don't get rain, we have
a potentially devastating situation shaping up in Texas
agriculture,'' state Agriculture Commissioner Susan Combs says.
Last year was one of the driest years on record, and weather
forecasts call for dry conditions to continue. Farmers, meanwhile,
haven't recovered from the droughts of 1996 and 1998. By JOHN
GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ You know the 21st century has
arrived when America Online and Time Warner get together for a
megabucks corporate dance, and AOL takes the lead. The astonishing
thing about the deal is that an Internet company came out on top.
By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A reader asks, ``I've got a
233-megahertz Pentium II computer, one of the first ones, which
came with Windows 95. I put Windows 98 on it, and recently upgraded
to Windows 98 SE. A friend said I should format my hard drive and
do a fresh install of Windows 98 SE, and that all those old
versions of the operating system are going to cause me problems. I
hate to go through that, but I want my computer to stay
trouble-free. Is he right?'' Assorted Q&AMP;As. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Labor Department has said
companies that give stock options to workers who receive overtime
pay must also calculate the overtime earnings based on the profit
earned from the options. Employers are hopping mad about the new
``advisory ruling'' because the new rule will make options hard to
administer. By L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Changing jobs just to get a higher
salary is a great short-term strategy that can hurt you in the long
run. Job hoppers have to make sure each jump gets them closer to
their retirement goals. By SHANNON BUGGS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-RUSSIA-NUCLEAR (Washington) _ In an unprecedented display
of cooperation, the United States and Russia plan to open a joint
military center near Moscow later this year to reduce the chances
of war between the world's two largest nuclear powers. By ERIC
ROSENBERG. (Filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ While recent attention has
focused on great and near-great American presidents, it's fair to
say that about half of the nation's chief executives have been
poor. Surprisingly, Richard Nixon and Bill Clinton would be rated
good if it weren't for the horrendous scandals that marred their
tenure. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
