<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Saturday, Jan. 15. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SECURITY (Moscow) _ Underscoring its darkening view of
the West, the Kremlin issued a new national security strategy on
Friday which inveighs against an expansionist Europe and United
States and contemplates the use of nuclear weapons in war ``if all
other means of resolving the crisis have been exhausted.'' The
revised language governing nuclear weapons is a subtle but
unmistakable change from the previous strategy, issued in 1997,
which allowed the use of nuclear arms only ``in case of a threat to
the existence of the Russian Federation.'' By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-SPACE (Seoul) _ Having scored success in making computer
memory chips, consumer electronics and automobiles, South Korea,
the most daring of the Asian tigers, has set its sights on a far
loftier goal: conquering outer space. The government plans to
develop a rocket capable of ferrying satellites into orbit within
the next five years at a cost that space agency officials estimate
at between $500 million and $1 billion, although independent
experts said the cost could run as high several billion dollars. By
Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-ABORTION (Washington) _ The Supreme Court on Friday set
the stage for its most important abortion ruling in recent years,
agreeing to decide whether states may ban a surgical procedure
opponents call ``partial birth abortion.'' The justices voted to
review a Nebraska law that made it a crime for doctors to perform
such abortions. A federal appeals court struck down that law,
calling it unconstitutional. (Summary from wires.) By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   GLAXO-SMITHKLINE (London) _ Glaxo Wellcome and SmithKline
Beecham, Britain's second- and third-biggest drug companies, say
they are in talks on a merger that would create the world's largest
pharmaceutical company. Talks between the two companies in 1998
collapsed over the issue of who would run the combination. By
Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-CANCER (Undated) _ Young women with the earliest
stage of breast cancer may need more extensive surgery than many
are getting to make sure that the cancer does not grow back,
researchers report. The additional surgery may include larger and
more carefully done lumpectomies, and in some cases even
mastectomies. By Denise Grady.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 1633EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6271 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-APACHE-INVESTIGATION-     01-14 2032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APACHE-INVESTIGATION-SHORT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Army scrutinizing Apache flight-control system
 &HT;    (Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Jan. 16. A longer version will move
also. A graphic on the BUCS system is available.)
 &HT;    By Russell Carollo
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The U.S. Army has launched a special
investigation into a complex flight-control system suspected in
more than 60 aviation incidents involving Apache helicopters,
including a fatal crash last year near Kosovo that helped ignite a
national debate over the readiness of the Apache fleet.
</P>
<P>
   At least three major accidents since 1985 are linked to problems
with the Apache's flight-control system, a Dayton Daily News
examination found. In addition, the examination found, the same
system remains a suspect in at least two other major crashes.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is the May 5, 1999, crash near Kosovo that killed
both pilots. That crash _ the second in nine days _ is now part of
a separate U.S. Justice Department examination, the Daily News has
learned.
</P>
<P>
   The other is a December 1997 crash near Fort Hood, Texas, that
also killed both pilots and is the subject of an ongoing lawsuit
against the companies that manufactured the flight-control system.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News examined never-before-released computer records
from the Army Safety Center, hundreds of pages of Army accident
reports and interviewed former and current pilots, accident
investigators and employees of the companies that helped design and
produce the AH-64 Apache and its flight-control system.
</P>
<P>
   The examination found that much of the suspicion by the Army and
its aviators over problems in the flight-control system is directed
at BUCS, the helicopter's unique emergency backup control system.
</P>
<P>
   The BUCS was designed to control the movements of the Apache
electronically if the helicopter's mechanical controls become
jammed or severed during combat or other emergency. But the BUCS
had problems, and the system was disconnected in the first 529
Apaches to roll off the assembly line in the 1980s, and is still
disconnected in a majority of the fleet.
</P>
<P>
   The BUCS is just one of several problems plaguing the Apache _
problems raising questions about whether the Apache, the military's
most advanced and lethal attack helicopter, is capable of
performing its mission.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the Apache fleet of 743 helicopters remains
grounded to replace bearings in the tail rotors or to replace
transmission parts.
</P>
<P>
   From 1998 to 1999, the rate of serious accidents involving
Apaches nearly doubled, from 2.97 accidents per 100,000 flight
hours to 5.72 _ a rate of one major accident every 17,500 hours.
And during a nine-day period last year, the Army lost two of the 24
Apaches it brought to Albania to support operations in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At least seven other countries also fly the Apache. Just last
month, Armed Forces News Wire Service reported that the Israeli Air
Force faulted Boeing and the U.S. Army for the fatal crash of an
Israeli Apache in June. The Israelis charged Boeing with
``systematic design flaws in the Apache's hydraulic system and
auxiliary power unit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Apache was developed by Hughes Helicopter as the Army's
newest attack helicopter. In 1983, the company was purchased by
McDonnell Douglas, and in 1997 McDonnell Douglas was purchased by
Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Though the military bought the expensive BUCS system to help
Apaches become better able to survive combat, the Army acknowledged
that the percentage of Apaches sent to Desert Storm with the BUCS
turned on was ``very low.''
</P>
<P>
   In a written response to the Daily News, the Army called 55 of
the 61 incidents linked to BUCS minor, resulting in less than
$2,000 in damage or the disruption of a mission. At least four
incidents, the Army says, are classified as Class A accidents,
currently defined as causing a death or total permanent disability,
at least $1 million in damage or loss or an aircraft regardless of
the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Three helicopters, the Army says, were ``saved'' by BUCS. The
Army did not identify the incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has not been a single incident during the life of the
aircraft where BUCS failure has been identified as the direct cause
of an accident when the aircraft was operated in accordance with
Army flight manuals,'' said Ken Jensen, a Boeing spokesperson at
the company's Apache plant in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   A special ``Red Team'' of aviation experts began investigating
the Apache's flight-control system last year. In December, the Army
released two safety messages related to BUCS. One announced that
the Red Team had identified specific actions required to ``reduce
risk,'' including increased training for pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The September 1999 issue of the Army's own aviation safety
magazine, Flightfax, says BUCS has ``become synonymous with . . .
aircraft loss of control and, in general, demons in the Apaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aviators fear the system, crew chiefs avoid it when possible,
armament personnel loathe the system and maintenance officers are
in awe of it,'' the article says.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Bowers, pregnant with her second child when her husband's
Apache crashed near Fort Hood in 1997, said she first learned about
BUCS at her husband's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just told it was the BUCS,'' Bowers said. ``I think all
the pilots know there has been a problem with it (BUCS), but what
can they do? They're like slaves to the military.''
</P>
<P>
   Army records show a part linked to BUCS was suspected to have
malfunctioned on a helicopter that crashed at Fort Hood, Texas, in
1990, resulting in only minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   In its written response to the newspaper regarding that crash,
the Army acknowledged that one of the linear variable differential
transducer (LVDT) probes had malfunctioned ``just prior to or
during the accident sequence.'' LVDTs, located throughout the
flight-control system, monitor coordination between movements of
the control sticks and pedals and movements of the servocylinders.
</P>
<P>
   Should an LVDT sense a problem, it can trigger an activation of
BUCS. If the LVDT is not set properly _ called setting the nulls _
it can signal danger when there is none, activating BUCS when
pilots aren't expecting it.
</P>
<P>
   However, a written response from Boeing says, ``The broken
(LVDT) probe was not the cause of the accident.''
</P>
<P>
   In October 1996, the BUCS in an Apache flying at Fort Knox, Ky.,
unexpectedly came on, although the pilot was able to land the
helicopter. After the incident, the Army again became concerned
about LVDTs, the part replaced after the 1990 Fort Hood crash.
</P>
<P>
   After the Fort Knox incident, the Army acknowledged in its
written response to the Daily News, it prepared a safety message,
but the draft copy was misplaced when personnel and files were
moved from St. Louis to a new office in Huntsville, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Fatal Texas crash
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 4, 1997, Chief Warrant Officer Phillip Wayne Bowers and
Capt. Donald J. Lee, the Army Aviation Association of America's
1996 Aviator of the Year, were flying a BUCS-active Apache on a
daytime training mission near San Saba, Texas. The crew of a nearby
Apache saw the accident happen.
</P>
<P>
   With no warning and for no apparent reason, the Apache Bowers
and Lee were flying banked left and flew into a rocky hillside at
100 mph, breaking the helicopter into pieces thrown more than 200
feet away as it burst into flames.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of pilots were considered as talented at Lee,
making the possibility of pilot error at least questionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a BUCS activation is the most plausible explanation
for the crash at this point,'' said Dallas attorney Jon Kettles,
one of several lawyers representing the two women left widowed by
the accident. ``It was a smooth left turn right into the ground,
and pilots just don't do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not normal for two pilots to voluntarily kill
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Kettles, a former Army helicopter pilot and former engineer at
the Army Safety Center, said he suspects the LVDT null settings
were not checked as required.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the Fort Hood accident, the Army was still more
than a year away from releasing its safety message concerning LVDT
settings _ the message prepared after the 1996 Fort Knox incident
but later lost.
</P>
<P>
   An Army investigation found that all four shear pins, designed
to break and activate BUCS during emergencies, had broken and that
the ``BUCS-ON'' light was illuminated. In addition, the report
says, the LVDTs were found in a position ``suggesting that a
possible uncommanded BUCS-on condition may have occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   But the investigation also found that the shear pins, the
``BUCS-ON'' light and the LVDTs could be explained by the impact of
the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was not enough evidence to support anything,'' said
Marvin Armour, an Apache test pilot who assisted in the Army's
safety investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But Armour, who officially leaves the Army next month, said
eyewitness accounts seemed to point to some type of uncommanded
flight input.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't believe they would have made such a stupid
mistake,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's public report on the 1997 Fort Hood crash does not
pinpoint a cause, but two of the five recommendations in the report
concerned flight controls: One calling for improved BUCS training
and another calling for the Army to initiate an investigation of
uncommanded flight control inputs.
</P>
<P>
   Fatal Albania crash
</P>
<P>
   In April 1999 _ 16 months after the fatal Fort Hood crash and 2
1/2 years after the original safety message was misplaced _ the
Army issued a Safety of Flight message warning that LVDTs ``may
move out'' of position.
</P>
<P>
   On May 5, two days before the compliance deadline for the safety
message, an Apache helicopter conducting a night training mission
in preparation for combat in Kosovo was leading a formation of five
helicopters over mountainous terrain in Albania when it began to
slow and move right. As the crew of another helicopter watched, the
nose of the Apache then pitched up as the helicopter rolled rapidly
to the right, falling 150 feet to the ground and exploding in
flames.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Warrant Officer David Gibbs, 38, of Massillon, Ohio, and
Chief Warrant Officer Kevin Reichert, 28, of Chetek, Wis., were
killed.
</P>
<P>
   The crash _ the second in nine days involving one of the 24
Apaches sent to Albania _ raised serious questions about the
readiness of the fleet of Apaches, which never entered combat in
Kosovo. There's no indication the first crash was related to BUCS.
</P>
<P>
   Findings, conclusions, recommendations and witness statements of
Army safety investigations usually are secret. Releasable portions
of the final report are not expected to be made public until as
late as April.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Army won't give me anything,'' said Reichert's wife,
Ridgely. ``I've asked for the safety report. I've asked them for
updates on how the safety report is coming.''
</P>
<P>
   In its written response to the Dayton Daily News, the Army
refused to discuss the accident in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``This accident is still under investigation, and it would be
improper to speculate on the final results of the investigation,''
the Army's response says.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Justice Department is now conducting its own
examination into the fatal crash in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did BUCS cause the accident? Unknown,'' Mark Metzger, Boeing's
flight operations manager for the Apache program, says in a memo
about the crash. ``The physical data doesn't support it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 23, the Army released two more safety messages
concerning BUCS.
</P>
<P>
   One of the messages called for an inspection of all BUCS
servocylinders to ensure that a sealant is applied to the threads
of the LVDT probe. A movement of the probe out of the null setting,
the message says, ``will cause BUCS system activation.''
Application of the sealant, the message says, ``eliminates this
condition.''
</P>
<P>
   The other safety message announced that a special Army ``Red
Team'' of aviation experts had identified specific actions to
``reduce risk'' involving BUCS, including increasing training for
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
