</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APACHES-INVESTIGATION16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Army scrutinizing Apache flight-control system
 &HT;    (Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Jan. 16. A shorter version will move
also. A graphic on the BUCS system is available.)
 &HT;    By Russell Carollo
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The U.S. Army has launched a special
investigation into a complex flight-control system suspected in
more than 60 aviation incidents involving Apache helicopters,
including a fatal crash last year near Kosovo that helped ignite a
national debate over the readiness of the Apache fleet.
</P>
<P>
   At least three major accidents since 1985 are linked to problems
with the Apache's flight control system, a Dayton Daily News
examination found. In addition, the examination found, the same
system remains a suspect in at least two other major crashes.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is the crash near Kosovo, which is now part of a
separate U.S. Justice Department examination, the Daily News has
learned.
</P>
<P>
   The other is a December 1997 crash near Fort Hood, Texas, which
also killed both pilots and is the subject of an ongoing lawsuit
against the companies that manufactured the flight control system.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News examined never-before-released computer records
from the Army Safety Center and hundreds of pages of Army accident
reports and interviewed former and current pilots, accident
investigators and employees of the companies that helped design and
produce the $16 million Apache and its flight control system.
</P>
<P>
   The examination found that much of the suspicion by the Army and
its aviators over problems in the flight control system is directed
at BUCS, the helicopter's unique emergency backup control system.
</P>
<P>
   The BUCS was designed to control the movements of the Apache
electronically if the helicopter's mechanical controls become
jammed or severed during combat or other emergency. But the BUCS
has had problems, and the system was disconnected in the first 529
Apaches to roll off the assembly line in the 1980s, and it is still
disconnected in a majority of the fleet.
</P>
<P>
   The BUCS is just one of several problems plaguing the Apache _
problems raising questions about whether the military's most
advanced and lethal attack helicopter is capable of performing its
mission.
</P>
<P>
   More than half the Apache fleet remains grounded because of
problems with bearings in the tail rotor system, and in November,
the Army announced it would begin inspecting the entire fleet of
743 helicopters for problems in the transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   From 1998 to 1999, the rate of serious accidents involving
Apaches nearly doubled, from 2.97 accidents per 100,000 flight
hours to 5.72 _ a rate of one major accident every 17,500 hours.
And during a nine-day period last year, the Army lost two of the 24
Apaches it brought to Albania to support operations in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   At least seven other countries also fly the Apache. Just last
month, Armed Forces News Wire Service reported that the Israeli Air
Force faulted Boeing and the U.S. Army for the fatal crash of an
Israeli Apache in June. The Israelis charged Boeing with
``systematic design flaws in the Apache's hydraulic system and
auxiliary power unit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Apache was developed by Hughes Helicopter as the Army's
newest attack helicopter. In 1983, the company was purchased by
McDonnell-Douglas, and in 1997 McDonnell-Douglas was purchased by
Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Though the military bought the expensive BUCS system to help
Apaches become better able to survive combat, the Army acknowledged
that the percentage of Apaches sent to Desert Storm with the BUCS
turned on was ``very low.''
</P>
<P>
   In a written response to the Daily News, the Army called 55 of
the 61 incidents linked to BUCS minor, resulting in less than
$2,000 in damage or the disruption of a mission. At least four
incidents, the Army says, are classified as Class A accidents,
causing a death or total permanent disability, at least $1 million
in damage or loss of an aircraft regardless of the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Three helicopters, the Army says, were ``saved'' by BUCS. The
Army did not identify the incidents.
</P>
<P>
   A special ``Red Team'' of aviation experts began investigating
the Apache's flight control system last year. In December, it
released two safety messages related to BUCS. One announced that
the Red Team had identified specific actions required to ``reduce
risk,'' including increased training for pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The September 1999 issue of the Army's own aviation safety
magazine, Flightfax, says BUCS has ``become synonymous with ...
aircraft loss of control and, in general, demons in the Apaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aviators fear the system, crew chiefs avoid it when possible,
armament personnel loathe the system and maintenance officers are
in awe of it,'' the article says.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Bowers, pregnant with her second child when her husband's
Apache crashed near Fort Hood in 1997, said she first learned about
BUCS at her husband's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just told it was the BUCS,'' Bowers said. ``I think all
the pilots know there has been a problem with it, but what can they
do? They're like slaves to the military.''
</P>
<P>
   Backup control system
</P>
<P>
   Like other helicopters, the Apache is controlled by sticks and
foot pedals linked mechanically to hydraulic servocylinders. The
servocylinders control the movements of the main and tail rotors,
which determine the direction of the helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike other helicopters, the Apache's mechanical control
system is backed up by an electronic system, BUCS. If the Apache's
mechanical controls become jammed or severed during combat or other
emergency, BUCS is designed to allow pilots to operate the
helicopter's hydraulic servocylinders electronically.
</P>
<P>
   But pilots and other experts suspect that BUCS is taking control
of the helicopters when there is no emergency, causing so-called
``uncommanded flight control inputs'' _ steep banks, sharp turns or
other unusual maneuvers not initiated by the pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Once BUCS is engaged, there's no turning back. To return to
mechanical flight control, a helicopter has to land and undergo
ground maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they first came out with the BUCS system, I had some
concerns about it,'' said Richard Langer, former chief Apache
quality assurance supervisor for McDonnell-Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   BUCS was deactivated on the first 529 Apaches because the system
wasn't working correctly, Langer said. To deactivate BUCS, shear
pins that were designed to break and activate BUCS during
emergencies were replaced with solid steel pins.
</P>
<P>
   But even shutting off BUCS proved to be hazardous.
</P>
<P>
   The Apache that Henry Fowler and fellow test pilot Stu Park
climbed aboard on June 17, 1985, had solid steel pins in it, Fowler
said.
</P>
<P>
   As Fowler and Park started the engines, the helicopter _ the
31st production helicopter to come off the assembly line _ rolled
left and came to rest on its side, causing nearly $300,000 in
damage. BUCS was blamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was supposed to be shut off,'' said Fowler, who now works
for Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   That same month, the Army issued a Safety of Flight message, a
directive designed to inform pilots and mechanics of potential
aircraft dangers and of solutions the military has proposed to
mitigate those dangers. The message instructed Apache units to
``totally disable the BUCS.''
</P>
<P>
   Fowler said crews began removing BUCS parts in the hydraulic
servocylinders to make sure the system wouldn't come on again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on in the Apache fielding, aviator mistrust of the BUCS,
exacerbated by an incident at the aircraft plant involving
inadvertent BUCS activation, led to a decision to inactivate
BUCS,'' the article in the Army's safety magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   BUCS turned on
</P>
<P>
   The decision to deactivate BUCS was reversed in 1988, and for
the first time Apaches began leaving the assembly line in Mesa,
Ariz., with the BUCS turned on. In November 1989, the 530th Apache
to roll off the assembly line was delivered to the Army as the
first helicopter with an activated BUCS.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots began referring to their Apaches as either
``BUCS-active'' or ``non-BUCS,'' and they became very aware of
which type they were flying.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been an argument since BUCS hit the flight line
whether to turn it on or turn it off,'' said Thomas Boucher, who
flew Apaches for 10 years and trained Army instructor pilots before
retiring in 1994. ``There are a lot of concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those concerns is training. Pilots must make
life-and-death decisions in the critical seconds it takes BUCS to
engage, and the helicopter handles differently when BUCS moves the
controls electronically. But ``training on BUCS had never been
considered a critical task item,'' the Flightfax article says.
</P>
<P>
   Just 10 minutes of the Army flight controls portion of the
aircraft qualification course is devoted to BUCS, the article says,
and, ``There is no simulator or BUCS flight training.''
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 15, 1990, one year after the first BUCS-active
helicopter was delivered to the Army and as 430,000 American troops
were assembling in the Persian Gulf, Warrant Officers James D.
Ellis and Samuel D. Gentsch were flying an Apache on a daytime
training mission in Texas when they heard a loud noise while
hovering at 50 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopter began falling, its tail and main rotor blades
mowing down several small trees before the aircraft hit the ground
_ impacting with enough force to send a 2.75-inch rocket pod into
the main rotor blades, knocking the pod 84 feet from the crash
site. Gentsch carried Ellis from the wreckage, which had started to
catch fire.
</P>
<P>
   Both pilots escaped with only minor injuries, but the helicopter
was destroyed. The Army estimated the total cost of the accident at
$10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Army records examined by the Daily News show a part linked to
BUCS was suspected to have malfunctioned on the helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   In its written response to the newspaper, the Army acknowledged
that one of the linear variable differential transducer (LVDT)
probes had malfunctioned ``just prior to or during the accident
sequence.'' LVDTs, located throughout the flight control system,
monitor coordination between movements of the control sticks and
pedals and movements of the servocylinders.
</P>
<P>
   Should an LVDT sense a problem, it can trigger an activation of
BUCS. If the LVDT is not set properly, it can signal danger when
there is none, activating BUCS when pilots aren't expecting it.
</P>
<P>
   A written response from Boeing says, ``The broken probe was not
the cause of the accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Although investigators did not positively identify the source of
the malfunction in the 1990 crash, the Army response says, they did
determine that an LVDT failed because of a ``substandard weld.''
</P>
<P>
   In January 1991, two months after the accident, the Army issued
a Safety of Flight message for BUCS-active Apaches warning of
problems with welds on LVDTs. The message said 108 aircraft would
get replacement servocylinders.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's written response says that after the accident it quit
using LVDTs made by the same manufacturer and began using LVDTs
that had two methods of attachments.
</P>
<P>
   Another crash and more questions
</P>
<P>
   Less than two years later, on Sept. 28, 1992, civilian test
pilots James Mecklin and John Tulloch were flying a new BUCS-active
Apache over Delaware as part of a test for a classified project.
The test involved rapid movements of the flight controls _
movements that could cause the helicopter to believe it was
experiencing control problems and activate BUCS.
</P>
<P>
   As the controls moved during a 60-foot hover, the helicopter
went into an unexpected right roll and began to fall. Tulloch moved
his controls to stop the helicopter from rolling, but in seconds
the main rotor hit the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Mecklin broke his left arm and was pinned in the helicopter.
Tulloch suffered back injuries. The helicopter was destroyed, and
the Army estimated the total cost of the accident at $10.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher, the Apache pilot assigned by the Army to assist in the
investigation, said the cause of the accident was identified as a
malfunction in a microswitch used to activate BUCS. The
malfunction, he said, was linked to how certain BUCS parts were
being removed from the helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   In its written response, the Army blamed the accident on
``unauthorized maintenance at the factory during manufacture.'' No
other Apaches were found to have malfunctioning microswitches, the
Army response says, but new procedures were implemented as a
result.
</P>
<P>
   After the accident, Boucher said, the Army grounded all
BUCS-active Apaches to inspect the microswitches. The inspections,
he said, generated 86 reports on a variety of issues concerning
BUCS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them were potential accidents,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two months after the accident, in November 1992, the Army issued
a Safety of Flight message, warning that a recent accident
investigation had identified a problem with a BUCS microswitch. The
message recommended inspecting 220 aircraft. An inspection already
completed, the message said, found that several helicopters were
``shown to have relatively minor quality problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Mecklin, a former Air Force maintenance test pilot who flew
helicopters for 40 years before retiring in 1994, has a different
opinion on the accident. Mecklin said the shear pins designed to
activate BUCS simply break too easily.
</P>
<P>
   The time lapse between breaking a shear pin and activating BUCS
is critical. The Army says there is a one- to three-second delay
before BUCS engages.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 2 1/2 seconds, we were on the ground,'' Mecklin said. ``So
much for your backup control system.''
</P>
<P>
   The September 1992 crash wasn't the helicopter's only incident
involving BUCS. Records from the Army Safety Center show that on
Jan. 29, 1992, one of the shear pins designed to break during an
emergency and activate BUCS accidentally broke while the helicopter
was on the ground. The pin, records show, was replaced the same
day.
</P>
<P>
   Accidents trigger `null' concerns
</P>
<P>
   In October 1996, the BUCS in an Apache flying at Fort Knox, Ky.,
unexpectedly came on, although the pilot was able to land the
helicopter. After the incident, the Army again became concerned
about LVDTs, the part replaced after the 1990 Fort Hood crash.
</P>
<P>
   If the LVDT is not set properly, it can signal danger when there
is none, activating BUCS when pilots aren't expecting it.
</P>
<P>
   Setting the LVDT _ called setting the nulls _ is much like
setting the alignment of an automobile's front end. A properly
aligned front end should not turn a car when the steering wheel is
in the neutral position, and when the nulls are properly set on
LVDTs, the devices should sense no movement of the flight controls
and should not activate BUCS.
</P>
<P>
   After the Fort Knox incident, the Army acknowledged in its
written response, it prepared an Air Safety Action Message, a
safety directive similar to a Safety of Flight message but carrying
less urgency.
</P>
<P>
   But the draft copy of that message was misplaced when personnel
and files were moved from St. Louis to a new office in Huntsville,
Ala.
</P>
<P>
   It would be 2 1/2 years before the Army issued a new message.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in February 1997, McDonnell-Douglas became aware of
the Fort Knox incident and initiated an investigation, according to
a company memo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been determined that two failure modes could cause
inadvertent BUCS engagement,'' the memo says.
</P>
<P>
   One cause was a part that was found to be functioning properly,
the memo says. The other cause, the memo says, is an unexpected
movement of an LVDT probe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk assessment determined the worst mishap from a probe
movement to be catastrophic, and the probability that a hazard will
occur during the planned life of the system is remote,'' the memo
says.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, on Dec. 4, 1997, Chief Warrant Officer Phillip
Wayne Bowers, whose wife was expecting their second child, and
Capt. Donald J. Lee, the Army Aviation Association of America's
1996 Aviator of the Year, were flying a BUCS-active Apache on a
daytime training mission near San Saba, Texas. The crew of a nearby
Apache saw the accident happen.
</P>
<P>
   With no warning and for no apparent reason, the Apache Bowers
and Lee were flying banked left and flew into a rocky hillside at
100 mph, breaking the helicopter into pieces thrown more than 200
feet away as it burst into flames.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of pilots were considered as talented as Lee,
making the possibility of pilot error at least questionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a BUCS activation is the most plausible explanation
for the crash at this point,'' said Dallas attorney John Kettles,
one of several lawyers representing the two women left widowed by
the accident. ``It was a smooth left turn right into the ground,
and pilots just don't do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not normal for two pilots to voluntarily kill
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Kettles, a former Army helicopter pilot and former engineer at
the Army Safety Center, said he suspects the LVDT null settings
were not checked as required.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the Fort Hood accident, the Army was still more
than a year away from releasing its safety message concerning LVDT
settings _ the message prepared after the 1996 Fort Knox incident
but later lost.
</P>
<P>
   An Army investigation found that all four shear pins, designed
to break and activate BUCS during emergencies, had broken and that
the ``BUCS-ON'' light was illuminated. In addition, the report
says, the LVDTs were found in a position ``suggesting that a
possible uncommanded BUCS-on condition may have occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   The battalion, the investigation found, reported 10 uncommanded
flight control inputs in the 18 months preceding the accident.
Though pilots were able to recover each time, investigators warned
that ``an accident can occur.''
</P>
<P>
   But the investigation also found that the shear pins, the
``BUCS-ON'' light and the LVDTs could be explained by the impact of
the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was not enough evidence to support anything,'' said
Marvin Armour, an Apache test pilot who assisted in the Army's
safety investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But Armour, who officially leaves the Army next month, said
eyewitness accounts seemed to point to some type of uncommanded
flight input.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't believe they would have made such a stupid
mistake,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The maintenance records he researched during the investigation,
Armour said, showed one of the BUCS hydraulic servocylinders in the
helicopter had been replaced just prior to the accident.
</P>
<P>
   The Apache, like many other military aircraft, carried no flight
data recorder, and much of the helicopter was destroyed, making it
nearly impossible for investigators to determine if electronic
flight controls could have malfunctioned.
</P>
<P>
   The latest model of the Apache, the Longbow or D model, has a
maintenance data recorder that should solve that problem, Armour
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots, originally interviewed as witnesses to the Fort Hood
crash, told investigators about their own experiences with Apache
flight control problems.
</P>
<P>
   One pilot recalled an incident in which he was flying at 3,400
feet when, for no apparent reason, the helicopter pointed down,
rolled right and started falling before he was able to regain
control. Another pilot told investigators of a November 1995
incident in which he was flying his helicopter at 600 feet when it
suddenly began rolling left and shuddered.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked the front seat pilot whether he was on the controls,
and the response was, 'No,''' an accident investigator quoted the
pilot as saying.
</P>
<P>
   A flight surgeon who arrived at the 1997 Fort Hood crash site
told accident investigators that six pilots, during discussions
about the accident, told her of previous incidents of uncommanded
flight control movements. The surgeon, a captain, gave
investigators a list containing names of the pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's public report on the 1997 Fort Hood crash does not
pinpoint a cause, but two of the five recommendations in the report
concerned flight controls: One calling for improved BUCS training
and another calling for the Army to initiate an investigation of
uncomsmanded flight control inputs.
</P>
<P>
   Crashes draw world attention
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year after that accident, on Oct. 7, 1998, the
flight controls of a new D model Apache Longbow flying at Fort Hood
became damaged when the barrel of a 30mm gun exploded, according to
the Army. The BUCS engaged, Army records show, but the ``very
senior standardization instructor pilot'' was unable to
successfully land the helicopter, and it crashed.
</P>
<P>
   The crew escaped virtually uninjured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did BUCS work as advertised? If so, why couldn't a capable
master aviator regain control of the aircraft,'' the Flightfax
article says.
</P>
<P>
   It was this accident, along with other incidents, that sparked
the special Red Team investigation, the Army said.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1999 _ 2 1/2 years after the Fort Knox incident that
prompted the message that was later lost _ the Army issued a Safety
of Flight message warning that LVDTs ``may move out'' of position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investigation into a BUCS activation in flight has revealed a
suspect condition in the BUCS ... servocylinders,'' the message
says. ``If the LVDT probe moves out of the null condition, this
will cause a BUCS system activation.''
</P>
<P>
   The safety message set a reporting deadline of no later than May
7, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Two days before that deadline, on May 5, an Apache helicopter
conducting a night training mission in preparation for combat in
Kosovo was leading a formation of five helicopters over mountainous
terrain in Albania when it began to slow and move right, according
to an Army account of the incident obtained by the Dayton Daily
News.
</P>
<P>
   As the crew of another helicopter watched, the nose of the
Apache then pitched up as the helicopter rolled rapidly to the
right, falling 150 feet to the ground and exploding in flames, the
Army account of the incident says.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Warrant Officer David Gibbs, 38, of Massillon, Ohio, and
Chief Warrant Officer Kevin Reichert, 28, of Chetek, Wis., were
killed.
</P>
<P>
   The crash _ the second in nine days involving one of the 24
Apaches sent to Albania _ raised serious questions about the
readiness of the fleet of Apaches, which never entered combat in
Kosovo. There's no indication the first crash was related to BUCS.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Army won't give me anything,'' said Reichert's wife,
Ridgeley. ``I've asked for the safety report. I've asked them for
updates on how the safety report is coming.''
</P>
<P>
   In its written response to the Dayton Daily News, the Army
refused to discuss the accident in Albania, saying it was still
under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   A memo from Boeing's flight operations manager for the Apache
program says there's no record Army maintenance personnel checked
the LVDT settings as required by the Safety of Flight message.
</P>
<P>
   ``The personnel said that they had done the work but not
recorded the data,'' Boeing manager Mark Metzger wrote in the memo
obtained by the Dayton Daily News. ``Did it really get done?
Unknown. I believe the team consensus was sloppy paperwork.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the possibility that some type of uncommanded flight control
input caused the accident, Metzger wrote: ``This is the condition
that has been experienced a couple of times in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did BUCS cause the accident? Unknown. The physical data
doesn't support it.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Justice now is conducting its own
examination into the fatal crash in Albania, the Dayton Daily News
has learned. The Department of Justice did not respond to requests
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 23, the Army released two safety messages concerning
BUCS.
</P>
<P>
   One called for an inspection of all BUCS servocylinders to
ensure that a sealant is applied to the threads of the LVDT probe.
A movement of the probe out of the null setting, the message says,
``will cause a BUCS system activation.'' Application of the
sealant, the message says, ``eliminates this condition.''
</P>
<P>
   The other safety message announced that a special Army ``Red
Team'' of aviation experts had identified specific actions required
to ``reduce risk'' involving flight controls. Those actions include
increased training for pilots, something recommended after the
fatal Fort Hood crash two years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``My recommendation was disable them all,'' said Armour, the
former Apache test pilot. ``I think the drawbacks of BUCS outweigh
the benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell Carollo writes for the Dayton Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
