<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER LABOR DEPARTMENT BULLET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Secretary of Labor Alexis Herman has said that she wants to make
sure labor laws adapt to new work arrangements. But it appears as
if she's thinking more like she's back in the Industrial Revolution
than on the threshold of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   After criticism forced her to backpedal last week over the Labor
Department's proposal to ask employers to inspect the safety
conditions of their employees who work at home, her department has
issued another onerous opinion that has far-reaching implications.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Wage and Hour Administration recently indicated that
companies that give stock options to hourly wage workers may have
to figure as part of base pay the profits an employee makes on
exercised stock options when calculating overtime wages.
</P>
<P>
   The opinion, written a year ago but made public just recently,
is causing a stir among the growing number of employers who give
employees stock options. Employers predict that if the Labor
Department tries to broaden the opinion from what the department
said was its narrow focus, companies will be discouraged from
providing what has become the hottest employee benefit in this bull
market.
</P>
<P>
   Stock options were once a perk reserved for upper management,
but recently many innovative companies have extended the benefit
all the way down the corporate ladder. They work the same way on
the shop floor as they work in the executive suite: Stock options
tie an employee's compensation to a company's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Options have become so popular that the Bureau of Labor
Statistics is studying how important they are in a typical
compensation package.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Labor Department opinion, employers who offer the
options are subject to a new payroll liability along with a new
administrative headache. The overtime component would have to be
calculated individually for each employee using a complicated
formula of overtime hours and stock profits.
</P>
<P>
   That would be expensive and time-consuming, said William R.
Bufkins, director of special projects _ including compensation
design _ for Spacehab, a space manufacturing and services company
in the Clear Lake area.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SCOPE WAS NARROW, AGENCY SAYS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department is quick to point out that the opinion
doesn't apply to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   It was a specific response to a specific set of circumstances,
said department spokesman Howard Waddell. It was never intended to
be a general statement on stock option plans, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But compensation consultants are treating the opinion as a
signal of how the agency will handle future overtime wage
complaints in cases where stocks options are given.
</P>
<P>
   Ed McGaughey, who leads the compensation practice for Buck
Consultants in Houston, said it's an opinion employers must pay
attention to because if the department determines they're
responsible for overtime wages based on options, they could end up
paying up to two years of back pay.
</P>
<P>
   The stock option plan that was described by the unidentified
employer in the opinion was a typical arrangement, said Tim Bartl,
assistant general counsel for LPA, a Washington, D.C., trade group
that represents senior human resource executives in large
companies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A DEPARTURE ON OPTIONS ISSUE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The interpretation is a departure from the way the department
treated options in the past _ or at least how employers thought it
treated them.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal wage law, bonuses aren't typically used as part of
base pay when calculating overtime pay unless a bonus is tied to
performance. If the bonus is discretionary _ such as a Christmas
bonus given to everyone _ it's not considered part of the wage
base. Neither are profit-sharing plans.
</P>
<P>
   In the case involved in the opinion, the stock options were not
considered a gift like a Christmas bonus because employees had to
work for the company for three months before becoming eligible for
the options, Waddell said.
</P>
<P>
   Companies such as Chase Bank of Texas that offer all their
employees stock options said they weren't even aware of the
department's opinion letter. That's not because they aren't paying
attention to the department's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   It's virtually impossible to know about the opinion letters,
said Bartl. Although they can be found in the department's library,
it typically takes months before they're put there, he said. They
can also be found on online legal databases, but they're hard to
search unless you know what you're looking for, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
