<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6274 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CONTRABAND-ONLINE-NYT     01-14 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTRABAND-ONLINE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 eBAY CALLED A `BLACK MARKET' FOR ANIMAL PRODUCTS   By RON MATUS   The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Products being made from endangered species
are being sold on the Internet at a growing rate, alarming
conservation groups who fear the sheer volume of transactions will
revive markets for goods they want to eliminate.
</P>
<P>
   Items like statues made from elephant ivory and jewelry made
from sea turtle shells can't be sold across state lines because of
federal laws protecting endangered species. But every day, such
items are sold across cyberspace on the online auction outlets.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, conservation groups and federal wildlife
officials have raised concerns about trading on eBay.com, by far
the largest of hundreds of Internet trading companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like there's a zillion items there, but you have to
realize that every week there's new stuff,'' said Gary Appelson
with the Caribbean Conservation Corp., a Gainesville-based group
that works on issues related to endangered sea turtles. ``eBay may
be the world's largest online black market for endangered species
products.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservation groups say the problem is likely to get worse as
the popularity of online trading grows.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, which is charged with
enforcing laws banning sales of such products, says it does not
have the resources to deal with the problem, but has been
consulting with eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials say they are working to reduce illegal sales
through increased monitoring and user education. But they say there
is no way to stop every illegal item from being listed.
</P>
<P>
   They also say it's often difficult to know for sure that an item
is illegal unless it is examined by an expert.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce restrictions might apply to one species of animal, such
as Indian elephants, but not a related species, such as African
elephants. It is also possible that items such as jewelry made from
sea turtle shells could be made from other, similar-looking
materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, eBay doesn't have a team of sea turtle
scientists,'' said Rob Chestnut, the company lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Conservation groups say it is likely that many people posting
such items on e-Bay do not realize it is illegal to sell them. Many
of the products are trinkets, antiques and heirlooms, such as a
cigarette holder made from turtle shell that was posted on the site
this week.
</P>
<P>
   But whether they know it or not, conservationists say, people
selling those products are broadening markets that lead to
increased killing and poaching of everything from sea turtles to
elephants.
</P>
<P>
   Based in San Jose, Calif., eBay provides a forum for buying and
selling millions of products around the clock. With eBay, items
that used to be in garage sales can now be put on display in a
global flea market. More than 400,000 new items are posted daily.
</P>
<P>
   Company policy prohibits the listing of items made from sea
turtles, bears, leopards and other rare animals, but such items
could be quickly found on the site this week.
</P>
<P>
   Appelson said an eBay search last week turned up 50 items
believed to be made from hawksbill sea turtles, a critically
endangered species. Jewelry, eyeglass frames and even cigarette
holders are made from hawksbill shell, which is known commonly as
``tortoise shell.''
</P>
<P>
   A search by the Washington, D.C.-based U.S. Humane Society found
more than 400 ivory products on eBay, said Teresa Telecky, the
organization's director of wildlife trade. Laws dealing with the
ivory trade are complicated, but Telecky said the Humane Society
determined from a description of the products listed that many of
them could not be legally traded.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the items posted on eBay are pictured and contain a
short description and history.
</P>
<P>
   Telecky said online trading has ``defeated the normal
import/export systems that are used to keep these things out of the
country.'' Law enforcement officials who want to sniff out illegal
wildlife products can't just check bags at airports anymore, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The interstate sale of products made from endangered species was
outlawed by the Endangered Species Act in 1973. The act applies to
products made before the ban was implemented, wildlife officials
say _ at least as far back as the turn of the last century.
Violating the act is punishable by up to one year in jail and
$100,000 in criminal fines per person. Civil fines can be assessed
up to $25,000 per violation.
</P>
<P>
   The Humane Society and other conservation groups say the trading
problem is getting worse as online shopping grows. Currently, there
are 3.4 million items listed on eBay in 2,900 categories. Every
day, more than $8 million worth of merchandise is sold.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jane Lavin, a senior special agent with the U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service, said Internet trading poses problems that
traditional commerce does not. There's more volume, more speed and
more anonymity, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin said wildlife officials have been devising a strategy to
deal with the problem, but she said she could not disclose details
at this time.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Pursglove, eBay's spokesman, said eBay users have the
responsibility to abide by an agreement with the company not to
sell illegal items. If they persist in doing so, they can be barred
from using the service.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials agreed to step up monitoring after talking
with conservation groups in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut, the company attorney, said the difficulty in
enforcement goes beyond sales volume.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company immediately notified the Fish and Wildlife
Service after the Caribbean Conservation Corporation raised
questions about turtle products. But the federal agent said it was
difficult to tell which items were illegal without looking at them.
</P>
<P>
   Some items advertised as ``tortoise shell'' are made from
plastic or other products, not sea turtle. Others are old enough to
be legal to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want a reputation for selling illegal things,''
Chestnut said. But if a federal agent had problems easily
recognizing illegal products, ``it's a lot to expect us to
recognize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Telecky, with the Humane Society, said there's an easy answer to
selling items that may be illegal.
</P>
<P>
   When in doubt, ``they should just say no,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gainesville Sun, in Gainesville, Fla., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 1639EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
