<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-YOUNG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     YOUNG MAY GET OK TO PLAY FOR 49ERS AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _ Steve Young, who sat out the last 13 games of
the San Francisco 49ers' season after suffering back-to-back
concussions, will probably be cleared medically to play this year,
his agent said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite probable he will,'' Leigh Steinberg said Thursday
while watching practice for Saturday's Shrine Bowl game. ``He could
pass a physical. It's just his choice. Steve still wants to play.
He's weighing his options. His goal has always been to retire a
49er, and he's not ready to retire.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the 49ers never admitted it, Young apparently did
suffer a concussion on Sept. 19 against New Orleans when blitzing
safety Chris Hewitt used his helmet as a projectile in hitting the
quarterback head-on. The hit knocked Young into a supine position
on the Candlestick Park sod.
</P>
<P>
   A week later in Arizona, cornerback Aeneas Williams slammed into
Young on a blitz and knocked him out for a few seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Concussions in consecutive weeks compelled Young's neurologist,
Dr. Gary Steinberg of Stanford Medical School, to recommend that he
not play for the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Young has now had enough time to recover that agent Steinberg,
no relation to the neurologist, expects that Young will be cleared
to play again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the risk is his,'' Leigh Steinberg said. ``Steve's
decisions now are: Does he feel like he wants to do another season
or two? What will the 49ers' protection be like next year? We need
to hear their plans, how they plan to protect him.''
</P>
<P>
   Something else that may influence Young's football decision is
his impending marriage to Barbara Graham, 30, of Phoenix. They are
planning to wed sometime in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters for the 49ers is the NFL's unexpected new
date for the start of free agency, Feb. 11. That means teams have
to be in compliance with the salary cap for 2000 by Feb. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers must slash $24 million from their player payroll to
get in line with the per-team cap of $61 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It squeezes the timetable down,'' general manager Bill Walsh
said. ``It forces us to make our decisions quicker. It's the
accountants now, basically, trying to work this out. Maybe Feb. 10
is fine. When you first hear it you say, `Oh, my God,' then you
just face it and get to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said that if the 49ers are successful in slashing Young's
salary while offering him contract incentives to make up the
difference, the other five players targeted for salary reductions
might fall in line. Those players are linebacker Ken Norton, strong
safety Tim McDonald, left guard Ray Brown, wide receiver Jerry Rice
and center Chris Dalman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 1644EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
