<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6280 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-CITYOFANGELS-TEX     01-14 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CITYOFANGELS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREAT BLACK HOPE: CAN A BLACK DRAMA DRAW A MAINSTREAM
AUDIENCE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``City of Angels'' arrives on CBS Saturday night toting
enormously heavy baggage, so the least of its concerns is the
pre-hype view that it's nothing more than a darker (read: cheaper)
version of ``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   And I mean that literally and figuratively.
</P>
<P>
   Try as one might to judge the black-cast series as just another
drama to be dissed or defended on the merits of its writing and the
strength of its characters, ``City of Angels'' isn't just another
drama.
</P>
<P>
   It can't be. For one thing, I can't recall a black drama ever
sustaining life well into a second season. For another, black
dramas are asked to jump through the most impossible of hoops: to
be the social, political, cultural and emotional everything to all
black people, most of whom can't agree on real-life issues like
affirmative action, reparations and Louis Farrakhan, let alone TV
tastes. And on top of that, predominantly black series often work
as repellents to white viewers convinced that shows with ethnic
sensibilities will eventually wrap dramatic story lines around
white-on-black oppression.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is unfortunate, considering that the overarching
vision of co-creators and producers Steven Bochco and Paris Barclay
is to avoid focusing directly on issues relating to race. Bochco,
who chose the medical genre because of its life-and-death morality
plays, offers in ``City of Angels'' a mainstream series where the
medical heroes aren't black doctors as much as doctors who just
happen to be black.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, add this to the litany of hurdles this
series must clear to keep going: How do you write a show that's
universal enough to attract white viewers, yet culturally authentic
enough to satisfy viewers of color who want to see people who talk
and walk like them?
</P>
<P>
   ``City of Angels'' is already a cut above most black dramas _ it
at least looks like quality. It has the muted colors and shadowed
lighting of ``NYPD Blue'' and even ``Hill Street Blues,'' and, in
Blair Underwood, a real star presence _ or, at the very least, a
new fashion statement with that African-print surgical cap he
wears.
</P>
<P>
   The fictional Angels of Mercy hospital, nestled in a poor
neighborhood in Los Angeles, is a large sweat-on-the-walls place
where the equipment is third-generation, the floors are dirty, the
lights always seem to be flickering, and angry patients always seem
to be waiting.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of talk of money _ wanting it, finding it, getting
it _ which presents the hospital as a woefully underfunded,
understaffed operation that's essentially pieced together with duct
tape.
</P>
<P>
   If ``ER'' looks shabby compared to the country club corridors of
``Chicago Hope,'' then ``City of Angels'' looks like a Third World
country. It's home for those whose choices in life are slim to
none. These aren't doctors as much as Peace Corps workers.
</P>
<P>
   The backbone of the series is Dr. Ben Turner, played with
dashing passion by Underwood, who has incorporated quite a swagger
since he last worked with Bochco as a buppie lawyer on ``L.A.
Law.'' As acting surgical chief, he's overseeing a batch of
residents, including Dr. Williams (Hill Harper), a hothead quick to
play the race card in a turf war against a white resident (Phil
Buckman as Dr. Weiss).
</P>
<P>
   When not putting out that fire, he's tussling with Lillian Price
(Vivica A. Fox), a former flame hastily brought in to replace a
fired medical director.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Warren supplies suspicious conviction as the hospital's
CEO, and there's a wonderfully vulgar performance by Robert Morse,
who plays the hospital board president as though he's a
power-hungry mobster.
</P>
<P>
   Morse and Buckman are the only two playing main characters who
aren't black or Hispanic, and if viewers are jolted by this, ``City
of Angels'' will have a difficult road.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the first three episodes, few things happen you
haven't seen in another Bochco show or hospital drama: There's lots
of earnestness but little energy. But how it manages to squeeze its
ethnic sensibilities inside its mainstream jar is subtle and
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   The lighter, clunkier scenes include a white doctor
misdiagnosing a little girl's ashy legs as some kind of allergic
reaction (''It's a black thang,'' responds the girl, as two black
female doctors crack up laughing). The heavier stuff includes a
situation next week in which Williams makes a judgment call about a
black patient he thinks is a gangbanger (he's a doctor). ``ER's''
Dr. Greene was accused of the same thing, but black-on-black
prejudice presents quite a novel twist.
</P>
<P>
   Bochco and Nicholas Wooton wrote the pilot episode, and their
vision will remind you of ``Hill Street Blues'' in its look and
feel and ``L.A. Law'' for its attempt to provide us with a loftily
principled drama that refuses to take itself too seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``City of Angels'' is rife with Bochco's signature quirkiness,
including a chairman of the hospital supervisory board with a foot
fetish, a sedated gallbladder patient who is mistaken for dead and
sent to the morgue, and a man who needs a Golden Globe Award
removed from his, well, ``there.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also far too many contrived scenes, the most
unbelievable being when Price gets a drugged-out mother released
immediately from jail and has the woman undergo a rather miraculous
turnaround to care for her children and mother.
</P>
<P>
   CBS plans to give ``City of Angels'' time to find an audience,
but I wonder what kind of audience it'll attract at the sitcom hour
of 7 p.m. I also wonder if all this publicity will eventually do
this drama in.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to come out with a show that carries historical
significance. But one has to wonder about the risk of getting
buried under its heavy burden. We'll see.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
