<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6282 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-ART-$AD     01-14 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESISTANCE MAY BE FUTILE: THE CATALOGS ARE HERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 16)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I must be getting old. My frenetic seed-ordering self seems to
have flown off, leaving me to wade through my flood of catalogs
with a dry voice in my ear: ``You have plenty of seed packets
stuffed in the old ham boiler, so cool it.'' Is that you,
Grandmother?
</P>
<P>
   This year, I'm concentrating on improving the soil for the
20-some old roses I ordered, and I don't need another plant to
plague me. OK, so I had the fever, but I'm over it.
</P>
<P>
   My advice to anyone right now would be to spend the year
planting old seeds (or ones from friends), pruning and dividing the
plants you have, composting and tending your soil. You will do your
garden, and your bank account, a favor.
</P>
<P>
   But that's no fun, and besides, all those tantalizing seed
catalogs are pouring into the mailbox. There are too many good ones
to mention, and the famous old-timers, like Burpee, Cook's Garden,
Johnny's Selected Seeds and White Flower Farm, can fend for
themselves. So I want to give the best little guys some play, for
the sake of biodiversity.
</P>
<P>
   A few cutting-edge types who sold out to big companies but
apparently missed running their own show have created themselves
anew: Brent and Becky Heath, of Gloucester, Va., who sold their
superb Daffodil Mart to White Flower Farm, are now Brent &AMP; Becky's
Bulbs. It is offering some fine summer bulbs this year, like seven
different crocosmias and four different Colocasia esculentas, or
elephant ears, like Black Magic, which has an 18-inch dark purplish
leaf (877-661-2852; free catalog).
</P>
<P>
   Renee Shepherd, who sold Shepherd's Garden Seeds, also to White
Flower Farm, has resurfaced as Renee's Garden in Felton, Calif.
(831-335-7228; she also sells her seeds through Garden.com:
800-466-8142). Ms. Shepherd swears that Mignonette, a hardy
French-style alpine strawberry, can be planted from seed in spring
and bear sweet little berries by summer.
</P>
<P>
   I usually order my tomato seeds from Southern Exposure Seed
Exchange, in Mineral, Va. (540-894-9480; catalog, $2), because it
has everything from the reliable Rutgers to a heat-tolerant
Brandywine.
</P>
<P>
   Select Seeds, in Union, Conn. (860-684-9310; catalog, $1), has a
growing collection of unusual old-fashioned flower seeds and
plants. The vines are tempting, particularly the creeping gloxinias
(Asarina scandens), like Joan of Lorraine, a deep violet-blue
bell-shaped flower from Mexico, and Sky Blue, with arrowhead-shaped
leaves and tubular blue flowers with striped white throats.
</P>
<P>
   The owner, Marilyn Barlow, is excited about a very fragrant
night-blooming tobacco (Nicotiana x sanderae) in shades of white
and pale pink to rose and purple, which originated from the Flower
and Herb Exchange in Decorah, Iowa, and a claret-red Polish
amaranth (Amaranthus cruentus), ``a nice tall, sturdy plant, with
very airy flower heads, so it stands by itself without having to
tie it.'' Hear, hear.
</P>
<P>
   As for unusual trees and fruiting plants, Oikos Tree Crops, in
Kalamazoo, Mich. (616-624-6233; free catalog), offers American
persimmon, beach plum, pawpaw, hazelnut, black gum, medlar and many
others. Edible Landscaping, in Afton, Va. (800-524-4156; free
catalog), is another favorite, with its figs, peaches, plums,
persimmons, grapes, apples and even saffron crocus bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite for wildflowers is still the New England Wildflower
Society (508-877-7630; catalog, $2.50) in Framingham, Mass., a
nonprofit conservation group offering more than 200 species of
seeds and spores, from rare speckled wood lilies and dwarf
fothergillas to the spectacular giant wood fern, Dryopteris
goldieana.
</P>
<P>
   Territorial Seed Co., in Cottage Grove, Ore. (541-942-9547; free
catalog), has a good collection of vegetable and flower seeds,
including artichokes; cover crops like oats and buckwheat for
improving soil; and many medicinal herbs, from St. Johnswort to
stinging nettle.
</P>
<P>
   Seeds of Change, an organic seed company in Santa Fe, N.M.
(888-762-7333; free catalog), also offers medicinal herb seeds,
from Vitex agnus-castus, the chaste tree, to Papaver somniferum,
the poppies that put Dorothy out in ``The Wizard of Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Meadow Farm, in Montague Center, Mass. (413-367-2394;
catalog, $3), is a family-run nursery specializing in unusual
annuals and perennials, like Osteospermum ecklonis Silver Sparkler
(a white African daisy with electric blue centers and blue on the
reverse side of the petals) and seven different baptisias.
</P>
<P>
   Siskiyou Rare Plant Nursery, in Medford, Ore., which specializes
in alpine and rock garden plants, sells everything from bog
rosemary to a hardy daisy from South Africa (541-772-6846; catalog,
$3).
</P>
<P>
   Niche Gardens, in Chapel Hill, N.C. (919-967-0078; catalog, $3),
has unusual plants, from Eupatorium rugosum Chocolate, a native
with creamy white 6-inch flowers on chocolate-colored leaves and
purple stems, to Equisetum scirpoides striatum, a tiny, ancient
horsetail.
</P>
<P>
   Ronniger's, the old seed-potato farm in Moyie Springs, Idaho,
has sold its business to Greg Anthony's Seed Co., in Ellensburg,
Wash. The new company, called Irish Eyes With a Hint of Garlic, is
offering a great collection of organic seed potatoes, as well as
sweet potatoes, cover crops, onions, alliums and garlic, the last
for fall planting (509-925-6025; catalog, $2). Ronniger's now
specializes in heirloom beans (208-267-8218; free catalog).
</P>
<P>
   And if you don't know about J.L. Hudson, you must order ``The
2000 Ethnobotanical Catalog of Seeds,'' for $1, to keep up with
Hudson's views on invasive plants (``the myth of the menace'') and
benefit from his seed collection and encyclopedic knowledge. He
famously has no telephone (``If your phone doesn't ring, it's me,''
he writes), so you must use a pen, if you remember what that is:
J.L. Hudson, Star Route 2, Box 337, La Honda, Calif. 94020.
</P>
<P>
   You may read the catalogs, but don't forget all those seeds in
the ham boiler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
