<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, Jan. 16, and thereafter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-COMPUTER-GAMES (Undated) _ Many viewers today who were raised
on video games and science fiction movies are noticing how much new
television games show sets resemble computer games and special
effects from films like ``Star Wars'' and ``The Matrx'' and
futuristic music videos like TLC's ``No Scrubs.'' By Julia
Chaplin. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TIES-FASHION (Undated) _ For years we've been hearing that the
traditional uniform of male power was over. Casual Fridays gave way
to casual summers to polo-and-chinos year-round at Wall Street
firms like American Express. Cybernerds made it cool to wear ``I'm
With Microsoft, Stupid'' T-shirts to big meetings. But it seems
that reports of the tie's death have been greatly exaggerated. At
the men's wear shows in Milan last week, Prada and Gucci walked
suits and ties down the runway. Dolce &AMP; Gabbana, a house known for
shunning such formality, also knotted ties on its models. Hot
designers are now telling us we really (italics)do(end italics)
want to wear ties. Ideally, very expensive ones. By Rick Marin. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHAFT-FILM-FASHION (Milan, Italy) _ When Giorgio Armani took a
bow on Wednesday, at the end of a show that concluded the fall 2000
men's-wear collections here, he did it with a glimmering bracelet
on his wrist and a star in hand. Armani's show opened with the
theme music from ``Shaft,'' and wrapped up in a joint appearance
with Samuel L. Jackson, who is starring in the remake of the 1971
movie, about a Harlem police officer with few problems getting
women to have sex with him. The designer is doing the costumes. By
Ginia Bellafante. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Seed catalogs are pouring into my
mailbox. There are too many good ones to mention, and the famous
old-timers, like Burpee, Cook's Garden, Johnny's Selected Seeds and
White Flower Farm, can fend for themselves. So I want to give the
best little guys some play, for the sake of biodiversity. By Anne
Raver. WITH PHOTO. &QL;
</P>
