<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV16-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTOR'S EXPECTATIONS ARE TOO HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 16, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 59, single, and have no outstanding debt and no pension.
My current income is $50,000 a year. My assets are $61,000 in CDs,
a $13,000 annuity, $19,000 invested in Vanguard Health Care,
$14,000 in Vanguard Index 500, $11,000 in Vanguard Index Value,
$12,000 in Vanguard Prime Money Market, $24,000 in AARP Growth and
Income, $34,000 in AARP Capital Growth, and $7,000 in checking,
cash, and miscellaneous accounts. In addition, I have these IRA
accounts: $36,000 in Vanguard Windsor II, $21,000 in Vanguard
Wellington, and $42,000 in bank CDs. I would like to retire at 62
with a minimum of $36,000 a year. What can I do? What is realistic?
</P>
<P>
   D.B., Coopersburg, Pa. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think your expectations are too high. With your fairly
conservative portfolio, you can't expect a lot of growth over a
three-year period, and at current levels you would need a yield in
excess of 12.2 percent to deliver a $36,000 annual income stream
without invading principal.
</P>
<P>
   You don't mention whether you will be eligible for Social
Security in a few years, and that could make a lot of difference.
But I don't think you should count on this portfolio to deliver
much more than $20,000 in annual income _ and that may be pushing
it, too.
</P>
<P>
   You also don't say whether you're continuing contributions to
any of these accounts. If there are no further contributions and
you realize average annual returns of 7 percent over the next three
years, you might expect to accumulate a total of $360,168; if you
fully funded your IRAs to the tune of $2,000 a year, the
accumulation would be $366,804.
</P>
<P>
   Given that nearly 46 percent of the portfolio is on the
fixed-income side, you should not realistically count on more than
7 percent returns.
</P>
<P>
   One of the problems with that $20,000 projection is that you
would need to have almost all of your principal _ about $310,000 _
in fixed-income securities to deliver it; this would leave you with
very little principal devoted to growth to protect you against
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you could rebudget to live on $25,000 a year, you would
probably be best off thinking of deferring retirement to a more
traditional age, say 65; at that point, you might project a
$412,356 total accumulation with no further contributions, or
$424,227 if you funded the IRAs but did no further saving.
</P>
<P>
   Of course the most logical approach is to save more than the 4
percent of your annual income that is represented by maximum IRA
contributions. If you could double that, the three-year
accumulation would rise to $373,441, and the five-year figure would
be $436,100.
</P>
<P>
   Another option you might consider, whether you retire at age 62
or 65 or even later, would be to look for a part-time job during
the early years of your retirement.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you could budget yourself to live on $30,000 a
year, retired at age 65, and then earned $12,000 a year for the
first five years of retirement, the picture would be a little
brighter.
</P>
<P>
   If you had $424,227 at age 65 saved and withdrew only $1,500 a
month for the first five years, you would still have have $346,745
at age 70. You could then withdraw $2,500 a month for a little more
than 12 years before depleting the funds. Both of those projections
are based on projected average portfolio returns of 6.5 percent
after retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether a gloomy picture _ but as I said at the outset, if
Social Security is in the cards, things would be much brighter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 50 and my husband is 44. Our combined annual salary is
$118,000. Our long-term financial goals are to retire in 10 years
and to purchase a home and significantly pay down the mortgage by
the time we take early retirement. I estimate we will need $36,000
to $40,000 a year when we retire. I am not sure how much we need to
save to take this early retirement; it would be helpful to know,
because this number affects the amount of the mortgage we can take.
For the home purchase, we have saved $160,000 in CDs and money
market accounts. We also have $30,000 in emergency savings. Our
investments include a $56,000 portfolio of Vanguard stock mutual
funds, to which we add $12,000 a year. I have $333,000 in 403(b)
and Roth IRA accounts, and the contributions plus employer matches
come to $18,2100 a year. My husband has $165,000 in similar
accounts, with total contributions of $10,400 a year, including the
match. We both fully fund our Roth IRAs each year. I estimate that
we will be eligible for $16,000 a year in Social Security benefits
at age 65. Will this savings plan be sufficient to allow us to take
early retirement and save sufficient money as a hedge against
inflation? Should we increase our savings rate and not prepay the
mortgage?
</P>
<P>
   S.F., Brighton, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you keep saving at the aggressive current rate for a
decade, your current $554,000 (not including the down payment and
emergency savings money) would grow to $2,178,819, projecting
average annual portfolio growth of 10 percent. If inflation
averages 3.5 percent, you would need $56,423 in the year 2010 to
buy what $40,000 buys today.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, you would be in the enviable position of relying on less
than half of your savings pool to provide your income stream,
leaving you with well in excess of $1 million as a capital pool
that could be left in growth vehicles to protect you against
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, after five years of retirement, your Social Security
benefits would kick in, further reducing your need to rely on your
retirement portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   As for prepaying the mortgage, if you were to divert the entire
$12,000 a year that is now going into your Vanguard portfolio into
mortgage prepayments, you would still accumulate $1,978,768 over
the course of a decade _ again a pool that would allow you to
maintain a $1 million growth portfolio to deal with inflation.
You're in lovely shape, whatever course you take.
</P>
<P>
   The question whether to prepay the mortgage or to continue
building the retirement portfolio is really a matter of personal
preference. A paid-up home gives you a wonderful sense of security.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the mortgage provides tax advantages, in
direct proportion to the size of the balance, and if you take a
10-year view of your investments, they are likely to produce higher
returns than the level of interest that frugal people with a very
large down payment such as yourself should be able to obtain.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker will answer selected investors' questions in the
Sunday MutualFunds and Monday Money sections. Send letters,
including your name, address, and telephone number, to: Kenneth
Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
