<HEADLINE>
ELLIOT LEE RICHARDSON: POLITICIAN WITH CHARACTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 16, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I wish I could buy the argument that what voters want most in
leaders is ``character.'' I've seen evidence to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   No Massachusetts politician more epitomized character in public
life than Elliot Lee Richardson, the rectitudinous Yankee lost to a
brain hemorrhage on New Year's Eve at age 79. But Richardson, the
record holder for sitting in different Cabinet posts, a Dudley
Do-Right who almost always tried to do the right thing _ whether
marching across Utah Beach in the Normandy Invasion or standing up
against the perfidious Nixon gang over Watergate _ had too much
character for his own party, if not his own good.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents Reagan and Bush cut and ran from the expectation that
this senior and principled Republican should be given an important
government post. Richardson was too hot to handle for the party
that couldn't get over Nixon's crooked legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1984, Richardson lost, and lost badly, in a fight for a
US Senate nomination _ repudiated by Bay State Republicans. Against
the advice of friends, he had insisted on traveling to the 1984 GOP
convention, and challenging the precepts of Reaganism and
brain-dead tax cutting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a disaster,'' said Beacon Hill's Ann Kramer, one of
many Richardson admirers in Washington for the memorial service
held Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were up 27 points in June, then he goes to the national
convention and comes out against the Reagan platform on national
television, and we dropped 20 points in four weeks. It was a
killer. The '84 loss was very traumatic at the time, it really did
change his life. But the politics never won out over his
conscience. I just feel very blessed that I knew the man, not the
myth.''
</P>
<P>
   As a Massachusetts attorney general and lieutenant governor, as
a corruption-busting US attorney and as a sophisticated
undersecretary of state, then as the federal government's secretary
of various departments _ Commerce; Health, Education and Welfare;
Defense; and Justice _ he was one of the brainiest and most
high-minded of bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   But what people say they want in a public servant and what they
choose can be starkly different. In 1973 Richardson quit as Nixon's
attorney general rather than fire Archibald Cox, the special
Watergate prosecutor. Richardson's refusal on principle
precipitated the infamous Saturday Night Massacre that helped bring
Nixon down.
</P>
<P>
   But his quitting also gutted the stellar career to which
Richardson had dedicated himself. His own Republican Party spurned
him. Under eight years of Ronald Reagan, and then four years of
President Bush, Richardson was ostracized from his most cherished
work: public service. ``He told me that all government jobs were
more satisfying than any private-sector job,'' said Michael Deland,
a Bay State Republican now in Washington. ``The height of irony is
that he was sent to Siberia by his own party.''
</P>
<P>
   Deland called him ``a Renaissance man, who could have made a
career as a painter of landscapes or portraits. He had the
intellectual acuity of a real scholar. When Richardson was 33,
Deland said, Felix Frankfurter recommended him to be president of
Harvard. ``He relished risk, loved to fight. He often told me the
highlight of his life was landing on the beach at Normandy.''
</P>
<P>
   Deland, himself in a wheelchair, recalled encountering
Richardson in his own wheelchair downtown. ``With his impish grin,
he challenged me to a wheelchair race up High Street, risking life
and limb, tearing up High Street. He just relished a race.''
</P>
<P>
   To Marty Linsky of Harvard's Kennedy School, Richardson had an
undeserved reputation ``as a cold and distant person,'' belied by
the lively interest he took in colleagues and their families.
``Once when he was campaigning with me at a subway stop on Beacon
Street, he lectured me on how voter contact is all about touching,
and eye contact, but he did it in his intensely cerebral way, so
focused that he didn't hear the subway car coming. It brushed him
and spun him around into a mailbox.'' Linsky called him ``a man of
passion trapped in this WASP body and intellect. He believed in
what he believed in.''
</P>
<P>
   To retired Globe editor Tom Winship, a Richardson buddy for half
a century, ``Elliot had a tremendous wit, honed at Harvard. He got
A's automatically, but his whole life was the Lampoon,'' the
university's famous humor magazine. ``He was quite a painter, and a
terrific birder _ Roger Tory Peterson was one of his teachers at
Milton Academy. He had a huge amount of guts.'' Richardson, twice
wounded, came home from World War II with a Bronze Star. Winship
said he and Richardson went to Namibia as UN election observers
after apartheid was ended.
</P>
<P>
   In Namibia, said Winship, ``He was just a terrific spokesman for
decency and took on all those terrors, the apartheid people.'' The
two attended a soccer match one day. ``We turned out to be the only
two white people there in a sea of about 10,000 blacks,'' said
Winship. ``As we left, we were attacked by two crazed guys who
tried to steal our wallets. I had my money in my shoe. One guy
reached for Elliot's wallet. Elliot swung at the guy; he'd been a
helluva middleweight boxer at Harvard. The guy raked Elliot with a
broken beer bottle, which sent him to the hospital. But it was
typical of Elliot to fight rather than hand over his wallet.''
</P>
<P>
   To UMass President Bill Bulger, who once flashed a mock headline
at Richardson on St. Patrick's Day ``Vote Elliot _ he's better than
you are!'' Richardson had a fine sense of humor. ``He called me
`Muggsy.' When Richardson had to retire his 1984 campaign debt, he
got Bulger and Art Buchwald to host.
</P>
<P>
   It was two Democratic presidents who honored Richardson. Jimmy
Carter gave him the Law of the Sea Treaty, the longest and most
difficult of Richardson's many chores. President Clinton pinned him
with the Medal of Freedom, calling him ``a man of uncommon
integrity . . . (who) put the nation's interests first even when
the personal cost was very high.''
</P>
<P>
   To Harvard's Jonathan Moore, Richardson's reserve limited his
appeal on television, and masked ``this sweetness, this incredible
ability to connect on a spiritual level.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore said Richardson's commitment to public service was inbred.
`` `We all have the defects of our qualities, Jonathan,' he'd say;
it meant that within our strengths lie our limitations.''
</P>
<P>
   Mass. General's Dr. Tom Durant gives this example of the
Richardson clan's Yankee humor: ``After Mass. General merged with
the Brigham, I asked Elliot's brother, George, a doc here for 50
years, what he thought of the merger. He said, `Tom, I was raised
all my life to have three enemies: Russia, the Brigham, and Yale.
Now I have only Yale.' '' What Elliot Richardson's career showed
was that you cannot always choose your enemies, but your friends
choose you, and the people closest to him thought highly of him _
no doubt on that score.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
