<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDI S4 QUATTRO IS HIGH-PERFORMANCE VERSION OF AUDI'S A4 COMPACT
SEDAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G, CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is one of my favorites, no question.
</P>
<P>
   It's the all-new Audi S4 Quattro, a high-performance version of
Audi's entry-level A4 compact sedan.
</P>
<P>
   The S4 isn't for everyone; it's a bit pricey at $37,900 (plus
transportation and options), quite a bit higher than the price of
the base A4 1.8T, which lists for just $23,990.
</P>
<P>
   So what makes the S4 worth $14,000 more? After all, you could
buy the A4 1.8T and add a nice Honda Civic or Toyota Corolla for
the extra 14 grand, and have two cars instead of one.
</P>
<P>
   But as nice as the A4 is, it doesn't come close to the fun of
the S4, which is a virtual rocket on wheels _ not just with power,
but also with the precise control needed to make the driver feel
secure with all of that power.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a vehicle such as the Dodge Viper, full of raw muscular
power but short on precision roadhandling, the S4 does an
outstanding job of combining the two into a package that is equally
at home on the track as on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   The S4 is a wolf in sheep's clothing. On the exterior, it looks
almost like an A4, and there is nothing that tips nearby drivers to
its true nature: a street-legal race car that can carry four adults
in relative style and comfort.
</P>
<P>
   One of the keys to the S4's outstanding performance lies under
the hood. It's the 2.7-liter, 30-valve, twin-turbo V-6 engine,
rating at 250 horsepower and 258 foot-pounds of torque. With a curb
weight of less than 3,600 pounds, that's a lot of go-power. Turbo
lag is virtually eliminated by using two small turbochargers, one
on each side of the V-6.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with the standard six-speed manual transmission, the
turbo V-6 pushes this car from zero to 60 mph in 5.9 seconds. Top
speed is electronically limited to 143 mph for the U.S. market.
Without the governor, this car would go a whole lot faster, I'm
sure. A five-speed automatic with the Porsche Tiptronic clutchless
manual shifting feature is optional at no extra cost. You can let
it shift for you, or do it yourself
</P>
<P>
   Some of the superb handling comes from patented Audi Quattro
full-time all-wheel-drive system, which eliminates the torque-steer
problems associated with front-drive cars such as the base A4. The
S4's Quattro system comes with Audi's new electronic differential
locking, which works with both front and rear differentials to
virtually eliminate wheel spin. With this system, the S4 can get
moving if only one of the four wheels has at least some traction.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't one of those modern disabling traction-control
systems that reduces engine speed or applies a brake to a spinning
wheel to control the spin; instead, this is a true enabling system
that reads pavement conditions and applies power automatically to
the wheels that have traction.
</P>
<P>
   The Quattro system is available on all Audi models sold in the
U.S., but it is standard on the S4. I wouldn't want all of that
power without it, either.
</P>
<P>
   Steering is amazingly precise, and there is plenty of torque
throughout the low- and mid- power range (that 258 foot-pounds is
available from 1,800 to 3,800 rpm). The wide tires riding on
17-inch Avus alloy wheels manage to grip the road firmly.
</P>
<P>
   Driving is believing: Once you're behind the wheel of the S4,
putting it through a series of tight turns while adding more and
more power, it's easy to forget you're driving a sedan.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is a sedan, and quite a nice one at that. The rear
seat is a bit tight for adults, especially on long trips, but it's
great for local trips, and can hold up to three kids. Up front, the
driver and passenger are in the lap of luxury in the pearl nappa
leather bucket seats.
</P>
<P>
   Leather interior is standard throughout the car, including the
armrests, steering wheel, shift knob and door-panel inserts. There
is gray-stained bird's-eye maple wood trim, too.
</P>
<P>
   Other interior features include automatic climate control,
10-way power sport seats up front (including electric lumbar
adjustment and lockable head restraints), and a three-spoke
steering wheel.
</P>
<P>
   An 80-watt AM/FM/cassette/compact-disc stereo with eight
speakers is standard, but our test car came with the optional Bose
premium audio system ($650) and trunk-mounted CD changer ($550).
</P>
<P>
   Front and side air bags are standard. The side air bags are
large enough to protect the front and rear passengers from hitting
the windows or side pillars in a side impact. Unlike the front air
bags, which stay inflated for only a fraction of a second, the side
bags stay full for five seconds to protect the occupants in the
event of a rollover.
</P>
<P>
   Other standard features include a driver information display
with a six-function trip computer, power windows and door locks,
cruise control, power outside mirrors with defogger, 60/40
split-folding rear seat, full-size spare tire with matching allow
wheel, and both front and rear fog lights. There are disc brakes
all around, and the antilock system is standard. Rack-and-pinion
power steering is included, too.
</P>
<P>
   Our test car came with two options packages. The convenience
package ($1,200) added a power sunroof, built-in universal
garage-door opener, and auto-dimming inside and outside mirrors.
The cold-weather package ($575) tacked on heated front seats and an
expandable ski storage sack. The only other option on our vehicle
was the integrated hands-free mobile phone ($495), which I never
noticed during my weeklong test drive. I'm not sure where it was.
</P>
<P>
   Total sticker for our vehicle was $41,895, including $525
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   My only real gripe (other than the tight back seat and the high
price) was the absolutely awful ``imola yellow'' exterior paint.
Just about everyone I know who saw me driving this car felt obliged
to comment first about how ugly the color was. I call it either
``New York taxicab yellow'' or ``French's mustard yellow.'' Ugh!!!
</P>
<P>
   It does come in other colors, thank goodness.
</P>
<P>
   The yellow is one of only two colors that are unique to the S4
model, however; the other is ``Nogaro blue pearl effect.'' (Who
thinks up these silly names for car colors, anyway?) The other
colors offered are available on all A4 models.
</P>
<P>
   The trunk is big enough for a lot of stuff: It measures 13.7
cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   All of that power does eat up some gas. EPA fuel-economy ratings
are 17 miles per gallon in the city and 24 mpg on the highway.
Unleaded premium fuel is recommended, and the tank holds 16.4
gallons.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   AT a GLANCE: 2000 Audi S4 sedan
</P>
<P>
   THE PACKAGE: Compact, five-passenger, all-wheel-drive,
twin-turbo, V-6 powered, four-door premium performance sedan.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLIGHTS: New for 2000, this is a souped-up version of Audi's
entry-level A4 sedan, but at a premium price. It offers pure
driving enjoyment with lots of power and extraordinary
roadhandling.
</P>
<P>
   NEGATIVES: A bit pricey; back seat a bit tight for adults; truly
yucky yellow color on our test car.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR COMPETITORS: BMW 328i, Lexus GS 300, Infiniti I30t,
Mercedes-Benz C280/C43, Saab 9-3 Viggen.
</P>
<P>
   EPA FUEL ECONOMY: 17 mpg city/24 highway.
</P>
<P>
   BASE PRICE: $37,900 plus $525 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   AS TESTED: $41,895 (including transportation).
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD RATING: A-plus (what a ride!).
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III is the Star-Telegram's transportation
writer and automotive columnist. Contact him at 3201 Airport
Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford, TX 76021- 6000; telephone (817)
685-3810; e-mail chambers(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 1700EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
