<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A BOWL GAME WHERE THE WINNERS AREN'T ON THE FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN SHEA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _ Quick question: Who won last year's Shrine
Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   Quick answer: Who really cares?
</P>
<P>
   We do know who didn't win. It wasn't the North or the South.
</P>
<P>
   Or the Blue or the Gray.
</P>
<P>
   Or the Shirts or the Skins.
</P>
<P>
   That one team actually wins and another loses is among the more
insignificant factors of the Shrine Bowl, which isn't about winning
or losing as much as it's about exposure for kids trying to reach
the next level.
</P>
<P>
   College kids trying to live the NFL life.
</P>
<P>
   And hospitalized kids trying to live a normal life.
</P>
<P>
   The 75th Shrine Bowl, Saturday at Stanford Stadium, is expected
to generate nearly $250,000 for the 22 Shriners Hospitals, which
rely solely on donations and fund-raisers for operations.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, last year's winner was the East by a 20-10 score
over the West. Remember?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the few all-star games where the players and
coaches are not paid,'' said Florida's Steve Spurrier, the head
coach of this year's East squad. ``We do it because it's a good
cause. Nowadays, unfortunately, society is such that a lot of
people don't look at it that way. They say, `What's in it for
me?'''
</P>
<P>
   That may explain the no-shows. For various and obvious reasons,
not all of college's elite players will suit up on Saturday _
nobody from Florida State, the national champion that showcased
Peter Warrick. And nobody from runner-up
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech after center Keith Short (injury) and kicker Shane
Graham (family conflict) bailed out.
</P>
<P>
   Also absent is Heisman Trophy winner Ron Dayne of Wisconsin.
Dayne is reportedly playing in next week's Hula Bowl, where the
Badgers' Barry Alvarez will be coaching.
</P>
<P>
   Other players chose different all-star games that guarantee a
paycheck. Others listened to their agents and stayed home to avoid
possible injuries. And, of course, others were ineligible because
they're not seniors.
</P>
<P>
   But the Shrine organizers maintain there's no lack of talent
this year and point to the hundreds of NFL officials swarming the
sidelines for every Shrine practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 goal for the Shrine Bowl is to provide publicity for
Shriners Hospitals,'' said game coordinator Jeff Foster, ``and the
talented players we have here this week _ and the last 74 years _
have provided a vehicle for us to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second goal is to provide these players an opportunity to
show their talents.''
</P>
</TEXT>
