<HEADER>
A6302 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-TIES-FASHION-$ADV16-N     01-14 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIES-FASHION-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENTS: IT'S TIME TO TIE ONE ON AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 16)  
(lh) 
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tie or no tie?
</P>
<P>
   Tie, if you are the head of a new-media company trying to look
grown-up enough to merge with one of the world's biggest old-media
companies.
</P>
<P>
   No tie, if you are the head of that old-media company trying to
look like you can swing with the new.
</P>
<P>
   It did not go unnoticed, to say the least, that at the press
conference last week announcing the proposed marriage of America
Online and Time Warner, Steve Case, 41, of AOL put on a tie and
Gerald Levin, 60, of Time Warner took his off. Maybe they should
have e-mailed each other that morning. Maybe they did, and the
whole thing was a public relations ploy. But that is unlikely,
since one man looked so much more powerful than the other. It was
clear who was buying whom.
</P>
<P>
   For years, we have been hearing that the traditional uniform of
male power was over. Casual Fridays gave way to casual summers to
polo-and-chinos year-round at Wall Street firms like American
Express. Cybernerds made it cool to wear ``I'm With Microsoft,
Stupid'' T-shirts to big meetings.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems that reports of the tie's death have been greatly
exaggerated. At the men's wear shows in Milan, Italy, last week,
Prada and Gucci walked suits and ties down the runway. Dolce &AMP;
Gabbana, a house known for shunning such formality, also knotted
ties on its models. Hot designers are now telling us we really do
want to wear ties. Ideally, very expensive ones.
</P>
<P>
   So what's an aspiringly hip guy to do? Start wearing them to the
office on Fridays, at the risk of being asked repeatedly if he has
a job interview? When he goes out at night to tie one on, should he
tie one on?
</P>
<P>
   Say, for instance, a young Silicon Alley entrepreneur wanted to
spend some of his IPO loot at a four-star French restaurant. Le
Cirque 2000 still calls for a jacket and tie. But at Le Bernardin,
ties are optional, the new dress code meaning, ``We'd rather you
wore a tie, but if you're rich enough to pay $250 for a Burgundy,
please step right this way, sir.'' Even La Cote Basque gave up the
good fight a year ago, because, said Jean-Paul Zaremba, the
manager, ``We were running out of ties to give people.''
</P>
<P>
   Ties peaked in the early 1990s. Gerald Anderson, executive
director of the Neckwear Association of America, said that sales
swelled during the '80s power-tie era, then crescendoed with the
creative-executive look that called for novelties like the Jerry
Garcia tie: Dead from the neck down.
</P>
<P>
   The total number of ties sold is down since then, from about 117
million in 1994 to 105 million in 1998, Anderson said. But in
dollar terms, sales are up, from about $1.5 billion to $1.6
billion. Fewer men are buying ties, but they're buying more
expensive ones. ``The people who bought $15 to $20 ties went
casual,'' Anderson said. Maybe so, but the average price of a tie
has risen from $13.16 to $15.16 _ news that may shock shoppers
whose idea of a cheap tie is $80 at a Barneys New York half-price
sale.
</P>
<P>
   Did Levin blow his big media moment by not wearing one? ``Of
course I would say he did,'' Anderson said. ``Because there was
Case looking like a million bucks. More than that, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Calacanis, the editor and chief executive of The Silicon
Alley Reporter, which covers the new media industry in New York,
put the contrast between the younger Case and the elder Levin more
bluntly: ``Retired people don't need to wear ties.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early '90s, slackers shunned ties because they hated the
``Dilbert'' jobs that required them. But now that some of those
slackers have become titans of industry, ties have become what they
always were _ symbols of corporate success. ``The age of showing up
for meetings on Rollerblades is long over,'' Calacanis, 29, said.
``The funkiness was good because it said we're not afraid to do
something different. But dressing up now is also courageous because
it says we're not afraid to make this into a business.''
</P>
<P>
   It's about ``wearing a uniform,'' said Allen Questrom, chairman
of Barneys. Questrom is a staunch tie man and has a running joke
with Patrick McCarthy, the editorial director of W and Women's Wear
Daily, who never wears one. ``Patrick happens to be a very
attractive guy, and I think his appearance would benefit greatly
from putting on a tie,'' said Questrom, who does not believe in
casual Fridays. When his employees go tieless, he said, ``I can
literally see people's attitude toward work change.''
</P>
<P>
   For Calacanis' generation, dressing up rather than down might
have started up again with the whole ``Swingers'' cocktail-culture
movement of the late '90s. You can't wear a sharkskin suit without
a tie.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who dined last summer at Colina, the short-lived
restaurant in ABC Carpet &AMP; Home, could hardly have failed to notice
the sommelier's prominent neckwear. One evening, this hipster wine
guy was asking customers what they thought of his tie. The knot was
the size of a ham hock. It looked like something Ted Baxter would
have worn. Anyway, he was polling diners to settle a bet about
whether a fat tie looked phat or not. Apparently he spent hours
every morning tying the thing. The knot was so precarious that one
clumsy tug would collapse it. But to him, the effect was worth the
extra effort.
</P>
<P>
   DNR, the men's wear trade daily, says skinny ties are next. But
judging from the mostly moderate widths on display in Milan this
week, it may be a while before men feel ready to revive the New
Romantics look and start dangling bacon strips of red leather
around their necks again.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Steve Case starts wearing one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 1718EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6305 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-14 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET EVERY BENEFIT YOU ARE ENTITLED TO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SHANNON BUGGS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I accepted my first full-time reporting job, I negotiated
my salary, relocation allowance and vacation time. However, I
didn't ask one question about the 401(k) program or the pension
plan included in my benefits package.
</P>
<P>
   I figured I'd be moving on in two years or less and wouldn't get
vested in either plan. It never dawned on me that such job-hopping
meant I had to start planning for retirement as soon as I started
working.
</P>
<P>
   If I didn't, ``retiree'' might never be a word I could use to
describe myself.
</P>
<P>
   Changing jobs just to get a higher salary is a great short-term
strategy that can hurt you in the long run. Job hoppers have to
make sure each jump gets them closer to their retirement goals.
</P>
<P>
   _ Negotiate, negotiate, negotiate. Before accepting a job,
determine the dollar value of every benefit being offered. Each
perk _ or the lack of it _ affects your compensation bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a $20,000 raise might make anyone jump ship.
However, if the new company has a lower 401(k) match, a health
insurance plan that requires more out-of-pocket fees, a lower
mileage reimbursement rate, fewer stock options and no pension
plan, then that raise actually could be a $5,000 reduction in pay.
</P>
<P>
   If the new job doesn't pay you what you're making at your
current position, you've got two options: Turn it down or push for
more.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Schefft, director of corporate financial planning in KPMG's
Houston office, often counsels his executive clients to request
stock options that vest immediately. If that's not possible, he
tells them to ask the new employer for a loan to buy company stock,
with the loan being forgiven over a period of time.
</P>
<P>
   He also suggests they ask for immediate participation in the
health insurance plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Join the 401(k) program. Even if the time you spend in a job
is best measured in weeks, you need to store money in a 401(k) plan
as soon as you're eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, employees must work three to five years before they
vest or can keep the money the company adds to their 401(k)
accounts. So, if you're not going to be around long enough to vest,
you need to make up for that lost company match.
</P>
<P>
   You can do that by contributing the maximum pretax amount
allowed by federal law. This year it's $10,500.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've done that, you also can contribute the maximum
after-tax amount, if your company allows that. This is especially
important for people making more than $85,000 a year, who are
deemed ``highly compensated'' by the IRS and, therefore, may not be
allowed to contribute the maximum pretax.
</P>
<P>
   _ Leave the money where it is. Moving to a new job often means
waiting a year before you can participate in your new company's
401(k). Since rolling your money into your new employer's plan
isn't an immediate option, leave it in your former employer's plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way, you don't have to worry about management fees or IRA
set-up fees,'' Schefft says. ``Your old company takes care of all
the management fees for you until you can roll it into your new
401(k) plan and your new company starts taking care of them.''
</P>
<P>
   If the amount you have saved is less than $5,000, your former
employer may insist on cashing you out of its plan.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you are in the most dire circumstances, don't take a lump
sum payment. The tax consequences _ a mandatory 20 percent withheld
for federal taxes and 10 percent excise tax, if you are under age
59 1/2 _ are too severe. It's better to roll it into an Individual
Retirement Account, even if you have to pay management fees.
</P>
<P>
   _ Invest on your own. If fat bonuses are a part of the package
you get whenever you jump to a new job, don't blow them on
Brazilian vacations or down payments on sports cars.
</P>
<P>
   Invest in mutual funds. As you make more money, diversify your
portfolio by buying stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Do the same thing with any raises you receive. Take half of the
raise and invest it and use the other half to reward yourself for a
job well-done.
</P>
<P>
   _ Know before you go. Don't turn in your letter of resignation
until you fully understand your company's vesting policies.
Quitting a week before you're eligible to get 100 percent of the
pension the company has set aside for you is not a smart move. You
could wind up with nothing or much less than you would have
received.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than saying goodbye to my first paper in two years, I
accepted a promotion after 14 months. I wound up working for that
paper five years, two weeks and one day. Just long enough to vest
in the pension plan and get an extra month of health insurance
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   I figured it didn't make sense to leave any money on the table.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Shannon Buggs invites comments and column ideas, but cannot offer
specific financial advice about individual situations. E-mail her
at shannon.buggs(at)chron.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
