A6307 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-14 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AOL MUST SPURN AD-BLITZ TEMPTATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know the 21st century has arrived when America Online and
Time Warner get together for a megabucks corporate dance, and AOL
takes the lead.
</P>
<P>
   The astonishing thing about the deal is that an Internet company
came out on top. Who would have thought that Time Warner, a merger
of the largest Old Media companies in the world, would be bought by
a relative newcomer.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this is not just any newcomer, but the one that has
done more to get ordinary people online than any other technology
company. AOL understands better than anyone what it takes to bring
the Internet revolution down to the grass roots.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is not to make it feel like a revolution, which
implies that a lot of hard work must be done. Instead, AOL has
presented the online world like a giant party, and one where
everyone with a computer and a modem is welcome _ if you've got
$21.95 a month to spend, that is.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, this galls a lot of people who seem to think
that easy computing is not real computing. The whole idea that
someone might need some hand-holding and an attractive, simplified
interface to get around online is repugnant to them _ and that's an
elitist, arrogant attitude.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CASE'S VISION LIKE GATES' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's nothing new to AOL, or its chairman and founder, Steve
Case, who's been swimming upstream ever since he started the
company in 1985. But now it has become clear that Case's vision is
as important to the growth of a connected planet as Bill Gates'
original vision for Microsoft, which was a computer on every desk
and in every home.
</P>
<P>
   Case, in fact, understands better than anyone the implications
of Metcalfe's Law. This axiom, coined by Ethernet inventor Robert
Metcalfe, holds that the power of the network increases
exponentially by the number of computers connected to it.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, when more people link up, more information and
services are available, and the network to which they're connected
becomes more useful.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is the grand example of this. It is a far more
useful network than it was in its earliest days because there are
more people and businesses using it. But you don't need the vast
expanse of the Internet to see what Steve Case sees. You can ``get
it'' on a much more personal level.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the first person in your family to get connected to the
Internet? He or she likely told other members of your family and
friends how cool it was. That inspired others to get on. And once
your personal circle hit critical mass, the Net suddenly became an
important way for you to stay in touch with the ones you love. Your
personal network became more important as more people you knew
hopped on.
</P>
<P>
   Case understood from the beginning that computers are just too
hard for most people to use, but too important for them not to.
AOL's mantra has been to make its software easy to use, even if
that means leaving out features that some users would like to have.
The company has mastered the art of keeping it simple, stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream home computer users don't care about the geek-level
details about PCs beloved by many of AOL's critics. Spend some time
browsing the member profiles in AOL and you'll notice that, under
the category ``Computer,'' many AOL subscribers type something
like, ``Who cares?!?!?'' For them, a PC is a tool, a means to an
end, and not the end itself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AOL ARROGANCE SURFACING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this is not to say that AOL is perfect. The company
has stumbled more than once, and is beginning to show the signs of
arrogance endemic to a bloated organization. For example, its
recent insistence on forcing people to once again set their
marketing preferences to avoid pop-up ads and internal spam was
reprehensible. You should only have to say no to that kind of junk
once.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, AOL sometimes comes dangerously close to allowing its
marketing to overwhelm the vision of a simple, pleasant online
experience. With its pop-up ads and windows increasingly cluttered
with advertising, it's getting harder to tell the real information
from the come-ons. This blurring of the line between marketing and
useful information has always been a hazard online, but AOL has
made an irritating art of it.
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies a danger inherent in AOL's acquisition of Time
Warner. If the marketing of this behemoth becomes more important
than the product itself, then the combined entity of AOL Time
Warner runs a serious risk of alienating its customers. Just
because the masses want an online experience that's simple and easy
to use, doesn't mean they want to face a constant barrage of
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   If AOL becomes little more than a vehicle for pushing Time
Warner's brands and products, then Case &AMP; Co. will have killed the
goose that laid this golden, $162 billion egg.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
