<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Jan. 15, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Very cold air will cover much of Canada as unseasonably mild air
prevails in most of the Southwest and southern Plains. The large
temperature difference will provide energy for a fast west-to-east
jet stream that will direct moisture-starved disturbances across
the northern United States and southern Canada. Meanwhile, a plume
of Pacific moisture will bring damp weather from central California
to coastal Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning will dawn with an arctic chill in the
Northeast, but temperatures will gradually moderate, especially
west of the Appalachians. Sunshine will mix with some high clouds
near the coast, while mostly cloudy skies develop near the Great
Lakes as milder air is forced to rise over the cold air that is in
place over the region. Intermittent snow will develop near the
eastern shores of the Great Lakes where winds from the southwest
gather moisture over the water.
</P>
<P>
   A broken band of light snow will fall to the north of the track
of a low as it moves from the northern Plains to the northern Great
Lakes. South of the low, mild breezes will prevail from the Plains
to the southern Great Lakes. Afternoon temperatures will be 20 to
30 degrees above seasonal values in most of the central and
southern Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Rain will become heavier later on Saturday from southern Oregon
to central California. More than a foot of snow will accumulate by
early Sunday at elevations above 6,500 feet, although snow levels
will rise overnight. Lighter valley showers and mountain snow will
spread toward the central Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Arctic Sea Smoke
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the ocean east of New England looked like a giant cup
of hot tea as wisps of steam danced near the surface of the water.
The phenomenon, known as arctic sea smoke, forms when water vapor
is added to air that is much colder than the vapor's source. Vapor,
which is water in its gaseous form, is invisible. The vapor rising
above the mild waters mixed with air with temperatures in the
teens. The cold air quickly became saturated producing the visible
sea smoke. About 30 feet higher, the fog particles evaporated
creating the appearance of a steaming hot beverage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
