<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAFT-FILM-FASHION-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FALL, DO MEN JUST WANT TO HAVE FUN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 16)  
 (af)  
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ When Giorgio Armani took a bow on Wednesday, at
the end of a show concluding the Milan men's-wear collections for
fall, he did it with a glimmering bracelet on his wrist and a star
in hand. The show opened with the theme from ``Shaft,'' and wrapped
up in a joint appearance with Samuel L. Jackson, who is starring in
the remake of the 1971 movie. The designer is doing the costumes.
</P>
<P>
   This was a message delivered with considerably more oomph than
whatever it was that Armani was saying with the clothes he sent
down the runway. The show amounted to a hodgepodge of references _
to utility fashion, Las Vegas in the 1970s, hip-hop and old Armani
_ and an overall vision of not much at all.
</P>
<P>
   Preceded by a ``Shaft'' party on Tuesday night that Armani gave
with Vibe magazine, the whole show felt as though it were taking
place to promote a movie and to advance the idea that Armani really
does have something to say to the kids.
</P>
<P>
   A few nights earlier, Armani had run into the traditionalist
Nino Cerruti, a former boss of his, for the first time in 28 years.
Cerruti, who presented his collection last Sunday, happens to be
doing the clothes for the coming movie ``American Psycho,'' based
on the infamous novel about a status-crazed serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   Young fashion editors whine that Cerruti's clothes are boring
and irrelevant, but at least when his show ended, he didn't trot
out with the novel's author, Bret Easton Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   The point of a men's show is tricky to begin with. It's supposed
to be attention-getting, fantastical even; as with women's
collections, most of the clothes retailers buy are never paraded on
the runway in the first place. But the range of outlandish things
one can do with pants, a jacket and a shirt is pretty narrow, so
most of what's on view seems even more contrived than what appears
on the women's runways.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is worsened when designers try to justify the affair
with pronouncements about what men want, generally as well grounded
in reality as an episode of ``Gilligan's Island.''
</P>
<P>
   For fall it seems that what men want, according to those who
make clothes for them, is evening wear. The look was played up in
the clothes of Jean Paul Gaultier and the label Richard Edwards.
Stefano Gabbana, who with Domenico Dolce turned out a surprisingly
salable collection within the context of their outrageousness,
explained that just as women want to change out of work wear to go
out, a man wants a different outfit for going to dinner and ``to
the discotheque'' than for the office.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise at Costume National Homme, Ennio Capasa, who turned out
velvet and shiny silk and things most men who aren't Pet Shop Boys
would never approach, declared knowledgeably that men want
something special to go out in.
</P>
<P>
   John Bartlett, who held his show in Florence, said his
collection was based on the idea of the night. Certainly the sheer
silk-pleated shirt that was part of an Imperialist Russia theme in
his collection was nothing to go trading commodities in.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett, to his credit, didn't just throw glitter on pants and
call it design. He created a full-length military coat, jodhpurs
and other pieces beautiful to look at, if useless outside an ``Anna
Karenina'' production.
</P>
<P>
   To return to common sense, as usual, one sought refuge in Calvin
Klein and Jil Sander. Klein worked almost entirely in black, and
his short-cropped suits and pants were youthful and practical
without seeming gimmicky. When Ms. Sander was asked whether she
thought men wanted to go home after a grueling day and put on
something sexy, she said simply, ``No, I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   She turned out lots of light gray flannel and perfect-looking
neat suits and sweaters. Ms. Sander is a skilled reader of modern
living.
</P>
<P>
   She is apparently a good teacher, too. Roberto Menichetti, who
used to work for Ms. Sander and is now designing at Burberry, drew
raves from the mostly male fashion editors who attended his show.
And from the women, too.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes were well made and colorful without seeming
clownlike. Best of all, they came without pretensions of being
anything other than sporty.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the Gucci show a couple of days later, one female editor
said of what she'd just seen: ``I loved it as fantasy. If a guy
turned up in my door in any of it, I'd shoot him.''
</P>
<P>
   If a guy turned up in Burberry, he'd probably get a second
date. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
