<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERFAITH RETREAT FORGES FRIENDSHIPS, RESPECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes it amazes me how vastly different religions and
denominations can peacefully exist side-by-side in our nation. But
it happens.
</P>
<P>
   A good example of that came last week in the Texas Hill Country,
when 50 students from Jewish, Baptist, Catholic, Episcopal,
Presbyterian, Quaker and Methodist graduate theology schools came
together for a three-day retreat.
</P>
<P>
   They clashed at times, debated about sin and suffering, but came
away as friends.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are David Cantor, who is studying to be a rabbi at
the University of Judaism in Bellaire, Calif., and Greg Tomlin, a
doctoral student at Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary in
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Cantor, 28, and Tomlin, 29, became stellar friends during the
retreat, which has been sponsored for 11 years by the Fort Worth
chapter of the National Conference for Community and Justice,
formerly the National Conference of Christians and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hot topics that came up in small groups was the
insistence by evangelical Christians that Jesus is the only way to
salvation, said Tomlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Jewish seminarian thought I was saying Judaism was
useless, but I certainly wasn't saying that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was not a topic at the retreat, Cantor and Tomlin,
who roomed together, had several late-night discussions about a
Baptist effort to evangelize Jews, Muslims, Hindus and others,
including sending out prayer guides on the holy days of those
faiths.
</P>
<P>
   They also talked about tensions over a Baptist evangelism blitz
planned this summer in Chicago. Several religious leaders urged
Baptists to cancel, but they refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everyone was like my friend David Cantor, we would not have
any problems,'' said Tomlin. ``He understands we are witnessing to
people out of our love for them. We became friends. And it's a
friendship I want to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Cantor said he realizes that Baptists and many other Christians
believe they are commanded by God to share their faith, although he
disagreed with some of the Baptists' methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Jews are governed by God's Commandments, too. So I
understand and respect that,'' said Cantor. ``They can witness to
me, but I'll just say, `Thank you very much,' and go on my way.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``To me, it's like walking on a mountain path. If
a person believed there was a blind drop-off up ahead, they would
be morally obligated to tell me about it. But since I don't believe
there is this blind drop-off, I just keep walking.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Ralph Mecklenburger, one of the faculty members, said the
retreat was a excellent chance for seminarians to learn about other
faiths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody would deny that we have differences,'' he said. ``But
it is good to find that we have a great deal in common, too. In an
overwhelmingly secular society, people of faith are natural allies,
not opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   Having interfaith retreats is even more important in a day when
tensions arise among faiths, said Mecklenburger, rabbi of
Congregation Beth-El in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if those national Jewish leaders and Southern Baptists
would sit down face-to-face with one another and discuss their
problems, rather than trading press releases, they would do a lot
better,'' Mecklenburger said.
</P>
<P>
   Seminarians attended Jewish and Christian worship services and
held discussions on how different faiths view suffering. The event
was held in the tranquil setting of Laity Lodge in Leakey, and had
Jewish and Christian faculty.
</P>
<P>
   Students also came from Assumption (Catholic) Seminary in San
Antonio, Texas Christian University's Brite Divinity School in Fort
Worth, Episcopal Seminary of the Southwest in Austin, Baylor
University's Truett Theological Seminary, Austin Presbyterian
Theological Seminary, Houston Graduate School of Theology and
Southern Methodist University's Perkins School of Theology in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Stan Hagadone, director of admissions at Brite Divinity
School, said those in the many Christian traditions also found
themselves in disagreement during the seminar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like Christians on one side and Jews on the other,''
he said. ``We all learned more about each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi B. Allison Bergman, assistant rabbi of Temple Beth-El in
San Antonio, said the retreat broke down stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have meals together and take strolls together in
absolutely fabulous country, you begin to put a face on the people
of different religions and different cultures,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Trantham, retreat coordinator and executive director of
the Fort Worth branch of the National Conference for Community and
Justice, said she watched the seminary students change day-by-day.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what so fascinating about this,'' Trantham said. ``At
first they don't realize other people feel as strongly about their
faiths as they do about theirs. When they see that, respect
develops. When you have respect, it goes far beyond mere tolerance.
And it doesn't go away.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
