<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6313 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-PRINCE-PRINCEVILLE15-     01-14 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINCE-PRINCEVILLE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Musician donates $37,000 to N.C. town because of `Prince' in
name
 &HT;    By Viola Harris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCEVILLE, N.C. _ The musical artist formerly known as Prince
recently contributed $37,000 to the town of Princeville, just
because of the ``Prince'' association in his own name.
</P>
<P>
   The pop-rock music celebrity responded after reading articles
about the devastation in this flood-ravaged town of 2,100
residents. The floodwaters had swept through in September, after
Hurricane Floyd, and submerged Princeville, the first town in the
nation incorporated by blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Knight, Princeville zoning officer, said the money was
earmarked to purchase building materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although $37,000 will not go very far when you talk about
building supplies, we're very grateful to him for thinking about
us,'' Knight said. ``Even though you can't tell it from his music,
he's a very religious man who wanted no publicity about his gift to
the town.''
</P>
<P>
   Princeville public relations coordinator Kim Burwell said the
musician sent a representative to the town to assess its needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sent a representative from his charitable organization in
Ohio,'' Burwell said. ``We took her over to the distribution center
and gave an overview of some of the town's immediate needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Adams, the musician's representative, spent three days at
the center, talking to workers and residents who came for supplies.
When she returned to Ohio, the artist formerly known as Prince
signed off on the list.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing about the superstar's generosity, Some Princeville
residents said they wish he would come to town and perform a
concert. Knight said other obligations, such as a tour to Europe,
prevented him from doing the concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been cool if he had come to Princeville,''
27-year old Bertha Ransome said. ``I've loved his music for a long
time. He could have raised a lot of money for the town.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rave,'' the latest CD by the artist formerly known as Prince,
is rising steadily on the music charts.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 100 residents have returned to the town since water and
sewer became available. This is far from the 2,100 residents
estimated to have lived in Princeville, incorporated by blacks in
1885 on what's known as Freedom Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Knight said his office would be taking applications from
residents interested in getting some of the money donated by the
musician.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to set some kind of criteria first,'' Knight said.
``As I said, it won't go a long way, so we will definitely have to
take applications. Sheet Rock and other items are costly.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
