<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6315 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-THE-INSIDE-STORY-NYT &LR;      01-14 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-INSIDE-STORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors:
</P>
<P>
   This is a new communique to editors who receive  &UR; The New York
Times News Service &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Part of my role as executive editor of the wire, I think, is to
make some kind of personal contact with the people who read us and
use us. So I am reviving this periodic newsletter. A previous
incarnation, titled ``Listening Post,'' was allowed to die
peacefully a couple of years ago because it had become burdensome
on this end and, perhaps, boring on the other end.
</P>
<P>
   My challenge will be to make ``The Inside Story'' neither.
</P>
<P>
   I intend to produce this missive at least every other week, but
more often if developments warrant. It may be a several grafs, it
may be a couple.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to give editors occasional glimpses under The Times'
tent flap, illuminating who we are, how we think why we do what we
do.
</P>
<P>
   If I provoke comments or questions from you, I invite responses.
My e-mail address is at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   I hope wire editors will pass this along to managing editors,
executive editors, department heads _ anybody who might be
interested.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ON THE WIRE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A new column by  &UR; Paul Krugman &LR;  is now appearing twice a week on
The Times' Op-Ed page. Krugman is the widely known MIT economics
professor known for his theories on international trade and
economics _ and, with his lively writing, known for his ability to
make the dismal science not so. The new column ``Reckonings,'' is
The Times' first regular Op-Ed column devoted to economics,
business and finance. Editorial and op-ed editors will find it on
the wire on Saturdays and Tuesdays slugged BC-KRUGMAN-COLUMN.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN THE FIELD  &LR;  As you may have noticed the past couple of days,
 &UR; Nicholas D. Kristoff &LR;  has left the foreign reporting staff and
joined the national staff, covering the presidential campaign. His
dateline yesterday _ Sloan, Iowa _ is a long way from his last
assignment, Tokyo, where he was bureau chief, or from Beijing,
where he won a Pulitzer Prize in 1990 for coverage of the Tiananmen
Square uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Nick shared that prize, with  &UR; Sheryl WuDunn &LR; , his wife, who is
also undertaking a new job far removed from her former journalistic
posts in Asia. She is going to head a new marketing initiative in
The Times' circulation department aimed at attracting the next
generation of readers. (In addition to her many other credentials,
Sheryl has an MBA from Harvard.)
</P>
<P>
   The new bureau chief in Tokyo is a byline well known to foreign
editors,  &UR; Howard W. French &LR; . In Tokyo with him are  &UR; Calvin Sims &LR; 
and  &UR; Stephanie Strom &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN THE HOUSE  &LR;  Another familiar byline won't be in the news
columns anymore, although the name will be on the masthead.  &UR; Craig
R. Whitney &LR;  has returned to New York to become an assistant
managing editor in overall charge of the night news operation.
Craig has been played leading roles at The Times for many years. In
his 20s he was the Saigon bureau chief. He has also been bureau
chief in Moscow, Bonn, Washington, London and, most recently,
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Also assuming a new title as of the first of the year is
 &UR; Stephen Engelberg &LR; , who becomes senior editor for investigations.
Steve, who guided Pulitzer Prize-winning projects the last two
years, will head a small swat team of reporters, editors and
database experts. They will function not as an elite investigative
fiefdom that competes with beat reporters, but rather will be
available to parachute in on investigations and act as a ``force
multiplier'' for the departments that are conducting the projects.
</P>
<P>
   Later this month (the week of the 17th, to be exact),  &UR; Elvis
Mitchell &LR;  will join The Times' culture staff as a film critic.
Elvis is coming from The Fort Worth Star-Telegram, one of our
partner papers, so his reviews have been available to NYT News
Service clients on this wire. But he is perhaps best known
nationally as the entertainment critic on NPR's ``Weekend
Edition.''
</P>
<P>
   Another new film critic already writing for The Times is  &UR; A.O.
Scott &LR; , formerly the Sunday book critic at Newsday. Tony wrote a
piece a while back on Martin Scorsese for the Web magazine Slate
and it caught the eye of Joe Lelyveld, The Times' executive editor.
Joe began wondering if Tony could transfer his literary expertise
over to films. Early indications seem a resounding yes.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis and Tony will join the veteran  &UR; Stephen Holden &LR;  as The
Times' film criticism team. As you perhaps know,  &UR; Janet Maslin &LR;  has
stepped down from the job of senior film critic. After the
extraordinary run of 22 years of film criticism, with the volume of
movies increasing every year, she decided last fall that it was
time to rest.
</P>
<P>
   For me, and I suspect for you, it is now time to get back to
work.
</P>
<P>
   Laurence M. Paul
</P>
<P>
   lmpaul(at)nytimes.com
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 14, 2000
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Although my letterhead and byline name is Laurence M. Paul,
just about everybody knows me as Lad, a nickname my grandfather
gave me when I was one. I invite you to call me that too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
