<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6317 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MEAT-0115-COX     01-14 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEAT-0115-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    TEXAS MEAT PLANT REMAINS OPEN DESPITE FAILING FOOD SAFETY TESTS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) national categories 
 &HT;    By ELLIOT JASPIN and MIKE COPELAND  
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The federal government's embattled food inspection
program may face a new challenge from a small Texas meat packing
company that continues to sell beef to the public despite failing a
yearlong series of safety tests.
</P>
<P>
   The government could try to close H&AMP; B Packing Co. here, but it
has not.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the U.S. Department of Agriculture says the
agency is not afraid to act, but is likely to allow H&AMP;B to remain
open as it tries to improve.
</P>
<P>
   The H&AMP;B case comes at a critical time for the government.
</P>
<P>
   Last month Supreme Beef Processors Inc. in Dallas failed the
same kind of tests but a federal district court judge there
prevented the Agriculture Department from closing that facility.
Judge A. Joe Fish ruled that the plant can continue to sell its
meat while he decides if the government has the authority to close
the Supreme Beef facility.
</P>
<P>
   Although Supreme Beef and H&AMP;B are both operating under the
government's new science-based inspection program, which is
supposed to make inspections more objective than the old
poke-and-sniff method, the judge's ruling raises questions about
whether federal officials can enforce their new food safety
standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that USDA would be embarrassed to be faced with
another Supreme Beef situation and thus I think they are going to
work extra hard to keep that from happening,'' said Rosemary
Mucklow, executive director of the National Meat Association, which
represents meat packers.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Blake, a spokesperson for the Agriculture Department, said
that while her agency is still mulling its next step, it is likely
the government will allow the plant to remain open while the
company tries to improve sanitation. But she said the Agriculture
Department is not being more lenient with H&AMP;B Packing because the
agency wants to avoid another test of wills with the meat industry.
</P>
<P>
   Blake said that H&AMP;B packing has been very cooperative and has
submitted a formal corrective plan that the government is
reviewing. She said this was in contrast to Supreme, which never
submitted a formal plan.
</P>
<P>
   However, Dennis Johnson, an attorney in Washington who
represents H&AMP;B Packing, said he will go to court ``in a heartbeat''
if the government tries to shut down the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Blake said the government began testing in November 1998 for the
bacteria Salmonella in meat produced by the plant. While federal
rules require that a company can have no more that 7.5 percent of
its samples test positive, Salmonella was found in 22.6 percent of
the H&AMP;B tests done over a four-month period. Thirteen percent of
the samples were positive during the second round of tests that
started in April 1999 and another 12 percent failed during the
third round. The plant was notified on Dec. 15 that it had failed
the third round.
</P>
<P>
   Blake said the public can take comfort from the fact that the
plant's record has improved after each round of tests. Both the
government and the meat industry also advise consumers to
thoroughly cook meat to kill any bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Supreme Beef, the H&AMP;B plant is a small family-owned
business with approximately 80 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're shocked we didn't pass last time,'' Said Benjy Bauer,
the plant manager. ``We want to work within the system and make
things better. We do feel all of our products are safe to eat. We
stand by them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer said improvements have cost ``a pretty good amount of
money,'' but he declined to give a figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truthfully, we don't sell that much hamburger. Let me
emphasize, that was the only item we had a problem with. We're
working together with the USDA on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer said that it sells its product locally and to brokers who
distribute it nationwide. There have been no reported illnesses
from meat coming from the H&AMP;B plant during the testing period.
</P>
<P>
   (Jaspin reported from Washington. Copeland reported from Waco).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
