<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6320 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-RELIGION-MOVIE15-COX     01-14 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-MOVIE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Green Mile' serves up modern gospel
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Every Christian teen-ager in the country
should go to this movie.
</P>
<P>
   Send them to ``The Green Mile,'' a profound 20th-century
allegory of the life of Christ _ and superb entertainment to boot.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood may be a moral wasteland, but, occasionally, Tinsel
Town can do what most churches seldom seem to manage _ proclaim the
gospel in a fresh, compelling way.
</P>
<P>
   Unless churches can find new forms to tell old stories and a new
idiom to weave ancient truth, the third millennium may see
Christianity slip into irreversible decline.
</P>
<P>
   This film does some of their work for them. As a potential Oscar
winner, it should be in movie houses a long time.
</P>
<P>
   The story is about convicts and guards on Death Row in a
Louisiana prison. The floor of the proverbial last mile is a green
linoleum, explaining the film's title.
</P>
<P>
   The mile is a metaphor for life, one filled with warmth and
anger, petulance, pettiness, humor and grace. The movie has an R
rating for an ugly scene in the electric chair and some foul
language, but the story is about good news.
</P>
<P>
   Four guards _ or guardian angels _ ind this particular mile,
care for prisoners awaiting the electric chair and try to keep a
calm atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   A convicted black man, huge beyond imagination, illiterate,
unattractive, and all too human is brought into a cell.
</P>
<P>
   John Coffey, played by Michael Clarke Duncan, is as authentic a
Christ figure as Hollywood has ever produced, and the industry did
a pretty good job with the television version of ``The Fugitive.''
Every episode of that series involved a convicted hero changing
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Coffey is light and life itself, a miracle of a man, afraid of
the dark, but, as in the Gospel of John, the darkness cannot
overcome him. Everyone he meets is changed.
</P>
<P>
   Convicted of the rape and murder of two little girls, he was
arrested embracing their corpses crying into the wilderness that he
had not been able to get it done.
</P>
<P>
   The phrase meant restore them to life, but that is not clear
until the story unfolds. On the mile, he heals a nasty urinary
infection in a guard, played by Tom Hanks, and brings a dead mouse,
a jailhouse pet, back to life as Jesus did Lazarus.
</P>
<P>
   The miracles take place among convicts, foul language and
hideous images of human injustice, the arena in which Jesus served.
This is not an insipid Sunday School film but a profoundly
Christian drama.
</P>
<P>
   Coffey heals the wife of a prison employee from a cancerous
brain tumor by literally inhaling the illness into himself.
</P>
<P>
   He transfers a bit of his life-giving spirit to Hanks, who can
then ``see'' that he is innocent. Still, nothing can be done to
save him. Coffey goes innocently and willingly to his death.
</P>
<P>
   No analogy is perfect. Skeptics will find flaws in Coffey as a
Christ figure, but he and his work vividly recall Isaiah's
suffering servant, who has long been considered an example of the
life of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was despised and rejected by others, a man of suffering.
... Surely he has borne our infirmities and carried our diseases.
... He was wounded for our transgressions and crushed for our
iniquities. ... `` (Isa. 53)
</P>
<P>
   That is a portrait of Christ _ and Coffey.
</P>
<P>
   Youth groups would do well to skip Sunday School to see the
Gospel honestly presented in this modern guise.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
