<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 UPDATE &HT;    UPDATE
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, Jan. 15,
2000.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PILOTS _WASHINGTON _ The White House unveils an
agreement that guarantees protection for airline pilots and
mechanics against punishment for reporting problems to the Federal
Aviation Administration. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   MEAT _ WACO, Texas - Although the H&AMP;B meat packing plant here
has failed three consecutive sets of Salmonella tests, the U.S.
Department of Agriculture is allowing the plant to continue selling
meat to the public while federal officials decide what to do next.
It is unclear whether the USDA can enforce its new food-safety
regulations after a federal judge prevented the closure of a Dallas
meat-packing plant last month for the same kind of violation of the
government's new science-based inspection program. (Jaspin, Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   US-MIDEAST-$ADV17 _ WASHINGTON _ Momentum builds this week on
President Clinton's crusade to broker a comprehensive Mideast peace
accord before leaving
</P>
<P>
   office in a year. Clinton will host Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk Sharaa for a second round
of negotiations beginning Wednesday; the next day Palestinian
Authority President Yasser Arafat comes to town, amid talk of a
Barak-Arafat peace summit under White House auspices in the weeks
ahead. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving Fri., Jan. 14, in both International/Washington
categories.
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-REFUGEES _ MIAMI _ Six-year-old Cuban rafter Elian
Gonzalez wasn't the only dramatic, heart-rending immigration story
in Miami this week. Miami Haitians held their own marches and
emotional demonstrations over the fate of a pregnant Haitian woman
separated from her children when a rickety boat carrying 400
Haitians was stopped off the Florida coast on New Year's Day.
Haitians were happy Thursday when immigration officials said they
will allow the woman's two children to join her in Miami while she
awaits an asylum hearing, but still blast the agency for what they
say is its discriminatory policy. (Williams, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   PRINCE-PRINCEVILLE _ PRINCEVILLE, N.C. _ The artist formerly
known as Prince recently contributed $37,000 to the flood-ravaged
town of Princeville, just because of the association ``Prince'' to
his own name. (Harris, Rocky Mount Telegram)
</P>
<P>
   SHACKLEFORD-HORSES _ SHACKLEFORD BANKS, N.C. _ Wildlife
officials began a roundup this week of the wild horses of
Shackleford Banks _ a hardy breed that has become a beloved feature
of the remote North Carolina island. The horses, which will be
checked over for disease, soon will be available for adoption for
the first time in 18 years. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BABY-SAVER _ MOBILE, Ala. _ By the time television reporter Jodi
Brooks arrived in Mobile, Ala., she already had covered two
depressing cases of young females accused of murdering their
newborn babies. So when she wound up covering a third such case in
Mobile, she decided to take action. After a year of operation, ``A
Safe Place for Newborns'' is gaining national momentum. Several
Minnesota hospitals have adopted the program, and the attorney
general there, Michael Hatch, supports making it statewide. The
Alabama District Attorneys Association voted in November to adopt
the program statewide. Brooks, who is helping set up a program in
nearby Pensacola, Fla., said she has had inquiries from Seattle;
Boston; Los Angeles; Austin, Texas; and Paris, as well as George W.
Bush's campaign office. (David, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
(Freelancer, not for use by NYT News Service). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   DEBATES _ George W. Bush has debated more this month than in his
entire political career, and politics watchers say he's getting
better at it. After a rocky beginning in which he was criticized
for being too scripted and stilted, Bush seems to have warmed up to
debating, becoming more relaxed and taking the offensive more
often. After Saturday's debate, therer will be a lull, and we use
the opportunity to take stock of the debates so far, including are
they having an effect and whether anyone's watching. (Herman,
Austin American-Statesman). 25-30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 7 p.m. EST Friday.
</P>
