<HEADER>
A6323 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     01-14 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOR US SKEPTICAL: NETWORKS HAVE MADE EMPTY PROMISES ABOUT
DIVERSITY BEFORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ah, yes, deal-making in fantasyland.
</P>
<P>
   What a concept.
</P>
<P>
   What a way for TV networks to create some wiggle room and avoid
this chronic nuisance they have either no clue about, or no
inclination to solve.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement announced this week between the NAACP and two of
the four major networks is, sad to say, another example of the
networks extending one hand in a solidarity handshake while using
the other to cover their mouths and mute the laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Go right ahead and believe that ABC and NBC will beef up their
ranks of minority writers, producers, directors and executives via
``training programs'' and other initiatives, and that CBS and Fox
will soon follow in their footsteps. Have faith that the presence
of African-American, Hispanic and Asian characters in sitcoms,
dramas and news programs will last beyond this initial period of
forced enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what it is, isn't it? Nothing like a threatened
protest and a wave of negative publicity to bring out the
compassion in network executives who, if track records speak for
future endeavors, are awfully good illusionists when it comes to
doing what's fair and just.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, network heads have met with NAACP President Kweisi
Mfume to cop a plea and save their hides. They've gleefully
announced ``bold, new'' initiatives establishing goals and
timetables to increase opportunities for people of color at the
network level.
</P>
<P>
   But is the joke on us?
</P>
<P>
   The agreement at NBC, for instance, calls for more deals with
minority-owned production companies, going so far as to pay for a
writer on the staff of every second-year show. (To help develop a
pipeline of talent, they say.)
</P>
<P>
   ABC's diversity plea bargain does not include funding for
additional series writing staff positions. But it does outline a
number of new and ongoing executive-outreach, production,
programming and advertising initiatives, like setting a goal of
buying some $10 million of products and/or services from
minority-owned businesses over the next 18 months. Hold your breath
on that one.
</P>
<P>
   If you think these initiatives are examples of TV bending over
backward to appease whiny, greedy racial groups, consider that 55
of the fall season's 839 writers are African-American; 11 are
Latino, three are Asian-American, and none is American Indian. No
people of color are heads of TV studios. Few are in programming,
period.
</P>
<P>
   Most influential series _ the ``ERs,'' the ``Practices,'' the
``Law &AMP; Orders,'' the ``NYPD Blues,'' not only come from white
Americans but white men. No minority producer can greenlight a
project, not even three-time Emmy winner Paris Barclay, who had to
partner with Steven Bochco to get ``City of Angels'' on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   This is vital because it's widely believed that the more
diversity there is among show creators and programming executives,
the more diverse programs will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that you can have as many minorities as actors but you
have to have the words on the page to make it work,'' said Scott
Sassa, president of NBC West Coast. ``Television is a writer's
medium. And we thought the writing numbers were really the issue.
So we felt that attacking it at the writer level was the most
important way to make a real change over time rather than just a
cosmetic change.''
</P>
<P>
   Sassa's right, which makes it even more appalling that the
networks hadn't thought of this before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The networks won't do anything unless their arms are twisted,
and to them, addressing the nuts and bolts of diversity is nothing
more than saying they'll address it,'' said writer/producer Robert
Townsend, whose family series ``Parent'Hood'' was axed by The WB to
make way for dramas featuring mostly white characters.
</P>
<P>
   To veteran observers of the network song-and-dance, like
Townsend, these initiatives are not above suspicion. There's a
pattern to this: First there's acknowledgment, followed by public
acceptance of blame, followed by a brief deflection of the issues,
followed by the promise of changes that never come. Which is where
we are now.
</P>
<P>
   ``People move on to something else, people forget, pressure
subsides,'' Townsend says. ``And they're off the hook until next
time, because the black people and the Hispanic people they deal
with every day feel the inequity but don't say it because rent is
due.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, deal-making in fantasyland.
</P>
<P>
   What a concept.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
