<HEADER>
A6326 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-MARTIN-LUTHER-KING-DY     01-14 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTIN-LUTHER-KING-DYSON-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONOR DR. KING WITH PROGRESS, NOT SAINTHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By MICHAEL ERIC DYSON  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 (For release: Jan. 16 or thereafter)  
 &HT;    Like so many Americans, I first met Martin Luther King Jr. on
television. I was 9. He was dead.
 &HT;    ``Martin Luther King Jr. has just been shot in Memphis, Tenn.,''
the news bulletin announced.
 &HT;    I was sitting on the living-room floor watching a Western with
my father. As my mother joined us, the camera switched to King's
last speech.
 &HT;    ``We've got some difficult days ahead,'' King said as he peered
intensely at his throng of followers.
 &HT;    ``But it really doesn't matter with me now, because I've been to
the mountaintop.'' The audience erupted in cheers and with shouts
of ``Oh, yes!'' ``Go 'head!'' and ``Yes, sir!''
 &HT;    Before the applause subsided, he continued: ``Like anybody, I'd
like to live a long life. But lon-ge-vi-ty has its place.'' He
paused, deliberately letting the audience's cries ratchet up the
emotional pitch of his rhetoric. By now, I had goose bumps all over
my body.
 &HT;    ``I may not get there with you,'' he said, reaching his
thrilling climax. ``But I want you to know tonight that we as a
people will get to the promised land.''
 &HT;    That was the image of King that was scorched into my brain: a
Christlike leader who prophesied his people's redemption and his
own imminent martyrdom in the same breath. Countless books and
articles portrayed him as the Prince of Peace, an American Gandhi,
a latter-day Jefferson or Lincoln.
 &HT;    Schoolteachers extolled him as the superhuman ideal of eloquence
and restraint toward which all black people should strive. As his
talents were celebrated again and again, an official story began to
fall into place: King had been a humble minister who pricked
America's conscience, and America had responded by eagerly righting
all its historical wrongs.
 &HT;    It was a compelling story, but more than that, it was a useful
story. For millions of blacks, his saintly stature enhanced their
collective moral standing. For many whites, his public canonization
relieved their otherwise troubled racial conscience.
 &HT;    And for a fragmented nation still reeling from the social
upheavals of the 1960s, his public acclaim afforded a rare moment
of healing consensus.
 &HT;    But the hagiography of King harbored a distinct political
morality. In the name of unity, the official story silenced the
more radical aspects of King's challenge _ his advocacy of racial
compensation, his attempt to destroy poverty, his democratic
socialist beliefs, his opposition to the Vietnam War. And it
whitewashed the painful truth that America had harshly resisted his
call to do the right thing.
 &HT;    Most of all, it placed him far beyond the reach of mere mortals.
His flesh-and-blood struggles _ and failures _ became easily
dismissed as mere preamble to his inevitable ascension. And the
courageous role played by ordinary black folks and their supporters
was forgotten altogether.
 &HT;    I first started to question the official representation when, as
a 19-year-old minister in training, I heard whispers about King's
rampant womanizing.
 &HT;    Then in the late '80s, I discovered that one of King's sermons,
``Remaining Awake Through a Great Revolution,'' strongly resembled
the sermon of a white minister, Halford Luccock, that had been
published many years earlier.
 &HT;    King's adulterous liaisons eventually came into fuller view with
the publication of ``Bearing the Cross,'' by David Garrow, and
``Parting the Waters,'' by Taylor Branch; Keith Miller later
explored King's plagiarism at great length in his well-publicized
book, ``Voice of Deliverance.''
 &HT;    The awestruck 9-year-old I once was would have been horrified by
these facts, but as I became more conscious of my own moral lapses
and hypocrisies, I found them deeply moving. I felt that for the
first time I was able to grasp what King accomplished in its true
proportions.
 &HT;    When I shared these revelations with others, however _ in
publications and speeches in observance of his holiday _ I
encountered tremendous resistance.
 &HT;    Of course, it's easy to understand why black people are
suspicious of anyone who claims the need to scrutinize King: He was
torn apart in life, so shouldn't he be protected in death? But
protecting him from critical inquiry preserves his image at the
expense of his message.
 &HT;    Consider his current political fortunes. Since his elevation to
the position of national saint, his bowdlerized legacy has been up
for grabs by any and all. On the 1997 anniversary of King's birth,
Ward Connerly, the black conservative, opened his national campaign
against affirmative action by invoking (out of context) King's wish
for his children not to be judged by the ``color of their skin but
by the content of their character.''
 &HT;    This despite the fact that King advocated ``special,
compensatory measures which could be regarded as a settlement'' for
the ``exploitation and humiliation of the Negro in America down
through the centuries.''
 &HT;    Indeed, his image has been appropriated in electoral bids,
hip-hop songs, church sermons and fast-food ads _ of such diverse
and contradictory meanings that he couldn't possibly have approved
of all of them.
 &HT;    Worse yet, investing in King's perfection allows us to dismiss
the humanity of the underregarded, like many beleaguered black
youth, whose violence-drenched culture is said to prove their
distance from King's stature and dream.
 &HT;    King's real danger to American society is buried in all these
romantic portrayals; after all, he wasn't killed for preaching
nonviolence. With a more nuanced view of King in play, we should be
inspired to create social change in our own communities, armed with
the belief that good things can be done by imperfect people. It is
to our national advantage to recuperate the King who tested
America's mettle by challenging us to live right.
 &HT;    And it would benefit us personally to grasp hold of a King whose
blotches and brilliance live on the same block, if for no other
reason than to destroy the self-righteousness that King so rightly
deplored.
 &HT;     c.2000 Michael Eric Dyson  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Michael Eric Dyson, who teaches at DePaul University, is
author of ``I May Not Get There With You: The True Martin Luther
King Jr.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
