<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6335 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AFRICANAMERICAN-ART16     01-14 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICANAMERICAN-ART16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A collection of works by African-Americans looms so large in the
lives of one atlanta couple that they built their house around it
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoe for Sunday, Jan. 16.
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the decade since Danny Boston and his wife,
Catherine Ross, began collecting art, they have discovered, as have
many before them, that the art they acquire ends up owning them.
</P>
<P>
   Their 3-year-old brick and limestone house in Atlanta tells the
story. They had planned originally to designate one room to
showcase their 80-piece collection of African-American art.
Instead, the Bostons, who met in the registration line the first
semester of graduate school at Cornell University, ended up turning
the whole place into a gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted a daily relationship with the art,'' says Ross, a
former professor of planning at Georgia Tech in Atlanta, who is
executive director of the Georgia Regional Transportation
Authority, Gov. Roy Barnes' new transportation superagency.
</P>
<P>
   The core of the house is an intersecting pair of gracious halls
with crisp white walls and shiny marble floors. The halls provide
an intimate yet uncrowded space for displaying art. Architect
Michael Glass, who conceived the central space, also made sure that
the adjoining rooms offer ample wall space for more. The upstairs
landing serves that purpose as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a wonderful thing to do _ to build a house to prepare for
building a collection,'' says Atlanta art appraiser Ben Apfelbaum.
``The halls are deep, so that you can stand back and look at the
art.''
</P>
<P>
   The paintings and prints reveal an eclectic eye. An abstraction
by Atlanta artist Freddie Styles is around the corner from a
lithograph from Jacob Lawrence's John Brown series. Atlanta
sculptor Curtis Patterson's first lithographs hang in the yellow
living room.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, Boston and daughter Shani, 14, (son Linje, 19, attends
Carnegie Mellon University, studying computer
</P>
<P>
   science) will be adjusting to bare walls for six weeks.
Sixty-eight works from their collection are on display at Georgia
Tech through Feb. 28. But they are excited about sharing their art
with the student body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very concerned that the students be able to understand
and connect with it,'' say Boston, professor of economics at Tech,
who is overseeing the project. ``I would not like for them to be as
old as I was when I first began to appreciate fine art.''
</P>
<P>
   That process started in 1976, when Boston, then 29, joined the
faculty at Clark Atlanta University. He shared an office with Tina
Dunkley, director of the Clark Atlanta University Gallery, and
began going to shows there. His interest piqued, he and Ross
started spending time in museums, got hooked and began
investigating the how-tos of beginning an art collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we read suggested that it should have a focus,'' he
says. ``Since we couldn't collect older masters, we decided to
collect artists who were either born or spent some time in
Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   That covers a broad spectrum, from patriarch Henry Ossawa
Tanner, who briefly had a photographic studio in Atlanta, to the
wealth of contemporary artists who live in metro Atlanta. The
collection includes Ulysses Marshall, Kevin Cole, John Dowell and
Stefani Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``They buy with their own eye,'' says friend Jimmy Allen, an
Atlanta dealer whom Boston approached after overhearing him talking
about the collection of Malcolm X papers he had acquired. ``Their
choices are not out of a manual, of what African-American
collectors should get, but what appeals to them. That is
adventurous.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta printmaker Michael Ellison occupies a special place in
the collection. As part of their focus, they decided to acquire one
artist in depth, and they own 40 Ellisons, one of every print he
has made. Their dining room is a homage to the artist, who has a
mini one-man-show called ``The Art of Storytelling'' within the
Tech show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the simplicity of the scenes and the complexity of the
way he captures it,'' Boston says. ``The themes are of everyday
life of African-Americans _ the church, street scenes, night life.
He so vividly captures the experience of life in general.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellison has been able to count on their patronage for half of
his 20-year career. ``It means a lot,'' he says. ``Artists are at
the mercy of the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston commissioned Ellison to make the images for the covers of
his two-volume book, ``Different Vision,'' about black economics,
which the artist considers the highlight of his career. The
professor has continued the practice with other artists for other
publications. ``Inner City,'' essays on urban poverty and
revitalization strategies for inner cities co-edited with Ross,
uses a Jacob Lawrence piece.
</P>
<P>
   The couple has developed friendships with Ellison and
Philadelphian Jonas Allen. Allen lived with the family for two
months while he painted a large piece for a specially created niche
on the second floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bit of a trial,'' Boston laughingly remembers. ``He
would sleep all day, get up around 6 or 7 p.m., go out or entertain
friends and get to work about 2 or 3 a.m. He said he had to do it
when the inspiration hit him. The problem is, that was usually
before sunrise.''
</P>
<P>
   Collecting art has not only affected the architecture of their
home and expanded their circle of friends. It is part of family
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never visit a city that we don't go to a gallery,'' says
Ross. ``The kids used to complain, but now they're into it. They
have developed some expertise. It's rewarding to have them develop
an appreciation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's really encouraging and wonderful about the Bostons is
their level of commitment to learning and keeping informed about
the visual arts,'' says Dunkley. ``So many people who have the
means to buy art don't have the values, interest and knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   The late dealer Thurlow Tibbs of Washington helped them build
their collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave him a list of artists we were looking for, and he
would call us when he found something,'' Boston says. ``He would
discourage us, too, if he thought a work didn't fit. The more I
pull together the wall texts, the more I realize how important he
was in directing and curating our collection.''
</P>
<P>
   They have also benefited from a relationship with master printer
Lou Stovall, who runs Workshop Inc. in Washington. Boston is
excited about a recent purchase, a print by the late James Lesesne
Wells made in collaboration with Stovall.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's consumed,'' Ross says of her husband. ``I have to watch
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The collection is growing in scope as well as number. A
photograph by Albert Chong is a new acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we are beginning to expand in new directions,'' Ross says.
``Abstraction. Sculpture. It's a process of educating oneself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Survival: An Exhibition of African American Art, Selections
From the Collection of
</P>
<P>
   Drs. Thomas D. Boston and Catherine L. Ross''
</P>
<P>
   Through Feb. 28. Noon-6 p.m. Tuesdays-Saturdays. Ferst Center
for the Arts, Georgia Tech, 349 Ferst Drive N.W. 404-894-9600.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
