<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6336 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-FILM-FESTIVAL16-COX     01-14 1680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FESTIVAL16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sundance fest solid as a film launching pad
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes, the best Sundance Film Festival stories have little
to do with what's projected on a big screen.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax Films co-chairman Harvey Weinstein, whose studio helped
catapult ``Shakespeare in Love'' over ``Saving Private Ryan'' at
last year's Oscars, once reportedly stormed into a restaurant at
the fest and began yelling and screaming at a rival. Weinstein had
just been outbid for the distributing rights to a little Australian
movie about an abused piano prodigy. It was called ``Shine.''
</P>
<P>
   Following a screening of his much-praised documentary ``Gates of
Heaven,'' Errol Morris (``The Thin Blue Line'') got caught in a
snowstorm _ one of the festival's seemingly annual pet peeves in
its picturesque mountaintop setting in Utah _ and tried to get back
to his out-of-the-way condo in freezing weather by hitchhiking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was picked up by two people who'd been in the theater and
had hated the movie,'' he says. ``They asked me what I thought, and
since I had no alternative means of transportation, I said I, too,
was extremely disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   10 days of movies
</P>
<P>
   Tom Bernard, co-president of Sony Pictures Classics, made a
reported $700,000 distribution deal last year for the documentary
``American Movie'' with Athens-based R.E.M.'s Michael Stipe, a
financial backer of the film, sitting at the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I had lunch with these guys, and I didn't even know who
he was,'' Bernard says. ``After we made the deal, I found out he
was in the rock 'n' roll business.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sundance Film Festival, Robert Redford's annual 10-day fete
of independent movies in Park City, Utah, ushers in the new century
Thursday with all the behind-the-scenes dealmaking,
front-and-center celebrity preening and sheer movie fan mania
that's marked the festival for 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Soderbergh's ``sex, lies and videotape,'' which first
underscored profitability and mass-market acceptance of independent
films, took off there. So did the Oscar-winning ``Shine,''
``Affliction,'' ``Gods and Monsters,'' ``Hoop Dreams,'' ``El
Mariachi,'' ``Clerks'' and Quentin Tarantino's ``Reservoir Dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sundance is the premier American film festival,'' says Mark
Ordesky, president of Fine Line Features.
</P>
<P>
   John Anderson, film critic for Newsday, a newspaper on Long
Island, N.Y., has attended nine consecutive Sundance fests and
calls it ``among the three or four most prestigious in the world.
It is always a barometer of a film-crazy culture's national
cinema,'' he writes in his new book ``Sundancing.''
</P>
<P>
   The stars do come out. Robert Altman, Kenneth Branagh and Glenn
Close have all touted films there.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the 112 full-length movies, documentaries and film
shorts will feature such talent as Kevin Spacey, Ben Affleck,
Cameron Diaz, Heather Graham, Danny DeVito, Christian Bale, Emilio
Estevez, Omar Epps, Nia Long and Stanley Tucci.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most anticipated films: the opening night
Thanksgiving-themed ``What's Cooking?,'' starring Alfre Woodard,
Joan Chen and Julianna Margulies, from English-Indian director
Gurinder Chadha; and ``American Psycho,'' with Bale, Willem Dafoe
and Reese Witherspoon in director Mary Harron's adaptation of Bret
Easton Ellis' controversial Wall Street psycho-killer drama.
``American Psycho'' opens in theaters in April.
</P>
<P>
   This year's festival features more movies from women filmmakers
than ever before. Plus, there will be digital screenings of 17
films at theaters equipped with special projectors installed by
Kennesaw's Digital Projection Inc. It's a process that some expect
to revolutionize independent filmmaking, drastically reducing
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Deals and steals
</P>
<P>
   Among other Georgia connections: The Georgia Film and Videotape
Office will hold a breakfast to lure more filmmakers to the state.
(Recently, Redford filmed ``The Legend of Bagger Vance'' in
Savannah, and Denzel Washington made ``Remember the Titans'' in
metro Atlanta and North Georgia.) And Pat Mitchell, president of
CNN Productions and Time Inc. Television and board member of the
Sundance Institute, will serve on a panel also involving
representatives from HBO, PBS, Artisan Entertainment and other
outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Over two decades, Sundance has been a virtual breeding ground
where independent filmmakers can peddle their movies to Hollywood
studios. The festival has been a mixture of world premieres (Altman
debuted ``Cookie's Fortune'' last year), documentaries and
brand-new voices. Other films that made their mark at Sundance
include ``The Opposite of Sex,'' ``Longtime Companion,'' ``The
Waterdance,'' ``love jones,'' ``In the Company of Men'' and ``Pi.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there is ``The Blair Witch Project.'' A midnight
darling at last year's festival, ``Blair Witch's'' creators
brokered a distribution deal with Artisan Entertainment for roughly
$1.1 million and then stunned the movie industry as the horror
flick amassed more than $140 million at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Sundance, there were a number of people who walked out of
`Blair Witch,''' says Tom Ortenberg, co-president of Lions Gate
Releasing. ``There was not even unanimity within Artisan that they
had bought a picture worth buying. Believe me, at the end of the
day, Sundance is nothing but a crap shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a bet many studios lose big time.
</P>
<P>
   Hand in hand with all the success stories are plenty of
multimillion-dollar deals that end up bombing at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax paid anywhere from a reported $2.5 million to a rumored
$10 million-plus for last year's ``Happy, Texas,'' which has sold
only $1.9 million in tickets. Miramax also shelled out $6 million
for 1998's ``Next Stop Wonderland,'' only to see it earn a paltry
$3.4 million at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   Several festival winners _ including last year's ``Three
Seasons,'' the filmed-in-Vietnam debut from director Tony Bui,
which won the grand jury prize and audience award in drama _ hardly
registered nationwide in ticket receipts.
</P>
<P>
   Unexpected finds
</P>
<P>
   Often, the beauty of Sundance isn't what always sells or wins
awards, but what more quietly emerges.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Thomas Anderson, for example, debuted the film short
``Cigarettes and Coffee'' in 1993. It raised the young filmmaker's
profile, and over the next six years he wrote and directed ``Hard
Eight,'' ``Boogie Nights'' and ``Magnolia.''
</P>
<P>
   At last year's festival, Kimberly Peirce had roughly 20 minutes
of footage available for distributors to see of her
work-in-progress about a Midwestern woman posing as a man. The end
result: ``Boys Don't Cry,'' which could bring Oscar nominations
this year for stars Hilary Swank and Chloe Sevigny.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very organic festival,'' Fine Line's Ordesky says.
``The people who program the festival don't program it for
commerce, they program it for the best independent film has to
offer. The perception that Sundance is becoming more commercialized
is there because more studios are using it as a launch pad for
films they've already bought.''
</P>
<P>
   ``American Psycho'' is a prime example.
</P>
<P>
   The film, getting its world premiere at Sundance and set to
debut in theaters April 7, previously landed a distribution deal
with Lions Gate Releasing. It's one of several film premieres at
the fest designed to use Sundance as a way to market independent
movies to the press and public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think `American Psycho' will appeal to both the 18-year-old
demographic and highbrow movie audiences,'' Lions Gate's Ortenberg
says. ``The timing of Sundance is perfect and makes it a great
platform. It coincides with the deadlines for many national
magazines' April issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Other world premieres will include director Keith Gordon's drama
``Waking the Dead'' with Billy Crudup and Jennifer Connelly, and
director Valerie Breiman's dating flick ``Love and Sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the heart of the festival is its as-yet unsold dramas and
documentaries that compete for prizes. Among the full-length
dramas: Jenniphr Goodman's ``The Tao of Steve,'' about a cool guy
who attracts women naturally, and Kenneth Lonergan's ``You Can
Count on Me,'' with Laura Linney and Matthew Broderick, in a tale
of orphaned siblings who grew up apart.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more anticipated documentaries: Elizabeth Barret's
``Stranger With a Camera,'' about the 1967 slaying of a
documentarian in Appalachia, and Daniel McCabe and Paul Stekler's
``George Wallace: Settin' the Woods on Fire.''
</P>
<P>
   It's with unsold films like these that backstage deals get done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opening night film _ `What's Cooking?' I was told that $6
million could take it off the table today,'' Sony Pictures' Bernard
says. ``No one's seen it. Every year, every movie has some bizarre
amount of money, sight unseen. And that's the number they'll get if
they have a huge bidding war going. It's the most ruthless pack of
filmmakers in one place.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine Line's Ordesky says last year's fest was ``busy,''
producing five or seven pricey picture deals. ``There's usually not
less than three, and I've rarely seen more than five to seven.''
</P>
<P>
   What's decidedly more plentiful are the great off-screen
stories.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ben Affleck nearly getting crushed in a crowd's frenzy to
get into a screening. Or who the makers of ``Judy Berlin'' once
found living with them in their rented Park City house _ a groupie,
who melded into the ``Berlin'' team after a screening and even
joined them in their Jacuzzi.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's sort of living in our house, but nobody really knows
him,'' ``Berlin'' actress Edie Falco (an Emmy winner for HBO's
``The Sopranos'') recalls in the book ``Sundancing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems harmless enough, but nobody speaks to him really,
nobody knows him, and he kind of sits there and watches us,'' Falco
says. ``Everybody thought he was someone else's friend. Finally, we
all sort of said, `No, I don't know him either!'''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
