<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6337 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-RELIGION-SNAPSHOT15-C     01-14 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-SNAPSHOT15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Faith is not reserved just for the sabbath, researchers find
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a typical 24-hour period, many Americans are busy praying,
sharing their faith and reading Scripture.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the Princeton Religion Research Center set out to show
just how many Americans engage in religious or spiritual
activities.
</P>
<P>
   The center is a nondenominational organization that uses the
facilities and resources of Gallup International. Its executive
director, George Gallup Jr., calls the survey a ``snapshot'' of
American spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see data on the country as a whole for specific
items,'' said Gallup, who is also co-chairman of the Gallup
Organization. ``But it's very helpful to see them all in
relationship to each other. Is there a rhythm in spirituality? Does
it ebb and flow? Do people sense God's presence in a positive way?
In a negative way?''
</P>
<P>
   The recent survey, the result of interviews with 100 Americans _
a representative sample of a larger Gallup poll of randomly
selected people _ reinforced findings from earlier Gallup research,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those studies show that the percentage of Americans who say they
feel the need for spiritual growth surged 24 points in just four
years _ from 58 percent in 1994 to 82 percent in 1998 _ but that
the increased interest in spirituality is not coming at the expense
of organized religion. Religious preference and church attendance
have changed little in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a great deal of spiritual and religious activity
going on,'' said Gallup. ``It's not just a Sunday thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallup said he believes the most important questions his
organization can ask these days are about the inner life of
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The depth of spirituality, the depth of faith commitment,
really have a lot more to do with who we are than a lot of other
things, such as region or political party,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   How does Gallup, a 69-year-old Episcopalian, answer his own
questions?
</P>
<P>
   In the 24 hours before the interview, he said, he prayed at a
meal, talked to someone about God, shared his faith, read the Bible
and other spiritual literature, counseled someone from a spiritual
perspective, attended a worship service and listened to a religious
cassette tape. He did not watch religious television, listen to
religious radio, visit a religious computer Web site or use the
Internet to explore a matter of faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't use the Internet,'' he said. ``I'm a typewriter man.''
</P>
<P>
   55% PRAYED AT A MEAL
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim and I grew up in families where the focus around the
evening meal was that you said the blessing and then talked about
the day's activities. Sometimes that's the time when you reflect
back on what God's done that day. It's a time of quiet in all the
hecticness that goes on. For us it's a time of not only blessing
the food but for other prayers and petitions.''
</P>
<P>
   Sally English, metro Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Real estate agent
</P>
<P>
   Rehoboth Presbyterian Church
</P>
<P>
   36% READ THE BIBLE
</P>
<P>
   ``It's central to my life. It's strength for me. It's
encouragement for me. ... It helps me in my relationships with
others. I'm seeking to know what Jesus Christ was all about. It
helps me with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin Perry, Roswell, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Computer consultant
</P>
<P>
   Ben Hill United Methodist Church
</P>
<P>
   22% SPOKE OUT ON A NATIONAL ISSUE OUT OF RELIGIOUS CONVICTION
</P>
<P>
   ``I take my calling very seriously. I was called to preach the
gospel of Jesus Christ and I am so impressed with Jesus! He was a
doer. What he espoused, he implemented. ... I diligently seek to do
his will and his work. A lot of times when people see social
activists, they don't see the spiritual side. They see the
rabble-rousing, demonstrating side. But for me, it's my faith, my
belief in Jesus, and my sense of his calling me into ministry that
undergirds that. I hope that doesn't get lost in the persona of the
activist.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert Love, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Minister
</P>
<P>
   Boatrock Baptist Church
</P>
<P>
   15% ATTENDED A PRAYER SERVICE, BIBLE STUDY GROUP OR WORSHIP
GROUP
</P>
<P>
   ``In Judaism you can pray alone and you can pray anytime, but
the optimum situation is to pray in a group. Everyone around you is
praying in their own way for whatever their own needs are, but you
also have a community that supports each other. We praise in
unison, which is also mentioned in the Bible. I believe as we
combine our voices, we create a stronger presence before God and
that singing pleases God. Even though you can sing alone, it's a
lot more meaningful, a lot more warming to the soul to sing
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Rosenbaum, Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Teacher
</P>
<P>
   Etz Chaim synagogue
</P>
<P>
   3% USED THE INTERNET TO RESEARCH OR EXPLORE MATTER OF RELIGIOUS
FAITH
</P>
<P>
   ``Marianne Williamson has a Web site. Deepak Chopra does. There
is a site connected to the Dalai Lama. I have them all bookmarked.
... Our church has a prayer tree, a group of people committed to
praying for special needs. We learned that it was very easy to
share information over the Internet. You just check your e-mail
every day and have requests waiting for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathie Lumberg, Woodstock, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Bookstore manager
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Unity Church
</P>
<P>
   OTHER RESULTS
</P>
<P>
   51% talked to someone about God or some aspect of their faith or
spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   49% felt ``a strong sense of God's presence.''
</P>
<P>
   45% went out of their way to help someone because of spiritual
or faith reasons.
</P>
<P>
   44% shared their faith.
</P>
<P>
   32% read books or articles with spiritual themes.
</P>
<P>
   25% counseled someone from a spiritual perspective.
</P>
<P>
   24% watched religion on TV or listened to religious radio.
</P>
<P>
   15% listened to cassette tapes with spiritual themes.
</P>
<P>
   5% called a psychic hotline or read a horoscope.
</P>
<P>
   2% visited computer Web sites related to churches or that
contained religious themes.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
