<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6338 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SUPERBOWL-ENTERTAININ     01-14 1620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERBOWL-ENTERTAINING15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    34 party tips for Super Bowl XXXIV
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlanta is hosting Super Bowl XXXIV. You are hosting a Super
Bowl party.
</P>
<P>
   In two weeks, the city will be bustling with scores of the rich
and the famous, the corporate and the connected.
</P>
<P>
   Your den will be packed with neighbors and co-workers; friends
and true football fans.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, a few lucky ducks get to spend the day at the Georgia
Dome. But the rest of us are carrying on a tradition that may as
well be a national holiday. The Super Bowl is the biggest at-home
party of the year, according to Hallmark Cards research.
</P>
<P>
   And even those who shy away from entertaining find this gig
manageable. After all, the theme is set _ football. And so are the
activities _ watch TV and eat.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, since we are the host city, Super Bowl party
hosts may want to go an extra few yards to make the evening
special.
</P>
<P>
   You'll need a good game plan because usually there's a two-week
break between the final playoff game and the Super Bowl. This year,
there's only one. The final two teams won't be decided until
Sunday, Jan. 23.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no need to procrastinate. We've got ideas _ 34 of
them in fact _ to keep you busy, from today until it's time for the
antacid.
</P>
<P>
   INVITING
</P>
<P>
   I. Draft a guest list. The average number at a Super Bowl party
is 17, Hallmark Cards research shows. Take into consideration the
size of your house and the number of TVs.
</P>
<P>
   II. Seek balance among the fanatical football fans and those who
don't know a first down from first base. (And have a plan for
keeping these two groups at a safe distance from each other.)
</P>
<P>
   III. Issue the invites. This is a casual party, so phone calls
and e-mails are okay. Be ready with a list of needs (beer, chips)
to offer when guests ask what they can bring.
</P>
<P>
   VIEWING
</P>
<P>
   IV. Count your televisions. It's a good idea to have more than
one. The kids may want their own tube; the football fanatics won't
want to miss a moment, even in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   V. And measure them, too. Don't even think of crowding a dozen
people around a 13-inch screen. If you don't have a large screen
television, move the party to someone else's house. Or get one. The
National Electronic Dealers Association reports sales of large
screen televisions increase five times during Super Bowl Week.
</P>
<P>
   VI. Hook up the main television to the stereo. Nothing short of
surround sound will do for that stadium feel.
</P>
<P>
   VII. Gather enough chairs (you may have to ask guests to bring a
folding chair or two) and arrange chairs so that everyone can see.
Try forming a semi- circle ``stadium style.''
</P>
<P>
   DECORATING
</P>
<P>
   VIII. Once the teams are decided, think team colors in
everything from jerseys to streamers to paper plates. Or go with
football logos. The NFL licenses 50 companies to produce products
bearing the Super Bowl logo, from aprons to chip-and-dip sets.
Party goods stores will be a sure bet. There also are some online
sources such as partyforless.com.
</P>
<P>
   IX. Convert your ping pong table into a buffet table. Use white
duct tape to mark off yard lines and create goal posts using tubes
from rolls of paper towels, drinking straws or white pvc pipes.
</P>
<P>
   X. Raid your 10-year-old son's room and move the team posters
out to the TV room. Then raid your college-aged son's room and
borrow some beer posters.
</P>
<P>
   EATING
</P>
<P>
   XI. Speaking of beer, it would be tragic to forget you can't buy
beer to take home on Sunday. So make the beer run on Saturday at
the latest. Remember, if you get a keg, pick up several bags of ice
to keep it cool until you tap it. (A cold snap in the weather sure
could help.) Remember some folks don't imbibe, so have plenty of
soft drinks, tea and juice on hand.
</P>
<P>
   XII. And don't forget the chips and dip. An estimated 14,500
tons of chips and 4,000 tons of popcorn are eaten on Super Bowl
Sunday. And Americans average 8 million pounds of guacamole. So
start hoarding bags of chips like it's Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   XIII. But don't bother with the sparkling water. This isn't that
kind of party. Nor do you need to fuss over prissy appetizers or a
meal that requires attention at the stove while the game is in
play.
</P>
<P>
   XIV. Think make-ahead crowd pleasers for main courses. Lasagne
is great. So is chili. We'll give you some fan-tastic recipes in
Thursday's Food section.
</P>
<P>
   XV. Mix and match some of your favorites, advises Allan Souze,
owner of Divine Events Catering in Roswell, which will be catering
the Fox SportsNet tent during Super Bowl week. For instance, rather
than cocktail sauce, serve lightly breaded shrimp with the buffalo
sauce usually doused on chicken wings.
</P>
<P>
   XVI. Think football shapes. Some things are naturally oblong,
like deviled eggs and black olives. Others, like meatballs, can be
easily molded by hand. Football-shaped cookie cutters and molds can
be used to make cookies, cupcakes, sandwiches and Jell-O to
resemble footballs.
</P>
<P>
   XVII. If pizza is the plan, jot down the number for pizza
delivery and stick it by the phone now. Come game day, call early
to find out what time you should place your order. Super Bowl
Sunday is the busiest day of the year for pizza delivery.
</P>
<P>
   XVIII. Carryout can do. Load up at your favorite barbecue joint,
chicken wing shack or grocery deli. If you want to go fancy,
eatZi's is offering mini beef Wellingtons and Szechuan beef spring
rolls by the dozen, along with a full menu of Super Bowl favorites.
Order by Friday, Jan. 28. (404-237-8646.)
</P>
<P>
   XIX. Talk the kids into being vendors. Make some vendor boxes
that hang from their necks and have them move from room to room
hawking popcorn and peanuts to the hungry fans. Tell them they can
keep the tips.
</P>
<P>
   XX. Paper plates are proper. Anyone who complains can wash the
pots and pans during the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINING
</P>
<P>
   XXI. Just because you aren't going to the game, doesn't mean you
can't have a tailgate party. For festive pregame fun, talk everyone
on your street into pulling their SUV's to the end of the driveway,
dropping down the tailgate and putting on a spread of Super Bowl
snacks.
</P>
<P>
   XXII. While you're tailgating, organize a little street
scrimmage of touch football. Losers can host the winners for the
big game (or send them home with an extra beer or two.)
</P>
<P>
   XXIII. Set up a face painting station and encourage everyone,
not just the kids, to slap some color on their face.
</P>
<P>
   XXIV. Pull out the sports almanacs and write up a trivia game.
You can arrange it in the style of Jeopardy! and play rounds before
the game, during commercials and halftime. Or read questions from
the Sports edition of Trivial Pursuit or the sports category of the
genus?? edition. Award prizes.
</P>
<P>
   XXV. Play football party bingo. Instead of letters, players are
looking for first downs, completed passes, etc. For details visit
footballpartybingo.com or call 1-888-436-6822 to order a game set
with cards. Order no later than Jan. 21.
</P>
<P>
   XXVI. Wouldn't a little wager make the game more interesting?
Encourage folks to place bets on the winners, but set a reasonable
cap in the $1 to $5 range. Then place penny or quarter bets on
everything from who will win the coin toss to which beer commercial
will be on next.
</P>
<P>
   XXVII. Start choreographing now. Recruit some guests (including
kids) to stage a halftime show with skits and songs. Just about
anything could be more entertaining than the real thing. (Remember
the video camera. )
</P>
<P>
   XXVIII. For the real couch potatoes, make it a day-long event
and rent videos of football movies (''The Longest Yard'', ``Black
Sunday'', ``North Dallas Forty'') or highlights from previous Super
Bowls to screenbefore the game.
</P>
<P>
   XXIX. Rather than take care of all the details yourself, party
at a sports bar instead. The new ESPN Zone in Buckhead (3030
Peachtree Road) plans to make it's debut Super Bowl week. The
33,000-square-foot complex combines eating, viewing and playing.
With 210 screens for sports viewing _ including in the restrooms _
fans won't miss a moment of the action. ABC will broadcast portions
of their pregame show from there. Advance tickets will be required.
The cost will be $20 and will include a t-shirt; only 200 will be
sold beginning 9 a.m. Monday, Jan. 23 at ESPN Zone.
</P>
<P>
   GIVING
</P>
<P>
   XXX. Think prizes to reward folks for trivia knowledge, lucky
bets and winning bingo cards. Party favors are nice too, especially
for those who don't know squat about football trivia, who cheered
for the losing team or who drew a bingo card destined for the paper
shredder. Small footballs, pennants, posters and tickets to
sporting events are all good ideas.
</P>
<P>
   XXXI. Organize a ``Souper'' bowl at your church. Souper Bowl of
Caring is an effort that began a decade ago to get church goers to
donate a dollar each on their way out the door Super Bowl Sunday
for hunger relief efforts. To find out more, call 1-800-358-7687 or
go to www.souperbowl.com.
</P>
<P>
   XXXII. Ask guests to bring along some of those Y2K canned goods
they stocked up on to make a group donation to a food bank. Have
them load them directly into the back of a car or truck.
</P>
<P>
   RECOVERING
</P>
<P>
   XXXIII. Get ahead of the game and pick up the antacid at the
same time you buy the chili fixin's and hot salsa. The 7-Eleven
stores report sales of antacid increases 20 percent the day after
the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   XXXIV. Call in sick. While most of us fumble our way into the
office, about 6 percent opt for a longer post-game recovery time
and take the day off.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
