<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6339 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-ANGELS15-COX     01-14 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ANGELS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Angels' starts slow but potential's there
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a real hospital in Atlanta or other major cities, it wouldn't
be a shock to see mostly African-American doctors, administrators,
staff and patients.
</P>
<P>
   On a prime-time TV show, it's exotic, almost jarring, which of
course says a lot more about television than it does about black
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to ``City of Angels,'' the new medical drama from Steven
Bochco (``NYPD Blue,'' ``L.A. Law,'' ``Hill Street Blues'') that
carries the unfair burden of being the Great Black Hope of Prime
Time. CBS and Bochco already had the series in the works before the
NAACP charged the networks last year with ``a virtual whitewash.''
Now it's become TV's symbol of diversity, when what it really is is
a decent drama with potential.
</P>
<P>
   The fictional Angels of Mercy Hospital is the last place you
want to be in an emergency, or a non-emergency. A living patient is
shipped to the morgue. The medical director just got fired for
posing for photos with a corpse. Accreditation is a distant dream.
They can't even schedule a fire drill properly. The problem isn't
the staff, which is mostly dedicated and hard-working, but funding,
or the lack of it.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lillian Price (Vivica A. Fox) is the new medical director,
determined to get Angels accredited. She runs into Dr. Ben Turner
(Blair Underwood), a surgeon with whom she has a history, some
issues, and, we learn in Episode 2, still some sparks. Also regular
are the run-ins with Ron Harris (Michael Warren), the hospital's
CEO, who's a little too slick at the gamesmanship his job requires.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Edwin O'Malley (Robert Morse, one of the few
white faces), the seemingly avuncular chairman of the board of
supervisors, whose antics in the first couple of shows are puzzling
at best, and possibly sinister.
</P>
<P>
   Race is a subtext rather than a rallying cry on ``Angels,''
which is a smart move; ``Do the Right Thing'' may have been a great
film, but it wouldn't play as a weekly TV series designed to sell
Toyotas and Web portals.
</P>
<P>
   Bochco has wisely stocked his show with actors who aren't just
talented but are familiar friends. Underwood was Jonathan Rollins
on ``L.A. Law,'' Warren was Bobby Hill on ``Hill Street Blues,''
and Fox played Will Smith's girlfriend in the film ``Independence
Day.'' To his credit, Bochco is also using African-Americans behind
the camera, to write and direct.
</P>
<P>
   Any hospital show, no matter the color, has to cope with the
huge shadow of ``ER,'' and ``Angels'' feels dwarfed by that series'
show-off adrenalin and dizzying body count. Of course, this is CBS,
where things move a little more slowly, including, one hopes, any
urge to pull the plug if the ratings don't soar right off.
</P>
<P>
   That is, of course, the concern. There has never been a
majority-black network drama that has lasted more than one season.
(``Under One Roof,'' ``413 Hope Street'' and ``Paris,'' an early
cop show by Bochco starring James Earl Jones, are among the
commercial, though not critical, failures.) For reasons that have
prompted a lot of speculation, the white TV audience has embraced
black comedies more easily than black dramas. And there is anxiety
in the African-American community that if ``City of Angels''
doesn't score in the Nielsens _ meaning it has to attract a lot of
whites, who are 79 percent of the TV audience _ it will be a long,
long time before the next black drama.
</P>
<P>
   That anxiety is more than justified. It doesn't help that after
Sunday's premiere, ``Angels'' moves to 8 p.m. Wednesdays, a time
slot too early for the show's serious tone and Bochco's sometimes
wickedly tasteless sense of humor. ``City of Angels'' doesn't kick
off with the impact of a ``Hill Street'' or ``NYPD,'' but it
deserves to run its race without carrying so much baggage.
</P>
<P>
   ``City of Angels''
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Sunday on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Ignore the baggage, watch the show.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
