 For Release SATURDAY AMs, January 15, 2000  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-NUCLEAR (Moscow) _ Frustrated with its declining role in
the world, Vladimir V. Putin's Kremlin unveils a new security
doctrine that considerably broadens Moscow's authority to use
nuclear weapons. By Brian Whitmore. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   UN-TIMOR (New York) _ Hundreds of people were slaughtered after
East Timor voted in a UN-run referendum for independence from
Indonesia. But prospects are dim for East Timor to get an
international tribunal. By Joe Lauria.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-HEALTH (Londonderry, N.H.) _ It's almost primary day in
New Hampshire and the Republicans have maintained a near silence on
health care issues. By Anne E. Kornblut. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRADLEY (Manchester, N.H.) _ Bill Bradley seeks to
understand -- and address -- his relatively weak support among
women. By Jill Zuckman. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MOB-BODIES (Boston) _ The remains of two men and a woman are
unearthed by federal and state investigators after being directed
to the mob graveyard by a top lieutenant of fugitive crime boss
James ``Whitey'' Bulger. By Shelley Murphy. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-DRUG (Undated) _ The networks may have viewed the addition of
antidrug messages to prime-time programs as a harmless way to win
points in Washington. But the arrangement strikes critics as a
slide down the slipperiest of slopes. By Don Aucoin. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   TV-ANGELS (Undated) _ ``City of Angels,'' featuring an
inner-city hospital where race is not an issue, lacks in
originality. By Matthew Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FAA-PILOTS (Undated) _ Hoping to prevent aviation accidents,
President Clinton offers a program to protect airline
whistleblowers if they quickly report incidents. By Matthew Brelis.
450 words.
</P>
<P>
   RAYTHEON-MISSILE (Undated) _ Pentagon admits there were problems
during an anti-missile test last October, raising the stakes for a
planned test next week of Raytheon Co.'s ``exoatmospheric kill
vehicle.'' By Ross Kerber. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   AILING-HMO (Boston) _ Regulators are to name an investment
banking firm that will explore the sale of the near-bankrupt HMO,
Harvard Pilgrimn Health Care. By Steve Wilmsen. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-BELICHICK (New York) -- NFL concludes a hearing at which
ex-Jets coach Bill Belichick pleaded his wish that he be released
from his contract. By Nick Cafardo. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-VIKINGS (Earth City, Mo.) -- Lost in the tongue-in-cheek
hoopla of whether even the most powerful computers will be quick
enough to add up the points when the Vikings meet the Rams for the
NFC championship is the subject of Jeff George. By Michael Madden.
800 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   FBN-MIAMI-JAGUARS (Undated) _ The norm will not be the norm,
when the hometown Jaguars take on the revived Dolphins, kicking off
what is generally the league's best weekend of football each
season. By Will McDonough. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOX-RADIO-CITY (New York) _ The old building got a face lift and
now, for one night at least, it's in the facial rearrangement
business. By Ron Borges. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   MCDONOUGH-COLUMN (Undated) _ There are many important moments in
the painful history of the Red Sox that are monumental in our
memory, but never quite fully explained. By Will McDonough.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
