<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6342 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-KING-BOYCOTT-REMEMBER     01-14 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-BOYCOTT-REMEMBERED-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S MORE THAN JUST A HOLIDAY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this TIMELY ``one-shot'' commentary from The New York
Times Syndicate's NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE, contact sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax,
732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``k'' commentary and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By AKILAH MONIFA 
 c.2000 Akilah Monifa   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Martin Luther King Jr. Day is much more than a holiday to me.
</P>
<P>
   I am a 42-year-old African-American woman who grew up in
Huntsville, Ala. My parents strategized and marched with Dr. King.
I learned about civil disobedience and protests from them when I
was 4 years old. I heard them talk of taking part in sit-ins at
segregated lunch counters. And I remember them explaining to me why
we would not be buying new clothes from our town's segregated
stores during Easter because Dr. King had organized a boycott. The
logic was simple: If we couldn't shop at these stores by entering
the front door, then we wouldn't patronize them.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Easter clothes and accoutrements were important among
African-Americans in the South. It was a time when we put on our
finest new clothes _ and everything was new, from our underwear to
our gloves.
</P>
<P>
   It was a very big deal to join that boycott. In fact, our
strategy on that Easter Sunday in 1962 was to wear blue jeans to
church. Little black girls never wore pants to church in the '60s,
much less jeans. But it was a visible way to demonstrate our
displeasure with stores that discriminated against us.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. King knew this would be a hard sell in the black community,
but he also understood its significance.
</P>
<P>
   I never met Dr. King, but my father so vividly described the
meetings and organizing sessions involved in the boycott that in my
young mind I felt as though I had met the great man. Plus, in a lot
of black homes during the '60s three pictures hung on the walls:
those of Jesus Christ, John F. Kennedy and Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   My father, who was just three years younger than Dr. King, spoke
of him as both a good friend and a genius. Dr. King's oratory
skills were legendary, and I'm not simply referring to his ``I Have
a Dream'' speech. You had a chance to hear Dr. King preach, you
made a point of being there. His down-home preaching was so good
that it made you want to holler and fan yourself at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder what Dr. King, who would have been 71 this year, would
make of America in the year 2000. No doubt he would appreciate the
national holiday and all the streets named after him, but I imagine
he would not be impressed. Dr. King was a man of substance. Stamps,
holidays and street names were not in his master plan.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure he would be shocked to know that more than 30 years
after his death, African-Americans still experience discrimination,
despite state and federal legislation; shocked to learn that a
digital divide exists between white people and people of color.
That there are only five African-Americans and one Latino on the
boards of companies in Silicon Valley. That many cabs still will
not stop for African-American men, and that racial profiling
abounds.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure all this would sadden Dr. King, and he would question
whether it really was the year 2000 or the year 1950.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. King was an advocate for diversity and demanded an end to
discrimination. His ``dream'' has not been realized.
</P>
<P>
   These days, many people simply ``talk the talk'' rather than
``walk the walk'' when it comes to the diversity Dr. King hoped
for. Many of us spend the majority of our time with people who look
like us rather than with those who may reflect the diversity of
which we speak.
</P>
<P>
   So I will honor the anniversary of Dr. King's birth as I did in
the years before it became a federal holiday. I will shed tears
over the loss of a great man and a philosopher. I will rue the fact
that there are still so many people who know little about his life
and legacy. And I will remember that the best way to honor Dr. King
is by reading his speeches and making a commitment to ``walking the
walk'' of diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Actions do speak louder than words.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Akilah Monifa is a free-lance writer in Oakland, Calif.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
