<HEADER>
A6348 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-KING-FARRIS17-COX     01-14 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-FARRIS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    King's sister remembers tight-knit, loving family
 &HT;    EDs: EMBARGOED for Monday, Jan. 17
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Today, Christine King Farris will go to Ebenezer
Baptist Church and listen to the Vice President of the United
States talk about the significance of her brother's life. She'll
join others there in song and prayer and visits to Martin Luther
King Jr.'s tomb.
</P>
<P>
   Then she'll go home and think about him _ her way. ``He is not
an icon to me. Just my brother,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest of three children in a tight-knit, religious family
headed by ``Daddy'' and Alberta King, Farris is the only surviving
sibling of the family. She said that she and her two brothers,
Martin and A.D., were extremely close and although she was older,
the brothers were protective of her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin and I never had a fight, but he would fight A.D.,''
recalls Farris, who wrote the children's book, ``Martin Luther King
Jr.: His Life and Dream,'' in 1986. ``I remember one time, A.D. got
angry with me and was about to hit me. Martin got in the middle of
it and threatened to hit him with the telephone. One of those old
big telephones. A.D. stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Violence as a response would eventually disappear from Martin
King's life. The effectiveness of his use of nonviolent civil
disobedience for the cause of human rights led to the establishment
of a national holiday commemorated today in his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm appreciative of the fact that people are concerned enough
to want a holiday for him,'' Farris said. ``I want people to think
about Martin on this day because he was concerned about helping
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Farris' wood-paneled den is a shrine to her two favorite things
_ family and learning. Books are everywhere and a baby bed filled
with her granddaughter's toys sit in one corner of the room.
</P>
<P>
   A 1948 photo of her father in front of Ebenezer sits above the
sofa. Nearby is a photo taken of her and her brothers when they
were teen-agers. She notes that in the photo, she was taller than
both her brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She and her brothers were incredibly close,'' said Farris'
niece, Alveeda King, daughter of A.D. King. ``She misses her
brothers tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuously absent from the photos are pictures of Farris on
the front lines. She recalls only one instance when she was
photographed with her brother at a civil rights march, although she
rarely missed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``My role was support for Martin when he was out there. He had
to have our support and love,'' said Farris. ``So I was at every
march, except the March on Washington, because I was ill.''
</P>
<P>
   Even today, although she is the vice president and treasurer of
the King Center for Nonviolent Social Change, she remains in the
background, deferring most things relating to King to her
sister-in-law, Coretta Scott King, or his children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never taught to be out front. I do lots of things that
people don't know about and that is fine,'' Farris said. ``I don't
need the attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she prefers not to make news, the lifelong Atlantan has
seen her share of news and tragedy, with the deaths of both her
brothers and her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have strong faith in God,'' said Farris. ``For some reason,
this is all mine to face. I know I am in His hands.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same house she lives in now, Farris said she listened to
Chet Huntley tell America that her brother had been shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sewing and I had gone in the other room and I heard him
say `Dr. King had just been shot in Memphis,' '' said Farris.
``Then he said it was critical and I just screamed. I knew that was
it. When JFK died, he (King) said that is how he was going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, in July 1969, A.D. King accidentally drowned in a
swimming pool at his home. Then in June 1974, Alberta King was shot
and killed during a church service by a deranged 23-year-old man,
whom witnesses testified specifically targeted her as she played
``The Lord's Prayer'' on the church's new organ.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult when you think about it, so I try not to think
about it. I try to stay pre-occupied with other things,'' Farris
said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she stays busy with activities that would make her
parents and brothers proud, like working in the church,
volunteering and teaching, which she has done at Spelman for the
past 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``She always was very strong,'' said Alveeda King, a business
professor at Atlanta Metropolitan College and the national campaign
co-chair for Steve Forbes' presidential campaign. ``The younger
members of the family always turn to Aunt Chris for council or
advice.''
</P>
<P>
   As the world remembers her little brother today, Farris will
think about the last sermon he delivered in February 1968. In it,
he said he didn't want a long funeral with people standing up
talking about how great he was and that he won a Nobel Prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said remember him because he tried to give his life to
serve others. That he tried to love others,'' said Farris. ``That
is what we were brought up on. And when I start thinking back, I
think about what it would be like if he were here. How things would
be different.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
