<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6356 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-TV-COMPUTER-GAMES-2TA     01-14 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-COMPUTER-GAMES-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIZ SHOWS MAKE EVERY CONTESTANT A VIDEO GLADIATOR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JULIA CHAPLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When David Karraker, a computer games fanatic who works for the
Sega company in San Francisco, first tuned in to ``Who Wants to Be
a Millionaire'' and ``Greed'' last fall, what he noticed right away
was how similar they were to some of his favorite video games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire,'' the blockbuster quiz show that revived ABC, had
a circular glass stage raked by beams of light, while the host,
Regis Philbin, perched face to face with a single contestant
surrounded by a black void, like the gladiatorial arenas in games
like Virtua Fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greed,'' the me-too entry from Fox with a more sinister tone,
featured a set painted to look like stone blocks, reminiscent of
the torch-lighted medieval castles in games like Doom and Soul
Calibur.
</P>
<P>
   And when Philbin intoned his Yoda-like line, ``Are you confident
that's your final answer?'' _ suggesting a warrior guru, a stock
figure in fantasy games _ the case was sealed for Karraker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' said Karraker, 31, whose Sega job is in
public relations. ``Here was this fluffy, friendly person like
Regis hosting a show with extremely dark undercurrents that was
very similar to the video games I play. I thought, `This is
stranger than anything I've seen on network TV before.'''
</P>
<P>
   What he and other viewers who were raised on video games and
science fiction movies are noticing is how much new television game
show sets resemble computer games and special effects from films
like ``Star Wars'' and ``The Matrix'' and futuristic music videos
like TLC's ``No Scrubs.''
</P>
<P>
   The look of interactive computer games has come to that
stodgiest of television formats, the quiz show, and with it has
come an unexpected mirror of the anxiety felt by many Americans
over computer technology.
</P>
<P>
   As no television viewer can have escaped noticing (try though
one might), the programming phenomenon of last fall, when
``Millionaire'' ran 18 consecutive nights, has spread to the other
leading networks. Quiz shows consume more hours of weekly prime
time _ six and a half _ than at any point since the 1950s. They
have also spread to cable, where MTV's version, ``webRIOT,'' allows
viewers to participate via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning Lines,'' the latest network entry, which made its
debut on CBS last weekend, has a look and format described by Ron
Pearson, a comedian warming up the audience, as ``the Jetsons on
acid.'' Now, any game show with so much as a visible microphone
seems as archaic as an eight-track cassette.
</P>
<P>
   ``Action films with special effects and home video games like
Sony's Play-station have definitely influenced the look of these
new game shows,'' said Michael Davies, the executive producer of
``Millionaire,'' which now runs three nights a week. ``Whole
generations of people have grown up playing video games. The last
thing you want on prime time is something that looks outdated.''
</P>
<P>
   Game show staples from the ``Jeopardy!'' era, like catchy theme
songs and circus lights, are as passe as yesterday's fashions. The
new game show staging calls for music throughout the show, beating
like a heart when danger lurks and crescendoing for victory; black
backgrounds that resemble a galactic void; graphics that lie atop
one another as in a Windows computer program; and cockpitlike
chairs in front of computer screens.
</P>
<P>
   The ageless Dick Clark, who is now the host of ``Winning
Lines,'' which airs on Saturday nights, sounded amazed as he
explored his latest domain. ``Have you ever seen a set like that?''
he asked the audience in a pilot episode of the show. ``It's going
to be launched into outer space later on.''
</P>
<P>
   The producers of ``Winning Lines,'' a British import, like
``Millionaire,'' aimed to recreate the feel of an arcade video
game, particularly during the hectic final minutes, when a player
must defeat the Wonderwall to win as much as $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a black seat modeled after a video arcade chair, the
contestant holds a kind of joystick and maneuvers among three huge
video screens, shouting out the answers to questions in a race
against time.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Walmsley, 33, the English set designer responsible for both
``Millionaire'' and ``Winning Lines,'' said he was surprised when
he took a tour of the sets of ``Jeopardy!'' and ``Wheel of
Fortune'' while in Los Angeles recently, because they were so out
of date. ``They were still using video walls made out of plain
glass TV screens, instead of the flat plasma screens,'' he said.
``It was so '80s-looking.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout their history, game shows have held up a mirror to
the times. In the '50s, the set of ``What's My Line'' mimicked a
cozy suburban parlor, complete with seating area and pleated
drapes. Other shows spoke of the newness of television itself by
mimicking radio conventions like ``On the Air'' signs and isolation
booths.
</P>
<P>
   The most infamous of these shows, ``Twenty-One,'' which
precipitated a scandal over rigged questions, has just been revived
by NBC. Many elements of its vintage set remain intact, including
the isolation booths. (It is the only one of the new batch of
prime-time game shows not notably influenced by video games.)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In the late '60s and early '70s, psychedelia arrived on the sets
of shows like ``The Dating Game,'' with its bubble-shape lettering
and big plastic daisies. After the '70s, game-show ratings were
poor, and the no-frills set of ``Tic Tac Dough'' reflected the
lower budgets.
</P>
<P>
   But then came ``Millionaire,'' with its nerve-rattling music,
eerie blue lighting and space age metallic set. ``The set and
format is a look toward the next platform of programming, which is
a converged medium between the TV, telephone and the computer,''
Davies, its producer, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire'' embraces high-tech effects to heighten the
drama, which the new shows have emphasized over the mere answering
of questions. The show is shot almost entirely in close-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the contestants first walk out on the set, they're
terrified about falling through the glass floor or making too much
noise with their shoes on the metal,'' Davies said. ``They never
feel that comfortable, and here they are, ordinary people in a new
city, across from Regis Philbin, having to make the most important
decision of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Cuomo, the designer of ``Greed,'' noted that the overtones
of science fiction incorporated in his set, which was inspired in
part by the Starship Enterprise from ``Star Trek'' and by the
castle settings familiar from video combat games, contribute to a
sinister atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computer technology does represent a level of anxiety to the
middle generation,'' he said. ``It's like, `Do you really want your
credit card number out there in this void where people can steal
it?' There is a scary element. So computers and technology, or at
least the symbolism of them, can heighten the tension that's part
of the appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, MTV's game, ``webRIOT,'' which is pitched to a
younger audience, 12- to 24-year-olds, imparts a different vision
of technology. The colorful set was described by its producer,
David Salles, as having the ``user-friendly optimism of iMacs and
VW Bugs, rather than the foreboding hacker look of `Millionaire'
and `Greed.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our viewers don't have those same kinds of dark issues with
computers,'' Salles said.
</P>
<P>
   The four contestants on ``WebRIOT,'' shown daily at 4:30 p.m.,
are suspended in cartoonishly round pods and are referred to by
their screen names (as in, ``Vid-kitten, what's the answer?''). The
zany host, bullet-headed Ahmet Zappa, speaks remotely via a video
screen, which enlarges his image to four times life size.
</P>
<P>
   The audience, projected onto multiple screens, is also virtual.
The show goes further than any of the others in marrying life in
front of a computer screen to a television game show.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept for the show was that everyone lives in their own
private suspended reality now,'' said Brian Graden, MTV's head of
programming. ``You don't have conversations with people in the same
room. You communicate with people behind a screen via the Internet.
Players of computer games like Quake and Doom relate to each other
in an abstract space, and we want these kids to feel like MTV is an
extension of their community, much like the game worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   Which vision of computer technology, sunny or dark, exerts the
more powerful psychic hold on viewers just now? In a week in which
America Online, Pac Manlike, swallowed Time Warner, Karraker of
Sega made a case for the grimmer version, a view of everyday life
as mortal combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in this booming economy right now, where everyone is
reaching for that brass ring,'' he said. ``People read these
articles about kids making millions in IPOs. They're asking
themselves, `How do I get in on an Internet start-up?' There's a
desperate need to catch up, to have millions, and it's made us more
battle-oriented.''
</P>
</TEXT>
