<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6373 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CLINTON-PILOTS-0115-C     01-14 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PILOTS-0115-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    NEW PROGRAM LETS AIRLINE EMPLOYEES REPORT SAFETY CONCERNS
WITHOUT REPRISALS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox Newspapers 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Airline pilots, mechanics and flight crews will be
able to report their own errors and other safety concerns with no
fear of reprisals under a new program President Clinton announced
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, said Clinton, is to improve airline safety by creating
a new channel for employees to report on improper practices or
equipment problems without worrying about retaliation from their
companies or federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be encouraged to share their valuable insights about
doing the job more safely,'' said Clinton, and ``they will be freed
from the fear of being disciplined for admitting that something
went wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration will still have the right to
take action against airline employees who deliberately violate
regulations, use alcohol or drugs on the job or engage in criminal
activity.
</P>
<P>
   And, if an airline feels it is warranted, it could respond to an
incident report by issuing a letter of reprimand to an employee or
requiring additional training.
</P>
<P>
   But under the so-called Aviation Safety Action Program, or ASAP,
employees who file a written report on a specific incident within
24 hours of its occurrence would be otherwise protected against
disciplinary action. Fear of such action has been a deterrent to
open reporting in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a completely different way of looking at safety,''
Clinton told reporters during a brief announcement ceremony in the
ornate Roosevelt Room of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It requires business, labor and regulators to work together in
a completely different way _ as partners, not adversaries,'' said
Clinton. ``Everyone must focus on fixing problems, not fixing
blame.''
</P>
<P>
   The program is voluntary, at the discretion of each airline
company.
</P>
<P>
   FAA flight standards director Nick Lacey said the country's 18
major airline companies _ including Atlanta-based Delta Air Lines
Inc. _ and some cargo companies _ including Atlanta-based UPS _
have applied to participate. It will likely take several months for
the program to be up and running, he said, citing the need for
corporate and employee training.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is a moral imperative to have that exchange of
information going, where it concerns aviation safety,'' said Delta
president and chief executive officer Leo Mullin, who accompanied
Clinton at the White House ceremony. ``This is really a win for the
industry and for the general public.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the program, each airline would set up a three-person
committee, with a safety expert representing the company, its
employees and the FAA, to review incident reports. The review
committee would decide whether to recommend corrective action.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas-based American Airlines has operated its own ASAP plan,
in cooperation with the FAA, since June of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In that time American employees have filed some 18,000 incident
reports, according to the FAA. Many of these have resulted in
changes to operations, modifications of airport practices or even
the signs indicating how aircraft should move along runways or
taxiways.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots, mechanics and even flight attendants routinely encounter
glitches, mostly minor, in procedures employed during the course of
airline or airport operations. Equipment, also, doesn't always
function as smoothly as operators would like.
</P>
<P>
   Many such problems go unreported, however, unless they cause an
accident or near miss.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA has operated anonymous hotlines in the past to allow
airline employees to report safety concerns. And employees have
long had the option _ or, in the case of serious incidents, the
requirement _ of filing an incident report with the FAA.
</P>
<P>
   But voluntary incident reports are, by law, stripped of their
identification, to protect the airline and its employees from
punitive action. That sharply limits the FAA's ability to ferret
out additional information about the incident or to recommend
corrective action on all except the most blatant of problems.
</P>
<P>
   The ASAP program will help to remedy that, said Capt. Rhea
Nichols, a jumbo jet pilot with 30 years experience with a major
airline.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols said pilots will feel free to report incidents _ even if
they are at least partly to blame. And safety officials with the
airlines, labor unions or the FAA will be able to follow up, if
need be, to try to prevent such problems from occurring again.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can come back to you for additional information and
you'll still have immunity to help them solve problems before they
cause a disaster,'' said Nichols, of Naples, Fla. ``It's going to
increase the safety of the entire system.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the industry safety record is a good one, but not
good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Already there is less than one fatal crash for every 1 million
commercial flights,'' Clinton said. ``But we know we can do better
still. Any accident, any death in the air, is still one too many.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans can be reached by e-mail at:
bobdeans(at)coxnews.com).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
