<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6374 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TV-DRUG-BOS &LR;      01-14 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DRUG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALARM VOICED ON ANTIDRUG SCRIPT CHANGES AT US BEHEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As federal regulators squint at media mergers and Congress
clamors for a crackdown on TV sex and violence, the networks may
have viewed the addition of antidrug messages to prime-time
programs as a harmless way to win points in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But the arrangement with the White House _ under which the six
TV networks consulted on scripts with President Clinton's drug
policy office and reaped financial benefits by weaving antidrug
themes into shows _ strikes a variety of critics as a slide down
the slipperiest of slopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm horrified,'' said longtime TV activist Peggy Charren.
``With the government funding content, the government could stick
anything it damned well pleased in there. It's the institution of
free speech that suffers when this kind of thing happens.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's spokesman said Friday that the arrangement
does not ``dictate or infringe on any creative process,'' and said
the president considers it ``a very important and innovative'' way
to reduce drug use.
</P>
<P>
   But Charren and others, even as they said they agree with the
need to combat drugs, that when it comes to government involvement
with the content of TV programs, the networks should just say no.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are opening a Pandora's box with this,'' said TV Guide
columnist J. Max Robins. ``It is dangerous, because the history of
television is littered with examples where the government has tried
to influence news coverage, all sorts of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex McNeil, the author of ``Total Television,'' said that ``the
traditional demarcation line has been muddied.'' McNeil likened it
to a newspaper agreeing to run antidrug messages in news stories
and then gaining additional advertising space as a consequence.
</P>
<P>
   However, Lee Goldberg, executive producer of CBS's ``Martial
Law,'' said he feels so strongly about the evils of drugs that he
isn't bothered by the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Though he said he has not been asked to change a script by any
government agency, Goldberg said that ``I don't see a downside to
putting in a show the negative effects of heroin or cocaine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the government were putting a different message in, like
`You should sign up for military service, go join ROTC,' I could
see people getting up in arms,'' he added. ``But it's hard to get
in a lather about putting on antidrug messages.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the government's role on such entertainment programs
as NBC's ``ER,'' Fox's ``Beverly Hills 90210,'' and the WB's
``Smart Guy.'' The networks have insisted that they never
surrendered creative control of such shows to the government.
</P>
<P>
   However, the networks did allow the White House drug policy
office to review scripts on those and other shows and to suggest
ways they could accurately depict drug abuse. The networks entered
into a deal whereby programs containing antidrug content could be
used to reduce the number of public service announcements networks
are required by law to air. The freed-up ad time could then be sold
at higher rates.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement between the networks and the government, first
reported in the online magazine Salon, attracted wide media
attention. It was the No. 2 story on ABC's ``World News Tonight''
on Thursday, and stories appeared Friday in most major daily
newspapers. In addition, the arrangement was the subject of lively
debate on CNN's ``TalkBack Live.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on that program, White House drug czar Barry McCaffrey
insisted ``there is zero government approval on how the shows are
produced and run,'' adding that his office is ``not involved in the
decisions the creative community makes.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Fischoff, a professor of media psychology at California
State University in Los Angeles who formerly wrote for television,
suggested the eagerness to cooperate by the TV industry, which is
often at loggerheads with Washington, may be a preemptive act
designed to ward off federal laws or regulations governing other
aspects of program content.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have people breathing down their necks about sex and
violence,'' he said. ``They have fought tooth-and-nail on sex and
violence, but their money is not in drugs. They can give the drug
thing away. They draw lines elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts wondered if the recent spate of mergers and
acquisitions involving television networks played a role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to draw those direct kinds of lines, but the
networks are in businesses that are heavily regulated,'' said
Robins, of TV Guide. ``They want Washington on their side, they're
looking for relief with the FCC. It doesn't hurt them to work
hand-in-glove with the government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
