<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6376 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SUPERNOVA-FILM-REVIEW     01-14 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERNOVA-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUPERNOVA': A BUBBLE-HEADED MONSTER OF A MOVIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes are at the end of the review) 
(lh) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A funny thing happened to ``Supernova'' on its way to the
theaters. Its director abandoned ship and was replaced by a
phantom.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad that the director could not have been joined by the
stars, good actors like James Spader, Angela Bassett and Lou
Diamond Phillips, who are trapped aboard this vehicle in the
deepest reaches of outer space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supernova'' demonstrates that when a space adventure is
combined with a soap opera and sufficient scientific mumbo jumbo
about explosive ninth-dimensional matter encased in a
three-dimensional shell, sufficient critical mass is achieved to
create a bubble-headed monster of a movie.
</P>
<P>
   The director of record is the nonexistent Thomas Lee, a name
assigned after Walter Hill, whose directing credits include ``Hard
Times'' and ``48 Hours'' and whose producing credits include
``Aliens'' and ``Aliens 3,'' distanced himself from the project.
</P>
<P>
   Light on originality and low on suspense, though high on design
and special effects, ``Supernova'' belongs to the class of
futuristic space films that indicate that a tough, suspicious
customs officer with a tendency to bar imports at the door should
be part of every craft that explores the galaxy and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Asking its audience to wonder on the one hand whether its young
lovers will be allowed to breed and whether the chief medical
officer will warm to the advances of the new co-pilot,
``Supernova'' also poses a question about the future of Earth after
a villain from a supposedly abandoned moon comes aboard with some
unusual cargo and begins to renew acquaintance and foment evil.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest clone of the species that began with ``Alien'' in
1979, the craft in question is the medical rescue vessel
Nightingale 229, cruising space in the 22nd century while two of
its medical technicians, Yerzy and Danika (Phillips and Robin
Tunney) fornicate; the computer engineer, Benj (Wilson Cruz) plays
chess with his true love, the ship's computer, Sweetie (Vanessa
Marshall), and the captain (Robert Forster) works on his doctorate
in anthropology, an analysis of 20th-century television cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   New aboard ship is its co-pilot, Nick Vanzant (James Spader), a
recovering narcotics addict who is attracted to the chief medical
officer, Kaela Evers (Ms. Bassett), whose coolness toward him comes
from the heart hardened by Karl Larson, a long-ago lover who
suffered from a similar addiction.
</P>
<P>
   The plot thickens into overused sludge 12 days into the ship's
mission, when the Nightingale receives a distress signal from a
rogue moon in unmapped space 3,432 light years away.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, for most moviegoers, it's familiar territory.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SUPERNOVA'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Thomas Lee; written by David Campbell Wilson, based
on a story by William Malone and Daniel Chuba; director of
photography, Lloyd Ahern II; edited by Michael Schweitzer and
Melissa Kent; music by David Williams; production designer, Marek
Dobrowolski; produced by Ash R. Shah, Chuba and Jamie Dixon;
released by Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Pictures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: James Spader (Nick Vanzant), Angela Bassett (Kaela Evers),
Robert Forster (A.J. Marley), Lou Diamond Phillips (Yerzy
Penalosa), Vanessa Marshall (Sweetie), Peter Facinelli (Karl
Larson), Robin Tunney (Danika Lund) and Wilson Cruz (Benj
Sotomejor).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 91 minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Supernova'' is rated PG-13 (parents strongly cautioned). It
includes simulated sex, nudity, amputation, bloody violence and a
couple of words of familiar profanity and street language.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
