<HEADER>
A6388 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DP-CAMPS-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      01-14 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DP-CAMPS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFERENCE LOOKS BACK ON DPS, PEOPLE WHO WILLED THEMSELVES TO LOOK
FORWARD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, Austria, Poland, Fla., N.Y.)   By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Edmund Goldenberg looked up one spring
afternoon in 1945 and finally saw American soldiers, not Germans,
perched on tanks outside the Ebensee concentration camp in Austria,
he was a fleshless shadow of the vigorous young man he had been
before the war.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 feet 10 inches, he weighed 100 pounds, so weak and
emaciated he required a two-week hospital stay. Worse than the
physical pain was his unrelievable sorrow. His parents, Polish Jews
from Krakow, were dead, his father shot, his mother gassed. Of a
family of 300 uncles, aunts and cousins, only 26 emerged from the
war alive, he learned later.
</P>
<P>
   Yet within weeks, he was not only sheltered and regularly fed in
a refugee camp, but he was working again as a doctor, for which he
had been trained, ministering to other undernourished and heartsick
survivors of Ebensee in a makeshift hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``You resume the spirit for life,'' Goldenberg said. ``This is
biologically necessary. You have to start living or you perish. We
had people who emotionally or mentally perished.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Goldenberg, more than 230,000 European Jews who survived
the concentration camps, or hid out during the war or fled to the
Soviet Union, found themselves after the Allied victory shorn of
homes and families, with no country ready to take them. Along with
more than a million non-Jews uprooted by the war or fleeing
communist control in Eastern Europe, they became known as displaced
persons. For a period that lasted six years for many of them, the
Jewish refugees were housed in more than 90 camps in Germany and
Austria, sometimes, as in the Bergen-Belsen camp, in former German
military barracks near the grounds of a concentration camp.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in those crowded, jostling refugee camps, most of the
displaced people found the will to go on, to prepare themselves for
lives in the countries to which they would eventually be admitted.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the DP's, as they were called, is one that is
little remembered today, but it is a remarkable chapter of the
Holocaust era and is the subject of a three-day conference that
began here on Friday night: ``Life Reborn: Jewish Displaced Persons
1945-1951.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference at the Marriott Wardman Park Hotel, sponsored by
the U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum, has registered 840 people,
including onetime refugees who have not seen each other for half a
century, and scores of graying men and women who were born in the
camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people think that once you got liberated that was it,
you were free, you were happy,'' said Goldenberg, now 82 and still
practicing, among nursing home residents in Binghamton, N.Y. ``Not
so. You never forget it. The DP camp was a slow revolution of
faith. The DP camp was trying to re-establish our life, whatever
was left.''
</P>
<P>
   Testimony at the conference and the artifacts and photographs at
concurrent exhibits at the Holocaust museum and the B'nai B'rith
Klutznick National Jewish Museum will show that the displaced
people, while living on hardtack, Spam and other rations, were able
to recreate communities out of the shreds of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   They found lovers _ sometimes ill-fitting matches with whom they
shared little but horrible memories _ so they could establish
families to replace those they had lost. Among the displays is a
white wedding dress that Lily Friedman, a resident of
Bergen-Belsen, patched together out of a German airman's nylon
parachute and then passed along to 17 other women for their
weddings.
</P>
<P>
   On their own initiative the DPs set up schools and nursery
schools. In the Bergen-Belsen camp, where the grounds held the
corpses of more than 60,000 Jews, 2,000 children were born from
1945 through 1950.
</P>
<P>
   Relief agencies provided assistance and taught trades like
carpentry and tailoring. But the DP's refused to be passive and in
the chaotic economy of the time, many smuggled contraband
cigarettes and chocolate across porous Allied occupied zones to
earn money they would need on their journeys to new lands.
</P>
<P>
   Though many had yet to forgive God for what he had permitted to
happen, they held prayer services and Passover seders. From more
destitute Germans, they bought used cameras to photograph their new
children and porcelain figurines to add a touch of beauty to their
lives. Among compatriots who understood in their marrow the anguish
they had been through, they made friends that often substituted for
family.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about the Holocaust, the survivor is looked down
upon as a victim,'' said Rositta Ehrlich Kenigsberg of North Miami,
Fla., who was born in the Bindermichel camp in Austria. ``This is
the time when the survivors were in charge of their own fate. In
the aftermath of the Holocaust, to pick up all the pieces and bring
life into a world when they witnessed only death, is quite a great
act of faith.''
</P>
<P>
   The Holocaust museum features evidence of the craving to return
to a semblance of normal life, to reclaim personal and occupational
dignity. Goldenberg's wood stethoscope, the boxing gloves Abraham
Malnik used in camp matches, a child's fur coat made for Miriam
Levitt _ now a Scarsdale pediatrician _ by a father who wanted to
keep his daughter warm on the journey to America, a poster
advertising a performance by an operatic troupe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went from camp to camp and gave concerts to people who
didn't know what opera was,'' said Rena Berliner, who was able to
sing operatic and Yiddish songs after losing her entire family
except for her mother, who hid out with her. ``They were absolutely
enthralled, in seventh heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After losing everybody, people still had a will to live,''
said Mrs. Berliner, now a 74-year-old grandmother in Queens County,
N.Y. ``That doesn't mean I have forgotten. I live with it everyday
of my life. I think of my sister. I mourn my father. But life goes
on.''
</P>
<P>
   The camps for those displaced by the war were hardly idyllic,
especially in the early months. Some of the residents were penned
behind barbed wire and needed passes to leave, as though they had
committed crimes. In many cases, they were mixed in with the
Baltics, Poles and Hungarians who had helped the Germans round up
and slaughter Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. George S. Patton referred to ``the Jewish type of DP'' as a
``subhuman species.''
</P>
<P>
   The DP's also had excruciating waits for resettlement. For
political reasons, the British made it hard for them to get into
Palestine, and many in the U.S. Congress were reluctant to relax
immigration quotas if it meant taking in penniless Jewish families.
</P>
<P>
   The children who were born in the DP camps now speak of the era
as a heroic time, a sharp contrast to the degradation and
powerlessness their parents experienced during the war. Menachem Z.
Rosensaft's parents, Josef and Hadassah Bimko Rosensaft, were
leaders of Bergen-Belsen, drove hard bargains with the British
about their treatment of the refugees and made sure 100 war orphans
were settled in Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's remarkable because they were no longer willing to be a
victim for one moment more than necessary,'' said Rosensaft, a
Manhattan lawyer who was born in Bergen-Belsen in 1948 and is one
of the conference organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Dorit Mandelbaum, a Manhattan painter whose parents, Auschwitz
survivors, gave birth to her in the Landsberg camp near Munichin
1946, has a whimsically bittersweet way of looking back at her
family's refugee experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The DP camps,'' she said, ``were the last Jewish shtetls in
Europe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
