<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-THESOPRANOS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HBO'S `SOPRANOS' RETURNS AMID A CHORUS OF HYPE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by SOPRANOS-THE FAMILY) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The year is barely 2 weeks old, and already HBO's gangster saga
``The Sopranos'' is an early candidate for Hype of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the Entertainment Weekly and TV Guide cover stories
that make it a candidate _ those you expect. It's not the features
in magazines such as Vanity Fair and Mirabella _ you expect those,
too.
</P>
<P>
   But the ad in The New Yorker, with four of the esteemed
magazine's cartoonists contributing ``Sopranos-''themed cartoons _
that you don't expect.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the billboards, the Web site, the CD, and the
second-season premiere party that drew 1,800 guests _ including
Christopher Walken and Stephen King _ in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   All this for a show that has aired only 13 original episodes,
all of them months ago, on a pay-cable service that only 25 percent
of TV viewers subscribe to. HBO has spent a good part of this month
making a fuss again, airing back-to-back-to-back repeat episodes as
a refresher course leading up to ``The Sopranos''' second-season
premiere at 8 p.m. CST Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Which might leave the HBO-less hordes among us _ who include me
_ wondering what all the fuss is about. Fortunately, through the
magic of TV-savvy colleagues who do subscribe to HBO, I've been
able to take a crash course in ``The Sopranos''' first season, as
well as get a sneak peek at a few of the second season's new
episodes.
</P>
<P>
   And now I understand. And then again, I don't.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you don't subscribe to HBO, you probably know the basic
premise behind ``The Sopranos,'' at least if you care about TV.
Here's a quick primer: Tony Soprano (James Gandolfini), the brains
behind a New Jersey crime family, begins passing out from anxiety
attacks. So he reluctantly enlists the services of a psychiatrist
(Lorraine Bracco) who shares his ethnic heritage. This doesn't
necessarily sit well with Tony's colleagues, but when you get a
look at his life, you sympathize: His friends, his enemies, his
work and his family _ especially his manipulative mother (Nancy
Marchand) would be enough to send anyone into therapy.
</P>
<P>
   The show can be addictive, especially when viewed in several
episodes back-to-back. It can be tremendously funny _ my favorite
moment came when a topless dancer, having just overheard a bit of
bad news, says, ``I'll always remember where I was at this
moment,'' which happens to be a, er, ``gentleman's lounge'' called
the Bada-Bing Club.
</P>
<P>
   And it can be unpredictable _ its characters are volatile, and
often a scene will be so innocuous that it will lull you to
distraction, only to erupt in violence. It's also often lauded for
its authenticity _ HBO even runs a promo in which real-life crime
figures wonder whether the inspiration for ``The Sopranos'''
plotlines comes from an inside source.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was the best show of 1999, as both of Entertainment
Weekly's TV critics and many others called it, is up for debate. If
anything, it earns the honor by default, as former TV giants such
as ``ER'' and ``NYPD Blue'' begin to wheeze and critical faves such
as ``Homicide: Life on the Street'' vanish. Because ``The
Sopranos'' is not without its problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos'' is derivative, and gleefully honest about it,
boldly quoting ``The Godfather'' saga, ``GoodFellas'' and
``Scarface.'' But it's also derivative in ways you might miss: The
upper-class suburb where the Soprano family seems out of place,
calling to mind ``The Beverly Hillbillies''; Tony's frustrations
and longing for the old ways is reminiscent of Hank Hill of ``King
of the Hill.'' The show has a whiff of ``The Addams Family'' about
it as well, especially with Robert Iler's Pugsley-esque performance
as Tony's son. And like much of HBO's original programming, ``The
Sopranos'' has a little too much of a ``We're this sexy, violent
and foul-mouthed because we can be'' feel about it.
</P>
<P>
   The characters are what makes ``The Sopranos'' work, especially
Tony, whom Gandolfini portrays with sly smiles and menacing
authority, and his mother, played by ``Lou Grant's'' Marchand as
someone who would drive anyone up a wall _ but also with just
enough ambiguity to make you wonder if her actions are intentional.
Tony's Uncle Junior (Dominic Chianese), his rival for control of
the family, and his ambitious screw-up nephew Christopher (Michael
Imperioli) are also characters who keep you coming back, but that's
more because of Chianese's and Imperioli's performances than any
compelling plotlines or wildly original writing. Edie Falco, who
won an Emmy as Tony's frustrated wife, is also good, but her role
often requires her to react more than act and comes off a little
underwritten.
</P>
<P>
   The writing flaws could be a problem with the new season,
although it's difficult to tell from the handful of tapes that HBO
sent to the Star-Telegram. It begins beautifully, with a montage
set to Frank Sinatra's ``It Was a Very Good Year'' updating us on
all of the series' characters _ and with a key mystery from Season
One solved within minutes. But when Aida Turturro shows up as
Tony's mooch of a sister, who's possibly even more manipulative
than their mother, the series threatens to become a family saga of
the wrong kind.
</P>
<P>
   You can't judge a show's season by a couple of episodes, though,
and perhaps the writers have something more interesting in store
for the Turturro plotline. The series' potential for a quick
flameout looks high, however, thanks in large part to all the hype
surrounding it. It's often good, and if you already have HBO, it's
a reason to be glad. But if you don't have HBO, missing ``The
Sopranos'' is no reason for you to cry into your baked ziti.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 1843EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
