<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPSONSTURN10-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YES, `THE SIMPSONS' HAS BEEN TELLING US TO NOT HAVE A COW FOR A
DECADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC CELESTE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hit television show ``The Simpsons'' has celebrated its
10-year anniversary as one of the most irreverent ... (editor's
note: blah blah blah; who cares, let's get to the funny stuff) _
</P>
<P>
   OK, OK. But first I need to tell readers that ``The Simpsons,''
which began as a series of short animated skits in 1987 and had its
nonseries debut as a Christmas special in 1989, has become one of
America's most beloved (editor's note: How cliche; you stink, get
to the comedy) _
</P>
<P>
   Huh.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, from the first episode, where the opera the Simpsons go
see, ``Carmen,'' is advertised as ``Tonight Only in Russian,'' the
show has dazzled with its wit, insight ``editor's note: Move over;
you are so fired.''
</P>
<P>
   (Editor's note: Here are things about the show that made us
chuckle.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Quotes
</P>
<P>
   Marge's advice to Lisa:
</P>
<P>
   ``Take all your bad feelings and push them down, all the way
down, past your knees, until you're almost walking on them. And
then you'll fit, and you'll be invited to parties, and boys will
like you ... and happiness will follow.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Grampa on his medication:
</P>
<P>
   ``The pink ones keep you from screamin'.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Troy McClure's introduction to ``Fuzzy Bunny's Guide to You Know
What'':
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, I'm actor Troy McClure. You kids might remember me from
such educational films as `Lead Paint: Delicious but Deadly' and
`Here Comes the Metric System!'''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Homer's advice on fighting to Bart:
</P>
<P>
   ``First, you gotta shriek like a woman, and keep sobbing till he
turns away in disgust. That's when it's time to kick some back.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Homer on love:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ridiculous as this sounds, I would rather feel the sweet
breath of my beautiful wife on the back of my neck as I sleep than
stuff dollar bills into some stranger's G-string.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Bart on his grades:
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of this D-minus belongs to God.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Homer's advice to Lisa on how to get Ralph Wiggum to leave her
alone:
</P>
<P>
   ``Six simple words: I'm not gay, but I'll learn.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Grampa on why he didn't think it odd he was receiving checks for
``absolutely nothing'':
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured 'cause the Democrats were in power again.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Kent Brockman on the fake pope:
</P>
<P>
   ``Authorities say (he) can be recognized by his high-top
sneakers and his incredibly foul mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Homer on alcohol:
</P>
<P>
   ``The cause of _ and solution to _ all of life's problems.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Homer on a snack:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for something in an after-dinner burrito.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Marge during a lima bean harvest:
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got married, you promised me my harvesting days were
over.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Homer while reading ``Internet for Dummies'':
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, they have the Internet on computers now.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Fave characters (well-known)
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Burns (evil power-plant owner): while making his assistant,
Smithers, dance by threatening him with an electric cattle prod,
``Conga like you mean it! Please don't make me shock you.''
</P>
<P>
   Troy McClure (washed-up actor): ``As an actor, my eyeballs need
to look their whitest.''
</P>
<P>
   Krusty the Clown (hilarious clown): ``Would it really be worth
living in a world without television? I think the survivors would
envy the dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Edna Krabappel (fourth-grade teacher): ``I don't entertain much.
Usually it's just soup for one, salad for one, wine for three ...
.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent Brockman (local news anchor): on his secret to success,
human-interest stories _ ``They tug at the heart and fog the
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hibbert (wealthy family doctor): ``We don't believe fur is
murder, but paying for it sure is.''
</P>
<P>
   Moe Szyslak (charming bartender): ``When I get ahold of you, I'm
going to use your head for a bucket and paint my house with your
brains.''
</P>
<P>
   Professor Frink (Jerry Lewis-like scientist): ``Brace
yourselves, gentlemen. According to the gas chromatograph, the
secret ingredient (of a Flaming Moe drink) is ... love!? Who's been
screwing with this thing?'']
</P>
<P>
   Principal Skinner (school principal): ``Well, Edna, for a school
with no Asian kids, I think we put on a pretty darn good science
fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Groundskeeper Willie (Scottish janitor): as a substitute French
teacher, Willie says, ``Bonjour, you cheese-eatin' surrender
monkeys.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
