<HEADER>
A6396 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-DEBATES-COX     01-14 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush improving during debates
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES _ Six weeks and six debates ago, Gov. George W. Bush
looked like a back-of-the-classroom kid hiding from the teacher and
trying to say as little as possible when discovered.
</P>
<P>
   At that first debate in New Hampshire in early December, Bush,
smirkingly confident by nature, spoke only when spoken to and
rarely used all his allotted time in offering up stump-speech sound
bites as answers.
</P>
<P>
   But by last Monday's debate in Grand Rapids, Michigan, Bush was
more like the hyperactive kid the teacher has trouble controlling,
constantly looking for ways to get as much attention as possible in
a six-man egofest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm listening, George,'' candidate Steve Forbes said after
challenging Bush to ``pledge'' not ``hedge'' on an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Bush snapped back scoldingly. ``You're interrupting.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the GOP combatants head today to a TV studio here for
their seventh debate, political scientists around the country say
Bush has grown into the format.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, he looked like a scared schoolboy,'' said
University of Texas government professor Bruce Buchanan. ``He is,
at least, relaxed now. He has not deviated from his standard
pronouncements, but he seems more comfortable in his skin.''
</P>
<P>
   After drawing criticism for skipping some early presidential
debates, Bush (who had only one debate in each of his two
gubernatorial races) has become more willing to mix it up and run
the risk of popping off inappropriately. Sometimes the mouth takes
him where he might not have planned to go, such as last week's
promise to cut taxes, ``so help me God.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has shown a penchant for rambling in search of a precise
answer when a questioner injects a new topic. In Grand Rapids,
responding to a question about ``racial profiling'' by police, Bush
took a relatively long time to go a relatively short distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants racial profiling to take place in any state,'' he
began as he wound his way to the conclusion that ``This is a nation
where all people are created equal.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the occasional verbal walkabout, experts say Bush has
benefitted from the debates. On Friday, after a town-square
campaign swing in Glenwood, Iowa, Bush was asked what viewers may
have learned about him in the debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've learned I've got a couple of nice red ties,'' he
joked.
</P>
<P>
   Bush aide Karen Hughes said her boss' personality ``is showing
more and more each time'' he debates. The Bush personality includes
a wise-guy mode, in the more non-pejorative sense of the term. In
Michigan, the increasingly-famous Bush smirk showed up as an
involuntary sign that he didn't think much of a panelist's question
about the racist comments of Atlanta Braves pitcher John Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought for a minute you were going to bring up the Sosa
trade,'' Bush said dismissively, referring to another debate when
he joked that the biggest mistake he had made was approving the
Texas Rangers' trade of Sammy Sosa, who later became one of
baseball's greatest sluggers.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Linda Fowler of Dartmouth's Rockefeller Center for
Public Policy and Civic Leadership said Bush seems to have finally
hit on a package that works.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems more in control of what he is saying,'' she said.
``He is still giving a canned speech, but it doesn't sound quite so
canned.''
</P>
<P>
   Fowler gives Forbes the prize for ``staying on message'' and
credits Arizona Sen. John McCain for getting less ``fidgety.''
</P>
<P>
   University of Iowa political scientist Arthur Miller said Bush
has cleared the lowest of hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was so concerned that he was just going to fall on
his face and get up there and babble and not really have any
substance to him,'' said Miller. ``I think people have learned that
he didn't do that. On the other hand, I don't think he has really
risen above the other contenders who are on the stage with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman for top challengers McCain and Forbes say Bush has
improved since the first debate. Forbes aide Greg Mueller gives
Bush credit for looking ``a lot calmer.'' McCain spokesman Dan
Schnur said Bush has figured out the format.
</P>
<P>
   ``It begs the question of why his handlers were so reluctant to
let him debate early on,'' said Schnur, diagnosing a case of
``frontrunner-itis.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the debates have appeared on a patchwork of local
stations and cable, nobody has a clear handle on who has been
watching. A survey by the Annenberg Public Policy Center at the
University of Pennsylvania found that 38 percent of New Hampshire
respondents and 26 percent of those questioned in Iowa had watched
at least one debate. Nationwide, only 15 percent said they had
watched any.
</P>
<P>
   The closest thing to tradition says there are usually two major
debates in Iowa and two in New Hampshire. But in 1988, eventual
nominee Michael Dukakis participated in 21 during the primary
season.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a less-wired world then and few of the debates were
televised anywhere. Now, with the increase in cable outlets, almost
any debate can find a TV home.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
