<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6397 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-14 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PRESBYTERIAN'S ADVICE: LOOK FOR THE ELUSIVE PRESENCE OF GOD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt., Switzerland)   By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Pay attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words, coming from many people, would be a command, and
not necessarily a friendly one. But when spoken this week by
Frederick Buechner, a Presbyterian minister widely known as the
author of more than 30 works of fiction and non-fiction, they came
across as both advice and a statement of principle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pay attention to what happens to you,'' he said, in an
interview in New York this week. ``It's so easy not to do that, so
easy to go through life on auto-pilot.''
</P>
<P>
   Buechner (pronounced BEEK-ner) was responding to a question he
had just been asked: what does it mean to write from a religious
perspective?
</P>
<P>
   He was sitting in an office at the Episcopal Church Center, a
building housing the denomination's headquarters, where he was to
give a reading from his latest memoir, ``The Eyes of the Heart''
(HarperCollins, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   To write from that perspective, he said, does not mean
``pitching propaganda,'' as some people might fear. Instead, he
said, it means keeping one's eyes open for ``the elusive presence
of the holiness of God.''
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate, Buechner recalled an experience he had about two
decades ago, when one of his three daughters was ill and he was
feeling deeply anxious. He was sitting in his car by the roadside
in a Vermont town, he said, when another car swung into view and
sped past him. As he looked up, he caught sight of its license
plate, which spelled out the word ``Trust.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hadn't been paying attention, I wouldn't have noticed
it,'' Buechner said. ``Of all the words in the lexicon, that was
the one I needed to hear. Trust your daughter, trust yourself,
trust God.''
</P>
<P>
   Much later, after he had written about that epiphanic moment in
one of his books, he opened the door of his Vermont home to a
stranger who had come knocking. It was the driver of the passing
car, come to give Buechner his old license plate. The man worked in
a bank's trust office.
</P>
<P>
   Buechner is a tallish, slender man, with a high forehead and a
baritone voice. His historical novel ``Godric,'' about an early
English saint, was a finalist for a Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   His most recent book, from which he read aloud to the audience
at the Episcopal center, is an excursion through personal and
family memories, and a meditation on death as part of life. He
offers recollections of his friend the poet James Merrill, his
mother, his brother and others.
</P>
<P>
   But a central character is his long-dead maternal grandmother,
known in his family as ``Naya,'' who appears in the book's very
first sentence, when Buechner invites her into a conversation as he
sits in his study, a part of his house he calls the Magic Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   He asks her about death: ``You've already set sail. What can you
tell me about it?'' She responds that she considers it misleading
to speak of people as having passed away. ``It is the world that
passes away,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Buechner said he did not grow up in a
religious environment, which makes his journey an anomaly in his
family context. Moreover, he could point to no single conversion
experience.
</P>
<P>
   But there were formative moments, like the one in 1953, when he
was a young writer in Manhattan and often attending Madison Avenue
Presbyterian Church, to hear the preaching of the Rev. George
Buttrick.
</P>
<P>
   One Sunday, Buttrick used the news of Britain's coronation of
Queen Elizabeth II as a starting point from which to say that in
the Gospels, Jesus is in effect offered the crown of worldly rule
by Satan and rejects the temptation. Yet, Buttrick said (as
Buechner recalled), Jesus is continually crowned in the hearts of
believers, ``amidst confession, and tears and great laughter.'' The
phrase struck Buechner so deeply he can quote it verbatim half a
century later.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Eyes of the Heart,'' he recalls other encounters with
unexpected words. One occurred in Switzerland, where he and his
wife were visiting their grown daughter and her children. On a
family hike in the Alps, they came across a picturesque cowshed,
where a previous visitor had scrawled something. Buechner took a
closer look at the graffitti, wondering if it would be ``a Swiss
version of the crudities'' one sees in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But instead the words declared (in German), ``God is love and
life,'' a phrase that seemed, he writes, as ``serene and
transcendent as the snow-capped mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust says the crumpled green license plate that hangs in my
office,'' he writes in his memoir. ``Trust what? Trust that it is
worth scratching on the wall that God is Life and Love because, all
appearances to the contrary notwithstanding, it may be true. Trust
that if God is anywhere, God is here, which means there is no
telling where God may turn up next _ around what sudden bend of the
path if you happen to have your eyes and ears open, your wits about
you, in what odd small moments, almost too foolish to tell.''
</P>
</TEXT>
