<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES TO DECIDE BOY SCOUT BAN ON HOMOSEXUAL LEADERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Friday agreed to decide
whether the Boy Scouts have a constitutional right to bar
homosexuals from becoming troop leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The Boy Scouts of America, saying its goal is to impart moral
values to youngsters, argues that its First Amendment rights to
speak and associate freely would be stripped away if it were
required to hire a known homosexual to lead a group of boys.
</P>
<P>
   But James Dale, an assistant Scoutmaster who was fired after
disclosing his homosexuality, counters that the Boy Scouts have no
constitutional right to exclude gays and must abide by a New Jersey
law that bans job discrimination on the basis of sexual
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's highest court ruled in Dale's favor in August,
prompting the Scouts to appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The justices are expected to render their decision in the case,
Boy Scouts of America vs. Dale, by July.
</P>
<P>
   The Girl Scouts are not a party to this case.
</P>
<P>
   Under a policy the Boy Scouts have followed since at least 1978,
no boy or man can be admitted to Scouting, or remain a Scout or
leader, if he is an ``avowed homosexual.'' The policy regards
homosexuality as morally wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Dale had been in Scouting for 12 years, rising to the rank of
Eagle Scout and becoming an assistant scoutmaster in New Jersey. He
was fired in 1990 after he publicly declared while a student at
Rutgers University that he was gay. He served as co-president of
the school's Lesbian/Gay Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Dale then sued the Boy Scouts, alleging illegal discrimination.
The trial court, however, threw out his case, ruling that the
organization had a First Amendment right to express its views about
homosexuality by dismissing him.
</P>
<P>
   But the state Supreme Court resurrected Dale's lawsuit, saying
the New Jersey law barring the Scouts from firing gays did not
interfere with the group's right to speak out against
homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   The Scouts, in its successful request that the U.S. Supreme
Court hear its appeal, argued that its freedom to speak on moral
issues and advance that message through association ``involves
constitutional rights at the heart of our free society.''
</P>
<P>
   The organization, in its legal brief to the justices, conceded
that many people might consider its blanket exclusion of
homosexuals to be evil but argued that the Constitution protects
even unpopular views and their expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``These principles of freedom of speech and freedom of
association are essential to preserving what many call `civil
society' _ the network of private institutions, societies and
congregations between the individual and state that enable free
people to work together for common ends,'' wrote the Scout's
attorney, George Davidson of New York City. ``These ends may
include moral beliefs that are controversial in society at large.''
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate his point about freedom of association, Davidson
said no one would object if the Scouts rejected a Ku Klux Klansman
to be a scoutmaster because having such a leader would interfere
with the group's message of racial harmony.
</P>
<P>
   ``In analogous contexts, churches and synagogues have an
absolute right to choose their own ministers and rabbis; political
parties have the right to select their own leaders,'' the lawyer
added. ``Expressive associations enjoy a comparable protection to
select their leaders without governmental interference.''.
</P>
<P>
   Countering the Scouts, Dale's attorney urged the justices in
vain not to hear the group's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney, Evan Wolfson, argued that the Boy Scouts, despite
its purported message of morality, had no right to fire Dale simply
because he acknowledged his homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Organizations are free to fire people for what they advocate but
not for who they are, added Wolfson, a lawyer with the gay-rights
group Lambda Legal Defense and Educational Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``Treating a gay person's simple honesty and openness about his
or her identity as inherently disqualifying `advocacy' that removes
him or her from the protections of an anti-discrimination law _ let
alone inferring from such identity any particular viewpoint _
typifies the overbroad assumptions, stereotypical notions and
`sexual stereotyping'' that the Supreme Court has rejected as
illegal in prior civil-rights cases, Wolfson wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cannot be that Jews, Catholics, Puerto Ricans, lesbians and
gay men, or others whose identity may initially go unnoticed, shed
all protection _ or can have viewpoints or positions ascribed to
them and then used with impunity as the basis for discrimination _
the moment they identify themselves,'' the lawyer added.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson also argued that the Scout's purported stand against
homosexuality is belied by the group's appeal to all young men and
its welcoming as sponsors many religious, civic and corporate
groups that undoubtedly support the rights of homosexuals, Wolfson
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
