<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANHEIM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Manhiem to purchase competitor for $1 billion
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Manheim Auctions will pay $1 billion in cash to buy a competitor
in a deal that gives the Atlanta-based company nearly 40 percent of
the U.S. sites for auto auctions.
</P>
<P>
   Manheim is already the nation's largest auto auctioneer, with 67
sites in the United States. But the company will extend its reach
through the purchase of ADT Automotive, a unit of Tyco
International. It owns 28 sites.
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of ADT, Manheim will own 95 of the 260 auto
auction sites in the country. Many of ADT's sites represent new
markets for Manheim. Among them are Albuquerque, Honolulu and
Colorado Springs. Manheim also operates auto auctions in Canada and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``ADT is an excellent operator,'' said Hal Logan, Manheim's
senior vice president of marketing. ``It gives us a lot of new,
desirable locations.''
</P>
<P>
   Manheim is a unit of privately held Cox Enterprises, which also
owns the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Both auction companies sell used cars wholesale, primarily to
dealers, not consumers. The vehicles usually come from rental
fleets, manufacturers, financial companies or other dealers. ADT
does conduct some retail sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not very glamorous, but it's a very important part of the
business,'' said Sheldon Sandler, owner of Bel Air Partners, a
Princeton, N.J.-based adviser to auto dealers. ``Every dealer uses
these services either to find access to used cars they want to get
or to get rid of cars when they have too many.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, Manheim has been moving into the Internet. The
company owns a stake in AutoTrader.com, a leading consumer used-car
sales site with about 1.25 million listings. Manheim Online, which
provides wholesale listings and other services for dealers,
reported selling $625 million worth of cars last year. That's up
sharply from the $58 million it sold online three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect them to be an even more aggressive retail
marketer over the Internet,'' said Chris Denove, director of
consulting operations for J.D. Power &AMP; Associates in Agoura Hills,
Calif. ``They're becoming an increasingly vital link between buyers
and sellers of used vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   While growing rapidly, online sales represent a tiny part of
Manheim's overall business. The company's overall revenue was $1.4
billion. It sold 6.5 million cars at auction valued at $36 billion
in 1998. ADT sold 2.3 million cars in 1999. Tyco does not break out
sales figures for ADT.
</P>
<P>
   Tyco International is the world's largest manufacturer of
electrical and electronic components, including undersea
telecommunications systems. It is based in Hamilton, Bermuda, and
has projected sales of $26 billion for this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``ADT Automotive is an excellent business but one that does not
directly fit with our four key segments,'' said Dennis Kozlowski,
Tyco's chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Manheim owns three auto auctions in metro Atlanta, and ADT owns
Southern States auto auction in Newnan.
</P>
<P>
   The sale is subject to regulatory review. It will generate a
one-time gain of $300 million for Tyco, company officials said.
Tyco had acquired ADT Automotive in its 1997 purchase of ADT Ltd.,
the security systems maker. On Friday, Tyco International shares
rose 18 3/4 cents to $34.56 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
