<SLUG> BC-MLK-COKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    King Center set to award Coke, Winfrey
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tonight, when the King Center honors the Coca-Cola Co., it will
do so with J. Paul Austin in mind, not the recent controversy
embroiling the beverage company.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Ivester, chairman and CEO of the company, and Oprah
Winfrey will receive the King Center's ``Salute to Greatness''
awards.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Hill, co-chair of tonight's dinner and the former chairman
of the board of the King Center, said award recipients are chosen
based on their King-like works.
</P>
<P>
   But while Coke is being honored for what Hill and the Center say
are efforts to promote diversity, the company is being sued over
allegations of systematic discrimination against blacks in pay,
promotions and performance evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   Eight plaintiffs are seeking class action status to represent
more than 2,000 black, salaried employees in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs are current and former Coca-Cola employees.
</P>
<P>
   A federal suit was filed in April, and a decision on class
certification by the federal judge is still months away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ambassador Young (the dinner's other co-chair) and I decided
long ago that in 2000 Coke would be honored because of what J. Paul
Austin did,'' said Hill. ``This is a tribute to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill said that Austin, the former chairman and CEO of Coca-Cola,
played a huge moral, supportive and financial role during the early
planning stages of the King Center. ``The driving influence was the
unique partnership and contribution Austin provided Mrs. King,''
said Hill. ``And they have, until this suit, made enormous
contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill admitted that during recent meetings, the issue of the
lawsuit did come up, although there was never any discussion to
change anything.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he and Young also met with civil rights leaders to
discuss the Center's position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came up in a natural context with all of the publicity
involving the suit,'' said Hill. ``We are very sensitive to that.
But this selection was made before all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Coke and Winfrey will receive their awards at an 8 p.m. dinner
at the Hyatt Regency.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
