</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Retailing heavyweights on way to N.Y. for national show
 &HT;    By Renee DeGross
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Metro Atlanta retailers will be heading to New York
City next week to join counterparts from across the nation for the
industry's largest trade convention.
</P>
<P>
   Rich's Chairman and Chief Executive Arnie Orlick, Ahold USA
President and CEO Robert G. Tobin and Haverty Furniture Chairman
Rawson Haverty will be among the thousands of department store and
specialty retail executives dissecting the latest trends and issues
at the National Retail Federation's 89th annual convention and
exposition.
</P>
<P>
   They'll rub elbows with other such notables as Jay Walker,
founder of Priceline.com, and J. Daniel Nordstrom, a co-president
of Nordstrom. The convention will be held at the Jacob Javits
Convention Center from Sunday to Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the topics include how retailers are dealing with
technological advances that are transforming the industry. Orlick
will be on a panel discussing the strategic importance of fashion
accessories to retailers' bottom lines. Scarves, jewelry, purses
and other accessories typically bring in the highest gross margins
in store sales and play an important role in overall profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of technology companies will demonstrate the wares that
are often used behind the scenes in retailing. For instance,
Motorola plans to tout the importance of its two-way radios used
for security or customer service in such stores as the Gap and in
malls, including Underground Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
