<HEADER>
A6405 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DEBIT-CARD-HOLDS-NYTR     01-14 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBIT-CARD-HOLDS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBIT-CARD DRAWBACK: CASH PLACED ON HOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CAROL BENFELL   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press-Democrat   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Use of a debit card, a credit-card
look-alike that pulls money from your checking account, could leave
you with bouncing checks even though there is plenty of money in
your account.
</P>
<P>
   Without a card-holder's knowledge, some merchants who accept a
debit card can direct your bank or credit union to hold an amount
greater than the actual purchase from your checking or savings
account and block your use of the money for up to three days.
</P>
<P>
   This little-known practice, which is perfectly legal and is
sometimes called ``blocking,'' happens most often at the gas pump
but can occur whenever you run a debit card through a machine
before you know how much you'll be spending.
</P>
<P>
   Other instances include checking in at a hotel or taking out a
rental car, said Liz Tung, a spokeswoman for VISA, which operates
both credit-card and debit-card systems.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer agencies say they have not received complaints about
the practice, but bankers say customers sometimes complain when a
debit-card purchase has been declined. Many consumers will not
notice a hold placed on a debit card for a gas purchase because
they don't buy gas that often and their checking account balances
are high enough to cover the blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one reason for the lack of complaints may be that many
people don't know what is happening. The blocking policy is not
disclosed in the informational material that accompanies debit
cards, and bank statements don't record blocks.
</P>
<P>
   J. Anderson, 47, of Sebastopol learned the hard way during a
motorcycle tour of the Pacific Northwest last summer. Because a gas
tank on a motorcycle usually holds only enough to go 100 miles,
Anderson stopped four or five times in a single day on his trip
across Washington state. Each time, he used his debit card. That
night when he tried to pay a restaurant bill, the debit card was
rejected for lack of funds.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson knew his account had more than enough money to cover
his expenses, called his bank and complained. After more than an
hour on the phone, he was able to use the debit card to pay for the
meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really disconcerting,'' he said. ``Then the next day
when I went to Bainbridge Island to get gas, they rejected the card
again. I made another angry call that night, and the rest of the
way down the coast I didn't have a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank never satisfactorily explained the event, Anderson
said. It wasn't until he talked to fellow bikers who had had
similar experiences that he learned about the debit card hold.
``Then it made perfect sense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What happens in cases like these is that the card machines at
gas station pumps are programmed to seek pre-authorization before
the sale is made. So the pump sends an electronic message to the
bank asking if the buyer's account holds an arbitrary amount of
money pre-determined by the station owner. The amount is generally
large enough to cover the largest gasoline purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The block is used by merchants to ensure there is enough money
to pay the bill when the final amount is known, Tung said. No block
is used at grocery or retail stores, where the amount of purchase
is known at the time the card is used.
</P>
<P>
   But the practice of blocking can mean other debit-card purchases
may be rejected and, if your checking account is delicately
balanced, a check can bounce and you may be stuck with bounced
check charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all send a pre-authorization transaction, which comes to
the financial institution, and asks if the customer has the dollar
amount,'' explained Brad Hunter, vice president of Exchange Bank.
``Some will send $35, some $50, some $100, depending on their risk
management philosophy. Some will send a $1 message, basically
saying all they need to know is if this is a valid account.''
</P>
<P>
   When the pre-authorization is approved by the bank's electronic
circuitry, the customer can pump the gas.
</P>
<P>
   A similar hold occurs when you use a credit card to reserve a
hotel room. The hotel doesn't know what your final bill may be, or
how much you may run up in room service or meals or telephone
calls. So it blocks a large chunk of money on your credit card to
assure the final bill will be paid.
</P>
<P>
   Blocking usually doesn't make a difference with a credit card
because consumers generally have thousands of dollars more in
credit allowance than they have spent. For that reason, bankers
urge consumers to use credit cards, not debit cards, for lodging
and car rentals.
</P>
<P>
   With a gas purchase, the debit card hold is lifted when the bank
processes the final transaction amount by matching account numbers
on the pre-authorization message to those on the sale message,
Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the pump's programming, this process can be
automatic and happen immediately after the customer finishes
pumping or it can happen later, when the merchant clears his
machine, said Dennis DeCota, executive director of the California
Gas Station and Automotive Repair Association in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Stations of major gasoline brands have satellite disks that
allow the sale to be processed immediately and the hold lifted,
DeCota said. Older stations, off-brands or stations in rural areas
sometimes do not have that kind of technology and the sales may
clear more slowly.
</P>
<P>
   To protect customers from holds that could last for weeks, banks
automatically lift a hold after a few days even if the transaction
has not cleared, Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Exchange Bank lifts the hold after two days. Banks
on the VISA debit card system are required to lift it after three
days, said spokeswoman Tung.
</P>
<P>
   ``Debit cards work well most of the time, but they don't work
well for all people,'' Hunter said. ``I don't like the delayed
settlement aspect of it, there's not that much reason for it. It's
just the architecture of the processing systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Benfell writes for The Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press-Democrat,
which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
This article was distributed by The New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 1902EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
