<SLUG> BC-LEND-LEASE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lend Lease CEO to be baseed in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Tony Wilbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lend Lease Real Estate Investments will relocate only one
position to Atlanta this spring, but the move will be significant.
</P>
<P>
   The investment management company said Friday it hired Sheryl
Pressler to take over as CEO in March, and she will be based in
Atlanta. When she arrives in Atlanta, Lend Lease effectively will
end its practice of having dual headquarters in Atlanta and New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is, with Sheryl there _ the CEO _ and with the
other officers there, Atlanta really is the headquarters,'' said
Jonathan Miller, senior vice president of corporate communications.
</P>
<P>
   Currently chief investment officer for California Public
Employees Retirement System (CalPERS), Pressler said she needs to
be in Atlanta, where Lend Lease has the bulk of its U.S. employees.
``You got to be where your people are,'' she said. ``You can't be
an absentee leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Lend Lease is the largest adviser to pension funds in the United
States. It advises more than 500 pension funds and institutional
clients, and manages about $31 billion in real estate funds in the
United States. Its annual Emerging Trends reports are considered a
key prognosticator of the country's real estate market.
</P>
<P>
   CalPERS, the nation's largest public pension fund, has been a
client of Lend Lease and its predecessor since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Lend Lease employs 1,500 in 30 cities on five continents. When
Lend Lease completes its announced acquisition of five mortgage
business units of Amresco in March, it will have about 750
employees in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Lend Lease grew by acquiring Boston Financial.
</P>
<P>
   At CalPERS, Pressler led the restructuring of its $8 billion
portfolio, which includes office, apartment, warehouse, retail and
other space. When she replaces current Lend Lease Real Estate
Investments CEO Matthew Banks in March, Pressler will be one of the
few women to lead a national real estate company.
</P>
<P>
   Banks will remain in New York as chief executive of Lend Lease's
international operations. He said he will work with Pressler over
the next several months to ensure a smooth transition.
</P>
<P>
   Lend Lease Real Estate Investments was formed in 1997 when Lend
Lease Corp. of Australia acquired Equitable Real Estate Investment
Management of Atlanta and merged it with the Yarmouth Group.
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception, Lend Lease had claimed dual headquarters in
Atlanta and New York. ``Atlanta has been the center of our
operations for many years,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
