u e BC-DAVID-COPPERFIELD-NYT     01-14 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVID-COPPERFIELD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGIC MAN: A CONVERSATION WITH DAVID COPPERFIELD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BILL DeYOUNG   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Copperfield knows that people everywhere are trying to
unravel his latest trick: How did he make Claudia Schiffer
disappear? The master illusionist and the drop-dead gorgeous
supermodel were inseparable for six years. Maybe ``how'' isn't the
question; maybe it's ``why?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like every relationship,'' Copperfield sighs during a
telephone interview. ``We both had careers and dreams that took us
apart a lot. And like a million other couples, we're still really
good friends. She's a very, very nice person, I care about her
very, very much, and we're just doing our own things.''
</P>
<P>
   With that out of the way, Copperfield settles down to the
business at hand: Talking about his reputation as the greatest
magician since Houdini, and about the 2000 version of his touring
stage show.
</P>
<P>
   Copperfield, 44, whose real name is David Seth Kotkin, has been
a working prestidigitator since the age of 12. The native of
Metuchen, N.J., has built an empire around his talents, and is
currently one of the top 10 highest-paid entertainers in the world.
</P>
<P>
   He's very careful to make the distinction between illusion and
magic. ``I'm clearly an illusionist who does magic,'' Copperfield
says. ``The effect is magic. But I'm honest; I'm an illusionist.
I'm not claiming to have any supernatural powers _ I may have them,
but I'm not claiming to have them.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if I call myself an illusionist, then you know
everything's fair. I'm going to create illusions, and you're not
supposed to believe anything, but I'll try to make you believe it.
But you're not supposed to, and my truth is, it's all illusions.
I'm going to make them look like magic.''
</P>
<P>
   Copperfield became famous in the 1970s for his large-scale
illusions. He made the Statue of Liberty disappear, escaped from
Alcatraz, walked through the Great Wall of China and levitated
across the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Even his sleight-of-hand routines involve more than rabbits and
hats. He once destroyed and restored a priceless Honus Wagner
baseball card in the presence of its nervous owner, hockey great
Wayne Gretsky.
</P>
<P>
   Copperfield's shows are big, loud, showy affairs, with the star
surrounded by beautiful, scantily clad women (``We walk the line
very carefully,'' he says. ``We try not to go too far, but on TV
you can see stuff that's way more risque'').
</P>
<P>
   The show's production quality, he explains, ``is a Broadway
conceit. Or a movie musical. I love doing things that are very
grand in scale, because I'm kind of known for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I also love the intimate, `unplugged' section. Getting out
there and showing what I can do, without all the fluff and stuff,
you know? And I think that contrast is very good. There's a lot of
that in the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Television's recent run of ``Secrets Revealed'' programs, in
which illusions such as Copperfield's are explained in detail to
the audience, annoys him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been guessing my things for years. They get on the
Internet, they come up with theories, and some theories are better
than what I actually do,'' he says. ``Those shows, mostly, are just
guesses. They're not really how to do it.'' The Copperfield team
has developed ``four or five'' different ways to climax each
illusion, to throw off the party-poopers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are thousands of performing magicians out there who
don't have the resources to change the way they do an illusion.
These are people who are trying to feed their families, and it's
hurtful to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Before a recent performance in Turkey, a reporter printed, in
detail, exactly how one particular illusion was accomplished. ``It
was a huge scandal,'' Copperfield says. ``It wasn't a scandal for
us; it got us great publicity. We just kept the illusion and
changed the method.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was rooting for me. Because even though they're
curious to see how it works, they really don't want to know how it
works.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 1904EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6409 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-SEATTLE-WTO-CHIAPAS-N     01-14 1546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-WTO-CHIAPAS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 THE LEGACY of SEATTLE ... ITS LINKS to CHIAPAS  
 &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)  By JORGE G. CASTANEDA  
 c.2000 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was only six years ago that Subcomandante Marcos and his
masked Zapatista rebels rose up in Chiapas, Mexico, ostensibly
against NAFTA, or the North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   On the very eve the trade treaty became law, the army of peasant
guerillas marched into the plaza of San Cristobal de las Casas, in
Mexico, identifying themselves and declaring open war on the
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The free trade agreement is a death certificate for the Indian
peoples, which are expendable for the government of Carlos Salinas
de Gortari,'' Marcos said, catching the pro-NAFTA patriciate
off-guard.
</P>
<P>
   By now, of course, the insurgents and their revolutionary
movement leaders have tailored their demands to more modest aims,
hidden their dismally few weapons and essentially gone back into
the hills. As such, the Chiapas rebellion belongs more to Mexico's
history books than to its everyday political life. And an
assessment of its impact is more properly a historical exercise
than a political one.
</P>
<P>
   But part of the Zapatista rebellion's legacy lives on, if only
through its promise, in recent events in Seattle: the
demonstrations and riots during the Nov. 30-to-Dec. 3 World Trade
Organization meeting. Once again the protest was, at least in part,
about the enormous gap between the have-nots and the beneficiaries
of world ``free'' trade.
</P>
<P>
   There always was a missing party during the entire 1992-'93
NAFTA debate involving Mexico, the United States and Canada. The
latter two nations were aptly represented not merely by governments
and industry but also by social and political forces such as
grassroots activists, NGOs or non-govermental organizations, labor
unions and environmental groups. But where were their Mexican
counterparts?
</P>
<P>
   With a few exceptions _ a scattering of women's and human-rights
groups, a tiny band of intellectuals, occasionally Mayor Cardenas
of Mexico City and his Party of the Democratic Revolution _ the
civil society and political forces of Mexico did not participate in
the NAFTA debate.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe the reason for this absence was the fact that all
Mexican interests were totally identified with those of the former
Salinas administration and the business community. Why, even
environmentalists and maquiladora workers found themselves
``represented'' by the Salinas technocrats and plutocrats or the
Monterrey magnates.
</P>
<P>
   Others believe that the social silence and absence sprung from
the repressive remnants of the Mexican authoritarian political
system.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, there certainly were critics of the free-trade
treaty in Mexico. They supported, for example, the inclusion in
NAFTA of chapters on stringent protection for labor, environmental,
human and consumer rights, with real sanctions and teeth in them.
They also advocated transparent, expeditious and accessible
mechanisms for complaint and conflict resolution. Ironically, these
critics and their demands enjoyed far more support in Washington
than in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   That is, until Marcos and his troops burst forth upon the scene.
</P>
<P>
   As Tim Golden wrote in The New York Times on Jan. 9, 1994, ``In
timing their strike to NAFTA's implementation, the rebels took aim
at the official faith that by fixing their economic destiny to that
of wealthier nations, all Mexicans would be raised into a modernity
of more jobs ... and a fuller democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Now this was a strange occurrence, in certain ways, because one
might have imagined that the best way to accomplish, for example,
the unionization of more than 1 million maquiladora workers in
northern Mexico, given the difficulties of prying open the Mexican
labor movement, would be through international means. But it did
not happen at the time.
</P>
<P>
   And it did not really happen in Seattle either. All the
governments from the rich ``North'' and the poor ``South'' were at
the event. Every protester and his or her cousin from the United
States and Western Europe, it seemed, was also there, clamoring at
the convention center against corporate greed, global
commercialism, the rich-poor gap and so forth. But grassroots
organizers, non-governmental organizations, ``greens,'' labor
unions, consumer protection groups _ as well as women's-rights,
child-labor and student activists from the South were largely
absent.
</P>
<P>
   Partly this relates to cost and distance. For many, the plane
fare is too expensive; so are hotel rooms and accompanying travel
costs. But there are social factors too, such as the well-founded
fears of many Indonesian, Pakistani and Egyptian activists to
openly voice their complaints. Also a nationalistic reluctance in
many left-wing quarters of the ``South'' to acknowledge any
international alliances as totally kosher.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, what Seattle and other global venues (such as the 50th
anniversary World Bank celebration) have shown is quite instructive
_ for instance, that if Indonesian workers organizing for better
conditions in local sports-shoe factories are to find any allies,
it will be most likely among the up-scale consumers of Nike
footwear in New York, Chicago and Los Angeles _ though not
necessarily among the teen-agers in the projects and ghettoes.
</P>
<P>
   Or that if sweatshop workers in El Salvador fighting for their
basic rights are to have any chance of winning their struggles, it
will likely be thanks to consumers boycotting GAP jeans and
clothing in the United States. Or that if child-labor adversaries
in Pakistan and India are to find support, it will probably be from
groups that force governments to compel Pakistani or Hindu
importers to desist from employing children _ those under 14, at
least.
</P>
<P>
   Or that if indigenous groups in Chiapas, Ecuador or the Amazon,
or environmentalists in Mexico and Brazil, or fruit pickers in
Chile are to make any headway in their demands, it largely will be
as a result of alliances with consumer groups, ``greens,'' labor
unions and citizens' organizations in the ``North'' who, for their
own reasons, and with their own agendas, will bring their
burgeoning power to bear on the defects of the globalization
process.
</P>
<P>
   Capital has become fluid and terribly footloose today, mobile
and transient across state and continental borders. That, we are
told by economists and globalization boosters, is why any form of
national regulation, taxation, protection or ambition is hopelessly
condemned to irrelevance. However self-serving or plainly false
such an argument may be, it does contain a grain of truth, as well
as several positive implications.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, indeed, capital can move anywhere, and make it possible
to manufacture elegant leather goods or trendy clothes, exotic
fruits and cheap but sophisticated electronics. But there are only
a limited number of consumers of these items, and they are all
grouped together in 20-or-so nations. Moreover, these consumers are
linked by the same networks _ of advertisers, activists, Internet
servers and lifestyles; they belong to the same ``niches'' for
marketing purposes.
</P>
<P>
   In these countries, small, active and dedicated groups of
minorities can move mountains _ particularly if they are made up of
social strata with increasing leisure time, money to spend, causes
to back and '60s nostalgia and liberal ideals to nourish.
</P>
<P>
   At some point soon _ maybe at the next round of WTO talks _
those folks who were so notably absent from the Seattle summit will
show up. Perhaps they'll meet their U.S. and European counterparts
and begin to bridge the gaps between North and South in a way few
would have imagined just a few years ago _ for instance, the way in
the Seattle streets the protesting Teamsters allied with
environmentalist supporters of an international ban on the kinds of
tuna nets that pick up turtles.
</P>
<P>
   When that happens, the labor, consumer, environmental,
human-rights, gender and generational rules in international trade
treaties will begin to bite. Their advocates will no longer be
written off as misguided anti-trade protectionists or blind
isolationists.
</P>
<P>
   Those who want a more humanitarian, balanced and
environment-friendly type of free trade will perhaps become part of
the same globalized world that today's corporate beneficiaries are
so enthusiastically promoting.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jorge G. Castaneda, Latin America's leading political
scientist, is the author of the best-selling ``Companero: The Life
and Death of Che Guevara.'' Castaneda lives in New York and Mexico
City and teaches at New York University.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
