   (Center display)
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-TOURISM (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ Determined to
dispel the myths that surround it, South Africa has turned to
Madison Avenue. This month, the country makes its first major foray
into the world of international marketing with an $18 million
promotional campaign. Its emphasis is on enjoying South Africa's
exotic outdoor attractions and urbanity rather than experiencing
the opening of a door to a new multiracial democracy. By Henri E.
Cauvin.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 7:30 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Bottom right)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-BALLMER (Seattle) _ Steven A. Ballmer, who on Thursday
was named to succeed his longtime business partner and best friend,
Bill Gates, as Microsoft's chief executive, is known for his
fist-pounding, bellowing, bombastic style. Although some suspect it
is one of the most finely honed acts in the computer industry,
there is no disputing the passion he brings to his role as the
industry's supersalesman. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Bottom center)
</P>
<P>
   OIL-PRICES (Undated) _ The price of oil, which had been stuck in
a trading range since it popped above $27 a barrel once in
November, topped $28 a barrel Friday after an OPEC committee
recommended extending current production cuts beyond March's
expiration date. The surge pushed oil to its highest price since
the beginning of the Persian Gulf war, and also pulled up the
prices of home heating oil and gasoline. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
