<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6413 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV16-B     01-14 1335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV16-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILDING THE SUPERNETS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 16, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
 
(poetry style) 
We shall not cease from exploration 
And the end of all our exploring 
Will be to arrive where we started 
And know the place for the first time. 
T. S. Eliot, ``Little Gidding'' 
(end poetry style) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the news came over the radio Monday that AOL intended to
buy Time Warner, I couldn't help but think that something like
another big television network was in the process of creation.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's a super-duper kind of smart TV that AOL will offer. It
will propagate its signal mostly via fiber-optic cable and
satellite instead of broadcast waves in the atmosphere. It will
offer more kinds of products than simple programming: games,
software applications, e-mail, and all the rest. But what did the
new company really have that I wanted?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos.'' And I didn't want that very much.
</P>
<P>
   The new technology is full of stories like this one. Where there
was a Dow Jones broadtape in my office now there is a Bloomberg
terminal. Where there was a mail tray now there is a fax machine.
Where there had been typewriters now there are PCs and printers.
Downstairs, the linotypes are gone, and most of the colorful guys
who operated them. That's a real difference. Colorful designers
with Apple computers have taken their place.
</P>
<P>
   At home, instead of a phonograph there is a compact disc player.
Where there was a telephone there is a telephone, wireless,
perhaps, but still a telephone. There is a television and a VCR.
Where there was a radio by the bed, there's still a radio, and on
the front porch, a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   A few doors down from the once-busy magazine stand at the corner
is a video store. The movie theater across the street is thriving,
too, and the used-book store.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing that is really new in all this is the
Internet, with its distribution wizardry and all-but-free messaging
system. It is very new indeed. Whether it will be able to preserve
its singularity in an otherwise commercial world remains to be
seen.
</P>
<P>
   The really interesting aspect of the AOL-Time Warner story has
been the markets' reaction to the deal. In the first three days
after the deal was announced, AOL's shares fell 19 percent to as
low as $60 a share on Wednesday. By Friday it had regained a
little, to close at $63. There was an abiding sense of fragility
about the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The reason usually given was that ``momentum'' investors had
jumped off, recognizing that the nature of AOL's business had
changed. Indeed it has. A comparison of price earnings ratios shows
how differently the firms are valued by investors. AOL, one of the
few dot.coms to make money, is valued at something like 55 times
earnings, while Time Warner, which only recently returned to
profitability, had a multiple of about 14.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first time anyone had used high-priced dot.com
shares to buy a real operating business. The markets' reaction just
may have signalled the beginning of the end of the wacky Internet
stock bubble.
</P>
<P>
   Without Time Warner, AOL was just another pure play on hope,
like Yahoo and Amazon.com and other companies whose shares have
traded as high as 400 times their meager earnings. With Time
Warner, AOL is . . . well, just a new-fangled television network in
the making with a lot of extras bundled in and a media conglomerate
on the side. It is a much less magical proposition. To get some
perspective on the matter, I went back to see what George Gilder
was saying about the subject 10 years ago. For all his bombast,
Gilder is a shrewd and energetic technology reporter, who now sells
his newsletter (www.gildertech.com) for $295 a year and commands a
loyal following in several industries.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990 he wrote a little book called ``Life After Television:
The Coming Tranformation of Media and American Life.'' It was one
of those short-lived Whittle Communications books, with glossy ads
for Federal Express every few pages.
</P>
<P>
   Gilder then was concerned mainly with disparaging the boomlet
for high-definition TV _ widely supposed to be a great new Japanese
threat to US leadership in electronics. He sure got that one right.
His big bet was what he called the ``telecomputer'' _ a PC hooked
up to a new fiber optic highway of incredible efficiency. He was
right there, too.
</P>
<P>
   It was when Gilder came to industrial organization that he began
to lose me. He was convinced that the great capacity of fiber-optic
to carry signal _ its enormous bandwidth _ would spell the end to
monopolies, hierarchies and pyramids of all sorts.
</P>
<P>
   By changing the balance of power between the distributors and
creators of culture, he wrote, ``the telecomputer will forever
break the broadcast bottleneck. . . . The creator of a program on a
specialized subject _ from fly-fishing to quantum physics _ will be
able to reach with one video everyone in the United States, Europe
and Asia who shares the interest.'' Not a bad guesstimate of a
technological capability that came to fruition with the World Wide
Web!
</P>
<P>
   But Gilder foresaw in 1990 that this would spell the end of big
business _ at least the end of big communications business. It was
true, he allowed, that the mass-market magazines such as The
Saturday Evening Post and Life had yielded their position at the
pinnacle of national culture to the three great broadcast
television networks. But in the future there would be no more need
of such organizations. ``Appealing to a mass audience works only
when people cannot gratify their special interests,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, what's a nice distributor of culture like
AOL doing paying $165 billion or so for a mediocre producer of
culture like Time Warner? Futuristic Megadeal? Century of the
Internet? Or just a way for AOL to add another 30 million HBO
cable-TV subscribers to its list of 22 million AOL subscribers,
acquire Cable News Network, pick up Time Warner's extensive cable
holdings across the country, and add a grab-bag of movies, music
and magazines to its home-grown inventory of ``content.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL achieved its astonishing growth in the '90s by understanding
that consumers wanted a ``dashboard'' through which to connect to
an increasingly interconnected world. It described itself as
selling ``branded convenience in a box.'' Soon enough all the other
giant companies in the computer-Internet, infotainment, and
telecommunications industries will be following its example.
``Pipeowners'' and content providers will mix and mingle and sort
themselves out. Eventually a few new oligopolies will emerge.
</P>
<P>
   The next big battle, however, will be over telephony. With the
advent of Internet switching, no longer is there a need to meter
the service through giant central switching stations, when
decentralized routers and servers will do. The regional telephone
companies will fight hard _ and probably fail _ to maintain their
monopolies; they'll become parts of pipeline companies instead. At
that point, the great telecommunications restructuring that began
in 1982 with the breakup of the old AT&AMP;T will mostly be complete.
</P>
<P>
   How long before AOL restructures itself to look more like a
network, with news, entertainment, and services divisions, complete
with ``Chinese walls'' aimed at protecting. AOL chairman Steve
Case, 41, slowly will morph into a media mogul, on the order of
Bill Gates: more important in his day than Henry Luce, who founded
Time; more important than William Paley, who founded CBS. Others
will join him at the small top of a very big heap.
</P>
<P>
   The new Supernets will be important in the manufacture of
opinion _ but probably not as important as newspapers and magazines
that manage to preserve their respectability and independence.
People will still want their referees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
