<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN BOY STIRS MOUNTING POLITICAL BATTLE ON CAPITOL HILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers) (lh) 
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old Cuban boy who
survived his mother's ill-fated bid to reach U.S. shores, is
quickly becoming the center of attention on Capitol Hill as
lawmakers bicker over his fate, each side accusing the other of
injecting politics into the emotional controversy.
</P>
<P>
   While Elian's Cuban father demanded his son's return and federal
immigration authorities ordered it, GOP lawmakers and a few
Democrats argued for his remaining in Florida, citing Cuba's
communist rule. They've lavished gifts on Elian and trotted him
before the media. Their critics say he should be returned and
contend other nationalities are treated unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   A vote on U.S. citizenship for the boy could occur quickly once
Congress convenes later this month as the result of a push by
conservatives such as Jesse Helms, R-N.C., a longtime foe of Fidel
Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is almost inconceivable that a court in the United States
of America would conclude that it is in the best interests of a
6-year-old boy to be returned to a totalitarian government, which
will in essence tell the little boy what he can learn, what he can
think, what he can say, what he can become,'' said Sen. Connie
Mack, R-Fla., a chief citizenship backer.
</P>
<P>
   Another congressman subpoenaed the boy to testify before a
congressional panel to delay his ordered return to Cuba though
Elian is not expected to have to appear.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, many black lawmakers are beginning to complain of a
double standard. They point out that illegal Haitian immigrants are
routinely turned away from U.S. shores while illegal Cuban
immigrants are welcomed as heroes.
</P>
<P>
   And they question why Republicans who love talking about strong
families are intent on keeping a boy from his father and
grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something wrong with that,'' said Rep. Jim Clyburn,
D-S.C., chairman of the Congressional Black Caucus. ``That doesn't
sound like family values to me.''
</P>
<P>
   AT THE MOVIES
</P>
<P>
   Two thumbs down.
</P>
<P>
   That's the review from one tobacco executive about the movie
``The Insider,'' a thoroughly unflattering look at how the industry
makes and markets its cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were defamed,'' declared Nick Brookes, CEO of Brown &AMP;
Williamson Tobacco Corp. Speaking at the National Press Club,
Brookes said the movie wrongly suggested his company threatened a
whistle-blower who told ``60 Minutes'' that tobacco companies
manipulate their products to make them more addictive.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Brookes _ who has not seen the movie but
caught the previews _ allowed there are ``some fairly critically
acclaimed acting performances.'' But he concluded that the movie's
poor box-office showing demonstrated the American public doesn't
buy the ``premise'' of the film.
</P>
<P>
   GOING SOUTH
</P>
<P>
   They're talking about taxes in New Hampshire and farm policy in
Iowa, but expect some new themes once the presidential candidates
head South.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll probably see the social messages increase,'' said Dan
Hazelwood, a Republican consultant. ``You'll even see more social
messages from the Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   But more pressure appears to be on the GOP contenders. With the
South Carolina primary _ the gateway to the South _ set for Feb.
19, Republican candidates are being asked to weigh in on such
issues as the flying of the Confederate flag and abortion
restrictions. For conservative activists, a strong base in the
party in the South, these can be make-or-break issues.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, anti-abortion groups are already running ads,
saying that Arizona Sen. John McCain, who is running a strong
challenge to Texas Gov. George W. Bush, is not sufficiently
pro-life.
</P>
<P>
   ET TU, NEWTUS
</P>
<P>
   It had to hurt. Ex-Speaker Newt Gingrich was on television,
predicting Republicans were going to have trouble holding on to the
House this year unless the GOP presidential candidate wins in a
landslide. He wasn't putting any blame on his own political
missteps or his nasty divorce. No, it was strictly a numbers game.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I read the tea leaves right now, there are 21 Republicans
who announced that they're retiring or they're running for another
office,'' said Gingrich. ``There are only six Democrats who are
leaving at this stage. That's a terrific advantage. ... I believe
that Governor Bush or Senator McCain or someone is going to have to
win by a pretty decisive margin to keep the House Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats quickly pounced on the forecast, proclaiming that even
Gingrich has given up on the House GOP. Republicans were no doubt
happy they did not invite the ousted speaker to their recent
celebration marking five years of House control.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin are in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
