<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-$ADV17-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET FREEDOM RING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monda, Jan. 17, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a sunny spring day three decades ago, my kindergarten teacher
in Miami wrote a long word on the blackboard. She asked her class
of 5- and 6-year-olds to repeat it after her. It wasn't like the
words on our weekly spelling list; it took us several tries to get
out so many syllables.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ass-ass-in-ation,'' we chanted shakily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does anyone know what an assassination is?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Too young to wait for a school bus without supervision, we were
not too young to learn what a political killing was. It was April
5, 1968.
</P>
<P>
   I knew what an assassination was. Sort of. It had been explained
to me the night before in the rush of emotion that followed the
first reports that Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. had been gunned down
in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I didn't know who King was; I knew only that all the
grownups around me were in shock. My mother was sobbing; my father
tried to snap a picture of King from the television set.
</P>
<P>
   My mother tried to explain. She told me he was a great man, that
he was killed by white people for trying to free black people. But
there was little more she could say. She was in the throes of a
private grief. My classmates and I would learn that this public
tragedy would cause personal pain for a lot of us.
</P>
<P>
   A little less than 32 years later, we are left with a holiday, a
postage stamp, and a lot of history, not all of it true. Millions
will take today off with only a vague idea of what they are
commemorating. Among black kids who absorb much of their history
from hip-hop music, King is dismissed as an ``accommodationist''
who suffers in comparison to Malcolm X's forceful stand for black
power. Even among those who understand how absurd that is, the
unique moral force of King's crusade is fading.
</P>
<P>
   Please, let's all take a moment to remember what today is really
about. It marks more than one great man's birthday, it honors the
most successful, historically important people's political movement
America has ever seen. It's about the triumph _ the tragically
short-lived triumph _ of the idea that right could prevail, that
America could not only be challenged to live up to its cherished
ideals but could, to some degree, meet that challenge.
</P>
<P>
   King, and the anonymous thousands he led and inspired, put their
lives on the line for more than a decade to give flesh to a century
of empty promises of equal opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   As revolutionaries, ultimately they failed. Most revolutions
fail. King's tactics did not translate well to the North, where
civil rights issues were different, and where blacks often equated
nonviolence with weakness. Even before King died, the movement had
shattered, in terms of serving as a unifying force for black
America. In his genius, King recognized that the issues of voting
and public accommodation would be much more easily addressed than
the economic and social issues that would later prove so divisive _
and have remained so.
</P>
<P>
   We still have ``civil rights leaders'' _ but the movement
expired on that night in Memphis. Jesse Jackson and Al Sharpton
claim to lead black America, but whom they lead and where they are
leading them has never approached the clarity of King's grand
crusade.
</P>
<P>
   Recent years have not been kind to the King legacy. Lieutenants
have revealed his infidelities; his doctoral dissertation at Boston
University was the subject of an embarrassing plagiarism probe. His
children have faced charges of being mercenary keepers of the flame
after selling a piece of their father's legacy to corporate giant
Time-Warner. Absent from most contemporary civil rights debates,
they have spent years attempting to prove that James Earl Ray, long
ago convicted of King's murder, was part of a shady conspiracy
involving the Mafia, the US government, and, for all the sense
they've made, an army of flying saucers.
</P>
<P>
   King's message was that the path to freedom lies not only in the
Constitution but in the personal courage and dignity of each of us.
His challenge to us was to be true to our better selves. He
anticipated his death, but did not fear it; he made the movement
was his life, but understood it belonged to each person willing to
sacrifice for its ideals. In that belief he lives, and continues to
inspire.
</P>
<P>
   Let freedom ring.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Adrian Walker can be reached by e-mail at walker(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
