<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER DROUGHT THREATENS TEXAS FARMERS, RANCHERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas' third drought in four years is
devastating livestock producers, endangering crops and threatening
municipal water supplies, state officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   While assuring farmers and ranchers that state officials are
working diligently to address drought-related problems, Agriculture
Commissioner Susan Combs said the best solution can only come from
above.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it does not start raining soon, many areas of the state may
see no little or no spring planting,'' said Combs. ``The needed
moisture is not there.''
</P>
<P>
   Huge sections of the state had below-average rainfall last year,
and aside from one brief soggy spell, this year is looking like a
rerun with ``potentially devastating'' consequences, Combs said.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-five of the state's 254 counties have been declared
disaster areas and 13 more are seeking that status from the U.S.
Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of rain causes more than cracks in the dirt, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stock tanks are drying up in many counties. Some ranchers are
now hauling water or moving livestock to other pastures ... Forage
supplies are short. Grazing is limited in most areas,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 percent of the state's pastures are rated in poor or
very poor condition, she said, offering more telling statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state's overall reservoir storage capacity is the lowest
that it's been in 22 years at this time of year. In addition, 55
public water systems have already imposed voluntary or mandatory
water use restrictions to prevent outages. There are 115 counties
that have imposed an outdoor burning ban to prevent wildfires,''
Combs said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, San Antonio is the only sizable Texas city that has
warned of imposing water-use limitations. That city said it may
have to implement restrictions as early as March if relief isn't
felt.
</P>
<P>
   Citing estimates that the droughts in 1996 and 1998 cost the
state's farmers and ranchers $4 billion for lost income, blown away
soil and other repercussions, Combs enumerated steps her agency and
others have taken to address urgent drought woes.
</P>
<P>
   Among them:
</P>
<P>
   _ Federal authorities have been petitioned for financial aid and
expertise and for permission to allow grazing on protected lands.
</P>
<P>
   _ State officials have pleaded with bankers and their regulators
to be flexible with agribusiness borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   _ State transportation officials have been petitioned to allow
farmers and ranchers to mow and bail grasses along highway rights
of way.
</P>
<P>
   _ Agriculture officials in Colorado, Kansas, Mississippi,
Nebraska, New Mexico and Oklahoma have been asked to locate grazing
pastures and water resources for use by Texas ranchers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Texas is operating a toll-free ``hay hotline''
(1-877-429-1998) to help ranchers find food for their livestock.
</P>
<P>
   Longer-term solutions also are being sought, Combs said. They
include:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Stepping up brush control programs to help conserve water.
</P>
<P>
   _ Continuing a 25-year-old weather modification, or
``rain-making'' initiative.
</P>
<P>
   _ Expanding efforts to remove salt from brackish water to make
it drinkable.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pressing ahead with university research to improve drought and
heat tolerance of crops.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, ``unless we have a very substantial downpour, there is
no quick fix,'' Combs said.
</P>
<P>
   Additional information is available on the Internet at
www.agr.state.tx.us.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
