<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOPRANOS-THEFAMILY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE BIG HAPPY FAMILY _ AND THEN SOME
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies TV-THE SOPRANOS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Sopranos neophytes, we offer this guide to who's who.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Soprano (James Gandolfini): Head of a New Jersey crime
organization, specializing in ``solid waste management.'' Prone to
anxiety attacks and depression, though you'd never know it by the
authoritative way he handles colleagues and the ruthless way he
rids himself of rats within the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Livia Soprano (Nancy Marchand): Tony's extremely hard-to-please
mom, who at least implicitly allowed a hit on her son after he put
her in a nursing home _ er, retirement community. May have had a
stroke. May be suffering from Alzheimer's. May be such an
accomplished manipulator that she's using one or both of the
ailments as an act.
</P>
<P>
   Carmela Soprano (Edie Falco): Tony's wife, who's so sexually
frustrated that she had designs on a handsome young Catholic
priest. Typically suburban mom who wants the best for her family,
and is willing to ignore many, but not all, of Tony's
indiscretions. Often sweet-natured, but her patience only goes so
far.
</P>
<P>
   Janice Soprano (Aida Turturro): Tony's sister, a new arrival who
quickly begins kissing up to Mom. She's after something, but so
far, it's unclear what.
</P>
<P>
   Meadow Soprano (Jamie Lynn Sigler): Tony's smart, athletic,
attractive daughter, who's about to enter college and has pretty
much figured out what dad's real job is.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Soprano Jr., aka A.J. (Robert Iler): Tony's
not-so-bright son, who's entering puberty and has a tendency to say
the wrong thing at the wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   Corrado ``Uncle Junior'' Soprano (Dominic Chianese): Tony's
uncle and rival for control of the family. Spent most of the first
season believing that he was in control, even putting out a hit on
Tony when he discovered that Tony was seeing a psychiatrist.
Escaped Tony's revenge when he was thrown into prison.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Moltisanti (Michael Imperioli): Tony's
short-tempered, movie-loving nephew. Trying to figure out what to
do with his life: Become a mob capo, a music producer, a
screenwriter or a stockbroker? So far, he has screwed up all of his
endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   Adriana (Drea de Matteo): Christopher's girlfriend, who's
smarter than she acts but not as smart as she thinks. Now working
two jobs in an effort to fulfill her dream of becoming a rock-music
manager. Too bad she has such lousy taste in music. Often breaks up
with Christopher, only to inexplicably be back together with him
the next time you see her.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jennifer Melfi (Lorraine Bracco): Tony's annoyingly patient
psychiatrist, who still has her limits, especially when her
involvement with Tony endangers her life. Has her own issues, for
which she uses her own shrink.
</P>
<P>
   Richie Aprile (David Proval): The newest cast member _ he
doesn't show up till the third episode of the new season _ is the
brother of deceased mob boss Jackie Aprile. Already, he looks like
trouble for Tony. Wields a mean coffeepot; once had a fling with
Janice.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Where the story is now:
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the first season, things looked good for Tony _
his mother was incapacitated, his rival Uncle Junior in prison, his
family largely under control. Dr. Melfi, on the lam and fearing for
her life, has moved her practice to a cheap motel, and no longer
has Tony as a patient. Watch out for Tony's sister Janice and new
rival Richie to drive Tony back to the shrink.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
