<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6426 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SOPRANOS-INSIDE-VIEW-     01-14 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOPRANOS-INSIDE-VIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE-TIME WISE GUY RATES ANOTHER KIND OF MOB HIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tommy Del Giorno will be watching critically when the much-hyped
television mob series ``The Sopranos'' begins its second season on
HBO Sunday night at 9. ``I get a kick out of the show,'' said Del
Giorno, who has lived the mob life.
</P>
<P>
   Del Giorno, 59, who admitted in court to taking part in five mob
hits, is a former capo with the Scarfo mafia family led by Nicodemo
``Little Nicky'' Scarfo, who is currently serving a life sentence.
The family controlled mob operations in Philadelphia and southern
New Jersey during the 1980s and '90s. Del Giorno has been in
hiding, living under an assumed name since he turned informant and
entered a federal protection program in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Del Giorno was once a swaggering figure among colleagues with
nicknames like Faffy, Crow, Frankie Flowers, Pat the Cat, Chicken
Man, Crazy Phil, Tony Bananas and Nicky Whip. Like most real
mafiosi, he is a mob movie buff who worshipped Godfathers I and II,
hated III, loved ``Goodfellas'' but had contempt for recent comedy
efforts like ``Analyze This'' and ``Mickey Blue Eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   In telephone interviews this week, Del Giorno agreed to critique
``The Sopranos.'' He said that he admired much about the dramatic
narrative of the show, which, he said, ``tries to stay level about
the real mob life and still be entertaining.'' But as they say at
Hollywood script meetings, he had some notes:
</P>
<P>
   General characterization: ``One thing good, it makes people
realize these guys ain't that smart. `The Sopranos' shows how dumb
some of these guys really are. You know when you say somebody don't
have peripheral vision? Well, a lot of mob guys don't have any
peripheral thinking, if you know what I mean.''
</P>
<P>
   On motivation: ``There's not enough fear in the ranks. They
ain't afraid of none of their people. But in real life, there are
some guys in charge that you had to be very afraid of. Take Nicky
Scarfo. He'd turn on you in a minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Giorno had a lot to say about the characters:
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Malfi, Tony Soprano's psychiatrist, ``is a bit out in left
field. I never knew anybody in the mob that went to a shrink, not
even court-ordered.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Carmella, Tony's wife, who in an episode last year shared an
intimate dinner with her parish priest and confessor in the Soprano
home while Tony was away on business: ``She's realistic most of the
time, but the priest goes to the house? Come on! I mean, a mob
wife, she might go to church, but she don't bring the priest home
with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Tony's mother, Livia, who gave the nod to a set-up to have
her son whacked: ``Who the hell's going to kill their own kid? Get
out of here with the mother! Things like that are way out!''
</P>
<P>
   Of Uncle Junior, the passive, craven, publicity-shy Soprano
family boss, whose wardrobe trends toward Ban-Lon shirts and
Sansabelt slacks: ``He don't seem very real for a modern boss. Take
Nicky Scarfo. Scarfo always wanted his name in the paper. He got
mad when somebody else's name got in the paper. Now, Scarfo didn't
have no taste, but he would always dress up in expensive clothes.
He'd be in a restaurant and, like, there'd be six or seven of us at
the table. He'd talk real loud, start making sure people were
noticing he was there. He would curse, too, almost to a point where
you got embarrassed, because I didn't like the cursing. Mentally,
there was a guy probably should have seen one of them
psychiatrists, but of course he didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Giorno also had some thoughts about the context of the show:
``Except for the strip bar, nobody in `The Sopranos' seems to go to
a job. We didn't all have jobs, but some of us had businesses.
Sometimes we had numbers businesses and some guys had loan shark
(operations). Also, they seem to have money. A lot of guys in our
mob, let's say we had 80 guys, well 60 of them were always broke.''
</P>
<P>
   And he had suggestions for new episodes: ``You got to make them
a little more violent. Sometimes they let things go too far. They
let fresh guys get away with too much. Also, they have to bring in
more characters. If you look at it right now, basically you got
four mob guys besides the old uncle: the head guy, the two friends
and the young kid. I'm not counting the wife and mother. You got to
have characters start interacting with the mobs in New York. I
would put him (Tony) in charge and have that young kid get real
strong and give him a threat just like he gave the uncle a threat.
He has to have an enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the writers of ``The Sopranos'' are probably going
to want to create an informant who is relocated under a new
identity. Del Giorno, who knows of such things, says this will be
an opportunity to expand on one of the secrets to the show's
success _ the dramatic idea that the world outside can be even more
morally disillusioning than the violent, but codified mythology of
mob life.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the time I was in the mob, I never really wanted to kill
anybody. Out here in the legitimate world, there's 10 people I've
met that I would kill. These legitimate people are worse than mob
guys. They can do things and get away with it, and there's no
consequences. When you're in the mob, there's certain things you
can't say to people and get away with.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some mob guys that are really kind. Guys like Faffy
(Francis Iannarella Jr., a Scarfo capo convicted of murder), he's
got a nice heart. And Joey Punge (Joseph Pungitore, a Scarfo
soldier also in prison), he's got a good heart. They wouldn't hurt
people unless they're put in a position where they had to.''
</P>
<P>
   For Del Giorno, living in the legitimate world is a big
disappointment: ``You don't know how disappointed I am. You have
people out here that are supposed to be legitimate _ my God, they
wouldn't give you a drop of blood. They wouldn't give you air. I've
met legitimate people that if you gave them that kind of power over
life and death like Nicky Scarfo had, they'd kill a thousand
people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
