A6427 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-PEREZ-COX     01-14 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEREZ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A whirlwind tour for Perez: `Going, going, going ... '
 &HT;    By Joe Capozzi
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tony Perez returned to work at Pro Player Stadium on Thursday
for the first time as the newest inductee to the Baseball Hall of
Fame. And he arrived in style _ emerging from a stretch limousine
to find a battery of television cameras recording his every move.
</P>
<P>
   From there, it was off to a press conference. Then three hours
live on WQAM's Baseball with Boog radio show. A cocktail party with
the Florida Marlins tonight at the Coral Gables Hyatt. And finally,
Hall of Fame induction ceremonies on July 23.
</P>
<P>
   The whirlwind that hasn't stopped since he got the news Tuesday
that he had received baseball's highest honor. He was at home in
Puerto Rico when he got the call. Then the phones rang nonstop: Lee
May. Pete Rose. Sparky Anderson. Johnny Bench kept yelling into the
phone, which didn't leave Perez's ear until he left for the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, he was in New York City with Carlton Fisk for
the official presentation of the Hall's Class of 2000. The flight
from San Juan was delayed four hours. ``I didn't sleep much but I
didn't want to,'' Perez, 57, said. ``I was afraid I would wake up
and I would still be in Puerto Rico.''
</P>
<P>
   The special assistant to the general manager strolled into Pro
Player Stadium concourse to a hearty applause from about 100
Marlins employees and friends, including his former teammate George
Foster.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ask me how I feel the last two days? I don't care if I go
through a wall,'' Perez said. ``I'm still going and going and
going, like the rabbit, but it feels great.''
</P>
<P>
   It feels great because it's been a long time coming. Nine years,
which perhaps was meant to be for a player known more for his
clutch hitting with the Cincinnati Reds than for his 379 home runs
and 1,652 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son, Eduardo, was asked in Puerto Rico (how) it took me
nine years to get into the Hall,'' Perez recalled. ``He said,
'Well, it didn't surprise me because my dad came out with a big hit
in the ninth inning all the time. This time he did the same.'''
</P>
<P>
   As Perez stepped to thepodium, after a warm introduction General
Manager Dave Dombrowski, a wall of television monitors behind him
showed a 25-year-old Perez hitting a home run in the 15th inning to
win the 1967 All-Star Game for the NL. ``That was really my career
start,'' he would say later.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, his career start came at age 17, when he left his
native Cuba to play baseball in Puerto Rico. That's where he met
his wife, Pituka.
</P>
<P>
   Perez said Hall of Famer Frank Robinson is the player who
influenced his early baseball career and Pete Rose is another. ``I
hope one day the right people will do the right thing and he'll
make it in (the Hall).''
</P>
<P>
   There were other people, too: ``Bench. (Joe) Morgan. Rose.
(Cesar) Geronimo. (Dave) Concepcion _ I can name them all _ Lee
May. Bobby Tolan. They all helped me be what I am today.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he turned toward his wife. ``But Pituka, you helped the
most ... She is my inspiration. She is everything.''
</P>
<P>
   She was sure this day would come. It was in the numbers, she
said. ``(Son) Victor was born May 11 (1966). Eduardo was born Sept.
11 (1969). The home run he hit in the All-Star Game was July 11.
And Tuesday was Jan. 11. Everything good happened on the 11th.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
