<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEM ON A MUNICIPAL BOND PORTFOLIO  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Municipal Bonds, The Online Way &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Putting together a municipal bond portfolio has just become
easier, at least for online investors.
</P>
<P>
   With a click of some computer keys at its Walnut Creek, Calif.,
headquarters, eBondTrade.com, a new online muni bond trading site,
opened for business last Wednesday, offering individual investors
live price quotations, credit data and the ability to search a
large inventory to find the specific type of bond they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most efficient way that munis have ever been sold,''
said Richard W. Meister, the chief executive of eBondTrade.com, a
broker-dealer.
</P>
<P>
   The muni market has long been hobbled by a lack of transparency
_ individuals, institutions and even brokers often have little idea
of the exact market prices of bonds. To buy and sell them, they are
often at the mercy of brokerage firms' trading desks which
sometimes take a substantial cut of the price. And the time needed
to buy or sell a bond _ between placing an order and confirmation _
can be more than a half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole process is fairly inefficient,'' said Meister, a
former managing director of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.. ``There hasn't
been much change.''
</P>
<P>
   EBondTrade has an inventory of more than $75 million of bonds,
all rated A or higher. Individuals, brokers and institutions can
gain access to the site, www.ebondtrade.com, and search the
inventory after registering. Aside from bid and offer prices, the
site has links that connect users to credit reports provided by
Fitch IBCA for different bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Gruye, president of eBondTrade, says it is in talks to
sign up other credit rating agencies, including Moody's Investor
Service.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum trade is for a face value amount of $25,000, typical
for a round lot of munis. Trades are completed in as little 30
seconds, with a brokerage account credited within three business
days.
</P>
<P>
   The service has the venture-capital backing of Philip F.
Anschutz, the Denver billionaire, as well as Chase Capital Partners
and Access Technology Partners. But what does Meister think about
starting his service after a year in which the Lehman Brothers
20-year municipal bond index lost 4.67 percent?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to bring investors back to the muni markets,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Richard Teitelbaum
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
