<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OFFERS PROTECTION TO AVIATION WHISTLEBLOWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hoping to prevent aviation accidents before they occur,
President Clinton Friday unveiled a program designed to protect
airline pilots and mechanics from punishment if they quickly report
incidents _ such as taxiing onto an active runway or flying at too
high an altitude _ that could lead to catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   By using the so-called Aviation Safety Action Program, officials
hope to improve areas such as flight operations, airport signage,
pilot and mechanic training by learning about issues early on and
jointly resolving problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a completely different way of looking at safety,''
Clinton said. ``It requires business, labor and regulators to work
together in a completely different way _ as partners, not
adversaries. Everyone must focus on fixing problems, not fixing
blame.''
</P>
<P>
   The program grew out of a test at US Airways and was formally
adopted by American Airlines five years ago. It allows pilots and
mechanics to report an event to the company, a mistake they may
have made, and do it in a climate without punishment.
</P>
<P>
   The reporting process also involves the employee's union and the
FAA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The incentive upon the employee to do this is that there is no
threat that the company will come back and discipline the employee
and even less threat of regulatory action.'' said L. Nicholas
Lacey, director of the FAA's office of flight standards. The ASAP
program does not cover issues resulting from susbtance abuse,
alcohol, possible criminal acts, or willful violations.
</P>
<P>
   Under the American Airlines program, some 18,000 reports were
generated in a four-year period and improvements were made in
preflight checklists, airport signage and pilot training.
</P>
<P>
   When American extended the program to mechanics and dispatchers
``they improved equipment manuals and maintenace procedures,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   FAA officials said 18 airlines _ virtually all the major US
airlines, many commuter airlines and cargo companies have expressed
interest in adopting programs.
</P>
<P>
   ASAP is a critical part in the Clinton Administration's goal of
reducing aviation accidents by 80 percent by the year 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Another program, known as Flight Operational Quality Assurance,
uses information taken from flight data recorders on routine
flights to track potential problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the combination of human collected data from ASAP and
real recordings of what was experienced by an aircraft in FOQA will
significantly impact on how aircraft are designed, how we train
flight crews, and how we set up flight procedures,'' said Lacey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
