<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6439 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-RADIO-CITY-BOS &LR;      01-14 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-RADIO-CITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MUSIC FOR AN OLD BUILDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The old building got a face lift and now, for one
night at least, it's in the facial rearrangement business.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night Radio City Music Hall will play host to its first
professional fight card when undisputed light heavyweight champion
Roy Jones Jr. is led down the building's famous circular staircase
by a troop of Rockettes and into the ring to meet challenger David
Telesco. When he gets there, it will be a crowning moment for a
landmark whose founder probably never thought the kind of
entertainment Jones provides would grace the stage he had built 67
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Radio City was the world's largest indoor theatre when it opened
Dec. 27, 1932, and for years it was one of the world's
entertainment showcases. But like most things, the building grew
old, hurt by age and inattention, until Cablevision signed a
20-year lease last year and poured $70 million into restoring it,
as it was in the days when Roxy Rothafel ruled an entertainment
palace the New York Herald Tribune called at its opening ``the most
remarkable auditorium ever built.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a building that had housed many things, but never a
boxing match. That's a trend that would have continued were it not
for the NBA's schedule-makers and Jones's willingness to ignore an
extra million dollars for a chance to make a little history.
</P>
<P>
   Had the New York Knicks not been scheduled to play the Charlotte
Hornets Saturday night at Madison Square Garden, Jones would be
facing Telesco in a building that used to be called ``the Mecca of
Boxing,'' but is now considerably less despite its recent comeback
under the direction of boxing director Kevin Wynne.
</P>
<P>
   Months ago, executives from HBO and Madison Square Garden sat in
a dining room at Time Warner Inc.'s offices and batted about places
to host the fight. The first suggestion was The Theatre at Madison
Square Garden, but Jones had already worked there and had no
interest in a repeat performance.
</P>
<P>
   HBO executives Seth Abraham and Lou DiBella then suggested going
to the legendary Apollo Theatre in Harlem, an idea that has been
floated before without any luck. About that time, Wynne voiced an
idea discussed before but never really thought possible. He
suggested to Jones's promoter, Murad Muhammad, that perhaps Radio
City might work.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the bombastic entrepreneur, Muhammad jumped on history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been kicking around the idea of possibly trying to put a
fight into Radio City, but the circumstances were never right,''
said Wynne, who has brought back major boxing to the Garden,
reviving the place as a boxing palace and prize fighting as a
viable sport in New York. ``Big names want such huge site fees that
we couldn't afford to do it in a 5,900-seat house, but I threw it
out to Murad and he asked if anyone had ever fought there before.
When I told him no, he said, `Fantastic. We'll do it. Roy will do
it to be a part of history.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy really made this happen. He was willing to take less money
than he could get from a casino (a reported $1 million less than
the Grand Casino in Biloxi, Miss., was willing to put up) to be the
first champion in history to defend his title there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few fighters today have enough fan appeal to fill 16,000
seats. And even if they do, there are even fewer opponents who are
compelling enough to bring people out en masse. But because of
Roy's cooperation, we feel we can make this unique enough to charge
enough to make some money and put on a show that will make
history.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of entertainment history has been made at Radio City but
the building had taken on the battered appearance of an old
fighter, still possessing some grace but frayed around the edges.
</P>
<P>
   Things were different in the '30s. More ornate work was done on
buildings. They weren't mere blocks of cement, but featured
limestone exteriors and intricate woodworking, all of which the
renovation project stayed true to. Care was taken to make it look
as much like the original hall as possible. Additional millions
were spent to re-create the carpeting that was down the night the
place opened. Hours of research and meticulous workmanship went
into finding examples of original wallpaper and paint colors and
reproducing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had become a dilapidated place,'' said Dan Schoenberg, who
now works in public relations for the Knicks but was serving in a
similar capacity at Radio City during the remodeling and the grand
opening Oct. 4. ``It took them three weeks just to get the
scaffoldings up in the place before the work began.''
</P>
<P>
   It took six months to restore the famous Fountain of Youth mural
with 20 people working on it, 1 square foot at a time. More than
750 gallons of paint were needed for the auditorium's proscenium
ceiling and 675,000 sheets of metal leaf were used on the ceiling
of the Grand Foyer, promenades, and the undersides of the
mezzanines. Cablevision even brought in a representative of the
American Seating Corp., which was used for the original seat design
in 1932, to help ensure accuracy in the work that was done on the
carpets, wallpaper, light fixtures, and seating.
</P>
<P>
   When the project was completed, a huge bash, featuring Billy
Crystal, Liza Minnelli, Sting, Mary J. Blige, and, of course, the
Rockettes, was held. Three months later, arguably the world's best
fighter will be brought through Radio City's doors to defend his
title against a guy who can punch with the kind of power that
upsets are made of.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean Telesco will pull one off, but it does mean
Radio City is getting the kind of boxing event a place with its
history deserves. It's getting a soldout gala, with 5,700 seats
filled, many by people more interested in the building and the
oddity of boxers being inside it.
</P>
<P>
   But regardless of the reason, they will be there because Jones
agreed to show up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Murad said Roy would do this, I was skeptical,'' Wynne
said. ``He said he wasn't the prototypical athlete only interested
in making money, and his words were borne out. Roy proved he's an
athlete not driven by the dollar. He wants to make what he's worth,
but he also had the vision to see fighting here was a way to set
himself apart. He's looking for a place in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people will be floored to see this building. I
promised them it would be breathtaking and when they first saw it
they were speechless.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
