<HEADLINE>
OPEC MOVE LIFTS OIL PRICES TO HIGHEST RATE IN 9 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The price of oil, which had been stuck in a trading range since
it popped above $27 a barrel once in November, topped $28 a barrel
Friday after an OPEC committee recommended extending current
production cuts beyond the March expiration date.
</P>
<P>
   The surge, which pushed oil to its highest price since the
beginning of the Persian Gulf war nine years ago, also pulled up
the prices of home heating oil and gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Some oil analysts had predicted that the production cuts would
be extended,. but this is the first formal move by the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries to do so. And although the
announcement did not say how long the extension would be, it was
tougher than some analysts expected.
</P>
<P>
   The length of the extension will be decided by a full meeting of
OPEC members in March. But the talk leading up to the meeting had
been of an extension of at least six months. The recommendation for
the extension was made by OPEC's Ministerial Monitoring Committee,
which reviews how closely member countries have adhered to the
production cutbacks. The committee met in Vienna, Austria.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this strong a statement with a consensus was
expected,'' said Frederick P. Leuffer, senior energy analyst at
Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. ``If they do what they say, my model says we
will all be waiting on gas lines this summer.'' He also said that
the price of oil should easily pass $30 a barrel now if the
agreement holds.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for $30-plus oil, he said, is that crude oil and
product inventories are now the lowest they have been since the end
of 1997 and would drain to very tight levels if OPEC continues
holding back production at the current rate of 4.3 million barrels
a day.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Leuffer said, OPEC has backed off production cuts
when oil inventories got low. But he said this statement makes the
group sound much more determined than it has been previously.
Still, he said that once the price spiked up, OPEC would restore
some production and the price of oil would fall later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Although American oil inventories are low, the statement issued
after the Vienna meeting said that OPEC officials think that
overall world inventories are too high. This is probably because
the price rise of 112 percent last year was not holding. From the
$27.07 high in November, the oil price had fallen 10.5 percent to
$24.22 last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In light of the continuing market volatility and the remaining
high stock levels, all those present at the meeting agreed to
strongly recommend the extension of the current agreement,'' said
Fernando Garay, an OPEC spokesman, according to Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   In trading Friday on the New York Mercantile Exchange, the price
of oil for February delivery rose $1.33, or 5 percent, to $28.02 a
barrel. The price of the near-term home heating oil futures
contract rose 4.53 cents, or 6.5 percent, to 73.81 cents a gallon,
its highest since the end of 1996. The price of the
unleaded-gasoline contract for February climbed 3.25 cents, or 4.6
percent, to 74.53 cents a gallon, back near the high of 77.11 cents
a gallon it hit in November.
</P>
<P>
   The price of oil has been moving up all week as comments from
OPEC members suggested that they would agree to extend the
production cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Iran's deputy oil minister, Kazempour Ardebili, said
that OPEC oil ministers wanted to extend the production reductions
at least another three months.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Saudi Arabia's oil minister, Ali as-Naimi, was
reported to have said that members of OPEC had already agreed to
extend the product cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Friday, before the Vienna meeting, the Iranian oil
minister, Namdar Zanganeh, said he expected OPEC members to approve
a six-month extension of the production cuts. ``We think we are
going to get a unanimous decision,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
