<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINNESOTA QB GEORGE IN A WELCOME TRANSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EARTH CITY, Mo. _ Lost in the tongue-in-cheek hoopla of whether
even the most powerful computers will be quick enough to add up the
points Sunday when the Vikings invade the Trans World Dome for a
wide-open NFC playoff game against the St. Louis Rams is the
subject of Minnesota quarterback Jeff George.
</P>
<P>
   All of football outside of Minnesota has been waiting for George
to play like Jeff George, and so far George hasn't. The
self-centered, selfish, coach-killing quarterback so well known and
disliked in Indianapolis, Atlanta, and Oakland has yet to make an
appearance for the Vikings. Instead, George has been solid, stable,
and a winner.
</P>
<P>
   And Vikings coach Dennis Green has yet to receive his due for
the transformation of George. This is the second straight year
Green has revived a quarterback from the football dead and, quite
clearly, the play of Randall Cunningham last season and George this
season can't be merely a coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one thing, we have continuity,'' said Green, refusing
to toot his own horn. ``So we have the exact same system that we
put in years ago. So whether it was Rich Gannon or Sean Salisbury
or Warren Moon or Brad Johnson or Randall Cunningham or Jeff
George, I think the players already know the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. Several of those quarterbacks who have played from
good to very good under Green were new to the Vikings' system. Such
as George this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think also, we have a lot of players _ and not just
quarterbacks _ who in this day and age sign just one-year contracts
and come in and play just one year,'' said Green. ``And we think we
have a system these guys understand. Many times they are looking to
revitalize their career and we don't have a problem with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Green is the dean of NFL coaches, finishing his eighth season as
Vikings coach (tied with Pittsburgh's Bill Cowher for longevity).
And when he notices Ray Rhodes fired after only a year at Green
Bay, Chan Gailey gone after only two seasons in Dallas, and Pete
Carroll after three in New England, he instinctively rebels at the
trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Continuity is probably the best way to have a successful
program,'' said Green. ``I know the grass always looks greener on
the other side of the fence, but the more changes you make and the
more things you have to do, I think the more difficult it is. I
don't think there's a magic system. I don't think there's a magic
pill, but I do know that I think continuity is the best way to
build a progran. Every time you change, you have to start over
again.''
</P>
<P>
   George, for his part, has taken to giving vanilla answers to any
questions about his transformation. Criticism, he said, ``goes with
the job. It's just part of the game. If you're a young guy, a
second- or third-year guy, you tend to worry about that more. But
I've been around too long to worry about what people think of me.''
</P>
<P>
   And lately, people are saying only good words about George. And
Green should be taking a bow for what many thought was impossible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 1934EST &QL; 
