<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV17-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YES, HE'S OFF HIS ROCKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, Jan. 17.)  
(lh) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like most sensitive Americans, I have spent a great deal of time
wringing my hands over the remarks made by Atlanta Braves pitcher
John Rocker in Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks were so offensive that I cannot repeat them here for
fear that you will go blind or your newspaper will spontaneously
combust in your hands.
</P>
<P>
   But trust me when I say they are the most lame-brained remarks
to come out of a professional athlete's mouth in at least a week,
maybe longer.
</P>
<P>
   Now Rocker is in big trouble. He was made to undergo
psychological testing to see if he has a mental disorder, and there
is a possibility _ quite remote, I would think _ that he will be
kicked off the team and maybe even banned from baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It is my opinion that Rocker deserves whatever happens to him
because Americans are dependent upon professional athletes for
guidance in the important social issues of our time, and Rocker has
let us down.
</P>
<P>
   The way I look at it, if you can't take lessons about the human
condition from a guy who throws 95-mph heat and talks to himself on
the mound, then there is something fundamentally wrong with our
society.
</P>
<P>
   Professional baseball players only work six months a year, so
they have a lot of free time to contemplate race relations, the
AIDS virus and immigration law. While some cynics might argue that
a man who lives in a mansion and makes $10 million a year is
unlikely to generate great insight on the plight of single mothers
or the urban poor, I prefer to think that a huge salary and
four-hour workdays help sharpen a player's mind and heighten his
compassion for those who aren't similarly blessed.
</P>
<P>
   While it is true that professional ballplayers are not, as a
group, particularly well-educated and that their hobbies tend to
lean more toward hunting and fishing than theater and ballet, that
does not mean they are a bunch of unsophisticated louts.
</P>
<P>
   For example, during a game you may notice that the third-base
coach gives a lot of bizarre-looking signals to the batter.
Sportscasters would have you believe that the coach is telling the
batter to hit, bunt, take the pitch or do some other
baseball-related thing.
</P>
<P>
   Nice theory, but untrue.
</P>
<P>
   When the coach touches the brim of his hat, he's asking the
hitter: ``Have you read any good existential fiction lately?''
</P>
<P>
   When he swipes his hand across his chest, he's saying: ''I can't
get enough of that National Public Radio.''
</P>
<P>
   To the untrained eye, baseball players seem to spend an
inordinate amount of time spitting and scratching. While these may
appear to be nothing more than rude mannerisms, they are really the
outward manifestations of deep thought. You will notice that
President Clinton hardly spits or scratches at all when he is on
national TV, which could explain how he got in that mess with
Monica Lewinsky and why Al Gore treats him like a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, professional baseball players have a huge social
obligation over and above going to the opposite field and breaking
up the double-play. We live by their example and depend on them to
teach us the difference between right and wrong.
</P>
<P>
   When someone like John Rocker betrays this trust, we all feel
the pain.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 1936EST &QL; 
