<HEADLINE>
CONSUMERS, HOSPITALS SEEK ROLE IN HELPING HMOS OUT OF TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX AND STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Two groups representing Massachusetts consumers and
hospitals asked the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court Friday to
grant them official standing as ``friends of the court'' in
decisions about the fate of Harvard Pilgrim Health Care.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer group Health Care for All and the Massachusetts
Hospital Association asked the court to give them the opportunity
to weigh in on decisions in the ongoing proceedings involving the
state's largest health plan, which the court placed in receivership
last week.
</P>
<P>
   If granted, the petitions also also give the groups access to
some but not all documents relating to the court proceedings and
the state's analysis of Harvard Pilgrim's financial position.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly was meeting with
his staff to decide which of three investment banking firms would
get a state contract to explore buyer options if the
court-appointed receiver, insurance commissioner Linda Ruthardt,
concludes that Harvard Pilgrim must be sold.
</P>
<P>
   In another development, US Representative Patrick J. Kennedy of
Rhode Island said he plans to meet with Governor Paul Cellucci next
Wednesday to argue for a joint task force to sort through Harvard
Pilgrim's troubles. The HMO shut down its Rhode Island operations
last month after suffering heavy losses.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said he will ask Cellucci ``to make sure Rhode Island is
not left out of the decision-making process.''
</P>
<P>
   If the court grants status to the Massachusetts consumer and
hospital groups, that would give those advocates a voice on such
questions as whether Harvard Pilgrim should be rehabilitated, sold,
carved up, or liquidated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be scrutinizing everything that comes out of the
receivership and making sure that the health system that came out
of this is responsive to consumer needs,'' said Robert Restuccia,
executive director of Health Care for All, at 15-year-old statewide
advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Health Care for All told the court in its petition that it can
contribute ``rich and relevant experience in maintaining essential
services in the conversion of nonprofit health care facilities to
for-profit entities.''
</P>
<P>
   One important set of questions in any plan to reorganize, sell,
or liquidate Harvard Pilgrim, observers said, involves how the
HMO's creditors ultimately get paid _ in what order, in what
amounts, and whether each creditor's financial condition or role in
the health care system is taken into account.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital association's executive committee met Friday
afternoon with Ruthardt to begin hashing out what Harvard Pilgrim
owes to hospitals. The trade group has claimed that total hospital
receivables amount to $300 million, but Harvard Pilgrim has said
that all its outstanding debt to doctors and other vendors, as well
as hospitals, equals about $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a process of going back and forth about
what these numbers really are,'' said Judy Glasser, a hospital
association spokeswoman. ``This is just the beginning of that
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruthardt and Reilly plan to compile a report on Harvard
Pilgrim's top 10 creditors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 1946EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6477 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-JAGUARS-BOS &LR;      01-14 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAGUARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAGUARS CARRY INJURIES INTO DIVISIONAL PLAYOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ The norm for a divisional playoff game in
the National Football League is the home team has the major
advantage, because it has had the bye week and two weeks to get its
injured players healthy.
</P>
<P>
   The norm will not be the norm when the hometown Jaguars take on
the revived Miami Dolphins Saturday, kicking off what is generally
the league's best weekend of football each season.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars, who finished with the best record in the AFC and
are the No. 1 seed in the conference, are wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't know until game time if (quarterback Mark) Brunell is
ready to play,'' said Jaguars coach Tom Coughlin. ``He's been
praticing, but he hasn't been near full speed. We've been getting
(Jay) Fiedler ready so if he has to go, he can go. I feel good
about him. I think we can win with him, if we have too, but
naturally we are hoping that Brunell can play. But I won't put him
out there unless I think he can do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Brunell is the catalyst of the Jacksonville offense, which has
run hot and cold. In the final game of the year, Jacksonville
suffered two serious blows. Tackle Tony Boselli, the best in the
league and a force on the left side, went out for the season with a
knee injury. Boselli usually handles the other team's best pass
rusher, and when he played against Miami's Jason Taylor, wired him
to the line of scrimmage and made Taylor a nonfactor. Today, the
Jaguars will switch guard Ben Coleman to tackle and replace him
with Rich Tylski. Tylski has been a starter in the past, but lost
his job to Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin acknowleged that he doesn't know for sure what to
expect from Miami, which had an impressive upset victory over the
Seahawks in Seattle last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to figure out which Jimmy (Johnson) we are going to
see,'' said Coughlin with a chuckle. ``He has changed up several
times this year with his offense. He has gone from throwing a
handful of passes and running the ball, taking time off the clock
to control the game, to throwing it 45 times and opening the
offense up. He's had the short week of practice, and we don't know
how much he can change, but we're sure he'll have a couple of
surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin has told his team that they are where they have wanted
to be the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in the playoffs, but always lost out in the end on
the road,'' he said. ``As the No. 1 seed, we've got the chance to
be at home all the way. This is going to be a tough game. We played
(Miami) here last year in a night game, and we had to make a couple
of big plays to pull it out in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a very good defensive team, so we know it's going to
be hard to score points on them, but we have to. We have to make
big plays. I don't think you can just march the ball up and down
the field on their defense. They're too good for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami has an idea of what the Jaguars might be thinking. ``I
think we're going to get a large dose of blitzing,'' said assistant
head coach Dave Wannstedt. ``Jacksonville's had one of the best
pressure teams in the league this year. We're sure they'll try
several different ways to get after Dan (Marino). They try to get
you three and out in a hurry. We can't let them do that. We have to
move the chains on offense. Try to control the clock and the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we can do it. I think we reinforced in our minds in
Seattle that we can run the ball. I think if we can throw less than
30 passes, run the ball, and pass protect for Dan, we can win. If
we can do that, we like our chances. Our players feel pretty good
about themselves right now. We went all the way across the country
to Seattle, played in a dome, on turf, in a noisy building, and
came away with a win. This game we're playing in the same state,
outdoors, on grass, which is what we do all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Coughlin, ``Turnovers will be the key. Whenever we won the
turnover battle in games this year we are 12-0. We were first in
the league in not turning the ball over. That is critical to the
way we play. We win the turnover game, we play our best game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
