<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-MISSILE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVIGATIONAL PROBLEMS CLOUD RAYTHEON MISSILE PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Pentagon said Friday it discovered navigational problems in
a Raytheon Co. antimissile system that weren't apparent when
military officials declared a test shot a success in October.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure will likely put new scrutiny on a second test
launch planned for next week.
</P>
<P>
   In the first experimental launch, a craft known as an
exoatmospheric kill vehicle built by Lexington-based Raytheon Co.,
destroyed a mock warhead 140 miles above the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The test was hailed as a key demonstration of technologies
designed to find and destroy enemy ballistic missiles, a challenge
akin to knocking down one flying bullet with another.
</P>
<P>
   But the concept also depends on extreme technical precision,
since the stakes of a miss are so high.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews Friday, Pentagon and Raytheon officials confirmed
that the kill vehicle's guidance system didn't function properly
during the test because of programming errors, prompting critics to
question the validity of the results overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how well it worked, and I'm not sure they know,''
said Lisbeth Gronlund, a physicist who works at the Union of
Concerned Scientists in Cambridge, Mass. The group believes that an
antimissile system could ruin nuclear-deterrence policies.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon spokesman said the test was still a success, since
the problem didn't prevent the target from being destroyed.
Interpretations matter as the Clinton administration mulls the
merits of deploying the system, which would cost about $10.5
billion through 2005, the Pentagon estimates.
</P>
<P>
   A decision is expected this summer, after two more test
launches. The next test is planned for Tuesday and will be
conducted under circumstances similar to October's, but this time
the kill vehicle will be guided by a Raytheon-built radar system
operating from an atoll in the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   The navigational problems were first reported Friday by The New
York Times. Specifically, because of computer-programming errors by
Raytheon, the kill vehicle couldn't make proper use of a star map
stored in its memory.
</P>
<P>
   That data was meant to help the kill vehicle orient itself to
pick out warheads released by enemy missiles, and to distinguish
them from decoy warheads and used booster-rocket stages that might
also descend through the outer atmosphere during an attack.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the kill vehicle relied on other input for guidance
after it was launched by a two-stage rocket booster. It did manage
to identify one star successfully, Raytheon said, and then found a
decoy balloon that had been released by the test missile.
</P>
<P>
   The kill vehicle still knew to ignore the decoy, then find, ram,
and destroy the test warhead itself. The chronology was discovered
during an analysis in the weeks following the launch, the Pentagon
said Friday, and congressional staff members were briefed.
</P>
<P>
   But the navigational problem, coupled with the potentially
helpful role played by the decoy balloon, was seized upon by some
critics to question whether the $100 million test had shown
positive results after all.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's slow public disclosure of the issue ``really says
something about the quality of the information you get out of this
organization,'' said Theodore Postol, a security specialist at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology and a longtime Raytheon
critic.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Lieutenant Colonel Rick Lehner, a Pentagon spokesman,
said the issues weren't announced before because they ``didn't
affect the capability (of the vehicle) to successfully intercept
the target.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, ``Nobody in the BMDO ever said things were done
perfectly,'' he said, referring to the ballistic missile defense
organization, the tests' overseer.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon spokesman Dave Shea said the difficulty shouldn't be
seen to detract from the firing's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It overcame bad information,'' he said. ``We understand the
problem and we're confident it won't happen next time.'' The kill
vehicle would have destroyed the test warhead even without the
balloon's presence, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Evaluating the performance of missiles made by Raytheon and
other military contractors often has been a contentious matter.
During the Gulf War the company and military spokespeople made
claims about the Patriot air-defense missile that later reviews
found were overblown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
