<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW YORK GROUP, CUBANS FIND MUTUAL INTEREST IN TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KATE GURNETT  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ Talk of U.S. products started right at customs for
Henry Zwack, when guards demanded to know what those 75 bottles
were in his suitcase when the delegation of Americans arrived in
Cuba late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   You put it on pancakes, said Zwack. And on ice cream. This was
made in my home town of Stephentown, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, it's rum? one guard responded.
</P>
<P>
   No, maple syrup, said Zwack, the Rensselaer County executive. To
help with the translation, Zwack dunked his pinky in the miniature
bottle, licked his finger and passed it around for the others to
taste. They liked it. They passed him through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected Checkpoint Charlie,'' Zwack said, referring to the
former border crossing between East and West Germany. ``I got
Checkpoint Como Esta.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first of many interactions that quickly made one
thing clear to this group traveling to Havana: Cuba offers a range
of opportunities for trade, culture and tourism exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   The group from upstate New York ate rice imported from China.
Why not from the United States? someone asked. They rode a bus
imported from Brazil. Why not from the United States? they said.
They saw medical shortages that need to be filled. Why not from the
United States?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put the word `international' into Albany International
Airport and start our own trade,'' said New York State Assemblyman
Robert Prentiss, a Republican who would like to end the U.S. trade
embargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have General Electric silicones that could be shipped to
manufacture the medical products they need,'' he added. ``Cuba has
wood pulp that could be bought by International Paper. Plug Power
in Latham is developing energy for houses they could use here. If
we don't lift this embargo, foreign powers would get an economic
stronghold here before we do.''
</P>
<P>
   They got no argument from the Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuba will be a wonderful buyer,'' said Carlos Franco
Parellada, head of the International Relations Department for
Havana's provincial assembly. In exchange, it has nickel, rum,
cigars and citrus to trade, along with tourism. ``It will be very
positive for both countries,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fidel Castro and his Communist insurgents took power in Cuba in
1959, leading to the eventual U.S. embargo against the island
nation just 90 miles from Florida. Although tensions had begun to
ease, the dispute over the return of a 6-year-old Cuban boy to his
father has fueled old animosities.
</P>
<P>
   In a white briefing room before a wall-sized blue map of Cuba,
Parellada gave the group a spirited two-hour history lesson that
rivaled a speech by Fidel Castro himself in intensity and devotion
to the survival of this Communist state.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in Old Havana, the conversation turned to Internet
start-ups as three Columbia University students sat on the stoop of
the old Hemingway haunt, La Bodegita del Medio. Columbia is one of
dozens of U.S. schools to send groups of students to Cuba in recent
years, including Tulane University, the University at Buffalo and
New York University.
</P>
<P>
   This delegation from the Albany area will offer the Cubans
cultural exchanges, with letters of support from two local schools,
Siena College and the College of Saint Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Saint Rose would welcome a cultural exchange with a similar
Cuban college, President R. Mark Sullivan said in a letter to Cuban
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Albany-area group, the Columbia students were given
tours of a hospital, a school and other sites. Both groups said
they hope to reach beyond the curtain of propaganda to find out
what it's really like for the people who live here.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of young people come up and talk to you about discos,
but we haven't gotten down to the nitty gritty yet,'' said Columbia
student Amber Gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents and grandparents thought I was crazy to come here
and I would be held captive here,'' said fellow student Shannon
Lightner. At least I can go back and tell them what it is _ and
what it's not. I walked the streets safely. Even books here are
free. But then, at what price?''
</P>
<P>
   At a fourth-grade elementary class, Lightner said, posters all
over the walls called for the return of Elian Gonzalez, the
6-year-old Cuban boy who was plucked from the ocean near Florida in
November and remains with relatives.
</P>
<P>
   A large billboard demands that U.S. officials ``Devuelvan Elian
a la Patria'' (send Elian back to the fatherland.)
</P>
<P>
   The delegation from New York is spending six days visiting a
range of sites to prepare a report for Congress on conditions here.
It will also donate roughly $50,000 in medicine and medical
equipment to the Calixto Garcia Hospital in Havana.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
