<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-TOURISM-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN $18-MILLION CAMPAIGN AIMS TO LURE TOURISTS TO SOUTH AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain, Germany, France, Italy, Spain, Australia, the
Netherlands, Calif., Fla., Ga.)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(Eds., spelling Malcom, in 14th graf, is CQ) 
(DW) 
 By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ South Africa's name is famous
around the globe, a legacy of the apartheid era that etched the
country into the conscience of the world but left it a foreboding
and unfamiliar place to many of the travelers it would now like to
attract.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to travel agents in the United States or Britain who
specialize in South Africa, and they report the same queries from
curious but confused customers: Is there toilet paper in the
bathrooms? Are the roads paved? Do the people speak English? Are
there restaurants? Do we have to bring our own food?
</P>
<P>
   Anne Bellamy, vice president of African Travel in Glendale,
Calif., has heard them all. ``Some people think all they eat is
fresh elephant meat,'' Ms. Bellamy said.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to dispel the myths, South Africa has turned to
Madison Avenue. This month, the country makes its first major foray
into the world of international marketing with an $18-million
promotional campaign aimed at the United States, Britain, Germany,
France, Italy and the Netherlands. Its emphasis is on enjoying
South Africa's exotic outdoor attractions and urbanity rather than
experiencing the opening of a door to a new multi-racial democracy.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, where travel to South Africa jumped almost
25 percent from 1997, to more than 166,000 trips in 1998, the
effort will focus on New York, Los Angeles and Miami, the three
markets where South Africa thinks it has the best chance of drawing
far more tourists.
</P>
<P>
   For a country like the United States, the numbers are small, but
the already increasing interest from the world's richest nation
gives South Africa hope. ``It won't be easy, but we're really
making a start,'' the country's minister of environment and
tourism, Valli Moosa, said.
</P>
<P>
   By world standards, the campaign is modest, forsaking television
in favor of more affordable media like newspapers, magazines and
billboards. For a country that until now had placed just a handful
of ads overseas, it is a huge step into the media age.
</P>
<P>
   The advertising giant Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide, a unit of the
WPP Group, was hired to develop the campaign. The firm's
Johannesburg office, Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Rightford, has spent the last
18 months working with the country's tourism industry to design a
strategy that will try to turn tourism into the humming economic
engine that so many in South Africa believe it can be.
</P>
<P>
   To listen to the leaders of this new democracy talk about
tourism, nothing less than the future of the nation is at stake.
Widespread unemployment, poverty and crime have made employment one
of the government's highest priorities.
</P>
<P>
   With just over 3 percent of the South African work force
directly employed by the tourism industry, and another 4 percent
employed by related industries, the tourism business here still has
a long way to go before it overtakes the country's mines, whose
mineral and metal riches built modern South Africa. Mining accounts
for just under 11 percent of the nation's jobs, down from 13.25
percent a decade ago but still the economy's biggest single source
of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The tourism minister said he was confident that in just a couple
of years more than 300,000 additional tourism jobs could be created
in this country of about 44 million people. ``We've reached a point
now where there is a consensus in South African society that
tourism must be regarded as a priority,'' Moosa said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not always so. For many years, South Africa was
ostracized because of its repressive racist regime. Promoting South
Africa, particularly in the 1970s and 1980s, would have been a
waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   That changed in 1994 when Nelson Mandela was elected president.
With little effort, tourism took off, albeit from almost nothing.
It did not take long, however, for it to taper off, as the curious
came and went, and not all that many people followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to build for the future, and South Africa did
not,'' said Malcom Peasnall, the director of the Independent
Traveler, a British agency that saw its bookings to South Africa
surge from none during the apartheid era, when the agency refused
to book trips to the country, to 500 a year immediately after
Mandela came to power, before leveling off at about 1,000 trips a
year. ``South Africa got a lot for free, but now they've got to
pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn van Heerden, deputy chairman of Avis South Africa, the
regional franchisee for Avis Rent a Car System, and deputy chairman
of the country's Tourism Business Council, looks back on the days
after the election and wonders where the country might have been
today if tourism had had the attention then that it has now. ``We
probably had a golden opportunity to launch something then,'' he
said, ``but it was obviously and regretfully not a priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he says, the industry and the government have realized that
the country's vast potential will begin to be exploited only if
they take their message to the people of the world _ to the people
with the money and the motivation to make the trip. ``Nothing will
sell in the supermarket unless it's on the shelf when you go in,''
van Heerden said.
</P>
<P>
   That is a welcome message to the travel agents around the world
who, until now, have found themselves alone in their struggle to
steer tourists to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been playing the role of educating people about Africa
as a whole, geography lessons, cultural lessons, anthropology
lessons, the whole gamut,'' Ms. Bellamy said.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Waddell, a minister from a suburb of Atlanta, was among
the untutored. For years, her husband had been trying to coax her
into joining him on a trip to southern Africa, where he had long
dreamed of hunting. But she was scared of South Africa, with its
turbulent history _ fearful of how her little blue-eyed,
blonde-haired daughters would be treated in a country with a
history of racial tensions. Last year, her husband's lobbying
finally won her over, or at least wore her down. ``I was
terrified,'' Mrs. Waddell, 44, said. ``I was so afraid that I
almost canceled the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   She is happy now that she did not. ``It was just absolutely
amazing,'' she said. ``The people were so friendly and so helpful
and so warm that I just wanted to stay there forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The new campaign is aimed at making South Africa an easier sell.
That will be a challenge, and not just because crime is a problem
here. Less serious, but no less formidable a challenge is
convincing people to fly 17 hours or more from the United States or
nearly 11 hours from London, to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   For inspiration, South Africa has looked across the Indian Ocean
to Australia. Far from the lucrative North American and European
markets, Australia has managed to make international tourism a
major part of its economy.
</P>
<P>
   Like South Africa, Australia knows it is never going to attract
as many visitors as Spain or France. But no country save the United
States makes more money per tourist than Australia, because its
visitors are almost always coming from afar, which means that, on
average, they stay longer than tourists any place else. (More than
75 percent of visitors to South Africa come from other African
countries; among non-African nations, Britain is South Africa's
biggest patron, with 321,000 visitors in 1998, or 5.6 percent of
South Africa's total.)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   South Africa, however, plans to spend only a fraction of the
more than $85 million a year that Australia sets aside for tourism
promotion. ``We can't spend that kind of money, and we'll never be
able to because we have pressing needs in this country,'' said
Sheryl Ozinsky, the tourism manager in Cape Town. ``We have to be
creative in everything we do.''
</P>
<P>
   The innovations include repainting 50 London taxis in the colors
of the South African flag and flying the cabbies to South Africa
for a look at the country so they can chat it up with passengers
back in the West End.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to do it in New York, too, but they won't let you,''
said Dale Pretorius, the assistant general manager of marketing for
the South African Tourism Board. ``The cabs there have got to be
yellow.''
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the campaign will be waged with glossy inserts and
print ads in upscale magazines like Conde Nast Traveler in the
United States, Der Spiegel in Germany and Gente Viaggi in Italy,
publications most likely to be read by the sort of people who South
Africa is convinced will visit if given the right message.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out that message was not easy for a country that is
still figuring itself out, said Nunu Ntshingila, one of the Ogilvy
account managers who oversaw much of the day-to-day work on the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when work started on the glossy insert, Mandela
seemed to be the obvious choice to grace the cover. But when the ad
managers test-marketed the brochures, they discovered they were
wrong. Beloved as Mandela is, his image did not evoke thoughts of
carefree days spent on the beach, strolling through a vineyard or
hiking around a game reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing how it was interpreted internationally,'' Ms.
Ntshingila said. ``Some people saw it and expected some sort of
political message.''
</P>
<P>
   So Mandela was moved inside the brochure and a panoramic shot of
Cape Town's majestic Table Mountain took his place.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, it is not so simple. Much of the country's charm lies
in its wildlife and ecosystem, from the whales and penguins off
Cape Town to the lions and elephants in Kruger National Park in the
northeast of the country. Yet a unique element of South Africa's
appeal, especially to visitors from the United States, is its
modern infrastructure, unmatched in Africa, with first-class
hotels, fine restaurants, good roads and airports and excellent
private hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is aimed at making sure people see, or at least
sense, both sides of South Africa. ``Where the world's most
intelligent creatures take their breaks,'' reads one ad that
features a sun-splashed photograph of a whale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a very tricky balance,'' Ms. Ntshingila said,
``because we don't want to lose the African heritage, but we want
to communicate the more sophisticated side of South Africa.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
