<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: NO LIMIT BUT THE SKY FOR JUDICIAL OVERREACHING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY LEWIS  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``Judicial activism is out of control and must be
stopped,'' Steve Forbes said in New Hampshire last month. ``Courts
that make laws from the bench threaten the foundation of our
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't waste it on the voters, Forbes. Go preach it to the five
members of the Supreme Court who are carrying out a radical
reshaping of our constitutional structure.
</P>
<P>
   The latest example of judicial overreaching came this week. As
in three cases decided last June, the five-justice majority read
into the Constitution words and a concept that do not appear in its
text: ``state sovereign immunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The target this time was the federal law that prohibits
discrimination in employment on the basis of age. The law allows
victims of discrimination to sue employers for damages. It was
extended to employees of state agencies in 1974, but the Supreme
Court said this week that they could not sue _ because the states
are immune.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th Amendment to the Constitution bars federal courts from
hearing lawsuits brought against a state by citizens of another
state. It was intended to deal with issues arising under state law,
such as contract disputes.
</P>
<P>
   In this case a Florida agency was being sued by Florida
citizens, and they were suing to enforce a federal law. So neither
the language nor the purpose of the 11th Amendment stood in their
way.
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, was Florida immune from the suits? Because of a
constitutional doctrine created by the five-justice majority of the
Supreme Court in recent years: that the states must have sovereign
immunity to maintain their ``dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   That notion cannot be traced to the Framers of the Constitution.
Americans had just won their independence from a Britain whose
Parliament claimed absolute sovereignty, and the Framers wanted a
republican United States in which rulers were answerable to the
people.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the Framers assign to the Supreme Court, especially, the
role of protecting state interests. They sought that protection
primarily in the political structure they created: for example,
equal state representation in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The issue may sound abstract, the business of lawyers and
historians. But it is far from that. It goes to the heart of all
the politics swirling around judges and their appointment these
days.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives like Steve Forbes denounce ``liberal judges'' and
``activism,'' coupling the two. Right-wing lobbyists have run
campaigns against some of President Clinton's judicial nominees on
those grounds. The chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee,
Orrin Hatch, has warned repeatedly against ``activist judges.''
</P>
<P>
   The word activist is a verbal brickbat, without a fixed meaning.
But if it suggests judges who invade the province of legislators,
then it applies primarily today to judicial conservatives _ as this
week's Supreme Court decision showed.
</P>
<P>
   The majority opinion, by Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, read in
places like a parody of judicial legislating. ``Our examination of
the legislative record,'' she wrote, ``confirms that Congress' 1974
extension of the [age discrimination) act to the states was an
unwarranted response to a perhaps inconsequential problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether legislation is warranted is not a question for judges to
decide. It is the business of the political branches of government.
</P>
<P>
   The result of this and the other recent federalism cases is to
throw a cloud of hypocrisy over conservative statements that judges
who construe the Constitution should respect the text, the
intention of its Framers, and so on. When the decisions came down
last June, Professor Vincent Blasi of the University of Virginia
and Columbia Law Schools said: ``After this I want to hear no more
about original intention, textualism, strict construction or
judicial restraint.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice John Paul Stevens, writing for the four dissenters in
the Florida case, actually charged the majority with ``judicial
activism.'' But that is not likely to give the five pause.
</P>
<P>
   In 1930, when a willful majority was striking down economic
legislation as violative of ``due process,'' Holmes wrote in
dissent, ``I see hardly any limit but the sky'' to invalidation of
statutes ``if they happen to strike a majority of this court as for
any reason undesirable.'' So it is on the federalism issue today.
</P>
</TEXT>
