<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ROLE OF SATELLITES IN A WORLD THAT'S WIRED  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Questions may be italicized)  
(af) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beam me up, Scotty: Let's talk satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Cable pipes and telephone lines are widely seen as the speediest
access lines linking homes and the Internet. That sort of thinking
was underscored last week by the America Online-Time Warner deal.
</P>
<P>
   It bears remembering, though, that as recently as last June, AOL
sank $1.5 billion into Hughes Electronics' satellite communications
venture. It could be that AOL made that investment because, so far,
talk about two-way cable modems and digital subscriber lines has
been mostly just that. Have you asked your local cable or telephone
company lately exactly when those upgrades are expected in your
neighborhood?
</P>
<P>
   Vijay Jayant, a satellite communications analyst at Bear Stearns
&AMP; Co., took some time last week to talk about things
extraterrestrial. Following are excerpts from the conversation:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. So far, most satellite ventures have offered one-way service,
like television, and not two-way, Internet-related access. Why? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You haven't had pure-play stories yet because the technology
is not there. It costs a lot of money to develop a network that can
talk back to a satellite.
</P>
<P>
   But Gilat Satellite Networks and Hughes Electronics will have
products in about 6 to 12 months that will provide two-way access
with data streams that will be comparable to cable modems.
Manufacturing costs on these products is somewhere between $1,000
and $1,500 per unit, so the real challenge will be how they price
the hardware. The companies will probably have to subsidize the
units, but we don't know by how much. Monthly pricing hasn't been
determined, but it will likely be competitive with similar two-way
cable service. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is it fair to look at this as a broadband race involving the
telephone, cable and satellite companies? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It is a race, but satellites have their own position in the
scheme of things.
</P>
<P>
   In this country, satellites will target rural America, where
household densities are not sufficient for laying out a broadband
ground network, be it cable or broadband fiber.
</P>
<P>
   That is the target market, the low-hanging fruit. There are
about 30 million rural homes in this country.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a lot of opportunity in the developing world. The
challenge is to get the cost of the dish and the receiver to
reasonable levels.
</P>
<P>
   Globally, it is about a $60 billion to $70 billion market in
terms of revenues, one that is growing at about 15 percent a year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is it reasonable to think that satellites will compete with
digital subscriber lines, DSLs, or cable in urban areas? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There will be more competition, especially if delays in
getting cable and DSL upgrades drag out. But I don't think
satellites will outdo cable or telephone links in high-density
areas. An entrenched terrestrial network, be it cable or telephone,
is already in place in all high-density areas. I think you will see
upgrades in most major markets in the next year or two, when voice,
video and data will be truly bundled.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the world doesn't have this sort of infrastructure and
is not connected for voice, video and Internet service. A satellite
signal is distance insensitive, and is the way to satisfy demand in
those areas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. So why did AOL make its investment in Hughes? And what
happens to that now that they have bought Time Warner?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. AOL wanted a foot in the door to every mode of distribution,
and I think they possibly wanted to do more with them. AOL has no
effective control over the asset. They own less than 5 percent of
General Motors Hughes stock and have no board representation. But
Hughes has to figure out if there is a conflict, and if they are
comfortable with a cable company owning a piece of them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Investors pushed the Bear Stearns index of 14 satellite
communications stocks up 86.8 percent for the 52 weeks through
Thursday. Are the stocks vulnerable? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The stocks have done extremely well. Hughes Electronics more
than doubled in the last year. EchoStar has been a six-bagger and
Gilat has more than tripled.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these good performers have priced in a lot of success in
the future, so there is a limited flexibility for them to miss.
They have to deliver now. If they don't, there is a chance the
stocks will decline. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You cover more than 20 of these stocks. Which ones do you
like? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I am very bullish on the whole sector and have buy
recommendations on most of my stocks.
</P>
<P>
   I really like Hughes Electronics. It is the bellwether satellite
name in everything that it does. And it is not a matter of if, but
when General Motors spins them out as a separate company. I also
like Orbital Sciences, a manufacturer of small satellites and small
rockets. And I like Sirius Radio, which will be providing 100
channels of radio via satellite for subscription.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
