<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST JOLTS OF THE INTERNET SHAKEOUT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For months, if not years, the virtual has trounced
the real in the stock market. Valuations of Internet concerns
vastly exceeded the values that investors assigned to companies
unlucky enough to own tangible assets. Companies with profit were
bounced for those with ``eyeballs.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, on the strength of several significant announcements,
the tables turned. The real world is back in the ascendant, and
investors are about to experience the Great Internet Shakeout.
</P>
<P>
   A big indication that the tectonic plates of the virtual world
were shifting was the bid of the highflying America Online to
acquire the landlocked Time Warner. Then the Charles Schwab Corp.,
online broker to the world, said it would acquire U.S. Trust, an
investment firm known for asset management services it provides its
decidedly blueblood clientele. Schwab appeared to be protecting
itself should the online trading boom evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   Another straw in the wind: Wal-Mart Stores announced on Jan. 7
that it was spinning off its Web operations into a dot-com.
Wal-Mart is expected to show that brick-and-mortar retailers can
beat e-tailers at their own game.
</P>
<P>
   So, even as Alan Greenspan rhapsodized in New York on Thursday
about the joys and gains relating to the Internet, that world was
starting to undergo wrenching change.
</P>
<P>
   ``This week is a bit of a watershed, in which the highflying
world of the Internet meets the concrete test of the marketplace,''
said Brian J. Fabbri, chief economist at the Paribas Corp., an
investment firm in New York. AOL and Schwab were the first. ``For
the rest of the unreal world, the acid test is to come,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, investors remain extremely optimistic about
Internet stocks. The Interactive Week Internet index of 30 stocks
closed at 555.27, just 7.7 percent below its record high reached on
Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``My general concern is investors are feeling too complacent
over the extraordinary gains they got in Internet stocks in 1999,''
said David Readerman, director of Internet strategy at Thomas
Weisel Partners in San Francisco. ``It's not going to be that easy
this year. There are going to be some collosal failures.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Breyer, managing partner at Accel Partners, a venture
capital firm that is a partner with Wal-Mart.com, believes last
week's shift was epic in its significance. ``The reckoning is
coming soon,'' he said, adding that second- and third-tier Internet
companies are highly vulnerable. Equally threatened are old-economy
companies that do not get Web strategies off the ground now.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in the stock market have been very forgiving of
Internet companies with big plans but little in financial results.
``Public investors have played the role of venture capitalists in
these companies,'' Breyer said. Now, venture capitalists are
getting tough with Internet companies trying to raise money, and
individual investors ought to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Readerman suspects that the shakeout has begun, noting that in
the first half of January, as Wall Street firms held Internet
investing conferences, Internet stocks did not perform that well.
``If calendar 1999 was one of discovery of the Internet, 2000 is
going to be characterized by much more rigorous scrutiny of the
business models,'' he said. ``You don't want to be completely out
of these stocks, but I'm not averse to taking some profits.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
