<P>
   IRAN-SOCCER (Los Angeles) -- With the United States and Iranian
soccer teams set to meet for the first time ever in this country at
the Rose Bowl on Sunday, local Iranians say the event also will be
a platform to express national pride and focus attention on the
repressive regime in their homeland. Iranian soccer fans now living
in the San Fernando Valley, many of whom fled their country after
the 1979 Islamic revolution, say while they plan to root for Iran,
they may sit while the anthem of the current Islamic regime is
played. ``This is one of those rare times that Iranians here can
speak out about human rights in Iran,'' said Bijan Khalili,
director of Van Nuys-based Ketab Corp., which publishes a weekly
Iranian newspaper and the Iranian Yellow Pages. Community leaders
say the Valley has the biggest population of Iranians outside of
Iran, with 100,000 to 150,000 living in the region. By Harrison
Sheppard (Will move on the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news
wires.)
