u a BC-LITASULLIVAN16-COX     01-14 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITASULLIVAN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Millionaire fugitive wanted worldwide
 &HT;    EDs: EMBARGOED for Sunday, Jan. 16
 &HT;    By Bill Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fugitive millionaire James Vincent Sullivan, accused
of contracting for one of Atlanta's highest-profile murders, now is
a wanted man around the world and in cyberspace, too.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan's scowling face appears second from the top on the
Georgia Bureau of Investigation Web page that shows mug shots of
fugitives sought in connection with 14 Georgia crimes. Sullivan's
photo appears right below that of Centennial Olympic Park bombing
suspect Eric Robert Rudolph.
</P>
<P>
   The same photo of the 58-year-old former Palm Beach, Fla.,
investor also is posted on the Internet site of Voice of America.
He is the subject of an international crime alert stating that he
may be in Latin America or Thailand. Anyone with information is
urged to contact the nearest U.S. embassy or consulate, or to
telephone the Fulton County District Attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say Sullivan paid another man to murder his wife,
Atlanta socialite Lita Sullivan. She was shot in the head 13 years
ago today (Sunday) by the gunman, who gained access to her
townhouse house by posing as a deliveryman bringing a box of pink
roses.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities contend the hit man was a North Carolina truck
driver. Philip Anthony ``Tony'' Harwood, 48, now sits in the Fulton
County jail accused of the murder, for which authorities claim he
was paid $25,000. District Attorney Paul Howard has given legal
notice he intends to seek the death penalty for Harwood, who was
arrested in April 1998 at his home in Albemarle, N.C., after police
got a tip from Harwood's former girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Harwood's lawyer, Tom West, said his client denies he was the
triggerman. ``He has consistently and repeatedly denied killing
Lita Sullivan, and he continues to do so,'' West said. ``Come on,
he's not a slick hired gun, he's just a truck driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta lawyer Ed Garland, who has represented Sullivan, said
last week he has no knowledge of his client's whereabouts or even
if Sullivan is alive. But, he said, ``if and when we are asked to,
we are prepared to defend him in court.''
</P>
<P>
   Lita LaVaughn McClinton Sullivan, daughter of Emory and JoAnn
McClinton of Atlanta, was described as a vivacious and generous
35-year-old with a love of flowers. She had left her husband of 11
years, claiming he was unfaithful and stingy with the $5 million he
had collected from the sale of an inherited liquor distributorship
in Macon, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   She was gunned down when she answered her doorbell, just hours
before a scheduled hearing in Fulton Superior Court on property
division in the couple's bitterly contested divorce suit.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 minutes after she was shot, someone placed a collect
phone call from a pay phone at an exit on Interstate 85 near
Suwanee, Ga., to James Sullivan's $3.5 million oceanfront mansion
in Palm Beach, according to testimony in court. Telephone records
show the call lasted less than a minute.
</P>
<P>
   A 1992 attempt by federal prosecutors in Atlanta to try Sullivan
on a charge of interstate conspiracy to commit murder was thrown
out for lack of evidence. But two years later, a civil jury in West
Palm Beach awarded the McClintons $4 million in damages after
concluding that Sullivan had arranged his wife's murder.
</P>
<P>
   A break in the criminal investigation came in 1998, when a woman
living in southeast Texas had her lawyer contact authorities in
Atlanta after seeing lawyers for Lita Sullivan's parents discuss
the case on the tabloid TV show ``Extra.''
</P>
<P>
   GBI agent Bob Ingram, Atlanta police Maj. G.M. ``Mickey'' Lloyd
and assistant Fulton prosecutor John Cross went to Texas to
interview the woman, a former trucker who had an on-and-off
relationship with Harwood, according to her lawyer, Ed Lieck of
Beaumont, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``My client told them she was with Tony Harwood when he was paid
off for Lita Sullivan's murder,'' said Lieck. He said the meeting
occurred at a restaurant, perhaps in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Lieck would not identify the woman because she fears for her
safety. He said she identified Sullivan from a photo lineup.
</P>
<P>
   But Harwood's defense lawyer, Tom West, claims no one ever has
identified Harwood as the killer. ``There are eyewitness reports of
people who saw the killer, and who saw a physical lineup including
my client, and they could not identify him,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Howard and investigator Ingram would not talk about
the woman's account, and would neither confirm nor deny that she
had identified Sullivan's photo. The FBI, working through U.S.
consulates and embassies overseas, is handling the foreign search
for the fugitive millionaire. ``We have leads in several
countries,'' said FBI spokeswoman Celestine Armistead, but she
would not provide specifics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the last to know anything officially about any
progress,'' said the victim's father, a retired federal official
and member of the state Board of Transportation. ``The most
difficult day for us is Christmas, not the day Lita was killed. But
I'm encouraged by any publicity, from the press, the Voice of
America, that keeps people focused on him.''
</P>
<P>
   GBI agent Ingram said he understands the family's frustration,
but he believes Sullivan, far from living the life of a millionaire
in exotic climes, is in a prison of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every fugitive I've ever interviewed said they got tired of
looking over their shoulder every time they get up and move around.
It's not a way to live; it's freedom without being free,'' Ingram
said. ``When he's caught, I think he'll fold like an accordion.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
