<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICAN HORSE IMPRESSES AT GULFSTREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How good is racing in South Africa? Judging by the easy victory
of South African star Horse Chestnut in last Saturday's $100,000
Broward County Handicap at Gulfstream Park, it must be pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   Horse Chestnut had captured 9 of 10 starts in his native country
and obviously is a superior individual, but he had never run on
dirt. However, the going proved no problem for the powerful
5-year-old, who stalked the pace from third place under Mike Smith,
then drew off through the lane to win by better than 5 lengths as
the 2-1 ($6.40) second choice. Isaypete was second at 8-1, and 6-5
favorite Rock And Roll finished third. The time for the 1 1/16th
mile was 1:42 3/5, just two ticks off the stakes record for the
Grade III event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy,'' said trainer Mike de Kock, who conditions Horse
Chestnut for owners Harry and Bridget Oppenheimer. ``I'm not too
surprised he won like that, but I wasn't sure about the horses in
another country.''
</P>
<P>
   South Africa is in the Southern Hemisphere _ horses change age
there July 1 as opposed to Jan. 1 _ so the Triple Crown season
there comes when horses in the United States would be age 4. Horse
Chestnut swept the Triple Crown, concluding his 1999 season finale
with a 10-length victory in the South African Derby April 24. He
has proved to be versatile, winning at distances from 5 furlongs to
1 1/2 miles.
</P>
<P>
   With the $6 million Dubai World Cup, which is run on dirt in
March, in mind, his connections shipped Horse Chestnut over for a
Gulfstream campaign. He has been working in Florida since
mid-December, going 5 furlongs in a rapid :59 3/5 over the
Gulfstream strip in his final tuneup for the Broward.
</P>
<P>
   Next for Horse Chestnut will be the Grade I Donn Handicap Feb.
5. If he takes that one, he will become a major player on the
international scene.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Surfside on rise
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's only the second week of January, and trainer D. Wayne Lukas
is already in top form. After the outstanding filly Surfside
captured her 3-year-old debut in the $100,000 Santa Ysabel Sunday,
Lukas declared his charge a possible contender for the Kentucky
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Surfside has tremendous breeding. She is by Triple Crown winner
Seattle Slew, out of 2-year-old champion Flanders. Surfside has
taken five of seven starts and got the worst of it in the Breeders'
Cup Juvenile Fillies, finishing third after a wide trip. In the
Santa Ysabel, she dominated three overmatched foes despite carrying
a heavy package of 123 pounds, romping home by 8 lengths at odds of
1-5 ($2.40) with Pat Day aboard. The time for the 1 1/16th miles
was 1:43 2/5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is falling into place now,'' said Lukas. ``We can
run back in the Las Virgenes (Feb. 12), then it's 30 days to the
Santa Anita Oaks. Then we can go to either the Santa Anita Derby
(vs. males) or the Ashland (vs. females at Keeneland). Because of
her style and pedigree, Surfside looks more like a
mile-and-one-quarter horse (the Kentucky Derby distance) than
Winning Colors (a Lukas-bred filly who won the Run for the Roses in
1988). We haven't considered the Kentucky Derby this early in the
year with any other filly.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Out a lot of bucks
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Buck's Boy, winner of the 1998 Breeders' Cup Turf and third last
year, wiped out the grandstand at Gulfstream Sunday when he
finished off the board in the $100,000 Mac Diarmida Handicap at
odds of 3-10. Unite's Big Red, who was first with Jorge Chavez,
returned $25.20 to win and $55.20 to show; Thesaurus, who was
second, paid $54.60 to show; and show horse Carpenter's Halo paid
$48.80 as the bridge jumpers hit the water hard. Ridden by Garett
Gomez, Buck's Boy, a noted front-runner, was pressed every step of
the way by longshot Special Coach, ridden by former Suffolk jockey
Stewart Elliot. The pair blazed through a half in :45 4/5, 6
furlongs in 1:10, and a mile in 1:35, simply too fast for a 1
1/2-mile contest, even though they opened a 12-length lead while
running like a team. Buck's Boy, who is age 7, was cooked turning
for home, fading to seventh, ahead of only Special Coach in the
eight-horse field, as the enemy flew by. ``Every time I tried to
make a move, the other horse went with me,'' said Gomez. ``Every
time I tried to take back, he laid on me. I didn't expect that. He
was on me the whole trip.'' . . . Real Quiet, winner of the 1998
Kentucky Derby and Preakness, was thought to be retired after he
fractured a splint in his leg while training for the Pacific
Classic last August. However, it now appears he will return to
action this year under an agreement made by owner Mike Pegram, no
stranger to the spotlight, and George Hofmeister, who had acquired
the breeding rights. ``He will not go to stud this spring,'' said
Bob Baffert, who trains for Pegram. ``He's over at Hollywood Park,
jogging a mile every day.'' . . . Lemon Drop Kid, winner of last
year's Belmont Stakes and Travers, is back in training at
Gulfstream. ``He's going to the track now,'' said Randy Schulhofer,
who is managing the stable while his father, Scotty, recovers from
triple bypass surgery. ``He likely won't be able to run until later
in the meeting. The Donn is out, but there is a chance he might be
ready for the Gulfstream Park Handicap (Feb. 26).'' . . . More Than
Ready, who was considered the best 2-year-old in the country last
season until he failed (fifth) in the Champagne at Belmont Oct. 9,
is also ready to return to action. More Than Ready worked a
best-of-the-day :47 4/5 for a half mile at Hialeah last Thursday to
attest to his fitness. ``He's coming along nicely,'' said trainer
Todd Pletcher. ``We're playing it by ear right now, but maybe his
first start will be in the Hutchinson (at Gulfstream Jan. 29).''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from publicity departments at various racetracks was used
to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
