<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BREAST-CANCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCTAL BREAST CANCER RECURRENCES LINKED TO AGE AND AMOUNT OF TISSUE
REMOVED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)   By DENISE GRADY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women under 45 who have lumpectomies for an early form of breast
cancer are more likely than older women to have the disease come
back, and that may be in in part because surgeons are not removing
enough breast tissue, researchers are reporting Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid it's going to scare people, but I think clinicians
and patients need to know this,'' said Dr. Frank Vicini, a clinical
associate professor of radiation oncology at William Beaumont
Hospital in Royal Oak, Mich., and first author of a study being
published Saturday in the Journal of Clinical Oncology. He
suggested that surgeons performing lumpectomies on younger women
may be reluctant to remove enough of the breast, out of concern for
the women's appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Vicini said his findings applied only to women with ductal
carcinoma in situ, a very early form of breast cancer that is still
confined within the milk ducts. Commonly referred to as DCIS, or
intraductal carcinoma, they are noninvasive, meaning they have not
spread to other tissue in the breast or to lymph nodes or other
parts of the body. The tumors are usually too small to feel, and
most are detected by mammography.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 40,000 cases of intraductal breast cancer per
year in the United States. They are not counted as part of the
180,000 cases of invasive breast cancer diagnosed each year. The
number of intraductal tumors detected has increased sharply during
the past decade because mammography has become more sensitive, and
more women are being screened.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to treat the tumors has been the subject of intense
debate among doctors. Until the past decade, most cases were
treated by mastectomy, which had a cure rate of nearly 100 percent.
But when studies showed that many women with invasive breast cancer
did not need mastectomies, doctors began to question whether women
with DCIS needed the mutilating surgery, either. Medical practice
for DCIS began to shift away from mastectomy and towards a
breast-conserving procedure, lumpectomy with radiation, even though
no studies had been done to compare the two treatments for
intraductal tumors. By 1992, only 44 percent of intraductal tumors
were being treated with mastectomy, and the rest with either
lumpectomy alone or lumpectomy with radiation.
</P>
<P>
   But tumors can recur after lumpectomy and radiation: in various
studies, recurrence rates after five years varied from 6 percent to
21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Vicini's study included 146 women with DCIS who had lumpectomy
and radiation at his hospital from 1980 to 1993. The patients were
followed for a median of 7.2 years. His team found that younger
women were more likely to have recurrences: 26.1 percent of the
younger women had recurrences, as opposed to only 8.6 percent of
the older ones.
</P>
<P>
   Other studies have also shown higher recurrence rates in younger
women, and researchers have assumed that it was because breast
cancer was faster growing and more aggressive in them, and would
come back no matter how extensive the treatment was. But Vicini's
team found that surgical technique may also play a part: the
highest recurrence rates occurred in young women who had the
smallest amount of tissue removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not definitive,'' he warned, saying that the study was
small, with only 17 recurrences, and needed to be confirmed by
other studies.
</P>
<P>
   But a study published in November in the journal Cancer had
similar findings: higher recurrences in young women who had the
least amount of breast tissue removed.
</P>
<P>
   The first author of that study, Dr. Kimberly Van Zee, a breast
surgeon at Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center, said it was
important to remove all the cancer, but that it could be especially
difficult to do so with intraductal tumors because they can spread
widely through the ducts like the branches of a tree. She also said
that intraductal tumors could spread more extensively in younger
women, possibly because their ductal tissue is more open and
interconnected than that of older women, in whom the ducts begin to
break down.
</P>
<P>
   ``More attention is paid towards cosmesis in younger women,''
she said. ``I'm not placing any judgment on that statement. It's a
fact.''
</P>
<P>
   If an entire intraductal tumor is not removed, it is not safe to
assume that radiation will take care of the rest. In fact, the risk
of recurrence within 10 years can be 30 percent to 40 percent.
Faced with those odds, Dr. Van Zee said, some women choose
mastectomy.
</P>
<P>
   Recurrences tend to be local, meaning within the breast. Half
are intraductal once again, but the other half are invasive,
according to Dr. Jeanne Petrek, a breast surgeon at Memorial Sloan
Kettering Cancer Center in New York.
</P>
<P>
   All the surgeons said that a cancer recurrence, even a local
one, is physically and emotionally devastating for most patients. A
woman who has had a course of radiation cannot have another, Dr.
Petrek said, and recurrences are nearly always treated with
mastectomy. Women with invasive recurrences, if they are an early
stage, have ten-year survival rates of 85 percent to 90 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
