<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nurturing Diplomacy At the Waldorf-Astoria &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 31, 1999, the Waldorf-Astoria wanted to be the most Year
2000-ready hotel in New York City. Each of the nearly 1,000
employees on duty knew their midnight drill, thanks to a
color-coded battle plan drawn up in military fashion. The architect
of the plan: Alon Ben-Gurion, grandson of David Ben-Gurion, the
founding father of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Alon Ben-Gurion, 48, has been the manager _ the No. 2 executive
_ at the Waldorf since 1997. As a child, he often visited his
grandfather at many of Israel's best hotels.``Roaming the
corridors, the dining room and swimming pool fascinated me,'' he
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he joined Israel's elite paratroopers _ and was badly
wounded in an ambush during the Yom Kippur War in 1973. Then he
attended Tel Aviv University, ``where I started to poke my fingers
into the hospitality business,'' he said. Then on to Cornell
University for graduate study in hotel management.
</P>
<P>
   At his bar mitzvah, his grandfather told him that ``not
everybody has to be a prime minister.'' None of David Ben-Gurion's
three children or seven grandchildren went into government. ``We
were brought up that every job is respectable, regardless of
whether you wear a tie and suit or wash dishes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wash dishes he did. He started as a busboy in a Tel Aviv
restaurant; one day, he recalled, a patron refused to be served by
a Ben-Gurion, offering to switch places. In that egalitarian
spirit, on one recent evening when the laundry truck showed up
late, he helped unload.
</P>
<P>
   The Ben-Gurion name has its advantages. Last summer, he was able
to attract Ehud Barak, the Israeli prime minister, to stay at the
Waldorf during a visit to New York _ the first time the Waldorf has
demonstrated such clout since Yitzhak Rabin visited seven years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   _Jennifer Frey &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Defense of Auditors  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When PricewaterhouseCoopers catches a cold, James E. Copeland,
chief executive of Deloitte &AMP; Touche, sneezes. And wonders how to
keep employees from leaving to join public companies for the stock
gains that private accounting and consulting firms cannot offer.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission said earlier this month
that most partners of PricewaterhouseCoopers had violated rules
forbidding them from investing in companies they audit. Five
partners were dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Copeland had already arranged to speak last week on the subject,
``Attracting and Keeping Your Best People,'' in a series sponsored
by the Forum Corp., a provider of corporate education and training.
His speech recounted how his firm has maintained the lowest
turnover rate of the Big Five by encouraging the advancement of
women, allowing flexible hours and rewarding employees who recruit
friends.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview, he portrayed the SEC's pressure as an
obstacle. In his view, when the rules conflict with the way members
of accounting and consulting firms might behave, it is time to toss
out the rules, not necessarily the partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to modernize the independence requirements,'' he said.
``They are arcane, archaic, overly complex.''
</P>
<P>
   Spread the wealth, not the blame, he said. ``We have to have
rules that make sense,'' he explained. ``And we have to have the
ability for our consultants to do what they do well and prosper in
this economy as a result of it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Julie Dunn &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Professor Winfrey Gives Herself a B &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oprah Winfrey gives herself a strong but not top grade for the
``Dynamics of Leadership'' course she taught at Northwestern
University's Kellogg Graduate School of Management last fall with
her friend, Stedman Graham. She will teach again this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give myself a B and I'm coming back to get an A because I
now know how to get it,'' Ms. Winfrey said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   After the first lecture, Ms. Winfrey gave herself only a
B-minus. By the end, students generally awarded her A-minus',
citing her experience and guest lecturers including Henry A.
Kissinger; Jeffrey P. Bezos, chief executive of Amazon.com; Robert
A. Iger, the ABC Network chairman, and Coretta Scott King.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her intelligence just shines through,'' said Todd Conroy, who
graduated at the end of the fall quarter. ``She was extremely
knowledgeable on the subject of leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   _Catherine K. Enders
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
