<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-IMAGE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY'S STYLE: SOMETIMES CHARMINGLY FOLKSY, SOMETIMES PRICKLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT17 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley often opens his
campaign events around Iowa with a story about a prickly waitress
and two late-night diners.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about a kind word?'' one of the diners asks the waitress.
She ignores him. When she returns, gruffly tossing down their
plates, the man asks again, ``What about that kind word?'' This
time she relents. ``If I were you,'' she growls, ``I wouldn't eat
them eggs.''
</P>
<P>
   The story is Bradley's lighthearted way of telling audiences he
thinks it is time for greater honesty in American politics. But in
an unintended way, it is also about the dangers of so-called
straight talk. In the race for the Democratic presidential
nomination, Bill Bradley has tried to cast himself as his party's
gruff truth-teller. He talks about poverty though the economy is
soaring. He rails against the corrupting influence of campaign
contributions. He bemoans the persistence of racial injustice.
</P>
<P>
   But in style as well as substance, Bradley often resembles the
rough-edged waitress of his story. He can be curt and
uncommunicative. He sometimes ignores questions he considers silly
or intrusive. Former colleagues say he is aloof. And, as he has
shown in debates with his lone Democratic rival, Vice President Al
Gore, he can be sarcastic and condescending when attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me explain to you, Al, how the private sector works, OK?''
Bradley said patronizingly at a debate earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   To his supporters, such traits are part and parcel of what make
Bradley a different kind of politician, more honest, thoughtful and
trustworthy. To them, Bradley's bristly ways are evidence that he
can see through, and rise above, typical politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm running on the radical premise that you can say what you
believe, and win,'' he often tells audiences.
</P>
<P>
   But to the undecided voters who are vital to his success,
Bradley runs the risk of being viewed as simply surly, someone
whose attacks on regular politics might be viewed as a criticism of
regular voters.
</P>
<P>
   So on a daily basis, Bradley tries to balance his rough-hewn
ways with his folksy humor, seeking to charm voters even as he
offers them tough medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it works. Bradley is easily annoyed by boom mikes that
hang in his face, and he seemed particularly irritated by a fluffy
gray one that kept flitting about his lectern during a speech in
Mason City, Iowa, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than have his staff clear the sound man away, as they
often do, Bradley interrupted his delivery to introduce ``this
little bird that has been following me.'' He then began dodging
around the flustered sound man, drawing laughs from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it falls short. Last fall at St. Anselms College, a
Catholic school in New Hampshire, Bradley opened the floor to
questions with a little joke. ``I'll call on you, and if I don't
like the question, I'll just point to the next person,'' he said to
laughter. ``Wouldn't you like it if politicians just told you what
they think?''
</P>
<P>
   But one of the first questions was one he clearly didn't like:
Would Bradley, as president, veto a ban on later-term abortions?
Bradley, a strong advocate of abortion rights, curtly answered
``Yes.'' And then without pause, or explanation, he turned away and
said, ``Next question.'' For several seconds, an awkward silence
hung over the packed room.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In running as a ``different politician'' who lives by higher
ethical standards, Bradley has also created pitfalls for himself
that other politicians might not face.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when he was asked last week whether he would
release the letters he had written to federal agencies, Bradley
practically invited reporters to check his Senate files. And
without being asked, he offered that he'd be surprised if they
found evidence he had intervened on regulatory matters.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, three letters quickly emerged showing that Bradley
had sought to help New Jersey companies who had contributed to his
campaigns. And while all seemed typical of the letters senators
write on behalf of constituents, Bradley came under criticism
largely because he had made his original claim to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's style may have created the most problems for him
during nationally televised debates where he frequently returned
fire from Gore with scornful sarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   In a December debate, Bradley practically sneered when the Vice
President suggested that both candidates give up campaign
commercials. ``Al, that's good,'' Bradley said, looking at Gore's
outstretched hand. ``I like that hand. But the answer is no.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's aides said the insurgent's barbed remarks then and in
a later debate thrilled his supporters, who have been angered by
Gore's steady attacks on Bradley's record and platform. But the
aides acknowledged that some undecided Democrats might have found
the performances off-putting, and Bradley toned down his sarcasm
during the most recent debate in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the voters who came to Bradley's events do not generally see
his sharper edges. More often than not, the are entertained by an
upbeat, plain-spoken, somewhat goofy guy whose seems remarkably at
ease with the absurd pressures of a presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   An unscheduled late-night visit to a party at an American Legion
hall in Des Moines last week showed off his silly charms. After
shaking a few hands, the candidate suddenly marched up to a table,
grabbed a pitcher of beer and took a chug straight from the
container. The crowd roared appreciatively.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, as he posed with a few supporters, Bradley began
idly tossing a basketball at the feet of the photographers, forcing
them to step back. The crowd laughed. And when his wife, Ernestine,
began dancing with another man, Bradley played the jealous husband,
stomping around in a faux huff, then grabbing another woman and
twirling her gracefully to the sound of ``Unchained Melody'' as her
beer splashed around the floor.
</P>
<P>
   And though Bradley can sound contemptuous when he criticizes
Gore to reporters, Bradley masks such feelings with voters. At the
Mason City event, for instance, he was asked about ``Corn Man,''
the Gore campaign volunteer who follows him around this state
dressed up as huge ears of corn, distributing literature
criticizing Bradley's record on farm policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Real class, you know,'' Bradley said of Corn Man's appearance
that morning, sounding more like a disappointed parent than an
offended candidate. The crowd applauded, and one man even
apologized that a local resident would be so uncouth as to step
into a Corn Man suit.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's efforts to remain a ``normal person'' in an abnormal
situation often involves games of cat-and-mouse with news
reporters, whom he often chides for being overly intrusive. His
campaign has refused to release the names of some advisers,
asserting that they want their privacy protected. And after Bradley
was hospitalized for a bout with irregular heartbeat last month, he
declined to release his full medical history on the grounds that it
would provide more information than people needed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his sparring with reporters is largely invisible to voters,
whose questions he rarely turns aside. In Council Bluffs last
weekend, 17-year-old Lindsay Hamilton approached Bradley following
a speech and asked him his favorite film. ``The Loneliness of the
Long Distance Runner,'' Bradley replied, referring to a 1962 film
based on the eponymous novel by Alan Sillitoe.
</P>
<P>
   But when some eves-dropping reporters asked him about the film,
Bradley demurred, as if the information would allow them to form
off-base judgments about him. ``I don't have one favorite movie,''
he said. ``It's just one of many.''
</P>
<P>
   A day later in Exira, 10-year-old Sarah Anthofer privately asked
Bradley a question that he has repeatedly declined to answer from
reporters: ``If you lose this race, will you run for president
again?'' Later, Ms. Anthofer revealed Bradley's reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, probably,'' he told her.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
