<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-WARCRIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR CRIMES COURT SENTENCES 5 BOSNIAN CROATS FOR MASSACRE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The international war crimes tribunal in the Hague, in
its largest case to date, convicted five Bosnian Croat militiamen
Friday for taking part in the massacre of more than 100 Muslims in
a Bosnian village in April 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling, the court rejected arguments that the massacre in
Ahmici, a village in central Bosnia where Muslims, including
children, were burned alive in their homes _ was a random act.
Instead, the court found that the killings and burnings were part
of an organized effort to terrorize Muslims and get them to leave
the region.
</P>
<P>
   The presiding judge, Antonio Cassese, noted that the killing of
unarmed Muslim civilians had served no military purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indisputably, what happened on April 16, 1993, has gone down
in history as comprising one of the most vicious illustrations of
man's inhumanity to man,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, the name of that small village must be added to the
long list of previously unknown hamlets and towns that recall
abhorrent misdeeds and make us shudder with horror and shame,''
Cassese said, referring to Dachau and My Lai. A total of 116 people
were killed, including 33 women and children.
</P>
<P>
   The court ordered the five men _ Zoran and Mirjan Kupreskic,
their cousin Vlatko Kupreskic, Drago Josipovic and Vladimir Santic
_ to serve sentences from 6 to 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution praised the sentences, saying they set a
benchmark for future cases of ``ethnic cleansing.'' Several
higher-ranking defendants still await verdicts.
</P>
<P>
   The court also acquitted one defendant, Dragan Papic, saying his
role in the local militia was unclear and there was insufficient
evidence to show that he had played an active role in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Since the trial began more than 15 months ago, the three trial
judges had heard testimony from 158 witnesses, some of whom
described in detail the horrors of the day when Ahmici was overrun
by fighters who machine gunned entire families, killed their
livestock and set houses on fire. One witness in the case told how
she stood on a balcony, her dead son below, as jeering Bosnian
Croat soldiers told her to jump.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the five convicted men were convicted of persecution for
helping to organize or taking part in the violence, first shelling,
then house-to-house attacks, as soldiers of the Croatia Defense
Force swept through the Lasva Valley from January to May 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The court described how the five had taken part in a rampage
that resulted in the killing of Muslims and the burning of 169
houses and two mosques. The ``tragic episode'' was aimed at
expelling the Muslims from the village, stopping short of the most
serious war crimes charge, genocide, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the five convicted men said they were shocked by the
ruling and planned to appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
