<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6528 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-TIME-ART-$ADV1     01-14 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-TIME-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE INTEREST OF TELLING ALL, SORT OF  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: opening graf is in italics) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shareholder meetings are not usually the occasion for utter
candor _ or for that matter, arch sarcasm _ by chief executives.
But what if Gerald R. Levin, chief executive of Time Warner, which
announced on Monday that it would merge with America Online, were
to depart from tradition? He might say something like this: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Greetings, fellow shareholders!
</P>
<P>
   As you may be aware, this has been a very exciting year for Time
Warner. In addition to the creative and financial success of movies
like ``Wild Wild West'' and ``The Astronaut's Wife,'' we again
demonstrated the benefits of synergy by the nearly simultaneous
release of ``Pokemon: The First Movie'' and a Time magazine cover
story on the phenomenon. This, of course, follows our flagship
publication's teamwork with the CNN cable network in their 1998
coverage of the Tailwind incident.
</P>
<P>
   We began the new year with a very big bonus for you, the often
beset-upon Time Warner shareholder. After a decade in which our
company's stock nearly matched the Standard and Poor's 500 index,
we began 2000 by announcing the biggest deal in history, when
America Online agreed to buy us for $165 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Did I say America Online agreed to buy us? My mistake. This is a
merger of equals. Sure, America Online shareholders are getting 55
percent of the new company, while we will receive only 45 percent.
But that's almost equal, isn't it? I mean, 55-45 or 50-50 _ who can
tell?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, I get to be chief executive of the new AOL Time Warner,
and chief executive is really more important than chairman. Not
just any executive, mind you, but the top guy, the Numero Uno _
except for Steve Case. Er, Mr. Case.
</P>
<P>
   And no, I could not care less that Steve, um, Mr. Case, is about
20 years younger than me. No, I am pleased that AOL Time Warner
will be in strong hands long after I have retired.
</P>
<P>
   So, shareholders, you may be asking yourself why I agreed to
merge shares in our venerable enterprise for the paper of a company
that barely existed a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   The short answer: I had to.
</P>
<P>
   Let me tell you about Time Warner and its entertainment kin,
which Wall Street is fond of calling growth companies. Yes, over
the past 10 years we've had success with new magazines like InStyle
and even started a television network. But the part of our business
that's really growing is our share base, as we hand out more and
more options to our worthy executives, producers, editors and key
grips. (Even I have no idea how we got to 1.5 billion shares.)
</P>
<P>
   The movie industry is saturated, our music business has stunk
for two years in a row and the circulation of our flagship product,
Time magazine, for years has been as flat as Tori Amos's tummy.
</P>
<P>
   Want the hard numbers for our most recent quarter, ended
September 1999? Revenues were $6.72 billion, a fat 2 percent
increase over the $6.59 billion we posted in the 1998 quarter.
Excluding one-time gains, net income was $110 million, up from $35
million in the same period in 1998. Shareholders, I'll spell it out
for you: a 2 percent net profit margin and 2 percent annual sales
growth isn't Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, our business is celebrities, not, say, groceries,
so investors tend to lose perspective on just how anemic our
returns are. (The hundreds of millions of dollars in investment
banking fees we threw at Wall Street last decade probably help,
too.)
</P>
<P>
   In fact, shareholders, there are only a couple of media
businesses that are growing. Cable networks are pretty decent, and
we have a couple of those. People are starting to believe in the
value of broadband cable systems _ and we are the nation's
second-largest cable system operator.
</P>
<P>
   So before DirecTV took away too many of our cable subscribers, I
decided to trade my assets for the chance at a real growth
business: the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   You might think that the world's largest media company would be
able to get onto the Internet on its own. There you would be wrong.
Entertaindom.com isn't eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some say AOL is overvalued. I can hardly disagree, given
that it trades at about 200 times earnings. But do you know what?
So do we.
</P>
<P>
   True, our shares trade at only about 20 times cash flow, but
despite what we have managed to convince the analyst community,
taxes are a real cost. You've got to pay them, or the government
gets very testy. And, I should add, that goes for interest, too.
This despite our success in focusing Wall Street's attention on
Ebitda, or cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that if I'm going to be trading at a
price-earnings multiple of 200, I would much rather be a real
growth business than a pretend growth business. So when AOL came
knocking, looking to put our cable systems to good use, I was more
than happy to tell Steve, ``I do.''
</P>
<P>
   All in all, considering that AOL was more than twice as highly
valued as we were before Jan. 10, I'm pretty pleased.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for coming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 2025EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
