<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6529 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MOB-BODIES-BOS &LR;      01-14 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-BODIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOB BURIAL SPOT YIELDS BODIES OF TWO MEN, WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Digging through the night shielded from biting cold,
authorities early Friday unearthed the remains of two men and a
woman after being tipped off to the burial spot by a top lieutenant
to fugitive South Boston crime boss James ``Whitey'' Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   While authorities have yet to identify the victims believed to
have been killed by Bulger and his longtime cohort, Stephen Flemmi,
sources said Bulger confidant Kevin Weeks claims Arthur ``Bucky''
Barrett, John McIntyre, and Deborah Hussey, Flemmi's stepdaughter,
were buried in the eight-foot deep grave in the city's Dorchester
section.
</P>
<P>
   Bulger and Flemmi have long been suspects in the murders of
Barrett, one of six men charged with the $1.5 million Depositors
Trust bank heist in suburban Medford in 1980, and McIntyre, who was
suspected of cooperating against Bulger in an ill-fated plot to run
guns to the Irish Republican Army. Barrett disappeared in 1983 and
McIntyre vanished the following year.
</P>
<P>
   And Boston police have for years considered Flemmi a suspect in
the 1984 disappearance of Hussey, 26, who was allegedly about to
expose her sexual affair with Flemmi, her mother's longtime
common-law husband.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks, who has been described as Bulger's ``surrogate son,'' has
turned on Bulger in the wake of his own indictment on federal
racketeering charges in November.
</P>
<P>
   His revelations are expected to bring an avalanche of new
charges against Bulger and Flemmi, both longtime FBI informants,
and possibly against their former handler, retired FBI Agent John
J. Connolly Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Bulger and Flemmi were indicted on federal racketeering charges
in January 1995 that ultimately led to the disclosure that they
were informants. That prompted a number of former cohorts to
cooperate against them.
</P>
<P>
   Bulger remains a fugitive, while Flemmi is in jail awaiting
trial.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Connolly was charged in a new federal racketeering
indictment along with Bulger and Flemmi that alleges he protected
them from crimes and warned them about the 1995 indictment so they
could run.
</P>
<P>
   During a press conference, US Attorney Donald K. Stern and
Suffolk District Attorney Ralph C. Martin 2d confirmed that bones
retrieved during a painstaking search were those of two men and a
woman.
</P>
<P>
   But they refused to identify the victims, noting that it will
likely take a couple of months for DNA tests to determine who they
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have preliminary views of who they might be,'' said Stern,
adding that forensic experts will compare DNA found at the
gravesite with other DNA evidence in an effort to find a match.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investigators quietly notified the families of
McIntyre, Barrett and Hussey about the possibility that their
bodies had been located and began seeking DNA evidence from them to
match with remains found in Dorchester.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett's widow, Elaine, declined to comment Friday but said
investigators told her there was a ``possibility'' one of the
recovered bodies was that of her husband. They also told her
forensic tests must be conducted to confirm identities.
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre's son and Hussey's mother, Marion, both declined to
comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a court ruling last September, US District Judge Mark L. Wolf
concluded there was ``reason to be concerned'' that Connolly had
warned Bulger and Flemmi that McIntyre was cooperating against them
-- a breach that probably would have marked him for death.
</P>
<P>
   In the days before Barrett disappeared, there were rumors
circulating in the underworld that he was cooperating with the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett was among a number of men arrested on April 6, 1983 when
FBI and DEA agents raided a South Boston warehouse loaded with
marijuana. The FBI had apparently received a tip about the
warehouse from Bulger, who was miffed that Charlestown gangster
Joseph Murray was storing drugs in his hometown without his
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Marion Hussey and Flemmi were not married, but they raised her
children from an earlier marriage together in Flemmi's house, a
typical suburban home in Milton, just outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi often referred to Deborah Hussey and her siblings as his
children and was introduced to their friends as their father,
according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Hussey reportedly had problems with drug abuse and had a
criminal record, including an arrest for auto theft.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Dennis J. Kelly, who represents Weeks, declined to
comment Friday on whether Weeks has negotiated a deal with
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi's lawyer, Kenneth Fishman, said only, ``Obviously, if and
when there are additional charges that result from this
investigation we will comment on them at that time and deal with
them at that time.''
</P>
<P>
   The bodies were found underneath about seven to eight feet of
soil along a former freight train railroad spur being converted by
the Metropolitan District Commission into bike path connecting
Castle Island in South Boston to Pope John Paul II park on the
Neponset River.
</P>
<P>
   Although the site is at the edge of a well-lighted parking lot
along a busy street, it was heavily wooded during the early 1980s,
according to neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts State Police, the US Drug Enforcement
Administration, the Internal Revenue Service, the Boston Police and
the Suffolk County Medical Examiner's Office focused with
laser-like precision on the area where the first human bones were
discovered early Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The search was conducted like an archeological dig. Enclosed in
yellow and white striped party tents and warmed by portable
heaters, police and medical examiner staffers used spoons, small
tools and sifting screens to carefully extricate even the smallest
pieces of remains from the mass grave.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the investigation that led them to the bodies was
likely to bring investigators any closer to catching Bulger, Stern
replied, ``Well, we don't believe he was one of the two (male)
bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe staff reporter John Ellement and Globe correspondent Ralph
Ranalli contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
