<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6532 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-PROFILE-DOLMAN-AR     01-14 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-DOLMAN-ART-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING A HIGH TONE AT CHRISTIE'S  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Every morning when Edward Dolman goes to work, he has
to fight his way through the throngs outside the NBC studio windows
as fans try to catch a glimpse of Katie Couric or Matt Lauer on the
``Today'' set.
</P>
<P>
   Dolman slips through unnoticed as he heads to a fifth-floor
office with views of Rockefeller Center's Art Deco towers and its
skating rink.
</P>
<P>
   In the auction and art world, however, where Dolman has worked
for 16 years, his celebrity is growing. On Christmas Eve,
Christie's sent an e-mail message to its staff announcing that he
would be its new chief executive. While the name of Dolman, a
sandy-haired Briton who had risen through the ranks at Christie's,
had been bandied about within the company as a possible successor
to Christopher Davidge, its chief for six years, many of its
clients had never heard of him.
</P>
<P>
   For months, there had been talk that Davidge was on his way out.
Board members say he fought with them and was not liked by Francois
Pinault, the French investor who bought Christie's a year and a
half ago. Pinault, whose holdings also include Printemps, Chateau
Latour and Gucci, has a reputation for studying a company's
performance the first year after he buys it and then changing
management.
</P>
<P>
   Dolman is young for someone in such a position. Asked his age,
he replied coyly, ``39 but I turn 40 in February.'' Dolman's wife,
Clare, is a former journalist. They have two children, ages 9 and
11.
</P>
<P>
   He described his preparation for Christie's with an irreverent
grin. ``I studied economics and history at Dulwich College in
London where I wasn't a particularly good student but I was
obsessed by sport,'' especially rugby, he said. ``From there I went
to Southampton University. By the time I left, I wanted to do
something in the art business.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he did not have the capital to become a dealer and found
the museum world ``too stale,'' he joined Christie's South
Kensington, where lower-priced objects were sold. (Generally, it
took family connections to start at Christie's London headquarters
on King Street.) ``That was in 1984,'' Dolman recalled. ``In those
days if you were male you were made a porter. I was making an
appalling annual salary of 2,800 pounds a year so I gave myself a
year.'' (That pay is about $4,480 at today's exchange rates.)
</P>
<P>
   His rise from porter to chief executive is not a fairy tale come
true but rather a frequent path to an auction house's executive
suites.He was made a junior expert in the English furniture
department exactly a year after his hiring, all the while
continuing to play rugby. ``I'd always been the captain of teams,''
he said. ``I had an obvious aptitude for leading teams.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an aptitude, he said, that he wanted to exploit. In five
years, he worked his way up to join the management team at South
Kensington. There, he reached out to Christie's richer clients, who
had shopped only at the higher-priced King Street or Manhattan
locations, by offering more specialized sales, like ones devoted to
the contents of stately English country homes, and publishing more
elaborate catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized there was a huge appetite for furniture and art
that wasn't expensive but looks the money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One promotion led to another. By 1995, he was managing director
of Christie's in Amsterdam; two years later he was back in London,
where he would become managing director of Christie's for all of
Europe. Last July, he came to New York to run North and South
American operations.
</P>
<P>
   For 200 years, Christie's has had the same goal: to beat
Sotheby's. Sotheby's was the market leader for 43 years until 1997,
when Christie's edged ahead in sales, $1.602 billion to $1.599
billion. They have run neck-and-neck since.
</P>
<P>
   While the companies have had different personalities _ the
cliche is that Christie's has gentlemen trying to be businessmen
and Sotheby's has businessmen trying to be gentlemen _ Pinault has
brought a new distinction. When he bought Christie's for $1.2
billion, he took it private; Sotheby's is still a public company.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues see Dolman as a feet-on-the-ground manager, but not
necessarily a creative deal-maker or strategist. But his
malleability might have helped him win and keep Pinault's favor,
they say.
</P>
<P>
   Dolman takes over as Christie's and Sotheby's, forever copying
each other in business practices, are moving in opposite
directions. In a surprise announcement in November, Christie's said
it would not link up with an Internet company as Sotheby's had done
with Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was great pressure to go into partnership with an
e-commerce company but we felt it would be diluting our brand and
throwing away our expertise,'' Dolman said. ``We realized we
couldn't make enough money selling low-priced, high-volume
merchandise.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Christie's intends to make all aspects of the company
interactive, with online auctions, Internet views of auctions in
sales rooms and technology that lets clients view merchandise on a
virtual-reality Web site _ with the ability, for example, to open
drawers of a piece of furniture.
</P>
<P>
   But with Pinault, known for capitalizing on luxury brand names,
as its owner, people in the art world wonder how he and Dolman plan
to exploit Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no plans to put Christie's name on handbags or
perfume,'' responded Dolman, alluding to Sotheby's failed 1971
introduction of a Sotheby's cigarette. ``We want to concentrate on
the core of our business, the top end of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   To get a return on his investment, however, Pinault, with
Dolman's help, is looking at Christie's real estate holdings. The
company controls one of the most prestigious blocks in London, in
the St. James area. Surveyors recently studied the possibility of
retail and hotel development of the site. Christie's headquarters
on King Street, Dolman said, will stay put.
</P>
<P>
   Dolman, however, said he did not even know which city would be
his own base, though he maintained that London would remain the
company's home. In March, Christie's will open such a large,
well-located building on Avenue Matignon in Paris _ in anticipation
of the the planned opening of the French auction market to
foreigners _ that company employees are speculating whether the
headquarters will move to that city, where Pinault is based. Or
perhaps to New York, the site of its biggest auctions.
</P>
<P>
   But Dolman has a clear notion of how he sees Christie's brand
name versus the competition. ``When people think of Christie's they
will think fine art auctioneers. When they think of Sotheby's they
will think of Sotheby's.Amazon.com or Amazon.Sotheby's.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Which will end up the more profitable _ the auction house going
after the mass market or the one trying to turn a profit from
another record-breaking van Gogh? It is too early to say.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the sportsman _ and the businessman, rather than the
aesthete _ Dolman is betting that as soon as large estates come up
for grabs, Christie's will be more likely to snag them than
Sotheby's, which is now steeped in its Internet endeavors. As
Dolman put it, ``They will have taken their eye off the ball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
