<HEADER>
A6535 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-AMR-FUNDS-ART-     01-14 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-AMR-FUNDS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUYING AIRLINES' MUTUAL FUNDS: IS IT THE RETURN, OR THE MILES?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: R.I., Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic of
performance of American AAdvantage mutual funds is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coffee? Tea? Intermediate-term bond funds?
</P>
<P>
   As if airlines did not face enough competition from fare wars, a
few carriers are now venturing into one of the most competitive
businesses around _ money management. They are offering mutual
funds that compete with those from the giants like Janus, Vanguard
and Fidelity Investments.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways, one of the world's largest airlines, teamed up
with the Royal Bank of Canada to introduce a multiple-currency
money market fund in November that holds cash in bank deposits and
money market securities.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the Virgin Group, the parent of Virgin Atlantic,
British Air's archrival, jolted the staid British fund industry by
opening two no-load equity funds; it now has a tidy $3.65 billion
in assets under management (though no tie-ins yet with Virgin Cola
or Vodka, or with Virgin's record stores).
</P>
<P>
   But the grand fund marketer of the world's carriers is the AMR
Corp., parent of American Airlines. Over the last 12{ years, AMR
has been building a family of funds under the American AAdvantage
brand and now has 10 funds, including three money market funds,
with about $22 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   The funds marketed by American AAdvantage and British Airways
allow them to offer frequent-flier miles to investors, but
investors may want to think twice before buying shares. Returns on
most of the airlines funds have been subpar, and many of the
mileage awards, when an investor does the math, do not come cheap.
</P>
<P>
   People who need just a few miles for an upgrade to a first-class
ticket, for example, might be able to save money by simply buying
miles directly from their favorite airline _ something American
generally does not allow)
</P>
<P>
   British Airways said it would give a one-time award of 500 miles
for an initial investment that exceeds 5,000 pounds (about $8,200).
The American Airlines' funds are more generous _ one mile a year
for every $10 invested in its Mileage class shares. That means an
$8,200 investment would earn 820 miles a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When American Airlines started the funds, they were clearly
unique,'' said Geoff Bobroff, a fund consultant in East Greenwich,
R.I., adding that ``it was very innovative to link miles with
account balances.''
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines' funds offer one clear benefit. Their expenses
are relatively low, according to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago
financial publisher. For example, expenses for the cheapest share
class of the American AAdvantage Large Cap Value fund that is open
to the public, the PlanAhead class, are 0.86 percent, versus 1.33
percent for its peers, according to Morningstar.
</P>
<P>
   While the airlines may seem odd purveyors of mutual funds, the
fit is more natural than it looks. Many airline companies _
including AMR _ have long relied on outside money managers to run
their pension funds and other investments.
</P>
<P>
   AMR soon figured that it could make money by attracting
investments, largely from passengers, and then turning over the
capital to money managers handling its pension fund. As the funds
grew in number and assets, AMR brought in more outside managers,
known as subadvisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``By using a subadviser, the airlines can save on the fund's
expenses,'' said William Dougherty, president of Kanon Bloch Carre,
a Boston consulting company. ``The airlines usually negotiate a
good rate with companies to manage their pension money.'' They then
can use that relationship to get low rates for their fund assets as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The American AAdvantage funds include a balanced fund, large-
and small-capitalization value funds, an international equity fund,
a Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fund, intermediate and short-term
bond funds and three money market funds. (Not all of them, however,
are tracked by Morningstar, and therefore do not appear in the
mutual fund tables of The New York Times.)
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the funds may appeal mainly to conservative or novice
investors; several experts pointed out that the funds have
relatively conservative subadvisers. That leaning is
understandable: an airline would not want to risk losing valued
frequent fliers by exposing them to big losses during a market
downturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you buy the American Airlines fund,'' Dougherty said,
``you may not get a blockbuster, but you won't make a big
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the subadvisers for the AMR funds is Barrow, Hanley,
Mewhinney &AMP; Strauss, for its intermediate bond funds; the Barrow
firm also manages some Vanguard funds. Another is Brandywine Asset
Management, which manages American's small-cap value fund.
</P>
<P>
   In general, airline funds have been lackluster performers of
late. The British Airways currency fund, for example, bills itself
as an alternative to ordinary savings accounts, but its best
performer _ the United States dollar class _ had a 12-month return
of 4.32 percent through Dec. 30, a gain that trails that of many
certificates of deposit and the average money market fund.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Nor have most ofthe AAdvantage funds, perhaps because of their
conservative bent, looked like dynamos. The Mileage class of the
American AAdvantage International Equity fund, for example, notched
a three-year annualized gain of 15.09 percent through December,
according to Lipper Inc., a fund research firm. That puts it in
well into the bottom half of the 394 funds in its peer group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Airlines funds have not reached a high-powered
performance,'' Bobroff said. ``But this is a sideline business for
AMR. They may not have dedicated all the resources internally that
the business needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many mutual funds, those offered by AMR have several
classes of shares. Investors who want frequent-flier miles buy the
Mileage class; financial advisers and those who are not interested
in the points can buy the PlanAhead class. AMR employees can buy
the AMR class, and institutions _ or those who with a minimum of $2
million to invest _ buy the institutional class.
</P>
<P>
   Each class has a different set of fund expenses. For the Large
Cap Value fund, investors in the Mileage class pay 1 percent of
assets annually, according to Morningstar, compared with 0.86
percent for the PlanAhead class, 0.31 percent for the AMR class and
0.57 percent for the institutional class.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of airline funds say that American is too stingy with
the miles it awards and that the increased expenses for Mileage
class investors, in comparison to those for the PlanAhead share
classes that don't provide miles, are not a good deal.
</P>
<P>
   It helps to do the math: an investor who puts $10,000 in the
Mileage class of the international fund pays 1.48 percent in
expenses and receives 1,000 frequent flier miles a year. Those who
buy PlanAhead shares of the same fund would pay just 1.08 percent a
year and receive no miles. The cost to the Mileage class
shareholders? Four cents a mile.
</P>
<P>
   But the going rate for a frequent-flier mile is 2.5 cents,
according to InsideFlyer, which tracks frequent flier perks. And
miles can be had for even less than that. MCI and Citibank, for
example, routinely buy miles from the airlines for consumer
giveaways and seldom pay more than 1.5 cents each.
</P>
<P>
   The other American AAdvantage funds don't have the same wide gap
in expense ratios between those share classes. But none of this
takes into account the price an investor is paying because of the
relative underperformance of the funds compared with their peers.
</P>
<P>
   A better deal appears to be the three American AAdvantage money
market funds available to the public. Their three-year performances
are all well above average.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Gallagher, director of marketing for AMR Investments,
said the mileage shares ``are for our customers who are real
collectors of miles.'' Such customers find the free miles just as
important as expenses and a good return, she said.
</P>
<P>
   AAdvantage Mileage shares are not reversible _ that is, if
investors earn more frequent-flier miles than they can use, they
cannot convert them into dollars to invest in the funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're flying 200,000 miles each year, chances are you
already have a 401(k) plan taking care of you,'' said Edward S.
Rosenbaum, research director at Lipper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
