<SLUG> BC-UN-TIMOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR-CRIMES TRIBUNAL FOR TIMOR UNLIKELY, ENVOYS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAURIA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The UN Security Council, which responded to Yugoslav
and Rwandan atrocities by ordering the first international
war-crimes courts since the end of World War II, appears unlikely
to follow suit in East Timor, UN officials and diplomats said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition from China and Russia and questions about financing
might doom an international court, say the UN officials, who spoke
on condition they not be named.
</P>
<P>
   For now, diplomats such as US Ambassador Richard init? Holbrooke
are pinning their hopes on an internal tribunal held by Indonesia,
whose military controlled East Timor from 1975 until August and is
blamed by human-rights groups for the atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is watching to determine whether the Indonesia
leadership has the strength to impose its own internal inquiry
without an international inquiry. . . . If the people in the
military continue to oppose it, they will do great damage to their
country and will bring international pressure to a much higher
level,'' Holbrooke told reporters here and by telephone to
Indonesian officials Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In Yugoslavia and Rwanda, the international tribunals found
evidence that senior political and military leaders had ordered
numerous mass killings, the targeting of civilians and rape as a
means to conduct war.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the horrors of those places were evoked when at least
hundreds of people were slaughtered after East Timor voted in a
UN-run referendum for independence from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke's hope that Indonesia can prosecute its own war
criminals comes despite intimidation of investigators there and
stonewalling by military leaders suspected of organizing atrocities
carried out by militias.
</P>
<P>
   However, Holbrooke told reporters that the ``international
pressure for a tribunal will increase directly to the extent that
the Indonesians cannot settle this problem internally.''
</P>
<P>
   The UN sent a commission of inquiry to the newly independent
territory last November for nine days to see if a war crimes court
is warranted. Its report, called ``tough'' by one official, was
given this week to UN Secretary General Kofi Annan, who will
forward it to the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is extremely unlikely the council will create a new
(international) tribunal because they can't persuade Russia and
China,'' said one of the officials. ``If a political decision is
made, then we can find the money.''
</P>
<P>
   The UN's commission of inquiry was faced with many obstacles
while it was in the area. The Indonesian government, for instance,
would not allow it to interview East Timorese who had fled to West
Timor. Opposition from many Asian governments, including China, had
also delayed the commission's departure to the area for two months.
</P>
<P>
   The United States would continue to deny military to military
cooperation with Indonesia until there is accountability for the
crimes committed, Holbrooke said.
</P>
<P>
   He also responded to persistent rumors of a military coup in
Jakarta. ``It would do Indonesia perhaps irreparable damage. Any
Indonesian army officers thinking of military adventurism, have
forgotten we are now in the 21st Century, the events of the past
cannot be repeated. No rational Indonesian would want it, except
the few people trying to protect their own skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Saunders, deputy Asia director of Human Rights Watch, agrees
that a meaningful prosecution in Indonesian courts is still
possible. ``Right now it doesn't look good, however, there is
tremendous intimidation of some of the Indonesian investigators and
the generals are getting worried. There's a civilian-military power
struggle going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said, ``A huge struggle is continuing on all fronts
between the forces of progress of President Wahid and Indonesian
military who are protecting themselves, refusing accountability and
openness and thwarting the process.''
</P>
<P>
   The question of justice for East Timor hinges on the outcome,
Holbrooke said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
