<HEADER>
A6545 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-CITY-OF-ANGELS-REV     01-14 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CITY-OF-ANGELS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CITY OF ANGELS' COULD GET BETTER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: EMBARGOED until Sunday, Jan. 16; in this story, tonight is
Sunday. Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The show: ``City of Angels.'' &QL; 
What: Drama about the challenges facing an inner-city hospital. &QL; 
The stars: Blair Underwood, Vivica A. Fox, Michael Warren, Hill
Harper, T.E. Russell, Robert Morse, Phil Buckman, Maya Rudolph,
Viola Davis. &QL; 
Where: CBS. &QL; 
When: 8 tonight, then 8 p.m. Wednesdays. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By David Kronke &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV Critic
</P>
<P>
   ``City of Angels'' is prime-time network television's great
black hope. Given the fall season's all-white-all-the-time lineup,
the mere astonishing fact that this is the only drama on the major
networks with a predominantly minority cast rates it immediate and
significant attention, but it also places an undue burden on this
show. Just as a minority character on a show shouldn't be
considered representative of a particular race, this show or its
fate with viewers shouldn't be considered representative of all
series with pointedly multiethnic casts.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if they were all this good, that certainly wouldn't
be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   You wonder if this series would even make it to the tube if it
weren't under the aegis of Steven Bochco (collaborating with his
A-list, Emmy-winning ``NYPD Blue'' director Paris Barclay).
Bochco's first CBS series, incidentally, was ``Paris,'' starring
James Earl Jones as a police captain. It passed quickly from the
airwaves despite critical acclaim and adoration of its target
audience _ and is often, along with Tim Reid's ``Frank's Place,''
cited as an example that quality series exploring African-American
issues can't sustain big enough audiences to survive on network TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``City of Angels'' focuses on Angels of Mercy, a crumbling urban
Los Angeles hospital running more on heart than adequate equipment,
held together by the sweat and passion of its dedicated physicians.
As befitting a Bochco production, ``City of Angels'' opens with a
splash, in a shocking sequence that catches Garrett Morris, as a
soon-to-be-dethroned administrator, in a compromising position.
</P>
<P>
   The series nails the telling details of a hospital suffering
from terminal neglect _ the two indifferent reporters attending a
press conference about a blues singer's death, the destructive
administrative mindset that prefers spending money to settle a
nuisance lawsuit rather than make meaningful, genuine improvements.
</P>
<P>
   And the cast, led by Blair Underwood as Dr. Ben Turner and
Vivica A. Fox as Dr. Lillian Price, the newly ensconced medical
director, shows the facility to switch from earnest drama to high
comedy at a moment's notice. Robert Morse, as the dubiously
motivated and apparently besotted politico in whose hands the
hospital's fate rests, is a nicely quixotic character whose
peccadilloes the writers carry a whit too far.
</P>
<P>
   The racial tensions existing within the TV industry itself are
manifested in some fairly self-conscious moments on screen: One
character jokingly introduces himself to a Jewish resident
physician, ``Greetings _ I'm a black man.'' It's self-conscious
about its quirky plotting and inside jokes, as well. Two patients
who share a common name are confused; one ends up in the morgue and
the other ends up nearly getting the wrong operation. There's one
outlandish storyline, however, that provides a particularly
appropriate and wonderfully tasteless dig at the Golden Globe
Awards in episode two.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, however, the series' biggest challenge seems to
be coming up with medical stories that are as compelling as they
are convoluted. In tonight's episode, an elderly woman needing
surgery refuses it because she's her grandchildren's legal guardian
and fears losing custody if she's out of commission _ and the only
solution is to bust the mother out of jail. Semi-legally, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a doctor endangers a patient he assumes to be a
gang member by first attending to others with less dire injuries,
which inevitably leads to a message about the evils of prejudice,
even if it's intraracial. The gospel wailing on the sound track
(``All right, oh yeah, ooh oooh'') is significantly more emotional
than the scenes it plays over, making it feel terribly
manipulative. It likewise wasn't necessary to give Turner and Price
an only-in-Hollywood past love affair. The actors' chemistry
supercedes such a back story, and, at any rate, they have enough to
do restoring the hospital's vital signs. Using their personal
feelings as an obstacle feels like a bit of a cheat.
</P>
<P>
   So far, ``City of Angels'' is a solid, fairly smart series that
doesn't quite reach out and grab the viewer as Barclay and Bochco's
previous collaborations have done. But a cast capable of doing that
when the writing hits its stride is definitely in place. When
Underwood tells Fox, ``Make this a proud place again,'' he seems to
be referring to the predominantly white television landscape as
much as Angels of Mercy. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 2036EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
