<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL NEWS IN BRIEF  
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: CONVICTIONS OVERTURNED
</P>
<P>
   Citing procedural errors by the prosecution, an appeals court
overturned the murder convictions of 24 pro-government Indians from
the state of Chiapas, in a case stemming from a 1997 incident in
which 45 unarmed people, mainly women and children, were killed.
The victims were sympathizers of the Zapatista rebels. Prosecutors
can present their case again, and the accused will remain in jail.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: ALBRIGHT IN TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has arrived in Cartagena
for two days of talks with President Andres Pastrana on a trip that
will also take her to Panama and Mexico. The talks follow a
two-year plan announced by Washington to funnel $1.3 billion in
emergency help to Colombia, much of it for military equipment and
training to fight leftist guerrilla groups.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA: U.S. AID SPURNED
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has delayed the arrival in Venezuela of two U.S.
ships, on their way with 450 marine and navy engineers to help the
country rebuild from floods and landslides. The action came after
President Hugo Chavez was quoted as saying he did not want American
troops on Venezuelan soil. ``Clearly, if they don't want the help,
we won't provide it,'' the Defense Department spokesman, Kenneth H.
Bacon, said.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: EMERGENCY PACKAGE
</P>
<P>
   President Fernando de la Rua introduced to Congress an emergency
economic package that would allow him to fire thousands of
government workers and refinance the public debt. The legislation
also requests authority to create special judges to prosecute tax
evasion.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: BARAK AND ARAFAT TO MEET
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak will take a break from negotiations
with Syria to meet with the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, in
Washington next Thursday, Foreign Minister David Levy announced.
Thursday is also the day that Israeli is expected to undertake
another large withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: KOHL TO TESTIFY
</P>
<P>
   Former Chancellor Helmut Kohl was summoned as the first witness
by a parliamentary committee investigating his use of secret funds
channeled to his Christian Democratic Party. The panel, which will
press Kohl to reveal the identity of donors of more than $1 million
during his tenure, begins work next Wednesday, and he is likely to
appear soon after that.
</P>
<P>
   FINLAND: CLOSE VOTE PREDICTED
</P>
<P>
   Opinion polls for Sunday's first round of balloting for the
successor to President Martti Ahtisaari shows former Prime Minister
Esko Aho, the Center Party candidate, running even with the Social
Democrat, Foreign Minister Tarja Halonen. No one is expected to win
more than 50 percent of the vote, and a runoff is scheduled for
Feb. 6.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: BASQUE LEADER FREED
</P>
<P>
   Jose Antonio Urrutikoetxea, 48, a former top commander of the
Basque separatist group ETA, left prison after the high court freed
him on the ground that he had been convicted in France in 1990 on
the same terrorism charges he faced in Spain, where he was sent in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA: LEADER EMERGES
</P>
<P>
   Stipe Mesic, 66, Croatia's last representative to the Yugoslavia
that broke apart in 1991, has emerged as a narrow leader in the
presidential race to succeed the late Franjo Tudjman, according to
a poll to be published by the newspaper Jutarnji List on Saturday,
Reuters reported. The first round of elections will be held on Jan.
24.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: FALUN GONG SENTENCE
</P>
<P>
   A court has sentenced a retired senior air force official, 74,
to 17 years in prison on charges he was an organizer of the Falun
Gong spiritual group, according to the Information Center of Human
Rights and Democratic Movement in China, based in Hong Kong. Yu
Changxin was formerly a pilot and Air Force Command Institute
professor. The Ministry of Defense would not confirm the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
