<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6557 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-SHOW-ART-2     01-14 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-SHOW-ART-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARMAKERS GO ONLINE AND OFF ROAD AT DETROIT AUTO SHOW  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By JAMES G. COBB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ In a simpler time, carmakers came to auto shows simply
to dazzle the public with their latest, sleekest designs. But the
car business is hardly so easy now; at this year's North American
International Auto Show here, the companies seem to be trying to
figure out whether to go online, off road, onto the racetrack or
simply out of the box.
</P>
<P>
   At press previews for the show, which opened this weekend at
Cobo Center, the automakers seemed to be rushing headlong in all
directions, and their collective efforts sometimes looked like
chaos theory embodied in sheet metal.
</P>
<P>
   This smokestack industry is clearly trying to find its place in
a digital universe, to relate to the inscrutable ``echo boom''
generation that will soon be buying vehicles in large numbers, and
to keep pace with rapid advancements in pollution controls, safety
devices and alternative-fuel technology.
</P>
<P>
   But most obviously, manufacturers tried to show that they can
meet consumers' contradictory demand for brutish trucks that handle
and ride like plush sedans but have the cubbyholes, miniclosets and
power outlets of a house trailer. And still, of course, the
industry must offer something for the romantics who thrill to
sleek, fast automobiles and the gearheads who keep tabs on who's
who in motorsports.
</P>
<P>
   Gearheads are not the core demographic group likely to be
impressed by the 24.7, Ford's vision of the car as a sort of
computing platform that could deliver information anywhere _ 24
hours a day, 7 days a week. Three variations on this theme _ a
wagon, pickup and coupe _ share squared-off, simplistic styling and
advanced voice-activated technologies that would let drivers
personalize the controls, make phone calls and manage e-mail on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford, like its competitors, seems to think that while some
young people want to be connected all the time, others are itching
to get away from it all, or at least to leave that outdoorsy
impression as they sit in rush-hour jams.
</P>
<P>
   As if in anticipation of the smaller, gentler Hummer that
General Motors displayed, based on a pickup truck chassis, and the
equally macho Dodge MaxxCab pickup, Ford served up a design study
called the Equator, a brutal four-door utility vehicle with a
pickup box. And it rolled out its sixth production SUV, the compact
Escape, which will challenge the Honda CR-V and Toyota RAV4 in the
$20,000 range when it goes on sale this summer.
</P>
<P>
   A sibling, the Mazda Tribute, shares the Escape's mechanical
components and carlike unit body, but has distinct styling. Ford
expects to sell 100,000 Escapes a year to newlyweds and the ``young
at heart.''
</P>
<P>
   GM is covering some of the same ground at its auto-show display,
a sprawling two-level edifice that pulled all of the company's
brands together for the first time. With a mosh pit of hired
teen-agers shouting approval, Pontiac presented the Aztek, the
company's first attempt to bridge the gap between car, van and SUV.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the front-drive Montana minivan, the Aztek will have
optional all-wheel drive. It also has a cabin filled with storage
trays and compartments, along with a lift-out cooler in the center
console.
</P>
<P>
   The product planners, trying to erase the lines that once
separated cars, trucks and vans, were also busy melding the pickup
and sport utility vehicle. GM's first attempt, and its answer to
new ``crossover'' trucks from Ford, is the Chevrolet Avalanche, an
aggressively styled four-door with a short cargo bed. The cargo
capacity of the Avalanche can be expanded by flipping down the back
seats, removing the rear window and dropping the ``midgate'' that
separates the cabin from the pickup bed. Subaru and Nissan, among
others, have shown similar designs.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler's crossover design, the Jeep Varsity, ``blurs
the line between boulevard and boulder,'' said Tom Gale, executive
vice president of product development and design. Although styled
like a Jeep, the Varsity is shorter than the existing grand
cherokee and more carlike than any Jeep yet.
</P>
<P>
   Even Volkswagen showed an interest in jumping into the game,
introducing a design study called the Advanced Activity Concept.
This stylish extended-cab pickup has a plush interior with a
distinct SUV flavor; indeed, it is based on the platform of a
utility vehicle that VW hasn't yet brought to market.
</P>
<P>
   Other SUV design studies at the show included the Acura MD-X,
destined to replace the SLX built by Isuzu; the Suzuki XL6, the
largest and fanciest vehicle yet from that company, and three
sharp-edged Isuzus. One of these, the Kai, a combination of rounded
shapes, sharp edges and origami-like highlights, ``is a return to
traditional Japanese architecture,'' said Scott Hyde, Isuzu's
director of product planning. Mechanical components, including
parts of the suspension, are left visible.
</P>
<P>
   Ford made a safety announcement with implications for other SUV
makers, promising to offer rollover-protection air bags in its 2001
utilities. These high, side-mounted bags would be tripped by
sensors that detect an imminent rollover and they would stay
inflated for up to six seconds _ far longer than conventional bags
_ in case a vehicle rolled several times.
</P>
<P>
   Among the show's concept cars _ design studies aimed at gauging
public opinion, many of them obviously future models wearing thin
veils _ one standout was the Jaguar F-Type. A sensuous roadster
based on sketches made by Geoff Lawson, the highly regarded head of
Jaguar design until his death last year, the F-Type is destined to
become a smaller alternative to the company's XJR sports car,
priced against the Porsche Boxster in the $40,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes-Benz showed two roadsters, one large and one small, and
Chrysler, its sibling brand, rolled out the 300 Hemi C, which seeks
to recapture the excitement created by Chrysler's luxurious
high-performance 300-Series cars of the 1950s and 1960s. Unlike any
current Chrysler, this imposing convertible has rear-wheel drive
along with a 353-horsepower V8 engine. It could become the flagship
that Chrysler brand executives have long been seeking.
</P>
<P>
   After years in which budget constraints at GM resulted in crops
of concept cars that rarely won critical acclaim, the company took
back at least part of the spotlight. One of the show's unqualified
hits was the Chevrolet SSR, a sporty, low-slung pickup that evoked
both Chevy trucks of the early 1950s and the later El Camino _
itself a car-truck combination that presaged the crossovers so
popular this year. GM executives enthusiastically confirmed that
the SSR, although ostensibly only a design study, was on a ``fast
track'' for production.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Another distinctive GM show car, the Buick LaCrosse, offered a
fresh, flowing interpretation of Buick's distinctly American
styling heritage, complete with ``porthole'' trim along the sides
of the hood and ``suicide doors'' that open from the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda's RX-Evolv, a stylish four-door sports car with a
rejuvenated rotary engine, made its North American debut. Infiniti
took the wraps off its first-ever concept car, the XVL, which is
likely to be produced as a rear-drive competitor to the BMW
3-Series and the new Lexus IS 300.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies made technology announcements. Ford said that
it would sell a family of electric vehicles under the Think brand
name and that it would offer by 2003 a family-sized hybrid car with
both an internal-combustion engine and electric drive. GM showed
the Precept, a diesel-electric hybrid said to be capable of fuel
economy in the 80 mpg range.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a breakfast speech, the president of Toyota, Fujio Cho,
called on automakers to work together on environmental issues. ``To
reach our goals as an industry, we must continue to cooperate in
the laboratory and compete in the showroom,'' said Cho, the first
top Toyota executive to attend the Detroit auto show.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the Detroit show is also the delivery room for
the newborn vehicles that will crawl to market in coming months,
and plenty of 2001 models made their debuts. Of particular note
were the fourth-generation minivans from DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   While breaking no ground in styling, the vans will have added
safety features and conveniences like a power rear liftgate and a
removable center console with power accessories. Another family
hauler, the next Volvo V70 wagon, was also introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota fired a shot at Detroit in the sport-utility wars,
unveiling a big SUV based on its full-size Tundra pickup. Called
the Sequoia, it is close in size to the popular Ford Expedition,
and, with an expected starting price in the mid-$30,000 range, will
be priced well below the existing Toyota Land Cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   Executives and engineers from GM, Ford and DaimlerChrysler
repeatedly dropped by the Toyota display to try out the Sequoia's
ingenious second-row seat that can be released with one hand to
fold neatly for access to the third seating row. Those seats also
slide, fold and come out in a variety of ways.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota's Lexus division also showed its next flagship sedan, the
LS 430, with a bigger V8 engine and an array of sybaritic luxury
features, including seats with built-in massagers and a
chilled-beverage compartment. More sophisticated even than its
famously quiet-riding predecessor, the new LS will more directly
challenge the big Mercedes S-Class sedans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These were among other categories of vehicles making news at the
show:
</P>
<P>
   _ Convertibles. New models included the BMW 3-Series, Mitsubishi
Eclipse and Audi TT Roadster. Rolls-Royce reintroduced its Corniche
convertible (base price: $359,990) and VW confirmed that it would
build a New Beetle convertible in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   _ Luxury cars. Acura showed its CL coupe, redesigned for 2001 at
prices starting at $28,000. Audi added a version of its A8 luxury
sedan with a wheelbase five inches longer, giving more room to rear
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Small cars. Nissan showed an all-new Sentra, with a clean,
simple appearance. Kia introduced a four-door hatchback, the
Spectra, that will start around $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sport utilities. New production vehicles making their debuts
included the compact Hyundai Santa Fe, a redesigned Mitsubishi
Montero and a new, small two-door, the Daewoo Korando, that will be
among the least-expensive sport utility vehicles in America.
</P>
<P>
   Several manufacturers announced initiatives in auto racing.
Dodge displayed the Intrepid R/T that will race in the Nascar
Winston Cup series in 2001. Audi said it would compete in the
American Le Mans racing series this year.
</P>
<P>
   Even Daewoo was eager to note its sporting connections, having
entered its small Nubira car in the Sports Car Club of America's
Pro Rally Series last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
