<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAROLINA-PRIMARIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JUSTICE DEPTARTMENT IS EXAMINING THE SOUTH CAROLINA PRIMARIES 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., S.C.)   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Alerted to the closing of polling places in black
neighborhoods during South Carolina's last Republican presidential
primary, the Justice Department has begun asking pointed questions
about both parties' coming primaries, political officials around
the state said Friday. The inquiry raises the possibility that the
primaries could be challenged by the government under the Voting
Rights Act.
</P>
<P>
   If the government finds that the poll closings violate the
voting rights of blacks, the Republican Party _ whose Feb. 19
primary is critical to the presidential hopes of Gov. George W.
Bush and Sen. John McCain _ faces the possibility of having to
spend hundreds of thousands of dollars to open every polling place
in the state, which was not done in previous primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats could also then have to cancel their March 9
primary and move to a caucus system, said the party's state
chairman, Richard A. Harpootlian, because like the Republicans the
Democrats were not planning to open every polling place in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Neither party wants to spend the money to open polling places in
each of the state's 1,914 precincts, but neither party informed the
Justice Department of its plans to deviate from the procedures used
in the general election, as they are required to do under the
Voting Rights Act. While the inquiry began after a complaint to the
Justice Department last week that was instigated by Democrats, both
parties realized that the department had never been informed that
the parties picked their own polling places in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department would not comment on the issue Friday,
but several people who had been called by the department's lawyers
said they had asked about the precise mechanics of the primaries,
and whether the voting methods had ever been cleared with the
department. A. Lee Parks, an Atlanta lawyer who drafted the
original complaint, said he had been told the department was
conducting an expedited inquiry, in order to get the matter
resolved before Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Republican state chairman, Henry McMaster,
issued an appeal Friday for more volunteers to work at polling
places on Feb. 19, in order to show the Justice Department that the
primary would be conducted fairly. At the moment, the party has
enough volunteers to open more than 1,000 polling places, he said,
but not enough for each precinct. Some polling places would have to
be consolidated with others, he said, but he promised that race
would not be a factor in which ones would remain closed.
</P>
<P>
   Opening polling places in each precinct would cost the party
more than $500,000, he said, compared with the $150,000 it has
budgeted.
</P>
<P>
   He accused the Democrats of concocting the issue to embarrass
the party and reduce black turnout in the Republican primary.
Although there are few black Republicans, South Carolina has an
open system that does not require party affiliation to vote in a
primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this whole thing is about is, they don't want black
people voting in our Republican primary,'' McMaster said. ``They
see us getting all the attention. They see their base getting soft.
So what they do is play the race card and falsely accuse us of
keeping black people out of the primary. They're trying to inflame
public opinion against us, and I think they should be ashamed of
this kind of race baiting.''
</P>
<P>
   McMaster, a former U.S. attorney, said he did not believe a
presidential primary was covered by the Voting Rights Act, which
was intended to prevent discrimination in voting. But either way,
he said, the party would do whatever it took to conduct a
completely open primary.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party has not denied, however, that many polling
places in black areas were not open in the 1992 and 1996 primaries.
Party officials said that was because they did not have enough
volunteers to open polls in heavily Democratic areas _ many of
which were mostly black _ because few Republicans tended to vote
there.
</P>
<P>
   Harpootlian was unapologetic _ and perhaps the slightest bit
gleeful _ at having helped point out this fact to the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy that the Republicans will now have to live up to
their rhetoric,'' he said. ``Bush and McCain travel the country and
urge African-Americans to participate, while the state party is
bleaching the primary so African-Americans can't vote. It's time
for them to either shut up or open up all the precincts.''
</P>
<P>
   But Harpootlian, who had earlier said his party's primary would
be open in all precincts, acknowledged Friday that it did not have
the resources to do so. If the Democrats need to keep all polls
open to comply with the Voting Rights Act, he said, they could
switch to a caucus system, where voters informally elect delegates
to a state convention that later picks the state nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic vote is not as important as the Republican
primary because it comes after more significant primaries. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
