<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans Are No Longer Investing for the Long Term
</P>
<P>
   Investing in the stock market for the long term, the strategy
that has made the most sense and the most money for people over the
years, is all but dead. Last year, investors held stocks for just
over eight months on average, well short of the two years that was
typical a decade ago. Among Nasdaq stocks, the average holding
period was five months. The trading frenzy has even infected the
staid mutual fund world: investors are holding funds for less than
four years on average, while a decade ago, investors held mutual
funds for 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Price Index Rises Slightly
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Price Index rose 0.2 of 1 percent in December, a
figure that was lower than expected and showed inflation remains
under control, even as the economy roars toward a record for
uninterrupted expansion. Combined with reassuring comments from the
chairman of the Federal Reserve, Alan Greenspan, on Thursday, the
report set off a rally in stocks but that fervor was cooled after a
report from the University of Michigan showed consumer optimism at
a record high, reviving fears of overheating and pushing interest
rates higher.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of AOL and Time Warner Dip
</P>
<P>
   The shares of America Online declined $1.3125, or 2 percent, to
$63.1875, while Time Warner's fell 75 cents, to $83.25, as
investors struggled to figure out the financial outlook for the
$165 billion merger the two companies announced on Monday. The only
new development Friday was AOL's filing of documents outlining the
merger agreement with the Securities and Exchange Commission. The
filing disclosed that if America Online cancels the deal and is
bought by another company within a year, it must pay a breakup fee
to Time Warner of $5.4 billion. If Time Warner pulls out and is
acquired within a year, it must pay America Online $3.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann Chief Fights Takeover
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Mannesmann AG issued his formal response to
Vodafone AirTouch's $140 billion takeover bid, urging shareholders
to reject the proposal because a takeover would slow his company's
growth. The chairman also said Mannesmann might spin off its
Internet business.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea Revives Rocket Plans
</P>
<P>
   Now that South Korea's economy has started to recover from the
Asian financial crisis, the country plans to revive its attempt to
develop a rocket that can carry satellites into orbit within five
years so that it can join the ranks of space-faring nations.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Industrials Hit Another Record
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average surged to a record for the
third time this week, propelled by a strong earnings report from
Intel and diminished concerns about higher interest rates. The Dow
Jones industrials closed at 11,722.98, up 140.55 points, or 1.21
percent. The Nasdaq composite index gained 107.06 points, or 2.71
percent, to 4,064.49, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
increased 15.47 points, or 1.07 percent, to 1,465.15.
</P>
<P>
   Tyco Plans to Sell Auto Auction Unit
</P>
<P>
   Tyco International agreed to sell its ADT Automotive car auction
unit for $1 billion in cash to Manheim Auctions, a unit of the
privately held Cox Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Battle for Phone Concern Settled
</P>
<P>
   British Telecommunications will give as much as 49.99 percent of
Irish telephone company Esat Telecom Group to Telenor of Norway in
exchange for 50 percent of Esat's mobile telephone subsidiary,
settling a battle for control of the Irish concern.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Financial Markets Closed
</P>
<P>
   United States financial markets will be closed on Monday in
observance of Martin Luther King's Birthday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
