<HEADER>
A6573 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-XRAY-ASTRONOMY-NY     01-14 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-XRAY-ASTRONOMY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNUSUALLY COOL AND CLOSE BLACK HOLE IS DISCOVERED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Looking into the deep sky with new eyes, the Chandra
X-Ray Observatory has taken the temperature of a surprisingly
``cool'' black hole at the core of the nearby Andromeda galaxy,
examined stars in infancy and death and tracked the debris from an
exploded star, the stuff out of which planets may take shape.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers analyzing data from a smaller X-ray satellite and
radio telescopes have discovered the closest black hole yet _ 1,600
light-years from Earth, which is relatively nearby on the cosmic
scale of things. But not to worry. Scientists said the object with
the awesome gravitational power to consume matter in its
neighborhood was still far enough away and of modest enough
strength to pose no danger, even if it might inspire another
cosmic-killer movie from Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The new findings from X-ray observations were reported here
Friday at a meeting of the American Astronomical Society. Much of
the attention at the meeting has been focused on the first reports
of results from the Chandra observatory, which was launched into
orbit around Earth last July and is now handing astronomers and
theorists new insights and puzzles, particularly concerning black
holes.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephen S. Murray of the Harvard-Smithsonian Center for
Astrophysics in Cambridge, Mass., said the Chandra observations of
the Andromeda galaxy had pinpointed X-rays emanating from the
galaxy's central black hole, a known compact object with the mass
of 30 million suns.
</P>
<P>
   The energies of the X-rays, Murray reported, revealed that the
gas plunging into the black hole is remarkably cool, a few million
degrees Celsius. In contrast, the typical radiations from stars
elsewhere in the galaxy reflect temperatures of several tens of
millions of degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the low radio and X-ray temperature readings from the
black hole, Murray said at a news conference, ``We obviously need
some new ideas to explain this object.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Eliot Quataert, an astrophysicist at the Institute for
Advanced Study in Princeton, N.J., said, ``The Chandra observation
is telling us that an entirely different flow pattern is operating
around the Andromeda black hole.''
</P>
<P>
   In another report, astronomers described the fireworks of stars
being born and dying in Messier 82, the nearest of what are often
called starburst galaxies. The unsettled conditions there are
thought to be the result of a near collision with another galaxy
about 100 million years ago. The X-ray data provided astronomers
with previously unobserved details of exploding stars, black holes,
hot gas, powerful galactic winds and binary systems that contain a
normal star in a close orbit around a dead compact star or a black
hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the disk of our Milky Way galaxy, stars form and die in a
relatively calm fashion like burning embers in a campfire,'' said
Dr. Richard Griffiths of Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh.
``But in a starburst galaxy, star birth and death are more like
explosions in a fireworks factory.''
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers from Pennsylvania State University described
Chandra's detection of more than 1,000 young stars in the Orion
Nebula, including some objects so small that they may fail to reach
stardom and wind up as brown dwarfs, stellar objects not large
enough to have nuclear furnaces. Many of these details had never
been seen before.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time X-ray astronomy has resolved individual
massive stars still embedded in their natal cloud,'' said Dr. Leisa
Townsley, a research associate at Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gordon P. Garmire of Penn State reported on more Chandra
observations of X-ray sources coming from black holes so deep in
space that they must have existed soon after the universe began
organizing itself into large structures like galaxies. Like similar
evidence reported on Thursday at the conference, these findings
seemed to suggest that some early black holes may have appeared
before galaxies, which then formed around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're exploring to the very edge of the universe to learn the
history of these black holes and where galaxies come from,''
Garmire said.
</P>
<P>
   An examination of X-rays from the remnant of an exploded star,
or supernova, enabled astronomers to identify and measure in detail
the heavy chemical elements produced by the explosion 1,000 years
ago and now being dispersed into space. Dr. Claude Canizares of the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology said that the exploded star
had had 20 times the mass of the sun but was scattering enough
oxygen to supply 1,000 future solar systems. ``Real fountains of
life,'' he called these outpourings of oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   The recently discovered black hole, in the constellation
Sagittarius, was spotted last September when the Rossi X-Ray Timing
Explorer satellite picked up a flare of radiation from the region.
Astronomers at the Very Large Array, a network of radio telescopes
in Socorro, N.M., confirmed the discovery and detected jets of gas
issuing from the black hole at close to the speed of light. The
black hole is consuming gas from an accompanying normal star.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ronald Remillard of MIT said the black hole was small, with
only 10 times the mass of the sun, but added that the sudden flares
were perplexing _ ``a novel system to pay attention to.'' To quiet
any fears, he said the black hole was rotating around the center of
the galaxy, not approaching Earth and ``not free to roam on its own
and gobble up things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
