<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLALETHAL-INJECTION15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jeb Bush signs lethal injection into action
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Gov. Jeb Bush signed a bill changing
Florida's method of execution from its 76-year-old electric chair
to lethal injection Friday, hours before death row attorneys wrote
the U.S. Supreme Court trying to keep alive a February showdown.
</P>
<P>
   By signing the bill, Attorney General Bob Butterworth argued in
a letter to the court this week, the death row lawyers' challenge
to the electric chair is now irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony B. Bryan, 40, the death row inmate whose case finally
persuaded justices to consider the constitutionality of
electrocution for the first time in more than 100 years ``has never
challenged his execution by lethal injection, nor has he raised
execution by lethal injection as an issue,'' Butterworth wrote.
``In fact, he has cited with favor lethal injection as a method of
execution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In light of the above, Bryan's challenge to the
constitutionality of Florida's electric chair no longer presents a
(justifiable) issue ripe for review,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But in his response filed Friday, Bryan's attorney argued that
the Florida Constitution prohibits changing the method of
punishment once it is imposed and legislators have no power to
amend the Constitution. Attorney Martin McClain urged justices to
keep their Feb. 28 appointment for oral arguments and accused
Butterworth of not explaining the constitutional dilemma to the
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``As it stands now, it's the law of the state because there's a
peculiar state constitutional provision,'' said Palm Beach County
assistant public defender Steve Malone, who worked with the team
preparing the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also signed a bill shortening the time for death penalty
appeals, a law he personally insisted on during the legislature's
special session earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
