A6576 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-SUNDANCE16-COX     01-14 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDANCE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ski bums, beautiful people in black round out cast at Sundance
 &HT;    EDs: EMBARGOED for Sunday, Jan. 16
 &HT;    By Lori Cumpston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Look out!
</P>
<P>
   It's the attack of the PIBs.
</P>
<P>
   Run for cover.
</P>
<P>
   Not in the movie theater, silly. That's the first place they'll
go.
</P>
<P>
   Psssst! Over here.
</P>
<P>
   That was close. Just look at them in their black turtleneck
sweaters, black pants, black trench coats, sunglasses and carrying
attache cases, in black, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Yes folks, it's the Sundance Film Festival at its finest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Park City call it the attack of the PIBs,''
jokes Grand Junction filmmaker, Rhea Gavry, ``because all you see
is this wave of black. You can always tell the filmmakers because
they are dressed in black. They can't afford anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, PIB stands for ``people in black.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sundance Film Festival, which drew nearly 20,000 flick fans
to the ski hamlet of Park City, Utah, last year, is gearing up for
its annual run Jan. 20-30. Park City is located about 40 miles
southeast of Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   The festival originally was called the U.S. Film Festival until
actor-director Robert Redford brought it under the auspices of his
Sundance Institute. The institute promotes the development of
independent voices and visions in the arts.
</P>
<P>
   Gavry has been planning her annual pilgrimage since October.
</P>
<P>
   Her efforts paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a festival `B' packet,'' says Gavry. ``It's not my first
choice, but it's better than no ticket at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the madness works: Movie junkies must apply for
ticket packages months in advance. The cost can run the gamut _
several hundred to several thousand dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to Fed Ex your ticket request,'' explains Gavry.
``When it's signed for, that's when they assign you a number.''
</P>
<P>
   Gavry's number was 709.
</P>
<P>
   She had exactly one hour to call in with her movie choices. The
selection process wasn't easy considering there were 112 feature
films to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   Must-sees on her list are ``Americanos: Latino Life in the
United States,'' co-produced by Edward James Olmos; ``Dark Days'';
``Songcatcher''; ``Blessed Art Thou''; ``Love and Basketball,''
produced by Spike Lee; ``Shadow Magic''; ``The Charcoal People'';
and ``Luna Papa.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had tickets for 20 films over five days,'' says Gavry.
``That's an average of four films a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't sweat it if you don't have tickets and you're not a
personal friend of film critic Roger Ebert.
</P>
<P>
   There are still ways to snag a seat without sneaking in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get on the waiting list and get in line,'' advises Gavry,
whose husband, Doug Monroe, works the festival as a free-lance
cameraman for ``Entertainment Tonight,'' E! Entertainment, HBO and
Showtime. ``You are more likely to get into an early morning
screening because people stay out late for the parties and the late
night screenings are pretty easy to get into.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, about that party thing. Unless you have a Fast Pass, Packet
``A,'' Packet ``B,'' press pass or a date with Charlie Sheen,
you're not going.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that Park City has transformed itself from a
sleepy mining town to a play in the snow cultural mecca. If cinema
tickets are scarce, strap on the boards and hit the slopes for a
great day of skiing. While you're there, check out the America's
Cup Bobsled Races or the Visa Intermountain Division Nordic Jumping
Junior Olympic Qualifier competition, both of which are going on
during the 11-day festival run.
</P>
<P>
   After a day on the slopes, stroll through one of 20 art
galleries, grab some grub at the Grub Steak Restaurant then hang
out at the Mulberry Street piano bar where everyone will be in the
same boat you are: no tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttles make it easy to get around since parking is at a
premium.
</P>
<P>
   The Park City experience alone is definitely worth the price of
admission, even if you can't get into the films, many of which
eventually will be at your local theater anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, most people come to ski, screen and gawk at the
celebrities. Big names are expected to include Kevin Spacey,
Julianna Margulies, Kyra Sedgwick, Alfre Woodward, Nick Nolte, Anne
Heche, Donald Sutherland, Spike Lee, Danny DeVito and Emilio
Estevez.
</P>
<P>
   You can tell the seasoned veterans from rookie festival-goers
who usually have their head buried deep in the film guidebook
trying to figure out what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let that scare you, though, if you're a first-timer.
</P>
<P>
   Gavry remembers her first festival in the mid-'80s when it was
still called the U.S. Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   As a film student attending on a press pass, she was bitten by
the film bug.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a whole entourage of Australian films and they had
all these great filmmakers,'' recalls Gavry. ``The Australians were
a rowdy bunch, and there were all these parties in the street. It
was really low key and everyone was like family.''
</P>
<P>
   The next year, she was hired to work in the press office as a
liaison between the filmmakers and the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember sitting in this theater and I turned around and
Clint Eastwood is sitting right here,'' she says motioning with one
hand, ``and Faye Dunaway is sitting right there.'' She laughs, then
adds, ``You kind of do a double take and I remember thinking, `He
looks a lot older than I thought.'''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't Gavry's only brush with fame.
</P>
<P>
   Enter a young filmmaker by the name of Steven Soderbergh with
his low budget film, ``Sex, Lies and Videotape.''
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had seen the film and I thought it was great,'' recalls
Gavry. ``Soderbergh was so young, it was kind of electric.''
</P>
<P>
   Soderbergh drew a late night screening slot for his film, which
is probably the worst thing that can happen to a young filmmaker
with stars in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the bigger press were leaving,'' says Gavry. ``I
talked to a woman from The New York Times and I said, 'You've got
to see this film, it's great.'''
</P>
<P>
   The writer reluctantly agreed to sit in on a second hastily
added press screening the next day before her noon flight back to
New York. When it was over, she demanded that Gavry track down
Soderbergh so she could interview him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember running around and finding him,'' laughs Gavry,
``and finding her in the ladies restroom at the Egyptian Theater
screaming, 'I got him, I got him!' She came out with the story the
next day and he was on his way.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
