<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CSUNNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UDOKA WAS BIG PROBLEM FOR NORTHRIDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ It took only a few minutes to realize there was
a problem for the Cal State Northridge men's basketball team
Thursday night. He wore No. 11 for Portland State.
</P>
<P>
   Senior forward Ime Udoka, a mystery in the Big Sky Conference
after he sat out last season after transferring from San Francisco,
proved tough to guard. Although Udoka made only 2 of 14 shots, he
had a season-high 13 rebounds and a game-high nine assists in the
Vikings' 76-42 win over Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's maybe the best player on their team,'' CSUN coach Bobby
Braswell said of Udoka, a 6-6, emotionless swingman who played with
fluidity rarely seen in a Northridge opponent this season. ``We
were prepared for (him).''
</P>
<P>
   But if CSUN is going to take care of the Vikings at home on Feb.
26, the coaching staff might have something different in store
defensively for Udoka, who is too tall and quick for the Matadors'
best defenders _ guards Carl Holmes (6-1) and Marco McCain (6-3).
</P>
<P>
   Udoka was able to get to the line frequently because of his
slashing ability; he made 12 of 14 free throws and had 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   Class reunion: Udoka starred in the mid-1990s at Portland's
Jefferson High, where he was all-state. One of his high school
teammates was in the seats behind the CSUN bench Thursday night:
Chazz Moore, a starting cornerback for the Northridge football team
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Moore is in Portland for the winter break. He was among five
Matadors who have interested NFL scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Home-grown: Redshirt freshman center Dan Read, who played with
Holmes at North Eugene High, had several members of his family in
the stands Thursday. He gave them a thrill by making 3 of 4 shots
and scoring seven points in a season-high 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Name change: Braswell isn't known in the Northwest as CSUN's
coach. Almost universally, he's referred to as ``former Oregon
assistant Bobby Braswell'' in the newspapers every time CSUN comes
to Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Braswell was on the Ducks' staff for four years in the 1990s
before coming to Northridge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
