r s BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN     01-14 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORY ON HIGH: DEAN DOME CEILING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPEL HILL, N.C. _ Say this about North Carolina's vacuous,
antiseptic Dean E. Smith Center, with its older crowd and binocular
seats: The place has great rafters.
</P>
<P>
   A chunk of college basketball history hangs from the Carolina
blue and white ceiling. There are four national-championship
banners, 14 Final Four banners and 22 ACC-championship banners. The
jerseys of legends _ Jordan and Ford, Worthy and Kupchak _ hang
from the east rafters like specters.
</P>
<P>
   `This is unbelievable,'' UCLA freshman Jason Kapono said after
Friday's practice. ``You see all the banners and jerseys and all
the great players they've had here. It's similar to Pauley
Pavilion.''
</P>
<P>
   Great history, average team. This is not a classic North
Carolina outfit. It's talented, sure, but it doesn't ooze lottery
picks and it doesn't rule the ACC. In fact, the Tar Heels have much
in common with the Bruins, who today make their second appearance
in the 21,000-seat Dean Dome. (They lost by 26 points in 1988.)
</P>
<P>
   Both teams have endured roster changes and inconsistency. Both
lost Wednesday night _ UCLA to USC, North Carolina to Wake Forest.
Both have rosters dominated by freshmen and sophomores. And both
are performing below preseason expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been looking forward to this game, but we never thought
we'd be 11-5,'' Tar Heels point guard Ed Cota said. ``Both teams
have been kind of up and down.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference is quality of opponent. UCLA (9-4) lost to
Colorado State, Washington and USC; North Carolina failed against
heavy hitters: Michigan State, Indiana, Cincinnati and Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   Comparative scores heavily favor the Tar Heels. They beat Purdue
by 15, and UCLA beat Purdue at the buzzer. They beat USC by 17 in
the season opener, and UCLA lost to USC by 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely have to play our best game of the year,'' Kapono
said. ``There can't be any spurts when we don't do things right or
they'll jump on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Once their schedule softened and sophomore forward Kris Lang
returned from a virus and shin splints, the Tar Heels seemed poised
for a charge through the brutal ACC. They beat Clemson and N.C.
State with sterling defense and 64 points from the backcourt, Cota
and freshman guard Joe Forte.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday's loss to Wake Forest was a prime example of
season-long inconsistency. Cota was 3 of 12, Forte was 1 of 10, and
junior center Brendan Haywood scored eight points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to find our identity,'' UNC coach Bill Guthridge
said. ``With the lineup change with Lang coming back, everybody's
in different roles. I think we improved after Christmas with those
two good wins, then we had that tough loss.''
</P>
<P>
   But being North Carolina, there's no dearth of talent, only of
experience and execution. The pressure's squarely on UCLA to
elevate its play or suffer another bad loss. That means smart
defense, patient offense, passion and, most important, focus.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it's easy to lose concentration in the Dean Dome. The
ceiling's quite a sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd isn't really that tough _ it's like our crowd,''
said Bruins forward Rico Hines, a Greenville, N.C., native. ``But
the whole Dean Dome thing can be intimidating. They've got Michael
Jordan's jersey hanging in the rafters. It can get intimidating. As
soon as you look up, you're finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Note: UCLA forwarded the results of its JaRon Rush investigation
to the NCAA on Thursday night. A decision is expected in the next
week or two. Sources close to the investigation believe Rush could
be ruled ineligible for the season, then recoup eight or 10 games
on appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
