<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-BELICHICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL IS EXPECTED TO DECIDE ON BELICHICK'S FUTURE BY MONDAY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Jets begin another uncertain weekend Saturday.
This time, at least, they know who their new owner is, but still
unsettled is the identity of the next head coach. The team also may
face another bitter dispute with the New England Patriots over the
price for snatching away a coach who is already under contract.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday, Commissioner Paul Tagliabue is expected to decide
whether Bill Belichick is free to become someone else's head coach
or must remain under contract to the Jets, the team he spurned. On
Tuesday, Robert Wood Johnson IV will undoubtedly be approved as the
new owner of the Jets by the National Football League. Within a
day, if not immediately, Johnson will preside over the selection of
a coach. Many people believe that will be the former and future
coach, Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the players know what's going on,'' left tackle Jumbo
Elliott said Friday. ``But if you had to press them, they'd guess
Bill is coming back. But Bill will do whatever he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has promised his ``total dedication to bringing a
winning and championship team to this area.'' He is a sports fan,
and wants to establish immediately a solid base as the owner by
stabilizing the team. This he can do most readily by reappointing
Parcells or having Parcells name Al Groh, his linebackers coach, as
the head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Marcus Coleman, who will be a free agent, has said
that his decision on whether to remain a Jet could be influenced by
whether Parcells returns as coach.
</P>
<P>
   If the new coach is Parcells or Groh, then most of the assistant
coaches will return, too. The one certain change will be Eric
Mangini, a defensive assistant who helped coach the secondary.
Mangini will wind up with Belichick, who seems destined to coach
somewhere else once his contractual status is cleared up.
</P>
<P>
   There is uncertainty whether Charlie Weis, the offensive
coordinator, will opt to follow Belichick, with whom he has become
friendly, or stay with Parcells, who has encouraged him in his
career.
</P>
<P>
   If Tagliabue rules that Belichick is under a valid contract with
the Jets, as the team has maintained, that will set up a familiar
scenario: a team that wanted to hire Belichick as coach would most
likely have to part with draft picks to land him.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are confident they have an ironclad agreement with
Belichick. They declined Tagliabue's invitation to present more
evidence or additional witnesses Friday to bolster their position.
</P>
<P>
   After Parcells retired as coach last week, Belichick, who had
been designated as Parcells' successor, stepped down as head coach
after one day on the job. Belichick contended that his contractual
status changed significantly because of the death last May of the
Jets' owner, Leon Hess. Belichick filed a grievance against the
Jets with the NFL after the team denied him permission to talk with
the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   If Tagliabue rules in Belichick's favor, then he will be free to
become the New England coach and general manager. On Jan. 3, the
day after the regular season ended, the Patriots requested
permission to interview Belichick but were rebuffed by the Jets,
who cited Belichick's contract, which said he would be the head
coach when Parcells retired.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the league upheld the Jets' contention that
Belichick was off limits to any other team. Assuming that
Tagliabue's stance remains the same, the give-and-take of
negotiating between the Jets and the Patriots will begin, just as
it did in 1997 when Parcells wanted out of his contract, which
bound him to New England.
</P>
<P>
   When the Jets and Patriots were unable to reach an agreement
over appropriate compensation, both sides requested Tagliabue's
intervention. Tagliabue decided to award the Patriots four Jets
draft choices over a three-year period in return for freeing
Parcells from his contract with New England.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he will mediate between the Jets and the Patriots
only if both sides ask him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Many current and former Jets will attend a charity auction
Monday night for the David Center, a proposed center on Long Island
for autistic children. Among the items for auction will be jerseys
signed by Keyshawn Johnson and Dan Marino, a baseball autographed
by Roger Clemens and a hockey goalie's stick signed by Martin
Brodeur. The event, from 6 to 9 p.m. at the Official All Star Cafe
in Manhattan, is expected to attract quarterback Ray Lucas, center
Kevin Mawae, tackle Jason Fabini and the former Jets Marty Lyons,
Bruce Harper and Greg Buttle. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
