u w BC-AIR-SAFETY-ART-NYT &LR;      01-14 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-SAFETY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AIRLINE SAFETY PROGRAM FOCUSES ON PILOTS REPORTING THEIR
ERRORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(HLW) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton announced a program on Friday to
encourage airline pilots to report their own rule violations, in
exchange for immunity from punishment, to make it easier for the
government, the airlines and the pilot unions to detect trends that
could hurt safety.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the program, which has been in use on a test basis
at American Airlines for five years, would help aviation join other
American industries in ``moving toward a zero-defect approach'' by
compiling anecdotal evidence from pilots.
</P>
<P>
   But a larger program that would give pilots immunity for
reporting data that is important to safety is still mired in
bureaucratic rule making. That system, used successfully by several
European carriers for the last few years, involves downloading data
from on-board computers and analyzing thousands of flights to look
for patterns of violating restrictions on altitudes, or on climb or
descent rates. Such patterns could give clues to problems in air
traffic control or other aviation systems.
</P>
<P>
   News organizations, lawyers who represent crash victims'
families and others have objected to the program because it would
keep the data secret from them.
</P>
<P>
   The Aviation Safety Action Program announced by the president
will be open to all airlines. More than a dozen, including all the
major U.S. carriers, have expressed interest, the Federal Aviation
Administration said.
</P>
<P>
   The president of American Airlines, Donald J. Carty, and the
president of the union that represents American's pilots, Richard
T. LaVoy of the Allied Pilots Association, said that the program
had already resulted in changes that improved safety.
</P>
<P>
   For example, LaVoy said, several pilots reported that at one
airport with intersecting runways, they had moved their airplanes
too far forward when told by air traffic controllers to yield to
other planes that were landing. The pilots did this, he said,
because they sometimes confused one runway's ``stop'' line with the
other's. The problem was solved when the lines were repainted, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But without a promise of immunity and a common practice of
reporting their own errors, pilots probably would not acknowledge
such an error and no one would realize that it was widespread, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The government already runs a hot line for pilots to report
their violations and gain immunity, operated by NASA under contract
with the aviation agency. But that data is ``de-identified,''
meaning it is stripped of details that could pinpoint the airline
or airport, making it harder to use to glean safety information,
officials said. The new program is not anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   The immunity from punishment does not extend to deliberate
violations of the rules, criminal activity or substance abuse,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the program was part of the administration's goal
of cutting the crash rate by 80 percent over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Outside experts say that to reach that goal, airlines and
regulators will have to move beyond finding problems by analyzing
crashes, because crashes are rare.
</P>
<P>
   At the College of Aeronautics, located near La Guardia Airport
in New York, Maxine E. Lubner, the chairwoman of the college's
aircraft operations department, said that the challenge now was to
find patterns of human error, because so many mechanical problems
had already been solved. ``The system is not likely to be improved
by technological and mechanical fixes as much as it once was,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Dr. Lubner said, comparing the pattern of reports
from several airlines might help spot that one had a training
deficiency or that another had a strong training program or
procedure in some particular area of operations.
</P>
<P>
   The aviation agency's bigger hope is for a program called flight
operations quality assurance, which would take data from computers
on planes. European carriers, using American-built planes, have
used such data to determine, for example, that pilots frequently
violated restrictions on altitude and rate of descent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
