<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coughlin holding off on whether to start Brunell
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE _ There are no sure things in Tom Coughlin's world,
which is why Jacksonville's coach declines to designate Mark
Brunell as his starting quarterback today.
</P>
<P>
   Though Brunell took the majority of snaps during the week and
has expressed no reservations about his left knee, Coughlin said he
won't name a starter until before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Brunell went down with a strained medial collateral ligament in
the knee in a Dec. 26 loss against Tennessee. While Coughlin has
argued, ``We will not start Mark Brunell if he can't defend
himself,'' the quarterback showed improved mobility as the week
wore on. He will wear braces on both knees.
</P>
<P>
   BRING YOUR A-GAME
</P>
<P>
   Keep an eye on the right side of Jacksonville's offensive line,
where tackle Leon Searcy is anticipating an eventful day. Miami
defensive end Trace Armstrong opened the week by trying to downplay
the Jaguars' threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we feel everybody has to play their best game to
beat them,'' said Armstrong, the league's defensive player of the
week.
</P>
<P>
   Searcy was not amused.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't bring his B-game,'' Searcy said, ``because I'm going
to bring my A-game.''
</P>
<P>
   With nine career sacks in the postseason (including three
against Seattle last weekend), Armstrong needs two more to tie
Charles Haley for third place on the all-time playoff sack list.
</P>
<P>
   THE BIG SPREAD
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars opened the week as a nine-point favorite, a spread
that dipped only a point, despite the uncertainty of Brunell's
knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot to go in there and prove,'' Miami defensive
tackle Daryl Gardener said. ``We're kind of ticked off about it,
but we're just going to go play our game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what an underdog is,'' Miami running back J.J.
Johnson said. ``I've never been an underdog in my life. There are
no underdogs on a football field.''
</P>
<P>
   INJURY REPORT
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins tight end Troy Drayton, who underwent arthroscopic
surgery on his right knee Dec. 23 for cartilage repair, is the
day's biggest question mark. An inactive for last weekend's
wild-card round at Seattle, Drayton went through his first practice
Tuesday and expects to play, though he officially is listed as
questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Miami wide receiver Oronde Gadsden (ribs) is also questionable.
Jacksonville offensive tackle Tony Boselli (knee) and linebacker
Bryan Schwartz (hamstring) are on injured reserve and out.
</P>
<P>
   ETC.
</P>
<P>
   Winds gusted to 35 mph Friday, and temperatures dipped into the
mid-30s overnight. But forecasts call for temperatures in the upper
60s with 8 mph winds at kickoff. ... Both teams are 2-2 against
common opponents. Both beat Denver. Miami lost to the New York Jets
twice while Jacksonville beat them once, but Miami was 1-0 against
Tennessee while the Jaguars were 0-2. ... The clubs did not face
each other this year but Jacksonville prevailed in their only
previous matchup, a 28-21 victory last season in a Monday night
game. Fred Taylor ran for two scores and Keenan McCardell caught
two touchdown passes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
