</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFCNOTES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Even injured, Davis is a pain to defenses
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Judging by his performance last week against
Detroit, Redskins running back Stephen Davis will be just fine
running on a sore ankle and a sore knee.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbled by a sprained ankle going into the Redskins' playoff
game against the Lions, Davis rushed for 119 yards and two
touchdowns in the first half before leaving with a sprained knee.
</P>
<P>
   It's still the ankle, which kept him out of the last two
regular-season games, that is giving Davis the most grief. But he
predicted Thursday, in his only practice time this week, that he
would play today.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt (I'll play), but I have a long way to go,''
Davis said. ``I'm just getting myself prepared. Hopefully, it will
work out like last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Redskins center Cory Raymer said he also expected to give it a
try today, despite a pulled rib-cage muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I don't have to run and hit somebody, I think I'll
be all right,'' said Raymer, who has started every game for the
past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   DUNGY'S SIDE
</P>
<P>
   Bucs coach Tony Dungy, one of four African-Americans to be hired
as an NFL head coach, told reporters this week that he disagreed
with Jesse Jackson and the Rainbow-PUSH Coalition accusation that
the Green Bay Packers held fired coach Ray Rhodes ``to a higher
standard'' because he's black.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the Packers made a move,'' Dungy said. ``They hired a
guy, and, for whatever reason, they decided not to continue with
it. But I think we need to look at the situation where they don't
hire people, as opposed to the Packers situation.''
</P>
<P>
   OTHER INJURIES
</P>
<P>
   Tampa cornerback Donnie Abraham missed a couple of practices
this week with a right hamstring strain, but he is expected to play
today. Abraham tied for the NFL lead in interceptions with seven.
Buccaneers backup receiver Reidel Anthony aggravated a quadriceps
injury in practice and is questionable.
</P>
<P>
   SUNSHINE STATE
</P>
<P>
   Former University of Miami standout Warren Sapp is feeling
nostalgic,with three Florida teams still vying for the Super Bowl _
Tampa Bay, Jacksonville and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you what, the whole state of Florida is buzzing right
now,'' Sapp said. ``That is something special that we all got
going, with Jacksonville, ourselves and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always keep an eye on the other team,'' he said, ``because
it's kind of like, who is going to be champion of Florida right
now, and Miami and Jacksonville play, so that will eliminate one of
us. It's just one of those things where who goes the furthest has
the bragging rights for a whole year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hold that to be kind of like college ball, the state
championship between Florida and Miami and Florida State. It's just
a great, great state for football and right now we are showing how
good we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
