<HEADER>
A6586 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-JAGS-DOLPHINS15-C     01-14 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAGS-DOLPHINS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jags favored, but Marino a favorite
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ The future of the Dolphins' Dan Marino and
the health of the Jaguars' Mark Brunell are two of the questions
the teams will start answering at 12:35 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   Miami needs another big game out of the rugged right arm of
Marino, who last week in Seattle ignored the numbers on his NFL
odometer.
</P>
<P>
   Favored Jacksonville must protect Brunell and his tender left
knee without Pro Bowl tackle Tony Boselli, out for the playoffs
with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   With the winner of this AFC playoff game in Alltel Stadium one
victory away from Atlanta's Super Bowl XXXIV, the teams face other
questions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Who will come off the bench as interpreter if Jimmy Johnson
and Marino have to talk over something on the sideline?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will the five Jaguars who have produced a Super Bowl rap song
spend any anxious moments if the Dolphins are more resilient than
the bookies are figuring?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will Dolphins defensive end Trace Armstrong be forced to eat a
few paragraphs from a newspaper clipping after stating this week,
``It's not like we feel like everybody has to play their best game
to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its injuries, 14-2 Jacksonville is favored to handle
Miami (9-7 in the regular season) and then host the AFC
Championship Game next Sunday against either the Colts or the
Titans.
</P>
<P>
   Miami has defied the odds already, losing five of its last six
regular-season games before upending the Seahawks on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The home-field advantage could be significant for the Jaguars,
who are 29-4 at the former Gator Bowl. Nationally, however, there
is sentiment toward Marino, who has not been to a Super Bowl since
1984 and could be playing his last game in the NFL. Marino
acknowledges the support but doesn't expect much in the first
playoff game between two Florida teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think because of the years that I've played in the league
and playing for the Dolphins ... the whole time,'' Marino said, ``I
do sense that the people are pulling for me to do well, and it's a
good feeling to have the support of the fans and the people around
the country. But I think their fans will be real fired up. Their
fans are extremely loyal.''
</P>
<P>
   Criticized for a soft schedule that inflated their record, the
Jags led the NFL in rushing but did not beat a team with a winning
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't care much about what the critics say,'' said Brunell,
who took more snaps with each practice day this week. ``We won 14
games, and you'd hope that would be enough to earn a little
respect.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams do not have a fierce rivalry, but they do have a
history, and Brunell is aware of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before there ever were the Jacksonville Jaguars, the Miami
Dolphins were the big team in this town,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you were to go out and ask people on the street who
they wanted to see come to Jacksonville to play, it would have been
the Dolphins,'' Jags coach Tom Coughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin said he is counting on Jaguars fans not to make any
assumptions and look past Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendous opportunity, I think,'' he said, ``for
our fans to come forward and make a statement about the city of
Jacksonville and about our people.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
