<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6587 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SKINS-BUCKS15-COX     01-14 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SKINS-BUCKS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFC: Playoffs putting question to passers
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Questions abound about the four quarterbacks remaining
in the NFC playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa Bay Buccaneers' hopes rest on rookie Shaun King, who
has started only five games. The Bucs' offense is anchored by the
run, but if the Redskins stop it, can King hold his composure under
an assortment of blitzes? The Washington Redskins' ambitions ride
with Brad Johnson. Before this season, Johnson was known more for
completing a pass to himself _ and for not playing a complete
season in five years with Minnesota. With Stephen Davis'
availability questionable and Tampa Bay's defense ferocious, could
Johnson be one hit away from a gurney?
</P>
<P>
   In St. Louis, former Arena League star Kurt Warner emerged as a
one-of-a-kind story, leading the Rams to the best record in the NFC
and winning the league's MVP. But St. Louis has not beaten a
winning team, and Warner has not played in an NFL playoff game.
Will the pressure get to him?
</P>
<P>
   And in Minnesota, former Falcons player Jeff George finally got
a playoff victory, throwing three touchdowns Sunday against Dallas
in an effort buoyed by an effective running game. But what if the
Rams contain Robert Smith? Can George resist the temptation to
trust his phenomenal arm in situations that require him to throw it
away?
</P>
<P>
   Questions, questions, questions, questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a quarterback,'' Johnson said, ``it's about
getting to a point where you're in a groove and you're not thinking
about the circumstances or what's at stake. You're just playing
like you're in the backyard as a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   It's very difficult to get to that point in the NFL playoffs
particularly for King, who started the season as the backup to the
much-maligned Trent Dilfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows a lot of wisdom on (the coaches') part, because as
much as I wanted to play at the beginning of the year, I probably
wasn't ready,'' King said. ``I was sort of glad that I wasn't in a
situation where I was playing and we were losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, ``I'm just excited for the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Buccaneers change their scheme, King's opportunity to
pass will not be as frequent as for the others. The Bucs build
their offense around the running of Mike Alscott and Warrick Dunn,
with an occasional _ or necessary _ display of King throwing deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaun has grown,'' coach Tony Dungy said. ``We won four of the
five games he started, so we feel the experience he's gained will
work for him (Saturday). We have confidence in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's confidence is at a career high. He's healthy, thanks
to a massive offensive line that will be missing tackle Andy Heck,
out with a hamstring injury. His absence could be a significant
blow against the tenacious Bucs' defense.
</P>
<P>
   But during the regular season, on a day that San Francisco shut
down the Washington's running game, Johnson threw for 417 yards.
That talent, and his ability to play an entire season, answered
many questions that haunted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been putting up with a lot of rumors about having a tired
arm, about being an injury-prone quarterback,'' Johnson said.
``Coming here, being a part of it, it's a special feeling. That's
all that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Warner, for everything he has done in a remarkable season
_ 109.2 quarterback rating, 41 touchdowns _ the Rams rewarded him
monetarily. The team had an extra $500,000 under the salary cap and
granted that money to Warner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money's not something that I'm hung up with,'' said Warner,
who earned the league minimum $250,000 this season. ``It's
obviously a nice gesture, to see that they appreciate what I've
done this year. Obviously, it's going to help out the family. And
I'm very grateful for it. The best part about it is not what they
gave me, or the fact that they gave me anything, but just the fact
that they felt strongly enough about my performance to offer me
something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   A free agent after the season, Warner's performance Sunday
against Minnesota probably won't have any effect on deal
negotiations. Not that it is on his mind now. Warner has a chance
against a suspect Vikings secondary to compile more impressive
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what my mind is on,'' he said. ``The playoffs are a new
experience for me, another part of an incredible season. But I
don't want it to be over yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither does George. He took over for a struggling Randall
Cunningham with 10 games left in the season and directed the
Vikings to nine victories. Sunday, he can continue to dispel the
negative notions about his ability to lead a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even thinking about that,'' George said. ``We have a
chance to get to where we want, which is the Super Bowl. So,
there's a lot of work ahead of us. But this is a great
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
