<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6591 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FREDTAYLOR15-COX     01-14 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FREDTAYLOR15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taylor wants reason to show off pearly whites
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Out went the gold teeth. Thug, rapper,
gangster, the stereotypes said, and Fred Taylor listened before his
second NFL season.
</P>
<P>
   In came the white caps. After leading all rookies with 1,223
rushing yards, Taylor's future as a pro star and potential endorser
of products seemed as gleaming and wide as his smile.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a hamstring injury and six games on the bench in 1999.
After a pre-season marketing deal with Pepsi, talks with Nike went
into a holding pattern. Gone were a reported $1 million in Jaguars
contract incentives he probably would have met easily on healthy
legs.
</P>
<P>
   Nike looked elsewhere, such as to Edgerrin James. Like Taylor,
James grew up without much money in Immokalee, a rural South
Florida community not far from Taylor's home in Belle Glade. Unlike
Taylor, James kept his gold teeth, resisting advice to the
contrary, and left intact his dreadlocks, which Taylor never had.
James went on to become NFL Rookie of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Now Taylor, as healthy as he has been since midseason, has a
chance to bolt back into the spotlight as the Jaguars host the
Dolphins in the playoffs Saturday, two games from the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was headed in a good direction, headed up,'' Taylor
said. ``Getting injured kind of hurt my marketing a little bit, but
not a whole lot. I've still got a lot things open to me with the
team doing very well. I think it all pretty much balanced out.
It'll only get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake: Taylor's concern Saturday is not his teeth,
except to the extent they might get rattled if somebody misses a
block. Nor is it is his endorsement prospects. If he helps his team
win, he says, the rest will take care of itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had all those different things,'' Taylor said. ``I just
hadn't taken advantage of it. I was trying to get my leg right and
I wasn't even worried about that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville must get past Miami to reach the conference title
game for the second time in four years. The Jaguars are not anxious
to appear to be looking ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Still, consider the possibilities Saturday: A monster rushing
day by Taylor, who grew up in the long shadow of Dan Marino's
passing arm in South Florida, might usher the legendary quarterback
into retirement or a new NFL city. And if the Colts also win,
Taylor could find himself in a marquee rushing matchup with James
in the AFC title game.
</P>
<P>
   When healthy, Taylor is the most explosive spark in the league's
leading rushing offense. He ran 77 yards for a touchdown on the
first play from scrimmage in last year's 28-21 Jaguars win over
Miami, the only other time the teams have met. With Jags
quarterback Mark Brunell trying to work out the stiffness of a
sprained knee, Jacksonville can be expected to ask more than ever
of its running game and Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to try to win,'' Taylor said. ``I'm not
worried about Dan retiring. I'm pretty sure he'll be back next
year. He's a great player, man, and you just can't throw him out.
He'll retire when he's ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor admired Marino growing up, but his loyalties ran to the
Chicago Bears and running back Walter Payton, whose moves and
stiff-arm James also happened to idolize. Taylor's own stiff-arm
was the one that crumpled Broncos linebacker Glenn Cadrez on a
38-yard touchdown run with 2:38 left to give the Jaguars a go-ahead
score against Denver in the 13th game of this season, marking his
return from injury.
</P>
<P>
   The hamstring has prevented him from matching the production of
this rookie season in 1998, when he became Jacksonville's first
1,000-yard rusher. James Stewart has more yards this season for
Jacksonville, 931 to Taylor's 732, and more touchdowns, 13 to 6.
But Taylor, when full speed, remains the more dangerous threat,
averaging more yards per carry, 4.6 to 3.7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fred is a great back because he has the ability to break one
on every play,'' Brunell said. ``We're counting on Fred to have big
game. Last year against the Dolphins he did and hopefully he will
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's rookie season stirred talk of 2,000 yards this year,
which he now regards as a jinx. A similar thing happened at the
University of Florida. After an eye-catching freshman year, Taylor
endured a sophomore slump, missing much of the season to injury and
suspensions for minor but embarrassing disciplinary infractions. He
would be involved in three such incidents in his college career,
for things like misusing bookbags and charge cards that did not
belong to him.
</P>
<P>
   That was part of the reason for the attention to Taylor's image
in the off-season, helped along by advisers from the Jags media
relations team to agent William ``Tank'' Black. Taylor has become
increasingly at ease before cameras, and corporate sponsors have
nibbled if not yet offered the big-dollar contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a discussion or two with him,'' said Nike spokesman
Scott Reames. ``With someone like Fred, we're certainly keeping an
eye on those who are not under contract already with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Deciding who is marketable and who is not ``is a complex
calculation,'' Reames said. ``We don't have a protractor. If you
fit between the lines, you're a Nike guy.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is that gold teeth and dreadlocks may be considered
interesting and nonthreatening for a player like James, whose
off-the-field behavior is actually quite mild-mannered, by all
accounts. For Taylor, capped teeth might yet prove to be a good
move, if it helps dispel any bad-guy stigma that might linger,
fairly or not.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, what happens on the field counts for a lot. With a
strong showing in the playoffs, Taylor might find plenty to smile
about off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's mother will be there Saturday at Jacksonville's Alltel
Stadium, as will friends from home and college, but not his
grandmother, Rosetta, the woman who essentially raised him in Belle
Glade. That has not changed since his high school playing days at
Glades Central, where he was a Parade All-America.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can't bear to watch,'' Taylor said. ``Not in person
anyway. But she'll watch on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   So will thousands of Dolphins fans, who might like to see Taylor
better his business fortunes another day.
</P>
<P>
   They know it's a bad sign for Miami if it's late in the game and
the camera pans to helmetless Fred Taylor on the sidelines,
flashing the whitest enamel marketing science can find.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
