<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP SCOUT TEAM LOOKS OVER COMPETITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ We're down to the Elite Eight in the NFL's
postseason tournament, and it's time to analyze what these teams
have to do to have the best shot of advancing to their respective
conference championship games. As always, commentary from men whose
teams have faced both participants.
</P>
<P>
   Miami at Jacksonville, Saturday at 12:30, analysis by Jets
director of football operations Bill Parcells: ``There is one
important factor here to begin with that should not be overlooked.
Miami's preparation time. Jacksonville has been off for two weeks,
getting healthy, and with plenty of time to prepare. My guess is
that they probably prepared more for Seattle, thinking Seattle
would win the game, but they still should have a wide preparation
edge on Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miami, I'd bet, didn't get home from Seattle until 2 or 3
Monday morning. So Monday was ruined as a practice day. Then they
have to play Saturday at (12:30), another day taken off a normal
preparation week. Miami has to run the ball well to win. If they
become one-sided against the Jacksonville defense, then they'll
have a hard time scoring points. If Miami runs as well as they did
against Seattle, they've got a good chance to win. I don't think
Jacksonville will run on Miami, either. Miami's defense is pretty
good. The big decision they have to make is how they are going to
cover Jacksonville's wide receivers, Jimmy Smith and Keenan
McCardell. Smith is the go-to guy for Jacksonville. It will be
interesting to see whom Miami matches up Madison with. Jacksonville
likes to screen a lot, and throw the ball to Smith. Their tight
ends haven't been a big part of the passing game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jacksonville is good on defense. They use the zone blitz very
well. I don't know if Miami can exploit that. I think Miami will be
a little charged-up after winning in Seattle, and if they don't
turn the ball over, and play the same kind of game they played in
Seattle, run well, no turnovers, they can win this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington at Tampa Bay, Saturday at 4, analysis by Lions coach
Bobby Ross: ``This should be a great matchup with the Washington
offense going against Tampa's defense, which to me is the fastest
in the league. They are so quick on defense that if you don't play
against them on a regular basis, like we do twice a year, their
speed kind of blindsides you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington is very good on offense, and overall, when they
beat us last week, they were a much better team than when we beat
them in Detroit during the season. Their defense seems to be
playing better now. Washington can hurt you just about every way
possible on offense. They can throw deep with the speed and size of
their wide receivers, they have role players out of the backfield
like (Brian) Mitchell and (Larry) Centers for special occasions;
their tight end, (Stephen) Alexander, is a good pass catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they will have to deal with Tampa's speed. Warren Sapp is
one of the most dominating players in the game. Their linebackers
can run with the best of them, and (Donnie) Abraham is one of the
best cover guys in the league. I think Tampa will be very
conservative on offense, and try to protect the young kid (Shaun)
King at quarterback. They'll try to bang into the line with (Mike)
Alstott, and run screens and draws with Warrick Dunn to try to get
him in space for the big play. My guess is that Tampa will be very
conservative on offense, trying not to turn the ball over and make
mistakes, and let their defense try to set good field postion, and
win that way. But in the playoffs a team has to have more than one
element to win, so I think you'll see Tampa take a few deep shots
down the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota at St. Louis, Sunday at 12:30, analysis by 49ers
general manager Bill Walsh: ``I think St. Louis is the best team in
the league this year and should win the Super Bowl. They are very
good on offense, good on defense, and good enough on special teams.
They're probably the only team with balance in all three areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minnesota has to outscore them. I see St. Louis scoring 35
points against that defense. Minnesota is not good on defense, and
St. Louis has it going on offense. The quarterback (Kurt Warner)
hasn't had any problems yet. But you never know. He could come out
a little nervous, throwing incompletions, or interceptions, and
then it's a ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. Louis has outstanding speed at wide receiver. Marshall
Faulk is a weapon, running and in the passing game. Both teams can
hurt you deep, go downfield with the ball. What Minnesota has going
for it is Jeff George and the deep passing game. George is playing
exceptional football. He should try to make big plays in the
passing game all day long. I see St. Louis winning something like
38-24. But if they make some mistakes, turn the ball over, then
Minnesota can beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee at Indianapolis, Sunday at 4, analysis by Browns coach
Chris Palmer: ``The team with the better defense in this game will
win. Neither team has a `great' defense, although they both can
play well at times. Indy is a great play-action pass team. What
will help Peyton Manning is the double tight end, one-back set they
always play. This could be very effective in stopping Jevon Kearse
pass rushing off the corner for Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manning reads the defense fast and gets rid of the ball. It's
very hard to sack him. Jeff Fisher plays a variation of the old
Buddy Ryan `46' defense. Tennessee pressures. They bring Blaine
Bishop, a very good safety, up to play eight men in the box and
they dare you to run. They're good at stopping the run. But,
Manning, with his play-action passing, and Edgerrin James, with his
running, might open up the field deep for Marvin Harrison and
(Terrence) Wilkins to make some plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tennessee is not great against the pass. If they try to double
Harrison, then Wilkins can hurt them. On offense, Tennessee is a
gimmick-type team. They always have a couple of trick plays, to
back off the defense. Eddie George is a great runner, but I think
(QB Steve) McNair is the best runner on their team. That guy is
hard to bring down. He didn't pass well against Buffalo, but he
threw five touchdowns against Jacksonville, so you don't know what
you're going to get.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pete Carroll is telling friends he expects to sit out a year
before he returns to coaching. Pete also told some of his coaches
that he was forced to fire Larry Kennan, Paul Boudreau, and Steve
Walters following his first two season, and prevented two more from
being fired.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It has been reported ad nauseum that Phil Luckett, who was the
referee in Tennessee's win over Buffalo last Saturday, is the guy
who made the ``bad'' calls in games involving Pittsburgh and the
Jets in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Luckett was the referee who flipped the coin in the Thanksgiving
Day game where Steeler Jerome Bettis called ``head, tails.''
Luckett was villified for saying Bettis called ``heads'' when a
national television audience heard ``tails.'' During the offseason,
an electronically enhanced tape proved that Luckett was right, and
was not only exonerated, but given a bonus from the league. So he
did not blow that call.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the media types said he was the one who made the bad
call in the Jets-Seahawks game, when Vinny Testaverde was brought
down inches short of the goal line, but incorrectly given a winning
touchdown. Luckett was the referee, but he didn't make the call.
The line judge, backed up by the umpire, raised his arms signaling
touchdown. Luckett was stationed deep in the backfield behind
Testaverde and it was not his call.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And the reason Carroll seemed so at ease following his final
game in Foxboro Stadium, waving to the crowd on the way out, is
that owner Bob Kraft told him before the game he was going to be
fired the next day. Carroll asked Kraft before the game to know his
fate so he could relax and enjoy the day, so Kraft told him that
was going to be it, but not to tell anyone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
