<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge picks British firm to re-create events at Davidian
compound
 &HT;    By Tommy Witherspoon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ A federal judge in Waco on Friday chose a British
firm to stage a demonstration designed to determine if FBI agents
fired into Mount Carmel on the final day of the 51-day siege with
David Koresh and his followers.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Walter S. Smith Jr., in a pivotal, two-page
order in the wrongful death lawsuit filed against the government by
Branch Davidian survivors, laid some preliminary ground rules that
will govern the re-creation of events at Mount Carmel on April 19,
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Smith tabbed Vector Data Research, a British firm that
specializes in infrared and thermal imaging, to conduct the
re-creation, but set no date or location for the tests.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiff attorney Mike Caddell, who is confident the
re-creation will prove that FBI agents fired at Branch Davidians on
the final day of the siege, said he thinks the tests will be
conducted during the first two weeks of March at Fort Hood.
</P>
<P>
   Smith ordered the re-creation in November at the urging of
Special Counsel John Danforth. The former senator from Missouri was
appointed in September by Attorney General Janet Reno to
investigate revelations in the Branch Davidian controversy,
including the government's belated admission that they used
pyrotechnic devices in the early-morning hours of the final tear
gas assault on Koresh's compound.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs have alleged that bursts of light on government
aerial infrared surveillance tapes from April 19, 1993, are gunfire
from federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials have maintained that their agents didn't fire a
single shot on that day, despite their claims that they were
showered by Branch Davidian bullets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The test will occur, at a minimum, with the current FBI camera
and aircraft,'' Smith ordered. ``The (Office of Special Counsel),
with the cooperation and assistance of the parties, will attempt to
secure a camera and, if necessary, an aircraft that contains a
camera, of the type the FBI used in 1993, without the upgrades that
are on the current camera. If both cameras may be procured, the
test will use both cameras.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials, at first, protested the notion of the
re-creation, claiming that the equipment had changed since 1993 and
noting the difficulty in approximating the exact conditions of that
day.
</P>
<P>
   Smith ordered that his court and Danforth's office will submit a
first draft of a protocol to the government and plaintiffs by Jan.
31. Experts from both sides then will confer and develop a
protocol, including where and when the tests will be conducted,
weapons and ammunition to be used, types of planes and cameras,
weather conditions and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vector is very well respected,'' Caddell said. ``Our people
have checked them out and we are very comfortable with them serving
as the neutral expert for the court and the OSC. For us, having a
truly neutral expert and utilizing the original camera and aircraft
were the key components to maintaining the credibility of the
test.''
</P>
<P>
   At the court's invitation, government attorneys submitted the
names of three infrared experts in December as neutral experts to
participate in the test. Caddell, however, charged that the
government's choices all had been former colleagues of Irving
William Ginsberg, who submitted an affidavit on the government's
behalf in November claiming that there are ``too many unknown
variables'' to accurately re-create the conditions of April 19,
1993.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also ordered that results from the re-creation be
provided to the parties at least eight weeks before trial, which is
set for May 15 in Smith's court in Waco.
</P>
<P>
   The parties will pay for the tests ``as the court deems
appropriate after consultation with the parties,'' Smith wrote.
Danforth's office will pay Vector's bill, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
