u s BC-FBN-DOLPHINS15-COX     01-14 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Long odds, odd song? Dolphins not listening
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Think about this: It has been more than two
months since the Miami Dolphins won back-to-back games.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Dolphins shut out Tennessee on a hot November
afternoon at Pro Player Stadium, they have had only one kind of
streak. Losing.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as they walk onto the field at Jacksonville's Alltel
Stadium today, six days after a first-round playoff victory at
Seattle, the Dolphins players and coaches honestly believe they can
win again, advance to the AFC title game for the first time since
1992 and turn a recording done by five Jacksonville players _ ``Uh
Oh, The Jaguars Super Bowl Song'' _ into a premature parody.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the oddsmakers pegged the Dolphins as
eight-point underdogs. Or that when ESPN's Tom Jackson was asked to
rate the remaining eight playoff teams, he put them dead last. Or
that when a reporter from The Associated Press broke down the
first-round playoff games, he wrote of the Miami-Seattle matchup
``the winner here has no chance of winning a second-round game.''
</P>
<P>
   That quote is now posted on the bulletin board. Circled and
highlighted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we can beat Jacksonville,'' assistant coach Dave
Wannstedt said. ``We're playing here close to home. We're playing
on grass. We're in the state of Florida. We're healthy. There's no
reason not to think we can win this football game.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there are lots of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Look at Jacksonville's resume: Finished the regular season with
an NFL-best 14-2 record ... won seven of eight home games ... did
not allow an opposing passer to throw for 300 yards ... allowed
only one running back, Tennessee's Eddie George, to rush for 100
yards ... spent last weekend resting.
</P>
<P>
   Look at Miami's: Finished the regular season with a 9-7 record,
losing six of its final eight games ... only made the playoffs when
the Seahawks and Jets lost on the last day of the regular season
... had to rally in the fourth quarter to beat a Seattle team that
had lost five of its last six games.
</P>
<P>
   Uh Oh?
</P>
<P>
   Not if you listen to the tone coming out of the Dolphins locker
room. After snapping one streak in Seattle _ 27 years without a
road playoff victory _ the optimism seemed to grow each day,
building until, in his last meeting with reporters, Dolphins coach
Jimmy Johnson scoffed at the idea that his recently slumping team
doesn't have a shot at becoming the first No. 6 seed to make it to
an AFC title game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Want to get on a roll?'' he said. ``Win the first playoff
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Dolphins did that last year. When defensive end
Trace Armstrong jarred the ball loose from Doug Flutie, preserving
a first-round playoff victory against Buffalo, it set the stage for
a game that, in many regards, looked similar to this one.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins headed to Denver, home of the team that finished
the regular season with an NFL-best 14-2 record.
</P>
<P>
   They lost 38-3 _ the worst playoff defeat in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was different,'' Armstrong said. ``You just went into
Denver hoping. You hope you get a break. You hope they have a bad
day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have had to have been real, real fortunate to have
any chance last year,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Dolphins say, they don't need luck or hope or even
one of those everything-falls-into-place games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that we need to latch on to anything,'' Armstrong
said. ``Now, we've kind of got a tough row to hoe. ... But it's not
like we feel like everybody has to play their best game for us to
beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons for why this meeting with the
regular-season champions feels different than the last one. Start
with the injuries. Last year at Denver, the Dolphins were missing
seven players who at the beginning of the season were starters.
This year the Jaguars are the ones hurting. Tony Boselli,
considered the best left tackle in the NFL, is out with a knee
injury. Quarterback Mark Brunell has been limited in practice with
a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the matter of the schedule. Five of the Dolphins'
regular-season opponents _ including two division champions _ made
the playoffs. Meanwhile, the Jaguars played only one team that
finished with a winning record. They lost to that team, Tennessee,
twice.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the same Tennessee that the Dolphins beat on that hot
November day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat the team that beat them,'' Dolphins offensive
coordinator Kippy Brown said. ``So we know we're capable of
competing with anybody _ if we play well.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Dolphins tried to conceal their game plan this
week, it seems clear that they plan to stick with what worked in
Seattle. Run the ball. Avoid turnovers at all costs. Play good
defense. Hope the game is close. And then, if you need to, let Dan
Marino use his 38-year-old arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what serves Dan Marino and the Dolphins best,'' said
Phil Simms of CBS, who covered the Seattle game. ``He is not the
same Dan Marino. He doesn't need to stand back in shotgun and throw
40 passes. He is not capable of doing that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   But are Marino and the Dolphins capable of wining today in
Jacksonville?
</P>
<P>
   CBS' Dan Dierdorf, who will be calling the game, thinks so. He
says the oddsmakers have it wrong. He looks at the Jaguars'
banged-up offensive line, the Dolphins' defensive front and calls
it a toss-up.
</P>
<P>
   And although the Dolphins aren't heading to the recording studio
just yet, after a regular season filled with uh-ohs _ seven
interceptions returned for touchdowns _ they believe this isn't
Denver all over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach convinced them,'' Brown said. ``There's nobody in this
league that we can't beat if we play how we're capable of playing.
Nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
