<SLUG> BC-TRUMP15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Supporters urge Trump to try presidential run
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ They sipped his wine, nibbled his salmon,
gawked at Mar-a-Lago and wrapped arms around Donald Trump's waist
urging him to run for president while having their pictures taken.
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party leaders from across the country came to Trump's
private club to mingle with the candidate who is trying to convince
himself that he can win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Trump said he will make his decision Feb. 15 and will likely
announce it in the atrium of Trump Tower _ ``is there a better
place?'' _ in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think that he brings an excitement to the Reform Party
that can only help us if he stays involved,'' said David Goldman, a
Sarasota attorney and chairman of the Florida Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 members of the party from New York, Georgia,
Virginia, Michigan, Massachusetts, Florida and other states were
given free copies of Trump's new book: ``Trump: The America We
Deserve'' as they entered the White and Gold Ballroom, which was
added to the 1927 estate in 1960 by cereal heiress Marjorie
Merriweather Post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to learn more about his ideas,'' said Russell Verney,
the party's outgoing national chairman. Verney works for party
founder Ross Perot. ``I think he still needs to get a handle on
just how difficult it is to win this election,'' said Verney. ``I
want to make sure that he has all the information he needs to make
his decision.''
</P>
<P>
   For Marji Mathieu of North Palm Beach, seeing Mar-a-Lago was too
good to pass up. ``What a place,'' said the Reform Party activist.
``He sure does make it interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever the businessman, after leaving his guests, Trump headed
toward the members-only dining room pausing long enough before
entering to ask one of the staff, ``Are we up over last night?''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
