<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-IOWA-GORE-BRADLEY-NYT     01-14 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-GORE-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EYES ON IOWA, BRADLEY JABS AS GORE HOLDS BACK PUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JAMES DAO with KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHNSTON, Iowa _ With just 10 days to go before the Iowa
caucuses, former Sen. Bill Bradley sharpened his efforts Friday to
portray Vice President Al Gore as a ``nibble around the edges''
politician, saying Gore was too willing ``to settle'' for small
solutions for big problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say we cannot do big things,'' Bradley said before
several hundred students, teachers and supporters in a high school
auditorium here. ``We're a great country at the time of our
greatest prosperity. And now is not the time to settle.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech echoed criticisms Bradley has made before against
Gore in their battle for the Democratic presidential nomination.
But Friday was the first time in recent days that Bradley pulled
all those varied criticisms together into one address.
</P>
<P>
   His aides said Bradley would continue to use that approach in
the coming week to clarify the distinctions between the two
candidates as well as to strengthen his assertion that he would be
a bolder leader than Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's approach has been the opposite of Bradley's
aggressiveness. Gore has been keeping his head down and trying not
to make waves _ and not to make news of the sort he made last week
with his comments on gays in the military.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two days in New Hampshire, it has been hard to tell
that he is campaigning at all. Gore is avoiding rallies and the
normal hoopla that attends the approach of an election. Instead,
his only public events have been detailed policy discussions with
small groups of people, where he speaks in a quiet, near-monotonous
voice and is careful to show the cameras, which usually outnumber
the voters, nothing but a low-key, thoughtful vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that voters, especially the independents in New
Hampshire, are loath to reward any candidate for a negative
approach to campaigning, and, after months of harsh assessments of
Bradley _ from raising doubts about his loyalty to the Democratic
Party to faulting his health care proposal as unfair to blacks and
other minorities _ Gore is sidestepping all opportunities to
criticize his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   At a brief news conference at a retirement home in Concord,
N.H., Gore passed up several chances to respond to Bradley's
remarks Friday. ``The only thing I can figure is that he didn't get
the word on the nice things I said about him,'' Gore drawled to
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Iowa caucuses little more than a week away,
Bradley's advisers are concerned that many Democrats do not
perceive significant differences between the two candidates on
major issues.
</P>
<P>
   So Bradley used much of Friday's speech to tick off his
proposals on universal health insurance, gun control, child
poverty, campaign finance reform and education. In each case, he
contended, Gore would do far less.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Bradley even mimicked the quavering voice of a
timid person in describing what he said was Gore's limited health
care proposal. Then he drew a comparison between his proposals to
reduce poverty and expand health care to what Franklin D. Roosevelt
and Lyndon B. Johnson did to create the Social Security and
Medicare systems. And he suggested that he would be a truer heir to
their expansive tradition of Democratic politics than Gore would
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Franklin Delano Roosevelt, 1930s, depression,'' Bradley said.
``The elderly of this country were destitute. He said, `We're going
to pass Social Security.' He didn't say we're going to pass Social
Security for 20 percent of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was accompanied Friday by Sen. Bob Kerrey, a Democrat
from the neighboring state of Nebraska, who has endorsed him. And
in a talk with reporters before Bradley's speech, Kerrey fiercely
attacked the Clinton administration and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   He berated Gore for having called Bradley a ``quitter'' for
retiring from the Senate in 1996. Gore asserts that Bradley should
have stayed in Washington to fight the Republican congressional
leadership, as Gore says he did. But Kerrey argued that the
Republican landslide of 1994 was caused by the Clinton
administration's poor leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please don't tell me I ought to give you a round of applause
for standing around and fighting Newt Gingrich,'' he said,
referring to the former Republican House speaker. ``You brought us
Newt Gingrich. That would be like asking me to thank the arsonist
after he sets a house on fire and then sticks around and helps us
put out the blaze.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey went on to assert that the Clinton administration was
``corrupted'' in 1995 and 1996 by its efforts to raise large
campaign donations, that it had dropped efforts to enact universal
health care for political reasons, and that Gore would ``say
whatever it takes to score political points.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
