<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, JAN. 15
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-PINOCHET-CHILE-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Jan. 12)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Jan.
12, about the presidential runoff election in Chile tomorrow
referred incorrectly to the actions of Joaquin Lavin, the
conservative candidate, after Gen. Augusto Pinochet was arrested in
Britain at the request of a Spanish judge. Lavin, at the time mayor
of a community in Santiago, did not suspend garbage collection at
the Spanish and British Embassies. The action was taken by the
mayor of a neighboring community.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CODEBREAKERS-NYT (moved on Monday, Dec. 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Dec. 6,
about the cracking of a code protecting some wireless telephone
transmissions referred imprecisely to the achievement. Although
cracking the code could jeopardize the security of phone calls, the
ability was thus far theoretical; no occurrence was reported.
</P>
<P>
   The article also included an outdated reference to a wireless
communication standard known as G.S.M. (A brief report on the
subject in the Week in Review on Dec. 12 also included the error.)
The expression now stands for global system for mobile
communications, no longer Groupe Speciale Mobile. The errors were
pointed out in a letter from Omnipoint dated Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ATHLETES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT (moved on Thursday, Jan. 13)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Jan. 13,
about Jon Entine's ``Taboo: Why Black Athletes Dominate Sports and
Why We're Afraid to Talk About It'' misspelled the surname of a
pathbreaking boxer in some copies. He was the heavyweight champion
Joe Louis, not Lewis.
</P>
</TEXT>
