<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6623 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WALMART-APPOINT-NYT &LR;      01-14 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALMART-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAL-MART CHIEF STEPS DOWN; LONGTIME AIDE STEPS UP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Kan.)  (mk) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   David D. Glass, who aggressively expanded Wal-Mart Stores Inc.
from a rural discounter into a worldwide powerhouse during his
12-year tenure as chief executive and president, announced Friday
that he would step down immediately. As expected, he will be
succeeded by his long-trusted lieutenant and chief operating
officer, H. Lee Scott Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Since Glass took the reins of Wal-Mart from Sam Walton in 1988,
the company's annual revenue is estimated to have expanded tenfold
to an expected $165 billion for the current fiscal year ending Jan.
31. Glass' biggest achievements include the retail chain's shift to
the supercenter format _ stores that sprawl as big as two football
fields and carry groceries and pharmaceuticals as well as general
merchandise _ and a substantial move into overseas markets,
including Argentina, Brazil, Germany and China.
</P>
<P>
   While Scott inherits perhaps one of the most efficient retail
companies, he has several serious challenges ahead. First of all,
it will be hard for him to maintain the extraordinary momentum of
18 percent annual sales growth as competitors overseas like the
French retailer Carrefour and domestic rivals like Safeway fight
back. He will also be responsible for helping Wal-Mart revive its
lagging Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   ``International growth and the Internet will keep him busy,''
said Scott Swanson, portfolio manager of Phoenix Engemann Growth
Fund, which owns about 5 million shares of the stock. ``He is going
to have a lot to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart did not say why Glass, 64, decided to retire now, but
said it was his decision. He will stay on for at least a year as
chairman of the executive committee of the board. While the timing
was a surprise, the eventual transition to Scott as chief executive
has been anticipated for more than a year. The company took pains
to paint the change in leadership as almost irrelevant because of a
dominant corporate culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no doubt that the same collaborative culture which has
always driven the success of our company and served our leaders so
well will also help make Lee Scott successful in his new role,'' S.
Robson Walton, Wal-Mart's chairman, said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers also emphasized what would stay the same at
the retailer instead of what would change. ``He won't do a thing
different,'' said Richard Church, an analyst with Salomon Smith
Barney, ``and investors should take comfort in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffery Feiner, an analyst with Lehman Brothers, concurred,
saying, ``This is a seamless transition.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, shares of Wal-Mart fell 62.5 cents Friday, to $64.50.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, 50, started with the company, which is based in
Bentonville, Ark., 20 years ago, as head of the trucking division.
Like many Wal-Mart executives, he came from a small-town,
state-college background. The son of a gas station owner, he grew
up in Baxter Springs, Kan., attended Pittsburg State University in
Kansas and married when he was 21.
</P>
<P>
   After joining the trucking division, he rose swiftly through the
ranks of the retailer's logistics department. He has held a wide
variety of positions at the company, including head of
merchandising and president and chief executive of the Wal-Mart
Stores division.
</P>
<P>
   While Scott will continue the growth strategy started by Glass,
there are some notable differences between the two leaders. For
starters, Scott is thought to be more of a people person than the
sometimes brusque Glass. ``He has that little extra charisma,''
said Brian James, a portfolio manager at Loomis Sayles &AMP; Co., which
owned 532,688 shares of Wal-Mart stock in September. ``He is a good
cheerleader, a good speaker and has leadership presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also say that Scott represents a new generation more
willing to tackle areas studiously avoided by the old guard. ``The
previous leadership had a Mao Tse-tung,
conquer-the-countryside-but-leave-the-cities-alone strategy,'' said
Burt Flickinger III, managing director of Reach Marketing, a retail
consulting firm that follows Wal-Mart. ``The current generation is
clearly moving to urban areas and into markets that are heavily
unionized.''
</P>
<P>
   Flickinger also predicted that under Glass the company would
focus on consumables and fashion. Wal-Mart's supercenters have been
criticized for their quality of produce and meat, especially in
foreign markets where standards for freshness are higher than in
America. The retailer has lagged behind competitors like Kmart and
Target in offering fashion to consumers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
