s f BC-AT&AMP;T-ARMSTRONG-Q&AMP;A-AR     01-14 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-ARMSTRONG-Q&AMP;A-ART-3TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR AT&AMP;T'S CHIEF, A REDEFINED CABLE LANDSCAPE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo.)   (Eds: Questions may be italicized)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic of AT&AMP;T
stock price vs. S&AMP;P 500 is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all of the communications and media companies affected by
America Online's deal to acquire Time Warner, perhaps none will
feel the impact as deeply as AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   The king of a stagnant industry _ the long-distance telephone
business _ AT&AMP;T has bet more than $100 billion of its shareholders'
money that the road to reinvigoration is paved with cable
television systems. Under C. Michael Armstrong, the company's
chairman since 1997, AT&AMP;T has acquired Tele-Communications Inc. and
agreed to buy MediaOne Group Inc. When the MediaOne takeover is
completed, AT&AMP;T will be the nation's biggest cable company.
</P>
<P>
   But it may no longer be the most important. A combined AOL Time
Warner would not only rival AT&AMP;T in cable television; it would also
be the biggest Internet company and would dwarf AT&AMP;T in other media
including movies and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   As the Bell local phone carriers move to eviscerate AT&AMP;T's core
long-distance business, AT&AMP;T badly needs to sign up cable companies
like AOL Time Warner to jointly offer phone service over cable
lines. A telephone deal AT&AMP;T had reached with Time Warner is on
hold until AT&AMP;T completes its MediaOne deal. AT&AMP;T, meanwhile, could
become a valuable partner in the distribution of America Online's
Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's cable systems do not compete directly with AT&AMP;T's,
and AT&AMP;T has been trying to form a partnership with America Online
at least since last summer.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Friday, Armstrong spoke by telephone from
Englewood, Colo., near AT&AMP;T's cable headquarters, about the broad
implications of the America Online-Time Warner agreement _ and
about what it means for his company. Following are excerpts from
the conversation: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's on your mind with all the news about the AOL-Time
Warner deal? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. First, I was delighted that it really confirms that broadband
is the future of communications, and in particular, that I think
cable has to be now declared the broadband preferred technology.
The largest transaction in American corporate history was a lot
about that. And I think as a result it's going to stimulate
boardroom thinking about new relationships between content and
distribution, including we and AOL-Time Warner. I think also,
finally, maybe it may _ and I'm out on a limb here _ it may begin
the reconciliation of the very disparate valuations that are in the
marketplace between what is a dot-com and what isn't a dot-com, as
all of us become Internet-enabled and -based. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are you thinking of this new company mostly as a competitor,
as a potential partner or somewhere in the middle? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This was very positive for the relationship, not only between
Time Warner and AT&AMP;T but now, AOL and AT&AMP;T. My bottom line is that
I believe that there's more opportunity for communications and
strategic relationship because our core strengths today now
complement each other much more than they did before. They are more
content-centric, we are communication-centric. But we both carry a
common purpose. We both seek ubiquity in reach and in devices. And
the one arena that we share, I think, a strength by working
together, is in the interactive TV area, which I think is going to
really help this whole digital revolution come to maturity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Specifically, what are some of the ways in which we might
anticipate some sort of cooperation? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think our ability to help them reach a large population of
consumers and commerce, through our infrastructure, is something
that they should be interested in, and I think they are. And surely
we have interests in using their infrastructure for our
communication-centricity to do the same, to reach an
ever-increasing number of consumers and commercial enterprises. So
we ought to be sitting down _ and I believe we will _ and expand
upon just the negotiation we were having with Time Warner to now
include a wholly new, a newly aligned AOL. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. At their news conference on Monday, Gerald Levin, the
chairman of Time Warner, and Steve Case, America Online's chairman,
said they had called you first thing that morning. Why do you think
they made that public, and what did they have to say? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, first, I think they made that public because they, too,
believed that the relationship that was developing with Time Warner
_ and it was a very sound as well as friendly relationship and we
were in discussions _ was obviously now going to be redefined. And
I don't think anybody would have suggested that AOL and AT&AMP;T, at
least publicly, were getting on that well. It was more adversarial.
And so Steve Case in particular wanted me to know that we now had
much more alignment. We now had much more common interest, and that
he very much looked forward, along with Jerry, to coming to some
communications and strategic relationships with AT&AMP;T. Finally, they
wanted to let me know that even though there were a lot of things
that were going on, they would make the time to have these
negotiations so that this would not in any way impede our
schedule. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Would it be logical to think about a potential arrangement
going forward being basically an exchange in which you agree to
carry America Online on your systems, in return for which you help
them offer telephone or some other service? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Oh, I absolutely think that carriage of AOL would be
something that we would be interested in. As well, I hope they're
interested in having us be the communications provider in their
infrastructure. I will at this time point out that we will honor
our contracts with (the Internet access service) Excite(at)Home,
though, and we will exclusively, until 2002, carry Excite(at)Home
on the very high-speed, broadband systems that we currently have.
But there are several other opportunities that are before us to do
things now, and we will be exploring those with them. We're putting
in fixed wireless systems that in the next 24 to 36 months will
pass 10 million homes. We are from the get-go opening that for
multiple Internet service providers, and that should be very
attractive. And so it's not that we have to wait for 2002 to do
some really interesting things. We can begin to do things together
that are interesting starting this year, though we will continue to
work with Excite(at)Home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How does AT&AMP;T respond most broadly to this new being? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Take advantage of it. Of course, the content production of
all the studio operations and publication operations of Time Warner
are world-class. They now are available over our infrastructure and
in turn we would hope to be the communications infrastructure that
they might implement to their customers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You mentioned the content side. You and your team have been
quite explicit about how you do not want to be a content company
per se. Does it make sense generally for a traditional source of
content to be linked with the distribution mechanism, as they are
with America Online-Time Warner, or does it make more sense not to
have that integration, the way you've chosen? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm a great believer in focus. I'm a great believer in
leading from strength. I want us to be the best communications
company in the world, and that definition includes the applications
associated with communications, content associated with
communications, like e-mail. I have to believe that Jerry Levin and
Steve Case wish to be the best originator of content, aggregator of
content. Will there be some overlap in the two definitions? I bet
there will be. Will there be any model that is the only model that
works in the marketplace that is as complex and big and exciting
and changing as fast as it is? I don't predict that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Obviously, the vast majority of your revenue still comes from
the long-distance telephone business, a business that is under some
pressure. Explain how valuable that asset is and the extent to
which it is simply a burden. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The long-distance business is not a growth business. And it
is a blessing because it is a cash machine. The long-distance
business is a commodity, and our strategy with our investments is
to decommoditize voice. And by making voice a part of a greater
communications value that customers, both consumer and commercial,
can buy, we believe we both enrich the voice application by
integrating it with those other applications, and we permit it to
continue to contribute. So voice is not dead. It's just that voice
by itself doesn't have the value to really sustain itself as a
stand-alone business. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Time Warner's media businesses _ magazines, movie studios,
books, music _ aren't growing that quickly. AT&AMP;T's historic core
business _ long-distance telephone service _ is not growing and
parts are shrinking. Which of those legacy businesses would you
rather build on? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, I happen to think cash has value. I know that it's not
``in'' these days. But I believe that in the end, cash will be
king. The AT&AMP;T company next year will generate 24 to 26 billion
dollars of Ebitda, basically cash flow. That's more cash flow than
any other nonfinancial institution in America. I believe that has
terrific value, and of course the value of cash is that it can be
deployed for growth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Delivering a Bundle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has not moved into the cable TV business to sell just cable
television. The idea is to provide a basket of futuristic
interactive television, local phone service and high-speed Internet
access over the same cable pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   But ideas and reality do not always coincide. AT&AMP;T has spent a
lot of money on its plans, but hardly any of its millions of
customers have yet entered AT&AMP;T's digital vision. Armstrong says
2000 is the year that AT&AMP;T will finally deliver. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. This integrated world of voice, video and data in an
integrated platform is something that we've been hearing about for
quite some time. Where are we in terms of making that a reality? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This is not the World's Fair for 2005, and it's not something
that's just happening now. It's happened. We have pilots now in 16
cities and we now have close to 8,000 to 10,000 subscribers for our
telephone service. In the fourth quarter we will roll out with
Microsoft and other vendors an interactive television pilot in
several cities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. When will local telephony over your cable infrastructure and
these new sorts of interactive television be broadly available in
your markets? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. By the end of the year we will have 400,000 to 500,000
telephony subscribers on our cable infrastructure. And then as we
go into 2001, that will go to the millions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. It's been a year and a half since you agreed to acquire
Tele-Communications Inc. and we haven't seen any telephony deals
with other cable providers. Is there a problem here? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Obviously, negotiating these deals, we were more optimistic
in suggesting the time frame. I think you'll see several in the
next several months because we've come that far and they're in that
stage. But it would be premature for me to say ``by this date, this
company.'' I just don't want to get caught in that again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Turnabout Is Fair Play &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, AT&AMP;T and America Online have battled about
whether the government should make cable companies open their
systems to outside Internet providers. In hearing rooms, op-ed
articles and interviews with journalists, AT&AMP;T has said no; America
Online has said yes.
</P>
<P>
   But now, America Online appears to have changed its tune. While
America Online and Time Warner said they intended to open the
combined company's systems, they appear to have joined AT&AMP;T in
arguing that the free market will eliminate the need for new
regulation about what is variously called ``open access'' and
``forced access.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. America Online seems to have had a change of heart in terms
of the need for government regulation of the Internet on cable
systems. Were you surprised at that? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I was surprised at the AOL acquisition of Time Warner. But
given that, I was not surprised at the change of heart because they
now are us. We're the No. 1 cable company and they're the No. 2
cable company. I think we together now will kill this whole issue
of forced access, because we both have the same interests. We both
want ubiquity. We want to go anywhere, and thus we want everyone to
come with us, because if everyone comes with us we'll make the most
money. I think one of the very positive things from this merger is
that the whole issue will now go away because both of us will have
common interests and be pursuing multiple providers on our
network. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How does this private-market, open-access structure operate? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Take fixed wireless, because it's a real live example of
commercial terms. We are in the Dallas-Fort Worth area next month
expanding our pilot footprint, so we'll cover thousands and
thousands of homes with fixed wireless. And that capability can
carry not only the four telephone lines but a one-megabit
online-all-the-time data line. We are currently in negotiations
with several ISPs. So we might show, for example, five, six
different ISPs that a consumer could simply click and subscribe
to. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In terms of the commercially negotiated terms, though, there
is a huge asymmetry in simple market power between an AT&AMP;T on the
one hand and most ISPs on the other. How can an ISP really think it
can get a fair shake from AT&AMP;T? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We are motivated by self-interest and greed just like they
are. And so if I go down to, I don't know, Austin _ and I'm making
this up _ and there's a UniversityofTexasnet.com ISP that really
has captured a good part of that market, and I really wish to sell
as much of my data services over this infrastructure as I can, then
having that very popular ISP on my infrastructure is the way that I
can gain new subscribers. I don't find it asymmetrical at all. And
the terms and conditions are something that we would mutually
negotiate. I need to make a return on my investment for the
infrastructure as well as a profit. And they're going to want to be
able to make a return, whether it's from advertising or e-commerce
or transactions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fair Market Value &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Next year, a combined America Online-Time Warner is expected to
have about $40 billion in revenue. AT&AMP;T's sales will probably top
$55 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, America Online and Time Warner's combined market
value Friday was about 40 percent higher than AT&AMP;T's _ roughly $245
billion, compared with $175 billion. For all of the vigor of
Armstrong's plans, the company's stock has not quite responded. On
Friday, AT&AMP;T's shares closed at $54.6875, 6.25 cents lower than
their closing price on Jan. 14, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has not hidden his frustration at the stock's
lethargy. Now, AT&AMP;T has plans to issue a separately traded stock to
track its fast-growing wireless business. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Side by side, as a stock, which company, AT&AMP;T or AOL Time
Warner, should be more valuable? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, I think there's going to be a convergence here. The
market today has been operating with disparate valuations, which is
a statement of the obvious. Dot-com companies have incredible
multiples that one can't even begin to apply to more traditional
companies. AOL built a huge market capitalization based upon the
Internet portal-type valuations the market was willing to afford
it. And it went out and bought what I would call a traditional
content company, a very strong and a very high-quality company. But
its market valuation was predicated on a much different set of
metrics. Now that they're one, the AOL Internet-space kind of
metrics are not going to prevail. And in fact the AOL growth rate,
which was 30 to 40 percent in the combined company, I heard them
announce, is now going to be 12 to 14 percent. Well, that's not far
off of AT&AMP;T's growth rate. Next year we're going to grow 8 to 9
percent. And if you looked at our business minus the consumer
business, we'd be probably growing at the same rate they are. And
so this may be the beginning of reality in terms of the convergence
of the disparate values. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What do you have to do to persuade investors to enhance your
valuation on that basis? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think the very first thing is that we need to continue to
make the commitments and execute to the potential we've defined,
both financially and operationally. The second thing is, we roll
out our wireless tracker. One, it's operationally ready for public
investment. Two, we need a currency that is defined in the
multiples that the industry is participating in so that the company
can participate in industry consolidation _ read that acquisitions
and investment. And we anticipate that the new valuation of the
tracker and a new valuation of the remaining AT&AMP;T is going to add
up to a new market capitalization. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You mentioned acquisitions and investment. What sorts of
deals do you think make sense going forward, not only for AT&AMP;T but
also for the industry? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We have some investments that have not realized the potential
that we think they have. Take Worldnet, take Web site hosting, take
Excite, as three. We believe that there's a lot of potential with
those businesses through additional investment, through new
relationships with others, so we really can create a much higher
level of growth and a much bigger critical mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where the Action Is &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong spent the first three decades of his career at IBM In
1992, when it became clear that he would not get the chairman's job
there, he jumped to General Motors' Hughes Electronics unit.
</P>
<P>
   He helped turned Hughes around, pushing it into satellite
television with its DirecTV service. But his challenge is even
greater at AT&AMP;T. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. If you had to go run one other company right now, what would
it be? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, let's see. I think that either Excite or Yahoo has got
to be a lot of fun to be in and a part of today because they are
moving so fast and doing so much and redefining themselves every
day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I know you're having fun now. But it doesn't get any easier,
does it? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. No. This is tough. And I say this is tough, not to, in fact,
suggest that the other people's jobs and other industries aren't
just as tough. The faster leadership has to manage change, to
convert attitudes and cultures, to realize the potential of
investments, to redefine markets, to retrain and retool people and
assets _ when that pace accelerates, the test of leadership is more
demanding. And that makes it increasingly tougher. I figure these
jobs maybe have, going forward, the life of an NFL halfback.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
