<HEADER>
A6641 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VODAPHONE-MANNESMANN-     01-14 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VODAPHONE-MANNESMANN-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME HARSH WORDS ON VODAFONE'S BID 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUESSELDORF, Germany _ Facing an uphill fight to ward off the
biggest hostile takeover in history, the chairman of Mannesmann AG
sought to fortify his defense against Vodafone AirTouch PLC Friday
with both sweet talk and intransigence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best response of shareholders is to do nothing at all,''
said Klaus Esser, the chairman of Mannesmann. ``They don't need to
fill out any forms. Offers not accepted are simply for the
wastepaper basket.''
</P>
<P>
   And as a sweetener for shareholders, Esser announced that
Mannesmann was likely to take its Internet business public, a move
that could help the parent company benefit from the astronomical
valuations on Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Less than four weeks remain before Mannesmann shareholders must
decide on Vodafone's offer of more than $140 billion, about 263
euros a share at current prices. But despite his defiant stance,
Esser is under increasing pressure.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few days, several investment advisers have strongly
recommended that Mannesmann shareholders accept Vodafone's offer.
Mannesmann's stock rose 8 percent Friday, to 259.25 euros. The
stock has risen 81 percent since reports emerged in late October
that Vodafone was considering a hostile bid.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, issuing Mannesmann's formal response to Vodafone's bid,
Esser reiterated his longstanding argument that Vodafone would
merely slow Mannesmann's own growth.
</P>
<P>
   He belittled Vodafone as a ``setting sun'' and said its global
strategy was based largely on properties in ``Fiji, New Zealand and
Uganda.'' He also warned that Vodafone would need to get full
control of the company to carry out its plans, and that it would
need to pay huge sums of cash to settle with a minority of
shareholders who refuse to agree.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann, based here, is currently the biggest single operator
of wireless telephone networks in Europe. Vodafone owns Britain's
second-largest mobile telephone network and holds minority stakes
in wireless networks across Europe, Asia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It is still too early to say which side will prove most
persuasive with shareholders. But in contrast to many other German
companies, which are often shielded from takeovers because large
blocks of shares are in the hands of friendly partners,
Mannesmann's stock is distributed very widely and more than 60
percent is owned outside of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Institutional Shareholder Services, which advises hundreds of
U.S. institutional investors, came out strongly in favor of
Vodafone's offer earlier this week. The advisory firm, based in
Rockville, Md., said that the combination of Vodafone and
Mannesmann would create Europe's dominant wireless carrier and that
Vodafone's offer, at current stock prices, represented a premium of
71 percent of Mannesmann's share price last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers endorsed the Vodafone bid even more strongly in
a 65-page report on Jan. 4. Jo Oliver, Lehman Brothers'
telecommunications analyst, acknowledged that Mannesmann's real
value is actually about 350 euros a share, far higher than
Vodafone's current bid.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He also agreed with Esser's assertion that Mannesmann was
growing faster than Vodafone and that a merged company would grow
slightly more slowly than Mannesmann by itself.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he contended that Vodafone's offer gave Mannesmann
a generous premium over its stock price before the takeover battle
began. And he said that the two companies would immediately create
the world's leading wireless operator and would ultimately be worth
more than if they remained separate.
</P>
<P>
   Also, ABN Amro, the big Dutch bank, issued a third ringing
endorsement of a merger on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Both Esser and Vodafone's chief executive, Chris Gent are
barnstorming for shareholder support. The deadline for Vodafone's
offer is Feb. 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
