<HEADER>
A6642 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-ROBERTS-COLUMN-NY     01-14 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROBERTS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ANOTHER PLAYER GOING ONE - ON - ONE WITH A PORSCHE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ As the hymn music ushered in the mourners, a
restless 3-year-old boy in the first row of pews noticed the bright
orange bouquet arranged in the shape of a basketball.
</P>
<P>
   He slipped from the hands of a family member like a soap bar and
skipped toward the flowers resting at the front of the church. A
trailing relative lifted him up, allowed him to touch the
candy-colored flower petals and put him down. He then turned and
pointed to the peaceful, strong figure resting in the casket, and
said, ``Daddy ... Daddy,'' as if waiting for an answer.
</P>
<P>
   Trey Phills could not comprehend the moment. No one could as the
grieving searched the church rafters for answers, inspiration and
even a little humor during a memorial for Hornets guard Bobby
Phills that elicited the raw emotions of a revival. Beneath the
shouts of ``Amen,'' scattered throughout the service, only one
person had more answers than the rest.
</P>
<P>
   There stood the distraught David Wesley. With his head tilted
down, he was the last Hornet to slip through the side door at the
Central Church of God and find his seat in the roped off section of
pews. Only Wesley knows how the final moments to Phills' life
began. Only Wesley knows what led him and his best friend to engage
their two Porsches in what the police say was a drag race that
ended with Phills' losing control of his car while streaking up a
busy, cresting curve on Tyvola Road.
</P>
<P>
   Was it as simple as, ``Race you to the light?''
</P>
<P>
   As Wesley took a deep breath, gathered his emotions and spoke at
the service Friday, he didn't allude to the instant Phills died.
But there were clues as to what might have provoked the tragedy
that unfolded Wednesday as the two self-described mischief-makers
left the Hornets' shoot-around and continued a little one-on-one on
the highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I can say, but he was my partner in crime,''
Wesley said as his voice trailed off. ``He always had to win. And
whatever he didn't do well, he'd talk enough trash to make you
think he could.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd laughed at the moment of levity. It seemed everyone in
the church knew this side of Phills. His wife, Kendall, talked
about how her husband competed ``whether it was golf, basketball,
bowling, dominoes, cards, bike riding or even a little black jack;
Bobby was playing to win. He had to make everyone know that it was
his high score on the arcade game in our game room at home.''
</P>
<P>
   But this mentality doesn't make Phills any different from other
athletes. It makes him exactly the same as all of the others who
are addicted to kind of adrenaline that ribbons its way through the
body and creates a high they seek in every facet of their life.
</P>
<P>
   Phills was bright, well-educated, well-spoken and introspective.
He also purchased a Porsche that had a top speed of 171 miles per
hour. And he foolishly pushed it to a reported speed of more than
75 miles per hour in a 45 zone without pondering the consequences
to himself or someone else.
</P>
<P>
   It's a teen-ager's mentality. Phills was 30, but he was also
part of a sports culture that retards a player's ability to grow
into an adult. The team plane, the team bus and the team locker
room, the atmosphere around each is only a half step above the
frat-house level. It's rips, jabs, put-downs and card games. Who's
got the best girl, the nicest stereo and the finest car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby had a passion for exotic cars, trucks, boats and his
black, little convertible Turbo 911 Porsche,'' Kendall Phills said
as she expressed her husband's zest for the good things in life.
``He had to make all of our cars distinct from all the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   The money only makes the addiction to adrenaline a greater
danger. The faster the car, the harder it is to resist the
temptation to push the limits. The more time on their hands, the
more room for error. Most players work four or five hours a day,
including hours in the gym and a practice session. The time lapse
in between creates boredom, and idle time breeds a window for
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   What else did Wesley and Phills have to do after practice on
Wednesday? Racing was just an outlet for their energy. Yet, it's
only natural for an athlete as aggressive as Phills to look for
ways to channel his intensity off the court. He pushed it every
night on the floor and bathed in the adulation _ just like the
mourning basketball players in attendance Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Among them, the Knicks' Latrell Sprewell and the Hornets'
Derrick Coleman. Both have been charged in connection with car
accidents. Both stand as examples of how thin the line between a
tragedy and a fender-bender can be. But the death of Bobby Phills
will not change anything. As one Knick was overheard saying,
``Bobby must have let that Porsche get away from him.''
</P>
<P>
   They all think they can handle it. That's why almost every day
after practice, one Knick player or another, is seen speeding
around the curves at SUNY-Purchase on the same street joggers use.
They all believe nothing can touch them. That's why when Magic
Johnson announced that he was HIV positive, it didn't alter
anyone's life style.
</P>
<P>
   The chase of women, racing of cars, flirting with danger, it's
all the offspring of an athletes addiction to adrenaline.
Truthfully, few would be as successful without it. Phills was able
to rise from the Continental Basketball Association and make his
way into the NBA because he had that 24-hour jones for competition.
Right to the end.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
