<SLUG> BC-PG&AMP;E-PG&AMP;E </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Lower Rate Increase Sought for PG&AMP;E  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
A member of the California Public Utilities Commission yesterday
proposed that Pacific Gas and Electric Co. receive a rate increase
well below the $822 million sought by the utility.
<P>
   Commissioner Carl Wood said he is offering an alternative rate
increase of about $400 million ``because PG&AMP;E asked for too much in
the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood's proposal must be voted on by the entire five-member
commission, which is also mulling a rate increase of $243 million
recommended by an administrative law judge.
</P>
<P>
   However, Wood's ``alternate decision'' suggests that PUC members
are dissatisfied with Judge Mark Wetzell's ruling and are trying to
come up with a workable compromise.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E has warned that as many as 3,500 workers could be fired and
tree trimming around electrical lines could be reduced if it fails
to get close to its desired increase.
</P>
<P>
   Wood said the $243 million increase now on the table ``has cut
too deeply into muscle and bone.''
</P>
<P>
   Under his alternative plan, he said he would emphasize tree
trimming to prevent fires, along with ``mechanisms to assure that
moneys earmarked for those programs are in fact spent on those
programs.''
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E spokesman Ronald Low said the utility was gratified by Wood
proposing a higher rate increase than Wetzell but noted that the
new amount was still only about half what had been originally
requested.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, The Utility Reform Network, a consumer group, said
it was mystified by Wood's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This alternate only makes sense as either an effort to rescue
PG&AMP;E's management from its own incompetence or as a decision to
hand PG&AMP;E revenues far in excess of the amount the company needs in
order to provide safe and reliable service,'' said Bob Finkelstein,
a TURN attorney.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
