r f BC-BAY-BAY_SFCHRON &LR;      01-14 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAY-BAY </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 HP Hints at Education Revolution  &HT;     By Henry Norr, Todd Wallack and Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Heading an all-star lineup at the Bay Area Council's annual outlook
conference yesterday, Hewlett-Packard's new chief executive
Carleton ``Carly'' Fiorina offered a sneak peek at a ``learning
appliance'' the company expects to announce in April.
<P>
   Encased in a red plastic shell slightly larger than a Palm
device, the handheld device ``has the potential of creating a
revolution in education,'' she said. It apparently will offer
Internet access, but she didn't demonstrate and offered no details
about what else it will do or how much it will cost.
</P>
<P>
   The new device, Fiorina said, is just one of HP's many efforts
to create a ``digital bridge'' to overcome the ``digital divide''
or the fact that white and well-off people have far more access to
new technologies than minorities and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, Silicon Valley companies don't have a great track
record in terms of inclusion and diversity,'' Fiorna said, in
calling for a new policy of ``e-inclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just an obligation, it's good business,'' she said,
in part because it's increasingly difficult to recruit outside
technical talent to move to the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Another speaker, ExciteAtHome chief executive Thomas Jermoluk,
told reporters that his company finally achieved profitability late
last year, fulfilling a promise it made when it went public.
``We've met our commitments every single quarter ... and I can
guarantee you that we've met them again,'' he said. ExciteAtHome is
expected to report earnings next week.
</P>
<P>
   Jermoluk also said his phone ``has been ringing off the hook''
with calls from prospective ``partners'' since America Online
unveiled plans Monday to buy Time Warner for about $160 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Redwood City company's stock jumped 19 percent Thursday amid
speculation that AT&AMP;T, which owns 58 percent of ExciteAtHome, might
buy the remaining shares.
</P>
<P>
   Jermoluk said the AOL-Time Warner deal helped ``validate''
broadband, or high-speed Net service, boosting interest in
ExciteAtHome.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts say AOL bought Time Warner to sell a faster
version of its service to Time Warner's 13 million cable
subscribers. Likewise, ExciteAtHome sells its high-speed Net
service through cable TV operators, including AT&AMP;T, which serves
most of the Bay Area. ExciteAtHome has 1.1 million customers
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``ExciteAtHome is very attractive,'' he added, but declined to
comment on the AT&AMP;T rumors or name which companies he's talking to
about potential deals.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Jermoluk conceded the company has had significant
service problems but said that's natural when rolling out any new
technology. On Thursday, a message on the company's technical
service hotline said there were outages in Olympia, Wash., the
entire state of Michigan and other locales, along with e-mail
problems in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take a lot of heat, but this is a tough thing,'' Jermoluk
said. He said phone companies have had similar troubles introducing
another type of high-speed Net service, called digital subscriber
line. Overall, he said, surveys show ExciteAtHome customers love
the service.
</P>
<P>
   Jermoluk also dismissed a threat from several Usenet
administrators to block ExciteAtHome customers from posting
messages to many Internet bulletin boards.
</P>
<P>
   The Usenet administrators, who oversee bulletin boards, have
posted messages on the Internet calling for the ``death penalty''
against ExciteAtHome.
</P>
<P>
   Spammers apparently were using ExciteAtHome's computer network
this month to flood bulletin boards with ads.
</P>
<P>
   But Jermoluk said the spammers simply exploited a hole in the
company's software to make their messages look like they were
coming from ExciteAtHome. The Usenet administrators believed that
ExciteAtHome knew of the problem and did nothing to stop it, but
Jermoluk said the problem has since been fixed.
</P>
<P>
   University of California economist Janet Yellen, formerly chief
economic adviser in the Clinton White House and a Federal Reserve
governor, offered an optimistic forecast for the U.S. economy this
year, tempered by concerns that roaring growth could ignite
inflation and force the Fed to raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. economy is operating outside its speed limit,''
Yellen said. But if Fed policymakers succeed in heading off a surge
in prices, ``this expansion probably still has a lot of life.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, as in many other regions, a booming economy has
left employers scrambling to fill jobs. ``Bay Area firms will face
difficulty in hiring and retaining workers,'' she noted.
</P>
<P>
   But even a slowdown in national growth wouldn't knock the props
from under the area economy. ``We are at the center of the new
economy and this technology revolution has a very long way to play
itself out,'' Yellen said. ``Our region will continue to grow and
prosper.''
</P>
<P>
   One beneficiary of the new economy, Wells Fargo Chief Executive
Officer Richard Kovacevich, warned against overestimating the power
of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Wells Fargo operates the country's largest
online banking business, with more than 1 million customers,
alongside its traditional branch network. But Kovacevich argued
that dot-com competitors who operate Internet-only banks will fall
by the wayside.
</P>
<P>
   ``For financial services, there are very few customers who are
single channel users,'' he said. ``I would bet on clicks and
bricks.''
</P>
<P>
   The business model of some online banks seems to be to ``sell a
dollar for 85 cents and make money on advertising,'' he quipped.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
