<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6647 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WALMART-WALMART_SFCHR     01-14 1494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALMART-WALMART </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Wal-Mart Is Poised to Swoop Online  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
``This is Wal-Mart.com,'' said Jim Breyer, standing amid a handful
of empty cubicles, boxes of computer gear and an unused foosball
table. ``Welcome.''
<P>
   Actually, the global headquarters of Wal-Mart.com, the
soon-to-be online arm of the world's biggest retailer, is just some
extra space in the Palo Alto offices of venture-capital firm Accel
Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer, Accel's managing partner and one of three Wal-Mart.com
board members, is now trying to quickly assemble the team,
including a chief executive, that will shift Wal-Mart's Internet
activities from the company's Arkansas base to an
as-yet-undetermined location in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high. Although Wal-Mart has had an online
presence since 1996, and revamped its site only a couple of weeks
ago, the company's Internet operation has not exactly been an
e-commerce powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   By reinventing Wal-Mart.com as a separate company co-owned by
Wal-Mart and Accel, the aim is nothing less than rapid domination
of online sales of everything from books and CDs to toys and
appliances _ in other words, creation of an outlet that competes on
the Net as aggressively as Wal-Mart overshadows the
brick-and-mortar world.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer is setting his goals high. ``Amazon.com is the most
obvious and logical initial competitor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some on Wall Street are already saying that the question should
not be whether Wal-Mart can go head to head with the likes of
Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is if Amazon can go head to head with Wal-Mart,''
said Bernard Sosnick, director of research at Fahnestock &AMP; Co. in
New York. ``Wal-Mart has never said anything less than that it
intends to be a major factor on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazon is in trouble,'' agreed Jennifer Secallus, an analyst
at Atlantis Investment in New York. ``Wal-Mart is a force to be
reckoned with.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever else, Wal-Mart.com vaults onto the playing field with
incredibly deep pockets. With a market value of nearly $300 billion
_ more than 10 times that of Amazon _ and annual revenue expected
to top $160 billion this year, Wal-Mart has money to burn in making
its online subsidiary pay off.
</P>
<P>
   And the company has no illusions about how much it's going to
lose on the venture, at least in the short run.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been braced,'' Breyer said. ``They know what they're
getting into.''
</P>
<P>
   Many details of the new company have been kept under wraps since
it was unveiled last week. While Breyer said Wal-Mart will hold the
majority of shares in Wal-Mart.com, he declined to specify the size
of the stake or how much either Wal-Mart or Accel have ponied up.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said reports that each firm has invested between $50
million and $100 million are ``not far off.''
</P>
<P>
   Breyer also said Wal-Mart's good-old-boy executives are
comfortable with the tech-industry notion of luring talent with
oodles of stock options, and have every intention to take
Wal-Mart.com public at some point.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are stock options that are going to be worth a
fortune,'' he said with a gleam in his eye. Moreover, Breyer noted
that a generous dollop of options will be ``the key part of the
benefits package for the CEO.''
</P>
<P>
   The CEO's seat should be filled within the next three months.
And for other positions, Breyer said ``thousands'' of resumes have
already been received _ even though the company has made only
minimal recruitment efforts and isn't even sure how many people it
will hire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  All this sounds rosy enough now. But it remains to be seen
how smoothly the down-home Wal-Mart corporate culture will
translate to a warp-speed Silicon Valley startup. start-up.  &LR; And
although both Wal-Mart and Accel present themselves as kissing
cousins at the moment, not all relationships between established
retailers and hotshot hot-shot  &LR; VCs end up going the distance.
</P>
<P>
   The most notorious fallout involved New Jersey's Toys R Us and
Menlo Park's Benchmark Capital.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies said last April that they were joining hands
to create Toysrus.com as an independent e-commerce entity. But as
the partners attempted to nail down key points about control and
operation of the Web site, relations between the two sides quickly
soured.
</P>
<P>
   Within months, Toys R Us and Benchmark said their alliance had
collapsed. The toy giant's CEO subsequently resigned, and the
company's online operation faced a disastrous holiday season, with
numerous orders undelivered before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Toys R Us nor Benchmark responded to calls seeking
comment on the episode.
</P>
<P>
   For Accel, which manages about $1.4 billion in tech-related
assets, making its newly forged partnership with Wal-Mart work has
been an exercise in anticipating problems before they crop up.
``The last thing anyone wants is another Toys R Us,'' Breyer said.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Accel addressed key points like going public and
offering employees stock options well in advance of the deal being
announced. And both partners appear to be unusually sensitive to
the challenge of finding common ground for their respective
cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The differences that people talk about don't register with
us,'' said Lee Scott, who was named yesterday as Wal-Mart's new
president and chief executive, and who sits on the Wal-Mart.com
board. ``Because we're in so many different countries, our culture
cuts many different ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Silicon Valley can be an alien landscape to outsiders.
Wal-Mart, taking no chances, met with nearly a dozen VC outfits and
contacted numerous business affiliates before settling on Accel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Accel has a history of longer-term commitments,'' Scott said.
``We liked that. We want to build a history.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Wal-Mart has no desire to repeat the mistakes of
Toys R Us. ``That whole thing was a good road map for us,'' Scott
admitted.
</P>
<P>
   One element of Wal-Mart's decision to spin off its Internet
operation that hasn't gotten much attention is the fact that the
new firm will be able to avoid sales taxes for most of its online
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Companies are now required to collect sales taxes for online and
catalog purchases in all states where they have a physical
presence. Wal-Mart has more than 2,400 outlets nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   But as a separate firm with physical operations only in
California and Arkansas, as well as a distribution center in Utah,
Wal-Mart.com will be able to avoid collecting sales taxes in most
states, making it a more nimble e-commerce competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, consumers themselves are required to pay
sales taxes for online and mail-order purchases from companies that
do not have a physical presence in their state. In practice, few,
if any, actually do.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer said Wal-Mart.com's management will be entirely separate
from Wal-Mart's, with the ability to purchase and price goods as it
sees fit. As such, he said it's possible that the Web site will
offer prices even lower than the bulk-order discounts that are a
hallmark of brick-and-mortar outlets.
</P>
<P>
   He said Wal-Mart.com's main strategy, at least initially, will
be to lure existing Wal-Mart shoppers to the site, as opposed to
reaching out to a whole new demographic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wal-Mart gets 100 million customers a week,'' Breyer pointed
out. ``If we can get to these people and bring them onto the Web,
the numbers are just immense.''
</P>
<P>
   A crucial ace in the hole is a recent deal between Wal-Mart and
America Online to create a co-branded Internet service targeting
rural communities. The service, which will cost less than AOL's
regular service, will of course make it easy for users to find
their way to Wal-Mart.com.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer said the Web site will benefit as well from AOL's
megamerger with Time Warner, although it's too early to say just
how that deal will affect the site's content. He hinted, though,
that users can expect an emphasis on high-speed features like video
applications.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology is going to be state of the art,'' Breyer
stressed. For example, he said Wal-Mart.com will offer ``group
shopping,'' whereby users in different locations can browse the
site together, and real-time assistance from online salespeople.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wal-Mart is famous for its service,'' Breyer noted. ``We need
to reproduce that on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Easier said than done. In any case, rivals like Amazon, for
which top-notch service is also a priority, will not simply roll
over and play dead just because Wal-Mart is finally getting serious
about the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so obsessed with providing the best customer service, we
don't have time to worry about what others are doing,'' said Paul
Capelli, a tough-talking Amazon spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Wait until Wal-Mart.com actually has people in its cubicles _
which should happen within the next few weeks. That's when things
will start to get interesting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
