u s BC-BKN-WIZARDS-NYT &LR;      01-14 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WIZARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA HOPES   FOR THE DEBUT   OF JORDAN,   THE EXECUTIVE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Basketball Association is eagerly awaiting the
return of its supernova.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan continued negotiations with the Washington
Wizards' majority owner, Abe Pollin, Friday in an effort to take
over the struggling franchise's basketball operations. Barring a
last-minute snag, an agreement could be reached as soon as this
weekend, a person with knowledge of the negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   If an agreement is reached to give Jordan total control _
trading, signing and drafting players _ he would face the daunting
task of trying to resuscitate a franchise without taking a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret that we'd like Michael Jordan, in whatever
capacity, to return to the NBA,'' said Russ Granik, the league's
deputy commissioner. ``He's a tremendous asset to the NBA, and his
association with the league can do nothing but help us.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Whether it's in Washington or anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached by telephone while on vacation Friday, David Falk,
Jordan's agent, would neither confirm nor deny that a deal had been
struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone through this with Denver, Orlando, Vancouver and
other franchises,'' he said. ``We're not going to respond to
Michael rumors. We haven't done that for the last 15 years. It's
been our consistent position until an agreement is finalized.''
</P>
<P>
   Falk added: ``I don't know if Michael is going to come back to
the NBA in any shape or form. But there's no question he is perhaps
the biggest influence in the game, a wonderful spokesman, performer
and role model. He stands for everything good about the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the remaining snags in a potential deal that was reported
Friday by The Washington Post was the amount of equity in the
franchise that the minority owners, Ted Leonsis and Jon Ledecky,
would cede to Jordan. Leonsis and Ledecky own 44 percent of the
team, and they have been given the right of first refusal by
Pollin, who owns the other 56 percent, when he decides to sell his
majority share.
</P>
<P>
   What's in the deal for Pollin?
</P>
<P>
   Whether it is spending $200 million to build the MCI Center in
downtown Washington so that a broader commercial life might return
to the city, or paying $105 million to hang on to the team's
emerging star, Juwan Howard, three years ago, Pollin has done
nearly everything possible to make sure his moribund franchise
returns to prominence _ without many results.
</P>
<P>
   With his team at 12-24 and the playoffs again slipping away, the
league's senior owner has a chance to give the Wizards an
incalculable image boost before eventually giving up his majority
share of the team. Always a civic-minded philanthropist, Pollin
could go out a winner with Jordan in charge.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing to put Jordan's likeness on a billboard. It is
quite another when Jordan is making the recruiting call to free
agents like Grant Hill and Tim Duncan in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   However inaccurate, there was a perception that Dean Smith made
fewer home visits in his later years as coach of North Carolina.
College basketball's career winningest coach, it was said, simply
told Jordan whom to call and when, and the Tar Heels would produce
another blue-chip recruiting class.
</P>
<P>
   No one in the world of sports or business approaches his
celebrity pull.
</P>
<P>
   An Eastern Conference general manager who spoke on condition of
anonymity said he spoke with the Wizards' general manager, Wes
Unseld. He said Unseld, who has refused to comment on the
negotiations, was unaware of where the parties were as of Thursday
and was unclear what his role would be if Jordan took over the
basketball operations.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has never held a management position in the league, but
his marketing savvy and his ability to successfully negotiate with
NBA Commissioner David Stern during last year's labor standoff gave
him valuable experience.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen how Jordan will react when a nettlesome
agent is not on his side at the bargaining table. Or whether he can
negotiate a salary cap and handle the day-to-day grind of working
behind a desk.
</P>
<P>
   But he appears on his way back, and the NBA cannot wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be great,'' said B.J. Armstrong, Jordan's former
teammate in Chicago and good friend. ``As competitive as he is, I
think he's going to do a wonderful job. He knows the league and
everyone currently playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would have thought five years ago that Michael Jordan
would be running a team already? Believe me, you could see this was
coming.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 2230EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
