<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6649 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-IMAGE-NYT &LR;      01-14 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-IMAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH IMPROVES ON THE STUMP (WITH RESERVATIONS) 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The question-and-answer session was chugging along
rather unremarkably, with Gov. George W. Bush coasting on automatic
pilot through all of the usual issues, when he suddenly encountered
an unexpected pocket of potential turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody wanted to know his feelings about the human genome
project.
</P>
<P>
   This was not a topic that had emerged in any of the Republican
debates. Almost certainly, the Texas governor had not been briefed
on it. Quite possibly, he had never addressed it before.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, without missing a beat, Bush flew confidently and
gracefully into the heart of it. He told the audience at St.
Anselm's College in Manchester, N.H., earlier this week that the
mapping of the human gene would probably bring cures for
``genetically driven diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   But he noted that there were ethical dilemmas embedded in
forecasting a person's biological destiny. ``You can imagine what
that would mean for the ability to spread risk across insurance
pools,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   And there were temptations. ``I worry about people taking the
place of God,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush clearly knew what he was talking about, and over the last
two weeks, during which the Texas governor has been campaigning
with more intensity than ever, there have been many similar moments
when he seemed wholly in command.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been at least as many episodes when Bush seemed a
bit lost, or at least unwilling to stray from familiar oratorical
terrain. And despite three debates this month and dozens of
campaign speeches, he remains something of a muddle: authoritative
and insightful one day, hazy or scripted or platitudinous the next.
</P>
<P>
   He has performed well enough not to diminish the strong
likelihood that he will cinch the Republican presidential
nomination. But he has left unanswered the question of just how
potent an adversary he would be for the Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon Bush will participate in his seventh debate,
the last before the Iowa caucuses Jan. 24. The candidate's senior
advisers seem genuinely optimistic about how he will do; in their
view, his performances have steadily improved and he has taken to
heart whatever failings he noticed in a videotape of all his
remarks in the three debates in December. Aides prepared it for
him, and he studied it over his holiday break.
</P>
<P>
   But there were several stretches in the most recent Republican
debate in Grand Rapids, Mich., on Monday when Bush seemed to be
indulging his oft-noted habit of resorting to well-practiced
strokes, when he treaded water and did not keep his head much above
the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the federal government should send hundreds of
millions of dollars to help relieve the scourge of AIDS in Africa,
Bush seemed intent on pivoting into tried-and-true language, and
started talking about the need to ``rally other compassionate
nations around the world to provide the money.''
</P>
<P>
   It was essentially his canned riff on the need to ``rally the
armies of compassion,'' a line in his stump speech about
encouraging religious groups to do more social work, only now he
had gone global with it.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the derogatory racial comments of the baseball
pitcher John Rocker and what his team, the Atlanta Braves, should
or should not do to punish him, Bush hastily constructed a verbal
bridge to another signature phrase from his stump speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'd like to do as president of the United States is usher
in the responsibility era,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if he were rummaging through previously composed index
cards in his mind and plucking the one that seemed the most
relevant.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Bush's tendency to do that so confusing is that in
private conversations, with no television cameras around and are no
tape recorders on, he demonstrates a much more impressive
intellectual and verbal fluency.
</P>
<P>
   One senior adviser explained this discrepancy by saying that
when the clock is ticking, as it is in a debate, Bush feels
pressure to be concise and pithy, which sometimes translates into
superficial and canned.
</P>
<P>
   Another adviser said Bush, by nature, adopted a more formal,
constrained manner in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an element of caution,'' the adviser said. ``He does a
lot better one-on-one than in multiperson formats. He's what I like
to refer to as a serially monogamous campaigner. He doesn't win
over voters en masse. He wins them over one at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Bush's usual ebullience and confidence, he seems prey at
times to nervousness and exhaustion, either of which might explain
the curious grammatical lapses and verbal blunders that the
candidate has been committing.
</P>
<P>
   This week he told an audience in Florence, S.C., that
educational yardsticks needed to be implemented so that lawmakers,
teachers and parents had answers to the question, ``Is our children
learning?''
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, in Mount Pleasant, S.C., he muffed a line in the
foreign policy section of his speech, referring to the danger of
``potential missile launches'' with a phrase that sounded like
``potential menshul losses.'' The second word is spelled
phonetically, because the word itself does not exist.
</P>
<P>
   But in between those two events, at a brief news conference in
an airport hangar in Florence, Bush was back in the saddle again.
</P>
<P>
   While he had previously weighed in on whether Elian Gonzalez
should be returned to his father in Cuba, Bush was asked something
more specific: Was it really responsible of the boy's dead mother,
who has been hailed by some people in the United States as a hero,
to put her young son at such risk by taking him to sea?
</P>
<P>
   Bush's answer was not linguistically elegant, but it was
politically deft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible to second-guess the decision of a mom, because
you and I don't know what it's like to live in tyranny,'' he said.
``It shows how amazing the great beacon of America is.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, he hit a note of winning charm in answering a
voter's question about what might distinguish his presidency from
his father's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I've got half my mother in me,'' he said, to a roar of
laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Humor has been Bush's consistent forte, and he has leaned on it
more and more frequently in his debates and public appearances over
the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in a debate in Columbia, S.C., Bush responded to a
question about the biggest mistake he had ever made by citing his
former career as managing general partner of the Texas Rangers and
his decision to trade the baseball player Sammy Sosa for Harold
Baines. Sosa went on to greatness; Baines did not.
</P>
<P>
   It showed voters just how quick and funny Bush can be. But it
told them little _ at least for now, as he carefully protects a big
lead _ about his capacity for reflection, about how deep he can or
cannot go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
