<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIN98 UPGRADE DOESN'T TAKE DISKS _ JUST A LITTLE FAITH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: I purchased a used PC and did not get any disks
or CDs with it. I want to upgrade to Windows 98 or Windows 2000,
but I do not have the Windows 95 CD. Do I need this? Also, will I
lose anything that is on my PC? I do not have the backups for the
software. _ Uneasy Upgrader
</P>
<P>
   Dear Uneasy: I realize this is closing the barn door long after
ol' Dobbin has been packed off to the glue factory, but you should
never buy a used computer if the seller won't provide you with the
original disks for software loaded on the machine.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, if you don't have the disks, you have no way of
proving the software isn't bootlegged. Second, even if you don't
care about the legal stuff, there'll come a day when your computer
goes kerblooey, and you'll have to rebuild it from the ground up.
</P>
<P>
   Simply upgrading to Win98 or Win2K shouldn't be a major problem,
though. You don't need the Win95 CD to do it, unless the upgrade
installation fails and leaves you with a very expensive
paperweight. And don't listen to all those Microsoft apologists who
say that can't happen. It does. Not often, but it does. It happened
to me. I lost hundreds of irreplaceable files. But I'm not bitter.
No, not the least little bit. I just hope Bill Gates roasts in ...
Hmmm, I see I've strayed a tad. Sorry.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead and try the upgrade. The odds are actually pretty good
that you'll get through it OK. Maybe my problems had to do with
karma.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: My 2 1/2-year-old computer has begun to freeze
up. The error message is ``Rnaapp not responding.'' The only way to
resolve the problem is to shut down and reboot. _ Mr. Freeze
</P>
<P>
   Dear Mr. Freeze: It's a little-known theory that when software
engineers design the complex ways their programs interact with
Windows and other installed products, they use the clown-car
principle. In other words, they stuff Mr. Chuckles into the car and
hope that his elbow doesn't jab Flopsy in the eye and that his big,
dopey clown shoes don't wind up in Moopie-Pie's ear.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Chuckles is not getting along with one of the other clowns.
Somewhere along the line, you have installed something that upset
another program. Remember the warning that most setup routines
display? The one that says you should probably close all other
Windows programs before proceeding? Of course not. Nobody ever pays
attention to that, and most times you can get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, though, you got busted. Maybe you didn't turn off
your virus checker before doing the installation. I always forget
that one, and I've gotten that same error. All you can do now is to
uninstall possible offending programs in reverse order, turn off
everything else, put on your big red nose, then reinstall.
</P>
<P>
   If none of that works, uninstall again, then go to Windows Setup
and get rid of Dial-Up Networking (Rnaapp is part of that). Now
reinstall, reinstall, reinstall.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: Tell me how to burn a CD of a copy-protected
game. _ Bandit
</P>
<P>
   Dear Bandit: Why don't I just show you how to hold up a liquor
store? That's just as illegal, but at least you'd have the cash to
buy the game.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: Why do you feel it necessary to be so rude and
sarcastic? Please change your attitude. _ Shocked and Offended
</P>
<P>
   Dear Shocked: No. But thanks for asking. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay says if you want to read all those terribly
polite but extremely unfunny computer columnists, that's entirely
your decision. He still gets paid. E-mail your complaints to
drbombay\Nstar-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort Worth Star-Telegram,
Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax: 390-7257. In real life, Dr.
Bombay is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
