<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLAXO-SMITHKLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGER TALKS BY SMITHKLINE AND GLAXO 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Two British pharmaceutical giants, SmithKline Beechham
PLC and Glaxo Wellcome PLC, are near agreement on a $80.7 billion
merger that would create the world's largest drug maker, executives
close to the talks said here Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   A deal, which could be announced as early as Monday, comes
almost two years after merger talks between the two companies
collapsed in a dispute over who would control the combined company.
</P>
<P>
   That stumbling block was cleared in large part in early
December, when Jan Leschly, the chief executive of SmithKline, who
had been seen as largely responsible for the management stalemate,
announced that he planned to retire in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been expecting this deal would be back on the cards
since the talks fell apart the first time,'' said Franc Gregori, an
analyst with BNP Paribas in London. ``You've got the making of a
super company that will have critical economies of scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Also propelling the deal forward was the announcement on
Thursday by Warner-Lambert that it was in talks with Pfizer over a
possible merger, upsetting an earlier agreement between
Warner-Lambert and American Home Products. Last month, Pharmacia &AMP;
Upjohn and Monsanto announced a merger deal.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that lack sufficient research and marketing muscle are
under pressure to seek partners, and analysts expect the furious
pace of consolidation in the industry to accelerate even more.
Novartis, Bristol-Myers Squibb, Eli Lilly, Roche and American Home
Products are considered likely to seek deals soon.
</P>
<P>
   For Glaxo and SmithKline, a combination may give them the size
to try to right laggard sales and marketing miscues as well as
vault them into a class of their own. A combined Glaxo-SmithKline
would have $17.88 billion in drug sales, based on 1998 data,
towering over the current No. 1, Aventis, with $10.8 billion in
sales, according to IMS Health, an industry consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo's top-selling drugs include Imitrex, an anti-migraine
treatment, and medicines for respiratory ailments and for HIV.
SmithKline makes Avandia, a leading diabetes drug, and Paxil, a
leading antidepressant.
</P>
<P>
   Though both Glaxo and SmithKline have extensive operations in
the United States, a successful merger would mean that of the top
five drug companies, only one would be American: a combined Pfizer
and Warner-Lambert. Two years ago, three of the five largest drug
companies were American. Still, a combined Glaxo-SmithKline would
control only 7.5 percent of the world market.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo's chief executive, Richard Sykes, ``believes vehemently
that bigger is better,'' said James Culverwell, an analyst with
Merrill Lynch in London. ``To him, Pfizer-Warner Lambert changes
the competitive landscape. He doesn't want to lose out.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in an interview in November, when Pfizer made a hostile
bid for Warner Lambert, Sykes said that a combination of American
Home and Warner Lambert ``would not have had a major impact on our
business, but if you get Pfizer and Warner Lambert, you are talking
about 7 to 8 percent market share, a big number.'' Noting what a
combined Pfizer-Warner Lambert could spend on research, he added,
``I think it should be a worry to anybody that one company is
spending between $3 billion and $4 billion a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, SmithKline and Glaxo representatives confirmed that they
were in talks, though neither would disclose any specifics except
to say that any deal would be a merger of equals. Glaxo is a much
larger company, however, and the combined company is expected to be
divided about 60-40 in favor of Glaxo shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to the talks said the two companies planned to
work out the final details over the weekend. They stressed that as
with any deal of this size, the companies could still decide to
abandon the effort.
</P>
<P>
   One issue that has been agreed upon, executives close to the
talks said, is that Sykes would become chairman of the combined
company, while Jean-Pierre Garnier, chief operating officer of
SmithKline, would become chief executive. Within a few years,
Garnier would be expected to succeed Sykes.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that Sykes and Garnier were much more compatible
as a management team than Sykes and Leschly, and that now the deal
had to be completed, if for no other reason than to save face.
``There is a real fear of failure if a deal doesn't get done now,''
Gregori, of BNP Paribas, said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors applauded the possibility of a tie-up. Shares of
SmithKline rose 56 pence, or 7 percent, to 847 pence. Shares of
Glaxo rose 78 pence, or 4.5 percent, to 1.8 pounds. SmithKline's
American depository receipts rose $3.9375, to $70, and Glaxo's
gained $2, to $60.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Times and USA Today reported Friday that the
companies were in talks.
</P>
<P>
   Would investors have fared better if the companies had completed
a deal in 1998? Culverwell, the Merrill Lynch analyst, said he did
not think so. ``If a deal had been done two years ago, the terms
would be very different,'' he said. ``It would have been out of
desperation. SmithKline has more broadly based growth now. And
Glaxo was in the throes of several patents expiring at the time.
And to be frank, this time around, with Leschly leaving, its just
more straightforward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 2244EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
