u f BC-ECON-EPORT-NYT &LR;      01-14 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-EPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMER PRICES INCREASE A MODEST 0.2 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the latest evidence that inflation remains in check, consumer
prices rose only modestly in December even as the economy roared
toward a record for uninterrupted expansion, Labor Department
figures showed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A lower-than-expected rise in the Consumer Price Index of 0.2
percent, combined with reassuring comments Thursday evening by Alan
Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, to help propel the Dow
Jones industrial average to its third record close of the week.
</P>
<P>
   But after the government issued its report on inflation and
other data on industrial output and inventories, word came in
midmorning that consumers might have become unduly optimistic. That
could mean continuation of a breakneck spending pace that the
Federal Reserve has been trying to arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The news pushed interest rates, which had initially subsided,
higher for the day and left economists less convinced that the
central bank can avoid repeated increases in its short-term rate
target, now 5{ percent. It is all but certain, analysts say, that
the Fed will decide on a quarter-point rise at the end of its
two-day meeting at the beginning of February.
</P>
<P>
   December's rise in consumer prices lifted the 1999 inflation
rate to 2.7 percent, with the acceleration from 1998's 1.6 percent
reflecting a sharp jump in the price of oil. Energy prices surged
13.4 percent last year after falling 8.8 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But with the wide-swinging energy and food components set aside,
the so-called core inflation rate last year was 1.9 percent, the
lowest since 1965.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement accompanying her department's release of the
report, Labor Secretary Alexis Herman said the economy remained
``strong and growing and should be nominated for best picture'' at
the Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Private analysts were also encouraged, saying that medical care
appeared to be the only unsettling major sector, assuming that the
price of oil stops rising. Medical costs advanced 0.4 percent for
the second consecutive month and 3.7 percent for 1999 as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty reassuring report,'' said Edward McKelvey, a
senior economist at Goldman, Sachs. He added that while Greenspan
would no doubt tighten credit another notch or two, the chairman's
speech to the Economic Club of New York indicated he was not ``on
the warpath.''
</P>
<P>
   That stance is perceived despite an increase of 0.9 percent in
inventories in November, which suggested that the economy's growth
rate could approach 6 percent for the quarter. Analysts hope that
much of the rise will prove temporary, reflecting stocks built in
anticipation of possible Year 2000 computer failures.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate tally Friday, the University of Michigan said its
index of consumer sentiment soared to 111.4 at the mid-January
reading, the highest in its 20-year history, from 105.4 at the end
of December. Although this unnerved the bond market, index sponsors
said the rise might have been magnified by relief that no computer
disasters occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the kind of reading that if it persists could suggest
consumer spending could ratchet up at a rapid pace,'' said Richard
Rippe, chief economist at Prudential Securities. On the other hand,
he said, Year 2000 considerations could mean it was temporary and
not worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the economy, which has been growing without
interruption since April 1991, is expected to break the longevity
record for a business expansion set in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few sectors not suffering some strain is American
industry, where output grew 2.2 percent last year, mostly in
technology equipment, the Federal Reserve reported Friday. Output
rose 0.4 percent in December, with plants operating at 81.3 percent
of capacity, still below the historic average of 82.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The inflation report showed housing and food and beverages each
up 0.1 percent in December; for the full year, housing rose 2.2
percent, with food and beverages up 2 percent. Transportation
climbed 0.7 percent in December and 5.4 percent for 1999, mainly
reflecting the surge in fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   The index for used cars and trucks fell 0.7 percent last month,
while the price of public transportation fell 0.5 percent, mainly
reflecting lower airline fares. For the full year, however, air
fares advanced 10.9 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 2247EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
