<SLUG> BC-AOL-TIME-WARNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AOL AND TIME WARNER RETREAT AS WALL STREET REVIEWS OUTLOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The shares of America Online declined $1.3125, or 2
percent, Friday, to $63.1875, while Time Warner's fell 75 cents, to
$83.25, as investors struggled to figure out the financial outlook
for the $165 billion merger that the two companies announced on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's drop Friday was modest compared with Thursday's upward
bounce, leaving it comfortably above Wednesday's closing price of
$60. Time Warner's decline was in line with that of other
communications company stocks Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts cautioned against trying to read too much into
Friday's action.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that if prices remain around current levels for a
couple of weeks, doubts about whether the deal will be completed
should evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   The only new development Friday was AOL's filing of documents
with the Securities and Exchange Commission outlining the merger
agreement. The filing disclosed that if America Online cancels the
deal and is bought by another company within a year, it must pay a
breakup fee to Time Warner of $5.4 billion. If Time Warner pulls
out and is acquired within a year, it must pay AOL $3.7 billion.
Those fees translate into 2.75 percent of the market valuation of
America Online and Time Warner respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Koch, co-head of mergers and acquisitions for Credit
Suisse First Boston, said the 2.75 percent breakup fee was typical.
``The absolute level, of course, is somewhat staggering,'' Koch
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the agreement contains a second breakup provision.
If AOL shareholders vote down the deal but AOL remains independent,
AOL must pay Time Warner 1 percent of its market value at the time
of the announcement, or $2 billion. If Time Warner shareholders
vote down the deal and Time Warner remains independent, Time Warner
must pay AOL $1.4 billion _ 1 percent of Time Warner's market
value.
</P>
<P>
   The 1 percent fee ``is not unheard of, but it's not the norm,''
Koch said. Courts in Delaware, where most corporations are based,
have found such fees to be reasonable because they compensate a
company for the time its management has spent on a deal and other
costs, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
