A6740 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-ENVIRONMENT-NYT &LR;      01-14 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ENVIRONMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SUING ON NATURE'S BEHALF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Jan. 15:
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court acted decisively this week to preserve one of
the nation's most valuable tools for protecting the environment _
the ability of citizens to enforce federal anti-pollution laws
through private legal actions. By a surprisingly lopsided 7-2
margin, the court voted to pull back from its own recent rulings,
and those of lower federal courts, that had significantly narrowed
the ability of environmental groups to pursue polluters in court.
</P>
<P>
   The case, involving a hazardous-waste incinerator in South
Carolina, posed a crucial test of the continued vitality of
provisions of the Clean Water Act, the Clean Air Act and the other
sweeping environmental measures of the 1970s that authorized
individuals to act as ``private attorneys general'' and collect
fines on behalf of the federal treasury. Congress wisely included
these provisions as a hedge against the tendency of government
regulators to become too cozy with the industries they oversee, and
much of the environmental progress the nation has achieved since
then has resulted from citizen-generated suits.
</P>
<P>
   To Justice Antonin Scalia, however, giving citizens enforcement
power gave plaintiffs too much bargaining power and threatened
democratic governance. Over the past few years his views persuaded
several courts to limit citizen court access in environmental
cases. Happily the new decision, written by Justice Ruth Bader
Ginsburg, takes a sharp turn in the opposite direction.
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg argues that the fact that fines imposed in citizen
suits flow to the federal treasury and not the plaintiffs does not
deprive the plaintiffs of the stake in the outcome of the case
required to establish standing. Moreover, the ruling makes plain
that a polluter does not render a case moot, thereby escaping fines
and the need to reimburse plaintiffs' legal fees, simply by
complying with regulations after a legal action has begun. A case
is moot, Ginsburg said, setting an appropriate standard, only if it
is ``absolutely clear'' that the violations will not recur.
</P>
<P>
   Had the court once again followed Scalia's preferred path, 30
years of forward progress on environmental issues would have been
put at risk. Instead &UR; , &LR;  the court took one look at this abyss and
turned aside.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
