<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STADIUM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TASK FORCE: PAY UP OR LOSE CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY PAT FLANNERY  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull's stadium task force sent Arizonans a pointed
message Friday:
</P>
<P>
   If you want to keep an NFL franchise, prepare to raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The panel released a tentative proposal to levy several special
taxes over the next three decades to finance $224 million of the
$329 million construction cost of a new football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But Arizona Senate President Brenda Burns offered an equally
pointed reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think voters have made it clear that they don't want a tax
increase to fund stadiums,'' she said through a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Burns also vowed a public vote on any proposed tax hikes, a
chilling prospect for stadium backers who watched Mesa voters shoot
down the Rio Salado Crossing stadium project last year.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's proposal, the product of two months of work by the task
force, would fund a facility to host the Cardinals, the Fiesta Bowl
and, panel members hope, several Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the upfront cost would be covered by the Cardinals,
the Fiesta Bowl and interest earnings on construction bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The task force asked the Cardinals to put up $75 million, the
same amount the team offered for the Rio Salado Crossing proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed new taxes include:
</P>
<P>
   _ A new 0.5 percent statewide hotel bed tax, which would be
added to the current statewide hotel/motel tax of 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _In Maricopa County alone, another 0.5 percent bed tax would be
added to the statewide hike. It would increase the 6.27 percent
hotel/motel taxes paid in Maricopa County to 7.27 percent, said
Vince Perez, an Arizona Department of Revenue spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   _A new 3 percent tax on car rental sales in Maricopa County,
replacing the flat $2.50 fee now charged on every car rental.
</P>
<P>
   _State income taxes already paid by professional football
players in Arizona, and new state income taxes levied on salary
earned in Arizona by all visiting pro sports players. Although the
tax on visiting players' salaries would apply to all sports, only
visiting NFL players' taxes would be earmarked for stadium
financing.
</P>
<P>
   _State sales taxes paid on the construction value of the
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   _State sales taxes paid on concessions in the new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Bank One Chairman Michael Welborn, who heads the task force,
said he was ``optimistic'' the plan could be embraced by the
Arizona Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the tax revenues being sought wouldn't be collected in
Arizona were it not for the Cardinals, Wellborn and others pointed
out. Others are narrowly targeted taxes affecting tourists, and
these levies would also generate revenue for tourism promotion.
</P>
<P>
   And Welborn warned that this could be Arizona's last chance to
keep the Cardinals. Though owner Bill Bidwill has not said he would
move the team without a new stadium, most members of the task force
expect that to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bidwills have been terrific in not trying to make this a
threat issue,'' Welborn said. ``But at the end of the day, this is
still a business.''
</P>
<P>
   Task force members noted repeatedly Friday that their
preliminary plan contained something for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cardinals are very happy to be a part of it,'' Bidwill
told the task force shortly before his son, Michael, unleashed
Aeneas Williams and two other Cardinals players to schmooze panel
members.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Cardinals' financial participation appears no greater
than in Rio Salado Crossing, task force members insisted the team's
commitment is stronger. That's because it came without any
guarantees that parking revenues would be available to cover some
costs, they said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Cardinals do want revenues from at least 7,500
parking spaces before buying off on the new deal.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's proposal pays only for construction of the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The task force has already said it is eyeing six sites in
Phoenix, Tempe and Mesa. It will confer with the cities during the
next few weeks, hoping to lure offers of free land, parking
facilities and infrastructure development.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the Fiesta Bowl's proposed $20 million contribution
would be raised by selling permanent seat licenses for club seating
at the bowl. However, panel members noted that the $20 million
figure is still being negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed new taxes, applied for the next 29 years, would
raise more than $2 billion, some of which would go to other causes,
such as tourism promotion and bolstering the Cactus League, the
10-team spring training league based in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   State tourism officials say the Cactus League, which lured a
million visitors to the state last year, is in danger of being
raided by other states.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona hopes to keep the teams and lure others like the Los
Angeles Dodgers, which are looking for new facilities.
</P>
<P>
   If the stadium plan succeeds, the Cactus League will be
guaranteed revenue to help build new facilities and maintain older
sites so teams don't bolt.
</P>
<P>
   To get the hospitality and rental-car industries to accept the
new taxes, the task force also would beef up state tourism
spending.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal earmarks a percentage of new revenues each year for
promotion, with the immediate effect of doubling the state's annual
tourism promotion budget to $12 million from $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens are invited to find out more about the stadium plans
and offer their own suggestions at a public meeting Tuesday, from 6
to 9 p.m. at the Salt River Project's PERA Club, 1 E. Continental
Drive, Tempe. The facility is west of Scottsdale Road between
McDowell and Curry roads. &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Pat.Flannery(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or at (602) 444-8629. &QL; 
The Bidwills have been terrific in not trying to make this a threat
issue. But at the end of the day, this is still a business.Michael
WelbornBANK ONE CHAIRMAN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 2315EST &QL; 
