<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAT BUCHANAN: BACK IN NEW HAMPSHIRE
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Buchanan on Friday made his first campaign stop in New
Hampshire since a brief appearance Oct. 25 when he announced his
bid for the Reform Party presidential nomination. Buchanan said of
the Democrats and Republicans, ``The two Washington parties have
become Xerox copies of one another.'' But he called himself ``the
defending champion of the New Hampshire primary,'' referring to his
defeat of former Sen. Bob Dole in the 1996 Republican contest
there. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OPINION SURVEYS: TEXANS BACK BUSH
</P>
<P>
   No surprise, but Gov. George W. Bush's fellow Texans support him
overwhelmingly, according to a new Dallas Morning News/Houston
Chronicle poll. Bush leads Vice President Al Gore 59 percent to 32
percent and former Sen. Bill Bradley 62 percent to 28 percent. Gore
led Bradley 54 percent to 24 percent in the poll, which had a
margin of sampling error of 6 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   ORRIN HATCH: PAID NOTICE
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, his Republican presidential candidacy barely
registering in the polls, bought his first television
advertisements in New Hampshire this week. They are 30-minute
speeches, which began at 7:30 p.m. Wednesday and Thursday on WMUR
in Manchester. In the advertisements, he attacks the Clinton
administration as ``the most deceitful and corrupt'' in history.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: FAMILY OUTINGS
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush's campaign is bringing out the big-name
surrogates. His father, former President George Bush, who stumped
for his son in Iowa on Thursday, will campaign for him in South
Carolina on Saturday, the Bush campaign announced Friday. Gov.
Bush's brother Jeb, the governor of Florida, will work in New
Hampshire for him Saturday, and Elizabeth Dole will make three
appearances on his behalf in Iowa on Saturday and another three in
South Carolina on Sunday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLICANS: E-CAMPAIGNING
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee became an Internet service
provider Friday, offering direct access to the World Wide Web.
Besides free e-mail and chat rooms, the service will give members
customized Web pages that will provide updates on Republican
developments, as well as what party officials called an ``anti-smut
filter'' and unbiased reporting about news events. The service is
intended for ``people who want freedom FROM the press,'' according
to an advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN McCAIN: OWN MEDICINE?
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain has upbraided the Republican establishment in
New York, which is allied with Gov. George W. Bush, for considering
a challenge to McCain's nomination petitions to get him thrown off
the ballot. But in 1998, McCain's Senate campaign challenged the
petitions of a Republican candidate named Bert Tollefson. Tollefson
was effectively forced to withdraw, leaving McCain with no primary
opponent. But a McCain campaign spokesman, Howard Opinsky, said
yesterday that the laws in Arizona were far more forgiving than
those in New York.
</P>
<P>
   THE CROWD: ROAD TRIP
</P>
<P>
   Why bother with Daytona Beach when you can spend winter break in
New Hampshire? Cam Winton, 21, a junior at the University of
Pennsylvania, packed four friends into a rented Dodge Caravan and
hit Dublin, Londonderry, Hooksett, Peterborough and Manchester in a
quest to shake hands with the next president of the United States,
logging nearly 800 miles by yesterday, when they caught up with
Vice President Al Gore. They ribbed Bill Bradley for being a
Princeton Tiger, and caught George W. Bush's attention when they
made eyes after the candidate mentioned his 18-year-old twin
daughters.
</P>
</TEXT>
