<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOBBYIST-REPORT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR WANTS PUBLIC TO KNOW WHICH LAWMAKERS RECEIVE LOBBYISTS'
LARGESSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN L. PETTERSON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   TOPEKA, Kan. _ Just ask Gov. Bill
Graves. He'll tell you it's time for lobbyists to start naming
names when they report the cost of their efforts to influence the
Legislature.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tab for steaks and wine for a couple of senators? It should
show up on the monthly report, right next to the names of the
diners.
</P>
<P>
   Same for the cost of those Royals tickets lobbyists bought for
the House members they accompanied to Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has asked the Legislature to require members' names
to be reported on official lobbyist spending documents that would
be available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't like lobbyist reporting,'' Graves said Monday after
he made the recommendation in his State of the State address. ``I
think it's time.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor may think it's time, but he appears to be short of
supporters in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Dick Bond, an Overland Park Republican, said he
sees no problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is: Is there abuse?'' he asked. ``I don't believe
we have a serious abuse problem. You've got to prove that before
you change the law.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been previous efforts to pass similar legislation,
but such efforts have been unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Hellebust tried to get similar legislation approved when he
headed Common Cause in Kansas from 1986 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never did get a very receptive hearing,'' he said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the legislators wanted people to know who was taking
them out or buying them tickets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For some time, the legislature in Missouri has required
lobbyists to report the names of lawmakers who receive lobbyist
largess if it isn't provided to the entire legislature or to an
entire party caucus or committee.
</P>
<P>
   Records of those individual expenditures are available for
public inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Not in Kansas, though, and the governor isn't optimistic he'll
be able force a change this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that its chances are particularly good, but I
think it is important, especially in an election year,'' Graves
said.
</P>
<P>
   All 165 legislative seats are up for grabs this year.
</P>
<P>
   In the first eight months of last year, the 588 registered
lobbyists spent $432,098 on food and beverages to influence the
Legislature. That averages out to $2,619 for each representative
and senator.
</P>
<P>
   But most lawmakers don't see the need for tighter reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rich Becker, a Lenexa Republican, thinks any reporting
legislation should be tied to a thorough discussion of the
legislative pay issue.
</P>
<P>
   Becker thinks lawmakers' pay, $74.58 per day while they are in
session or are attending summer committee meetings, is too low.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't like to read news stories about the average amount
lobbyists spend on lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Give him the average amount, he said, ``and I'll buy my own
chips and dip, and sodas out of the Coke machine.''
</P>
<P>
   To the argument some lawmakers advance that they are paid too
little to afford three squares a day while maintaining a residence
in their home districts, the governor offered this response:
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, baloney.''
</P>
<P>
   Legislation containing the governor's recommendation was
introduced this week by the House Governmental Organization and
Elections Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lisa Benlon, a Shawnee Republican and chairwoman of the
committee, said hearings on the measure probably will be scheduled
for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some legislators, she predicted, may have a problem with the
bill ``because they have standing evening meals set up (with
lobbyists).''
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Sen. Janice Hardenburger, a Haddam Republican and
chairwoman of the Senate Elections and Local Government Committee
that handles ethics legislation, said lobbyists won't like the bill
because it will require extra paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   Should the legislation emerge from the House, Hardenburger
promised to give it a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public should know who's entertaining us,'' she said. ``If
there's excessive spending on a small number of legislators, that
certainly indicates there might be undue influence.''
</P>
<P>
   One lawmaker who openly supports Graves' idea is Sen. Don Biggs,
a Leavenworth Democrat, who says simply, ``it's needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports that name names would raise the awareness on the part of
the legislators and the public, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is basically opening up the window on the process,''
Biggs said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
