r a BC-DRUNK-SENTENCE-KAN &LR;      01-14 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUNK-SENTENCE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUNKEN DRIVER WHO KILLED FAMILY OF THREE SENTENCED TO 15 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The man who killed a
young family of three while driving drunk on Christmas Day in 1998
was sentenced Friday to 15 years in prison.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although less than the 23 years recommended by a jury, the
sentence of Anthony Lamar Fields is thought to be the longest ever
in Jackson County for a drunken-driving conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not exactly what we wanted, but we are satisfied with
that,'' said Laverne Robinson, mother of victim Tracy Stowers.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy and Cecil Stowers and their 4-month-old daughter, Sydney,
had spent their last evening at Tracy's parents' home before
Fields' vehicle rocketed into them at more than 85 mph on
Interstate 435 near 83rd Street.
</P>
<P>
   Fields' blood-alcohol content was 0.16 percent. The Missouri
limit is 0.10 percent. Gov. Mel Carnahan is pushing to lower the
limit to 0.08 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County Circuit Judge Charles E. Atwell heard nearly two
hours of emotional testimony from the victims' families and from
Fields' family and friends. Atwell said that he did not think the
maximum penalty was appropriate but that severe punishment was
warranted.
</P>
<P>
   He sentenced Fields, 28, to seven years each on three counts of
involuntary manslaughter and one year each on two counts of
second-degree assault. But he grouped some of the terms to run at
the same time so that Fields must first serve seven years, then
another seven years and then one year, consecutively, for a total
of 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Jackson County Prosecutor David Fry estimated Fields
will serve at least half the term in prison before being paroled.
Fields was taken into custody Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Fields tearfully addressed the Stowerses' families, his words
barely understandable through his sobbing. His Bible lay before him
open to Psalm 86, a prayer for mercy and compassion.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I live I can't change what happened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The finality of that Christmas Day also weighs on Laverne
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sydney was my only granddaughter, and I'll never have
another,'' she told the court. ``So precious, so precious, and
death is so permanent.''
</P>
<P>
   Cecil Charles Stowers Jr. was 29 and Tracy Lynette Stowers was
30. They both worked at Hallmark Cards Inc. She had a master's
degree in business administration. They had been married 5 years.
Both were active in community and church affairs. Atwell called
them role models for young adults.
</P>
<P>
   Cecil Stowers' mother, Idora Henderson, spoke of a dutiful and
caring son who called her every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the nicest people you could ever meet,'' she
told the court. ``I tell people now: If you didn't know him, you
missed a treat.''
</P>
<P>
   Fields' family and friends told the court how he had changed
after the accident, how he was remorseful and started a Bible study
group. He also voluntarily enrolled in a substance-abuse counseling
program.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of that program testified that Fields was one of the
most sincere clients he has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   But Assistant Jackson County Prosecutor Rick Knight told the
court that Fields had been arrested three times for drunken driving
before that Christmas evening when he crossed the highway median
and struck the Stowerses' vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Vernon Robinson, Tracy Stowers' father, asked the judge to be
fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``This drunken driving has got to stop,'' he said. ``It's taking
too many lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
