<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6749 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SECURITY-1STLE     01-14 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SECURITY-1STLEDE-WRITETHRU-620(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE KREMLIN'S EYES, THE WEST IS NOW A RIVAL ONCE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS 2nd graf to change `easing' to `stiffening'; adds sentence on
Putin to end of 3rd graf; deletes phrase on `information wars' from
end of penultimate graf; in last graf, deletes phrase `in the
world' to correct quote.) 
 (js) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Underscoring its darkening view of the West, the
Kremlin issued a national security strategy Friday that inveighs
against an expansionist Europe and United States and contemplates
the use of nuclear weapons in war ``if all other means of resolving
the crisis have been exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   The revised language governing nuclear weapons is a subtle but
unmistakable stiffening of the previous strategy, issued in 1997,
which allowed the use of nuclear arms only ``in case of a threat to
the existence of the Russian Federation.''
</P>
<P>
   The new strategy was signed by acting President Vladimir Putin
on Monday and published Friday. It reviews not just foreign threats
but a sweeping array of internal dangers, from organized crime to
terrorism, to separatist movements like that of the militants in
Chechnya. Buoyed by the campaign in Chechnya, Putin is the leading
candidate in the election for president on March 26.
</P>
<P>
   In many respects, the document simply incorporates changes in
military and political doctrine approved over the last year as
Russia's domestic situation deteriorated and its judgment of
Western intentions changed.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, however, those changes comprise a new view of
the world by the nation's leaders _ one in which the West is no
longer benign but a competitor that benefits from and even schemes
to ensure Russian weakness.
</P>
<P>
   In the opinion of the document's drafters, Russia is weak in
almost every respect.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy calls the armed forces' readiness ``critically
low,'' and says that social stability is at risk because the
population is being stratified into ``a thin layer of
well-to-do-people and a predominant layer of citizens of scanty
means.'' It says that terrorism poses a serious internal threat,
that foreign economic influence over the economy and natural
resources might be more tightly controlled by the state, and that
national security is endangered by a brain-drain of technologists
and the leakage of intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy chief of the Russian defense ministry's general
staff, Col. Valery Manilov, said Friday that the strategy's
apparent suspicion of Western intentions should not be blown out of
proportion.
</P>
<P>
   In comments to the Russian news service Interfax, Manilov said
Moscow remains interested in ``mutually beneficial and neighborly
cooperation on an equal footing with Western countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Even that wording reflects the altered sentiment of the
strategy, which has dropped all mention of ``partnership'' with the
West in favor of the more neutral term ``cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Little of this bleak picture is new to people who have watched
Russia's elite and average citizens alike turn against the West
after the NATO bombing campaign against Yugoslavia last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce G. Blair, an expert on Russian and U.S. nuclear forces at
the Brookings Institution in Washington, said the change is ``a
codification of something that's really already been pretty well
cemented in the Russian psyche, at least among their security
planners.''
</P>
<P>
   And the discussion of nuclear contingencies, which attracted by
far the most attention, may not prove to be of much practical
significance.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, who spent a decade or more watching the West as a KGB
agent in East Germany, is said by friends to be well aware that any
threat Europe and the United States pose to Russia is not military
but economic and cultural.
</P>
<P>
   And the United States _ which also periodically redraws its
security landscape, in an exercise not dissimilar from that of the
Kremlin _ has traditionally been more hawkish about the first use
of nuclear weapons than has Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department and Pentagon declined comment Friday on the
announcement from Russia, its longtime rival in the Cold War arms
race. Both sides now cooperate militarily in some spheres.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   America's Cold War policy was never to renounce the first use of
nuclear arms but to counter a Russian invasion of Europe with
nuclear force, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, on the other hand, renounced the first use of nuclear
missiles for some years but abandoned the pledge in 1993, and by
then it viewed itself as a Western ally and no longer a rival.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, the Kremlin and White House nuclear policies are
now not that far apart.
</P>
<P>
   But in terms of security, the Russian and U.S. nuclear forces
are now far apart, Blair said, with U.S. forces remaining under
tight control while control of Russian nuclear missiles is more
problematic.
</P>
<P>
   In Blair's view, the new security policy may increase the
chances of potentially catastrophic lapses within a Russian
military hobbled by financial problems and lapsed military
discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is forced to rely more and more on its nuclear force to
deter threats, experts warn, because its conventional military
forces are no longer able to repel outsiders. That requires keeping
nuclear arms on high alert, which invites mistakes in a system
where missing radars and balky satellites already provide only
spotty warning of incoming missiles. The situation may also
increase the chance of false alarms.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has increasingly shown its nuclear card in recent years,
more as a reminder of its potential to wreak havoc _ and to command
respect _ than as any threat. President Boris Yeltsin startled U.S.
leaders only last month when, in response to a mild criticism of
Russia's policy on Chechnya, he tartly reminded President Clinton
that the Kremlin controls an arsenal of nuclear missiles.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the Russian military unveiled its response to the
West's bombing of Yugoslavia by staging the largest military
exercise since the collapse of the Soviet Union. It carried out
mock nuclear strikes on an unspecified - but inarguably Western
enemy.
</P>
<P>
   The plan for the exercise envisioned a Kremlin that was unable
to repel Western forces with its cash-starved army and was thus
forced to resort to nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Then the defense minister, Igor Sergeyev, all but parroted the
text of the document released Friday. ``The exercise tested one of
the provisions of Russia's military doctrine concerning a possible
use of nuclear weapons when all other measures are exhausted,'' he
said then.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did pursue such an option. All measures were exhausted. Our
defenses proved to be ineffective. An enemy continued to push into
Russia. And that's when the decision to use nuclear weapons was
made.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy formalized Friday is hardly so apocalyptic. It
stresses that Russia can regain superpower status _ its clear aim _
only if it pursues capitalism and integrates itself further into
the global economy and political system.
</P>
<P>
   On a list of threats to Russia's national security,
``complication of international relations'' came only at the end of
a parade of domestic dangers, including economic chaos, social
decay, crime and terrorism, political polarization and ethnic
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the document is laced with Soviet-style references to
``some countries,'' generally unnamed but clearly the United States
and Europe, said to be bent on global hegemony and thwarting
Russia's ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts of ``some nations'' to bypass the United Nations'
global security mechanisms is a threat to Russian security, the
document states. So are efforts ``by other states'' to oppose
Russia's role as a locus in a multi-polar world and to weaken its
influence along its western and southern borders. The document also
warns that ``some countries`` are trying to dominate the flow of
information worldwide and to force Russia out of the information
market.
</P>
<P>
   And the text states that NATO's decision to use force outside
its borders, as it did in Yugoslavia, ``is a threat of
destabilization of the whole strategic situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
