<HEADER>
A6753 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-ALAN-KEYES-KAN &LR;      01-14 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALAN-KEYES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL HOPEFUL KEYES' CAMPAIGN CENTERS ON MORALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   MONROE, Iowa _ Everything about Alan
Keyes is moving. Always moving.
<TEXT>
<P>
   His hands are ever gesturing. His feet carry him from side to
side, turning his body this way and that to make sure no part of
his audience can feel ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Even the voice moves, riding the scale in pitch while the volume
rises and dips to emphasize one point and the next.
</P>
<P>
   After talking, almost yelling, to a gymnasium full of high
school students for 15 minutes, he took a step closer to the
bleachers and lowered his voice in conspiratorial tone. It was as
if he's letting them all in on a dangerous secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a kernel of dignity in every person in this room,''
he said, ``not because any man says so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's determined by the great unmentionable, determined by the
one the courts say we can't talk about in the public schools, but
which our founders said you have to talk about. Remember?
`...endowed by their cre-a-tor.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the perpetual motion that is Keyes _ the radio talk show
host who could be president _ one thing stays put. His message
never changes.
</P>
<P>
   America, Keyes insists to everyone in earshot, is in a moral
crisis. The country's soul is in jeopardy because its children are
denied the moral teaching and discipline that he believes made the
great experiment of democracy a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the challenges that we face are fundamentally not
challenges that money could address,'' Keyes said as his speech
quickened and his arms lift toward the ceiling. ``They are
challenges that involve questions about our moral character, our
moral understanding, our moral commitment, about the kind of things
we do not because we get money for them, but because they're
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes' world is one where there is little danger of confusing
right from wrong, where faith in God holds America's best hope for
the future and a secular outlook devoid of religion threatens to
doom the world's last standing superpower.
</P>
<P>
   For Keyes, nothing marks so clearly the country's depravity than
abortion. He mocks the argument that carrying a child to term is a
``mother's choice.'' The U.S. Constitution, Keyes argues, makes no
room for abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are killing our children,'' he said. ``It threatens our
very freedom. If the unborn are not safe, no one is safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtually no question escapes Keyes' sermon on morality. What's
to be done about agriculture? Step in with a special banking system
that allows bumper crops to be stored for leaner times and save the
family farm. The family farm, by his reckoning, is the ``nursery of
America's moral character.''
</P>
<P>
   What about income taxes? Keyes contends they put the control of
all money in government hands. He calls them ``slave taxes,'' says
they should be eliminated entirely. Instead, Keyes would impose a
national sales tax with exemptions for life's necessities of food,
medicine and clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you could determine how much money you want to give the
government,'' he said. ``You don't feel like giving money to the
government right now, you don't go out and get those extras.''
</P>
<P>
   He favors school vouchers that would allow parents to route tax
dollars into private schools. Keyes talks with disgust of
``government schools,'' places he says have sacrificed the goals of
discipline and classic education on an altar of liberal political
agendas.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, his campaign doesn't much bother with specifics.
Keyes says nearly nothing about the programs he would overhaul,
launch or scrap. There is little room for that kind of talk, after
all, when the candidate is concerned with bigger things like
calling America to task for its failings of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that he's new to the alphabet soup of the federal
government. From 1978 to 1983 he held several low-level jobs in
various State Department outposts. Then he spent two years as
ambassador to the United Nations Economic &AMP; Social Council, and
three more as assistant secretary of state for international
organization affairs.
</P>
<P>
   During the Reagan administration he was a chief spokesman for
so-called ``constructive engagement'' with the then-white minority
government of South Africa and in opposition to boycotts and
sanctions. Today he talks of a much harder line with China, a force
he sees as formidable and scary.
</P>
<P>
   Although he talks derisively of politicians and the media, he's
belonged to both clubs. He twice ran for the Senate from Maryland,
and this is his second bid for the White House. Keyes briefly wrote
a syndicated newspaper column in the early 1990s and spent the last
half of the decade on AM radio as host of ``The Alan Keyes Show:
America's Wake-up Call.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 49, he wears a crucifix on a gold chain outside his shirt
but behind his tie. His coat lapel bears a gold pin of a pair of
feet of a fetus.
</P>
<P>
   Talking to Rotary clubs, high schools or business luncheons he
plays the part of a congenial man of letters. Keyes is all
extemporaneous, themes repeated from one place to the next but the
language he uses is all eloquent. There's nothing timid or
rehearsed in his talks.
</P>
<P>
   But in debates with his rivals for the Republican nomination, or
in interviews with the reporters and television crews taking a
growing interest, he comes on more strident. He harangues fellow
candidates, regularly accusing them of dodging the nation's most
important issues _ his issues _ out of fear of dashing their
political fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again after debates, he has stormed into the nearby
rooms where reporters file their stories to complain that they pay
too little attention to his campaign because he is
African-American.
</P>
<P>
   Lately he has seen his poll numbers spike a bit. Where once he
barely drew 1 percent in many surveys, a recent poll by The Des
Moines Register found him placing third with 9 percent of likely
caucus voters behind Texas Gov. George W. Bush and magazine
publisher Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he remains beyond skeptical of polls. Keyes said polls
are manipulated to make voters think some candidates have no chance
of winning. Lowering expectations for those candidates, he said,
could provide cover for vote fraud that wipes out the real support
they get in the ballot booth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not paranoid. It's the world we live in,'' Keyes said.
``It's the danger that we get into if we put too much faith in
these polls....Don't turn (the election) over to pollsters. Don't
turn it over to media moguls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
