<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSFER OF POWER IS VITAL PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ When two of the most
powerful titans in American business relinquished their chief
executive officer titles this week, both demonstrated why they've
been so successful.
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Glass, who took Wal-Mart's leadership torch from Sam
Walton, announced Friday he was being succeeded by his chief
operating officer, Lee Scott. Bill Gates, co-founder of Microsoft,
did the same Thursday and handed his chief exec mantle to longtime
friend and lieutenant Steve Ballmer.
</P>
<P>
   At 64 and 44 years old respectively, Glass and Gates are as far
apart in age as they are in the types of Old Economy-New Economy
enterprises they have headed. What they showed in common, though,
by moving aside for the next management generation helps explain
their greatness as business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Their acknowledgement of the need for an orderly management
succession reassures the investing public they are willing to
sacrifice any ego-driven desire for power to what's best for the
company. It's consistent with their management track record, which
is reflected in the share price of their companies.
</P>
<P>
   Compare their actions to, say, Michael Eisner, who appears
unable to share power by grooming a successor at Disney. As
Wal-Mart and Microsoft investors have prospered, Disney stockholder
fortunes have withered, due partly to Eisner's failure to nurture
the next generation of top management.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as though Glass and Gates are out to pasture. Gates
remains chairman and ``chief software architect'' while Ballmer
deals with government trustbusters and competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The Glass situation is more interesting from a Kansas City
perspective because he hopes to own the Royals and ensure the
continued community presence of major league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be a matter of Glass withdrawing entirely from
Wal-Mart's affairs to hang a ``gone fishin' (for the Royals) sign
on his door. His intention to remain full-time for at least a year
with Wal-Mart as chairman of the board's powerful executive
committee implies he will remain a force at the company.
</P>
<P>
   There's often more to transitions than developing a successor
and giving him or her the opportunity to run the company. The wise
corporate leaders choose to remain handy long enough to finish the
mentoring process in real, operational time to ensure a smooth
transfer of power.
</P>
<P>
   The bonus for area residents concerned about the Royals' future
is that Glass now will probably have more time and energy to devote
to his dream of being a big-league baseball owner. His public
acceptance as an honorary Kansas Citian is virtually complete; all
that remains is for the baseball ownership club to approve his bid
to buy the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   The reassuring aspect of this for Royals fans is that in Glass
they get not only a hard-core baseball devotee, but also one of the
20th Century's most able enterprise builders. The management skills
Glass honed helping build the Wal-Mart empire don't promise
miracles for the Royals, but they do promise it will be an
organization dedicated to doing its best to please its biggest
group of stakeholders, i.e., its fans.
</P>
<P>
   David Glass knows a lot about doing right by his stakeholders.
He proved it again this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 2330EST &QL; 
