<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-PRAYER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLICK AND A PRAYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can a person talk to God on the Internet? The answer probably
depends on a person's concept of God and his or her powers of
concentration. The devout person might answer that the human heart
can pray just about anywhere, including Grand Central Station _ so
why not on the Web?
</P>
<P>
   Viewed broadly, the Web site ``newprayer.com'' is harmless
enough, offering a selection of inspirational writings and a place
for harried Net surfers to compose some spiritual thoughts of their
own and type them into a box.
</P>
<P>
   Viewed narrowly _ as site designers appear to have crafted it
and as many visitors seem to be using it _ the address makes a
presumptuous mockery of religious meditation, boasting of a direct
line to the infinite and promising to send prayers there via radio
transmitter.
</P>
<P>
   The destination is an ancient star cluster known as ``M13,''
chosen because NASA astronomers have pinpointed it as one of the
oldest clusters in the universe. The logic, or illogic, is that
anything that old must have been involved in the big bang and so
must have been touched by God.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply click on the PRAY button and transmit your prayer to
the only known location of God,'' read the directions, which also
explain that ``you will receive e-mail notification that your
prayer was sent.''
</P>
<P>
   That's about as mystical as ordering a book from Amazon.com.,
and it feeds into the ``click-click, buy-buy'' fever pervading much
of the Internet. The prayer site did start out selling its services
for $5 an order but pulled back after people complained _ Martin
Luther would be proud.
</P>
<P>
   It's a free country, and a person can post just about anything
out on the wild informational frontier. But the consumer, as ever,
must beware _ not only of financial scams but of the erosion of
meaning and cheapening of the sacred in an increasingly impersonal
technical age.
</P>
<P>
   Prayer is, or should be, deeply personal. It needs no radio
transmitter to reach its target, for it flows through the depths of
the soul _ as much a home to the infinite as any distant star.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-14-00 2334EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000114.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-14 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
