<HEADLINE>
STORR RESTORED; MURRAY ON INJURED RESERVE FOR KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Goaltender Jamie Storr turned in his ice pack
Friday afternoon, but Glen Murray grabbed it before it had a chance
to melt.
</P>
<P>
   Storr, sidelined since Dec. 15 with a concussion, will be in
goal tonight when the Los Angeles Kings face the San Jose Sharks in
a matchup of struggling Pacific Division rivals. But Murray was
placed on injured reserve and could miss up to three weeks with a
bruised upper chest.
</P>
<P>
   Storr was scheduled to make a start for minor-league Long Beach
on Friday, but the Kings medical staff cleared him to play after
another shaky outing by Stephane Fiset.
</P>
<P>
   The news was tainted by the medical report on Murray, who left
Thursday's game in St. Louis in the first period after getting
checked into the boards by the Blues Tyson Nash.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it happened, we thought he broke his collarbone,'' coach
Andy Murray said. ``Craig Johnson had a similar injury and it cost
him 10 days. Our medical staff says this one looks worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The news couldn't be much worse for the Kings, who are 2-9-1 in
their past 12 games. But they also are looking at another two to
three weeks before first line center Jozef Stumpel returns from an
injured left knee. Stumpel, who missed 10 weeks after a hernia
operation earlier this season, has a muscle tear and a deep bone
bruise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This season has been a nightmare,'' Stumpel said Friday before
the team left for San Jose. ``I thought when I got back from the
first injury, I would be here the rest of the way and get to help
out. It is so hard to just watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the poor record the past month, the Kings (18-17-7)
remain seventh of eight teams in the Western Conference playoff
race. Even though Calgary and Edmonton are just one point back and
the Mighty Ducks three points behind, Storr says their competitive
record is the reason the morale on the club remains strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, this stretch has been bad, but we're in the playoff
hunt,'' he said. ``We are a .500 team. After all that's happened,
we still haven't lost sight of that. Last year we opened 2-9-2.
That meant just a few weeks into the season we already had to win
seven games to get to .500. That was demoralizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with all the injuries, we're still right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick whistles: With Murray gone, that leaves Luc Robitaille,
Ziggy Palffy and Bryan Smolinski as the only healthy players from
the first two lines on opening night. Donald Audette is a week away
with a sprained left ankle. But there are concerns about Palffy,
who missed Friday's practice with lower-back soreness that has
bothered him the past five weeks. Until the injury, Palffy was the
team's leading scorer, but since then he has just two goals and has
missed four games with back problems. ``This is something that is
going to be with him the rest of the year,'' Andy Murray said. ``He
had so much jump in his game at the beginning of the season and
that is missing now.'' ... Aki Berg, who was benched after playing
poorly against Ottawa, will not play tonight against San Jose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
