<SLUG> BC-SMART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SMART' APPLIANCES COMING SOON TO A KITCHEN NEAR YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JONATHAN SIDENER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Futurists have long predicted the thinking toaster and the
Internet-ready refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   But the first ``smart'' kitchen appliances to hit stores may be
the coffeemaker and the mixer.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam Corp. plans to unveil nine intelligent home appliances
next week at the International Housewares Show in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The devices that talk to each other should be in stores by the
end of the year. The product line includes an alarm clock, smoke
detectors, an electric blanket, a blood-pressure monitor and a
bathroom scale.
</P>
<P>
   If you set your alarm 15 minutes earlier than usual, the smart
clock tells the coffee machine to start percolating earlier and
tells the blanket to cool down earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The clock's modem can connect to the Internet to wake you with
weather reports or sports scores.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunbeam has competition to be first in stores, said Joyce
Putscher, an analyst at Cahners In-Stat in Scottsdale. Whirlpool
and Cisco Systems are developing a line of computer-enhanced
refrigerators, stoves and dishwashers.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam says most of the products will cost about the same as
today's lower-IQ coffeemakers and mixers, $50 to $90.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a nice, cute product,'' Dataquest analyst Jay
Srivatsa said. ``But I don't see a mass market this year.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
